<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: NOW IT'S THE PRESIDENT'S TURN TO GAZE
ADORINGLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign for Senate this
week displayed what may be an unexpected new hazard _ her husband.
The problem is not any new question of ethics or morality or bad
taste threatening on the horizon. It is simply that President
Clinton can play a political crowd the way Van Cliburn plays a
piano. As the first couple proved this week, no matter how well she
campaigns with her spouse, she is still a political prodigy sharing
the stage with a maestro.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody at the White House apparently recognized this
possibility months ago. In the first stages of his wife's possible
campaign for Senate, Clinton not only receded into the background,
as much as a president of the United States can recede. He even
went to an Indian reservation out West while she made her first
public moves on New York's Senate seat now held by Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, who is retiring. Alone or with Moynihan, Mrs. Clinton has
been moving cautiously into the contest. In her ``listening tour''
of the state, the first lady adapted the public skills she learned
over the years as a political wife _ nodding and smiling and
avoiding thorny issues as she worked the campaign circuits.
</P>
<P>
   When the president comes along, as he has in recent days, it is
clear that he still needs lessons in accompanying a new lead
singer. At the state fair in Syracuse on Monday, the first state
political outing that included the entire first family, both
Clintons spoke to a crowd that was about as soft as a Democrat
could find in upstate New York. Comptroller Carl McCall, who had
gathered 500 supporters for a traditional political lunch,
demonstrated the gentleness of his audience when he told the same
wan joke two times and the crowd laughed loudly, twice. Thus when
Mrs. Clinton got up to speak, she performed adequately and earned a
solid round of applause.
</P>
<P>
   Then her husband sauntered to the microphone. Before the
president even got behind the lectern, the crowd started chuckling
and settling in for the show. ``You know, it's pretty nice to go to
a lunch like this when you know you're the only one who's not
running for anything,'' he joked, with an ease that suddenly made
his wife's performance sound brittle by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been my imagination, listening to the Arkansas
president in New York's upstate briar patch, but the accent seemed
to thicken as he talked, and the voice suddenly took on just a
touch of Merle Haggard. Sure, he thanked everyone and praised
everyone and talked about big issues that concern a president of
the United States, like taxes. But the nub of that brief speech,
the parts that crowd will remember, touched on earlier days at
other state fairs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton trotted out stories and little routines that had the
kind of yarn-spinner's polish that comes only with years of
practice. He confessed at one point to a group of ardent fairgoers,
``I never met a fair I didn't like.'' When he was being greeted
like a superstar by people who said later they wanted his wife to
go back to Arkansas, he admitted that he was enjoying himself
handsomely. ``I've done this all my life,'' he said with a touch of
nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   The question, of course, is how the first lady repackages her
husband as political spouse. In the expected contest with New
York's mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, she would draw decent enough crowds
as a famous first lady. But having along a president, even one who
does not have many fans left in upstate New York, draws even bigger
crowds. The pomp and the trappings stir a conservative Republican
community like Skaneateles into hanging bunting from every building
on Main Street. The restaurateur who has a baloney sandwich named
after Mrs. Clinton has been chastised in The Skaneateles Press for
not being respectful to the nation's chief of state and his Mrs.
</P>
<P>
   The nettlesome question of the president's role in her campaign
is probably being answered at this very moment by adroit pollsters
working phones in the Syracuse area for the first lady. Did she
lose your vote when she held his hand? Did you like the sound of
the helicopters? In the meantime, the president will probably have
to teach his wife how to carry off some of his best and oldest
lines, or he will have to wave from the stage, stare at her
adoringly and stay away from the microphone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
