<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTONS-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS APPEAR SET TO BUY HOUSE IN CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ President Clinton and Hillary Rodham
Clinton appeared Tuesday to be in the final stages of negotiating
to buy a house in Westchester County, a rambling Dutch Colonial in
the picturesque village of Chappaqua.
</P>
<P>
   The Westchester Multiple Listing Service, a computerized roster
that gives the status of properties for sale, indicated Tuesday
that the house, at 15 Old House Lane, was under contract, according
to a broker not involved in the deal. But it did not suggest who
the intended purchaser was.
</P>
<P>
   The real-estate broker who has worked with the Clintons on their
house search, Kathy Sloane of Brown Harris Stevens in Manhattan,
said Tuesday night that she had no information that a deal had been
finalized.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clintons, stopping off last Saturday in Westchester
between visits to Martha's Vineyard and the Hamptons on Long
Island, N.Y., saw only one house, the 110-year-old one in
Chappaqua, and they spent a leisurely two hours inside. And people
who have followed the first couple's real-estate quest said they
were very close to working out an agreement to buy the 11-room
house, which was listed for $1,695,000.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, home buyers will sign a contract with a number of
conditions, such as their qualifying for a mortgage. If there are
still conditions in the Clintons' case, security could well be one
of them, and rumors swirled Tuesday that the first couple was also
trying to purchase an adjacent piece of land so the Secret Service
could provide better security.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who is widely expected to run for the Senate from
New York, has been looking at houses in Westchester for weeks. Last
month, she was joined by President Clinton and their daughter,
Chelsea, on a tour that took them from Pound Ridge, in the
pristine, semi-rural northern part of the county, to New Rochelle
in the more congested south.
</P>
<P>
   The house in Chappaqua would place the Clintons in the county's
dead center, giving them speedy access to Westchester County
Airport and a relatively quick commute to the city. Situated in the
town of New Castle, Chappaqua is known for its beautiful old
houses, its gently rolling landscape and its school district,
considered one of the top two or three public districts in
Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   But Chappaqua is just south of Westchester's horse country,
where movie stars and industrialists have sought privacy in recent
years on giant estates in towns like Bedford and Pound Ridge.
Chappaqua is certainly wealthy and prestigious, but it is more
squarely suburban in spirit, with many two-career couples making
the commute into Manhattan on Metro North.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Clinton decides to run for the Senate, she has to
establish a New York residence.
</P>
<P>
   The other houses the Clintons had looked at had larger
properties, ranging from two to seven acres. This house has just
1.1 acres, a fact that may account for speculation about their
efforts to purchase adjacent land. ``The only thing that shocks me
about the whole deal is that it's one acre,'' observed one broker.
</P>
<P>
   The 5,200-square-foot house has appealing historic details, like
fat white columns on the ground floor, French windows and
traditional gambrel roof lines. It sits on a quiet cul-de-sac,
shielded from view by fir and maple trees, and has a master bedroom
with a wrap-around deck that overlooks a pool and wooded back yard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
