<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' CORNERS: DIMINUTIVE AND DOGGED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Minn.)   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Once upon a time in Texas, Ray Mickens and
Aaron Glenn had a dream: that they would both be playing in the
National Football League. ``I never imagined, though, being on the
same team with Aaron,'' Mickens said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could most people _ especially Jets Coach Bill Parcells.
It's the height thing. Glenn is 5 feet 9 inches tall, Mickens is 5
feet 8 inches tall. The Jets measured him in college early in the
morning, when people are taller.
</P>
<P>
   Each will be giving away at least a half foot in height against
the Vikings' receivers they face Friday night in the final
preseason game. But they will not be as challenged when the regular
season starts. Only one receiver on the Jets' first two East
Division opponents _ Andre Reed of the Bills _ is taller than 6
feet 1 inch.
</P>
<P>
   Mickens and Glenn will start the season against the Patriots on
Sept. 12. Glenn, a Pro Bowl selection last season, will be at left
cornerback, and Mickens will be on the right side, playing for Otis
Smith, who is recuperating from a broken collarbone. It will be
their first time starting a regular-season game together since
1996. Before then, it was during their Texas A&AMP;M days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're friends, but there's a competitive side between us,''
Mickens said. ``You always feel you're going to be the best.
Aaron's on top now, and I want to be better than him. We try to
outdo the other.''
</P>
<P>
   They have teamed up for every exhibition game following Smith's
injury. It has allowed each to study the other's technique up
close, and to kid about it.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday promises to be their most stringent test of the
preseason schedule, and perhaps their most difficult assignment of
the year. The Vikings' primary receivers are tall: Randy Moss is 6
feet 4 inches, Cris Carter is 6 feet 3 inches and Jake Reed is 6
feet 3 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether there had been a height issue with Glenn and
Mickens playing together, Parcells replied: ``Not right now. But
we're getting ready to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have effective jumpers,'' Parcells said of the Viking
receivers. ``Particularly Moss.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Mickens and Glenn can reach heights of their own. They have
to be outstanding athletes to have been so effective.
</P>
<P>
   They met as Aggies when Glenn was a senior in 1993, and Mickens
was a freshman. The next year, the Jets made Glenn a first-round
pick. Then in 1996, Mickens was drafted on the third round. They
played the first 10 games of the season in tandem before Mickens
was sidelined with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is going to help us,'' Mickens said. ``With the
quality they have, we're getting ready for them like a
regular-season game.''
</P>
<P>
   For Glenn, there will be a reunion of sorts with Carter. When
they last met in 1997, Parcells instructed Glenn to be physical.
Glenn and Carter shoved each other throughout the game. After one
incident, Parcells had to pull Glenn away. Carter snared six passes
for 105 yards, but the Jets won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was heated,'' Glenn said. ``But that's football. I was
trying to play him the way coach wanted me to play him, just try to
match being physical with him. They're all physical players when
they're big, so you can't help but be physical.''
</P>
<P>
   How will Glenn play defense? ``Play basketball; block out,
that's basically it,'' he said. ``The only thing you can do is just
try to jump with those guys. When the ball is in the air, you've
got to make sure you know where he is. When he jumps for the ball,
you've got to make sure you try to jump with him. Don't try to jump
for interceptions all the time. Just knock the ball down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try to jump for interceptions all the time, they're
going to be over the top of you and just grab the ball. So
basically you want to play the ball and knock it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Glenn and Mickens benefit from playing almost daily against
the 6-foot-3-inch Keyshawn Johnson. Johnson has had particular
success against Mickens, whom he has practiced against more often.
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn faces Johnson enough in practice to get something out
of it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I am playing Keyshawn, especially on a deep ball, I don't
go for the interception every time, especially if I'm not in the
right position,'' Glenn said. ``If I have a step on him and the
ball's thrown deep and I'm in front of him, maybe I can go for the
ball then. But when the ball is up in the air for either one of us
to get it, I'm not playing for the interception. I'm playing to get
the ball down.''
</P>
<P>
   To Steve Atwater, the free safety who can speak from the
comforting height of 6 feet 3 inches, there is no mystery about
height in pro football. ``When you're a good cornerback,'' Atwater
said, ``you've got to face guys that are tall, guys that are
short.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The Jets trimmed their roster to 65 players. The final cut to 53
is next Sunday. . . . The latest to go was tight end Lawrence Hart,
who said he was not ready to play because of an eye injury, while
Jets medical advisers said he could play. . . . Linebacker Marvin
Jones did not practice because of a sprained ankle. Coach Bill
Parcells said that Jones had started to play at a high level after
his yearlong recovery from knee surgery. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
