<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MAYOR-JUROR-NYT &LR;      09-01 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-JUROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI THE JUROR HEARS FIRST DAY OF TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There have been celebrity litigants and there have
been celebrity lawyers. Now there is a juror who brings his own
security team to court and stops to shake hands with voters _ er,
courthouse employees.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell something is different looking over the shoulders
of the artists in Courtroom 341. The instantly recognizable face of
Juror No. 1 sits at the centerpiece of their sketches rather than
fading into the background where the no-name jurors normally
belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a somewhat unusual case, and we're not going to hide
that,'' Justice Elliot Wilk of state Supreme Court told Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and his fellow jurors as the case of Johnson vs.
Riverton opened Tuesday morning. ``This case is important to the
plaintiff, this case is important to the defense, irrespective of
who sits as jurors, irrespective of who sits in the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Unusual indeed.
</P>
<P>
   As they waited in the assembly room for the trial to start, many
jurors were flipping through the morning's newspapers. But only
juror No. 1 was reading about himself, starting with an article in
The New York Times about the city's quest to quash a youth march in
Harlem. The mayor was soon exchanging backslaps with Howard Bell, a
judicial hearing officer, as they recalled their contacts back when
Giuliani was a federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony only made the situation more surreal. It turns out
that Oliver Johnson, the plaintiff, has worked on and off as a
security guard in several nightclubs, including the Tunnel, a
notorious spot that juror No. 1 has been trying to shut down.
Johnson's wife, Larene, is a social worker for the Health and
Hospitals Corp. _ a city agency that, of course, has close ties to
juror No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   And so it went, as the most personal of personal-injury cases
became as public as public gets.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnsons are suing Riverton Associates, their former
landlord in East Harlem, claiming that a sudden change in water
temperature four years ago while Oliver Johnson was in the shower
resulted in severe burns and the destruction of their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the case might make any juror blush, but the media
circus that followed the first New York City mayor ever picked for
a jury did not help. In the morning, Johnson testified that, at
first, he was too embarrassed to tell even his wife about his
injury, and that when several months of applying ointment to his
wounds did not heal them, he shunned further treatment, partly
because he did not want to reveal himself to more doctors.
</P>
<P>
   During the testimony, Giuliani sat quietly. As juror No. 1, he
was just a few yards from the witnesses, and frequently made eye
contact as Johnson told his tale of sexual dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up the next morning, I was horrified to look down,''
Johnson, 45, recalled of the incident on Feb. 16, 1995. ``My penis
was blistered and swollen. It was oozing and it was very painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Johnson, 46, whose claim against Riverton is for loss of
marital ``services,'' said that the injury stole the man she
married in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Riverton's lawyer, James Miller, implied that the injuries were
not very severe and repeatedly questioned the Johnsons about why
further medical attention had not been sought. Miller also attacked
the Johnsons' credibility, suggesting that they had pent-up
animosity toward the landlord after having been evicted because
they owed more than $13,000 in back rent.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, the only juror in a suit and tie, showed no reaction
during the testimony, but offered several of his trademark ticks,
holding his chin in his hand, removing and replacing his glasses,
crossing his arms tight across his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Heeding the judge's orders not to discuss the case, the mayor
declined to comment as he descended the courthouse steps. Earlier,
he said he thought that serving on a jury would be a ``fascinating
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried many cases in court, and I listened to many people
come up with the most inventive excuses for getting out of jury
duty,'' Giuliani said. ``It always offended me because it seemed to
me that jury duty is one of the few things that you are asked to do
in exchange for living in a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it is a message to people,'' the mayor added, ``that
this is something they should look forward to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
