<SLUG> BC-IDT-PHONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDT TO OFFER LONG-DISTANCE CALLS FOR 5 CENTS PER MINUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Undercutting the telecommunications giants, IDT Corp. plans to
begin offering domestic long-distance calls Wednesday for 5 cents a
minute at any time with a flat monthly fee of $3.95.
</P>
<P>
   For the last month, the three titans of the $80 billion
long-distance industry _ AT&AMP;T Corp., MCI Worldcom Inc. and Sprint
Corp. _ have been embroiled in a price war. On Monday, AT&AMP;T
responded to new offers from MCI Worldcom and Sprint by announcing
that it would offer consumers domestic long-distance calls for 7
cents a minute in addition to a $5.95 monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   IDT, which is based in Hackensack, N.J., is a mere fraction of
the size of the other companies, but it is nonetheless prepared to
offer lower rates to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making it clear that we're the low-price provider in the
industry,'' Howard S. Jonas, the chairman of the company, said
Tuesday. ``We think everybody else is playing games with a nickel a
minute at night, but if you take that it's a quarter during the
day, or 7 cents a minute all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint kicked off the latest round of price cuts last month with
a plan that offers 5-cent calls only between 7 p.m. and midnight
and a 10-cent rate at other times. That plan carries a monthly
charge of $5.95.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, MCI Worldcom created a new calling plan that
offers 5-cent calling on weekends and from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m. during
the week. But that plan charges 25 cents a minute during weekdays
and carries a $1.95 monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
   IDT's new offer appears cheaper than anything offered to
consumers by AT&AMP;T, MCI Worldcom or Sprint. Qwest Communications
International Inc. offers a flat-rate 5-cent plan, but that deal
carries a $9.95 monthly fee and must be charged to a credit card
rather than a standard phone bill.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 5-cent plan, IDT intends to offer a flat
long-distance rate of 3.5 cents to consumers who also sign up for
the company's Internet service, which costs $14.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Jonas said there might not be much profit in selling consumers
domestic long-distance calls for 5 cents a minute, but he said
overseas calling opportunities made the new deal worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not really much to be made at a nickel, but we believe
that a significant portion of the people who sign up will make
international calls,'' Jonas said. ``There a nice profit margin to
be made there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
