r s BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN     09-01 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLEMAN MAKES A SPLASH WITHOUT `SWIMMING'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Early in training camp, when the UCLA coaches
issued a ``no swimming'' edict, no one was happier than defensive
end Kenyon Coleman. Although he loves to swim, Coleman knew it
wasn't in his best interest.
</P>
<P>
   The proclamation had nothing to do with swimming pools or
swimming laps. It concerned Coleman's use of a standard
pass-rushing technique called ``the swim,'' in which the rusher
lifts his arm over a blocker in a freestyle-stroke motion.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman's problem was leverage. He's 6-foot-6 and 280 pounds.
Each time he tried the swim, which requires a vertical stance, he
became an easy target for blockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one thing we've stressed besides conditioning, it's
playing with leverage,'' defensive end coach John Pearce said. ``In
the past, Kenyon has not played with leverage. He has made himself
too easy to block. He's got to use his size and strength to his
advantage, and to do that he's got to stay low.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by Coleman's training-camp performance _ he was nearly
unblockable _ the swimming policy has worked as designed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing great; I hope he plays the games like he's
practicing,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``I told Kenyon this
has got to be his coming-out year. The junior year is really
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman's refined technique is but one aspect of his
transformation. He has a renewed spirituality thanks to Athletes in
Action. He's playing with unprecedented passion, in part to amend
last year's defensive collapse. He also has lofty personal goals
that include a possible jump to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents have left it up to me,'' he said of entering the
NFL draft. ``They know I'll make the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of mind and physique has produced the player
UCLA envisioned when it signed Coleman in 1997: an All-Pacific-10
talent who plays with consistency and aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, if it was in the third quarter and I didn't have
any sacks, I'd say, `How am I going to get some sacks?' '' Coleman
said. ``Now, I'm mature enough to know that if I work hard in
practice, the sacks will come. I feel like the pressure's off.''
</P>
<P>
   And if it's off Coleman, it's probably on his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer update: Receiver Danny Farmer removed the protective boot
Tuesday and jogged lightly on his sprained left ankle, but he
remains doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not ready to make a decision,'' Toledo said. ``It didn't
appear he was really ready at this point. We're going to keep
playing it day-to-day. We might wait until game time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready for action: Because of injuries and suspensions on the
offensive line, the Bruins have abandoned hope of redshirting true
freshman tackle Bryce Bohlander. He'll play Saturday, and for the
rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bohlander is just the second rookie offensive lineman to play
for UCLA since Jonathan Ogden in 1992. The other: right tackle
Brian Polak in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to, but we're forced to,'' Toledo said. ``If we
lose one more guy, (Bohlander) was going to have to play anyway,
and chances are we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the lights: The Bruins will hold a rare evening practice
tonight to prepare for Saturday's 6 p.m. kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get used to playing under the lights,'' Toledo
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
