<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LOST-CONTINENT-2TA     09-01 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOST-CONTINENT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.J.)  
 SEEKING A LOST CONTINENT A BIT WEST OF THE HUDSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GLENN COLLINS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOWN OF RAMAPO, N.Y. _ About a billion years ago, or so the
prevailing geological theory has it, the Earth's continental plates
collided, pushing up mountains the height of the Himalayas and
creating a supercontinent geologists call Rodinia.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the breakup of Rodinia created a lost ocean, Iapetus,
that was itself destroyed when the continents collided and formed
yet another supercontinent, Pangaea.
</P>
<P>
   By and by _ and, since we're talking geological time here, by
and by and by _ Pangaea split up, creating not only North America,
Europe and Africa, but also the Atlantic Ocean. Finally, then,
erosion and the burden of mile-high glaciers flattened much of the
landscape, including the swatch of drive-through topography we now
know as metropolitan New York.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Dr. Alexander Gates, a professor of geology at
Rutgers University in Newark, N.J., is navigating that landscape,
rock hammer in hand. Ranging the forests of New York's Harriman
State Park in Rockland and Orange counties, scribbling observations
in his leather-bound field notebook, he is, by his own description,
``looking to piece together the Rodinian story.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, Gates and his research team have been
mapping the tortured history of one of the last vast, geologically
pristine places in the region _ taking an inventory of significant
rock types, features and geological faults, photographing them and
collecting rock samples.
</P>
<P>
   Their ambition is not only to compile the most detailed picture
of the geological history of Harriman and its region, but also to
look for clues that will unravel important mysteries in the story
of the earth's lost supercontinents, which had a history of violent
assembly and reassembly as dizzying as the slam-dance of bumper
cars in an amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   On the urbanized, suburbanized, exurbanized face of it, New York
and environs might not seem to be the most fertile geological
ground. Lately, according to Gates, the region ``has been neglected
by geologists.'' But, he added, the basement rock of the
metropolitan area is actually some of the most complex in the
United States. in terms of the dazzling variety of rocks, their
spectacular deformation by wind, water, ice and volcanic fire, and
their intricate, baffling, Rubik's Cube construction.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to studying that local geology, Harriman is
the place to be. Across the region, development has obscured most
of what geologists refer to as ``exposures.'' Harriman, though,
``is pretty much the way it was left, after the glacier retreated''
12,000 years ago, said Dr. Yngvar Isachsen, principal scientist for
the Geological Survey of the New York State Museum in Albany. ``In
geology, it doesn't get much better than that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Gates said, the project has yielded new revelations
about the formation of the ancient continent of Rodinia, including
at least one ``Rosetta Stone,'' a Harriman rock outcrop that
provides significant information on the supercontinent's formation.
</P>
<P>
   The research could have some very practical applications as
well. As seismologists study the origins of the recent earthquake
in Turkey, they are calling for intensified research to gauge the
likelihood of future seismic events in the metropolitan area.
Though the region is often characterized as dormant, geologists say
it presents the potential for earthquake hazard.
</P>
<P>
   And at a time when Harriman had to close its hiking trails until
last Friday because of the drought, Gates' work ``can be very
helpful to us,'' said Carol Ash, executive director of the
Palisades Interstate Park Commission, which administers 100,000
acres of forest in New York and New Jersey, including Harriman.
``We hope that Dr. Gates' study of fissures in the rock will give
us a greater understanding of the park's ground-water system, and
help us to manage it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists say this focus on New York's geology is long
overdue. Geologists ``paid a lot of attention to the New York
region at the turn of the century, especially when the city's water
tunnels were being built,'' said Leonardo Seeber, a research
scientist at the Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory of Columbia
University in Palisades, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the region became ``unfashionable,'' Seeber said. High
mountains, active volcanoes, petroleum reserves and pure-science
research drew many academics elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other areas are trendier, and they get better funding,''
Isachsen said. These days, thanks to budget cuts, the Geological
Survey cannot even afford to assign a geological specialist to the
New York metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As they carry out their project, Gates and his team are also
studying and reinterpreting the observations of generations of
geologists who toiled before the era of plate tectonics, the
evolving theory that, since the 1960s, has viewed the earth's rock
record in the context of the interaction of the earth's continental
plates. The metropolitan area ``has always been where the action
is,'' said Gates, but now, he noted, geologists can finally make
sense of what all that action meant.
</P>
<P>
   These days, though, the metropolitan region is also ``important
from the standpoint of seismological hazard,'' Seeber of
Lamont-Doherty said.
</P>
<P>
   New York is currently designated a ``stable continental
region,'' Seeber explained. But while geologists have an aversion
to unduly alarming the populace, New York, they say, is in its
inactivity similar to the area east of Bombay, India, where an
earthquake of magnitude 6.3 on the Richter scale killed 10,000
people in 1993. ``That region was also determined to be
low-hazard,'' Seeber said. ``It clearly demonstrates that we know
little about how earthquakes in these areas are generated.''
</P>
<P>
   New York, New Jersey and Connecticut are riddled with ancient
geological faults. As recently as 1884, a magnitude 5.0 earthquake
is believed to have had its epicenter just outside New York Harbor,
breaking crockery, ringing church bells and toppling chimneys from
Connecticut to Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   That temblor was the same size as the recent earthquake on the
San Andreas fault near San Francisco. ``If you put that bull's-eye
right under Manhattan,'' Seeber said, ``the effect could have been
much greater,'' causing loss of life and substantial damage, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, who is 42 years old and grew up in Rockland County, hopes
his team's labors will lead to the creation of an unspoiled
geological park at Harriman _ a 75,000-acre outdoor laboratory that
will show how a wilderness park can be packaged as a geological and
environmental educational tool for scholars, teachers, students and
the general public.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gates says, the project is expected to generate
museum exhibits and educational programming for a variety of
institutions, including the American Museum of Natural History in
Manhattan and the Liberty Science Center in Jersey City, N.J. The
project is financed by $43,000 in start-up money from the National
Science Foundation, and the institutions have asked the foundation
for additional financing.
</P>
<P>
   Gates and the sponsoring institutions also hope to create a
library and Web site of materials that would guide visitors to
significant geological features on the walking trails of the
metropolitan region. A test version of the Web site is up and
running at http://geology2.rutgers.edu/harriman2/index.htm.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, Gates led a visitor to a grayish, weathered
outcrop on Seven Lakes Drive opposite Lake Tiorati. Previously
undocumented by geologists, the rock exposure provides new evidence
that the Rodinian supercontinent was assembled by a series of
continental collisions over time. The outcrop has preserved the
record of a rising plume of molten rock from deep in the earth's
crust as it scorched the older rock above it. But that rock had
itself already been tortured by a prior collision between
continental plates.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Gates concluded, the rock exposure provides important
new evidence in a primordial detective story: it shows that there
were at least two ancient collisions in the formation of the
supercontinent Rodinia.
</P>
<P>
   Gates pointed to the outcrop and smiled. ``I think of this as
the Rosetta Stone,'' he said, happily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 0027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6702 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BOEING-SPI &LR;      09-01 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING PACT, IF APPROVED, WILL HAVE FAR-REACHING EFFECT IN
INDUSTRY, LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Boeing's choice of compromise over conflict in its
attempt to win approval of its largest labor contract will embolden
unions within the company, across the nation and at rival Airbus
Industrie, according to labor analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Machinists union will vote Wednesday on a
contract hammered out early Saturday when the company dropped
demands for a longer workweek and higher payments for health care,
while offering competitive raises and a 10 percent bonus. The deal
was designed, in part, to keep production lines open at the
Seattle-based aerospace company.
</P>
<P>
   But the contract with members of the International Association
of Machinists will have a broader impact. The company's concessions
will encourage other unions to make similar demands when they
hammer out future agreements, according to labor scholars. That's
because the Boeing contract, which covers 44,000 workers, serves as
a bellwether for the industrial labor movement, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a large sense it really energizes the labor movement,''
said Harley Shaiken, a professor of labor relations at the
University of California at Berkeley. The union ``won gains in the
areas of wages, pensions and job security (and) these are all hotly
contested questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor movement takes some of its cues from Boeing because
the issues the company and the union fought over mirror battles
occurring throughout the U.S. manufacturing and aerospace
industries.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Boeing backed away from its demand that Machinists
should pay a portion of their health care premiums in the future.
That move will bolster organized labor's opposition to similar
corporate demands, according to Richard Bank, the director of the
Center for Collective Bargaining at the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company abandoned its push for a seven-day
workweek that would run 24 hours a day, an initiative other
companies are weighing. Throughout the negotiations the union
argued the idea would disrupt the family lives of its members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you are going to see more and more unions...are going
to draw the line on quality of life issues,'' said Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Companies also may find their workers are seeking bigger
bonuses. Boeing offered its Machinists lump-sum payments in 1999
that will average $4,400 for each worker covered by the contract.
</P>
<P>
   That ``creates expectations in other sectors, that (you have)
got to have a bonus system in place,'' said David Olson, a
political science professor at the University of Washington in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The contract offer also threatens to reach across the Atlantic
to Boeing's rival Airbus Industrie. That's because workers at the
Toulouse, France-based airplane consortium are likely watching the
negotiations, said Olson. Since Boeing workers are perceived to
have won some concessions from their boss, Airbus employees
probably are expecting a boost in their next contract, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus officials rejected the idea that contracts at Boeing and
Airbus are linked.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, ``I don't think there has been much correlation
between Boeing contracts and Airbus contracts,'' said David Venz,
chief spokesman in North America for Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus would stand to reap potentially huge benefits if Boeing
couldn't settle the contract and its Machinists struck. A strike
would hurt Boeing while it's locked in an intense bidding war with
Airbus for new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big losers are Airbus'' stakeholders, said Olson.
</P>
<P>
   The contract also will ripple through other collective
bargaining units at Boeing, raising expectations for workers.
Officials at the Seattle Professional Engineering Employees
Association, who will negotiate a contract for 24,000 Boeing
workers this fall, say they're already heartened by Boeing's offer
to Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials caution that the company's latest offer won't
dictate the terms of other agreements, even though it will serve as
a reference point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be looked at (but) it doesn't automatically translate
into a rubber stamp everywhere,'' said Peter Conte, the chief
spokesman for Boeing during the contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing hasn't eliminated its biggest labor headache yet.
Machinists will travel to their union halls in Seattle, Everett,
Auburn, Renton, Spokane, Portland, Ore., and Wichita, Kan.,
Wednesday to vote to either ratify or reject the contract.
</P>
<P>
   If they reject the proposal, and two-thirds of those voting
support a strike, they could be on the picket lines Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Many Machinists, however, have welcomed the offer, including the
competitive wage package, the absence of new health care bills and
the preservation of the traditional workweek. The response has left
union leaders optimistic about the outcome of Wednesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel they will ratify what may be one of the best contracts
in the aerospace industry,'' said Bill Johnson, the president of
the International Association of Machinists' District Lodge 751 in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some workers are upset, saying the package doesn't offer
a big enough jump in pension benefits and falls short in other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and the union will know the fate of their agreement at
roughly 9 Wedneday night, when the union plans to announce the
results of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   If workers ratify the contract it will represent another step
toward improving the often turbulent relationship between Boeing
and its most potent union, the Machinists. The union has struck
during two of the last three labor negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it ... indicates the importance to companies like
Boeing that maintaining harmonious labor relationships is important
over the long'' term, said Robert Scott, an international economist
at the Economic Policy Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Local companies should also take note if Boeing and its largest
union strike a compromise Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very hot labor market and labor exercised
considerable strength,'' said the University of Washington's Olson.
``Other firms similarly situated not only have to take labor
negotiations seriously, they have to learn from past mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
