</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET-MERGERS-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP-TIER FIRMS ON WALL STREET ARE MERGER SHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though many investors think it is just a matter of
time before America's big securities houses hook up with banks,
Wall Street firms are proving to be reluctant merger partners.
</P>
<P>
   Take Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which has the largest market
value of any Wall Street firm. Its top executives recently debated
and dismissed a merger offer from Chase Manhattan Bank, people told
of the talks said, making it the second time in a year that the
firm decided against teaming up with Chase.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of Morgan Stanley's securities and merger advisory
business with Chase's corporate loan expertise would have proved
formidable _ it would have become the largest financial services
firm in the world. But fears of a culture clash, and the challenge
of the Internet, prompted Morgan Stanley to reject the overture,
the people said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is the latest setback for Chase and its top
executives, Walter Shipley and William Harrison. Shipley, Chase's
chairman, has been courting Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch and
Goldman Sachs for more than a year. Harrison, who was appointed
chief executive last spring, has made fresh approaches to Wall
Street firms in recent months, so far without success, people told
of the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespeople for Morgan Stanley and Chase declined to say
whether such talks occurred, citing policies against commenting on
market speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Some stock analysts still expect that Merrill, Morgan Stanley or
Goldman will end up merging with a bank. The main reason is that as
Depression-era laws that once kept banks and securities firms off
each other's turf fall away, bankers are having an easier time
trespassing on securities firms' territory than the reverse, some
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Chase may also succeed in finding a partner. Market speculation
recently had Chase talking again with Merrill, though a person
involved in Chase's strategic planning said he believes that Chase
preferred Morgan Stanley and was disappointed by the failure to
reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Chase, Citigroup, Bank of America and other big banks are
threatening the long-standing dominance of Wall Street firms in
some corners of investment banking. Chase and Bank of America, for
example, dominate the syndicated loan business. Some analysts see
such lending as the most important single financial product that
banks or investment banks can provide to corporate clients these
days, suggesting that Chase could decide to expand its investment
banking franchise without a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chase is using its leadership in syndicated loans to get more
investment banking business and deepen its relationship with
corporations,'' said Ruchi Madan, a bank analyst at Paine Webber.
``The brokerage firms do not have that expertise, and the
competitive pressures are building.'' By her estimates, syndicated
bank loans account for about half of all funds raised by American
companies, a proportion that has risen sharply in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Chase also signaled that it was prepared to live without
acquiring a Wall Street firm when it hired Neal Garonzik, who had
headed Morgan Stanley's stock division, as a vice-chairman with a
mandate to build the bank's equity business. People at Chase say
Garonzik believes that the firm can use its lending relationships
with corporate clients to build its own full-service investment
bank.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's path to building a vibrant securities business is
unlikely to be smooth, however. The bank announced internally
Tuesday the resignation of George Brown, founder and chief
executive officer of its brokerage unit, Brown &AMP; Co. Brown was
quoted as saying that he disagreed with the strategy the bank was
pursuing for the brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   People told about the Morgan Stanley-Chase talks said that
executives on both sides felt the combination made strategic sense.
Price was not a major obstacle, nor was leadership. Morgan Stanley
executives expected that Shipley and Harrison would cede key
management positions to them, the people said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was culture. Though America's biggest banks have
become more streamlined and competitive in recent years, many Wall
Street veterans still believe that they are more bureaucratic and
less nimble than investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley, which merged with Dean Witter two years ago,
also worried about the difficulty of tackling another large merger
now. Philip Purcell, Morgan Stanley's current chairman and chief
executive and the former top boss at Dean Witter, and John Mack, a
Morgan Stanley veteran who is president of the combined entity,
clashed last year when Mack was seeking to be made a coequal and
was rebuffed, people at Morgan Stanley say. The two have a better
working relationship now than they did a year ago, but are said to
be reluctant to take on a fresh challenge like merging with Chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were reasons that a merger would have been a home run,''
said one person who was told of the merger discussions. ``But in
the end they worried about culture.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another problem was the Internet. Purcell has spent much of his
time in recent weeks plotting how Morgan Stanley, which operates
the online Discover Brokerage separately from its traditional
retail brokerage network, can offer discounted online trading to
all its retail clients without undercutting the commissions and
fees its brokers generate. The firm is scurrying to come up with a
plan to match Merrill, which has announced that it will begin to
offer low-priced online trading to all its retail customers by
year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley is eager to capture the enthusiasm investors have
for rivals that do more business through the Internet. Shares of
Charles Schwab, the leading online brokerage firm, trade at 65
times earnings, compared to roughly 14 times for Morgan Stanley and
Merrill Lynch and 16 times for Chase. That's even after a downturn
in Schwab's share price this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Morgan Stanley and other Wall Street firms
acknowledge that without a bank as a partner they face some
pressing problems. They are also-rans in the huge syndicated loan
business, in which banks extend loans to companies and then sell
all or part of them to investors. Moreover, the Wall Street firms
have much less capital than banks to make loans. That lending is
especially vital during periods in which the stock and bond markets
are rocky, when it's harder for companies to sell securities.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Merrill and Morgan Stanley say the two
securities firms are exploring ways of increasing the capital they
have on hand to make loans. They hope that the remaining
legislative obstacles to bank-brokerage combinations will disappear
by early next year, allowing them to buy a small- or medium-sized
bank themselves, an option some people at the two firms consider
preferable to merging with a giant like Chase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
