<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-TREES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORESTED LAND IN THE EMERALD CITY IS DROPPING DRAMATICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KRISTIN DIZON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Emerald City? Not according to a new study, which
suggests Seattle's nickname should be downgraded to a less
brilliant shade of green.
</P>
<P>
   What residents have noticed for years _ that the number of trees
are declining _ has been confirmed in an analysis by American
Forests, which bills itself as the oldest conservation group in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   And according to the city's own forestry experts, many of the
urban trees that remain are in poor health.
</P>
<P>
   Using a combination of digital satellite images, aerial
photography, Geographical Information Systems mapping and ground
surveys, the group said their analysis shows the amount of forested
land in the city is dropping dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, 10 percent of the city's land area was heavily treed.
By 1996, the amount of forested land comprised just 5 percent of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of treed land has had an economic impact, according to
the 20,000-member group. Seattle's tree loss has resulted in an
estimated additional 11.5 million cubic feet of stormwater runoff
during a peak storm. The cost of containing and managing that
runoff is a minimum of $23 million, the group says.
</P>
<P>
   The lost tree canopy also would have removed 159,000 pounds of
air pollutants from the atmosphere each year.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting in Seattle this week, American Forests also called for a
nationwide initiative to combat sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Its message is simple: Plant more trees, maintain existing ones
and uproot fewer trees.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's tree shortage is not unique. According to American
Forests' survey of other urban areas, cities across the nation have
lost about one-third of their canopy in the last quarter century,
much of it to suburban sprawl and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trees are very important to the quality of life of a
community,'' said Deborah Gangloff, executive director of American
Forests.
</P>
<P>
   She and others extolled the many benefits of trees, including
soaking up harmful gases that contribute to the greenhouse effect,
decreasing surface erosion, providing shade cover and keeping a
city's average temperature lower. The conference kicked off a round
of tree-planting fervor. King County Executive Ron Sims is expected
to announce Wednesday that the county is creating a public-private
initiative to plant 200,000 trees next year along the Interstate 90
Mountain to Sound Greenway.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Eddie Bauer employees planted trees in the shadow of
the Space Needle at the Seattle Center. For the last three years,
the Seattle-based clothing company has supported American Forests'
Global ReLeaf program, which aims to plant 20 million trees around
the world by next year. The company encourages donations of $1 or
more from customers and so far has raised enough money to plant 2.5
million trees.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Seattle has set its own goals for tree planting.
Mayor Paul Schell has called for planting 20,000 trees by Earth Day
2000. So far, about one-quarter of that has been planted. The
effort is expected to cost $2 million, with half the money coming
from private donations and corporate support.
</P>
<P>
   The last major tree spree in Seattle came in the early 1970s
when the ambitious voter-funded public works program Forward Thrust
led to a wave of plantings, said Shane Dewald, city landscape
architect.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Seattle's tall, leafy canopy dates back decades.
During the Great Depression, the Civilian Conservation Corps
planted trees across the city, said Paul West, the city's senior
urban forester.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to know for sure, but the city estimates that on
land it controls, there are more than 1.4 million trees.
</P>
<P>
   The various tree planting campaigns come at a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an aging urban forest,'' West said. ``Right now we're
losing a lot of trees that were planted at the turn of the
century.''
</P>
<P>
   While West said the average life span of a tree in a harsh urban
environment is just 10 years, many of Seattle's declining trees are
between 75 and 100 years old.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the city's concerted effort to thicken the
urban forest canopy includes free trees for residents to plant
along street rights of way and discounts for anyone wishing to
plant a tree from participating nurseries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really hope people call and tell us where the trees are
needed, because we've got them,'' said Duane Pentilla, the city's
park horticulturalist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
