<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-FASSEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 CANDLES AND GRIPES FOR FASSEL TO PONDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The birthday cake was brought onto the
field as the New York Giants' practice was ending. The cake was
four feet long, a couple of feet wide, so big that it took two team
employees to carry it on a wooden folding table.
</P>
<P>
   A script of icing across the top of the cake in Giants blue
feted coach Jim Fassel, who turned 50 years old Tuesday. The cake
was in place by the time practice had ended, but Fassel did not see
it. He was too busy chewing out the very players who were about to
surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel stood with his back to the cake, his team in a semicircle
in front of him. The coach's post-practice address is usually no
more than a few seconds. Tuesday, it was a three- to four-minute
harangue.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel lectured his players, raising his voice as he gestured
with both hands. He pointed fingers as he turned from side to side,
his face getting redder as he scolded them for what he considered a
careless, lazy practice on the heels of a disappointing performance
Saturday against the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   When Fassel was finished, he turned to leave the field and still
had not acknowledged the cake's presence when defensive end Michael
Strahan gathered a group of teammates and called Fassel toward the
cake and table.
</P>
<P>
   ``You made it all the way to 50,'' Strahan said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Jessie Armstead added, ``Man, that's old.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel cracked the thinnest of smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to pick the thing up and hit somebody in the
face,'' Fassel said, nodding his head at the cake.
</P>
<P>
   That drew laughter from his players, although they did not
linger around the cake or their coach. As they walked away, Fassel
asked: ``We're going to eat that in the locker room, right? OK,
thanks, guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The cake was taken inside Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was comic, and Fassel knew so. But he was not
distracted for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy,'' he said. ``And it's not because I turned
50.''
</P>
<P>
   His players seemed to understand. No one was chuckling as the
cake was positioned behind Fassel's back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Fassel thought we weren't taking practice seriously
enough; you know maybe because we weren't in training camp
anymore,'' Armstead said. ``But just because camp is over, it
doesn't mean the work stops. He reminded us how much work we had
left to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel's post-practice message got through to several Giants,
especially when Fassel told reporters that he was looking at
personnel choices in a few areas, including free safety, where
Percy Ellsworth is the starter.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth has been the starter at free safety since the
preseason began. There was supposed to be a competition at the spot
with Shaun Williams, the team's 1998 first-round pick. But the
competition never materialized as Ellsworth took virtually all the
snaps with the first-string defense while Williams was with the
second-stringers.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth, however, did not have a good game against the Jets.
He was one of two Giants who missed an open-field opportunity to
tackle Curtis Martin near the beginning of his 80-yard touchdown
run.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel may simply be trying to motivate Ellsworth, whose
strength is pass coverage not run support, by threatening his job.
Or Fassel may be beginning to yield to the pressure to play a
first-round pick like Williams somewhere other than in nickel
packages.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel would say only that he needed better play from Ellsworth
and that he planned to give Williams ample playing time at free
safety in Friday's final preseason game against the Baltimore
Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got some decisions to make,'' the coach said. ``And I'm
running out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said he was referring to the preseason schedule, not his
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, 50 isn't old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   _ JESSIE ARMSTEAD responded to comments by KEYSHAWN JOHNSON, who
criticized Armstead in a published report Tuesday. Armstead was
involved in a scuffle with VINNY TESTAVERDE in Saturday's Jets
victory. ``Don't talk to the media about me; talk to me about me,''
Armstead said. ``You got something to say, be a man about it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BRANDON SANDERS, waived by Cleveland last week, signed with
the Giants on Tuesday, vying for the fourth safety spot. He would
be used primarily as a special teams player.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHAEL STRAHAN did not practice because of a slightly
strained groin muscle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Giants continued to look for a long snapper on punts since
LANCE SCOTT, the long snapper for the last two years, has a torn
knee ligament. Tight end PETE MITCHELL is the player the team would
like to do the job _ and he probably will _ but the last time he
did regular duty as a long snapper was in college five years ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
