<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6724 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-INSURANCE-SPI &LR;      09-01 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER MAJOR INSURER PULLS OUT OF INDIVIDUAL COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regence Blue Shield of Washington, precipitating a crisis in
health insurance for individuals in Washington state, on Wednesday
will stop offering new policies to people who aren't covered by a
group plan, the company said. The action leaves 25 counties in
Washington with no major private insurer willing to take on
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   And Group Health, the only insurer among major companies still
offering such coverage and under pressure to get out, will announce
on Wednesday whether it, too, will stop selling policies to
individuals. That would leave just eight Washington counties in
which individuals can buy insurance.
</P>
<P>
   State Insurance Commissioner Deborah Senn responded by opening a
special ``high-risk pool,'' effective Wednesday, in counties with
no individual market. The premiums, however, are 50 percent above
the individual-market price.
</P>
<P>
   Regence's pullout follows the lead taken last November by
Premera Blue Cross, which was then the largest insurer in the
individual market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual market is broken,'' said Rich Nelson, Regence
chief executive. ``Regence Blue Shield can only participate in the
market if it is reformed to accommodate sound insurance principles
that we know will stabilize the market for members and carriers.''
</P>
<P>
   Regence will continue to serve its 65,000 customers with
individual health policies. But from now on it will sell insurance
only to people who are members of groups, such as the employees of
a company.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in insurance began in 1993 when the Legislature
passed insurance reform that required companies to sell policies to
all applicants _ sick or healthy _ at standard rates. The same
reforms also mandated that insurers cover pre-existing conditions
after only three months _ the shortest term in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms might have worked had the Legislature not repealed a
part of the law that required all individuals to have insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies complained that people would get sick, or
pregnant, and join a plan when they needed health care, then quit
when they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Regence was the largest remaining provider to the individual
market.
</P>
<P>
   The company made a profit of $13 million on $1.126 billion in
revenues last year. That's about a penny on the dollar. It has been
losing about $6 million a year on individual plans, despite
double-digit rate increases over the past several years. It expects
to lose $6.6 million this year even assuming a 28 percent rate
increase, which has been turned down by Commissioner Senn.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Vice President John Carlson said Regence is not pulling
out because Senn disallowed the rate increase. It still wants that
rate increase for existing customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's pulling out, he said, because of the prospect of a wave of
new applicants from the state's unsubsidized Basic Health Plan. The
state announced last week that the Basic Health Plan for the
non-poor would take no new applicants after Jan. 1, and that four
of the nine carriers (not including Regence) will drop their
existing enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Regence said, the seizure by the state of Kitsap
Physicians Service, which the state says may now be insolvent,
creates the potential that KPS's individual enrollees will flee to
Regence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already getting 1,700 applications a month,'' Carlson
said. ``When you've got a line of business that continually erodes
and erodes, you've got to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Scott, president of the only other major provider in the
market, Group Health, met with the cooperative's trustees on
Tuesday night, and is expected to announce Wednesday morning
whether the insurance carrier will continue to sell individual
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said Group Health should break even this year after being
in the red for the past two years. The individual plans have been
losing money.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Group Health, Regence's exit leaves only small
players in the individual market, including KPS in Kitsap, Mason
and Jefferson counties, Northwest Medical Bureau in Whatcom and
Skagit counties, and a handful of out-of-state companies selling
without fanfare. One of these is the Midwest National Life, whose
Bellevue, Wash., agent, Frank Miller, is still offering
non-managed-care coverage that includes maternity.
</P>
<P>
   These bit players, the remnants of a market that once included
more than 50 companies, don't show on the radar of the big players
or the state. Senn announced recently the opening of the Washington
State Health Insurance Pool to all individual applicants in 15
Eastern Washington counties, which she said had no individual
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   That order, to be effective Wednesday, immediately expands to 25
counties _ and maybe more, depending on what Group Health decides _
and effectively replaces the private market with coverage mandated
by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The pool she is opening is the old ``high-risk pool,''
subsidized by all carriers, which allows anyone rejected for
insurance to buy coverage (and non-managed care, at that) at 50
percent above normal rates. It has been dormant since the early
1990s because no one has been rejected for insurance. But Senn
decided that not having coverage for sale amounted to the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a reason to panic,'' said her chief deputy,
Robert Harkins. ``This is not about people losing coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance people have been forecasting a death spiral in the
individual market since the reforms of 1993 and 1995, which ended
the companies' right to screen applicants and required coverage of
pre-existing conditions within three months.
</P>
<P>
   The result, they say, is that sick people signed up and healthy
people dropped out. ``It's like allowing someone to purchase fire
insurance when the flames are going through the roof of their
house,'' Carlson said. ``And that isn't fair to people who keep
coverage all year around.''
</P>
<P>
   To stem losses, carriers have cut back individual plans. The two
plans Regence is now closing do not cover childbirth, and cap drug
benefits at $500 a year. Group plans, which are much more difficult
to jump into when you need care and out of when you don't, offer
much richer benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Senn has defended the 1993 reforms as a way to let sick people
get coverage. She has argued that the insurance industry was
unnecessarily alarmist, and that the problems that did exist could
have been avoided if the 1993 reforms had put individuals and
groups into one pool.
</P>
<P>
   Senn met with top executives of Regence, Premera, Group Health
and three other companies Aug. 10, and said in a statement that
progress had been made. ``We're really confident that we can get
things done,'' said her deputy, Harkins, who added that timing of
Regence's announcement was unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to seek ways to expand or open access, preserve the
principles of the 1993 reforms and give carriers enough
protection,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McCulloch, a past candidate for insurance commissioner and
one who had predicted a collapse of the individual market, said,
``The situation won't improve until the Legislature and the
insurance commissioner recognize reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Carriers have repeatedly gone to the Legislature and asked for
the 3-month rule to be changed. Last year they met with Gov. Gary
Locke and cut a deal that would have lengthened the three months
limit on pre-existing conditions and allowed for a limited
screening of applicants. Despite an intense lobbying effort by
Locke, the measure narrowly passed the Senate but died in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is precisely what we worried about last winter,'' said
Locke in a prepared statement. He said he hoped legislators,
insurers and consumers would ``come together to reach agreement on
a proposal to stabilize the individual market.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eileen Cody, D-Seattle and co-chair of the House Health
Care Committee, said Regence's move might provide the critical mass
needed to pass a bill in the next session. ``We won't see the same
bill go forward, but we'll probably revisit some of the same
issues,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
