<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA'S STAR KEEPS RISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ After most of the games he pitches _ and all of the
good ones _ Freddy Garcia calls his agent, Peter Greenberg, to tell
him how everything went. Monday night, after he beat the Chicago
White Sox to raise his record to 14-7, Garcia left this message on
Greenberg's voice mail:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell Omar I'm one up on him now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire are locked into baseball's
highest-profile duel. But Garcia and Omar Daal, an Arizona
Diamondbacks left-hander, are in a race of their own.
</P>
<P>
   With his 14th victory, Garcia pulled one ahead of Daal as the
two pursue Wilson Alvarez's single-season record for wins by a
Venezuelan pitcher. Alvarez, who now pitches for the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays, won 15 games for the White Sox in 1993 and '96.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up outside Caracas, Garcia knew of Alvarez but did not
idolize him. He related more to Roger Clemens, a power right-hander
like Garcia would become.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good, but he's a lefty,'' Garcia said of Alvarez. ``I'm a
right-hander, so I look at right-handed pitching. I like how
Clemens pitches, and I liked watching him pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia worked only 51/3 innings Monday, with manager Lou
Piniella removing him over concerns that Garcia's previous outing,
a 139-pitch shutout, had tired him. Garcia said he was not tired,
just missing with his location, and his numbers have stayed strong
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Since the All-Star break, Garcia has gone 5-2 with a 2.67 earned
run average. He has brought his season ERA down nearly a full run,
to 4.21, and is among the top 10 in the American League in wins,
opponents' average against (.256) and strikeouts (135).
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers should put him in the mix for the AL Rookie of the
Year award, with Texas pitcher Jeff Zimmerman and Kansas City
outfielder Carlos Beltran. With few pitchers distinguishing
themselves in the AL this year, Garcia could even merit
consideration for second- or third-place Cy Young votes if he
finishes strong.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will try to be cautious with Garcia in September,
but he has yet to reach his professional high in innings pitched.
Garcia threw 179 innings in Class A ball in 1997, then pitched
between 40 and 50 innings of winter ball in Venezuela. He will not
pitch winter ball after this season.
</P>
<P>
   He should stay busy, however; Garcia is expecting a warm
reception at home this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, but I have a feeling it's going to be
different,'' he said. ``I was playing in double-A and triple-A last
year, and now I'm in the majors all year. There's not many of us.''
</P>
<P>
   But his countrymen who are in the majors are doing well. In
addition to strong seasons by Garcia and Daal, Edgardo Alfonzo and
Roger Cedeno have stood out for the New York Mets and the
Philadelphia Phillies' Bobby Abreu is second in the National League
batting race.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg represents all of those players. Last winter, he and
Abreu turned down a four-year, $8.3 million contract offer that
would have bought out the outfielder's arbitration years. Because
of issues regarding service time, Garcia's case is somewhat
different, Greenberg said. The Mariners have not approached him
about a long-term deal _ they have several more pressing matters _
but something could happen this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if they want to do something long
term, with the year Freddy's having,'' Greenberg said. ``But it's
their call. If they want to do year-to-year (contracts), that's the
route we'll take. If they're interested in something multiyear,
we're certainly willing to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Garcia, ``I have to finish strong, and we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA BASES: Outfielder Charles Gipson and first baseman Mike
Blowers will be recalled from Class AAA Tacoma and join the M's
today. Several pitchers will be activated during the team's
upcoming homestand, including Brett Hinchliffe, Steve Sinclair and
Butch Henry. Outfielder Shane Monahan appears to be the only other
position player who may be called up. ... Center fielder Ken
Griffey Jr. held onto eighth place among outfielders in the latest
balloting results for baseball's All-Century Team. Griffey has
received 374,962 votes, the most of the eight active players on the
ballot. ... The Mariners are now the only team in baseball to hit
200 home runs in four consecutive seasons. They have 206 this
season, after collecting 245 in 1996, 264 in '97 and 234 last year.
Only three other clubs have ever hit 200 homers in any four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
