<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING PACT, IF APPROVED, WILL HAVE FAR-REACHING EFFECT IN
INDUSTRY, LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Boeing's choice of compromise over conflict in its
attempt to win approval of its largest labor contract will embolden
unions within the company, across the nation and at rival Airbus
Industrie, according to labor analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Machinists union will vote Wednesday on a
contract hammered out early Saturday when the company dropped
demands for a longer workweek and higher payments for health care,
while offering competitive raises and a 10 percent bonus. The deal
was designed, in part, to keep production lines open at the
Seattle-based aerospace company.
</P>
<P>
   But the contract with members of the International Association
of Machinists will have a broader impact. The company's concessions
will encourage other unions to make similar demands when they
hammer out future agreements, according to labor scholars. That's
because the Boeing contract, which covers 44,000 workers, serves as
a bellwether for the industrial labor movement, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a large sense it really energizes the labor movement,''
said Harley Shaiken, a professor of labor relations at the
University of California at Berkeley. The union ``won gains in the
areas of wages, pensions and job security (and) these are all hotly
contested questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor movement takes some of its cues from Boeing because
the issues the company and the union fought over mirror battles
occurring throughout the U.S. manufacturing and aerospace
industries.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Boeing backed away from its demand that Machinists
should pay a portion of their health care premiums in the future.
That move will bolster organized labor's opposition to similar
corporate demands, according to Richard Bank, the director of the
Center for Collective Bargaining at the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company abandoned its push for a seven-day
workweek that would run 24 hours a day, an initiative other
companies are weighing. Throughout the negotiations the union
argued the idea would disrupt the family lives of its members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you are going to see more and more unions...are going
to draw the line on quality of life issues,'' said Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Companies also may find their workers are seeking bigger
bonuses. Boeing offered its Machinists lump-sum payments in 1999
that will average $4,400 for each worker covered by the contract.
</P>
<P>
   That ``creates expectations in other sectors, that (you have)
got to have a bonus system in place,'' said David Olson, a
political science professor at the University of Washington in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The contract offer also threatens to reach across the Atlantic
to Boeing's rival Airbus Industrie. That's because workers at the
Toulouse, France-based airplane consortium are likely watching the
negotiations, said Olson. Since Boeing workers are perceived to
have won some concessions from their boss, Airbus employees
probably are expecting a boost in their next contract, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus officials rejected the idea that contracts at Boeing and
Airbus are linked.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, ``I don't think there has been much correlation
between Boeing contracts and Airbus contracts,'' said David Venz,
chief spokesman in North America for Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus would stand to reap potentially huge benefits if Boeing
couldn't settle the contract and its Machinists struck. A strike
would hurt Boeing while it's locked in an intense bidding war with
Airbus for new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big losers are Airbus'' stakeholders, said Olson.
</P>
<P>
   The contract also will ripple through other collective
bargaining units at Boeing, raising expectations for workers.
Officials at the Seattle Professional Engineering Employees
Association, who will negotiate a contract for 24,000 Boeing
workers this fall, say they're already heartened by Boeing's offer
to Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials caution that the company's latest offer won't
dictate the terms of other agreements, even though it will serve as
a reference point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be looked at (but) it doesn't automatically translate
into a rubber stamp everywhere,'' said Peter Conte, the chief
spokesman for Boeing during the contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing hasn't eliminated its biggest labor headache yet.
Machinists will travel to their union halls in Seattle, Everett,
Auburn, Renton, Spokane, Portland, Ore., and Wichita, Kan.,
Wednesday to vote to either ratify or reject the contract.
</P>
<P>
   If they reject the proposal, and two-thirds of those voting
support a strike, they could be on the picket lines Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Many Machinists, however, have welcomed the offer, including the
competitive wage package, the absence of new health care bills and
the preservation of the traditional workweek. The response has left
union leaders optimistic about the outcome of Wednesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel they will ratify what may be one of the best contracts
in the aerospace industry,'' said Bill Johnson, the president of
the International Association of Machinists' District Lodge 751 in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some workers are upset, saying the package doesn't offer
a big enough jump in pension benefits and falls short in other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and the union will know the fate of their agreement at
roughly 9 Wedneday night, when the union plans to announce the
results of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   If workers ratify the contract it will represent another step
toward improving the often turbulent relationship between Boeing
and its most potent union, the Machinists. The union has struck
during two of the last three labor negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it ... indicates the importance to companies like
Boeing that maintaining harmonious labor relationships is important
over the long'' term, said Robert Scott, an international economist
at the Economic Policy Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Local companies should also take note if Boeing and its largest
union strike a compromise Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very hot labor market and labor exercised
considerable strength,'' said the University of Washington's Olson.
``Other firms similarly situated not only have to take labor
negotiations seriously, they have to learn from past mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
