<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6729 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-SHROUT-LADN     09-01 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SHROUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWAII PUNTER BACK ON HIS FEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hawaii punter Chad Shrout dreaded going to
practice last season, knowing it was only a matter of time before
the screaming started.
</P>
<P>
   If the former Antelope Valley High star's punt didn't end up
exactly where former coach Fred vonAppen instructed Shrout to place
the ball, he heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were guaranteed to get yelled at every day,'' Shrout said.
``If the kick didn't go to a certain spot, you got yelled at. It
put a lot of pressure on me.I didn't get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The stress showed on Shrout's punting statistics. In 1997, he
had the nation's fifth-best average (46.1 yards) and was named a
first-team All-WAC selection.
</P>
<P>
   But last season, Shrout's average fell to 38.7 yards per kick
while vonAppen tried to change his style to a more ``directional
philosophy,'' instead of just kicking the ball as far as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It threw off my punting,'' Shrout said. ``I don't think I was
mentally prepared for that. I had a bad season.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that Shrout was also forced to do Hawaii's
placekicking, something he had never tried in college. He made just
seven of 15 field goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird,'' Shrout said. ``It's faster, and a lot more
pressure than kicking in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrout's problems from last season concern new Hawaii coach June
Jones enough that he said Tuesday he wanted to get his punter
``over the hump mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a high priority for Jones, because Shrout is one of the few
established players on a team that has lost 18 straight games
heading into Saturday night's game against USC at Aloha Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went through a very difficult season last year and he's one
of the guys we're trying to pull through,'' Jones said. ``We're
hoping he comes through. He has a big-time leg. I'm hoping he can
pull himself through the mental situation he was in last season.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jones knew what Shrout has been through the past three years,
he might not doubt the punter's resiliency.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, on the eve of Hawaii's season opener against
Boston College, Shrout received word that his mother, Terry, had a
heart attack. Chad immediately boarded a plane back to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Shrout underwent triple bypass surgery, but died three
weeks later. Her loss left Chad, who was adopted, without any
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the hardest thing I've had to face in my life,'' Shrout
said. ``I had to take care of the funeral arrangements. I had to
take care of a lot of business. I learned so much at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrout decided to take the fall semester off in order to remain
close to his grandmother and 12-year-old brother, who was also
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``After something like that happens, the thought goes through my
mind. `Do I want to be that far from my brother and grandmother?'
'' Shrout said. ``I wanted to be with my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrout returned for the '97 season and had the best year of his
career. Through it all, his thoughts have never strayed far from
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep her in my heart and mind all of the time,'' Shrout
said. ``I think of her all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even during the toughest times under vonAppen, Shrout's memories
of his mother helped pull him through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to credit my mom,'' Shrout said. ``She taught me
everything I would need to know. She taught me how to be
responsible. How to be an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrout is optimistic he can regain his '97 form, now that the
player-friendly Jones has been hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaching change is absolutely fabulous,'' Shrout said.
``They teach football. They know what they are doing. The tempo is
higher, everyone is into practice. Everyone has taken to it. It's
just nice having a coach who can believe in us. These coaches are
bringing fun back into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Shrout does this season, he will have surprised
some doubters. He did not have a single scholarship offer during
his senior season at Antelope Valley, when he got a random call
from Hawaii offering a plane ticket and campus visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 48 hours in Hawaii, I loved every minute of it,'' Shrout
said. ``I hadn't had any other offers. It made the decision easy. I
don't have any idea what I would have done otherwise. I probably
would have gone to Antelope Valley College.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrout has certainly made a name for himself at Hawaii. USC
knows enough about him that he's actually become part of their
scouting package on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a very good punter who's been there for four
years,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``He won't get rattled or
intimidated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
