<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SMOTHER WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In the clubhouse before games, Alex Rodriguez wears a
T-shirt commemorating Mark McGwire's record 70 home runs last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Since he's in Chicago, he might want to shop for an Ernie Banks
shirt. It is Banks, the Chicago Cubs Hall of Famer, whose home run
record Rodriguez might break.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners shortstop clubbed his 34th and 35th home runs
Tuesday night as the Mariners buried the White Sox, 11-4, at
Comiskey Park. Raul Ibanez and Tom Lampkin also homered to support
John Halama, who worked seven innings for the win.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez finished August with 11 home runs. He hit 12 in July,
and leads the American League in home run ratio, going deep every
11.1 at-bats. The all-time record for home runs by a shortstop
belongs to Banks, who hit 47 in 1958. Despite missing 32 games to
an early season knee injury, Rodriguez is within reach of the
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I've learned in baseball is anything's possible,''
Rodriguez said. ``It would be incredible to do that in a season
when I missed six weeks. But I have other kinds of goals at this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   A win tonight would put the Mariners over .500 for the first
time since July 6, and would be their first step toward the goal of
making the playoffs. But if a run never develops, the home run
heroics will still be there _ and not just from Ken Griffey Jr.,
whose swing was recently voted the ``sweetest'' in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did that thing on ESPN about the sweetest swing, and Alex
was the only right-handed hitter on that list,'' hitting coach
Jesse Barfield said. ``That says a lot. He has the best
right-handed swing I've seen in a long time. A left-hander can get
away with a slight uppercut, but with all the right-handed pitching
out there, right-handers have to have a level swing. Alex's swing
is picture perfect. That is a swing you want to teach kids right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez homered to right and left field Tuesday night,
connecting off John Snyder the opposite way in the third inning to
give the M's a 3-2 lead, and taking Jaime Navarro into the
left-field bleachers in the sixth to put the Mariners ahead 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've hit one like that in a long time,''
Rodriguez said of the second home run, which traveled 419 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The first homer gave Rodriguez and second baseman David Bell 50
for the season, making them the eighth middle-infield pair to reach
that mark. For all of Rodriguez's power, his all-around game stands
out most to Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting home runs is just one of the many things he does,''
Bell said. ``It's a big thing, but there are guys that are going to
hit as many home runs as Alex. But no one does everything as well
as Alex does. That's what impresses me most about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Also impressive: Rodriguez's two-homer night came at Comiskey,
where he owned a .176 average and just three home runs before
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``History shows I haven't hit the long ball at this park, but
after playing at Safeco Field for a month and a half, I have no
complaints about playing anywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lead that resulted from his first home run did not last
long. The White Sox tied it at 3-3 in their half of the third on an
unusual two-out rally. After Darrin Jackson singled and Frank
Thomas walked, Halama (11-5) got Magglio Ordonez to hit a
comebacker. But the ball skipped lower than Halama expected, and it
ricocheted off his left heel for a single. Jackson, who homered in
the first, then scored on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last time the M's had to worry. They knocked out
Snyder with a five-run barrage in the fourth, culminating in a
three-run homer to left by Ibanez. It was first baseman's fifth
homer of the year his first the opposite way.
</P>
<P>
   The M's did not take batting practice for the fifth day in a row
yesterday, but of those who did practice, Barfield said, Ibanez
stayed the longest, perfecting his stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a lot of extra swings,'' Barfield said. ``He wants to
maintain and keep the feel of everything he's been working on.''
</P>
<P>
   After suffering a miserable month and a half since the All-Star
break, Ibanez has homered in two of his past four games, and also
had a three-hit day. He has closed his stance more, and the results
showed on the homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hit an opposite-field home run, at least for me, it
tells you that you're doing something right at the plate,'' Ibanez
said. ``You're staying in there and things are going to start going
well.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
