<HEADLINE>
GALAXY LIKES ITS CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Now that the Galaxy has been eliminated from the
U.S. Open Cup and Las Vegas' CONCACAF Champions Cup, it can focus
on the one trophy that matters anyway -- the MLS championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy (15-9, 39 points) blew a chance to share the Western
Conference lead with Colorado (16-8, 42 points) following
Saturday's 1-0 loss to Dallas, but it can share the conference lead
tonight with a three-point victory over San Jose (14-10, 22 points)
when the two teams meet at the Rose Bowl beginning at 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A loss, and the Galaxy could find itself in fourth place before
the weekend is through, with Chicago and Dallas making a run at the
conference title as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're exactly where we wanted to be,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi
Schmid. ``Did I think we would be this close to them (Colorado) at
this point? Not really. When you look at it now, we've got 30
points in our last 13 games which is pretty good. Whenever you
average nearly 2{ points a game, you're doing pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Cup loss to Columbus followed by a CONCACAF qualifying
loss to Necaxa earlier this month cleared up Los Angeles schedule.
If they were still alive in both, they would have had the U.S. Cup
championship scheduled for Sept. 14, followed by the CONCACAF
Champions Cup, held Sept. 28 through Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Eight teams, including Chicago and D.C. United are participating
in the Las Vegas tournament, which could mean three or four games
in a week span, just before the MLS playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would rather be in Vegas and participating in the U.S. Cup,
but now that we're not, it makes the MLS championship that much
more important to us,'' said Schmid. ``Chicago and D.C. are two
quality teams that will be there and maybe they will be distracted
with that competition. They will go through a series of a lot of
games in a few days. I think the plus side is that it gives us more
of a chance to focus and be in a position to make a better run at
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Clint Mathis may return to action tonight -- three
weeks after injuring his left knee in a friendly with Guadalajara
Chivas, Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis had cartilage surgery two days after the injury and has
been training without a brace the past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels normal,'' said Mathis. ``I just have to work on my
fitness. I have a little soreness after practice but that's
intended after surgery. I have no problem cutting or doing anything
unplanned. I've taken a couple hits, but it's no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis had started to emerge before his injury, becoming the
team's second leading scorer (seven goals, two assists, 16 points)
in 19 games. Four of those goals came in his last five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just worked extremely hard to get back because I can't
stand to sit here and watch,'' Mathis said. ``I love what I'm
doing, that's why I've busted my butt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLASH-GALAXY
</P>
<P>
   Today's game: San Jose (14-10, 22 points) vs. Galaxy (15-9, 39
points), Rose Bowl, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: None; KTCD 1540-AM, KTNQ 1020-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Series: Galaxy leads 2-1 and 11-4 all-time.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy update: The Western Conference playoff seeds are nearly
finalized with Colorado, Dallas, Chicago and the Galaxy fighting
for playoff positioning. All four teams are within four points of
each other, with Colorado (42 points) holding a slight edge over
Chicago (40 points), Los Angeles (39 points) and Dallas (38
points). Both Ezra Hendrickson and Clint Mathis, who missed
Saturday's 1-0 loss at Dallas because of injuries are probable
tonight. The Galaxy is hoping striker Cobi Jones starts to find the
net soon. With eight games remaining in the season, Jones has only
four goals compared to the 19 he scored a year ago. And last year
he missed over a month of the regular season because of the World
Cup in France.
</P>
<P>
   Clash update: San Jose's record (14-10) is deceiving because 10
of its 14 victories have come through the dreaded shootout. It has
left San Jose with only 22 points, 16 behind fourth place Dallas,
who also has 14 victories. San Jose would need a miracle to clinch
a playoff spot in its final eight games but they have shown
improvement with three consecutive victories to move four games
over .500 for the first time in club history. Striker Ronald
Cerritos leads the Clash, tallying 11 goals and five assists this
season.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fred J. Robledo &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
