<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6732 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS &LR;      09-01 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALOU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Not many players suffer two season-ending injuries in the same
year. Then again, 1999 has been anything but normal for Astros
outfielder Moises Alou, who officially is out for the season after
his second freak injury in a seven-month period.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alou's recovery from knee surgery was derailed over the weekend
when he fell off a bicycle and landed on his injured left knee.
Alou suffered swelling around his knee and had fluid drained from
the area.
</P>
<P>
   MRI results revealed no structural damage to the anterior
cruciate ligament, which was torn prior to spring training when
Alou fell off a treadmill. He underwent successful arthroscopic
surgery shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the Astros said Alou likely would be out for the
season after the treadmill incident. But as he progressed through
rehabilitation, Sept. 1 became a target date for his return.
</P>
<P>
   The timetable was amended to mid-September after the 33-year-old
outfielder suffered a setback while the Astros were in San Diego at
the end of July. This latest incident kills any hope of Alou's
playing in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough couple of days,'' said Alou, who had 38
homers and 124 RBIs last season and finished third in National
League Most Valuable Player voting. ``I'm disappointed; my
teammates are disappointed; the fans are disappointed. It's very
frustrating to work this hard to come back and have it end this
way. I worked hard to come back, but unfortunately things didn't
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The bicycle incident occurred when the bike Alou was riding
accidentally hit his 3-year-old son, Percio, who suffered a minor
bruise on his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, my kid is OK,'' said Alou, who has a bruise on
his knee. ``Thank God for that. People are going to wonder why I
was riding a bike. But I have a family and kids who want to play
with their dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Riding a bicycle has been part of Alou's rehabilitation. He rode
for 10 miles with his therapist one week before the accident.
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker was only recently made aware
of the bike-riding, and the activity didn't exactly come with his
full endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riding a bike is part of his rehab, but it was probably poor
judgment on his part,'' Hunsicker said. ``Mo's intentions were good
_ spending time with his family and playing with his kids. It's
tough to find time to spend with your family in this business. But
to get on a bike and horse around with the kids didn't show very
good judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' outfield has been hit hard by injuries, with each
outfielder who started the season on the opening-day roster having
spent time on the disabled list at one point or another this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Alou was determined to return before the end of the season and
felt he still could make a contribution down the stretch and
possibly in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was going to come back next week,'' Alou said.
``I didn't want to say anything to jinx myself, but I guess I was
jinxed in another way. I feel like I let everyone down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was supposed to be out for the year, but I told those guys I
was going to try my best to come back, and that's what I did. My
teammates understand, and I'm glad they're behind me, and I hope
the front office is behind me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou's teammates were more concerned about his well-being than
another in a long line of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all feel bad for Mo,'' second baseman Craig Biggio said.
``The guy has been working his rear off to get back, and something
like this happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel worse for him than I do for the team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
