<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE PITCHES WELL, BUT THE A'S HIT BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Cone has admitted that the constant questions and doubts
about his right arm have bothered him, which means that the
questions and the doubts have really irritated him. Cone expects
the questions but lately he has felt like a lab rat. Poked and
prodded, dissected and discussed, Cone is the perfect-game pitcher
trying to validate himself all over again.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are destined to qualify for the post-season, and
they want and need Cone to be prepared. So they gave him six days
of rest before Tuesday night's start against the Athletics and
hoped that the stiffness and staleness that has infected his
performances over the past five weeks would finally vanish.
</P>
<P>
   For one night, they did. Using a sturdy fastball, a diving
slider and a nasty split-finger fastball, Cone pitched strongly
into the seventh inning as the A's eventually stopped the Yankees,
3-2, in 11 innings. Cone struck out 10 and was only damaged by a
two-pitch sequence in which he allowed back-to-back homers in the
fourth inning. Despite the aggravating defeat, the Yankees were
buoyed by Cone's revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Undeniably, the rest certainly helped,'' Cone said. ``It's
like somebody plugged my arm back into the light socket. It's the
most life I have had in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as much as Cone dominated Oakland, the very mortal Jimmy
Haynes also stymied the Yankees. Haynes had been battered for 32
earned runs in his last 16 and one-third innings while losing four
straight decisions, but he shocked the Yankees by merely
surrendering Paul O'Neill's two-run homer over seven innings. Doug
Jones followed with three shaky yet scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   That was why the A's managed to prevail on Rich Becker's
two-out, pinch-hit single off Ramiro Mendoza in the 11th. The
left-handed hitting Becker smacked a slow grounder between first
and second that allowed John Jaha to lumber in from second.
Becker's single was the first hit by either team in 14 at-bats with
men in scoring position and helped end New York's four-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had chances to break the 2-2 tie that lasted for six
innings. The A's stranded 10 runners from the sixth through the
ninth while the Yankees went zero for nine with runners in scoring
position and had the bases loaded and one out and failed to score
off Jason Isringhausen in the 11th. Luis Sojo blasted a bullet off
the right-field fence that looked like it might be a game winner,
but it was foul by about two feet. He then grounded out to end the
game
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, I was about to jump,'' Sojo said. ``No luck
today.'' It was no shock that Manager Joe Torre gave Cone
additional rest. In 12 starts with four days of rest, Cone is 3-3
with a 4.40 ERA. But in 14 starts in which he has received more
than four days off, the 36-year-old is 8-4 with a 2.01. Torre said
that Cone would start again on six days' rest next Tuesday as he
juggles the other starters. Torre also hinted that Cone would start
Game 3 of the division series because he could not pitch twice in a
five-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very curious about tonight and very pleased with the
outcome,'' Torre said. ``Not the outcome of the game. The outcome
of his performance.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a crucial start for Cone, who had to prove his arm was
not weary and that he could still be an asset during the
post-season. Cone was hesitating more than usual with his windup
and whiffed three of the first five batters. He wriggled through a
bases-loaded jam in the second and knew that it would not be a
repeat of last Tuesday's massacre in which Texas trampled him for
six runs in one and two-thirds innings. Seven of Cone's 10
strikeouts were swinging strikes, evidence that Cone's pitches were
jumping.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter singled in the third, and O'Neill's first homer
since Aug. 6 gave the Yankees a 2-0 bulge. Cone could not maintain
the lead for one inning. After Stairs worked the count to 3-2, Cone
tried to pump a fastball by him and Stairs drilled the high pitch
over the center-field fence for his 31st homer.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the homer unnerved Cone as he grooved the next fastball
to Olmedo Saenz, and Saenz belted it into the right-field bleachers
to even the score, 2-2. Cone stood in front of the mound after the
second homer on his second fastball, holding his glove above his
head and waiting for a new ball. ``Both fastballs, both crushed,''
Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back homers were distressing, but Cone rebounded to
strike out Ben Grieve and Miguel Tejada. He stranded two in the
sixth and needed Mike Stanton to get the final out in the seventh
to strand three more A's. Cone gave up two homers and the Yankees
lost, but the evening was about the bigger post-season picture and
about Cone feeling like himself again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was a big confidence builder,'' Cone said. ``For
nothing else, I had a lot of life in my arm again. I know Joe and
Mel are going to take care of me and I'm going to get the rest. I
feel good about that.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   DAVID CONE, who struck out 10 or more for the 58th time in his
career, is 1-3 with a 4.09 ERA since his perfect game. ... SCOTT
BROSIUS is home in Oregon with his gravely sick father and might
join the team Friday in Anaheim.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
