<SLUG> BC-CRASHES-DECLINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATAL CRASHES DECLINE AS DRIVERS GET CAUTIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Mirroring a statewide and national trend, fatal
traffic crashes in Los Angeles have declined significantly, despite
growing population and longer commutes, authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic deaths last year dropped to 1950s levels in California
and in Los Angeles County, which is the state's busiest county when
it comes to the number of drivers and miles driven.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities attributed the trend to safer cars and trucks,
improved driver awareness, better life-saving techniques and less
driving under the influence of alcohol. They also noted that baby
boom drivers are becoming more conservative behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of safer cars, seat-belt laws, air bags and
child seats, and the doctors are doing their magic. If you're a
responsible driver, you will live to drive another day,'' said
California Highway Patrol Officer Bill Preciado.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the number of deaths, the number of fatal crashes
dipped by 5.4 percent statewide last year and by 16 percent
citywide for the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 3,459 people were killed on the state highways in
1998, down nearly 6 percent from the number in 1997, the CHP
reported. That traffic-death toll was the lowest since 1955, when
3,431 were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The county decline was even greater: down 18 percent from 764 in
1997 to 624 in 1998. Those statistics do not include the five San
Bernardino area teen-agers killed Sunday when their car plunged off
Angeles Crest Highway after an all-night ``rave'' party.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry officials said the decline in the number of
serious-injury crashes drove down insurance rates by nearly 3
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hartwig, vice president and chief economist for the
Insurance Information Institute in New York, said the decline in
serious injuries is reflected in auto insurance rates, which fell
by nearly 3 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In part, he attributes the decline to 30 percent of the drivers
on the road being in their safer driving years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers are moving into safer driving years. As people
age, they tend to be safer drivers,'' Hartwig said. ``There is
something good about getting older.''
</P>
<P>
   Car designs and doctors are also credited with saving lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you had an accident 10 years ago, you might have had a
fatal injury. Now, it may be moderate. The injuries are going
down,'' said Sgt. Bob Rieboldt of the LAPD's Traffic Coordination
Section.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the decline are drunk driving arrests and collisions in
which drinking drivers are involved, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking and driving isn't as in vogue as it used to be,''
said Det. R.S. Uber at the LAPD's Valley Traffic Division.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles last year, there were 1,587 collisions in which
at least one driver had been drinking, down nearly 4 percent from
1997, when there were 1,651. And drunk-driving arrests were down 7
percent last year in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very heartening,'' said Tina Pasco, executive director of
Mothers Against Drunk Driving.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that, when drunk driving declines, people might pay
less attention to the problem, and soon it creeps back to former
levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we don't keep the visibility and pressure on, we see the
stats go up,'' Pasco said. ``In a lot of ways, it's like having to
start all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrian deaths also are down _ nearly 11 percent statewide,
from 783 in 1997 to 698 in 1998, the CHP said.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, 33 pedestrians were killed from Jan. 1 through
July 31 this year, compared with 51 in the same period last year, a
35 percent decline, according to George Callandrillo, a management
assistant in the LAPD's Traffic Coordination Section.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a growing concern to be cautious out there. Motorists
are looking out for those pedestrians, even if they're not in the
crosswalk,'' Preciado said. ``Those tickets are getting expensive
too.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
