r a BC-SHERIFF-OUSTER-KAN &LR;      09-01 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHERIFF-OUSTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI'S ATTORNEY GENERAL TRIES TO OUST SHERIFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Attorney General Jay Nixon, saying inmates
of the Miller County jail are ``literally running the prison,''
moved Tuesday to oust the county's sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Thomas Russell personally and through his jailers let
prisoners keep drugs and knives, provided a jail trusty with drugs
and allowed jailers to trade privileges for money and sex, Nixon
charged in a court petition.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff even let inmates out of jail to attend the sheriff's
barbecue and allowed them to transport evidence for drug cases, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to restore public trust in the office of Miller
County sheriff is to remove the current officeholder,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Truesdale, an attorney for Russell, denied the attorney
general's charges and said voters should decide whether the sheriff
remains in office. He said Russell has no plans to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not involved in any way with criminal wrongdoing,''
Truesdale said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's action followed a nine-month investigation by state
officials and the FBI. Three former Miller County jailers and a
former jail trusty earlier pleaded guilty to criminal corruption
charges filed by Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Three others face charges in connection with the same
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Miller County is a mostly rural, agricultural area near the Lake
of the Ozarks, about 130 miles southeast of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Russell took office in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A judge in nearby Dallas County set Sept. 10 for the first
hearing to consider the attorney general's allegations. Attorneys
said the ouster petition was similar to a civil lawsuit. A judge
will decide whether Russell stays in office.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said he had not filed an ouster petition in his seven
years in office. He said such petitions were filed several times in
the 1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's petition contends that Russell ``has engaged in willful
and fraudulent violations of the laws of the state of Missouri and
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's petition said that since January 1997 the sheriff
personally or through the jailers he supervised allowed inmates to
keep drugs, knives and alcohol and to assault each other. He said
Russell made longtime friend and former inmate David Birdsong a
jail trusty and then let him leave jail to drive department
vehicles even though he was supposed to be incarcerated. The
vehicles had loaded shotguns in them, Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon also charged that Russell provided Birdsong with
methamphetamine and marijuana while he was under sentence. After
Birdsong was released, the petition said, Russell put him on the
Miller County payroll even though there was an outstanding warrant
for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The civil petition also contends Russell failed to segregate
inmates by sex. That led to sexual contact among inmates and
between inmates and jailers, the petition said. Nixon's court
papers also said that Russell twice solicited sexual contact in
exchange for carrying out his official duties.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said in several cases Russell failed to properly carry out
arrest warrants and allowed prisoners access to drug evidence at
the jail. All but nine of 42 items of evidence disappeared in one
episode, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said that in May 1998 Russell auctioned
surplus and unclaimed property, failed to deposit all the proceeds
in the county treasury and paid himself and other salaried
employees fees for the auction they were not entitled to.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon downplayed questions on why his office did not file
criminal charges against Russell. He said the investigation is not
over.
</P>
<P>
   But Truesdale, Russell's lawyer, said Nixon filed an ouster
petition because it required less evidence than criminal charges.
Truesdale also said many of the allegations against the sheriff are
based on accounts by people who are cooperating with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Gier, presiding commissioner of Miller County, said
officials and taxpayers had grown weary of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready for the court system to take over and let's get
the evidence presented,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
