<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6740 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BUSH-COCAINE-KAN &LR;      09-01 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-COCAINE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTERS, DETRACTORS FLIP-FLOP ON BUSH COCAINE ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Peppered with questions about his past, Gov. George
W. Bush is dancing a kind of Texas two-step.
</P>
<P>
   He'll talk about his marriage, and he'll talk about his
drinking, but when asked about his rumored use of cocaine when he
was younger, Bush declares, ``Enough is enough....''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, as governor of Texas, he supports harsher
penalties for small-time drug users.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential front-runner is not the only one who
wants to have it both ways. Supporters, detractors and the news
media, observers say, all appear to be skirting the lines of
hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are the most vulnerable. Suddenly, many in a party
that extolls family values and law and order, and that rails
against Bill Clinton's personal behavior, declare that if Bush ever
used illegal drugs it was just a ``youthful indiscretion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Rev. Jerry Falwell, who founded the Moral Majority, has
proclaimed: ``It's forgiven. It's forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   But not every Republican thinks it's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think conservatives and Republicans are now at great risk of
looking like total hypocrites,'' Bill Kristol, editor of The Weekly
Standard a conservative political magazine, said on ABC's ``This
Week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't say in 1992 that, `Oh, what Bill Clinton did in
his early 20s didn't matter. That letter to the draft board, he was
22 years old. Whether he smoked dope over in England.'''
</P>
<P>
   And while some of his rivals for the Republican nomination say
the debate should be on issues, they have all answered the question
about drug use with an unequivocal ``no.'' Some candidates, such as
Gary Bauer, add that while personal questions about a candidate's
marriage and family should be off limits, ``I just see a question
related to a felony to be in a different category.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, are generally staying on the sidelines,
happy just to watch Bush squirm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Republicans' culture war, not ours,'' said Jim
Jordan, political director of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee. ``We just have to cook up the popcorn and watch.''
</P>
<P>
   But few Democrats have objected to the persistent questioning of
Bush even though many cried foul about the investigations into the
president's private behavior.
</P>
<P>
   And the news media face their own set of questions. Critics,
including some members of the profession itself, say the press has
kept the story alive for months without producing a speck of
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, they point to the story earlier this year of an
Arkansas woman who claimed Clinton raped her 21 years ago and whose
account was supported by several witnesses. But the press quickly
lost interest.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, questions have been raised as to whether the
press could withstand the same kind of scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``A reasonable number of reporters were drug users in their
youth,'' said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School
for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania. ``Where does
the press get off making assumptions that it's hypocritical for
Bush and not hypocritical for them? There is no evidence that he
ever did it. In absence of that, what right do reporters have to be
pushing the question?''
</P>
<P>
   Political hypocrisy lies in the eye of the beholder. Politicians
often ``reassess'' their positions in light of new information,
sometime sincerely, sometimes for political purposes. Clinton has
been extraordinarily skillful in finessing earlier actions.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton, for instance, who admitted during the 1992
campaign that he tried marijuana while a student at Oxford
University in the 1960s, but said he had ``never broken the laws''
of the United States. He also said he never inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has lately been accused of offering his own ``Clintonian''
answers regarding drugs. After not answering the question for
months, he began to tailor his responses when it was posed a
different way.
</P>
<P>
   First he indicated that he could meet the standard FBI
background question of not having used drugs in the past seven
years. He amended it the next day to being able to meet the 15-year
test used at the time when his father's presidency began in 1989.
That would make the 53-year-old son of former President George Bush
drug-free since he was 28, but not before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest sin in politics is not imperfection, but a lack
of basic honesty,'' said Phil Noble, a Democratic consultant who
used to specialize in opposition research. ``People don't expect
anybody to be perfect, but they don't expect anybody to lie. What
Bush did way back when doesn't matter in most people's eyes. The
only thing that matters is if he isn't straight about it now, if he
waffles and weasels around. That's what looks bad.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent ABC News poll showed that 84 percent said it made no
difference whether Bush used cocaine when he was younger.
</P>
<P>
   The public also has fairly low expectations in general of
politicians when it comes to questions of honesty and saying one
thing and doing another.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican, for instance, told
radio talk show host Don Imus recently, ``I don't think that
persons are ineligible (to become president) if they have had
indiscretions in the way they have conducted themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet nine years ago as governor of Missouri, Ashcroft supported
``no more second chances'' for casual drug users and backed
legislation that would have stripped beauticians, real estate
agents, accountants, nurses, doctors, and lawyers of their licenses
if they were convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how that squares with his forgiving attitude toward Bush,
Ashcroft said, ``To date, not one shred of evidence has been
produced with respect to Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue caught fire at a breakfast meeting in August with
reporters when Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota
said the press was being gentle toward Bush compared to how it has
treated President Clinton, Hillary Rodham Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore. He also said it was legitimate to ask the
cocaine question.
</P>
<P>
   But a year ago, after Clinton had publicly acknowledged his
relationship with Lewinsky and admitted lying about it, Daschle
said, ``I think people draw a distinction between politics and this
personal tragedy. I really don't think there's any political
ramification to be felt here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in both parties have tried to stay consistent. James
Carville, a pit bull Clinton defender, said he would advise Bush
not to answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never going to end,'' said Carville. ``If you answer one
question, he'll just get five more: Who was in the room with you?
Was there a minor? The best way is to say, `Just what part of
``no'' don't you understand?' ''
</P>
<P>
   William Bennett, a Republican who served as federal drug czar
under President Bush and an author of several books on values, said
Bush needed to answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous critic of Clinton, he wrote in a column for The Wall
Street Journal that when asked about drugs in 1992, Clinton gave an
evasive answer, ``and we drew conclusions from it. But at the time,
I don't recall anyone claiming the question itself was
inappropriate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
