<HEADER>
A6741 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-CHANCELLOR-HNS &LR;      09-01 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-CHANCELLOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
For the third consecutive year, Van Chancellor has been named Coach
of the Year in the WNBA.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``As anybody who's had some success will tell you,'' league
president Val Ackerman said Tuesday, ``one of the hardest parts of
being successful is staying successful. And that's especially true
in sports, where winning is everything, in many cases, and the best
teams end up being the biggest targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Van Chancellor simply won't allow the Houston Comets to stop
being successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor received 18 of a possible 51 votes from a panel of
sportswriters and broadcasters who regularly cover the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento's Sonny Allen finished second with 17 votes. Los
Angeles' Orlando Woolridge netted 11.
</P>
<P>
   Laboring all season under the cloud of illness and eventual
death of his friend and former point guard Kim Perrot, Chancellor
still guided the Comets to the best record in the WNBA (26-6).
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor said given the circumstances surrounding this season
_ the death of Perrot, the loss of center Monica Lamb to a
season-ending eye injury in late June, the decision of No. 1 draft
pick Natalia Zasulskaya of Russia not to report to training camp _
his latest coaching award was the one he cherishes most.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what we've gone through, and I mean this sincerely, I've
never really thought about this Coach of the Year situation five
seconds before today,'' Chancellor said. ``I've been so intent on
trying to help us win a championship, and that's been all of our
focus, that's about all it's been about.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what all we've been through, especially these last two
weeks or so, I'd say, yeah, this one is more special.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor, in a departure from the last two years, is the only
member of the Comets to receive a postseason honor this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento's Yolanda Griffith, previously named Defensive Player
of the Year and Newcomer of the Year, today will be named Most
Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mystics forward Chamique Holdsclaw, the first college
player taken in this year's draft, was earlier named Rookie of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players are responsible for me being here,'' said
Chancellor. ``I just wish some of them had been up here today. That
would have made this a little better for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years running, we're the best defensive team in the
league yet never got a defensive player award. We've won the
championship two years in a row, and we're in the finals for the
third time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's a little strange that I'm the only one to get an
honor. I don't understand it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
