<SLUG> BC-SMARTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA PANEL SPLITS ON USE OF STATE TRUST LANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a year of research and debate, Arizona's Growing Smarter
Commission approved a laundry list of solutions for urban sprawl
Tuesday, but imploded trying to deal with the most controversial
measure.
</P>
<P>
   At issue: a plan to set aside up to 890,000 of state Trust Lands
for conservation and open space purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the so-called Stewardship Trust, including Rep.
Carolyn Allen, R-Scottsdale, said it is critical for Arizona to
permanently protect up to 10 percent of the state's enormous trust
lands.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said that can only happen if Arizona's Constitution is
rewritten to allow Trust Land to be used for conservation, as well
as school financing.
</P>
<P>
   The change would require a three step process involving approval
by Arizona's Legislature, state voters and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Foes offered a litany of objections:
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jake Flake, R-Snowflake, insisted that the Stewardship
Trust would be ruin Arizona agriculture. Instead of preserving open
space, Flake warned, the measure would create a stampede of
cattlemen selling their property to developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I felt this was going through, I'm going home and selling
the ranch,'' he added. ``This is going to put the rancher out of
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gail Griffin, R-Sierra Vista, noted that Trust Lands were
set aside by Arizona founders to be sold as a financing mechanism
for public education. Putting that land into permanent conservation
would be like taking money from school children, she argued.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ed Cirillo, R-Sun City, said the stewardship plan is
unnecessary because Growing Smarter commissioners adopted other
measures to save open spaces around big cities, and properties in
the boondocks need no protection.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the panel also argued about how much land should be
set aside, and who should decide which parcels to protect.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they did not even vote on pivotal elements of the
Stewardship Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Chairman Jack Pfister devised a watered-down proposal
asking state lawmakers to approve the idea while leaving devilish
details to a task force yet to be created.
</P>
<P>
   Pfister acknowledged later that he did not want a vote on
divisive elements of the issue, because it could have sabotaged a
final vote on the entire Growing Smarter package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would feel utter despair if we broke down over a few
words,'' he said. ``...We will have done Arizona a grave
disservice.``
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, panelists adopted Pfister's compromise along with
more than 20 other smart-growth recommendations, on a 12-2 vote,
with one absence.
</P>
<P>
   The full package includes proposals to beef up urban planning,
increase voter involvement, encourage rural development and acquire
open-space ``jewels'' for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   Growing Smarter recommendations are expected to compete with a
more forceful measure, the Citizens Growth Management Initiative,
on ballots this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's package, which was to be presented to Gov. Jane
D. Hull Wednesday, will require approval by Arizona's Legislature
and voters. One provision, if adopted, would establish a $220
million fund to acquire and conserve prime Trust Lands.
</P>
<P>
   Others would:
</P>
<P>
   Create incentives for urban in-fill, along with legislation
authorizing local governments to refuse service beyond designated
growth margins.
</P>
<P>
   Require cities and towns to review their general plans every 10
years, and to get them ratified by voters.
</P>
<P>
   Encourage rural economic growth, including tax incentives for
development.
</P>
<P>
   Pay ranchers for good conservation practices.
</P>
<P>
   Require local government to obtain written consent from property
owners before rezoning their properties, and provide administrative
appeals when owners feel their land has been subjected to a
government ``taking'' for open-space purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Allow Maricopa and Pima counties to restrict so-called
``wildcat'' lot splits which create suburban subdivisions without
access or public services.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has spent months trying to pound out compromises
among 15 members who are split philosophically and politically.
Those differences reared up repeatedly Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   About half the panelists doggedly defended individual property
rights. They objected to government intrusion and the use of
taxpayer money, but favored economic development _ especially in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Other commissioners were equally determined to fight for
conservation and quality-of-life measures.
</P>
<P>
   The net result: either a marvel of reconciliation or a
collection of recommendations that accomplish nothing, depending on
the observer.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Bahr, a Sierra Club lobbyist, said the hot and cold
factions produced a lukewarm package that does little to force
smarter development.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing in here that substantially changes the
way we plan and manage growth in Arizona,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, Bahr's philosophical opposite, voted against the
package and said later, ``I've got real problems with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pfister and commissioner Steve Betts, a Phoenix land-use
attorney, insisted the panel's recommendations, if carried forward,
will dramatically curtail unplanned and unsightly growth on the
Arizona scene.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who also voted in favor of the final recommendations,
offered a less-than-glowing appraisal: ``It was not an exercise in
futility.'' &QL; 
Dennis Wagner can be reached at 444-8874 or at
dennis.wagner(at)pni.com via the Internet. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
