u s BC-BKL-COMETS-HNS &LR;      09-01 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The game had been one of the toughest uphill climbs for the Comets
during their three years in the WNBA.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final 15 seconds of a 72-62 win over the Los Angeles Sparks
at Compaq Center on Monday night that carried with it the Western
Conference championship were filled with some of the most heated
moments the league has seen.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the circumstances, the Comets said Tuesday it was
one of their most satisfying victories ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ranks right up there at the top,'' said Cynthia Cooper, who
matched Sheryl Swoopes with a game-high 23 points Monday and had a
career-high 12 assists. ``Los Angeles really didn't show a lot of
respect for us. I guess that's expected in the playoffs. LA's a
very, very confident team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough-fought game. And any time you win a game like
that, you have to be very happy. But they were gesturing to us out
in Los Angeles (when the Sparks opened the best-of-three series
with a 75-60 victory Thursday). We had an off night, and we
obviously weren't too happy about that. So to be able to come back
and win the series shut up a lot of people who doubted us.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely satisfying. But that's only one piece of the
puzzle. The major piece is still to be put in the puzzle. That's to
go out to New York and play better than we did in the Los Angeles
series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets face the Liberty in the first game of the
best-of-three WNBA Championship Series at Madison Square Garden on
Thursday night. The second game and a third, if necessary, will be
played at Compaq Center on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Saluting the Comets as champs of the West for the third year in
a row momentarily took a back seat to a bevy of ``military
salutes'' prevalent around the floor in the closing seconds Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, during a timeout, bounced up and down as she saluted
triumphantly at her teammates and some of those in the crowd of
12,673.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, able to smile for the first time on a night filled with
dour, desperate faces earlier, gave a salute to assistant coach
Alisa Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Jackson and Tina Thompson saluted the crowd. And Thompson
had the biggest gesture, a farewell salute to the Sparks' Lisa
Leslie, who started the charged scene with 15 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   TV cameras had caught Leslie moments earlier swinging an
unprovoked elbow into the midsection of Thompson as the two stood
along the free-throw lane. As they jogged upcourt afterward,
Thompson had a few words with her former Southern Cal teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, `You know, that's not even called for, but the
funny thing about it is you guys are going home,''' Thompson said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the TV cameras caught Leslie throwing a two-handed shove
at Thompson's throat. After another verbal exchange, the action
heated up anew. An enraged Leslie tried to fight through a crowd of
players and officials in an apparent attempt to get at Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she was going to kill me, or something like that,''
said Thompson. ``And I just saluted her. I wasn't going to
retaliate or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Once order was restored, Leslie and Thompson were ejected.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory secure, coach Van Chancellor was so overcome
with emotion he left the bench area, waded into the crowd and
embraced Connie Perrot, mother of Kim Perrot, who died of cancer
Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it would have been for the championship of the whole WNBA,
it would be the most satisfying,'' Chancellor said. ``I'd have to
say beating Phoenix (in the decisive game in 1998) was the most
satisfying. But Monday's game meant so much because of all the
things this team has overcome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
