<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SQUEEZE AND A SLAM BY ASTROS LEAVE METS FEELING WHIPLASHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Tuesday night was going to be an antidote for those
still feeling punchy from Monday's mashball marathon. It was going
to be a pitchers' duel between the Mets and Astros that featured
the execution of one of baseball's most fundamental _ yet still
breathtaking _ plays.
</P>
<P>
   And then the bashers' highlight reel flipped on again.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Caminiti, the Astros' hulking third baseman, slugged a high,
deep grand slam into right-center field to break open a tightly
played game in the eighth inning to give the Astros a 6-2 victory
over the Mets. The shot was redemption for Caminiti, whose throwing
error had opened the way for the Mets to tie the game in the top of
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But it was virtually a self-fulfilling prophecy for the Mets
reliever Turk Wendell. He does not relish having much time off
between appearances and this time it had been a week since he last
pitched. When he relieved Kenny Rogers in the eighth, Wendell
walked Craig Biggio and then, after getting Matt Mieske to swing
and miss on a hit-and-run play, gave up a double to Mieske that put
men on second and third with one out. The Mets intentionally walked
Jeff Bagwell to load the bases and set up a potential inning-ending
double play in a decision that Manager Bobby Valentine called ``a
no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendell struck out Caminiti the last time he faced him, but
Caminiti was 2 for 7 in his career against Wendell, and both hits
were homers. Tuesday night, Caminiti looked at one high and outside
pitch from Wendell, took a roundhouse swing at the next, and then
punched a fastball that was up and over the plate 10 rows deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, I always pitch badly when I have a layoff,''
Wendell said. ``I try to stay sharp in the bullpen, but it's not
the same. I'm not going to make an issue of it, but I hope they
look at it and say, `Maybe we should have gotten him in there to
face a batter.' I need to pitch to be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   With the loss, the Mets fell three and one-half games behind the
Braves in the National League East. But, because Atlanta beat
Cincinnati, 8-2, the Mets are still three games ahead in the
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   That was some comfort for Wendell, who joked that, although he
gave up four runs on two hits and two walks, this was not the worst
he had pitched. The grand slam is the outsize shot that will be
remembered from this game. But it was a far subtler, equally
dramatic play that the Astros used to break up a scoreless tie in
the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who told Valentine after the fifth inning that he could
no longer swing a bat because the soreness in his back was flaring,
had allowed just two balls hit in the air in the first six innings
and got 12 outs on the ground, using the same sinker that flummoxed
the Astros last week. So, on the night after the Astros had been
battered for 17 runs while producing only one of their own, it was
somehow fitting that they needed a suicide squeeze to finally
score.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Bagwell drew a walk. Caminiti singled through the
hole at short, sending Bagwell to second. Bagwell nearly stopped
there, but he looked directly at left fielder Rickey Henderson, who
could not cleanly field the grounder. Bagwell took off for third
and made it easily, the kind of heads-up play that has helped make
Bagwell a leading candidate for the league's most valuable player
award. Rogers was thinking strikeout when the pinch-hitter Russ
Johnson came to the plate, but Valentine had intelligence reports
telling otherwise. When the count reached 1-1, Mike Piazza called
for a pitchout. The Astros had squeezed four times on a 1-1 count
this year, but this time, the runners didn't move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the situation was coming,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   It was, on the next pitch, which, the reports showed, the Astros
had done only once before. With Bagwell shimmying down the
third-base line, Johnson put down a perfect slow-rolling bunt back
toward Rogers. Rogers slipped slightly coming off the mound and
although he fielded the ball cleanly, he had no chance to get
Bagwell at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to flip it,'' Rogers said. ``I could see him
coming and I'd rather make sure I get the out.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti scored the second run of the inning when Ryan Thompson,
who was designated for assignment after the game, hit a double to
the wall in center field. The Astros led by 2-0 and the Mets seemed
to have forgotten the magic bats that had belted out 21 hits Monday
night back at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first seven innings, the Astros starter Jose Lima
(18-7) had allowed no runner to reach third base, and Robin Ventura
and Henderson had both been thrown out trying to get there. But
fittingly, Edgardo Alfonzo, whose three home runs and six hits had
rewritten the record books Monday night, was involved in the Mets'
comeback. He hit a roller to Caminiti that the third baseman threw
wildly to first base. Alfonzo went to second to lead off the eighth
inning. John Olerud, just as mild-mannered and only slightly more
expected to slug the occasional home run than Alfonzo, belted the
first pitch from Lima into the seats in right center for his 16th
home run of the season to tie the score and send Caminiti into a
crestfallen crouch in the infield.
</P>
<P>
   A half-inning later, Caminiti would have his solace and the Mets
would be left to wonder if the rust from Wendell's rest now would
be worth the fresher arm later in a pennant race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
