<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS-HNS &LR;      09-01 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Ken Caminiti admitted to doing some tossing and turning in his bed
Monday night, wondering why his swing had chosen now to take a
leave of absence. But even in his deepest sleep, Caminiti could not
have dreamed of a better scenario for a coming-out party.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tie game, eighth inning. Grand slam, and goodnight, New York
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti made amends for an error that led to the Mets' only
runs by blasting the fifth bases-loaded homer of his career in the
Astros' 6-2 victory Tuesday night at the Astrodome. It was the
Astros' 13th last-at-bat victory.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic shot into the right-field mezzanine turned a
potential no-decision into Jose Lima's National League-leading 18th
victory. Lima, pitching on three days' rest, didn't allow an earned
run in eight innings and has a microscopic 0.89 ERA in his last
four wins.
</P>
<P>
   But as good as Lima was, he was more than willing to surrender
the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cammy was the hero, not me,'' Lima said. ``He's the man
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   That alone made it perhaps the most emotional of the Astros' 79
victories this season. Caminiti spent 79 games on the disabled
list, which makes being in situations like Tuesday's all the more
precious.
</P>
<P>
   The modest crowd of 24,982 erupted as Caminiti floated around
the bases, and the Astros' dugout was an absolute mob scene.
Considering the number of times Caminiti was pounded on the helmet,
thumbed in the chest and slapped on the rear, it wouldn't surprise
anyone if he were a little sore today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have hit him about 20 times,'' Lima said. ``I was so
happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner pitched a perfect ninth inning to close out the
Mets, who dropped to 3{ games behind Atlanta in the National League
East. The NL Central-leading Astros re-established a 1{-game
cushion over Cincinnati, which lost 8-2 to the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine anyone who was at the Astrodome feeling
cheated by Tuesday's game, which featured a little bit of
everything. Lima (18-7) and Mets starter Kenny Rogers were locked
in a scoreless pitchers' duel until the Astros broke through with
two runs in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a lover of good pitching could have appreciated the first
seven innings,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   So you like good defense?
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Astros are the Nos. 1 and 3 fielding teams,
respectively, in the NL, so naturally the glove work was exemplary
at times. Astros second baseman Craig Biggio, for instance, always
seemed to be in the right place at the right time, and Mets
shortstop Rey Ordonez was, well, Rey Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing sends fans into a frenzy like a grand slam.
Caminiti's bomb off Mets reliever Turk Wendell (3-2) was the
Astros' fifth slam of the season, and it undoubtedly was Caminiti's
biggest hit in his abbreviated campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was redemption,'' the switch-hitting third baseman said.
``I couldn't find a hole big enough to put my head into after that
error. I got a chance to get even, and I got a good swing on it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the eighth, it was Caminiti's throwing error on a
two-out grounder to third base that prolonged the Mets' inning and
set the stage for John Olerud's two-run homer off Lima, who has
allowed a team-high 25 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose pitched a great game, and I felt bad after I turned that
easy play into an ugly two-run inning,'' said Caminiti, who is
hitting .243 in the Astros' last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker visited Lima on the mound before Olerud stepped into the
batter's box, but only to give Wagner some extra time to warm up.
The plan was to have Wagner face Mike Piazza if the Astros had the
lead when the slugging catcher came to the plate. It was a moot
point after Olerud crushed Lima's first pitch into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Lima stole a glance into the Astros' dugout to see
if Dierker would make a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `Please stay in the dugout! Please stay in the
dugout!''' Lima said. ``I'm glad he let me get that last out. I
made a bad pitch to Olerud, but I'm a competitor, and I like to
finish what I start.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored their first run in the seventh on Russ
Johnson's squeeze bunt, which scored Jeff Bagwell from third base.
Ryan Thompson, hitless in his first 10 at-bats after being promoted
from Class AAA New Orleans, followed with an RBI double that scored
Caminiti.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
