<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABRACADABRA! MAKING MUSIC STILL MAGIC TO STEVE MILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY RODGERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his multiplatinum heyday, Steve Miller seemed to have the
magic formula for hit pop singles bottled on a shelf in his
recording studio, ready to be poured into each new album.
</P>
<P>
   Crisp guitar work, infectious lyrics and a danceable beat were
blended into such gems as ``Jet Airliner,'' ``Fly Like an Eagle,''
``Take the Money and Run'' and ``Jungle Love. ''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp production made these hits jump out of even the tinniest
car radio, and Miller _ who is on his annual summer amphitheater
tour _ became one of the most popular and well-paid rock artists of
the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's probably earned as much money selling albums as
Joe Montana made playing football, don't expect Miller to wax warm
and fuzzy about record companies.
</P>
<P>
   Today's huge recording conglomerates are ``destroying careers
left and right because of their own incompetence and their
inability to represent 200 artists (simultaneously),'' Miller says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much better if there's a lot of small companies competing
with each other than five companies all patting each other on the
back and going, `Hey, let's corner this and screw everybody.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who's made more than 20 albums and still sells a million
discs a year, has seen the industry change over three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record companies were so full of (expletive) when I was
signing with them in 1967,'' says Miller, calling from a tour stop
in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were racist, they stole money from people, they were
dishonest, their contracts were horrible, and it had to be
straightened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a hot guitarist who was making waves with his Steve
Miller Blues Band in San Francisco at the time, says he was able to
land a lucrative record deal because 14 companies were courting
him.
</P>
<P>
   But that was hardly his ticket to a life of leisure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys at (Capitol Records) were all flunkies at EMI, our
lord and master in London,'' Miller says. ``They were like
vacuum-cleaner salesmen; they didn't know how to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial rough going with his label, however, had its up
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Capitol Records in LA to record my first album, and
the engineering staff walked out because I was a hippie and they
didn't want to record `that hippie,' '' Miller recalls.
</P>
<P>
   So, Miller went to England to record and later met the Beatles,
forging a lasting relationship with Paul McCartney.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's London producer, Glyn Johns, also recorded the Beatles
and invited the American to a session.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I went down and watched John (Lennon) and Paul sing
``Don't Let Me Down'' and ``Get Back.'' ... It was the most
exciting moment of my life,'' Miller says.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Miller jammed with McCartney and George Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then George took off, and Paul and I did a tune ``(My Dark
Hour),'' and I released it on my record'' _ with McCartney listed
as ``Paul Ramon.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Miller and McCartney collaborated on six songs,
three of which appear on McCartney's 1997 LP, ``Flaming Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's career skyrocketed in the early '70s, when he decided
to produce his own records after six progressive rock albums had
earned critical raves but no hit singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to make my music positive and ... more upbeat,'' he
says. ``Plenty of people were covering the dark side of things. I
really like the `up' music more, and I like singing the
harmonies.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was 1973's ``The Joker,'' and its hit title track put
Miller in the ear of mainstream America. Two follow-up albums,
``Fly Like an Eagle'' and ``Book of'' ``Dreams,'' which contained
such megahits as ``Rock 'N Me, Jet Airliner ''``''and
``Swingtown,'' put Miller's bank account in the stratosphere, but
also took a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were two or three times when I just burned
out,'' Miller says. ``I remember walking off a stage in a football
stadium ... . It was like the 39th football stadium in a row at the
end of four years of non-stop touring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad because there were `only' 40,000 people. And I gave
my guitar to my roadie and said, `I don't care if I ever do this
again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But these days, at age 55, Miller has learned to balance touring
and his personal life, which is centered on life near Seattle with
his third wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've toured every year for the last 12 years, and it's great
because we've grown so much as musicians _ our tone, our chops,''
Miller says. ``I played the best guitar I've ever played the last
two gigs!
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just something in me that wants to play music. I love
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why his current outing is called ``Last Call Summer
Tour,'' Miller cheerfully clears up any doubts: ``That's the last
call for the century, the millennium. We're already planning next
year!'' &QL; 
Larry Rodgers can be reached at (602) 444-8043 or at
larry.rodgers(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 0128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
