<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTONS-VACATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWDS SEEKING CLINTONS PUT SPOTLIGHT ON CHELSEA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ua) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKANEATELES, N.Y. _ It was not the president of the United
States. It was not even the first lady. But when Chelsea Clinton
turned the corner onto the main street of this beguiling Finger
Lakes village Tuesday afternoon, unannounced and seemingly out of
nowhere, it caused a commotion of presidential proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of tourists, townsfolk, reporters and shopkeepers who
had been wandering in search of a Clinton converged on Chelsea, 19,
who had managed for a moment to walk unnoticed with a friend and a
Secret Service agent along Jordan Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, that's her!'' exclaimed Lena Faben, bounding to her
feet, her camera in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Shouts of ``Chelsea!'' filled the air. Emily Conklin, 85, seated
in a wheelchair, called out, ``Chelsea, I want to shake your
hand!''
</P>
<P>
   One woman running for an autograph caught her leg in a bicycle
that was parked on a sidewalk and flipped over hard on her back.
``Are you OK?'' Miss Clinton asked. ``I am so sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the president's daughter arrived at the Skaneateles
Library and John D. Barrow Art Gallery and turned to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to walk in there,'' she said. ``Please don't follow
me. I'm going to walk out the same door.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the crowd, she entered the art gallery, where she
signed her name in the guest book. (The sheet was instantly locked
away in the library safe.)
</P>
<P>
   She emerged 45 minutes later to a crowd that was three times as
large and twice as enthusiastic. The president's daughter slowly
worked her way down the line, shaking every hand and touching every
baby before she hopped into a van and took off.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Clintons arrived here on Monday, to spend five days
at the lake-front home of Thomas McDonald, a Clinton supporter, the
mood in this village, which is overwhelmingly Republican, was
somewhere between apprehension and hostility. One restaurant owner
vowed not to serve the Clintons if they showed up. But Skaneateles
was buzzing Tuesday, as even residents who said they had not voted
for Clinton enjoyed their village's sudden celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty infectious,'' Sally Brew said as she waited for
Miss Clinton to emerge from the library.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the warm reception that the Clintons have received here,
it would be a mistake to draw too strong a message about support
for Mrs. Clinton in her presumed race for the Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have to think about that,'' said Carol Haber, a
retired teacher who waited four hours in front of the McDonald home
to catch a handshake from the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
