<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6759 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-01 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FOR all the disappointment in the Astros' clubhouse over Moises
Alou's season coming to a screeching halt before it ever got going,
there is a bit of solace to be found.
</P>
<P>
   There's always next year. Alou should be fine by then. After
all, baseball for a talent like Alou must be like riding a bicycle.
You never forget.
</P>
<P>
   It's only in seasons like this one when baseball is like falling
off your bike, crashing, nearly running over your kid and having 70
cc's of fluid removed from your scarred knee.
</P>
<P>
   The season that couldn't get any stranger or take any more wild
turns for Alou and the Astros, did.
</P>
<P>
   Alou was riding a bicycle and playing with his 3-year-old son
over the weekend when he crashed and reinjured his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bleak'' is how Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker
described the prospects of Alou managing a return before the end of
this season, playoffs or no playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Consider it safe to say we won't see Alou again until next
spring.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the dark clouds that swarmed outside the Astrodome on
this dark, threatening day and the clouds that seemed to be forming
inside as news of Alou's season-ending setback spread, there was
the proverbial silver lining.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out today about Moises,'' Astros starter Jose
Lima said, ``I thought, `Oh, man, we're going to miss him.' It's
hard to replace him.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is. But how can these 1999 Astros miss what they
never had?
</P>
<P>
   As vital a player as Alou could be when healthy, the Astros have
climbed to the top of the division without him.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the biggest news that came out of Tuesday's 6-2 Astros win
over the Mets was not that Alou was still out but that Ken Caminiti
was back. He was his old self, and other familiar contributors
might not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti described his hitting from the left side of the plate
in recent games as, ``dormant, shut-down, bad, gone, nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Caminiti's dramatic eighth-inning grand slam that hammered
the Mets and helped Lima to his league-leading 18th win of the year
Tuesday might have been as good a sign for this team as Alou's
setback was bad.
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way: The Astros' troops might not be ready to attack
the playoffs full-force just yet, but they're assembling along the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti has yet to show any serious lingering effects of the
calf injury that put him out for nearly three months earlier this
year. Then Tuesday he looked as confident as ever swinging the bat,
even before the monstrous shot that earned the win and spelled
redemption for his throwing error, which led to the game-tying
homer.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spiers, who has been as clutch and consistent as any Astro,
also returned to the team after sitting out four days as his lower
back pain eased following a cortisone shot.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell, who might not be the most popular Astro but
certainly is among the club's top run-producers, will be back
today. Carl Everett, who has been as consistent with the bat as
Jeff Bagwell this season, will take a week, maybe 10 days at the
most, before he'll back in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was all that 10-10-whatever dialing that
Hunsicker did on the day that rosters had to be finalized for
playoff eligibility. The Astros released Sean Bergman, recalled
Jose Cabrera, designated outfielder Ryan Thompson for assignment
and traded for outfielder Stan Javier.
</P>
<P>
   The only one of those moves that could make a difference come
playoff time is the trade with the Giants for Javier, a 15-year
veteran who still has some speed with both his legs and his bat.
</P>
<P>
   In a season when they couldn't count on Alou, what the Astros
could count on was a consistent pitching staff and a lineup that
managed just enough clutch hits to keep the Reds at bay.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a while, we saw both of those things
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who fancies himself as the team's stopper _ someone who
takes the mound and stops the bleeding when things are going bad _
was superb for all but one pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But even after giving up the two-run tying shot to John Olerud
in the eighth, as stoppers go Lima's winning performance in the
wake of Monday's hammering was like suturing a severed artery. He
stopped some serious bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Caminiti, stopping a bad skid from the left
side of the plate and looking like his old self.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hit was huge for me,'' Caminiti said.
</P>
<P>
   It set off the Astrodome fireworks and had 24,982 fans screaming
for a curtain call, although Cammy couldn't take it because his
teammates were bombarding him with celebratory slaps and punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``My chest is all bruised up,'' Caminiti said. ``But that's all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   For this team that has been bruised, battered and broken,
finally things are starting to hurt so good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
