<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6762 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-ARAPIO-AZR &LR;      09-01 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAPIO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARPAIO DEPUTY IS CLEARED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINA LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio's chief deputy has been
cleared by federal prosecutors who closed an investigation into
allegations that he embezzled funds from the office's pink
underwear sales and ordered surveillance on political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's Office sent David Hendershott a letter
Monday, saying there was insufficient evidence to justify further
action on allegations that he committed bankruptcy fraud, illegal
electronic surveillance and misappropriated funds from the sale of
county-issued pink underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying it's garbage from Day 1,'' said Jack
MacIntyre, another aide to the sheriff. ``And it's garbage two
years after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheriff and Dave Hendershott have been fully vindicated
once again.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI probe included questions about missing money from a
posse program that Hendershott oversaw. But further details were
unavailable Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also have alleged that deputies were ordered to shadow
office critics to prepare dossiers on them and that they illegally
wiretapped dissenting employees within the Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hendershott, chief of operations for the Sheriff's Office who
oversees a $111 million budget and a $900 million jail construction
project, said in a statement Tuesday that ``these fabrications were
made by a few former employees and present disgruntled employees
and political enemies.'' He called the investigation an ongoing
witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's Office sent Hendershott the letter because
the investigation had received so much media attention, spokeswoman
Cathy Colbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Colbert said the letter was addressed solely to Hendershott
because ``nobody else was subject of this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   MacIntyre, however, views the notice as much more significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the allegations of federal investigation have all been
cleared,'' he said. ``There's nothing open and nothing pending.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the U.S. Attorney's Office and the FBI could not
confirm whether they are investigating additional cases.
</P>
<P>
   However, federal officials are still investigating allegations
of a cover-up in the 1996 jailhouse death of inmate Scott Norberg,
who died of asphyxiation in a restraint chair.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio said the allegations surrounding Hendershott and his
office were ``based on spite, malice and jealousy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheriff expects these kinds of attacks because of his
popularity,'' MacIntyre said. ``It's just unfortunate that his
political enemies stoop to this low level of mudslinging.''
</P>
<P>
   MacIntyre said detectives are still conducting an internal
investigation on allegations made that Arpaio ordered deputies to
tail political foes, including Maricopa County Attorney Rick
Romley.
</P>
<P>
   Romley declined to comment, but said through a spokesman that
they thought the allegations were serious enough to forward to the
U.S. Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results are as you have them,'' spokesman Bill FitzGerald
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gerberry,  &UR; president of the Maricopa County Deputies
Association, said he hopes investigations into possible wrongdoing
at the Sheriff's Office will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, I think they might have bowed to some of the
political pressure,'' he said. ``He's a very popular individual,
and I think the U.S. Attorney's Office _ and the FBI, for that
matter _ because of Waco and Ruby Ridge, have taken some very
strong hits. And I don't think they want to take on a very popular
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Colbert denied those accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our office treats any allegation as serious, particularly in
regards to people in a public position,'' she said. ``We are
dedicated to this, and we go where the investigation takes us.''  &QL; 
Includes information from the Associated Press. Christina Leonard
can be reached at (602) 444-8995 or at christina
leonard(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
