<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN ADMITS SUICIDE ATTEMPTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain, worried that he would crack under the strain of
repeated beatings and torture by his captors during the Vietnam
War, says in a new book that he twice made feeble attempts at
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despairing of any relief from pain and further torture, and
fearing the close approach of my moment of dishonor, I tried to
take my life,'' the Republican Arizona senator wrote in the
just-released ``Faith of my Fathers''.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dishonor'' in McCain's case could have meant confessing bogus
war crimes to the North Vietnamese or disclosing U.S. battle
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt I really intended to kill myself. But I couldn't fight
anymore, and I remember deciding that the last thing I could do to
make them believe I was still resisting, that I wouldn't break, was
to attempt suicide,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it wasn't an ideal plan, but it struck me at the
time as reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   He twice began to loop a shirt around his neck for a suicide by
hanging but was caught by guards, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a Navy flyer, was on a bombing mission over Hanoi when
his plane was hit by an enemy missile during the Vietnam War in
October 1967. He was a prisoner of war for 5{ years.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his top aide, Mark Salter, decided to write the book
a few years ago to tell the story of McCain's POW years and of the
senator's father and grandfather, both of whom were admirals.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Salter obtained from the Pentagon the senator's
classified debriefing papers from when he was released. That helped
McCain to refresh his memory for the writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked, talked and talked. We (he and Salter) are very
close,'' McCain said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt appeared earlier this summer in ``GQ'' magazine
focusing just on McCain's dad, who was commander of U.S. forces in
the Pacific while his son was impris oned during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Now, McCain, a presidential candidate, is preparing for a book
tour from Sept. 8-24 that will earn him invaluable free publicity
in such cities as Los Angeles, Phoenix, Boston, Chicago, Washington
and Manchester, N.H. McCain gave interviews about the book as he
toured New Hampshire this week on a campaign swing.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also recently recorded a six-hour, unabridged audio
version of the book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; His mother, Roberta McCain, 87, who has never done a broadcast
interview, has agreed to appear soon on television with Sam
Donaldson to discuss her son and his book, the senator said. In a
rare print interview, she told ``The'' ``Arizona Republic'' this
summer that she thought her son had died when she heard that his
plane had been shot out of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The book takes McCain, 63, from his days at the Naval Academy,
where he was rowdy and finished fifth from the bottom in his class,
to the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   At the academy, McCain tells how he ``drank a lot of beer (and)
occasionally we got in fights.''
</P>
<P>
   During those years, he once showed up for a date at a woman's
house drunk, then fell over and was sent home by the woman's
father.
</P>
<P>
   McCain describes scrambling out of a plane in July 1967 after it
was hit by a rocket that misfired on the deck of the USS Forrestal.
The subsequent fire on the deck led to a series of explosions that
killed 134 men.
</P>
<P>
   Small pieces of of shrapnel from an exploded bomb ``tore into my
legs and chest,'' McCain wrote. ``All around me was mayhem. Planes
were burning. More bombs cooked off. Body parts, pieces of the ship
and scraps of planes were dropping onto the deck.'' &QL; 
Jeff Barker can be reached at 1-(202)-662-7264 or at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
