<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS INJURY PUTS NEW FACE ON MEN'S U.S. OPEN DRAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sad thing is that a case could be made that
what's bad for Pete Sampras is not necessarily bad for the men's
draw at the 1999 U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to Pistol Pete, who is a fine tennis champion. He
gets serious consideration for being the best player ever, but it
may be that Sampras has simply been the most dominating.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where the men's side of the game has morphed into
130-mph serves and one-shot rallies, the ascension and reign of
Sampras has coincided with a pounding monotony in the men's game.
</P>
<P>
   In general, artistry and groundstrokes have gone the way of
thigh-revealing double-knit shorts for the guys, except for the
rare throwbacks like Patrick Rafter, the two-time U.S. Open champ
who is also no longer in contention after withdrawing Tuesday night
due to a shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   And as for pop, panache or pure
McEnroe-Conners-Nastase-Vilas-type personalities, the millennium
can't come soon enough to close out these hum-drum '90s of bland,
brain-numb hardcourt automatons who have benefited from racquet
technology and suffered from a shortage of novel reading or museum
hopping.
</P>
<P>
   Now the door is open for Andre Agassi, whose capitalist-consumer
economy personality is at this time being warranted by the
once-again steady level of his play.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you have to feel for Sampras, whose drive and focus and
commitment have to be lauded, even when during the Labor Day
stretch of the U.S. Open he has helped drive potential fringe
tennis followers to revel in the start of football season.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, news that a herniated disc forced Sampras to withdraw
as the No. 1 seed from this American Grand Slam sent a ripple
through the Open, especially when there is a question about whether
the booming nature of Sampras' power game may be a culprit in this
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really sorry for him, and I'm sorry for tennis,'' Agassi
said of his favorite co-competitor, buddy and Nike stablemate. ``It
would have been an awesome time. It's sad. It's too bad. It really
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone understands that in order for Sampras to give up this
chance to win his record-setting 13th Slam, his back must be in
very bad shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad for Pete. He's been playing the best tennis in the
world since Queens Club,'' Jim Courier said r he was ousted in his
first-round match Tuesday. ``To have your bubble burst like that,
it's tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen a lot of people's careers close with a back
injury, and I hope that isn't the case with Pete. But Pete's missed
a few Slams because of injuries. He's had to sit home on the couch.
It's not a lot of fun. It is what it is, though. Hopefully, he'll
back in the indoor season.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was not a very fun sight to see Sampras sit himself
stiffly down into a chair for a news conference at the National
Tennis Center. His usually amiable features were dark and drawn,
and that's not even taking into account the three days of beard
growth that had, surprisingly, given Sampras the suave look he has
failed to cultivate during his milk-and-cookies tenure as No. 1
tennis player in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the color or personality we have witnessed from Sampras
has come from unexpected blips, like the time he was ailing and
nauseous and lost his lunch during the U.S. Open finals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Sampras demanded empathy by the way disappointment
showed on his face and body, which is plagued by something much
more serious than an upset stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard to pull out of this event,'' he said, near
tears. ``I was looking forward to having the opportunity to play
here. I love playing the U.S. Open. The way I've been playing the
last two months, I liked my chances here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras felt his back glitch during a practice session Sunday.
He left the court immediately, cutting his hourlong stint short and
heading straight to the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was basically for the past 48 hours struggling with just
getting around my hotel room,'' he said. ``(Monday) night, I did a
few tests, CAT scan and an MRI, and it showed I have an herniated
disc.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no need for surgery, Sampras has been told, which is
good news. But it is no less daunting for an athlete like Sampras
to realize his body has betrayed him and that recovery will mean he
has to stop doing the one thing that defines him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself for the next couple of weeks just getting
treatment twice a week and not doing anything. I can't do
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The strange thing about this injury to the brutally dominating
and pummeling No. 1 player in the world could turn out to be that,
the closer this Open draws to its conclusion, the more everyone
might find they miss poor ol' Pistol Pete.
</P>
<P>
   We've grown accustomed to his face, even when his wearing power
game fails to enrapture.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
