<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' MALONE SEES POSITIVE MINDSET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Malone heard it when he became the Dodgers
general manager nearly a year ago. Manager Davey Johnson was warned
of it the day he took over, and he's had nearly six months to
experience it.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers used to do things a certain way, and lately that
wasn't cutting it, so a change was in order.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly a full season to analyze and evaluate, Malone said
the Dodgers had to break certain beliefs down before they could be
built up.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the Dodgers' 5-3 win over Milwaukee on Tuesday,
Malone said the iron will that was so much part of the organization
has been dissolved, and that gives hope of a quick turnaround for
the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to make some transformations and break some wills,''
Malone said. ``We needed to get people focused on what's important,
and that's winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the way the Dodgers have played lately, Malone believes
that has taken place. The Dodgers are long out of the playoff race,
but they entered the game with Milwaukee playing their best
baseball of the season.
</P>
<P>
   There also seems to be harmony in the clubhouse for the first
time this season, something that changed about the same time right
fielder Raul Mondesi lashed out of Johnson and Malone two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of positive things have happened,'' Malone said. ``I
think all the players realize we have to be on the same page to
reach our goals. If you're concerned about numbers and statistics,
you're not going to win. If you're not concerned about numbers and
statistics, then winning will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a transformation of our mindset, and I think the
players realize that. It's almost like we had to go through this to
get to where we want to go. It's almost like we had to take one
step back to take two steps toward where we want to go. We're still
breaking down barriers to where we want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   And, if the Dodgers accomplish what they want to in the
offseason, many of those barriers could crumble.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers still need a left-handed power hitter in the middle
of the lineup, a second baseman with more range and a leadoff
hitter with an on-base percentage higher than .363.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers need depth in the bullpen, options for more starting
pitchers in case another Carlos Perez situation arises and reliable
replacements in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   And they need flexibility on the 40-man roster so they can
shuttle players between Los Angeles and the minors, and flexibility
with payroll so they can make trades during the season to aid a
playoff push.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what we need to do,'' Malone said. ``We've known for a
while. There's a lot of work to be done. I was optimistic you could
accelerate the process. There's no easy route.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles found that out.
</P>
<P>
   The horrific season still has a month remaining. But what
matters now is what plans the Dodgers have for offseason
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the team plays well until time officially runs out Oct.3
at Houston, it will be impossible to forget one of the most
miserable seasons in the Los Angeles history of the club.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, picked by many to reach the playoffs, were 17{
games out of first place when the day began. Though they've won
lately to pull nine games under .500 at 61-70 and move into third
place, it wasn't too long ago they were 15 games under .500 and in
last place in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to see the little things, I believe,'' Malone
said. ``I'm starting to see a lot more team play, a lot more
attention to detail. Just some of the little things we need to do
to mold ourselves into a team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
