<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME QUESTION POLICE GUIDELINES ON CONFRONTATIONS WITH THE MENTALLY
ILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-POLICE-SHOOTING)  
(js) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When New York City police officers confront an emotionally
disturbed person, they are required to take several clear-cut steps
under the Police Department's guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   They should back off and try to contain the situation. They
should summon supervisors and the specially trained officers of the
Emergency Services Unit. They should use physical force only to the
extent necessary to restrain the individual, and deadly force only
as a last resort, to protect the lives of officers and anyone else
at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Officers appeared to have followed the guidelines to the letter
on Monday night, when they confronted a disturbed man wielding a
hammer in Borough Park, Brooklyn, Police Commissioner Howard Safir
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But some advocates for the mentally ill are questioning whether
the guidelines themselves offer adequate protections to people who
are sick and in crisis. Noting that Gidone Busch, the man with the
hammer, was the latest in a series of apparently mentally ill
people to be killed in confrontations with patrol officers, they
called for the Police Department to intensify training and improve
tactics for coping with the emotionally disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department responded to 36,000 ``Emotionally
Disturbed Person Calls'' last year, roughly 100 a day on average,
inspector Ray McDermott, commander of the emergency service unit of
the New York City Police Department, said in a recent interview.
But only about 4,000 were handled by McDermott's unit, which
receives special training for such encounters. The other cases were
handled only by uniformed officers who were on the scene first _ as
happened Monday night in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all of these cases were resolved with very little force
being used,'' McDermott said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday night, the police said, efforts to defuse the
confrontation failed.
</P>
<P>
   The officers who arrived at the apartment where Busch was
staying backed off when he brandished a claw hammer, Safir said.
They called for supervisors and emergency services.
</P>
<P>
   But Busch came out the door after them, still swinging the
hammer, Safir said. Pepper spray did not stop him, and as the
officers continued backing up, one of them tripped and fell, Safir
said. When a sergeant tried to help the officer to his feet, Busch
began hitting the sergeant with his hammer, the police said. The
other officers pulled their guns, ordered Busch several times to
drop the hammer, and when he did not, they opened fire, killing
him.
</P>
<P>
   Though people sometimes ask why the police cannot disarm an
assailant by using their nightsticks or shooting an arm or a leg,
they are trained to use deadly force if they believe someone's life
is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, Busch came running up the stairs and attacked
the police officers, and they had little choice but to defend their
lives,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Without questioning the police account of the incident, Ray
Brescia, a lawyer with the Urban Justice Center, an advocacy
organization, asked whether better police training in handling the
mentally ill might have protected everyone involved without lethal
shots being fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the mental health system shrinks, the police are filling a
critical gap whether they like it or not,'' Brescia said, calling
the city's Police Department ``the world's largest psychiatric
outreach team.'' Those first on the scene, he said, ``are
invariably beat cops who have exactly 16 hours' training in the
Police Academy on how to deal with emotionally disturbed people.''
</P>
<P>
   The police vigorously defend current practices, developed as
part of an overhaul of procedures that followed a bitter public
debate over the Eleanor Bumpurs case. Mrs. Bumpurs, a mentally
disturbed woman of 67, was shot and killed by a police officer in
1984 during an effort to evict her from her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Recent cases included the death in October of Kevin Cerbelli, a
schizophrenic who had been in and out of Elmhurst Hospital's
psychiatric ward. He was shot to death by the police in a Queens
station house after trying to stab a sergeant with a screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   The police and advocates for the mentally ill say that officers
are often forced to deal with these crisis situations because of
the mental health system's failures. In the case of Busch, the
details are still unclear. But Safir said ``he appears to have a
history of mental illness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
