<HEADLINE>
JUDD GETS JOB DONE FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Though right-hander Mike Judd has been neither
overwhelming nor eye-popping in any of his starts, he is pitching
well enough to make folks notice.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in four starts, Judd did enough to win as the
Dodgers beat the Brewers 5-3 Tuesday night at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have won four straight series for the first time
this season. Today, they can complete their first sweep since they
beat Seattle three straight heading into the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each one is supposed to be his last (start), and he's on his
fourth,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``I thought I'd look
at that position to give someone a spot start. I'm not saying I
won't give somebody else a chance to start before the end of the
year, but he's the best candidate here.''
</P>
<P>
   Judd (3-1) allowed three runs on seven hits, walked one and
struck out five in what is typical of his starts with the Dodgers.
The right-hander has pitched between 51/3 and 61/3 innings in each
start, but the competition wasn't the NL's strongest. He's pitched
against the Brewers twice, Florida and Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Judd's ERA is 4.94, he has kept the Dodgers in
contention, which can't be said about all their starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't as sharp as he was the other times out, but he
managed to make the pitches when he had to,'' Johnson said. ``He
gave me a good six innings.... He's made an impression on
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   What has Judd showed in his four starts?
</P>
<P>
   ``That I deserve a shot,'' the 24-year-old rookie said. ``I have
to keep going out there every single time and go after them and not
pitch afraid. You have to use your fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, if they don't want to give me a shot, then there's
not much I can do. They're in control. I'll do what they want. If I
go to the pen, I go to the pen. If they want me to start, then I'll
start. And if it's not with the Dodgers, then somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Viva, Las Vegas: For at least one more year, the Dodgers will
train at Dodgertown. But after that it's a crapshoot, and that
could lead them to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are still searching for a spring home for the 2001
season, and while a possible four-team complex in Las Vegas remains
a distant project, it is something the Dodgers will look at.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's worthwhile for us to pursue it,'' Dodgers
president and CEO Bob Graziano said. ``But a lot depends on whether
other clubs have an interest in it. It's a little more complex
situation because of the distance from the (Arizona) Cactus League
and you would need a core group of teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we're interested in, but it's a lot more
complex deal than in Florida or in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have had general discussions with other teams about
a complex in Las Vegas, but particulars haven't been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Cirillo honors Sutton: Milwaukee third baseman Jeff Cirillo, a
Providence High graduate, is wearing a ``PS'' on his hat in memory
of Providence coach Paul Sutton, for whom Cirillo played.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton died Aug.19 of colon cancer at the age of 41.
</P>
<P>
   FYI: First baseman Eric Karros, who leads the team with 29
homers and 90 RBI, missed the game for personal reasons. Todd
Hollandsworth started in his place.... Johnson said right-handed
pitchers Antonio Osuna (elbow) and Robinson Checo (groin) will make
rehab appearances for Single-A San Bernardino today.... Utility
infielder Tripp Cromer will be activated for today's game. He
hasn't played since July 4 because of an irregular heart beat....
Even though rosters expand today, Johnson said Triple-A pitchers
Jamie Arnold, Carlos Perez and Jeff Williams and Double-A's Eric
Gagne won't join the Dodgers until their respective seasons end.
Also, Triple-A infielder Alex Cora will join the Dodgers in the
next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
