<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT ROYALS 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-ROYALS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With reinforcements pouring in from the minor leagues and the
Cubbies, the Red Sox won their fifth in a row Tuesday night,
beating the Kansas City Royals, 6-3, as pitchers Mark Portugal and
Derek Lowe made their case that Jimy Williams shouldn't stray too
far from the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who added third baseman Wilton Veras from Double A
Trenton to replace John Valentin (now on the disabled list), then
traded for Cubs closer Rod Beck, rallied from a 3-2 deficit to beat
the Royals for the second straight night and maintain their
two-game advantage over Oakland in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Beck could return Lowe to his previous role of
set-up man, but given Beck's uncertain health _ he had bone chips
removed from his elbow in May _ Williams probably will leave well
enough alone until (or unless) Lowe falters.
</P>
<P>
   But Lowe, who picked up his 10th save and fifth in six chances
since Tim Wakefield went back into the starting rotation, said it
makes little difference to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care, as long as we make the playoffs,'' Lowe
said. ``I've got 10 saves this year. (Beck) had 51 last year. I
think when you acquire a closer, there's only one role a closer
does, and that's to close games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've still got to get outs. If I'm pitching in the eighth
inning, I still have to get three outs. That's not going to change.
Who said I was going to do this for the rest of my career, anyway?
This was temporary because Flash (Tom Gordon) was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beck is going to help us. I think it's a great move.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Lowe know about Beck?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's got really long hair,'' he said. ``And a good
changeup or forkball.''
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey doubled in the sixth inning and scored the tying
run on a wild pitch, and the Sox seized the lead in the seventh
when Jose Offerman, still picking on his old team, doubled and
scored on a sacrifice fly by pinch hitter Mike Stanley. The Sox
added another run in the same inning when Nomar Garciaparra
singled, stole second, and scored on Troy O'Leary's ground-rule
double, and closed the scoring in the eighth on three straight
singles, the last by pinch hitter Damon Buford.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who had 11 hits, have not homered during their winning
streak, these five games representing their longest homerless
streak of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're winning,'' Huskey said. ``That's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, whose spot in the rotation could be in jeopardy if
Ramon Martinez proves he's healthy, had lost four in a row and five
of his last six starts, but Tuesday night took a no-hitter into the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   He might have emerged with a win, too, if he hadn't adhered to
that baseball code _ either time-honored or hopelessly archaic _
that if the opposing pitcher hits your star player, you must
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal didn't hesitate. An inning after Garciaparra was
plunked in the left arm by Royals starter Jay Witasick, Portugal's
next pitch struck Chad Kreuter in the back. The no-hitter was gone
one batter later, as Jed Hansen chopped an infield single over the
head of Donnie Sadler, the rookie third baseman who made two errors
Tuesday night in place of Valentin, who was placed on the DL with
tendinitis in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Four batters later, the lead was gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   A sacrifice and infield out produced one run, and a single by
Carlos Beltran tied the score at 2. Jermaine Dye then doubled off
the center-field wall to give the Royals a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal did not stick around after the game, which could mean
(a) he had people to see, (b) he was ticked at not winning, (c)
he's already been told he's going to the bullpen. The latter would
seem premature, given the uncertain nature of what Ramon Martinez
will bring to the table Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched very, very well _ extremely well,'' said catcher
Jason Varitek, whose sixth-inning ground ball to the right side put
Huskey in position to score the tying run on the wild pitch. ``He
was extremely focused on what he was doing and finishing his
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This team knows how to win,'' said Huskey. ``We're not hitting
the ball out of the ballpark but we're still coming up with runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Runs and wins, and now Beck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you the type of dude he is,'' said Darren Lewis,
whose sacrifice bunt in the seventh put Offerman in place to score
the go-ahead run. ``He's a good guy. He's pitched in a lot of big
ballgames. He's the type of guy who's going to take the ball every
day, whether he's hurting or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
