<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIGSKY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG SKY TEAMS MAKE A RUN FOR IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three of the best single-season rushing
performances in Big Sky Conference history happened in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento State's Charles Johnsonbroke the Division I-AA record
with his total of 2,260 yards. Weber State's Morgan Welch had 1,629
and wasn't even first-team all-conference; Portland State's Charles
Dunn (1,561) nudged out Welch for second team.
</P>
<P>
   Is the Big Sky shedding its image as a pass-happy conference?
Not so fast, says Eastern Washington head coach Mike Kramer, who
said the Big Sky title will come down to who has the hottest
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's six great quarterbacks,'' Kramer said, ``and one of
those six is going to strap (his team) on his back.''
</P>
<P>
   Montana head coach Mick Dennehy, who has one of those elite six
quarterbacks in BYU transfer Drew Miller, agreed with Kramer, but
he has noticed a subtle change in philosophy. The conference's
up-and-coming programs, including the one at Cal State Northridge,
are all placing emphasis on running the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy's not worried, though. The Grizzlies, with no standout
running back, are the favorite to repeat as Big Sky winners.
</P>
<P>
   But Montana isn't reserving a spot in its trophy case yet.
Dennehy said ``four or five'' teams have a chance to win the title,
and only one team _ Idaho State, which finished last in '98 and
lost 10 starters _ isn't expected to have an impact on the title
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is playing pretty steady every week,'' Dennehy said.
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN WASHINGTON  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year: Struggled to 5-6, 4-4 in the Big Sky, after going
12-2 and going to the Division I-AA playoff semifinals in '97. The
Eagles lost their four conference games by a combined 13 points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key returnees: Junior DL Jeff Allen; junior LB Greg Belzer;
senior OL Lance Knaevelsrud. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key losses: OL T.J. Ackerman; RB Mike MacKenzie; KR Bashir
Levingston. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players to watch: QB Fred Salanoa, a JC transfer from Hawaii,
was named starter in spring. Knaevelsrud (6-4, 270) leads best OL
in Big Sky. Belzer had 132 tackles last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notable note: The Eagles' close losses in the Big Sky all came
in the fourth quarter, and each time EWU had a lead, its opponent
scored on the next possession. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Contender for Big Sky title. The Eagles return a
conference-high 19 starters, including 10 on defense. Salanoa is
being counted upon to make an immediate impact. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IDAHO STATE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year: Trying season for Bengals, who were 3-8, 2-6 and last
in the Big Sky. Head coach Tom Walsh resigned and Washington State
assistant Larry Lewis was hired. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key returnees: Senior K Pete Garces; junior QB Shane Griggs;
junior LB Jason Meador. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key losses: WR-KR DeRonn Finley; RB Craig Joseph; DB Jason
Trotter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players to watch: Griggs and sophomore Kevin McCarthy are
fighting to be starting QB. Garces was the CBS Sportsline Division
I-AA kicker of year last year after going 13 of 18. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notable note: Jacori Rufus, a starting DB last year, was killed
in a car accident in March. No Bengal will wear Rufus' No.26 until
after the 2001 season, which would have been Rufus' senior year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outlook Not good. The Bengals have had just two winning seasons
in the last 15 years. Finley, an all-conference KR, is out for the
season because of injuries he received in the crash that killed
Rufus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONTANA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year: Won share of Big Sky title and went to Division I-AA
playoffs at 8-3. Crushed by Western Illinois 52-9 in first round. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key returnees: Junior DL Tyler Martin; senior WR Jeremy Watkins;
senior LB Marcus Wilson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key losses: QB Brian Ah Yat; OL Scott Curry; OL Randy Allik. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players to watch: Drew Miller, a junior transfer from BYU, is
the next great Grizzlies QB. Watkins was first-team All-Big Sky
last year. Wilson has started 21 of UM's last 22 games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notable note: Their playoff loss last year was the Grizzlies'
worst in school history. UM trailed 31-0 in the second quarter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: UM returns 19 starters, including 10 on defense, and
Miller is one of the Big Sky's most exciting newcomers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONTANA STATE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year: Went 7-4, 5-3 in conference despite losing two of
final three games, including season finale to rival Montana. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key returnees: Senior DB Shon Flores; senior WR Chip Hobbs;
senior OL Brent Ludwig. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key losses: QB Rob Compson; LB Kevin Lundstrom; DL Ty O'Connor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players to watch: Flores, first-team All-Big Sky last year, had
20 tackles against CSUN last year. Hobbs should break school record
for career receiving yards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notable note: MSU's win total in '98 was its best since 1984.
The Bobcats also have three consecutive winning seasons for first
time in I-AA. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outlook Contender for Big Sky title. The conference championship
could come down to the Bobcats' Nov.20 home game against Montana.
MSU hasn't beaten its rival in 14 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN ARIZONA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year: Won final two games to finish 6-5 and finish over
.500 for sixth consecutive year. Only 3-5 in Big Sky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key returnees: Senior QB Travis Brown; senior LB Jake Crissup;
junior WR Francis St. Paul. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key losses: LB Afa Faraimo; LB Terrance Petty; DL Enrique
Olsen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players to watch: Junior RB Ronney Jenkins, a transfer from BYU,
rushed for 1,307 yards last year. Brown has passed for more than
300 yards in a game 13 times. Crissup is three-time All-Big Sky
academic selection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notable note: Head coach Jerome Souers picked himself as the
Lumberjacks' new defensive coordinator. Souers was the defensive
coordinator at Montana for eight years before going to NAU in '98. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outlook The Lumberjacks took their lumps last year, including a
41-10 loss at home to CSUN, but Jenkins should keep them in the
race for the Big Sky title. Faraimo tore ACL last week and is lost
for the season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PORTLAND STATE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year: Had four-game win streak at midseason, then lost last
three games and finished 5-6, 4-4 in conference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key returnees: Junior QB Jimmy Blanchard; junior WR Orshawante
Bryant; junior RB Charles Dunn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key losses: OL Bobby Singh; WR Art Williams; CB Hassan
Probherbs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players to watch: Blanchard led I-AA in passing efficiency
(167.58) last year. Dunn had 1,561 yards last year and was team
MVP. Bryant led Big Sky with 1,092 yards last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notable note: Vikings have improved each year since they joined
the Big Sky, going from three wins in '96 to five wins last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Darkhorse contender in title chase if defense improves.
PSU was second in Big Sky in scoring offense last year but eighth
in scoring defense. Also had bad turnover ratio last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO STATE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year: Rebounded from back-to-back one-win seasons to go
5-6, 3-5 in conference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key returnees: Senior OL Jon Osterhout; junior RB Charles
Roberts; OL Terence Wagner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key losses: LB Ryland Wickman; DL Dustin Smith; P Steve Thorns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players to watch: Roberts set a I-AA record with 2,260 yards
last year and scored 20 TDs. He had the third-best single season by
any Division I RB. Osterhout was first-team All-Big Sky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notable note: The Hornets' defense ranked ninth in I-AA last
year in turnover margin and ranked in the Big Sky's top four in six
categories. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Intriguing. Some feel the conference was down last
year, diminishing the Hornets' improvement. But the offense returns
10 starters, including entire offensive line. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEBER STATE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year: Won first five games, then lost five in a row before
beating rival Eastern Washington to finish 6-5, 4-4 in Big Sky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key returnees: Senior DB Wade Davis; senior RB Derek Poole;
senior RB Morgan Welch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key losses: DE Brian Edmisten; DB Scott Shields; LB David
Stroshine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players to watch: Welch rushed for a school-record 1,629 yards
in '98, but Poole's return from redshirt season gives Wildcats a
1-2 punch. Davis had 3 INTs last year and becomes leader in
secondary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Notable note: Shields, who finished his career with 23 INTs, was
Wildcats' first Big Sky Defensive Player of the Year since 1980. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Middle-of-the-pack finish in Big Sky unless WSU makes
major defensive strides. Wildcats lost eight starters from defense
that was best in conference last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
