<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE DEFENSE LESS RISKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three times the opposing offense went for the home
run _ and got it _ in Cal State Northridge's first three football
games last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors gave up a 79-yard touchdown pass in the opener
against Boise State, then allowed Eastern Washington to score on
passes of 96 and 60 yards. CSUN gave up five passing touchdowns of
46 yards or more in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   With Kansas looming on Sept.11 and Eastern Washington on
Sept.25, CSUN is planning a more conservative defensive approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew going in (last season) that we were going to play a
high-risk secondary,'' CSUN defensive coordinator Foster Andersen
said last week. ``We had to play a lot of man-to-man. Cornerbacks
get beat... it happens. Mike Haynes gave up touchdowns. Lester
Hayes gave up touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors' secondary has come together slowly. Hassan
Abdul-Malik, the projected starting free safety, missed most of
camp with a strained hamstring. Mel Miller, a senior cornerback
with two years of experience starting in the Pac-10 at Washington,
missed almost half the practices while finishing an independent
study course.
</P>
<P>
   Miller hasn't been cleared to play against Western Oregon on
Saturday in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Facing sophomore quarterback Marcus Brady, the Big Sky Newcomer
of the Year in '98, day after day in passing drills has shown the
secondary where it needs help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus is probably the best quarterback in the conference,''
defensive backs coach Brent Huff said. ``We get excited. That rises
our play all the more. It's good to have a guy like (Brady),
because you know you have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Lack of morale in facing Brady every day is not a problem _
among the starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our starters think they can go out there and shut down our
passing offense,'' Andersen said. ``They're ambitious, which is
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Addition, subtraction: Abdul-Malik was in uniform Tuesday for
the first time since his injury on Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked good and had fresh legs,'' CSUN interim head coach
Jeff Kearin said of Abdul-Malik, who started one game last year and
made 15 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, however, missed practice. Kearin said he's more
concerned about having Miller available for Big Sky Conference
games.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence man: Senior linebacker Kaleon Green's eligibility
remains uncertain, but at least there are no shortages of
linebackers on the team. If Green isn't cleared to play against
Western Oregon, linebackers coach Terrance Johnson said, the
Matadors can plug in Jack Heaslet, a senior who had 35 tackles last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Back in action: Wide receiver Ethan Beck, the Big Sky's leading
punter last year with a 40-yard average, was in uniform for the
first time since pulling a groin muscle two weeks ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
