<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLIAH-TRIAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLIAH TO BE TRIED AS SARA JANE OLSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Former Palmdale resident Kathleen Soliah won
permission to be tried as Sara Jane Olson on the 1976 charges that
she conspired with the Symbionese Liberation Army to kill Los
Angeles police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Larry Paul Fidler granted a
defense request to officially list the former fugitive as Olson,
the name she has lived under as a doctor's wife and mother of three
children in St. Paul, Minn. Court documents will now show she is
``also known as Kathleen Soliah,'' Fidler decided.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI arrested Olson in Minnesota on June 16 after an episode
of ``America's Most Wanted'' aired the story of her flight from
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Out of jail since July 20 on $1 million bail raised from
friends, neighbors and supporters around the country, Olson
attended Tuesday's hearing with her husband, Dr. Gerald ``Fred''
Peterson, in the criminal courts building downtown. At her home in
Minnesota, court-ordered video monitoring devices keep track of
her.
</P>
<P>
   After defense attorneys rejected one judge because he is a
former Los Angeles police officer, Superior Court Judge James
Ideman was assigned to preside over the trial. A hearing to set a
trial date was set for Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's San Francisco-based defense attorneys, Susan Jordan and
Stuart Hanlon, told reporters at a news conference after Tuesday's
court hearing that they expect a trial before year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very anxious to try the case,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Olson is ``anxious to get the matter behind her .
. . and go back to her regular, exemplary life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence includes a fingerprint of Olson's found at a Bay
Area house where the SLA made bombs, said District Attorney's
Office spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons. Prosecutors haven't revealed what
evidence ties Olson directly to the August 1975 attempted bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't discuss specifics of evidence,'' Gibbons said. The two
bombs are in LAPD custody, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Olson faces a sentence of life in prison with the possibility of
parole if she's convicted of all five counts against her stemming
from the August 1975 attempted bombings, said Gibbons.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether heiress Patty Hearst would be called as a witness,
Jordan and Hanlon said that will be up to the prosecution. The SLA
kidnapped Hearst in February 1974 but she later participated in a
bank holdup with the group, was arrested and convicted and spent
two years in prison. She is reportedly reluctant to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I think it would be awful to make her testify if
she's reluctant,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mentioned in court that Hearst is a potential
witness,'' Gibbons said, adding that the District Attorney's Office
can't say yet whether it will call her or not.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
