<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-BUSINESSES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST_GROWING BUSINESS SECTOR UPBEAT ABOUT GROWTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Latino-owned firms, already among the
fastest-growing business segments in Southern California, may be
the most optimistic as well, according to a study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study of large Latino businesses by the nonprofit Tomas
Rivera Policy Institute found that nearly 74 percent of those firms
expect sales to grow in the next year. Only 1 percent said they
anticipate a decline.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was based on responses from 273 Southern California
businesses with sales of $1 million or more and a majority of
Latino ownership. The Latin Business Association commissioned the
survey in conjunction with its fourth annual Latino Business Expo
at the Los Angeles Convention Center, which opens Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Waldo Lopez-Aqueres, director of economic policy research for
the institute, which is affiliated with the Claremont Graduate
University, said the health of larger Latino-owned companies is an
important indicator of the broader market.
</P>
<P>
   Although only about 1 percent of Latino-owned firms have sales
greater than $1 million, those firms account for nearly half of
sales and employment, according to Lopez-Aqueres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very important segment,'' he said. ``It's dynamic. It
has longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   Latino-owned firms may have good reason to be bullish on the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth of the Latino population and support networks
for Latino-owned businesses _ including trade associations _ are
giving those firms a strong foundation for success, said John
Tumpak, a spokesman for the Los Angeles office of the U.S. Small
Business Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole outlook for Hispanic-owned small businesses is
better than it has ever been,'' Tumpak said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the study's other findings:
</P>
<P>
   Extrapolating from 1987-1992 government data, the study
estimated that the number of Latino-owned firms in Southern
California grew by more than 150 percent between 1992 and 1999. The
current total, the study estimated, is around 440,000.
</P>
<P>
   About 63 percent of firms surveyed offer health benefits to
their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Firms in the survey with mostly Latino work forces were less
likely than others to offer life insurance, health insurance or
401(k) plans to their employees.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
