<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY PMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Dili, Indonesia) _ The anti-independence thugs
who have terrorized East Timor for months reasserted themselves
Tuesday, one day after an extraordinarily peaceful referendum in
which officials said 98.6 percent of eligible voters had cast their
ballots. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ACCORD (Lusaka, Zambia) _ The divided rebels in Congo
finally signed a peace agreement, a key step toward ending the
fighting but only the start toward reconstructing one of Africa's
biggest, richest and least stable nations. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-POLITICS (Caracas, Venezuela) _ President Hugo Chavez
moved to solidify his control over the powerful state-run oil
monopoly Tuesday by naming an ally as the company's new chief as
the country's political crisis continued By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Istanbul, Turkey) _ A strong tremor shook already
devastated towns in northwestern Turkey on Tuesday, bringing
several buildings crashing down and causing at least one death. By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DAGESTAN (Moscow) _ A powerful explosion rocked Moscow's
fanciest shopping center Tuesday night, bringing the threat of
terrorism to the foot of the Kremlin. The explosion coincided with
an upsurge in the fighting in Dagestan and provoked anxious
speculation that Islamic militants might have begun a series of
terrorist attacks against the seat of Russian power. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   LAUNDER-MANSION (Undated) _ Last September a California mansion
once occupied by Hollywood star Eddie Murphy was sold for $6.75
million _ in cash _ to a company controlled by the former Ukrainian
prime minister, Pavlo Lazarenko. But Lazarenko has not moved in; he
is in a U.S. detention center fighting a Swiss extradition request
on charges of looting millions from his homeland. With the U.S.
investigation of the billions of dollars moving through the Bank of
New York from Russia, there is increased concern in the West that
ill-gotten gains from Russia or other parts of the Soviet Union are
infiltrating the United States and Europe. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DEBT (Tokyo) _ One of the striking paradoxes of Japan is
that this is a country with the greatest savers in the
industrialized world, and yet everywhere one looks there is debt.
As a nation, this country has some of the worst accounts in the
industrialized world, and its debt trajectory increasingly looks
like that of a third world country like Tanzania. By Sheryl WuDunn
and Nicholas D. Kristof. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-ANNIVERSARY (London) _ Two years after the death of Diana,
princess of wales, on Aug. 31, 1997, Britons are struck by how
quickly the woman whose funeral drew the largest television
audience in history has come to be overlooked in her own land, how
swiftly buttoned-up royal reserve has returned and how few of the
societal changes that were so confidently forecast then have
actually taken place.By Warren Hoge. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-INFECTED (Undated) _ Death rates from AIDS in the
United States are no longer falling as rapidly as they did from
1995 to 1997, health officials at a national AIDS conference in
Atlanta said this week. New infections of the virus that causes it
were characterized by these officials as ``dangerously high'' among
minority gay men and heterosexual women, especially minority women.
Health care experts said swelling ranks of teen-agers and black and
nonwhite Hispanic men and women have also been walking through
clinic doors. By Jennifer Steinhauer. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-PRISONERS (Undated) _ The prevalence of AIDS among
prisoners in the United States is five times that of the population
at large, and the rates of other sexually transmitted diseases
among inmates are very high, scientists said in reporting the first
comprehensive study of these diseases in correctional facilities at
a meeting in Atlanta on Tuesday. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SAT-SCORES (Undated) _ Scores on the College Board exams
remained roughly constant last year compared with the previous
year, as boys continued to outscore girls by more than 40 points
and white students continued to do better than underrepresented
minorities, according to figures released Tuesday by the College
Board. By Karen W. Arenson. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-SHOOTING (New York) _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani Tuesday
defended the fatal police shooting of a mentally disturbed,
hammer-wielding man in the Borough Park section of Brooklyn, which
brought hundreds of angry Hasidic protesters into the streets of
the heavily Orthodox neighborhood late Monday night. By John Kifner
and Michael Cooper. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARCH (New York) _ A federal judge ruled Tuesday that Khallid
Abdul Muhammad, the self-professed successor to Malcolm X, may hold
a youth rally in Harlem, saying city officials had no right to use
the content of Muhammad's inflammatory speeches as a basis for
denying him a rally permit. By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KEYES-PROFILE (Greenville, S.C.) _ As he wanders the nation
prophesying a political apocalypse, Alan L. Keyes, the staunchly
conservative radio talk show host, is the invisible man in the race
for the Republican presidential nomination. But to his small yet
devoted cadre of followers, Keyes is the best kept secret of the
campaign. To them, Keyes, a former Reagan administration diplomat
with a Harvard Ph.D., has something his fellow conservatives lack:
mesmerizing oratorical skills twinned with a messianic vision. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   MCCONNELL-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ Sen. Mitch McConnell, one
of Congress' most ardent opponents of a bill that would overhaul
the campaign finance system, has aggressively urged 10 business
executives to resign from an organization that has endorsed a wide
array of reforms, including the banning of soft money. By Don Van
Natta. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WACO-INQUIRY (Washington) _ Hoping to head off any impression of
a conflict of interest, Director Louis J. Freeh of the FBI
wholeheartedly supports an outside investigation into the bureau's
failure to disclose the use of incendiary devices at the 1993 siege
of the Branch Davidian compound, a bureau spokesman said Tuesday
night. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR (Undated) _ The American dollar, which dropped again
Tuesday against the Japanese yen and the new euro, has begun a
moderate slide that could continue for the rest of the year as
economies in Asia and Europe rebound while the United States, under
the drag of higher interest rates, slows down. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BEANIES-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The maker of Beanie Babies, Ty
Inc., created a frenzy Tuesday when it posted this announcement on
its World Wide Web site: ``All Beanies will be retired'' as of Dec.
31. Customers, professional Beanie traders and even the company's
own employees were dumbfounded. By Dana Canedy. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-ECON (Paris) _ Total Fina's hostile bid for Elf Aquitaine
and a three-way bank brawl have been the latest illustrations of
how much French business has changed. In the last two years, France
has moved to shake up and slim down its corporate world. As a
result, France has become a darling of foreign investors. By John
Tagliabue. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   WALLSTREET-MERGERS (New York) _ Though many investors think it
is just a matter of time before America's big securities houses
hook up with banks, Wall Street firms are proving to be reluctant
merger partners. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ While traditional retailers
report changes in sales for stores open at least one year,
providing analysts a way to evaluate whether growth is real or
merely a construct, online merchants offer no such equivalent. By
Leslie Kaufman. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Kato Kaelin, the shaggy blond pool
boy-moocher of the O.J. trial is doing great. He is developing a TV
talk show called ``The 16th Minute,'' about people, much like
himself, who keep going after they have had their 15 minutes of
fame. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PAVAROTTI-TAXES (Paris) _ Luciano Pavarotti has paid an
undisclosed sum to a German court to settle a tax evasion case
arising from a lucrative world tour by the so-called Three Tenors
in 1996, the prosecutor's office in Mannheim, Germany, has
announced. Placido Domingo reached a similar settlement last week.
By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PRINCE-EDWARD (Los Angeles) _ Britain's Prince Edward has
plans to produce for American TV. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   TATE-EXHIBIT (London) _ London's Tate Gallery exhibits
contemporary art that isn't home-made: ``Abracadabra: International
Contemporary Art.'' By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-USOPEN-SAMPRAS (New York) _ A devastated Pete Sampras,
unshaved, unhappy and unable to make sense of the stabbing pain
that settled into his lower back during a Sunday morning practice,
announced his withdrawal from the U.S. Open Tuesday because of a
herniated disk in his lower back. By Robin Finn. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ The fans scurry around the
premises, looking for upsets, looking for interesting new players,
chasing down phenomena like Alexandra Stevenson suffering a sundown
massacre. Since Alexandra Stevenson burst into the public domain at
Wimbledon this summer, Open fans have been waiting for a glimpse of
her. Sports of The Times column by George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-USOPEN (New York) _ The U.S. Open Tuesday extracted its
usual emotional baggage from the combatants who took to the
wind-blown hardcourts at the National Tennis Center: frayed nerves,
gray hairs, stage fright and the mean streak that sets in when a
defending Grand Slam champion finds a friend blocking her passage
to the second round of a title defense. By Robin Finn. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-UMPIRES _ (Undated) A long day in a judge's chambers in
Philadelphia brought lawyers for Major League Baseball and its
umpires close to a deal Tuesday on the status of umpires who face
the loss of their jobs Wednesday, a lawyer familiar with the
general outline of the talks said. By Murray Chass. With photo.
</P>
