<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DID MAYOR'S PANEL EARN ITS BLUE RIBBON?
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One question I hope will be answered by Willie
Brown's blue-ribbon panel, appointed by the mayor to investigate
what the FBI has been investigating for several months, is how the
panel got its blue ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   Fattest pig at the county fair? Fastest car in the Pinewood
Derby?
</P>
<P>
   I worry about a panel that claims to have a blue ribbon before
it has whacked its first gavel.
</P>
<P>
   If it does a great job, does the blue-ribbon panel get upgraded
to platinum?
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has vowed to leave no stone unturned, and what's
underneath should keep biologists busy for months.
</P>
<P>
   That vow reminds my pal Lotta Dotz of the credo of the local
fitness community: Leave no stern un-toned.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, there's no gain without pain. Your goal is buns of
steel, but sometimes, you wind up with your ass in a sling.
</P>
<P>
   And since the mayor's panel has been impaneled to investigate
the alleged wrongdoings in several city agencies headed by mayoral
appointees, not to mention some key people fairly close to the
mayor, the next question is:
</P>
<P>
   Will we eventually need a blue-ribbon panel to investigate the
blue-ribbon panel?
</P>
<P>
   UNCLEAR on the concept: You know those public trash cans that
have a wire bin at the top for bottles, cans and other recyclables?
</P>
<P>
   Alma O'Brien, strolling near Geary and 21st, wonders what part
of the system the collection guys don't understand. She saw a
Sunset Scavenger truck crew dump the contents of the wire basket
into the trash bin, then dump everything into the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they sort it all out later, during their lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T BRING me your lame excuses for being tardy, Rosemary
Jacobs warned her English students last week on the first day of
class at Washington High.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day, student John Doe was late and presented
Jacobs with a note from the traffic cop who gave John a speeding
ticket on the way to school. ``Dear Teacher, please excuse John
...''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lesson there somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   JUST WHEN so many people are asking, ``How come there's no
Industrial Gothic Fetish Dance Night?'' the Blue Lagoon in Santa
Cruz steps up to fill the void on Monday nights.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're bored with the polka ...
</P>
<P>
   And it's got to be more interesting than Monday Night Practice
Football, 49ers' Third Stringers vs. Raiders' Wannabees.
</P>
<P>
   Where do ticket holders from that game go to get refunds for a
game between bitter rivals who exhibited no bitterness and inspired
no exciting brawls in the stands or parking lots?
</P>
<P>
   If you bought tickets for that game, pal, send me $5, and I'll
send you a ticket to watch the blip-races on the radar screen some
morning in Muni's Metro-tracking control room ($7 for VIP seating).
</P>
<P>
   YOU COULD SEE more exciting football in Y.A. Tittle's backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The former 49ers quarterback, now an insurance exec who lives in
Atherton, was tossing the old pigskin around his lawn with Gary
Ross, a general contractor. Tittle hit Ross with a dozen
consecutive perfecto spiral bullets.
</P>
<P>
   And Y.A. is 72 damn years old.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the Niners  &UR; do  &LR; need a reliable backup QB. And Y.A. is
already insured.
</P>
<P>
   CHEAP PUBLICITY stunts aren't dead. They're not even cheap.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Francis Hotel kicked out the jams Tuesday to announce
the equipping of all Westin hotel rooms with a new kind of bed so
comfortable that you won't want to get out of it, and probably
couldn't if you wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   My belief (possibly my only one) is that the last thing a hotel
needs is comfortable beds. Traveler, if you haven't worked hard
enough or played hard enough to sleep like a baby on the cold
bathroom tile, you've been cheating yourself and /or your boss.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the Harlem Gospel Singers sang at the press conference,
and Willie Brown Himself dropped by.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Willie would know about beds. He once told me he sleeps
four hours per night, and my guess is that he does it standing up,
so as not to wrinkle his jammies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
