<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke, ESPN unveil Super Bowl strategy
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. and ESPN cable sports network are
planning a big splash leading up to the Super Bowl in Atlanta with
a week of live shows at the World of Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   During the week preceding the Jan. 30 game, the beverage giant
and ESPN will be setting up two temporary TV studios, as well as a
football festival area between the downtown Coke attraction and
nearby Georgia Railroad Freight Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of viewers will be tuning in during the buildup to pro
football's crowning event as Coke hosts three ESPN shows:
SportsCenter, NFL 2Night and NFL Countdown.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, thousands of fans who will never get the chance to
see the big game at the Georgia Dome are expected to congregate at
the World of Coke, tossing footballs, watching on-air personalities
such as Chris Berman and Tom Jackson, and, of course, drinking
Coke.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, metro Atlantans will get the chance to win ESPN studio
tickets starting in October, when Coca-Cola launches a special
local promotion tied to its premier brand, Coke Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had an opportunity to see what Coke can do around big
events, and this is yet another example of what they're able to do
to enhance the experience for visitors, as well as people who live
here,'' said Robert Dale Morgan, president of the Metro Atlanta
Super Bowl XXXIV Host Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch what Coke does around mega-events, you can see
why they are regarded as the best marketer in the world,'' Morgan
said.
</P>
<P>
   That marketer has been planning its Super Bowl strategy for more
than a year, and its partnership with ESPN is the centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about being red. It's about being relevant,'' said
Steve Koonin, vice president of consumer marketing and the
architect of the program. ``We want to give people in Atlanta
access to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Koonin is a strong believer that ``presence marketing'' _ giving
fans and consumers an experience to remember _ is one of the keys
to driving beverage sales. In fact, the company has no plans to
advertise during the game, when a 30-second spot will run about
$1.6 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several Super Bowls, Koonin said, Coca-Cola has
seen its biggest domestic sales boost for the first quarter in the
game's host city.
</P>
<P>
   He said that is largely because of all the resources the company
pours into trying to make the game memorable for as many fans as
possible. Fans who do not win studio tickets to the ESPN shows will
be able to see the live broadcasts on a jumbo screen in the World
of Coke's plaza area.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 15,000 to 40,000 people go to Super Bowl cities without
ever planning to get a game ticket,'' said Morgan, of the Host
Committee. ``With Coke doing this, it gives Atlanta another dynamic
happening downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   The events are also likely to give a needed attendance pop to
Underground Atlanta, which is located right next to the World of
Coke.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN said it tries to pick Super Bowl broadcasting sites that
reflect the host city. One of the TV studios will be constructed
just outside the World of Coke, while the other will be stationed
inside the Georgia Railroad Freight Depot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to give people a sense of where you are,'' said Bob
Rauscher, a senior producer at ESPN. ``It's Coke's town.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney-owned ESPN will not be broadcasting the game. That will
be done by ABC, which Disney also owns.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
