<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge denies eagle feathers for Fla. man's Indian ceremonies
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There is no doubt that Harvey ``Fire
Bird'' Gibson is a Creek Indian, no less native to America than a
Seminole or a Sioux.
</P>
<P>
   But the Delray Beach man's request to own eagle feathers for
religious ceremonies has been denied by a federal judge who said it
would violate a law designed in part to nurture American Indian
customs and ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, 68, filed a lawsuit four years ago against the federal
government seeking to obtain five eagle feathers for daily prayers,
death ceremonies and other spiritual rites. The lawsuit forced the
court to unravel the knot where issues of American Indian rights
meet with conservation laws.
</P>
<P>
   Bald and golden eagles are protected by law, and possession of
one alive or dead is a crime. Eagle feathers and talons are also
considered sacred to many Native American tribes. The government
allows tribes to obtain eagle feathers for ceremonies, but only
from a repository for eagle parts in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   But Gibson can't get any feathers because his branch of the
Creeks _ those that stayed east while the rest of the tribe was
driven west by white settlers in the 1830s _ is not among the 550
tribes formally recognized by the government.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, U.S. District Judge Daniel T.K. Hurley said that
distinction, which Gibson calls unfair, is necessary to protect the
stock of eagle parts for all tribes, and to maintain the
government's Indian treaties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providing bald and golden eagle parts to members of federally
recognized tribes is an important step toward preserving the
religious heritage of Native Americans,'' Hurley wrote in his
ruling. ``Allowing members of non-federally recognized Indian
tribes to apply for eagle parts would create difficult issues of
proof that would significantly inhibit the implementation of the
regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the judge did not question Gibson's sincerity, saying he is
``truly deserving'' of the feathers, and calling Gibson's current
practice of using turkey feathers ``akin to using colored water for
sacramental wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson has appealed the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only people in the world that have to walk around
with an ID card saying we are Indian,'' Gibson said Tuesday. ``They
can write all the laws in the world but they can't change my
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
