<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doing the crime but not the time
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Did he or didn't he? Only Gov. George W.
Bush knows for sure, and he isn't telling. At least not everything
curious minds want to know.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Texas and would-be next president says he hasn't
taken drugs in 25 years. That leaves 28 years of his life
unaccounted for. Let's consider that during that youthful period he
tried cocaine. Let's suppose, as his hemming and hawing suggests,
he indulged in this illegal drug for recreation and overcame this
problem. He admits that drawing upon religious faith, he summoned
the resolve to give up drinking in 1986. Perhaps the same source of
strength worked against illegal drugs. Whatever the reason he
gained total sobriety, he declares he's been clean of drug use for
over two decades. Parents and loved ones of other youthful drug
users who took a playful walk on the wild side and got stuck there
applaud Mr. Bush's achievement and want a national drug policy that
will help rescue more of their kind who slipped along the way.
</P>
<P>
   We are told that baby boomers who experimented with marijuana
and cocaine and survived the experience without permanent addiction
are faced with the dilemma of whether to admit to their kids that
they used illegal drugs. Gov. Bush advises against such candor. He
says confession would ``send a signal that whatever I may have done
is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Moral standards would be sacrificed, he would have us believe,
as kids would mistakenly conclude playing around with drugs is just
another inconsequential rite of passage. Like most of us, he knows
that error could be fatal. Most illegal drugs are illegal because
of their potential powers to permanently ensnare their hosts and
destroy abilities to function except to satisfy cravings.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the newsworthy story is not whether Mr. Bush has ever used
cocaine nor that those who question him are indulging in what he
calls ``the politics of personal destruction.'' The issue that
needs to be acknowledged is our society has accepted illegal drug
use as a risky behavior to be condemned and punished only if
discovered among average citizens and to be tolerated and winked at
among people of wealth and status.
</P>
<P>
   This hypocrisy has sabotaged the war on drugs. Mr. Bush's
example only affirms the reality that a George W. Bush can walk
away from cocaine to lead a state and possibly a country. A John
Doe who uses and becomes mired in the drug culture inherits a more
ominous fate. Yet, undeniably, both users created the drug market
and caused the industry to grow into a lucrative business that
spawns crime from mean streets to banking corporations and beyond.
An affluent Mr. Bush has the resources and connections to fight his
drug problem in private. An impoverished Mr. Doe is more likely to
be incarcerated and tagged with a criminal record that limits
employment possibilities. Any attempt to rid our society of drugs
must address this double standard.
</P>
<P>
   Our children (who can cite a litany of the rich and famous who
pass through the Betty Ford Clinic) know the legal system rarely
severely punishes drug offenders with social status. That
knowledge, more than any confessions by parents, instructs that
drug use is OK.
</P>
<P>
   The exquisite irony is that the way our system works, the drug
experimenters who go unpunished for their drug offenses often gain
positions that allow them to design the punishment for those who
get caught. So far, having been there, done that, has not
influenced compassion. In 1997, Gov. Bush signed a provision
authorizing Texas judges to jail people convicted of possessing or
selling less than one gram (1/28th of an ounce) of cocaine. A
tough-on-crime reputation wins votes. As does a national drug
policy to build more prisons to hold nonviolent, small-time drug
users and sellers. The dominant and ineffectual strategy of our
drug war is to attack the addicted foot soldiers, leaving the
officers untouched and the infrastructure intact.
</P>
<P>
   The newsworthy story, if we would focus on it, is not politics
as usual, but the political manipulation of drug policy to gain
votes instead of solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
