<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tapping the reed-whistlers for `The Remote'
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I've begun the push to attract musical and dance
support from the Austin arts community for my upcoming spoken word
and dance production, ``The Remote.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ain't got no artists, you ain't got no art, right?
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, I fired off the following letter to Peggy Gunn,
development director of the Austin Symphony in hopes of getting
those reed-whistlers involved in the project. Here's the letter:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Ms. Gunn:
</P>
<P>
   ``On Friday, Nov. 26, on a vacant lot next to the Hog-Eye Bait
House on Lake Walter E. Long, if all goes according to plan, 100
men will sit in recliners watching the Texas-Texas A&AMP;M game on
television as part of a male statement spoken word and dance
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date we have lined up the Blazing Bows, a group of fiddlers
ages 5 to 16 taught by Mary Hattersley, to play 'Are You Ready for
Some Football,' the Hank Williams Jr. classic heard Monday nights
across America. We would be honored to have Austin Symphony
Director Peter Bay and an ensemble of 8-10 pieces from the symphony
accompany the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kickoff is at 10 a.m. There will be rehearsals _ well, OK,
maybe a rehearsal _ before the actual event is held. (The rehearsal
date has yet to be determined.) Kinky Friedman says he will attend
a rehearsal. We are still looking for a choreographer. We hope to
find someone from the University of Texas in a ponytail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for your interest in this artistic endeavor. We surely
would appreciate the symphony's help in this matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sincerely,
</P>
<P>
   ``John Kelso''
</P>
<P>
   I wait anxiously for a reply from the symphony. And if any of
you guys who dance on your toes want to help out, give me a holler.
</P>
<P>
   We are asking guys who take part in the TV watching part of
``The Remote'' to please bring their own recliners.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some of you men who plan to sit around watching football in
``The Remote'' may be thinking about buying the revolutionary $899
La-Z-Boy recliner with the beer cooler built into the arm.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I don't think I would buy this chair. Unless you are
a wienie, the cooler, built into the chair's left arm, doesn't hold
enough beer to get you through a football game.
</P>
<P>
   The cooler holds just six 12-ounce cans.
</P>
<P>
   If your brother-in-law is sitting within reaching distance of
your La-Z-Boy, that's only enough beer to make it through the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   What was La-Z-Boy thinking when it designed this chair cooler? I
thought the concept here _ a major part of the American dream _ was
to create a chair that makes it possible for men to watch an entire
game without having to go to the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   This chair needs help. In fact, not only does the cooler hold
just six 12-ounce cans, it isn't even deep enough to squeeze in a
12-ounce longneck in the upright position.
</P>
<P>
   If the La-Z-Boy engineers didn't have prunes for brains, they
would have created a chair with a keg in each arm, a chair that
comes with a ``trucker's friend'' so that you never have to leave
the chair, unless you are being subpoenaed.
</P>
<P>
   I'll keep you informed on the details of ``The Remote.''
Meanwhile, watch plenty of football so you can get in shape for the
big day.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes a humor column for the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
