r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN02-COX     09-01 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart family's `adventure' leaves a sea-sick feeling
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As a community, our reaction to the safe return
of the Stewart family resembles that of parents of errant
teen-agers who came home too late from a party they weren't allowed
to attend in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   First, we want to hug them: Thank God, you're home, safe and
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we want to scold them: What on earth were you thinking,
going off adventuring in a marginally seaworthy ship? Taking your
two children with you? Do you have any idea how worried we were?
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, though, you can't be too hard on the Stewart
family. They're merely reflecting a culture in which a popular
T-shirt boasts ``No Fear.'' A culture in which we expect nature to
be a playground for our adventures, prepackaged with thrills but no
danger.
</P>
<P>
   We are amazed when small planes crash in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   We are amazed when gravity-defying amusement park rides
malfunction and claim lives.
</P>
<P>
   We are amazed when an extreme sport such as canyoning _ which,
as best I can tell from the diagram, involves roping down into a
river gorge and leaping from rock to rock like crazed frogs _ turns
deadly in Switzerland, claiming 19 tourists in a flash flood. How
could it happen? Hadn't they paid exorbitant fees to a reputable
``adventure company''?
</P>
<P>
   If we pay enough money, we reason, nature's ride should come
absolutely risk-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are moving into the adventure of our lives,''
Richard Stewart wrote in an e-mail to the online Aboard Magazine.
``See you on the high seas!''
</P>
<P>
   Parents traditionally provide the voice of reason, of restraint,
the ones pulling in the reins on their coltishly reckless children.
More and more, in the baby boomer generation, we are seeing the
reverse: It was Lloyd Dubroff, remember, who encouraged his
7-year-old daughter, Jessica _ four-foot-two, 55 pounds _ to pursue
``her'' dream of becoming the youngest person to fly across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, all parents must perform a delicate dance between
caretaker and killjoy, a careful risktaker and a careless gambler.
No doubt I'm one of those parents who errs on the side of caution.
``Oh, Mom,'' my son complained recently, when I unreasonably
refused to let him play outside in a lightning storm, ``you're so
overprotective.''
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, kid, hurt my feelings. Certainly nobody could accuse
the Stewarts of being overprotective, sailing off without a float
plan on a boat that had been grounded by engine trouble for the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a ball,'' Richard said of the month the family spent
oblivious to the Coast Guard's three-day, $75,000 search and the
frantic state of relatives on shore.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the Jolly Joyce had sent the Coast Guard on a
not-so-jolly chase, Richard Stewart vowed to come in on his own
power and made light of the Coast Guard's request to call in every
30 minutes. ``We'd gone 900 miles on our own. If we would get to
shore we're going to do it on our own,'' his wife, Debra, quoted
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Nature interfered, as nature has a way of doing. The Jolly
Joyce, after losing all steering and the use of its engines, was
towed in by a 47-foot motor lifeboat.
</P>
<P>
   Carter Stewart, Richard's 27-year-old son, referred questions to
his father and stepmother: ``It's their drama, let them act in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, these dramas don't take place on an empty stage.
In this case, a 12-year-old and a 16-year-old were dragged into the
cast, not to mention dozens of Coast Guard rescuers and an anxious
community.
</P>
<P>
   The ending may be a happy one, but it leaves those of us on
shore with a queasy feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
