r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX     09-01 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No more same ol' same ol'
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``Politics should be put aside. Either Congress or
the president should initiate an independent investigation into an
event that began and ended in tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   I wrote those words in a column on April 20, 1993, while the
embers that covered the charred bodies of 76 men, women and
children at the Branch Davidians' Mount Carmel compound still
smoldered.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spin doctors and wind testers warned him to keep a low
profile. Let Attorney
</P>
<P>
   General Janet Reno, Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen and others
fade the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Congress also laid low following the fatally botched Feb. 28
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms raid and during the 51-day FBI siege.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to spot a political advantage, Congress members
studiously avoided an incident
</P>
<P>
   that had gathered a worldwide audience, including a swelling of
hard-core anti-government conspiracy nuts.
</P>
<P>
   After Reno's decision to cut off negotiations and gas the
compound went terribly wrong,
</P>
<P>
   Republicans suddenly wanted to launch congressional probes to
embarrass Clinton and his
</P>
<P>
   new administration.
</P>
<P>
   While Congress was involved in a head-butting standoff, Bentsen
was the only person in
</P>
<P>
   Washington with the backbone to do what was right for the
country. He ordered an independent investigation of ATF actions at
Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, either on her own or as a result of her endless supply of
bad advice, decided to investigate herself and the FBI, which
reports to her.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's self-investigation turned out to be an obvious whitewash.
Now that new evidence reveals that Reno and FBI officials misled
Congress and the public, Republicans again see
</P>
<P>
   a chance to embarrass Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has promised a new self-investigation. Clinton has issued
more platitudes and again
</P>
<P>
   retreated behind Reno's skirt.
</P>
<P>
   Same ol', same ol'.
</P>
<P>
   It's a waste of time, if not delusional, to ask Congress to
conduct a fair, impartial and nonpartisan investigation.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one way for the American public to ever receive a
credible report about what really happened leading up to the
decision to initiate the botched ATF raid and the
</P>
<P>
   decisions and actions that culminated in the deadly April 19
inferno.
</P>
<P>
   There needs to be a groundswell of public sentiment for an
independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Such a groundswell would be picked up immediately by the instant
and omnipresent public
</P>
<P>
   opinion polls that substitute for principled decisions by
today's Washington politicians.
</P>
<P>
   What is needed is an independent panel that investigates and
reports on the entire series of events pertaining to government
actions involving the Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation first needs to examine government decisions to
ignore reports of statutory rape, physical and psychological abuse
of children, polygamy and sham marriages within the cult. Those
reports and government decisions to ignore them were made two years
before the initial raid.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the military needs to be investigated since it
relied on baseless evidence of a
</P>
<P>
   methamphetamine lab at Mount Carmel. The meth lab evidence was
an obvious ruse that
</P>
<P>
   was used right up to the very end to justify assistance from the
super-secret Delta Force,
</P>
<P>
   whose commandos were at the scene the final day.
</P>
<P>
   Who made off with the steel front door of the building, and why?
Was Reno really misinformed time after time? If so, who is
responsible?
</P>
<P>
   Without this sort of top-to-bottom impartial investigation,
conspiracy nuts will thrive while the credibility in critical
government operations will wither.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
