<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6966 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GRASS02-COX     09-01 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRASS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Splendor in the grass
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Craig and Valerie Coleman, who had their new
house built in 1997, give some of the credit for the lush lawn to
neighbors who built in their subdivision before them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our neighbors encouraged us to get a sprinkler system, and we
did,'' Craig Coleman said. ``It comes on at about 4 a.m. and sprays
each zone in the yard for about 25 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said his experienced neighbors also suggested that he
find a commercial building site and ask the builders for topsoil.
He hired a truck and collected topsoil from the site of a nearby
Target store.
</P>
<P>
   ``They let me take away 10 truckloads of soil,'' he said. ``I
only paid a couple hundred dollars for the truck and a driver.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coleman family succeeded in establishing their lawn by
tackling two major problems that can stymie grass growth:
inadequate water and poor soil.
</P>
<P>
   Many people choose not to water their lawns in summer, allowing
them to go tan and dormant. Others have watered, maybe sporadically
or improperly, and their lawns are still in bad shape as a dry, hot
summer draws to a close.
</P>
<P>
   And still others have lawn problems unrelated to the heat, such
as shady patches that won't grow or heavy-traffic spots that are
worn bald.
</P>
<P>
   Mid- to late September and early October are good times for lawn
repair or replacement. A lawn and garden worker is a good source of
detailed information on improving your lawn, but we'll give you a
few guidelines today to help you get started.
</P>
<P>
   Soil
</P>
<P>
   If you're having trouble with your grass or if you have a new
home that has never had a lawn, you should have your soil tested to
see if it has everything it needs to support grass.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Fender, executive director of Turfgrass Producers
International, a sod industry group, said when home builders enter
a site they often strip away the topsoil because it's soft and
hampers the use of heavy equipment. They then dig a hole for a
foundation and spread the soil from deep underground across the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're basically turning the yard upside down,'' he said.
``They're replacing topsoil with all its organic material and
nutrients with soil that's never supported life.''
</P>
<P>
   A soil-testing laboratory can analyze your soil and tell you
what it needs to sustain a healthy lawn. Call Holmes Laboratories
at (800) 344-1101 for help. Holmes personnel instruct callers on
preparing a soil sample and can supply results and recommendations
in about two weeks for about $12.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Lane, director of the extension office in Montgomery
County, said the heavy clay soils common in this area often need
the addition of organic material such as humus, compost or manure.
Tilling in organic material loosens the naturally dense soil and
provides nutrients to help the grass grow.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy soils also benefit from humus, compost or manure, Lane
said. The organic material promotes growth and helps hold loose
sandy soil together.
</P>
<P>
   But if your lawn is already growing in heavy clay soil, Fender
and Lane say the best way to dramatically improve the quality of
your grass is aeration. Aeration involves poking holes in the soil
to promote the flow of air, water and nutrients below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to do the job is to rent a gas-powered
core-aerating machine; the machines are a bit larger than average
lawn mowers and run about $50 to $75 a day at tool-rental
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The type of aerator you should look for has hollow, tubelike
tines on a rotating drum. As the drum turns the tines dig out small
plugs of dirt and drop them on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Before using an aerator, cut the grass as short as possible
without scalping it. You then run the aerator over the yard,
leaving plugs of grass and soil as you go.
</P>
<P>
   The lawn will look awful immediately after the treatment, but
run the lawn mower again to break up the plugs or water the lawn to
start dissolving them. They'll be less noticeable as the grass
grows around them.
</P>
<P>
   Grasses
</P>
<P>
   Lane said almost all the grass in the Dayton area is of four
species: bluegrass, tall fescue, fine fescue (sometimes called red
fescue) and perennial rye grass. Most bags of grass seed contain
either blends or mixtures.
</P>
<P>
   A blend contains several varieties (sometimes called cultivars)
of the same grass species. A bag of bluegrass blend, for example,
would contain all bluegrass seeds, but several varieties of
bluegrass would be included.
</P>
<P>
   A grass-seed mixture contains more than one species. Some
mixtures even contain annual grasses that germinate quickly to give
you a green look quickly, then die at first frost. All the seeds in
a mixture will grow if cared for properly, and the types best
suited to conditions in your yard will become dominant.
</P>
<P>
   The type of grass you should choose depends on conditions in
your yard, how you want the grass to look and how much maintenance
you want to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Bluegrass, properly tended, produces a thick, even lawn.
Bluegrass spreads by sending runners along the surface of the
ground so it naturally fills gaps.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, bluegrass has fairly shallow roots and
doesn't perform as well in dry conditions as other grasses. If you
choose bluegrass, expect to do more watering and fertilizing to
keep it healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Tall fescue is hardier than bluegrass, but some people don't
like it as well. Rather than spreading, tall fescue tends to grow
in patches that can leave gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Tall fescue has deep roots that help it withstand drought and is
the preferred grass if you're not good at watering.
</P>
<P>
   Zoysia grass is sometimes advertised for its drought resistance,
but its brown fall and spring color is not acceptable to most
homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said perennial rye grass also stands up to drought fairly
well. Instead of deep roots, like tall fescue, perennial rye grass
has a glossy coating on the blades of grass that help it retain
water.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said some people love the glossy look of rye grass, but he
warns that damp rye grass can be slippery, so it's not recommended
for high-traffic areas.
</P>
<P>
   Fine fescue is a thin-bladed grass that is more shade tolerant
than the other species, and it may grow where other grasses won't.
</P>
<P>
   Solving problems
</P>
<P>
   If you don't water a lawn during the hot, dry months of summer,
it will stop growing and turn brown until wetter weather in the
fall. If your lawn has gone dormant, it should recover on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Until it does, don't apply fertilizer or weed killers. Let it
grow a little higher than normal and make sure your lawn mower
blade is sharp when you cut. Leave the clippings on the lawn unless
they clump.
</P>
<P>
   When the grass starts greening up, Fender suggests you add a
little balanced fertilizer with four parts nitrogen to one part
phosphorus to two parts potassium.
</P>
<P>
   Bald spots or trails can appear in heavy-traffic areas, but the
lack of grass is not necessarily caused by the trampling of the
grass plants. The problem is more often soil compaction; the ground
is packed so tightly that water, air and nutrients can't reach the
roots.
</P>
<P>
   To repair such an area, run a tiller or aerator to break up the
soil before reseeding. Or if the same areas go bald every year,
consider mulch or some kind of walkway.
</P>
<P>
   If you're committed to grass in the traffic lanes, tie pets and
vary play patterns to relieve the pounding. Also restrict traffic
while the yard is wet.
</P>
<P>
   You also need to make a decision about shady areas. Fine fescue
may grow in the shade, as will bentgrass and rough bluegrass. But
Fender said growing grass in deep shade is hard, and the grasses
that grow there aren't always attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Consider trimming branches of shade trees or replacing them with
smaller plants in areas where you want grass. Also consider mulch
around the base of trees or ground-cover plants such as vinca minor
and pachysandra.
</P>
<P>
   Standing water will kill grass within a few days. If you have a
spot that floods in your yard, you may need to regrade to improve
the water flow. Another option is burying a drain tile under the
swampy spot or installing wetlands plants.
</P>
<P>
   Several other problems can affect a lawn, such as underground
grubs. But if your grass is healthy, it generally will fight off
most pests on its own.
</P>
<P>
   New grass
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 reason new grass crops die is that people stop
watering before the plants are firmly established. Bluegrass,
particularly, takes weeks of daily watering to take hold.
</P>
<P>
   Follow directions that come with your seed to determine how you
should water the new grass, but, in general, water lightly and
often. Established grass, by the way, should be watered
infrequently (twice a week or less) and deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Sod shortens the time needed to get a lawn going, but it can be
expensive. Before buying sod, determine what killed the grass in
the first place and correct that problem first.
</P>
<P>
   To use sod, dig around the bald areas to create patches with
square sides and calculate the square footage of sod you'll need to
cover the patches. Remove roots, clods and debris where the sod
will go.
</P>
<P>
   Do not pick up the sod until the day you are installing it. Sod
is made of living grass plants, and it will die if improperly
stored.
</P>
<P>
   Follow directions on watering the sod to help the roots grow
down to tie into the underlying soil.
</P>
<P>
   Restrict traffic on freshly planted seed and sod until a couple
weeks after the grass is firmly established and growing.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Shuter of Greentech Lawn &AMP; Landscape contributed
information for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
