<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NUTS&AMP;BOLTS02-COX     09-01 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTS&AMP;BOLTS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dry run muddies outlook for well
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A reader was contemplating the old saying ``You
never miss the water until the well runs dry'' as he shopped for
his first home.
</P>
<P>
   I'll try to answer his question on private wells and a couple of
others today.
</P>
<P>
   How dry I am
</P>
<P>
   F.S.M. was considering a suburban property that gets its water
from a private well and had a ``recovery test'' done. An inspector
ran the taps, and at first the system put out six gallons of water
a minute. After half an hour, it was down to only one gallon a
minute and was putting out brownish-gray water. F.S.M. had no
experience with wells, but the weather had been dry before the
test. He wondered if the water situation could be improved since
everything else about the house was fine.
</P>
<P>
   Solution: Rod Jenkins, owner of Hall &AMP; Jenkins Well Drilling and
Pump Service, said six gallons a minute, the initial flow the test
showed, ``is not that bad.'' But he said getting only a gallon of
dirty water a minute after 30 minutes indicates a serious problem.
He said what probably happened was that running the tap pulled out
most of the water in the well. As surrounding groundwater flowed
in, it plunged to the bottom of the well, kicking up sediment that
discolored the water.
</P>
<P>
   The options for improving the water supply are refurbishing the
well or digging a new one. Jenkins said digging a new 100-foot well
probably will cost $1,500 to $3,000. Refurbishing the existing well
probably would cost about $700 to $800, but there's no guarantee
the repairs would work.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins noted that some well owners have good water pressure,
but they notice minor odors or discoloration. He suggested that
before they call a well contractor, owners with minor problems
should contact their local health departments for tips on
sanitizing the wells themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor power
</P>
<P>
   B.W. bought an electric string trimmer with a 5.2-amp motor and
wanted to know what kind of extension cord he needed to power it.
The work area extends as far as 90 feet from the nearest outlet, so
he assumed he'd need a 100-foot extension cord. Salespeople advised
him to buy everything from 12- to 16-gauge cords. Also he had both
a 50-foot, 16-gauge cord and a 50-foot, 14-gauge cord, but one
salesperson said the two cords should not be used together.
</P>
<P>
   Solution: The best source of information on the power cord for
any appliance, whether it's intended for indoor use or outdoor use,
is the owner's manual that comes with the appliance. I called the
Black and Decker help line at (800) 544-6986, and the adviser
suggested a 16-gauge cord for a 5.2-amp motor. He said if B.W. uses
two cords, their gauges should match. The issue, the adviser said,
is getting the appliance the voltage it needs. If you supply less
than the required voltage to any appliance, you'll damage the motor
over time.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Council, 16-gauge
extension cords are the minimum size for most uses around the
house. The lower the gauge number on a cord, the thicker the wire
it contains and the more power it can carry, so a 12-gauge cord is
heftier than a 16-gauge.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is matching the prongs on the appliance to the
cord. Appliances with three-pronged plugs should be attached to
extension cords with three-pronged receptacles and then plugged
into three-pronged outlets. It's also important that outdoor plugs
be equipped with ground-fault circuit interrupters. These devices
help protect you from potentially dangerous electrical shock if you
accidentally cut the cord.
</P>
<P>
   Uneven heat
</P>
<P>
   F.A. moved into a new house four years ago that she said is not
as uniformly warm in the winter as the house she left. Both houses
were well insulated and had good furnaces. But the new house is 400
square feet larger and is over a crawl space instead of a basement.
F.A. also noted that the cold-air ducts are near the ceiling in her
new house instead of near the floor. She wondered if the cold-air
ducts were pulling warm air out of her rooms, making her feel
colder.
</P>
<P>
   Solution: Walt Hibner, program manager of Dayton Power and Light
Co.'s Energy Resource Center, said the placement of cold-air ducts
near the ceiling probably is not the source of F.A.'s problem.
Hibner said the modern standard is to put cold-air return ducts
diagonally opposite heat registers. Registers are usually on
outside walls near windows, the area of rooms that tend to lose the
most heat. If the registers are near the floor, the cold-air ducts
will be on the opposite wall near the ceiling, and vice versa. Warm
air is pushed into the room from the register, and the increased
air pressure causes some of the air already in the room to flow
into the cold-air return, where it is carried to the furnace.
</P>
<P>
   Arranging the registers and cold-air ducts at different levels
keeps air churning in rooms to prevent stratification _ the
settling of cool air near the floor and warm air near the ceiling.
Hibner said room air entering a cold-air return duct near the
ceiling may be a little warmer than the air at floor level, but
pulling out a little warm air doesn't significantly cool the room.
And the slight extra warmth in the air means the furnace uses less
energy heating the air before pushing it back into the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Hibner said some houses with basements feel warmer than houses
on crawl spaces because people have the option of heating their
basements. F.A. said that wasn't an issue because her old basement
was unheated.
</P>
<P>
   Hibner suggested that F.A. try having her heating and
air-conditioning contractor balance her heating system. He said
balancing involves measuring the airflow coming from the registers
into each of the rooms in her house. A heating technician can
determine if some rooms are getting too much airflow and others are
getting too little. The technician can then balance the system by
partially closing vents in the ducts leading to the rooms that get
too much heat so that more of the air heated by the furnace will be
directed to rooms that are too cold.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
