<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-TAKE     09-01 1532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS TAKE 1 OF TWO TAKES.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that a telescope in space was taking pictures
of a star that blew up more than 300 years ago. How is that
possible?
</P>
<P>
   A: Astronomers can see events now that happened hundreds _ or
even billions _ of years ago because it takes light a certain
amount of time to travel from the event until it gets to the
telescope. If a star that is 300 light years away from us exploded
300 years ago, light is just reaching us now.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, we can _ in fact, must _ ``see back into time,''
explained J. Scott Shaw, professor of astronomy at the University
of Georgia's department of physics and astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   The report you cite is not an extreme example of the situation.
The furthest we have been able to ``see'' is back to shortly after
the universe was formed, Shaw said: approximately 12 billion years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Were all the original members of the band R.E.M. born in
Athens, Ga.?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, none of the four was born in Athens, according to
The New Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock &AMP; Roll, although the
band was formed there in April 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where they first saw the light of day: Michael Stipe,
Decatur, Ga., on Jan. 4, 1960; Peter Buck, Berkeley, Calif., on
Dec. 6, 1956; Mike Mills, Orange, Calif., on Dec. 17, 1958; and
Bill Berry, Duluth, Minn., on July 31, 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Berry has retired from the band, but made an appearance with
R.E.M. at a recent sold-out concert in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are hurricanes given people's names?
</P>
<P>
   A: The names help meteorologists and disaster planners avoid
confusion and quickly convey information about the behavior of a
tropical storm. Experience has shown that these short, distinctive
names also are less subject to error than the older, more
cumbersome, latitude-longitude identification methods. These
advantages are especially important in exchanging detailed storm
information between hundreds of widely scattered stations,
airports, coastal bases and ships at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know President Harry Truman didn't graduate from college.
Were there any others?
</P>
<P>
   A: The book ``Facts About the Presidents'' lists these others:
George Washington; Andrew Jackson; Martin Van Buren; Zachary
Taylor; Millard Fillmore; Abraham Lincoln; Andrew Johnson; and
Grover Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The remains of Adolf Hitler's top aide, Martin Bormann,
reportedly have been dropped into the Baltic Sea. Exactly where
were his remains until now? Newspaper and radio reports said only
that they were found at a construction site.
</P>
<P>
   A: Bormann apparently never left Berlin, despite rumors that he
fled to South America when the city fell to the Soviets in 1945.
DNA tests last year confirmed that remains found beneath a building
site in Berlin in 1972 were his.
</P>
<P>
   As first reported by the Hamburg-based weekly Der Spiegel,
prosecutors in Frankfurt ordered the remains cremated and committed
to the Baltic in an area outside territorial limits. Once the
second most powerful man in Nazi Germany, Bormann is believed to
have killed himself by taking poison May 2, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't revealed whether Bormann's ashes were scattered or
were in some sort of container that was sunk during the recent
burial at sea. The secrecy surrounding the timing of the burial,
and its specific site, was intended to preclude the possibility
that neo-Nazis might attempt to hold rallies there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to eat better, and I'm trying to use nutrition
information on food labels to help me make decisions. But how do I
know what I should consume?
</P>
<P>
   A: The nutrition facts panel is a useful tool to help you
improve your diet, said Chris Rosenbloom, a professor at Georgia
State University's department of nutrition and a spokeswoman for
the American Dietetic Association.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who is ``moderately sedentary, not real active but not a
total couch potato,'' probably needs about 1,800 calories a day,
she said. About 50-55 grams a fat per day is recommended. The label
also has information about a serving size, but that might be much
smaller than what you'd consider to be a portion.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a plan customized for you, a registered dietitian
can give you specific information about calorie and fat gram needs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm a fan of the cooking program ``Two Fat Ladies,'' shown on
PBS and the Food Network. I understand that Jennifer Paterson, the
one in glasses, died recently. Do you have any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: Paterson, who found fame in her 60s as half of a celebrity
duo with Clarissa Dickson Wright, died earlier this month after
losing a battle with lung cancer. She was 71. Described by BBC as a
``flamboyant eccentric,'' Paterson was the chef and presenter of
the hit BBC Two series in which she and co-presenter Dickson Wright
toured Britain on a Triumph Thunderbird (with sidecar) in a quest
to rediscover the delights of traditional British home cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson Wright said four editions of the fourth series of ``Two
Fat Ladies'' were completed before Paterson died, and probably will
be shown in the fall. But she added that she wouldn't complete the
remaining shows on her own. ``I would not want to do it, and I
think it would be totally inappropriate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the place name Yucatan?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Facts on File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins
offers an explanation, but prefaces it by saying it isn't proven.
According to the book, in 1517 Spanish explorer Francisco Fernandez
de Cordoba was in the area known today as the Yucatan Peninsula.
When he asked a native its name, the word Yucatan, meaning ``I
don't understand you,'' is supposed to have been the answer he
received and duly recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Alan Greenspan is chairman of the Federal Reserve Board. Who
are the board members? Who appoints them, and how long do they
serve?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System normally
has seven members. The current members, in addition to Greenspan,
are Edward W. Kelley Jr., Laurence H. Meyer, Roger W. Ferguson Jr.
and Edward M. Gramlich. The vice chair is vacant, and there's one
other vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   The members are nominated by the president and confirmed by the
Senate. A full term is 14 years. One term begins every two years,
on Feb. 1 of even-numbered years. A member who serves a full term
may not be reappointed. All terms end on their statutory date,
regardless of the date on which the member was sworn into office.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman and the vice chairman are named by the president
from among the members, and are confirmed by the Senate. They serve
a four-year term. Members' term on the board are not affected by
their status as chairman or vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the Lincoln limousine that President
Kennedy was riding in when he was assassinated?
</P>
<P>
   A: After it was examined by the Secret Service and the FBI, and
evidence was taken from it, the limousine was cleaned up and put
back into service, said Steven Tilley, chief of the JFK Collection
at the National Archives in College Park, Md. Later, after it was
removed from service as a presidential limousine, it was taken to
the Henry Ford Museum at Dearborn, Mich., where it's still on
public display.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Wasn't Mother Teresa born in Albania? What was her early
religious experience, and did she convert to Catholicism?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mother Teresa, who died in 1997, was born to Albanian parents
on Aug. 27, 1910, as Agnes Gonxha Bojaxhu, in what is now Skopje,
Macedonia. Then, it was part of the Ottoman Empire. Although the
majority of Albanians there were Muslims, her family was Catholic.
As a student at a public school in Skopje, Agnes was a member of a
Roman Catholic sodality with a special interest in foreign
missions. She often said that by the age of 12, she knew she had a
vocation to help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Agnes was inspired to work in India by reports sent home
by Yugoslav Jesuit missionaries in Bengal, and at 18 she left home
to join the Sisters of Loretto, a community of Irish nuns with a
mission in the Archdiocese of Calcutta. After training at Loretto
institutions in Dublin, Ireland, and Darjeeling, India, she took
her first vows as a nun in 1928 and her final vows in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, she received ``a call within a call,'' as she once
described it. ``The message was clear: I was to leave the convent
and help the poor, while living among them.'' Two years later, the
Vatican granted her permission to leave Loretto and pursue her new
calling. In 1948 she also became a citizen of India.
</P>
<P>
   The Missionaries of Charity, which she founded, became an
official religious community within the Archdiocese of Calcutta in
1950, and in 1965 the Vatican recognized it as a pontifical
congregation directly under the jurisdiction of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
