<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6973 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-TAKE     09-01 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS TAKE 2 OF TWO TAKES.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give us an update on the unnamed female physician who
discovered a lump in her breast while on duty in Antarctica? An
emergency mission to help her was reported not long ago.
</P>
<P>
   A: Her name has now been made public by the National Science
Foundation, which funds the Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station. Dr.
Jerri L. Nielsen, Antarctica's only doctor, is treating herself for
a lump on her breast that she discovered in June. The Air Force
braved Arctic storms in July to air-drop the supplies she needed.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, 47, works 840 miles from the nearest populated site,
another research station on the Antarctic coast. The polar darkness
and extreme cold prevent people from leaving the site from March
through October, so that means she must conduct her self-treatment
for at least another two months.
</P>
<P>
   National Science Foundation spokeswoman Valerie Carroll wouldn't
say if Nielsen's lump is cancerous. She did say Nielsen is working
on a diagnosis with the assistance of American doctors. ``She is
going about her daily business, and everyone seems to be in pretty
good spirits,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the Navy report on Y2K readiness available on the Web?
</P>
<P>
   A: Navy Public Affairs says this address _
www.nfesc.navy.mil/y2k _ will lead you to the information. Geoffrey
Dann at the Naval Facilities Engineering Service Center sounded a
note of caution, however, saying it's important to first read the
statement titled Master Utilities Y2K Preparedness Status
Spreadsheet. It explains that the document is a work in progress.
``It also represents our opinion of utility provider preparedeness
as it affects Naval installations only,'' the statement says.
</P>
<P>
   After it was widely reported that the Navy expected widespread
failures in power, water and other utility services in the United
States because of the Year 2000 computer bug, Rear Adm. Louis Smith
said the Navy's assessment reflected a ``worst-case scenario.'' The
White House, meanwhile, recently concluded that national electrical
failures are ``highly unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several months ago, country music entertainer George Jones
was seriously injured in a car wreck. How is he doing? Also, how
can fans write to him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Jones, said to be ``at death's door'' in March after he
crashed his Lexus sport-utility vehicle into a bridge near his
Franklin, Tenn., home, has made a remarkable recovery. In fact, he
performed recently at Nashville's Ryman Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-year-old singer was treated for his injuries _ the most
serious of which was a ruptured liver _ at Vanderbilt University
Medical Center. His right lung also was punctured.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Jones pleaded guilty to charges of driving while
impaired and violating Tennessee's open container law. He was fined
$500 on the DWI charge and $50 for the open container violation. He
also was billed by the Tennessee Department of Transportation for
the $2,492.44 expense to repair the concrete bridge abutment he
shattered in the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Mail can be sent to Jones in care of Asylum Records, 1906 Acklen
Ave., Nashville, TN 37212.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand there's some controversy between New York and
New Jersey over the Statue of Liberty. Which state is it actually
in?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you look at a map, you'll see that the Statue of Liberty
and Liberty Island are clearly on the New Jersey side of the state
border, which splits Upper New York Bay and extends up the center
of the Hudson River. But Liberty Island is officially under the
jurisdiction of New York, long creating a dispute between the two
states.
</P>
<P>
   Also confusing the issue is the fact that the statue on Liberty
Island, and the Ellis Island immigration station, compose the
Statue of Liberty National Monument. And while Liberty Island is
under New York's jurisdiction, most of Ellis Island is under New
Jersey's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has a legal defense fund been set up for Linda Tripp, who has
been indicted by a Maryland grand jury for secretly taping her
telephone conversations with Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The office of Joseph Murtha, Tripp's attorney, says
donations can be mailed to Linda Tripp Legal Defense Fund, 626
Admiral Drive, Suite 319, Annapolis, MD 21401. Checks should be
made out to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Nowhere in the news reports about the Turkey earthquake have
I seen any reference to temperatures there. Can you print what the
highs and lows are at this time of year in Ankara or other sites?
And what is the country's terrain like?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ankara's high temperatures in August were in the mid to upper
70s, with lows in the mid to upper 40s. Istanbul's highs also were
in the mid to upper 70s, with lows in the high 50s and low 60s.
Izmit's highs were in the low to mid 80s, with lows in the upper
50s and lower 60s.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter of the Aug. 17 earthquake was Izmit, about 55
miles east-southeast of Istanbul. Ankara, in central Turkey, is
about 200 miles east-southeast of the epicenter.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's terrain is mostly mountainous, with a narrow coastal
plain and a high central plateau known as Anatolia. Northern
Turkey, especially along an arc extending from the Sea of Marmara
to Lake Van near the border with Iran, is historically known for
very severe earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Dorothy Dandridge's dramatized biography was shown on HBO
recently. What did the singer-dancer-actress die of? I always
thought she broke a hip, and a piece of the bone went through her
bloodstream and reached her heart. Now it's said to have been a
suicide. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Drug overdose'' is the common explanation. ``Black Women in
America: An Historical Encyclopedia'' states that Dandridge was
found dead Sept. 4, 1965, in her apartment from an overdose of an
antidepressant. As the book says, the drug, Tofranil, ``is not one
that causes drowsiness or forgetfulness, making an accident
unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to Keiko the whale?
</P>
<P>
   A: Keiko, the Ornicus orca star of the movie ``Free Willy,''
remains in his native waters off Iceland. He was returned there in
September 1998 after undergoing rehabilitation at the Oregon Coast
Aquarium. Keiko is under the care of Ocean Futures, an organization
created in March from a merger between the Jean-Michel Cousteau
Institute and the Free Willy Keiko Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   On July 30, Ocean Futures announced plans to create an
innovative device for tracking whales and studying their behavior
in the wild. The device will use satellite telemetry technology to
provide a continuous stream of data on Keiko's location, depth and
swim speed.
</P>
<P>
   Keepers say Keiko will have to weather at least one more winter
in his man-made bay pen in Vestmannaeyjar, off Iceland's south
coast. Scientists caring for him plan eventually to release Keiko
into complete freedom in Icelandic waters _ once they have
determined that he is able to fend for himself in the wild. This
has never been attempted with a captive orca whale.
</P>
<P>
   It's hoped that ultimately Keiko can live without human care,
and will be able to communicate with other whales.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who monitors the accuracy of nutritional information on food
packaging? I'm suspicious of the fat grams listed on some packages
of chicken.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Food and Drug Administration oversees information found
on nutrition facts panels. Chris Rosenbloom of Georgia State
University, a spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association,
said that in a survey on label accuracy _ based on more than 2,000
laboratory tests on 300 sample food products purchased off retail
shelves _ the accuracy rate for correct nutrition information was
91 percent; for total fat it was 96 percent; for total calories, 93
percent; and for saturated fat, 93 percent.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
