<P>
   BRAZIL-CULTURE _ Not since ``The Girl from Ipanema'' became a
part of the American psyche of the 1960s has Brazilian culture been
so much in vogue. There's a tropical heat wave spreading over
Atlanta, and you read it here first. Celebrity chef Paul Luna has
just opened his long awaited South American restaurant Loca Luna in
Midtown, and the already established Tierra is planning a series of
South American theme dinners to entice the Latin-loving crowd. And
with Delta's recent addition of nonstops to Rio, Emory reports that
its ``Portuguese for Travelers'' is the hottest language course in
its continuing education program. Meanwhile, Starbucks has
introduced an ``Ipanema Bourbon'' bean, Beck and other hipsters are
paying homage to Brazilian music, and the churrascaria (Brazilian
barbecue house) is one of the hottest contemporary dining trends in
the country. We examine the emergence of a culture in Atlanta.
(Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. MOVED
</P>
