<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BECK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUQUETTE SWINGS DEAL WITH CUBS FOR BECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- General manager Dan Duquette, seeking to bolster the
Red Sox' bullpen for the stretch run as well as hedging against a
future without Tom Gordon, has traded for Rod Beck, one of the
decade's best closers until undergoing elbow surgery in May.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette acquired Beck, known for his Fu Manchu mustache and
flowing hair, from the Chicago Cubs for lefthanded reliever Mark
Guthrie _ ridding the Red Sox of their obligation to pay the
disappointing Guthrie the $1.6 million he is owed for next season _
plus a player to be named. Duquette said that player will be sent
to the Cubs Oct. 5, which incidentally would be the first day of
the playoffs for the Sox if they qualify.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cubs in need of center field help, it's possible that
they asked for Damon Buford or perhaps minor leaguer Michael
Coleman, who has 30 home runs for the PawSox this season. Another
possibility is lefthanded-hitting third baseman Cole Liniak,
bypassed at Pawtucket for Double A third baseman Wilton Veras when
the Sox needed a replacement for John Valentin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Beck saved 51 games for the Cubs last season, becoming only the
fifth reliever in history to save at least 50, and was a catalyst
in their drive to a wild-card spot. In six seasons from 1993-98,
Beck had 232 saves, more than any other closer in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Beck signed a two-year, $9.5 million contract with
a club option for 2001, but during spring training he developed
back problems and in May underwent surgery to remove bone chips in
his elbow that had been present for several years.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his job as closer, as the Cubs went to Willie Adams and
traded for Rick Aguilera. He comes to the Red Sox with a 2-4
record, 7.80 ERA, and seven saves in 11 chances. Opponents are
hitting .331 against him this season, but Duquette insists that in
the last couple of weeks, the three-time All-Star has been throwing
better.
</P>
<P>
   In seven appearances since Aug. 16 _ none of which has been a
save situation _ Beck has allowed just one run in 8 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are assuming the balance of the $5.5 million Beck is
owed this season. His contract calls fom him to be paid $3.5
million next season, with a club option of $4.5 million in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Beck, who spoke to reporters in San Diego after speaking with
Duquette by telephone Tuesday night, left little doubt that he
expects to slide into the closer's role when he gets here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the job is available right now, so I imagine so,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a lot of faith in (Boston's) scouting department. I
know I'm back. I'm ready, but you would think teams would worry a
little bit. I'm glad they had faith in me to get me over there, but
I'd rather be doing it here (with the Cubs).''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, however, said that Beck may serve initially in a
set-up role, with Derek Lowe pitching as well as he has. Lowe has
10 saves, including five in six chances since taking over when Tim
Wakefield was returned to the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to have his experience to stabilize our bullpen,''
Duquette said. ``This time of year, going into the playoffs,
successful teams have at least two top-flight relievers. One of the
things we wanted to upgrade going into the playoffs is our
bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck also gives the Red Sox another option if Gordon is unable
to pitch next season because of his elbow problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good split and a lot of mental toughness,'' said
manager Jimy Williams, who was with Atlanta when Beck closed for
the San Francisco Giants. ``That's what he showed against us (the
Braves). He has confidence in himself and his ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him, he had the stuff to go with whatever aura he
projected when he stood out there. He's a fighter out there, a
blue-collar kid. He's a competitor, always has been. Maybe that's
why he came back so quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Rapp was a teammate in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's easygoing until it's his turn to pitch,'' Rapp
said. ``He's a bulldog, all business, no fooling around when it's
his turn to pitch. And he's a guy who paints the corners. He's like
Pedro that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
