NYT-09-01-99 1110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV05     09-01 1491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARMY TROOPS, REBELS AND ANTI-REBEL VIGILANTES MAKE VOLATILE MIX
IN MEXICO'S CHIAPAS STATE
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, La Realidad is about 100
miles southeast of San Cristobal de las Casas, Chiapas state, and
about 50 miles east of Las Margaritas, Chiapas.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Sept. 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA REALIDAD, Mexico _ Armed with machetes, the men came out of
the darkness and swarmed the truck ferrying Mexican doctor Lydia
Rangel and two Spaniards out of the Lacandon jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tie them up!'' some of the vigilantes shouted, accusing the
three of being ``outside agitators'' and leaders of Mexico's
Zapatista rebels.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 yards down the isolated dirt road, Mexican Army
soldiers charged with keeping the peace in this volatile region in
Mexico's southern state of Chiapas surely heard screams, according
to Rangel. Yet they failed to rescue the terrified captives. In
fact, Rangel is certain one of the soldiers was among the mob,
which Rangel says tried to rape her and appeared close to lynching
all three captives on Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was with sheer complicity of the military,'' said the
24-year-old newly graduated physician from Mexico City, who has
requested a criminal investigation into the attack near a hamlet
called El Eden. She showed dark bruises on her legs and described
how the assailants tried to tear off her clothing before they
suddenly released her and the Spaniards.
</P>
<P>
   The chilling incident near this remote Zapatista rebel
stronghold is fueling fear that vigilantes loyal to Mexico's ruling
party are on the rise here, a year and a half after 45 people,
mostly women and young children, were massacred by similar
anti-Zapatista vigilantes in the village of Acteal.
</P>
<P>
   Although the military was not implicated in the Acteal massacre,
human rights groups accuse some soldiers of tolerating or even
assisting violent anti-rebel groups in spite of a truce and a peace
accord with the Zapatistas, who first emerged in Chiapas state more
than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army has a tremendous responsibility for what's happening
here,'' said Marina Patricia Jimenez, director of the Fray
Bartolome Human Rights Center, a Catholic Church group in Chiapas
whose lawyer is representing Rangel.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican military did not respond to repeated requests by Cox
Newspapers to talk about the alleged attack on Rangel and the
Spaniards, or other recent violent confrontations involving
government troops in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a number of violent clashes this month in
Chiapas, where the unresolved Zapatista rebellion remains a thorn
pricking at the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, politicians and business people who are
against the rebels have expressed outrage at foreigners who come to
Chiapas to visit communities as human rights observers or rebel
sympathizers. Now, that anger is widening to include Mexicans from
outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel, who volunteers in communities sympathetic to the
Zapatistas, said she and two Spaniards visiting villages here were
stopped at a makeshift roadblock by men claiming themselves to be
sympathizers, but of Mexico's ruling Revolutionary Institutional
Party, or the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The men said that PRI supporters were putting up a roadblock to
stop Zapatistas because the rebels were preventing the construction
of roads and other development projects.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel also said a man stepped out from among a crowd that
swelled to about 150 people and said, ``Here the autonomy of the
PRI supersedes the law of the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the crowd debated what to do with the three before
stealing some of their possessions, beating them and then letting
them go. Screaming, the three piled into their truck and pulled up
to the nearby military roadblock _ one of four along a 50-mile
stretch of road to La Realidad, the Zapatistas' reported jungle
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   A soldier Rangel recognized as a man among the mob said the Army
was watching the road and that the vehicle she was in had better
not stop or its occupants might be shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas first emerged in this remote part of Mexico when
they staged an armed uprising in Chiapas, Mexico's poorest state,
on New Year's Day 1994. Mostly Mayan Indians who speak limited
Spanish, they fought briefly with police and the military in
several cities in Chiapas before a truce was called and
negotiations began to address their demands for justice, Indian
autonomy and policies to overcome desperate poverty here.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 peace accords were signed between the rebels and
Mexico's federal government, which acknowledges that for decades it
has neglected the mostly agrarian Chiapas and failed to prevent
abuses committed against the state's large Mayan Indian population.
But the peace accord has never been fully implemented and talks
broke down between the government and the rebels, who enjoy empathy
if not active support from many Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels accuse President Ernesto Zedillo's administration of
breaking its promise to stick to the peace accords and opting for a
``low intensity'' war to erode support for the Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 22, 1997, divisions among Chiapas' population exploded
when pro-government Indians attacked the village of Acteal,
slaughtering 45 other Indians attending a prayer service. Police
officers in Chiapas were arrested for playing a role in the attack
and the governor of the state resigned under pressure from the
Zedillo administration. Thousands more Mexican Army troops were
sent into Chiapas, some of them ordered to offer medical services
and other humanitarian aid to rebel villages in an attempt to win
their confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government also began deporting foreign tourists
from the United States and Europe who were flocking to rebel
villages as observers at the request of Mexican human rights
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In the last couple of weeks, government officials in Chiapas
have turned their wrath on Mexicans from out of town. Local PRI
officials and the mayor of San Cristobal de las Casas, a tourist
town in Chiapas, declared a Mexican actress ``persona non grata''
and publicly threatened to run her out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They simply don't want any observers going there,'' said
Mexico City television actress Ofelia Medina, who received ample
national publicity for being the object of scorn in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Medina sparked criticism in Chiapas by traveling to a remote
jungle hamlet, Amador Hernandez, where pro-Zapatista Indians were
preventing the construction of a road. Although Amador Hernandez is
a six-hour walk from the nearest dirt road, villagers said they
feared a new passageway for vehicles would be used primarily to
move more Army troops into the area and position them against the
Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians also said they had asked the government to build a
road more than 10 years ago _ before the conflict _ but they were
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   When Mexican troops were dispatched to Amador Hernandez to
provide security for construction teams, groups of masked women
blocked their path. Joining them were Medina, and students who have
been on strike for more than four months at Mexico's National
Autonomous University in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The acting governor of Chiapas, Roberto Albores, lashed out at
the protestors, traveling to a different Indian village that has
expressed support for the road. He also urged federal officials to
``let Chiapas resolve its own conflict'' _ comments that were
interpreted by human rights organizations as inciting violence.
</P>
<P>
   Local newspapers also weighed in, publishing angry editorials
about Medina.
</P>
<P>
   After the Zapatistas mustered more than 10,000 supporters to
demonstrations Aug. 23-25 in three cities in Chiapas, the Zedillo
administration announced on Aug. 26 that the road to Amador
Hernandez would be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   That was one day after another incident flared up in the jungle.
The Army says villagers wielding sticks and machetes attacked
soldiers, wounding seven, patrolling in a village a two-hours walk
from the nearest road. Three villagers who were arrested said the
soldiers instigated the clash when they pushed women protesting
their presence and began firing their guns into the air. Two
villagers were shot and wounded.
</P>
<P>
   At the rebel headquarters here in La Realidad, Zapatistas say
they typically shut their doors when soldiers stationed about five
miles away drive through the hamlet on their way to another Army
outpost in the jungle. La Realidad is surrounded by a wall of
jungle and is about four hours from the nearest paved road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that one day the soldiers will try to stop here,
too,'' said a rebel named Maximiliano Hernandez. ``If that happens,
then the people will have to defend themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
