<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PUERTORICO-STATE-$ADV     09-01 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-STATE-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR DIVIDED PUERTO RICANS, QUESTION OF STATEHOOD IS NOT A SIMPLE
ONE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Sept. 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ The question dominates every political
conversation here, peppering the talk of old men sitting on shady
street corners, filling the radio airwaves, cropping up in news
articles on everything from politics to business and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Mainland Americans call it the ``statehood'' issue because they
think it's a simple question of whether Puerto Rico should become
the 51st state.
</P>
<P>
   For Puerto Ricans, boiling things down to a simple up-or-down
vote on statehood doesn't do justice to the complex mix of history,
culture, principles and emotions that most of this vibrant island's
residents bring to the discussion of what they call ``status.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know what we want and what we want to be,'' said
Margie Morales, a veteran of the capital's political scene and
press secretary to San Juan's pro-commonwealth Mayor Sila Calderon,
who will carry her Popular Democratic Party's banner in the 2000
gubernatorial election. ``For us it's a major question that we face
every four years. It's a matter of identity. It's like whether or
not to get married.''
</P>
<P>
   The complexity of the issue was demonstrated recently when
two-term Gov. Pedro Rossello _ perhaps the most ardent statehood
advocate ever elected here _ appealed to a United Nations committee
to list Puerto Rico as one of the world's nonself-governing
territories whose status is to be determined by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The move caused a stir here, as Rossello flatly admitted he was
frustrated that the U.S. Congress seems unwilling to deal with the
Puerto Rican question. The U.N. panel passed a resolution urging
the United States to speed up its deliberations on the issue,
although the measure has no power to force the American Congress to
act.
</P>
<P>
   First elected in 1992, Rossello has made the statehood campaign
the centerpiece of his administration, pushing through island-wide
votes on the issue in 1993 and 1998. Neither vote, however,
produced the results he hoped for: in both cases, voters failed to
give a majority to the statehood option.
</P>
<P>
   But the tallies came tantalizingly close. In both plebiscites,
statehood garnered just over 46 percent of the total. More than 70
percent of the island's registered voters turned out in both
elections, a clear sign of just how intensely Puerto Rico's 3.8
million residents feel about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The final decision, of course, rests with the U.S. Congress,
which must officially sanction a plebiscite in order for the vote
to be binding. Despite determined lobbying by Rossello, Congress
has failed to schedule such a vote, saying it is waiting for a more
clear-cut consensus to emerge on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans seem to be struggling toward that consensus, but
it may take years.
</P>
<P>
   With a gubernatorial election looming next November, statehood
will lose its most visible advocate as Rossello steps down. But his
New Progressive Party will continue to press the issue. A Rossello
deputy, former transportation secretary Carlos Pesquera, has been
christened the party's candidate for governor, and is already
dueling with Calderon on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Calderon proposes tweaking the commonwealth
relationship, guaranteeing irrevocable U.S. citizenship for Puerto
Ricans, while at the same time giving them more autonomy over
issues like trade.
</P>
<P>
   Observers discount the Puerto Rican Independence Party, which
has never attracted more than single digits at the polls. As for
the two major party candidates, they say it's too early to pick a
winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puerto Rico is very interesting politically right now because
neither of the two major parties has more than 50 percent of the
electorate,'' said Maximo Cerame Vivas, a pro-statehood columnist
for the San Juan Star newspaper. ``One is 48 percent, one is 46
percent. There is a floating swing vote that decides the issues,
but it isn't solidly in one column or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossello's New Progressives have made steady gains in the past
two decades, rising from obscurity to the 46 percent support they
received in the most recent statehood plebiscite. They are now a
formidable opponent for the once-dominant Popular Democrat Party,
or PDP, which controlled 48 percent in the recent statehood votes.
</P>
<P>
   The PDP is the party of legendary Gov. Luis Munoz Marin, who in
1948 became Puerto Rico's first elected governor. He was the
architect of the plan which led to Puerto Rico's current status
with the U.S. _ a commonwealth territory or ``associated free
state'' in which islanders are governed by their own legislature,
but cede ultimate authority to the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Marin is credited with bringing Puerto Rico into the 20th
Century, pushing for tax breaks that attracted U.S. manufacturers,
while helping develop the island's prosperous tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   But there are curious wrinkles to Puerto Rico's status that may
account for the island's deep divisions on the issue. Residents
receive most federal entitlement programs, including welfare, as
part of an estimated $10 billion in U.S. taxpayer dollars that
support Puerto Rico each year _ yet they aren't required to pay
U.S. income tax.
</P>
<P>
   They are U.S. citizens, but they cannot vote in mainland
elections. They have an elected representative in Congress, but he
has no vote.
</P>
<P>
   They fight and die in the U.S. military, but they have their own
national flag, their own contestants in beauty contests, and their
own Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   But while they enjoy many benefits from their association with
the United States, it is clear that most Puerto Ricans still feel
some ambivalence about the relationship. Intensely loyal to their
island's history and culture, they cannot forget the U.S. invasion
during the Spanish-American War of 1898 that relegated them to the
humiliating status of a colony.
</P>
<P>
   Along with that resentment is a lingering suspicion over a
particularly persistent Yankee problem: racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been 100 years since the U.S. invaded us,'' said Rafael
Roman, 51, a soft-spoken worker in a frame shop in historic Old San
Juan. ``Why haven't they given us statehood in all that time? I
believe they don't want us as a state because of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his fellow islanders, Roman shrugs when asked about
the status question. The population is split on the matter, he
said, because so many receive benefits from the United States and
have traveled there and like the opportunities they found.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they are still Puerto Rican,'' he said, holding a fist
near his heart. ``I am Puerto Rican. I want to be independent. This
is a nation, and the U.S. cannot take another nation within itself
as a state.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the young _ who switch effortlessly between English and
Spanish, dress in Tommy Hilfiger jeans and watch lots of MTV _
opinions seem more ambivalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you took a vote today, most people would choose
statehood,'' said Jose Ivan Girona, 22, an art student from San
Juan who was raised in the United States by a father in the
military. ``I love the States. There is so much opportunity
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Girona sees the value in maintaining his Puerto Rican
identity. He just isn't sure how to balance that with his love for
things American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we do become a state, we don't want to lose our
identity,'' he said. ``We are very different from the U.S. Our
culture and values are much more traditional. We know who we are.
We're Puerto Rican. But how that fits with being a state, that's
what we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
