<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7072 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-SKANEATELES-LAKE-HNS &LR;      09-01 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKANEATELES-LAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINGER LAKE VILLAGE IS PICTURESQUE, THOUGH NOT ALWAYS PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KRIS WORRELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKANEATELES, N.Y. _ The morning light skittered across the
serene lake. A father showed his young son how to cast a fishing
line as a fountain gurgled in the background. A clock tower chimed,
gracefully announcing the hour on this otherwise quiet summer
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, before tourists clogged the streets, Skaneateles
seemed to be exactly what one of the travel brochures promised: ``A
Storybook Village.''
</P>
<P>
   Located about 25 miles southwest of Syracuse and about 140 miles
west of Albany, Skaneateles Lake is the easternmost of the Finger
Lakes. Iroquois legend has it that this region was formed when the
Great Spirit placed his hand over the land in blessing.
Skaneateles, an Iroquois word meaning ``long lake,'' is also the
highest of the Finger Lakes at 867 feet above sea level. And the
16-mile-long lake is reportedly one of the cleanest in the country.
Clear, greenish-blue, like delicately colored glass, it is also
arguably one of the most beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   We'd decided to visit Skaneateles on short notice. But
spontaneity being what it is, my fiance, Dan, and I soon discovered
that Skaneateles was booked solid in its peak season. (President
and Mrs. Clinton vacationed in the staunchly Republican retreat the
week before Labor Day.) No problem. There are several equally small
and charming towns nearby, so we secured a room at the Blakeslee
House Bed and Breakfast in Marcellus, just a few miles north.
</P>
<P>
   After driving through a heavy rainstorm, we arrived in Marcellus
just after the clouds parted and the sun came out. Our hostess, Bev
Blakeslee, wasn't home. But she left the front door open and a note
telling us to make ourselves comfortable. Our room was small but
adequate, the larger suite upstairs being occupied by newlyweds
from Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   We drove south through winding country roads, past
wooden-furniture shops and boating businesses, onto Route 20 (also
called Genesee Street), the long main street that leads through the
village of Skaneateles at the north end of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   In the historic downtown district, shops, restaurants, and
galleries are housed in restored buildings dating back to 1796.
There's a little bit of everything _ jewelry shops, gift shops, a
pet store, candy and coffee shops _ but there are no chain
restaurants here, no fast food, no minimalls. If you need a
deep-fry fix, the place to go is Doug's Fish Fry on Jordan Street.
</P>
<P>
   The popular old-fashioned grill offers heavy (but yummy) fried
shrimp and fish, french fries, and ice cream. There's only limited
counter seating in the kitchen area, but outside is a lovely garden
with picnic tables, and a separate two-story dining room with
wooden floors and long tables, which looks like a mess hall at
sleep-away camp.
</P>
<P>
   Down Hannum Street is the Skaneateles Historical Society,
located in a converted creamery that had operated from 1899 to
1949. There we learned that Skaneateles was first settled by the
white man in 1794, and by 1830 about 1,000 people called the
village home. A major industry was boat-building, the most famous
being ``The Lightening,'' a boat design that was first built in
Skaneateles and is still used today. The last boat company closed
after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Other big enterprises included the cash crop teasel, a prickly
cob-like plant used in the woolen industry to raise the nap of
wool, and the manufacturing of sleighs and stagecoaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were quite an industrial area in the 1800s, which is hard
to believe since we're 99 percent tourism now,'' said village
historian Pat Blackler.
</P>
<P>
   Next we took a scenic drive down the western side of the lake on
Route 41A, past lush trees, cornfields and gracious homes. At the
southern tip of the lake we found the New Hope Mill, an operating
1823 flour mill that grinds buckwheat, a local crop. A tour of the
mill, which is powered by a huge overshot water wheel, is available
for $1 and can take 45 minutes. About halfway through the tour,
which was crowded with 25 or more people, we decided we had learned
all we needed to know about buckwheat flour and headed back to the
village.
</P>
<P>
   The Sherwood Inn was established in 1807 by Isaac Sherwood, a
300-pound mailman who eventually became a wealthy stagecoach baron.
The inn occupies a prime spot across from the north end of the
lake, and serves meals in its dining room and tavern, hosts
banquets and rents 20 guest rooms. The evening we visited, there
was a big wedding reception taking place, and the waitress said
they have some sort of function there almost every night.
</P>
<P>
   Touted as an exceptional restaurant, we found our dinner to be
average at best. The clams casino appetizer was overly breaded and
greasy, the scrod entree bland, the vegetables overcooked. The
exception was the portobello mushroom Wellington, which was wrapped
in a delicate pastry and accented with a light cream sauce. We also
enjoyed a bottle of Dr. Konstantin Frank's Johannisberg Riesling,
which the waitress said came from a vineyard near Keuka Lake, one
of the other Finger Lakes to the west.
</P>
<P>
   We had reserved tickets to attend the Skaneateles Festival, a
program of chamber music performed under the stars on a farm along
the lake in August and early September. Unfortunately, rain had
been forecast, the night was chilly (which can knock string
instruments out of tune), and the concert was moved indoors to the
much smaller St. Mary's of the Lake Church. A ticket didn't
guarantee us a seat, as we had been told, so we opted to enjoy the
beautiful night and explore the village.
</P>
<P>
   We stepped into Morris's Grill, a pub that sports a pool table
and dart board. Packed with tourists and locals, Morris's was fun
and friendly. The bartender poured stiff well drinks and played
great music. A couple of people from the wedding at the Sherwood
Inn were even inspired to dance to some Stray Cats tunes, which was
greeted with much enthusiastic clapping and cheering from the other
patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The bar at The Krebs was also hopping. We grabbed a table near
one of the many deer heads mounted on the wall, and ordered coffee
and dessert. The brownie a la mode was good, but the bread pudding
was too dry.
</P>
<P>
   After a less-than-restful night (Dan was awakened by the
newlyweds upstairs watching television, among other things), we
enjoyed a leisurely breakfast prepared by our hostess, then we
checked out and drove back into town for an afternoon brunch cruise
around the lake.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise on the double-decker Judge Ben Wiles was the
highlight of the trip, despite the fact that the brunch itself was
the equivalent of airplane food. For three hours we glided across
the glistening water as the captain pointed out elegant waterfront
homes, including the one where the Clintons stayed.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back home, we took a few detours, first to Camillus,
where we took a quick, free tour of the Wilcox-Fox Octagon House, a
funky, strawberry-colored eight-sided home built in 1856. Then we
continued east down Route 20, to Cazenovia, another quaint village
on a lake. We stopped in at The Lincklaen House for a lovely dinner
on the patio. For $20 each, we ordered fresh salads, a delicious
smoked salmon appetizer, bruchetta, tasty seafood pasta, and
lemon-seasoned salmon wrapped in phyllo dough. They even packed
some dessert to go.
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied, we found headed for home, eating chocolate mousse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7073 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-01 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR SENDS MIXED MESSAGE ON NEEDLE EXCHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As California Gov. Gray Davis ponders vetoing
local needle exchange programs, I wish he'd look at his own logic
and recognize its obvious flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Fatal flaw.
</P>
<P>
   According to Davis' spokesman, Michael Bustamante, the governor
is inclined toward a veto because he ``believes there are other
ways to address AIDS transmission and drug use without sending a
mixed message to California youth with state-sanctioned needle
exchanges.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that every medical and social services specialist in
the field of HIV transmission _ the people who actually work with
intravenous drug users every day _ have testified repeatedly to the
urgency and efficacy of needle exchange programs.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that six separate federally funded studies have found
that needle exchange programs not only decrease the transmission of
the human immunodeficiency syndrome, they do it without causing
drug use to rise.
</P>
<P>
   And _ strange though it seems for a governor so enamored of
public opinion polls _ never mind that a majority of adults in all
regions of the state who were polled by the Field Institute support
needle exchange programs to halt the spread of HIV and some strains
of hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Californians approve of the idea, and federal studies
say it works, and the people on the front lines of the war against
HIV say it will save lives, the governor doesn't want to send any
``mixed messages'' to kids.
</P>
<P>
   If that sort of reasoning is sufficient to ignore the public and
the specialists, then why don't we apply it to a whole passel of
things that are sanctioned by the state of California?
</P>
<P>
   Like speed limits.
</P>
<P>
   Aren't we sending mixed messages to our youth by allowing people
to drive 70 mph on some freeways and only 50 on others? Or by
simply allowing anybody to drive 70 mph anywhere in the state?
</P>
<P>
   Back when all highways were stuck with a mandated 55 mph maximum
speed, fatalities dropped markedly. By sanctioning the higher
limit, isn't the state telling young people that it doesn't care if
more people die, so long as we can all drive faster?
</P>
<P>
   What about liquor laws?
</P>
<P>
   The state says it's bad and wrong for a person who is 20 years,
11 months and 3 weeks old to buy or consume alcohol. But add
another week and let the person turn 21, and the state says it's
okey-dokey.
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't a mixed and confusing message, what is?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the state shouldn't sanction alcohol consumption for
anyone. All you have to imbibe is enough to get a blood alcohol
reading of 0.08 percent, and you're considered legally drunk and
unfit to operate a motor vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on people's size, weight, age and metabolism, it might
take anywhere from one lite beer to three martinis to reach 0.08.
Isn't that a mixed and confusing message? Why don't we make it
illegal to drive with any alcohol in the blood?
</P>
<P>
   And why do we allow some people to pay their income taxes in
August even though we tell everybody it's the law to pay by April
15?
</P>
<P>
   It's a scary thought, but maybe the governor actually believes
that millions of kids and teens would look at San Rafael
Assemblywoman Kerry Mazzoni's needle exchange bill and conclude:
``Gosh, I wasn't going to take drugs, but the state says it's fine,
so I'm going to shoot illegal, addictive substances into my veins
as soon as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   From what I know of kids, as soon as they think adults approve
of a taboo behavior _ let alone the stodgy old state _ the behavior
suddenly doesn't seem like such a cool idea.
</P>
<P>
   More compelling, my experience also tells me that most kids
aren't remotely stupid enough to confuse a program that provides
clean needles to people already addicted to drugs with a
state-sanctioned carte blanche for illegal drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Clean needles help prevent intravenous drug users from
contracting HIV and dying. That is an indisputable fact whose
message is about as mixed and confusing as tap water.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
