<SLUG> BC-SUNFLOWERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE SUN GODS AREN'T AFRAID OF CATCHING RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CELINA OTTAWAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Greek myth has it that Clytie, the daughter of
the king of Babylon, was forsaken in love by the sun-god Apollo
because he turned his attention to her sister. The myth is
recounted in the, ``Dictionary of Subjects and Symbols in Art'' by
James Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Clytie's jealousy caused her sister's death. Still, she was
spurned by Apollo. Slowly Clytie wasted away and turned into a
flower that always faces toward the sun. The marigold was the
likely flower in the myth.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the larger more dramatic common sunflower was imported
from its native North America to Europe. Poets and painters used
the flowers' movement as they followed the sun as a symbol of the
same kind of unending devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists prefer to cite biochemical reactions and swelling
cells to explain the turning.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of plants will move during the day,'' said John Hunter,
a professor of biological sciences at the State University College
at Brockport. ``We tend to think of plants just moving when they
wilt or grow. But some plants move in response to the sun, either
following it or avoiding it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some desert plants turn their leaves so that the thin edge is
facing the sun. This way they absorb as little heat as possible.
Others plants in colder climates will keep the flat side of their
leaves facing the sun to stay warm.
</P>
<P>
   Many kinds of flowering plants turn toward the sun: marigolds,
some members of the pea family, and the flat-growing ground weed
purslane are just a few.
</P>
<P>
   But none captivate and mystify the way a field of 8-foot stalks
topped with yellow disks do. The wide flat circles surrounded by
rays of yellow seem to both follow the sun and reflect its image.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how sun worship works at the molecular level:
</P>
<P>
   When the sun hits the molecules in a sunflower stem, it sets off
a series of biochemical reactions that move hormones away from that
part of the plant. The hormones shift to the section of the stem
that is away from the light and cause it to lengthen. This bends
the plant's head toward the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the sun moves across the sky, it strikes different parts of
the plant, causing the plant to bend and twist,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   The common sunflower is part of the Asteraceae family, along
with black-eyed susans, dandelions and goldenrod. There are more
than 20,000 species in the family, including 150 species of
sunflowers. Not all Asteraceae turn with the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are characterized by the disks, or heads, at the top
of their stems. From a distance, each head looks like a flower, but
is in fact a cluster of smaller flowers. The heads are surrounded
by long thin flowers that look like petals. On a sunflower, these
are the long yellow rays that surround the plant's face. The tiny
flowers in the face's yellow cluster bear fruit, known as the
sunflower seed.
</P>
<P>
   Why the sunflower turns its face to the sun is harder to
explain, Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that the light and warmth on the flowers affects the
behavior of insects that the plant needs for pollination. It may be
that the plant turns in order to benefit the stem or the leaves;
the head just turns because it is attached. It could be that the
warmth of the sun helps the fruit ripen.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanisms that turn sunflowers are at work from the time
the plant emerges from the seed to the time it dies, Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be any other way with such a devotion?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
