<HEADER>
A7092 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CHILDREN-LICE-HNS &LR;      09-01 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-LICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS MAY BRING MORE THAN BOOKS HOME FROM SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Every parent dreads a phone call from the school
nurse, but anxiety is compounded by disgust when the problem is
head lice.
</P>
<P>
   Head lice is one of the most common childhood problems. This
year, up to 20 million people in the United States are expected to
become infected, with the majority of cases in children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   As children head back to school, health experts are advising
that families take a proactive approach to dealing with the tiny
parasites.
</P>
<P>
   While nothing will guarantee that your child won't become
infested, you can minimize the opportunities by following some
common sense strategies:
</P>
<P>
   _ Remind your child not to share hair accessories or combs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask your school about ways to make sure coats and hats don't
mix in the cloak room. Some parents send their children to school
with a plastic bag to keep their coats separate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Comb your child's hair daily. Catching the problem early makes
it easier to manage.
</P>
<P>
   _ If your child has long hair, keep it pulled back.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the prevention measures are really just paying
attention to your child's head,'' said Kathy Sen, acting
supervising Community Health Nurse at the Schenectady County Public
Health Department
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with the best vigilance, many children still get lice.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, Dr. Joseph Hayes, a Schenectady County
physician, reminds parents not to panic or go overboard with toxic
prescription or over-the-counter shampoos that can cause
neurological problems if misused.
</P>
<P>
   Head lice by themselves are a nuisance, not a health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have the perception that it's such a terrible thing,''
he said. ``It's important to stress that it's a common thing that
healthy people get.''
</P>
<P>
   Adult lice look like six-legged grains of rice. They lay eggs
(known as nits) in hair, suck blood through the scalp and cause
itching.
</P>
<P>
   Known by their scientific name of Pediculosis humanus capitis,
lice are found worldwide and have been around for thousands of
years. Archaeologists have found evidence of head lice in the hair
of Egyptian mummies.
</P>
<P>
   And over the years, dozens of remedies, from pesticides to
mayonnaise, have been put forward as a way to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old medical adage that when there are a lot of
treatments, you can be sure there is no cure,'' said Deborah
Altschuler of the National Pediculosis Association in
Massachusetts. Over the years, she has heard horror stories about
parents burning their children with kerosene in an effort to get
rid of the pests.
</P>
<P>
   More common is the problem of parents misusing pesticide
shampoos, particularly those containing Lindane, a chemical that is
not only carcinogenic but highly flammable.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end, many companies are now starting to market
all-natural remedies to repel and remove lice.
</P>
<P>
   One such company, ARR Health Technologies Inc. in Massachusetts,
has come out with a mineral-oil-based hair spray that it claims
kept children lice-free in clinical studies done in Israel. Lice
Guard is slated to be on drugstore shelves this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Altschuler is skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Repelling head lice is a tall order,'' she said. ``Where are
they going to go? Your eyebrows? Head lice will feed on your arm if
they can't feed on your head.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why she echoes the consensus among many health experts:
The best way to get rid of lice is with thorough combing to remove
the nits that might cause reinfestation. ``People comb their hair
every day anyway,'' she said. ``That's where we want people to
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen still remembers how desperate she felt when her own son
contracted lice almost 15 years ago. She vacuumed the house, washed
his bedding in hot water and bagged up her son's toys and stuffed
animals in plastic to kill any wanderers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as a public health nurse, she offers those kinds of tips
and a sympathetic ear to parents. ``It's a lot of work for parents
to deal with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
