<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7099 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-TV-FASHION-HNS &LR;      09-01 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHIONS HELP DEFINE CHARACTERS IN EDGY HBO SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The best-dressed women on television are three
thirtysomethings and a 40-year-old for whom life is a constant
smorgasbord of designer clothes, lavish parties and one-night
stands.
</P>
<P>
   You will find them on ``Sex and the City,'' HBO's
Emmy-nominated, half-hour sitcom airing Sunday nights that marches
the plight of the unmarried New York babe right off the edge of
propriety.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major pleasures of watching the show is to see what
the women will be wearing from week to week. And their looks are no
accident _ they're very carefully put together by a pair of women
named Field: Patricia Field, well-known for her eponymous and
notorious Greenwich Village shop, and her partner, Rebecca Field
(no relation).
</P>
<P>
   Before she started costuming for theater and TV series, Patricia
Field and her shop were a source for fashion ideas that would later
turn up everywhere, including edgy stuff like fetish-wear shoes,
Spandex leggings (she had them first) and up-to-the-nanosecond
club-kid gear.
</P>
<P>
   Field and Field could have gone totally Madison Avenue with the
usual high-fashion New York stuff _ your basic Ralph Lauren/Calvin
Klein fashionista look. But to their credit, they have chosen edge
over predictability, which is totally in keeping with who Field and
Field are.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Field comes out of the club-kid scene. She is really
Rebecca Weinberg, a self-described ``Texas Jewish girl'' and
performance artist who moved to New York from Atlanta with drag
star RuPaul to appear in the New York underground in male drag as a
singer-dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, she signed on with Patricia Field as a production
assistant and adopted the name ``Field'' to identify the
partnership as a collective, or, as she says, ``a family sort of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The results of their labors can be seen on four carefully
delineated characters who have taste (some of it questionable) that
jibes directly with the message of the show: That the single New
York career woman is adorable, stylish, outrageous and
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   The series was created and produced by Darren Star, an Aaron
Spelling Productions escapee who turned Heather Locklear's legs and
hair into lethal weapons on ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' and ``Melrose
Place.'' Now, with the help of Fields, the focus is on belly
buttons, abs and assorted other, often-unclothed, body parts.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City'' is based on Candace Bushnell's New York
Observer column and subsequent best-selling book of the same name.
It features Sarah Jessica Parker, 5-feet-4 and a Size 0 (that's
enough to give any red-blooded American woman addicted to Chunky
Monkey a bit of performance anxiety) as Carrie Bradshaw, a New York
freelance journalist whose subject is her peers _ single New York
women and their three principle fetishes: Clothes, food and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly sex.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie has three best friends, each one an archetype of the New
York single woman. Kim Cattrall is Samantha, the fading 40-ish
party girl who bounces from bed to bed with lust in her eyes and
hope in her heart; Cynthia Nixon is Miranda, a red-headed lawyer
who is as tightly strung as a Stradivarius; and Kristin Davis is
Charlotte, a deeply superficial art dealer whose taste in men is a
whole lot worse than her taste in art or clothes.
</P>
<P>
   All four women are dressed in the latest styles as befits their
characters, that is: fashion-forward women with enough money to
indulge their various clothing and shoe addictions.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie, who is a pocket-sized Venus, dresses mostly in
sophisticated hippie-princess mode, baring her abs as often as she
can and affecting tight skimp sweaters, skirts that fall off her
pelvic bones and backless, high-heeled slides. Her style, says
Patricia Field, ``is based on Sarah Jessica's personal style.''
That she can wear just about anything, says Patricia Field, ``makes
my job easier.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sole brunette of the ``Sex and the City'' foursome,
Kristin, who comes off as a Chapin/Dalton school prepster, is, says
Patricia Field, ``more conservative. She reads magazines and buys
accordingly. This year, it's Tocca. Next year, it will be something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Samantha, well, ``She's been through it and she knows it,''
Field says. ``She's a bit of an '80s throwback, which was her time.
We put her in the Alexis Carrington-style power suit and we like it
to have a shine or something that indicates that she's maybe a
little retro, a little off.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Cynthia Nixon, the redhead, ``We've been experimenting
with her. We wanted to get her away from those lawyer suits. We
wanted to move her into a more interesting mix of clothing _ some
ethnic things and more textures.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a recent episode, the costumers dressed the redhead in
colorful (not to mention very tight) Custo Barcelona T-shirts and
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Field says that dressing an actress for a specific role depends
upon three considerations: ``You have your character and you have
the actress and you have the real person this character is based
on, or the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this instance, Candace Bushnell was her own character. She
made her statement. We take Sarah Jessica, who is portraying her,
and we don't look at what Bushnell wears, but we look at the
broader concept of it: Who is this person and how come she has to
be what she is?''
</P>
<P>
   What Carrie Bradshaw is is a woman who takes her laptop to bed
as she's bouncing around in a bra and panties, accessorized by a
kitschy, gold name necklace _ which, notes Field, has set off a fad
among 13-year-old girls _ and a Playboy bunny charm on a gold
chain. In other words: This is someone who understands irony.
</P>
<P>
   And she is someone who can agonize over wearing her hair
straight in one episode _ as she did when she left a hair dryer at
the apartment of her lover, ``Mr. Big'' (Chris Noth) _ and then
blithely wear an almost-see-through, floaty nude chiffon number to
have her promotional pictures taken for a bus placard.
</P>
<P>
   Propriety sometimes scampers through her mind; but not too
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's obviously very savvy because she writes about the city
where she has a full, single life,'' Field says. ``Because she does
not report for work like other people, she is completely
independent to do and wear what she wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Which makes Carrie Bradshaw (and Sarah Jessica Parker) the dream
date for her costumer. ``She is a very complex character,'' notes
Field, ``and her wardrobe defines her complexity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She is not ``a character who says, `I wear only vintage. Or
designer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte, on the other hand, wears Vogue or fashion mag stuff;
Samantha buys what Field calls ``sex-minded clothes,'' that are not
as up-to-date as her friends' wardrobes. She's a prime example of
the woman who gets stuck in time and clings to the period where she
thought she looked her best, or when her life was most intense.
</P>
<P>
   The Fields have taken on another complex personality, Heather
Locklear, who is making the jump from ``Melrose Place'' to Michael
Fox's hit comedy, ``Spin City,'' and is dropping her hemlines
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've pulled everything from Yves Saint Laurent Rive Gauche
and John Galliano for Dior to Gucci to Michael Kors. We're trying
to mix it up. She's sent us some tear sheets of how she sees this
character and it's a little harder-edged than what we see. But
we're definitely dropping the length of her skirts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City's'' four women, who seem to be on a
continuous whirl of cocktail parties, art openings, lunches out and
charity dos, dress up a lot, even when they're not ``dressed.''
Their closets are filled with designer names like Galliano, Marc
Jacobs, Dolce &AMP; Gabbana and some Donna Karan, although Field
decries that line as ``not shapely. It has gotten so baggy and not
body-conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   What both the Fields are looking for is clothes with ``edge,''
clothes that reveal the lifestyle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
