<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-PROVIDENC     09-01 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PROVIDENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUN, FILTH COME OF AGE IN `PROVIDENCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those expecting a gel-by-gel follow-up to the Farrelly
Brothers' most recent smash comedy, forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside Providence'' is neither ``There's Something About Mary
Redux'' nor any possible variation on the theme (``There's
Something Else About Mary''? ``I Still Know What You Did to Mary
Last Summer''?), though it does boast a couple of slightly
repulsive moments.
</P>
<P>
   A protagonist nicknamed after an unprintable erotic device is
one clue that we're on familiar Farrelly turf.
</P>
<P>
   It's not theirs alone. Although ``Outside Providence'' was
produced by Bobby Farrelly and co-written by Peter Farrelly from
his own novel, it was directed _ and co-written and co-produced _
by Michael Corrente, whose first two films (``Federal Hill'' and
``American Buffalo'') were heavy, character-driven dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Corrente is not a filmmaker for whom gross-out jokes come
naturally. But in ``Outside Providence'' this unlikely threesome
has created a fitfully funny, fitfully touching coming-of-age
comedy that looks at a working-class kid's senior year in a posh
Connecticut prep school.
</P>
<P>
   The era is the mid-1970s; the location is Pawtucket, R.I., a
scruffy industrial town outside Providence. Tim Dunphy (Shawn
Hatosy), the guy with the nickname, has a disabled brother (``We
were playin' touch football, and he fell off the roof,'' Tim
explains), a growly dad (Alec Baldwin, confirming that he was born
for weirdo character roles) and a mother who died when he was
small.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a circle of permanently and recreationally drugged
friends. When the bunch of them rear-end a police cruiser while
bombed on bong hits, Tim gets packed off to the Cornwall School for
Boys in Cornwall, Conn. There he encounters the usual run of
druggies, preppies, nerds and snide administrators (particularly
one named Mr. Funderburk, played by Tim Crowe), as well as a
beatific corn-fed beauty (Amy Smart) who attends the girls' school
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The plot at this point isn't much to speak of, and it's facilely
predicted at every turn: Guy woos girl, guy smokes weed, guy
hatches practical jokes, guy gets in biiiiig trouble with Mr.
Funderburk. The best snippets in the Cornwall half of the movie
involve Tim's bespectacled squid of a roommate, played by Jack
Waltham with extraordinary, orb-eyed discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, the best stuff is all Pawtucket. Hatosy, best
known from ``The Faculty'' and ``In &AMP; Out,'' gives a mash-mouthed
sibilance to all of his lines (``I know I'm not gonna shay thish
right'') and struts like a randy bulldog. His homegrown friends are
amiable potheads, among them a character named Drugs (a sweetly
out-there Jon Abrahams); his analysis of the inspirational poem
``Footprints'' is a succinct gem. Counterbalancing these scenes are
poker nights with Tim's dad, whose circle of pals includes George
Wendt as a galoot with a secret.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin is, while we're on the subject, a reason to see the
movie. Much more sympathetic (and funny) as this ursine mess of a
man than he's ever been playing the hero, he turns the elder Dunphy
into a gently tragicomic figure. His scenes with Hatosy are tender
without being trite, a far cry from the cliched histrionics that
punch up the drama at Cornwall School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you'll never forgive me until it happens to you,
Timothy,'' he says, after his son confronts him over the death of
his mother. ``Well, I hope you'll never forgive me.''
</P>
<P>
   Misty eyes in a Farrelly film? And not a mistaken hair product
in sight? Yes. And yes again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
