<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-WAR-ART-4TAKES-$ADV5-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HUNGER WEAPON: DEPRIVING CIVILIANS OF FOOD A VICIOUS TOOL OF
MODERN WARFARE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
 
 &HT;    War is not carried on by arms alone. It is lawful to starve the
hostile belligerent, armed or unarmed, so that it leads to the
speedier subjection of the enemy. _ Article 17 of Instructions for
the Government of Armies of the United States in the Field (Lieber
Code) 1863 
 
 &HT;    Starvation of civilians as a method of warfare is prohibited. _
Protocol 1, Article 54, The Geneva Convention, 1949 
 
By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   TAJURA, Sudan _ To the Sudanese forces who attacked this hot,
dusty village with artillery and tanks early this year, killing its
inhabitants was of little immediate concern.
</P>
<P>
   That, the soldiers hoped, would come later.
</P>
<P>
   On that January morning, as it has been throughout the
government's campaign to drive the rebellious population out of
Sudan's isolated Nuba Mountains, the troops' primary mission was to
destroy the people's ability to feed themselves and to force them
off their land.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers slaughtered livestock. They burned houses and grain
stores. They poisoned the precious wells. They bombed the nearby
airstrip, the people's only link to the outside world. And they
laid waste the fields of sorghum, the staff of life in this remote
part of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They destroyed everything,'' said Mohamed Tutu, a 28-year-old
father of four children, recalling the pre-dawn raid that destroyed
his life. ``They killed many cows and burned my house. They chased
us away into the hills.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 10 years since the Nuba people, in their quest for
self-determination, joined the rebels of Sudan's south in a brutal,
seemingly endless civil war against the government. And for 10
years, deliberately and efficiently, government forces have emptied
the fertile valleys of people, leaving the areas silent and barren.
</P>
<P>
   Where once there were 1 million people, less than half remain.
And what drove them out was hunger, not bombs or bullets _ a hunger
they feared more than the rumble of the tanks in the night.
</P>
<P>
   They feared it wisely.
</P>
<P>
   The current round of the civil war between the fundamentalist
Islamic, Arab government of Sudan and the mostly non-Islamic, black
African tribes of the south and their Nuba allies in the north has
lasted 16 years and has caused the deaths of more than 2 million
people, more than any conflict since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, only about 50,000 were soldiers who died in combat,
according to a study for the U.S. Committee for Refugees titled
``Quantifying Genocide in Southern Sudan and the Nuba Mountains''
by Millard Burr, a former U.S. State Department official.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of the dead were civilians who starved or fell
to a host of afflictions that hover around famines like flies.
</P>
<P>
   In this interminable, intractable war _ as it is in myriad other
conflicts _ hunger is the preferred weapon of mass destruction, not
guns and bombs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great successes of this century is that more than
enough food is produced to feed every soul on the planet. Another
is the growth of humanitarianism, a multibillion-dollar industry
devoted to aiding those whose lives are torn asunder by armed
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in Sudan, in Kosovo, in Somalia, in Afghanistan, in Iraq, to
name just a few, wars waged for a host of reasons bear at least one
thing in common: Millions of civilians who are caught in the middle
die or are set adrift on an ocean of refugees because, by one means
or another, they are deprived of food.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a novel concept. The soldiers who rousted Tutu and
his neighbors from their huts and left them with nothing to eat
were doing what raiding parties have done for centuries. &UR;  &LR; But
unlike other weapons of antiquity rendered obsolete by man's
incessant quest for a better way of killing, hunger alone has
endured as one of the most lethal tools of war ever conceived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes back to the Middle Ages,'' said Jean Francois Vidal of
Action Against Hunger, a private French humanitarian-aid agency.
``But it is more vicious now. Now we have warring parties who
purposely starve the people so they can attract international
attention and millions of dollars in humanitarian assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, independent aid agencies played relatively
minor roles in conflicts driven by the superpowers. Since the Cold
War ended, however, they have become a potent force, developing
into an influential industry that spends an estimated $8 billion a
year on emergency assistance. And because international relief now
plays such a large role in the economics and politics of war,
concern is growing that despite the industry's noble intent, the
rush to aid the afflicted may also be abetting those who have a
stake in waging war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think humanitarian aid (overall) is doing more harm
than good,'' said Joanna Macrae, an aid policy researcher at the
Overseas Development Institute in London. ``But it is true that it
can be, and is being, manipulated to the benefit of the warring
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than any other type of aid, food is most prone to
manipulation. It is stolen and diverted. It feeds the soldiers. It
makes merchants rich. It is used as a magnet to move masses of
people at will. It is denied to some, given to others. And nowhere
is this manipulation more of an art than in Sudan, where not even
the largest food relief operation in history has been able to stop
the cycle of war and famine.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan may be the poster child for the use of hunger as a weapon
of war, but it is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   For months, before Slobodan Milosevic launched his onslaught
against the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo earlier this year and
sparked 11 weeks of aerial bombardment by NATO, the Yugoslav leader
systematically degraded the Kosovars' ability to feed themselves,
aid experts said. His forces burned food supplies and crops,
destroyed livestock, prevented farmers from planting or reaping,
restricted the import of basic food items and looted the warehouses
of the aid agencies trying to provide assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not aware of the calculated steps Milosevic has
taken over the past year to use food as a weapon,'' said Bill
Frelick, a senior policy analyst for the U.S. Committee for
Refugees. ``After systematically depleting Kosovo of its food
stocks, he can freely use starvation as a tool of genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of the protagonists in civil wars in
Liberia, Angola, Afghanistan and Sierra Leone, where rebels are
known to have amputated the hands of some villagers simply to
prevent them from harvesting their rice.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the United Nations' protracted, low-grade war against
Iraq, the food weapon has been as effective as a Tomahawk missile
or a laser-guided bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Severe sanctions imposed on the country by the United Nations
after the 1991 Persian Gulf War resulted in the deaths of tens of
thousands of children from hunger and related ills, according to
the United Nations. The situation eased in 1996 when Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein was permitted to sell some of his
country's oil to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In Sudan's Nuba Mountains, the children are dying of hunger,
too. But not until late June of this year did the Khartoum
government allow the world to begin counting how many.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, Sudan's Islamic government declared a
``jihad,'' or holy war, against the Nuba people and closed the
mountains to the outside. Two years later, the Khartoum government
set about destroying the people's food supplies and banned all
deliveries of aid. It bombed schools, hospitals and airstrips that
the people had managed to carve out of the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred thousand, maybe 200,000, have died in the region.
Nobody knows exactly how many. Hundreds of thousands more have fled
the hunger and the bombs, lured to government ``peace camps'' where
food aid is permitted, but where the people reportedly are abused.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Mohamed Tutu, a sinewy man in his prime, chose to
retreat deeper into the mountains, to build new homes on the rocky
flanks, to coax the sorghum from terraces cut into the steep
slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all I can do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE MANIPULATION OF AID &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the African sky lightens with dawn, the chant of the
``muezzin,'' or prayer-caller, is drowned by the roar of a C-130
Hercules cargo plane taking off from the Operation Lifeline Sudan
airstrip in Lokichoggio, Kenya. Loaded with 16 tons of food, it is
headed for a drop zone deep in the heart of southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later it is followed by another, and, minutes after
that, by still another. Not until the last trace of light fades in
the west does the coming and going of the planes stop. In the
morning it will begin again, as it will the day after that, as it
has, virtually seven days a week, for the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Lokichoggio was little more than a collection of
huts a few miles from the Sudanese border, populated by about 150
people, mostly from the Toposa and Turkana tribes. Today, it houses
30,000 people of all nationalities and serves as headquarters to
one of the largest relief operations in history.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Lifeline Sudan, a consortium of United Nations
agencies and about 40 nongovernmental aid organizations, was
created in 1989 by the United Nations in response to a particularly
deadly, largely man-made famine that killed an estimated 250,000 in
southern Sudan. At the time, the U.N.-led alliance was a unique
experiment in the delivery of food and other humanitarian aid.
Never before had combatants on both sides allowed the United
Nations to mount a relief operation in the midst of a civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, the U.N. operation has spent nearly half a billion
dollars delivering more than 500,000 tons of food to millions of
people in dire circumstances on both sides of the war in Sudan.
There is no question that many of them would have died without it.
</P>
<P>
   But the inescapable truth is that so far, despite its best
efforts, Operation Lifeline Sudan has not been able to stop the
famines. Moreover, concern is growing among some people within the
organization, as well as academics, aid workers and politicians on
the outside, that the food being dropped into the maw of the civil
war may be helping to feed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strong school of thought that says humanitarian aid
in a complex emergency like this one prolongs the war,'' said a
senior official in an aid agency that works in Sudan outside the
U.N. umbrella and who did not want to be identified. ``The truth is
that the aid industry does not know enough about the ripple effects
of injecting aid directly into a war.''
</P>
<P>
   What the industry does know is that the nature of warfare has
changed ominously in the past 20 years: No longer content to rely
solely on famine as the tactical weapon of choice, the makers of
war have now added to their arsenals the manipulation of
humanitarian aid that those famines attract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the government and the (rebels) have shifted from using
starvation as a military tactic to the strategic manipulation of
aid, both to provision their forces and to protect key garrisons,''
wrote Alex de Waal, a former senior analyst for the humanitarian
organization African Rights and an expert on aid in Sudan. ``The
structure of the aid programs has come to have an important
influence over the structure of the military command.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sudan's government, de Waal said, the aid has made it
possible to maintain its garrison towns in the south, particularly
Juba, the largest and, for the rebels, the ultimate prize. Airdrops
of food by Operation Lifeline Sudan into Juba have repeatedly saved
the town from falling into the hands of the rebels who surround it.
</P>
<P>
   For the rebels, the airdrops have proved to be a major source of
provisions after neighboring Ethiopia cut off military and food aid
in 1991. One rebel commander, de Waal said, was alleged to have
deliberately attracted aid by corralling a group of destitute
refugees and keeping them in a state of near starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Such manipulation by both sides demonstrates the essential flaw
in Sudan's relief operation. It is widely held within the
assistance industry that to be effective, aid workers must have
direct access to those who are suffering, be allowed to decide what
the people need, and make sure that they get what is delivered.
</P>
<P>
   In Sudan, the workers have no such independence.
</P>
<P>
   Because Sudan is recognized by the United Nations as a sovereign
nation, its president, Lt. Gen. Umar Hasan Ahmad al-Bashir, and the
ruling National Islamic Front have absolute authority over where
and when and how much food can be dropped from the air. Throughout
the war, the government has abused this power, say relief workers
and Western officials. They add that the government repeatedly and
consistently denies Operation Lifeline Sudan access to vulnerable
people in rebel-held territory, while permitting unrestricted
access to people in those areas it controls.
</P>
<P>
   For two months last year, in apparent retaliation for rebel
attacks on three of its garrison towns, the government banned
relief flights into the southern province of Bahr el Ghazal. Sixty
thousand people died in the resulting famine, and they did so at a
rate seldom seen before.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last month, Operation Lifeline Sudan warned that
an arbitrarily imposed government ban on relief flights into the
Western Upper Nile was placing as many as 150,000 people at risk of
starvation. The ban, which is still in effect, was condemned by
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin as ``the latest example
of civilian needs being subjugated to military needs in this
long-running war.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, for the past five years the Khartoum government has
banned all relief flights into the Nuba Mountains in an attempt to
drive out the people. Only in June did the government relent under
intense international pressure and allow a U.N. team into the
mountains to assess the condition of the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest failing of Operation Lifeline Sudan is the failure
to achieve access to the people who are being targeted in the war,
like the Nuba Mountains,'' said Dan Collison, the program director
for southern Sudan for the British charity Christian Aid, one of
the few aid agencies able and willing to risk being shot out of the
sky to fly food into the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most cynical aspect of the Sudanese government's
manipulation of the aid is that, arguably, it doesn't need it. Last
year, while 60,000 of its people were dying of starvation, Sudan
produced a record 6.5 million tons of food, according to the United
Nations, which is more than enough to feed everyone in the country.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the Sudanese People's Liberation Army, the
biggest of Sudan's various rebel factions that controls virtually
the entire southern half of the country, wields enormous influence
on which populations are targeted for relief. The rebel
organization also monitors the distribution of the food that has
been dropped into the areas it controls.
</P>
<P>
   And it is common knowledge that on both sides of the conflict,
but particularly in the rebel camp, food intended for the victims
of the war ends up feeding the soldiers fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any war, the last ones to die of hunger will be the
soldiers,'' said Claude Jibidar, the liaison officer for the World
Food Program in Lokichoggio. ``We are handing over each and every
bag (of food) to a woman who has walked two or three days, and then
they are walking two to three days back. We cannot follow every one
of these women back to their homes to make sure it doesn't get
looted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, damn frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A DISASTER OF EPIC PROPORTIONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In better times, before it joined Africa's burgeoning list of
synonyms for death, Ajiep was a village of about 120 souls lost in
the ocean-flat vastness of southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Ajiep, like the Dinka elsewhere in Bahr el Ghazal,
eked out a living herding livestock and growing grain on small
plots next to their mud houses. Villagers fished in the nearby Jur
River, migrated with their cattle to marshlands in the dry season
and moved to whatever high ground they could find during the
frequent floods that come with the rains.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, in the nearby government-held garrison of Wau,
troops slaughtered innocent civilians after rebels attempted to
capture the town. As a result, some 120,000 people poured into
Ajiep. The village was one of only four where the Khartoum
government allowed the United Nations to drop relief food, which,
in turn, attracted more refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Desperately hungry people crowded together near Ajiep's dirt
airstrip to await the food. Others, hearing there was food in the
town, arrived from many miles around. Both the village elders and
the few foreign aid workers in the town were quickly overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Ajiep became an epicenter for the latest southern Sudanese
famine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were rushing in with the resources, but there was no
preparation,'' says Mawiir Nyok, a 33-year-old former U.N.
chauffeur who is in charge of the rebels' relief efforts in the
Ajiep area. ``It was difficult to manage, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   That is putting it too mildly, perhaps. Some called what
happened in Ajiep and other areas of Bahr el Ghazal last year a
disaster of epic proportions, a man-made and man-perpetuated
tragedy that killed people at rates never before seen in famines.
</P>
<P>
   Much soul searching has taken place within the aid industry and
Operation Lifeline Sudan about the response to the famine last
year. Why did so many people continue to die when so much food was
being delivered in one of the biggest relief airlifts in history?
</P>
<P>
   Much of the blame for the famine has been placed on the Sudanese
government, which banned flights into the most desperate rebel-held
areas of Bahr el Ghazal for as long as two months. When the
government finally relented under pressure, 380,000 people were in
immediate danger of starvation.
</P>
<P>
   And much of the blame has been placed on the rebels. Inept
attacks by maverick rebel warlord Kerubino Kuanyin Bol on three key
communities provoked panic-driven exoduses. Hundreds of thousands
of people, already dispossessed and on the edge of oblivion, were
uprooted and descended on towns that were unable and unwilling to
shelter them.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the view of aid workers, at least some of the
responsibility for what happened must be shouldered by the Western
nations that provided the food and turned a deaf ear to the dire
warnings from Operation Lifeline Sudan that a disaster was in the
offing. Even after the famine was in full bloom, Western donors
continued to doubt that the situation was as bad as the officials
on the ground were saying it was.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the slow start, the West's response to the famine
steadily gained momentum after the Sudanese government lifted the
flight ban. What had been a trickle of food into Bahr el Ghazal in
April of 1998 _ about 800 tons that month _ became a river by June,
when 4,000 tons were delivered. By the end of November, the relief
agency had flooded the famine zone with a total of 88,000 tons of
food.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the number of people at risk from starvation peaked in June
at about 800,000, and it was months before the death and
malnutrition rates declined to nonemergency levels. This year, the
World Food Program announced that more than $142 million would be
needed to feed an estimated 2.3 million people who remain
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   An exhaustive internal review conducted after the Bahr el Ghazal
famine by Operation Lifeline Sudan and the Sudanese Relief and
Rehabilitation Association, the humanitarian-aid arm of the rebels,
found that significant amounts of the food had never reached those
for whom it was intended. Instead, much of it was diverted to rebel
military commanders, clan leaders and local tribal chiefs _ who
felt no need to share it with the refugees _ and to profiteers.
</P>
<P>
   Several rebel commanders were replaced as a result of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Blind Freddy would tell you that in a war situation you
don't have diversions,'' said Hamish Young, a senior World Food
Program official in Nairobi, Kenya. ``The end result is that the
amount of food that gets to the bottom of the heap is so diluted
that it doesn't really help.''
</P>
<P>
   The French aid organization Doctors Without Borders &UR; , &LR;  itself a
member of Operation Lifeline Sudan, this year issued a virtually
unprecedented, scathing public report on the relief efforts in Bahr
el Ghazal. It charged that the U.N.-led operation dropped more than
enough food to feed everyone on the ground but that the famine
still persisted.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the food reaching those who needed it, the French aid
group declared, the aid was largely distributed among a privileged
few that included the rebel forces. Some aid workers reported
seeing sacks of grain stockpiled in huts by the local authorities
while the dispossessed were starving to death. In one instance,
they saw soldiers stealing rations from women and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of an emergency assistance operation should be
evaluated by its capacity to distribute aid to those who need it to
survive,'' the report concluded. ``The hundreds of tons of food
sent to Ajiep did not achieve this result. How long can
humanitarian agencies pour in tens of thousands of tons of food
without being able to control where it goes and without ensuring
that the aid actually saves those who really need it?''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Ajiep is a small village. But its population swelled
to about 120,000 over several months last year after droves of
desperate refugees arrived. By October, Doctors Without Borders
said in its report, 2,500 tons of food had been delivered to Ajiep,
more than enough to feed all the people there. Yet, half the
children were still malnourished, the report said, and at least
3,000 people died. Few aid workers had ever witnessed such high
rates of malnutrition and mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Within the U.N. relief operation, people who criticize the
rebels for diverting food do so at their own peril. Hamish Young,
the World Food Program official, openly admits that the task force
report on the response to the Bahr el Ghazal famine was
``sterilized'' so as not to offend the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to incapacitate your ability to deliver food if
you slam'' the rebels, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Or worse, as the French aid organization Action Against Hunger
discovered. A member of the Operation Lifeline Sudan consortium,
the organization was expelled from rebel-held territory last year
after trying to find out why malnutrition rates at Labone, a
refugee camp in Eastern Equatoria province, were staying high
despite the fact that ample food was being distributed by Catholic
Relief Services.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Aguer, the liaison officer of the rebels' aid agency in
Lokichoggio, acknowledged that within the rebel forces there were
people ``looking at relief as a tool that could be used negatively,
as a weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, he said, local commanders employed the ``food
magnet'' principle when they moved large numbers of displaced
people simply by stopping food drops in one area and starting them
in others. But, he said, this was not a policy of the rebel
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it is Khartoum that has used the food effectively as a
weapon,'' Aguer said. ``Today we have 19 locations that are denied
food by Khartoum. There is no single area that is denied'' by the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Far from seeing themselves as equal partners with the U.N.-led
aid operation, the rebels are frustrated by the fact that the
Sudanese government has veto power over where food can be dropped,
Aguer said. The rebels, he said, would like to renegotiate the
agreement to give them equal status.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement is useful to just one side, and that is
Khartoum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From the government's view, the rebels are nothing but ingrates
who fail to recognize that it is not required to offer any
assistance to a military force trying to bring it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is shouldering the responsibility to feed the
people in whatever area _ government- or rebel-held,'' Farouk Ali
Mohammed Badra, the Sudanese ambassador to Kenya, said in an
interview. ``The problem is, the rebels have the tendency to use
the kindness of the government to their favor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government, he said, also was unhappy with the agreement
with the U.N.-led relief operation, largely because of the
perception in Khartoum that there are people who work for agencies
who are ``eager and interested in giving aid to rebel-held areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Badra also criticized the Western media in general and the
United States in particular for what he termed bias against his
government. He hinted that Washington was supporting the rebels,
citing as an example a meeting between Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and rebel leader John Garang in Kampala, Uganda, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say we are the bad guys,'' he said. ``I ask you, `Who
is the bad guy?' It is Garang.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`THE FOOD IS ONLY A BLOODY PALLIATIVE' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the scant, dappled shade of a thorn tree at a rebel base in
the Nuba Mountain village of Gideil, Daniel Kodi, a senior member
of the rebel command, sat sipping tea, his attention focused on a
conflict thousands of miles away from the one to which he has
devoted his life.
</P>
<P>
   Why, he asked, had the Western powers relentlessly bombed Serbia
because of its genocidal policies against the ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo, while they had done nothing to punish the government of
Sudan for waging a genocidal war against the Nuba people?
</P>
<P>
   It is a rhetorical question, one for which there is no easy
answer. It is also a question often posed by those embroiled in the
misery of the Sudanese civil war, a conflict that has taken more
lives than any other in the past 50 years but which has drawn scant
international attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United Nations' answer is to send food,'' Kodi said.
``That is not a solution. If it was a solution, why aren't they
dropping food on Kosovo instead of bombs? The food has saved lives,
but it has not helped stop the war.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't intended to. The U.N. aid effort, Operation Lifeline
Sudan, was established to provide humanitarian assistance to the
victims of the war and to try to prevent the recurrence of famine.
That it failed was not entirely the United Nations' fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food aid has been blatantly manipulated by both sides,'' said
John Prendergast, an analyst for the United States Institute of
Peace and a former White House adviser on East Africa. ``But both
sides in this war are fighting for fundamental principles. If food
aid was ended tomorrow, it would have very little influence'' on
bringing the war to an end.
</P>
<P>
   If the United Nations did stop delivering food, however, it
would result in the deaths of thousands, and it would rob the
Western governments that donate the greatest amount of food of what
some in the humanitarian-aid industry refer to as their ``fig
leaf,'' the alibi that allows them to at least appear to be doing
something about a conflict without having to address its root
causes.
</P>
<P>
   For in Sudan's civil war, not much is at stake that is of
sufficient strategic importance to compel the outside world to
intervene. Significant quantities of oil have been discovered in
Sudan's south, but there is no shortage of oil on the world
markets, nor is there expected to be for many years. Some mineral
deposits have been found, but not enough to fight over.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to some observers, if the civil war is considered
in the context of the overall dynamics of the Middle East, there
may, in fact, be compelling reasons not to solve the crisis,
because one of the solutions, secession by the south, could
threaten neighboring Egypt's access to water from the White Nile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may actually be in Egypt's interests to see the war
continue,'' said Roger Winter, executive director of the U.S.
Committee for Refugees. ``Our interests in the Sudan are limited.
And because of that, I don't think the (Clinton) administration has
a solution-oriented policy toward Sudan. We've been encouraging the
administration to take the lead in pursuing the idea of
self-determination for the south.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a new idea. What peace efforts have thus far been
initiated to end the war have led to an agreement in principle
among all the parties that the ultimate solution would be to
partition the country into north and south.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that this has not ended the fighting, Winter said, is a
``macabre Alice in Wonderland reality.'' People continue to die in
man-made famines, international aid continues to pour in, and all
the while everyone agrees on the steps necessary to stop the
carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Eiffe, a former Roman Catholic priest who runs the Sudan
operation of Norwegian People's Aid, an agency that does not belong
to Operation Lifeline Sudan and which openly supports the rebel
cause in the war, said that in the absence of the will to work for
a political solution, Western donor countries should support aid
agencies outside the U.N. consortium, such as his, so they can work
in the region unrestricted. Failing that, he said, the Western
nations should support the rebels directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need food,'' Eiffe said. ``The U.N. is dumping food
in southern Sudan. Dumping it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can keep your beans, your grain, your oil. Give us guns.
The food is only a bloody palliative.''
</P>
<P>
   It is highly unlikely that Sudan's rebels or their supporters
will get guns from the West. But they may get indirect support if
efforts in Washington toward a more engaged U.S. policy in the
region succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Already, certain non-U.N. agencies are being given relief
supplies to distribute independently of Operation Lifeline Sudan,
said a source in the U.S. Agency for International Development, the
government body that provides the U.N. aid effort with grain.
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., points to an
inherent absurdity in current U.S. policy toward the war.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, he said, supplies ever-increasing amounts of food to
feed people being starved to death by the Sudanese government. But
aid workers are required to seek permission from the same
government to feed the people it is trying to starve.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Frist believes, should embark on a policy of
unilaterally providing aid to the people affected by the Sudanese
civil war without regard to the constraints placed on Operation
Lifeline Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we can't do anymore,'' Frist said, ``is drop food out of
the back of an airplane and think that is solving the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that it has been used as an instrument of war,'' he
said, ``and the lack of recognition of that in Washington is what
angers me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
