<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-SUDAN-NUBA-ART-$ADV5-     09-01 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-NUBA-ART-$ADV5-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE OF NUBA MOUNTAINS UNDER GOVERNMENT SIEGE SINCE 1989 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
(For release Sunday, Sept. 5) 
 
By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUBA MOUNTAINS, Sudan _ When the absolute, immemorial silence
that cloaks these war-torn mountains is disturbed by the distant
drone of an aircraft, the people pause and watch the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   If the dogs stay supine in the shade, the people return to the
daily grind of survival. But if the dogs raise their heads and
whimper, if they become agitated and seek shelter, the people brace
for the bombs that could, at any moment, rain from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   For the dogs know. They can detect the distinctive timbre of the
engines of the dreaded Antonov-32, the bomber of the Sudanese air
force, the plane that drops the cluster bombs at random from high
altitude, rolled out of the back, not intended for anyone in
particular, addressed, the locals say, simply ``to whom it may
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   And they have learned, recently, to distinguish that ominous
noise from the sound made by the few planes that these days fly in
illegally and deliver a meager allotment of food.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, when the people of the Nuba Mountains, an amalgam of
about 50 Sudanese tribes who have long struggled for
self-determination, aligned themselves with the Sudanese People's
Liberation Army, the rebel movement that controls much of the
southern half of the country, they have been under virtual siege by
the government.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, the region was cut off from the outside world
while the Sudanese government systematically attacked the people in
the rebel-held areas of the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   By destroying crops, livestock and homes, hundreds of thousands
were forced to seek food and shelter in government-held garrisons,
which are generously supplied with food aid.
</P>
<P>
   But after the rebels carved crude airstrips out of the sides of
the mountains, the world began to see what had been wrought.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a pretty sight. Lush, fertile valleys that were once
the breadbasket of the region lie quiet and empty, baking under a
relentless sun, the silence broken only by withered stalks of
sorghum rattling in the breeze. Burned-out houses dot the
landscape, which is scarred by bomb craters. The people who remain
scratch out an existence with implements fashioned from shrapnel.
The daily chore of collecting water sometimes involves a four-hour
trek to the nearest well.
</P>
<P>
   Painted by the numbers, the picture is just as depressing. Ten
years ago there were about 1 million people in the rebel-held areas
of the mountains. Today only about 400,000 are thought to remain.
Between 100,000 and 200,000 are believed dead. An estimated 60,000
are said to be close to starving to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is very bad,'' says Daniel Kodi, a senior member
of the Sudanese People's Liberation Army. ``This is genocide, but
nobody (in the West) will call it that. In Rwanda they refused to
use the word, and now they are refusing to use it here.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the government's blockade of the rebel-held areas of
the Nuba Mountains kept commerce, trade and aid out. But in June,
the government bowed to international pressure and allowed a U.N.
assessment team to tour the area.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the only clues to what was happening in the
mountains were provided by a pro-rebel organization, the Nuba
Relief, Rehabilitation and Development Society, which had patched
together a fly-by-night relief operation to supply the beleaguered
people with a trickle of assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Risking being shot from the sky by Sudanese government MiGs or
bombed on the ground by Antonovs, aircraft loaded with food and
basic tools of survival fly from a base in Lokichoggio, Kenya, to a
crude, rocky airstrip in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   After the planes swoop in for a white-knuckle landing, swarms of
people appear from the bush, and in 15 or 20 minutes the planes are
unloaded and refueled. Then they spin around and disappear again in
a cloud of dust.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few hours, with bags of sorghum on their heads, the
people have melted back into the bush, leaving a handful of
soldiers in thong sandals and threadbare clothes to defend the
airstrip against attack with their antiquated Kalishnikovs.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons the Islamic fundamentalist government in
Khartoum is so resolute about its desire to rid the mountains of
the rebels. For one thing, the region is technically in the north
but is allied with the rebel movement of the south. And at least
half the people are Muslims. Any successes by the Nuba Mountains
people against the Islamic fundamentalist government could become a
clarion call for other marginalized people in the north.
</P>
<P>
   For another, the Nuba Mountains are strategically and
economically attractive _ those who control access to the area rule
vast oil reserves discovered just to the south; Arab merchant
farmers of the north see great potential in the fertile valleys.
</P>
<P>
   But for whatever reason, the government's resolve to chase the
rebellious tribal people out of the mountains appears absolute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nuba are more repressed than any other people in the
Sudan,'' says Kodi, who served in Khartoum as a member of
Parliament from the mountains before deciding there was no future
in trying to achieve his goals politically and joining the rebels.
``We are discriminated against racially, socially, economically,
religiously. In all ways. They (the government) want us gone and
they will do whatever they have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's favored method, Kodi said, is the destruction
of food supplies, coupled, on the one hand, with permission to
distribute food in government ``peace camps'' and on the other, the
denial of food aid into rebel-held territory.
</P>
<P>
   But, when possible, the government also bombs schools _ the best
of which amount to little more than shacks _ and the region's only
hospital, which is run by a German medical aid organization out of
a mud hut in a remote village.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from these particular targets, what is striking about the
bombing campaign is its randomness. Its pattern is evident by the
craters spotting the landscape _ holes, scattered shrapnel, mangled
trees. But there's really nothing to bomb here. Not a house,
building or person in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't care if they hit anything,'' says Mohamed Omar, a
rebel fighter. ``It's just for terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar straightens, drops the shrapnel he is holding into the dust
and continues down the path. After a while, he stops, head tilted
to the side, listening. The sound of an airplane penetrates the
stillness. Omar waits, motionless, concentrating, and then he moves
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the food,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
