<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7122 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-SUDAN-AID-ART-3TAKES-     09-01 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-AID-ART-3TAKES-$ADV5-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAPPED BY DEMONS OF WAR, SUDANESE TURN TO AID FOR SURVIVAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photos available on NYT database) 
(For release Sunday, Sept. 5) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANTHOU, Sudan _ The woman crawls on hands and knees, her
fingers prying kernels of grain from the soil, squirreling them
away in a filthy cloth she carries for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``In God's name, I didn't get food,'' Amou Bak calls out in
raspy complaint, turning a beggar's hand to two relief officials.
``I swear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 16 tons of flour, peas and sorghum sit stacked in bags a
few feet away, ready to be passed out to the several thousand
refugees who have spent a scorched afternoon awaiting it.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the bounty will go to Amou. Not this food. Not
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``She received food yesterday,'' says James Mugo, a young Kenyan
who is the United Nations' representative here, throwing a
dismissive nod toward the prostrate woman. ``She's just making a
show of this, hoping she can get more.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, some 60,000 people died in the famine that seized
Panthou and scores of other hamlets in Bahr el Ghazal, a desolate
province just below the line separating Sudan's rebellious south
from the unyielding north.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by rebel and international aid agencies found
that death fell heaviest on women and children, many of them
refugees running from Sudan's now-perennial warfare, who lacked the
political or family ties to wangle food from local tribal chiefs
and rebel commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Amou changes her story and tries again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others took my food,'' she says, her voice shriveling to a
whining resignation. ``I swear it. I swear it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mugo and Victor Madut, a former grade-school teacher now
with the rebels' aid branch, turn their attention to the rows of
other women who will be fed today. The women, who have moved to
Panthou or nearby villages from war-racked areas, flare out on
three sides of the stacked food like the spokes of a broken wheel.
</P>
<P>
   On Mugo's signal, Madut orders the distribution to begin. His
underlings pass the command to the hard-faced men who walk the
lines of women like shepherds, growling warnings and slicing the
air with long switches.
</P>
<P>
   Amou's pleas fade as the late afternoon's golden quiet
evaporates in a rising din of hungry expectation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now!'' the herders shout to the women. ``Move!''
</P>
<P>
   The women rise to their feet in unison and march forward. They
hold open their empty sacks for the free food: some grain and some
peas, a little flour. Enough for a family, enough for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Chattering as they sling bags filled with food over shoulders or
upon heads, the women turn toward their makeshift homes. But many
walk only a few hundred yards before gathering again in tight
knots. Then, they divide the food among themselves, culling a share
for relatives and others, according to custom.
</P>
<P>
   Mugo and other relief workers say such redistribution doesn't
matter, that most of the food ends up in hungry bellies anyway. But
U.N. investigators say that an untold amount goes to local chiefs
and to rebel military units.
</P>
<P>
   Diversion, aid workers call it with frowns and shrugs. A
business cost in the relief game.
</P>
<P>
   Quarrels among the switch-wielding men erupt as the handout
continues. Curses are spat and fists shaken, as the men argue about
which family, clan or village has the right to be here.
</P>
<P>
   Today's food is being passed out to refugees from elsewhere now
living around Panthou. But that doesn't stop the locals from trying
to get a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always trying to sneak in,'' Mugo says after wading
into one knot of men to settle a fight that nearly had come to
blows. ``We have to screen them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food is not for everybody,'' Mugo says. ``There has to be
a selection of who is vulnerable. There has to be a lot of
cooperation. We target the displaced, but a lot of them never
receive help.''
</P>
<P>
   At the tail of one of the lines, 12-year-old Abuk Garang
prospects for dinner, burrowing into the dirt with her bare hands,
hoping to find what even the birds have missed.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd gathers around the girl. Several people offer
encouragement, others rebuke. But most just shake their heads and
stare, wizened smirks pulling at mouths.
</P>
<P>
   Abuk ignores her jury, holds firm to the task.
</P>
<P>
   Using thumb and forefinger, the child picks a few grains from
the hole and calmly lays them with others she has gathered in a
wooden bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not from here,'' explains a woman who says she is Abuk's
aunt. ``Our home is far away. There is no one to care for her. No
one to provide.''
</P>
<P>
   As the woman speaks, Abuk paws at the earth, harvesting another
day one kernel at a time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`THEY ARE NOBODY. AND THEY ARE NOWHERE.' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Life always has walked the thinnest of lines in this
heads-you-lose corner of southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   When conditions comply, the soil yields enough grain for people
to get by. Sprawling swamps and shallow rivers provide forage and
water for livestock, fish for the table. Wild fruits and seeds _
even the leaves and bark of trees _ nourish people through the lean
months.
</P>
<P>
   But usually it rains too little or too much. Seeds fail to
sprout, or crops wither beneath the relentless sun. Cattle, which
many people consider the bedrock of civilization, are stolen with
abandon and almost always with bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   And, for 16 years now, merciless war has reigned, tearing
asunder most everything worth anything.
</P>
<P>
   The people of southern Sudan whirl in a vagabond's orbit. Ever
more reliant on the kindness of strangers, they shuffle between
what they have been and what they have yet to become.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are forced to live a life they cannot understand,''
says Sam Okara, a relief worker from neighboring Kenya who has
supervised U.N. aid operations in southern Sudan for six years.
``They are not living a customary way, and they can't live a modern
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are nobody,'' Okara says. ``And they are nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The war is transforming the once proudly self-reliant Dinka, the
region's largest ethnic group, and other southerners ``into people
who are totally dependent,'' says Francis Deng, a Sudanese scholar
at the Brookings Institution in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the humanitarian tragedy of this war,'' says Deng, the
son of a famous Dinka chieftain who grew up in a village not far
from Panthou.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dinka have always seen themselves as the chosen people,''
he says. ``To have these people plunged into a conflict that is so
devastating really has gone to the core of what it means to be
human in their own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's current conflict started in 1983 when southerners _
black Africans who worship either their ancestral deities or the
Christian God _ rebelled against the economic, political and
cultural domination of the country's Islamic and Arabic north.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 2 million civilians from the south's Dinka, Nuer and
other ethnic groups have been killed. Livestock have been rustled
and crops laid waste. Entire regions have been gutted. Millions of
people have spent years fleeing tribal rivals, Islamic holy
warriors and pro-government mercenaries.
</P>
<P>
   Although government troops still hold many of the south's larger
towns, the Sudan People's Liberation Army and other rebel
organizations now control most of the countryside. In recent years,
squabbles among southerners _ fueled by tribal animosities, warlord
rivalries and northern intrigue _ have caused much of the
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Regional quarrels are nothing new in a land where loyalties long
have reached no further than an extended family, where identities
have been tied to the lands where a family's cattle graze.
</P>
<P>
   But automatic rifles and other modern weapons have transformed
even minor encounters into slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   And every so often _ when war and weather and human whim have
converged _ famine has flared.
</P>
<P>
   After one season of starvation killed 250,000 southern Sudanese
in the late 1980s, a horrified world created an aid pipeline called
Operation Lifeline Sudan to guarantee that it could never happen
again. Last year, another famine killed about 60,000 Sudanese
children, women and men.
</P>
<P>
   There seems little hope of ending the bloodletting _ or the
charity _ any time soon. Years of halfhearted mediation by other
countries and the Sudanese themselves have achieved only temporary
cease-fires.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the war is going on, we will have people depending
upon foreign assistance,'' says Philip Aguer, a ranking relief
official for the Sudan People's Liberation Army, the main rebel
faction.
</P>
<P>
   Though the international relief operation has saved an untold
number of lives, many worry that the aid is irrevocably altering
the societies it aims to rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thought of the negative impact of relief on the
population,'' says Aguer, a Dinka from a village along the White
Nile. ``It has affected us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many relief officials insist, however, that the aid operation's
purpose is nearly as much about preserving lifestyles as lives.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that effort focuses on helping the Dinka and other
ethnic groups avoid eating or selling their cattle. Considered by
many to be the truest measure of worth, cattle play a central role
in the southern Sudanese way of life.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange of cows and bulls by relatives of the bride and
groom seals marriages. Families name animals according to hide
patterns and other attributes, then christen their children after
the livestock. Boys achieve manhood tending to cattle herds far
from their villages.
</P>
<P>
   People nourish themselves with cow's milk and blood. But they
eat beef only on special occasions or when an animal dies of
natural or accidental causes.
</P>
<P>
   The theft of livestock has defined relations of families, clans
and villages for generations.
</P>
<P>
   But the dual onslaught of war and relief is straining the cattle
culture.
</P>
<P>
   So many animals have been stolen by raiders from both north and
south or sent to more peaceful areas far away that boys often have
no herds to tend. Many people postpone marrying because of a lack
of cattle. Marriages that do take place get sanctioned with animal
IOUs.
</P>
<P>
   And relief food has replaced the relentless scramble for
nourishment that once defined life's meaning here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people in the south used to depend on cows'' for
their livelihoods, Aguer says. ``Now people are accustomed to going
to relief centers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THIS IS THE RAIDING SEASON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A fleet of mud-and-thatch huts anchored in a golden sea of
grass, the Dinka community of Panthou teems with life.
</P>
<P>
   Laughing children flock to any diversion. Teen-agers, many
singing as they work, gather straw for roofs and the walls that
encircle family compounds. Women tend to chores. Men pass the
sultry afternoons beneath shade trees, arguing crops, livestock and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Cows and goats wade in shallow ponds and graze alongside the
dirt airstrip at the center of the village. Other cattle fan out to
feed in the marshy pastures straddling the Lol River to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Drums beat throughout the day, advertising the dance that will
come with the night.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's war seems distant, its hunger even more so.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Many Panthou residents only recently returned home after a long
exile last year, when much of Bahr el Ghazal province writhed with
famine, war and retribution.
</P>
<P>
   After many rainless months, the village's ponds have all but
evaporated, and the hardened earth has cracked. The ribs of the
grazing animals strain at their flanks.
</P>
<P>
   People will plant again once the rains come and the
foreign-donated seeds and tools arrive. But reaping what they sow
will depend on whether new attacks come before the crops are ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might plant, but you might not get to harvest,'' says
Okara, the Kenyan who has worked as an aid worker in Panthou.
``There is a lot of demoralization.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the raiding season, when pro-government militias, tribal
warlords and free-lance cattle rustlers traditionally sweep across
southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent peace agreements between Dinka and Nuer chiefs,
cease-fires called by rebels and the government, and the return of
one warlord's army to the insurgent side have eased the raids'
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   But Arab horsemen still escort the trains moving along the
tracks 12 miles west of Panthou. As the trains progress slowly
south with supplies for government troops in the garrison towns of
Aweil and Wau, the horsemen attack outlying villages to loot, kill
and sometimes carry women and children off into slavery. Recent
raids have killed scores of people across Bahr el Ghazal.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of refugees have fled to the dubious safety of Panthou
and surrounding villages from even more vulnerable areas to the
north. In recent months, however, relief workers have evacuated
Panthou twice because of insecurity. Past attacks have destroyed
much of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a family here that hasn't lost its house and many
of its animals,'' Piol Geng, Panthou's top chief, says in a blend
of halting English and rapid-fire Dinka. ``My village is always
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, families labor on new huts that rise alongside the shells
of houses wrecked in last year's fighting. Refugees throw up
makeshift dwellings close to the field where relief food gets
passed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that another attack will destroy these, too,''
Alfred Deng, the head of the rebels' aid agency in Panthou, says of
the new houses. ``But people have to get the roofs on before the
rains come.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of its central location and smooth dirt
airstrip, the community of 20,000 has become a hub of the
international relief effort. The compounds of a half-dozen relief
agencies hulk behind high grass walls like castles in some feudal
fiefdom.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers have had to adjust to new customs, brought by the
foreigners, that seem as alien as ice to this tropical plain.
</P>
<P>
   The relief agencies, for example, have tried to channel food
deliveries through women, bucking social customs that relegate most
power to men. South Sudanese men often have several wives and
children by each.
</P>
<P>
   According to the foreign logic, putting food into women's hands
seems a sure way to get food to the neediest. For that reason, the
relief workers have created aid committees dominated by women. The
Dinka have accepted them with a knowing wink.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some places, the relief committees work very well,'' says
Madut, the former Dinka schoolteacher who now works for the rebel
relief agency. But in others, he says, ``the chiefs have too much
power, and they decide everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. distributes to the women, but the men are definitely
in charge,'' Madut says. ``It's cultural.''
</P>
<P>
   The last word on who gets relief food in Panthou rests with
Piol, 32, who recently inherited the position of senior chief from
his father. Piol _ who, like many Dinka, usually goes by his given
name _ rules through a network of subchiefs and family heads, all
of them men.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting beneath a tree on the edge of the village, the young
chief and his men decide how much food each family will get and how
much the community at large will share.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers give some relief food to the chiefs as a tax. The
leaders then redistribute the aid, sometimes to people overlooked
by the relief workers' committees. Some of the food ends up in
rebel troops' stomachs, U.N. investigators admit, either when the
guerrillas eat meals with their families at home or with comrades
in military units.
</P>
<P>
   But, Piol says, providing for their own people remains the
chiefs' first priority. Refugees and other outsiders go to the back
of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always struggling ourselves,'' Piol says. ``There isn't
enough for the people that come from far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more food. We always need more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HUNGER ALWAYS HITS THE CHILDREN HARDEST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charity starts early and lasts the day in Panthou.
</P>
<P>
   By shortly after sunrise, several hundred women holding infants
and toddlers squat in disciplined rows outside an emergency feeding
center.
</P>
<P>
   Because the children they bring are severely undernourished,
these women have the right to twice the food allotted everyone else
in Panthou _ enough to fully feed their families.
</P>
<P>
   Other villagers must supplement the free food with their own
supplies, however they can.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger always hits the youngest hardest, aid workers say. Giving
double rations to the entire family of a badly malnourished child
lessens the chance that parents or siblings will steal food for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   During the famine that swept Bahr el Ghazal province last year,
more than half of the children examined in Panthou were
malnourished. Many of them desperately so.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions have improved after months of relative peace and
relief food deliveries. But the next famine remains an attack or
crop failure away. Any new crisis, aid workers say, will show
itself first in the children.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
