<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7126 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-RYAN-COLUMN     09-01 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-SCHOOL CAPTAIN FACES A CHEMISTRY TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Let the bonding begin, sayeth the captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every moment we can spend with one another is golden in my
mind,'' declares Ryder Cup captain Ben Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   The man cares so much about what he's doing that it's beyond
frightening. Should the US not retrieve the Ryder Cup four weeks
hence, please, somebody, hide all swords. I would be willing to bet
that Crenshaw has read up on the Samurai warriors and would know
exactly what to do in the event of a negative outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Ben was over at The Country Club Monday with eight of
his Ryder Cup boys. Absent because of the proverbial prior
commitments were Tiger Woods, Mark O'Meara, and Tom Lehman. Absent
because of a very sore neck was Davis Love. Eight out of 12 is not
exactly what the captain had in mind, but it's a start.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose was twofold: 1. Get in a practice round. 2. Start
working on developing some (itals)wa.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   The practice was important, but not that important. Everyone had
predictably nice things to say about the old girl, and you didn't
get the idea that the course intimidated anybody. Justin Leonard
pretty much summed up the feeling of the first-timers about the
personality of the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some blind tee shots and the greens are fairly
small,'' he observes. ``It's an old, classic course.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's one that has a definite appeal to captain's choice
Steve Pate, who made a run at the 1988 US Open title at The Country
Club. ``I love this place,'' he gushes.
</P>
<P>
   That said, might Mr. Pate have any advice for some of his
teammates?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing they probably don't already know,'' he shrugs.
``Obviously, the greens are pretty small here. The center of the
green makes for a good target. I think they'll figure that out.''
</P>
<P>
   The captain could do about seven hours on each and every one of
the 18 holes (it's starting to sound as if he's envisioning a
little retirement condo on the grounds), but it's very clear that,
in the mind of Crenshaw, the 1999 Ryder Cup isn't going to be about
the course, as worthy as it is. It's going to be about assembling a
T-E-A-M in the next four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a day of learning,'' he declared. ``It was a day to
be together. It is important for us to be together as a team,
because it's something they know and possess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They,'' of course, are the Europeans, who, despite coming from
many different countries (seven this year), have precisely the
spirit Crenshaw seeks for his squad. With no flag to rally 'round,
and nothing to bind them except a strong desire to whip the fat cat
Yanks, the Europeans have won the last two Ryder Cups.
</P>
<P>
   We all know what Crenshaw wants. What we don't know is whether
these men are even constitutionally capable of giving it to him.
</P>
<P>
   No one brought up the compensation issue Monday, but you'd have
to be pretty naive to think the matter has been forgotten. Strong
things were said behind that closed door in Medinah last month, and
let no one think they're all on the same, how you say, page.
There's been a public truce; that's all.
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart, age 42, is Old School. David Duval, age 27, is
New Wave. Stewart remembers when the Ryder Cup was a simple matter
of the Red, White and Blue kicking butt and taking names before
modest crowds and a handful of media folk. Duval is on record as
calling the Ryder Cup both an ``exhibition'' and a ``large
corporate outing.'' Psst, Captain Ben: This may not be an ideal
four-ball pairing.
</P>
<P>
   Duval may be trying, but he still has a hard time getting into
this ``team'' stuff. ``As much as you want to talk team,'' he says,
``when Phil (Mickelson, another New Waver) is out there, he has to
make that putt. We can't help him do that.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. But what you can do is give him a pat on the back
and a ``hang in there'' if he misses that 3-footer. That's what
being a good teammate is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, each man will be swinging his own club, but there are
dynamics inherent in team competition that do not exist in regular
tour play. Crenshaw is convinced that European mastery of those
dynamics has made the difference in the last two Ryder Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these guys are just phlegmatic by nature. This is a
sport, remember, in which a man can become very wealthy without
actually ever winning anything. At a big event you can cart home a
six-figure check for cracking the top 10. They all say they're
competitive, but pragmatism very often overrules dramatics. Why go
for it when laying up will guarantee a round-saving bogey?
</P>
<P>
   No offense, but Jim Furyk did not exactly come across Monday as
a man with a crackling personality. Even backed by a microphone, he
could barely be heard from 5 feet away. Perhaps he'll blossom over
the next few weeks, but you've got to wonder if he really has it in
him to get excited over anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developing some team chemistry is up to Ben,'' maintains
Stewart. ``I think he's got to work with the different
personalities and treat them gingerly at times while being firm at
other times.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Crenshaw will know where Stewart is coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will bring enthusiasm to this team because I love team
sports,'' Stewart says. ``I played football and basketball in high
school, and I love the team element. I like to support other
people. I'm just very rah-rah, I guess. I don't know if you'd call
me a motivator, but I am enthusiastic, and that enthusiasm will
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Great. There's one. Does Stewart see any allies?
</P>
<P>
   ``Other rah-rahs?'' he inquires. (Long pause). ``No. You're
looking at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there enough time? Crenshaw says he wants his Ryder Cuppers
to hang out together wherever they go in the next few weeks. But
will a couple of dinners be enough to make palsy-walsy teammates
of, for example, Stewart, Pate, and Hal Sutton on one side of an
age and attitude divide and Duval, Mickelson, and mega-celebrity
Tiger on the other?
</P>
<P>
   Pity Captain Ben. He may be coaching the wrong team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
