<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-SUDAN-AID-ART-3RDTAKE     09-01 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-AID-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV5-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
PANTHOU, Sudan: in the children. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they while away the hot morning outside the feeding center,
the women gossip and argue. Many of their young children cry. Local
men employed by a foreign aid agency move among them, keeping
order.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting instructions through bullhorns and carrying long
switches, the men command those waiting to be still, then to move
forward row by row. Mothers and children pass through the feeding
center gates and enter a gantlet of aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   Each child gets measured and weighed, poked and prodded.
Children under 80 percent of the normal height and weight for their
age win a continued slot in the feeding program and double rations
for their families.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have inched above the minimum for two weeks running
get gently turned away. A nurse clips off the ankle tags that serve
as the children's admission tickets to the program.
</P>
<P>
   Conflicting emotions cross the faces of the mothers whose
children have been culled. Graduating from the program means a
child's chance of survival has improved. But it also means that a
family's food ration is halved, making eating each day much harder.
</P>
<P>
   The mothers of children who remain in the program collect their
food, then walk out the narrow back door. Relatives await to
accompany the lucky malnourished home.
</P>
<P>
   On the fringe of the crowd, Dinka boys swarm aid workers, trying
to impress them with the worthiness of their own despair.
</P>
<P>
   Look, the boys signal, pointing at bare feet, tugging at
tattered shirts.
</P>
<P>
   I have no shoes. I have no clothes. Give me water. Give me food.
</P>
<P>
   Look.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will line up for food, will fight for it, beg for it
and die for it,'' says Chol Changath Chol, a Dinka intellectual
educated in Egypt who now works with an international aid agency in
Panthou.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the food is never enough. If disaster comes again, what
will these people do? Why don't the Dinka do something?''
</P>
<P>
   The sun seethes in the center of the sky as a U.N.-chartered
cargo plane sweeps over Panthou. Hundreds of women and children
rush through the dry grass to the shade trees alongside the drop
zone, prattling in anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Gripping hollowed gourds, old sacks, anything that can hold
food, the women and children stand with faces upturned, watching
the aircraft make a wide swing above the village.
</P>
<P>
   The food that this plane will drop has been triple-bagged. But
some &UR;  &LR; of the 110-pound sacks always burst in the plunge to earth.
The spilled contents provide easy pickings for the quick.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane cuts across the drop zone, its nose pulls up.
Hundreds of bags of food tumble from the tail hatch like manna,
raining onto the field with dull thumps.
</P>
<P>
   As the hum of the aircraft's engines fades into the southern
sky, village men begin collecting the sacks and stacking them in
one corner of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Someone gives a signal.
</P>
<P>
   The waiting scavengers sprint forward, diving into the soil with
hands outstretched, using handmade whisk brooms to gather the
spilled grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can they say we are creating dependency?'' Mugo asks, as
he watches the clamor. ``Last year here, people were walking
sticks. As long as people need food, we need to intervene.''
</P>
<P>
   Twilight grants its reprieve from the day's sun and scramble. In
the cooling air, Panthou begins to settle in for the night, cooking
fires flickering to life.
</P>
<P>
   Achol Mayon places a meager supper over the flame she has built
outside her family's hut.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight Achol is cooking the yellow peas she received in
yesterday's handout. She's boiling them plain.
</P>
<P>
   Achol and her three children never ate yellow peas before the
U.N. planes started bringing them. They don't particularly like
peas. But nowadays, people in Panthou eat whatever drops from the
heavens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peas are fine,'' Achol says as she stirs her pot, a toddler
suckling at one breast. ``Corn is better, but peas are fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`THAT'S HOW WE ARE. SO PROUD. SO INDIVIDUAL' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only a few hours past sunset and already the Sudan sky seems
dark as deep space. Stars splay across the black expanse, lining up
here and there to form constellations, jumbling into glitter that
stretches beyond sight, into time.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen aid workers sit on folding chairs around a small
wooden table in the center of the U.N. compound. The Dinka cook has
set the table with corn bread and a stew of yellow corn and red
beans. Somebody produces a can of beef, someone else a bottle of
scotch and several more of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Providence smiles.
</P>
<P>
   A teen-ager from the village points out a fast-moving star.
Likely a satellite, he's told. Dinner conversation turns to walks
on the moon and wireless communications, to the threat of space
invaders and the miracle of e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Burning marshlands to the north, where pastures are being
refreshed for livestock, throw off a muffled red light that throbs
like a heartbeat. The talk shifts to grazing cattle, to the coming
planting and to the horse-mounted raiders who could scrape
everything away again.
</P>
<P>
   James Mugo says he plans to do nothing but watch television
during his upcoming five-week leave back home in Kenya. He misses
the modern age, craves a world beyond this emptiness.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of young men pass just beyond the grass walls, heading
from family compounds toward the drums pounding in the distance.
There will be dancing tonight.
</P>
<P>
   While they walk, the young men sing improvised ballads impugning
their rivals, or old favorites bragging of their people, their
cows, their culture, themselves.
</P>
<P>
   So many cattle have been carried away, so many friends and
enemies have succumbed to the shooting and the starving. Pride,
even the foolish kind, seems all that remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how we are. So proud. So individual,'' says Chol, the
Dinka aid worker, as he listens to the singing. ``During the famine
last year, we died the same way: too proud and too
individualistic.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-moon rises in the east, its wan light shunting the
darkness. At the dancing place, on the village's northern edge, a
few dozen youths begin the ritual steps, circling a pole set in the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   As the young men dance, hundreds of people amble in wide circles
around them, trading gossip, preening and prancing. All seem
dressed in their finest clothes, the Dinka's tribulations stored
away with the daylight.
</P>
<P>
   One square-backed man arrogantly pushes through the crowd, a
rack of short spears slung across his back, marking him as a
revered hunter and warrior. A boy, scarcely 12 years old, strolls
in a fine white robe that flows to his ankles, an assault rifle
slung over one shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Adolescent girls stand in tight gaggles watching the dancers,
laughing shyly as other boys cruise by. Young women work the crowd
with more purpose, trying to keep their reserve while catching a
fellow's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to look for a wife,'' says William Deng, a 21-year-old
from the village who has just finished working on a U.N. anti-polio
campaign. ``Everyone comes looking for someone to marry.''
</P>
<P>
   With the war and the hunger, marriage comes harder these days.
</P>
<P>
   Yet courtship survives. The young people still dance, as the
Dinka always have. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Feet kick up clouds of earth, painting the night's pitch with
an even deeper ink. Grit clings to tongues, clots eyes, cakes hair
and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The drums pulsate, and the dancers speed and slacken to the
pace. Each boy's hands clasp the shoulders of the dancer ahead,
feet shuffle and stomp. Together they coil around the totem in a
scooting frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Clenched fists and waving arms. Spears and rifles. Flirting and
fawning, feigning and fretting.
</P>
<P>
   Life.
</P>
<P>
   Dinka life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chibac,'' the young women say, clinging nervously to one
another, offering the boys limp hands and winsome smiles. ``Hello
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chibac,'' answer the boys, chests thrusting, chins thrown
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your name?'' the young men ask in the thin light.
``What's your father's name? Your father's father's name?
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is your clan?''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, chibac then. And chibac to you.
</P>
<P>
   Something in the still air shifts. Heavy fumes suddenly mingle
with the dust, sending some into coughing fits. A brief rumor runs:
The enemy threatens. They have sent poison gas to kill us. We are
doomed.
</P>
<P>
   No. It's only smoke from the burning swamps. Food enough keeps
dropping from the sky. The cattle are fewer, but safe. Planting
will start soon.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble remains a shadow for now.
</P>
<P>
   The Dinka keep dancing, on toward another dawn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
