<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7129 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-SUDAN-AID-WORKERS-ART     09-01 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-AID-WORKERS-ART-$ADV5-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF WORKERS WRESTLE WITH RESTRICTIONS, FRUSTRATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Sept. 5) 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOKICHOGGIO, Kenya _ Charisse Tillman spends her working hours
seeking what she sees as balance in a place perpetually out of
kilter.
</P>
<P>
   Working in a small, air-conditioned office in this ragged Kenya
border town, the 32-year-old American plays a key role in helping
the United Nations decide how much grain and beans, cooking oil and
other supplies should be dropped on the war-plagued landscape of
south Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   In making the calculations, Tillman says that she and her
colleagues try to figure how much food people in a given area can
scrounge on their own. The World Food Program, the U.N. agency for
which Tillman works, will make up the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to understand how they meet their food needs, how they
compose'' their diet, Tillman says. ``The fact is, people have one
harvest a year, so they are permanently at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   For a decade now, people like Tillman have labored under an
umbrella of U.N. and private relief agencies that have delivered
tons of food and other supplies to the victims and perpetrators of
one of the world's deadliest and most intractable wars.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is tricky work at best.
</P>
<P>
   The mandate of the relief coalition, called Operation Lifeline
Sudan, is to save the lives of women, children and other innocent
civilians caught up in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   To do so, the organization must work with the permission of
Sudan's government and under the often severe limitations set by
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   If too much food is delivered, Sudanese villagers can get
comfortable with charity, trading survival skills developed over
centuries for lives on the dole. If too little is sent, famine can
rear.
</P>
<P>
   Tons of food dropped to people in one village may anger rivals
in another. Or an aid delivery may strengthen one warlord at the
expense of another. Either way, the food can spark violence. And it
often does.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for their delicate task, Tillman's field workers
receive a mere one month's training.
</P>
<P>
   Once deployed in rural south Sudan, they often find themselves
dependent upon one of the region's rebel groups for the completion
of their projects. Rebel military commanders often warn them of
impending danger or protect them from attack.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the tension caused by the fighting, relief
workers must wrestle with heat, boredom and deprivation. Malaria
and other diseases abound. The land swarms with poisonous serpents
and insects, with crocodiles and lions, with every kind of creature
that ``can sting, bite or spit,'' as one aid worker puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover among relief workers, not surprisingly, is high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The isolation, the difficult working conditions are almost
unparalleled anywhere else in the world,'' says Ted Chaibon, a
ranking official for Operation Lifeline Sudan in Kenya. ``It's
understandable that people take it for a year or two and say,
`Hell, I'll go somewhere else.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although they bring enormous, albeit fleeting, wealth into south
Sudan's villages, many of the aid workers have little or no
knowledge of the societies in which they operate. Few know more
than a handful of words from any of the region's languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``To work in this area, you need to know the history, politics
and culture,'' says Dan Eiffe, a former Roman Catholic priest from
Ireland who has performed relief work in south Sudan for the past
11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many aid workers seem engrossed with news about warlords
and the region's shifting alliances. They proudly toss around the
tongue-twisting names of villages, track the movements of warlords,
debate whether the crops will fail, whether the rains will fall too
little or too much, too early or too late.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the World Food Program's people in Sudan are Kenyans who
have chosen U.N. relief work as a career. The rest include young
Europeans, Americans and Australians, many of whom have fallen into
the field by chance and leave it after a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Though they are paid well by African standards, many of the aid
workers say that a desire to help people drives them more than a
paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``To know you can go in and make their lives a little bit better
to me is the motivation,'' says Waimiro Munio, a middle-aged Kenyan
woman who has worked in Sudan for three years. ``There is no reason
to watch a child die in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as they feed the victims of the conflict, which by some
estimates has killed more than 2 million people in the past 16
years, some relief workers wrestle with the purpose and
effectiveness of their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food is a lot of wealth being dropped from the sky,'' says
Hugh Greathead, a twentysomething Englishman who is returning home
after more than two years working in south Sudan for Save the
Children-United Kingdom. ``It has a lot of potential to go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relief influences the conflict,'' Greathead says, because it
is used by local political leaders as proof of their usefulness to
people. Aid, he argues, ``provides the services that a government
normally would supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Eiffe, the former priest who now directs the Sudanese relief
effort of Norwegian People's Aid, sees the issue even more starkly.
</P>
<P>
   By not actively taking sides or strongly pushing for peace,
Eiffe says, the U.N.-led aid operation is merely feeding the
victims of a conflict that could go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who is neutral should go home,'' Eiffe says. ``Help one
side or the other, and finish the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Eiffe, married to a south Sudanese woman with whom he has two
sons, has kept his relief agency out of the U.N.-led coalition.
That has allowed it to actively support the Sudan People's
Liberation Army, the largest rebel group in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Funded mostly by Norway's labor unions, Eiffe's organization
operates a network of hospitals that treat the rebel wounded as
well as feeding centers that hand out U.S.-supplied food to
guerrilla supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Eiffe has to maneuver within the ever-changing
atmosphere of the rebels' own factional feuding, his agency can aid
south Sudan's afflicted without the permission of the Khartoum
government. By shunning neutrality, he says, Norwegian People's Aid
enjoys an effectiveness that the U.N.-led consortium cannot muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this thing clearly,'' says Eiffe, who is called
Commander Dan by some Kenyan journalists because of his fervent
support of the rebels. ``We are actively, completely involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N.-led coalition, Tillman points out, must respect the
sovereignty of Sudan, a member of the United Nations. The charter
governing Operation Lifeline Sudan dictates neutrality in the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want our food to exacerbate the tension on either
side, to disturb the balance,'' Tillman says. ``We have to be seen
as objective as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Khartoum government, which is controlled by a fundamentalist
Islamic political movement, routinely restricts Operation Lifeline
Sudan's relief operations by closing dozens of southern villages to
food distribution in any given week.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, food dropped to farmers and herders
frequently ends up in the bellies of Sudan People's Liberation Army
rebels, many of whom are part-time warriors who live with their
families in the villages targeted for aid.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Lifeline Sudan's own investigators have found cases of
relief food being ``taxed'' by local tribal chiefs or rebel
officials. And food often is redistributed according to community
customs soon after it is passed out under the supervision of aid
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman acknowledges that local Sudanese officials often
pressure her workers, hoping to wheedle as much food as possible
from the aid agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you get some people who want to exaggerate their
needs,'' says Tillman, an African-American who studied business
administration in college and first became involved in the aid
industry by working for CARE.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N.-led coalition, she says, tries to make rebel and
village leaders ``understand that it's better that we get a clear
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't send us messages that your people are starving if
they are not,'' Tillman says.
</P>
<P>
   Her teams of assessors work up complex profiles on the
shortfalls in the nutritional needs of villagers, figuring the
availability of cultivated grain and wild food as well as the
prospects for fishing and hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle, which are seldom eaten by the south Sudanese, usually
are left out of the calculations. U.N. officials say the livestock
must be preserved to protect the region's way of life and to
prevent people from becoming totally destitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have a lot of cattle in a community, and people are
still in bad shape,'' Chaibon says.
</P>
<P>
   In struggling to save people whom they see as innocents, the aid
workers must wrangle with the incessant violence that sometimes
mocks even the best organized relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many wars within the war,'' Tillman says.
``Today, southern Sudanese are killing many more southern Sudanese
than the government is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can put people back on their feet,'' she says. But ``if
there is major fighting, we might be back to square one.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we see civilian women and children are
dying. It is frustrating. Damned frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
