<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' CARROLL EAGER TO FACE GOOD FRIEND SEIFERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The words kept coming, flowing and flowing
from the moment Pete Carroll opened Tuesday's press conference with
a quip, ``Other than the fact this is a grudge match between me and
George, what are your questions?''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll seldom seemed more at ease. His friend, his mentor, his
model for football operations was the subject _ George Seifert _
and Carroll went on and on.
</P>
<P>
   The irony in New England, of course, is that New England owner
Bob Kraft, when he was searching for a coach to replace Bill
Parcells, made his first phone call to Seifert, but Seifert turned
him down. And then recommended Carroll to Kraft in the next breath.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert's advice, Carroll recalled, was practical.
</P>
<P>
   All coaches go through hell, Carroll said Seifert told him,
adding, `` `You can take a job and battle to be 8-8 and bust your
tail off to do that but to have a shot at a team that has a chance
to win the championship, and you're fighting the same battles . .
.' That's what I was thinking, anyway, at the time but it was a
natural reinforcement coming from George.''
</P>
<P>
   As for replacing Parcells, and the trauma that could cause,
Carroll recalled Seifert saying to him, `` `Maintain the confidence
in what you've done and be yourself, do the things you know how to
do.' And he's continued to tell me that all along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Their situations had been nearly identical. Seifert had replaced
the very successful and very popular Bill Walsh in San Francisco
just as Carroll would be replacing a very successful and very
popular coach in New England. Time and again, in those crazy days
after the 1997 Super Bowl, Carroll and Seifert would talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it before I came here, about his situation and
how he had handled it,'' said Carroll. ``And he handled it so well,
it was so critical, because everybody was so much in love with Bill
Walsh and what he had done, for obvious reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Seifert, of course, was able to repeat Walsh's success with the
49ers. Carroll, as some Patriot fans mutter after every loss, has
yet to repeat what Parcells did here. Carroll may still be an
unknown after two years in New England, and Carroll's words about
Seifert _ ``He's a very enigmatic guy, and there're lots of sides
to George that people don't see'' _ could just as well be used to
describe Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll and Seifert will meet again on the football field
Thursday night in Charlotte, N.C., when the Patriots visit
Carolina, now coached by Seifert. Carroll had been Seifert's
defensive coordinator in San Francisco and the two were _ and are _
close.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to identify the one trait that enabled Seifert to
repeat Walsh's success, Carroll replied, ``I think it was his
ability to accept the situation as it was when Bill Walsh stepped
down and keep it exactly the same. Really, he was able to see in
his vision that they had something magnificent there and he just
wanted to keep it going. And George did things to keep it exactly,
precisely the same. In a quirky sense, George wouldn't change
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, of course, has gone much the opposite route in New
England, changing much of what Parcells did. Unlike Seifert, who
stepped into a system he was long familiar with, Carroll was
stepping into a different system.
</P>
<P>
   As for football, Carroll said Seifert ``is a very particular
guy, again to a quirky sense, and he's very precisionlike and very
precise about what he does. That is a good trait in football and he
picked that up from his own upbringing but also from Bill Walsh.
You see them being very particular in that offense of theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   The other football trait that has made Seifert successful,
according to Carroll (``and I know George doesn't like me to say
this''), is that he ``does everything the hard way. He makes hard
decisions and then makes them work. Remember those times when Steve
Young was questionable and George would make the decision to go
with the backup quarterback and make it work. He liked to do things
the hard way and then work through it.''
</P>
<P>
   So Carroll has tried to follow his mentor's advice and has
fashioned the Patriots' football operations after San Francisco's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say I had such a great time working for Bud Grant
(with the Vikings in 1985) and learned about football and the way
Bud saw things,'' said Carroll, ``but so many important things in
my football life have to do with what went on in San Francisco and
the way George and Bill built things there.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was surprised that Seifert would take a job so far from
the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``George is so San Francisco and it's so hard for me to
imagine,'' said Carroll. ``George is such a seaman, fishing and
ocean and boats and everything . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Much as many a Bostonian pictures the Hudson River as the West
Coast, Carroll then gave a West Coaster's view of Eastern geography
as he talked about Seifert in North Carolina:
</P>
<P>
   ``And now to see him in the middle of the country . . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
