<HEADER>
A7134 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-SUDAN-HISTORY-$ADV5-H     09-01 1778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-HISTORY-$ADV5-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFLICT IN SUDAN `A CHECKMATE THAT ONLY PRODUCES DEAD CIVILIANS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Sept. 5) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AJIEP, Sudan _ Almost from the moment Sudan became an
independent country in 1956, its various ethnic groups, warlords
and political factions have seemed determined to tear it apart.
</P>
<P>
   Rebellions have sprouted, flourished and died in a haze of
blood. Dizzying shifts in alliances and ideologies, gruesome human
rights violations and civilian suffering have punctuated the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere has the turmoil been greater than here in the country's
south, a Texas-size expanse of prairies and woodlands, shallow
rivers and marshes inhabited by tribes that have more in common
with people deep in Africa's heartland than with the desert
dwellers of the north.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners fought a war against the central government in
Khartoum from 1956 to 1972, settled into an uneasy peace for 11
years, then took up arms again in 1983 when the government reneged
on its promises of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   The war has claimed the lives of more than 2 million people,
almost all of them southern Sudan civilians, since it reignited 16
years ago, according to Millard Burr, a former U.S. State
Department official who tallies the casualties for the U.S.
Committee for Refugees, a Washington, D.C., advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Another 6 million civilians have been displaced by the fighting,
Burr calculates, with some 350,000 living in refugee camps in
neighboring Kenya and Uganda and the rest dispersed across Sudan.
About 1 million southerners have fled to the north, mainly to areas
around Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the south suffers bloody squabbles between ethnic-based
armies backed by either the Khartoum government or various rebel
groups. Militia horsemen sanctioned by the government launch raids
to steal cattle and burn villages. Sudan air force planes routinely
bomb communities held by rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is ``an intractable game of checkmate that only
produces dead Sudanese civilians,'' Roger Winter, director of the
U.S. Committee for Refugees, told a congressional committee in the
spring of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the southern rebellion has mutated from a
Marxist effort supported by Cuba, Ethiopia and other leftist
governments to a nationalist movement that receives limited support
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the U.S. government increased shipments of food and
other supplies to openly pro-rebel aid agencies as a way to
circumvent Khartoum's influence on relief efforts. These aid
agencies operate independently of a U.N.-led relief coalition that
delivers food and other help only to areas approved by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's view of Sudan has varied during recent decades. At
the height of the Cold War, the U.S. government considered the
staunchly anti-communist dictatorship in Khartoum a key African
ally. But since a 1989 military coup put a fundamentalist Islamic
movement in power, Sudan has been regarded as a supporter of
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say Sudan's rulers aided Osama bin Laden, the
Saudi financier accused of planning the deadly bombings of the
American embassies in Kenya and Tanzania last year.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the embassy attacks, the United States bombed a
pharmaceutical plant in Khartoum that Washington suspected of
producing ingredients of a deadly nerve gas. Sudanese officials
denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Often painted simply as a conflict between Sudan's Arab north
and its black African south, or between northern Islam and southern
Christian and animist faiths, the war actually is far more
entangled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war is racial. It is cultural. It is religious,'' says Dan
Eiffe, a former Roman Catholic priest. As director of the Sudanese
operations of Norwegian People's Aid, Eiffe openly backs the Sudan
People's Liberation Army, the main rebel group in the south
controlled by U.S.-trained economist John Garang.
</P>
<P>
   Economic factors also are driving the war.
</P>
<P>
   The south's relatively small population and large reserves of
oil and other natural wealth have long made it prized by the rulers
in the north.
</P>
<P>
   The White Nile River, the source of water vital to both Sudan
and Egypt, flows through the south. A large canal project, put on
hold by the fighting, aims to divert Nile water around swamplands
in the heart of rebel territory in order to increase the river's
flow to the north.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a new pipeline began pumping oil to the north from
fields in the south, providing the Khartoum government with badly
needed income. The rebels have vowed to shut down the pipeline, and
fighting recently has flared near the oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the violence seems rooted in cultural differences. Though
unified in the colonial era, people in the north and south have
never had much in common.
</P>
<P>
   The north, once known as Nubia, was deeply influenced by Egypt
in the time of the pharaohs and later by Islamic and Arabic
traders. Today, most northerners speak Arabic and practice Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Divided among several ethnic groups, southerners speak a variety
of languages and have cultural links to the tribal societies of
central Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Most southerners practice traditional religions that acknowledge
the existence of a supreme God but worship lesser spirits as well.
About 10 percent of the south's population, including many of the
educated elite, are Christians.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, many northerners viewed the south largely as a
source of slaves. Northern raiders often swept south to capture
women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say that a brisk slave trade continues today with
raids on southern villages made for the purpose of capturing women
and children to sell in the north. The extent of the slave trade,
however, is hotly debated.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt conquered northern Sudan in 1821 and later took control of
the south as well. Eventually, all of Sudan fell under the joint
rule of Great Britain and Egypt, which together granted the country
independence in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Southerners who launched the 1956 rebellion against the Khartoum
government objected to the use of Arabic as the country's official
language and the predominance of Islam, among other things. A 1972
agreement that granted the south extensive autonomy ended the first
round of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   But the violence erupted anew in 1983, when Khartoum reneged on
many of its promises of self-rule and imposed Islamic law on the
entire country. Southerners, led by Garang and other
English-speaking leaders of the Dinka ethnic group, launched a
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters from the Nuer and other southern ethnic groups joined
the rebels in the late 1980s. Early this decade, however, many
tribal warlords broke with Garang and other leaders of the Sudan
People's Liberation Army, and some became allies of Khartoum. Since
then, former rebel allies have waged much of the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle rustling, long considered a normal and honorable pursuit
among many of the south's men, has contributed to the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Various ethnic groups, even villages of the same tribe, have
fought over cattle-grazing lands for centuries. But now that most
fighters in the south have replaced spears with automatic weapons,
the death toll from the raids has skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   The Khartoum government has supported various factions against
one another in a largely successful effort to keep the south
fractured, experts say. Many officials in government-held areas of
the south are drawn from anti-rebel members of the region's various
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Garang's rebel movement has joined northern
opposition groups to form the National Democratic Alliance. The
alliance includes political leaders deposed in the 1989 coup as
well as northern rebels who bitterly oppose Khartoum's
fundamentalist regime.
</P>
<P>
   Because the fighting has hampered the people's ability to farm
or raise livestock, famine has struck southern Sudan repeatedly.
After one such crisis in the late 1980s, the United Nations and
three dozen private relief agencies set up Operation Lifeline Sudan
to funnel food and other aid to the south. The relief effort was
intended as a short-term humanitarian fix. It has been in operation
for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan will need about 150,000 metric tons of relief food this
year, according to the World Food Program, the U.N. agency through
which much of the aid from the United States and other donor
countries filters. The organization warned in July that more than
100,000 southern Sudanese still face the prospect of starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's is one of many wars plaguing Africa. On Sudan's borders
alone, fighting between Ethiopia and Eritrea has killed tens of
thousands. Somalia wrestles with persistent clan feuding. Uganda
fights loyalists of a former dictator and guerrillas from a
fanatical Christian movement. And the Democratic Republic of Congo,
formerly Zaire, struggles with a multisided civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and other industrial nations have failed to
force solutions to the conflicts in Africa. This stands in stark
contrast to the situation in Kosovo, where the U.S.-led NATO
alliance effectively forced Yugoslavia to surrender the province.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say that the United States and other Western
governments find it easier to aid the victims of the African
conflicts than to force a peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pathetic international situation,'' says John
Prendergast, a former Africa policy analyst with the Clinton
administration who now works at the U.S. Institute for Peace, a
government-funded think tank. ``If there were a sustained,
coordinated international pressure, you would see a quick
solution'' to Sudan's war.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict, Prendergast adds, simply ``is not a compelling
national security issue for the powers that have the capacity to
intervene.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Sudan's government and Garang's rebels met in
Kenya in July to start another round of peace talks. Past
negotiations have proved futile, however. And despite cease-fire
declarations for areas across southern Sudan, the violence
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the international community doesn't require a
political solution, the negative side effects of the problem will
get worse and worse,'' says Hamish Young, a former corporate lawyer
from London who is now a top official at Operation Lifeline Sudan's
headquarters in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   If the international community wants to end the suffering in
Sudan, Young says, it must end the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation-states of the world have to stop it,'' he says,
``and they have the means to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
