<HEADLINE>
U.S. ALLOCATES JUST 1 PERCENT OF OVERSEAS FOOD AID BUDGET TO SUDAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Sept. 5) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. government supplies most of the food delivered to
Sudan's needy by the United Nations and private aid agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Surplus U.S. wheat, corn, beans, peas and oil are donated under
a variety of programs, most of which help support prices for
American farmers while bolstering Washington's foreign-policy
objectives.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has committed nearly 143,000 tons of food aid
to Sudan this year.
</P>
<P>
   According to the World Food Program, U.S. donations account for
as much as 88 percent of the relief that will be delivered to Sudan
in 1999 through Operation Lifeline Sudan, an umbrella group of U.N.
and private agencies.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. food aid also has been sent to private organizations
outside the U.N.-led group.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the importance of the U.S.-supplied aid to Sudan, the
relief represents just a little more than 1 percent of the 12
million tons of relief food that Washington will send overseas this
year. Russia is scheduled to receive 3.2 million tons of U.S. food
aid, and Kosovo will get 250,000 tons in the last six months of the
year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The international community has earmarked $142 million for Sudan
relief this year. In July, 100 countries and international
institutions, such as the World Bank, pledged $2.1 billion for the
reconstruction and development of Kosovo, which has less than 10
percent of the population of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan is one of 80 countries receiving some sort of aid from the
United Nations' World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
   However, because of chronic insecurity and the lack of a
developed system of roads, the relief effort in Sudan relies on air
deliveries, making it one of the most expensive such operations in
the world. Spending on Sudan relief accounted for 13.5 percent of
all World Food Program expenditures in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say the United States is committed to the Sudan
relief effort for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we believe that people are seriously at risk and we
can monitor (the aid), we will be there,'' says Larry Meserve, an
official with the U.S. Agency for International Development in
Kenya who oversees U.S. donations to Operation Lifeline Sudan.
``It's not acceptable for innocent civilians to starve to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't pull out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
