<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7137 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-SUDAN-ATTACKS-ART-$AD     09-01 1673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-ATTACKS-ART-$ADV5-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREAT OF ATTACK KEEPS VIGILANCE CONSTANT AND RELIEF SLOW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
(For release Sunday, Sept. 5) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AJIEP, Sudan _ Two dozen relief workers slouch around a wooden
table inside the low-slung dining hall of the United Nations'
outpost in Ajiep, a village where famine preyed last year.
</P>
<P>
   The workers, most of them foreign, have come together to talk
about ways to better coordinate their efforts, so another crisis
can be averted.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting has started sluggishly, with vague questions,
evasive answers and thousand-yard stares.
</P>
<P>
   Midafternoon heat hangs like a demon's breath in the open-sided
thatched hut as Mawiir Nyok, a midlevel operative with Sudan's main
rebel movement, tacks some hand-drawn organizational charts to an
easel.
</P>
<P>
   Pacing commandingly, Mawiir ticks off what he sees as the aid
priorities for the hardpan country around Ajiep. With some old
scores to settle and some new arms to twist, he has decided to come
on tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not dictating any program,'' says Mawiir, a 33-year-old
former U.N. driver with the broad shoulders and expanding waist of
an aging athlete. ``But we need for something to evolve from
somewhere to somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one woman, new to the area, interrupts. What happens, she
asks, if there is an attack by government troops or one of the
area's many marauding militias?
</P>
<P>
   Good question.
</P>
<P>
   For years now, the big-money strategies devised by the world's
humanitarian industry for southern Sudan have been hampered by
inconsistent rebel policies, obstacles set by the government in
Khartoum and poor planning by the aid agencies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has been more disruptive, however, than the warfare
scraping back and forth across the south.
</P>
<P>
   Every attack delays or derails elaborate aid efforts. Food
stockpiles get stolen, and seeds meant for planting are eaten
instead. Tools get carted away or destroyed. Newly dug wells are
poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   And villagers scatter, refugees once more.
</P>
<P>
   No foreigners have been killed in southern Sudan since 1992,
when two aid workers and a journalist were ambushed. But there have
been plenty of close calls.
</P>
<P>
   Mawiir thinks for a minute, his scowl yielding to a sardonic
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very simple,'' he says. ``If danger comes from the west,
go east.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these aid workers have fled places like Ajiep before,
leaving with only a few minutes' notice, running and walking for
hours or days through the dry brush country, eyes ever scanning for
attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Ajiep itself has been evacuated twice because of insecurity in
recent months. And dozens of people have been killed in raids on
nearby villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fighting is not a permanent thing,'' Mawiir says of the
violence. ``It is a game we play every year. It's running back and
forth.''
</P>
<P>
   As the top aid coordinator for the Sudan People's Liberation
Army in the area that includes Ajiep, Mawiir holds the power to
veto any relief program and to expel any foreigner who displeases
him. But he assures the aid workers in the meeting that the rebels
understand the difficulties they face.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start with something and it's disrupted,'' Mawiir says,
referring to the possibility of evacuation in the face of attack,
``there will not be any blame.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good news. Because Ajiep has been consumed with
recrimination for a year now.
</P>
<P>
   An indifferent collection of stick and mud hovels built on sand,
the village anchors a stretch of scorched land in Bahr el Ghazal
province that famine stalked last year. With the number of people
needing help skyrocketing to nearly 1 million, the relief agencies
stumbled, critics say, failing to get food to those who needed it
most. No one knows for sure, but some 60,000 people are thought to
have perished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to repeat what happened last year,'' says Daniel
Ladoucer, 32, the newly appointed U.N. supervisor who called the
meeting. ``We would like to foresee a little better when the
emergency will occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like nobody knows who is doing what where,'' he tells the
relief workers.
</P>
<P>
   With the sun falling in the western sky, however, the meeting
breaks up with little accomplished. Everyone agrees to continue the
next morning.
</P>
<P>
   But a deep, predawn rumbling off to the west changes those
plans. The noise sounds like thunder, but there are no rain clouds.
Someone is shelling someone else, says a Sudanese worker in the
Irish relief agency's camp. And it's not that far away.
</P>
<P>
   Tension builds with the rising sun. Are government forces
attacking? Will they come to Ajiep?
</P>
<P>
   If the fighting marks the progress of a government convoy along
the road on the other side of the Jur River, and if the
government's horse-mounted militia is escorting the supply trucks,
attackers could be here within an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone in southern Sudan is terrified of the militia
cavalrymen, mostly members of Arabic clans from northern Sudan.
Armed with swords and automatic rifles and often riding several
hundred strong, the horsemen attack with little warning along the
dirt roads that cut through the thorny brush.
</P>
<P>
   There are few vehicles in the south, and people often must flee
the horsemen on foot. Hundreds of villagers die trying every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the horsemen attack, I would rather just shoot myself,''
says one aid worker. ``I have nightmares about those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladoucer works the radio in the U.N. compound, trying to get
information about the apparent shelling from Operation Lifeline
Sudan's base in Lokichoggio, more than 600 miles away in Kenya.
Radio conversations drift out of other aid compounds, as agency
workers check in with their own support bases.
</P>
<P>
   Lokichoggio responds that there is, indeed, fighting near Ajiep.
Rebels have attacked a convoy on the other side of the Jur River
that is carrying supplies for the government garrison in the town
of Gogrial.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Lifeline Sudan's security experts have placed Ajiep on
Level 3 alert. Everyone should get ready to run, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   The relief workers break camp in their adjoining compounds,
little more than tents and mud huts clinging to the sand. Backpacks
and tents, water and a little food are loaded into four-wheel-drive
trucks. All the equipment _ radios, medicine, tools _ and most
Sudanese employees will be left behind if the aid workers pull out.
</P>
<P>
   A visibly nervous Ladoucer walks over to talk to workers at the
Irish aid agency Concern. He argues for evacuating to a village 90
minutes by vehicle to the east.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the horsemen don't come, it is fine,'' Ladoucer tells
Concern supervisor Niall Roche, murmuring so that the Sudanese
cooks can't hear. ``If they do come, then the whole area is at
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Roche says he worries that Ajiep's civilian population will
panic if the aid workers leave. Still, Roche agrees to do whatever
the other aid workers decide.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone waits.
</P>
<P>
   By midmorning, however, no shelling has been heard for hours.
The relief workers decide to continue their meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But things have barely gotten started when the explosions start
again, seemingly much closer this time, sounding like some giant
fist knocking on a heavy metal door.
</P>
<P>
   Dark pillars of smoke curl on the western horizon. Going east
seems like a better idea than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Roche and other Concern staffers drive out to Ajiep's dirt
landing strip, where an air crew frantically works to repair the
engine of a charter plane that brought the Irish aid workers from
Kenya the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling with the engine, the mechanics and two pilots throw
nervous glances westward with each new explosion.
</P>
<P>
   High above, a government Antonov transport plane lazily
crisscrosses Ajiep, heading south toward the military garrison town
of Wau and north again toward Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
   The government uses the Russian-built planes to bomb rebel
positions. The Antonov crews simply roll explosives out the back in
the general direction of a target. Anyone can be hit.
</P>
<P>
   The charter pilots break out binoculars to track the Antonov.
But the plane flies too high to bomb and holds a course away from
the airstrip.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred local men and boys gather beneath a shade tree
near the crippled aircraft to watch the repair efforts. Few of the
Sudanese seem to take notice of the nearby explosions,
concentrating instead on trying to beg water, pens or anything else
from the handful of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of rebel soldiers, two and three at a time, saunter
across the airstrip, weapons slung lazily over shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people know,'' says Mawiir, the rebel official, as he
arrives to check on the mechanics' progress with the damaged
engine. ``If no one is running, there is no danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But southern Sudan's civilians are massacred by
raiders with sickening regularity. People don't always manage to
get away in time.
</P>
<P>
   Escape by air is not an option. The plane's engine has serious
problems, and new parts will have to be flown in from Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   The air crew and aid workers scrutinize the high grass that
stretches to the tree line marking the river a few miles away and
the road beyond. All minds are on the horsemen.
</P>
<P>
   Ladoucer drives to the airstrip with a decision. Planning will
have to wait for another, safer day. The other aid workers are
already in their trucks. They're evacuating Ajiep.
</P>
<P>
   Roche and his Irish colleagues agree. They say goodbye to the
pilots, the mechanics and the local Sudanese employees.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to go.
</P>
<P>
   The small convoy pulls away from the landing strip, heading
east. The men and boys gathered next to the plane impassively watch
the vehicles disappear into the thorny brush.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Ajiep never comes.
</P>
<P>
   But the foreigners have fled. And no one can say when they'll
return.
</P>
<P>
   Another threat. Another setback. Another day in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
