<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE COULD LIVE WITHOUT OLD-GROWTH FOREST, BUT WOULD BE POORER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having hiked through an old-growth forest this summer in Oregon,
I was happy to see the courts recently freeze nine big logging
contracts in national forests in the Pacific Northwest. In Seattle,
federal district Judge William Dwyer said the government has not
adequately assessed the state of wildlife in these lush, towering
woods that would fall before the chainsaw.
</P>
<P>
   What was refreshing about the decision was that it was not just
the spotted owl that Dwyer cared about, the bird that became the
symbol of West Coast environmentalism in 1994 when tree huggers and
tree cutters were at war. Dwyer said the Clinton administration,
which forged a compromise that let logging continue in about
one-third of federally owned old-growth forests, had not made a
proper inventory of 77 species of flora and fauna. Few of the
species inspire much romance, such as rodents and snails.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what the courts are here for,'' Doug Heiken,
the western Oregon field representative for the Oregon Natural
Resources Council told The New York Times. ``The point is, the
agencies are going to have to come up with a way to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Having the hike fresh in my mind, it was easy to understand the
judge's caution, as timber companies complained about big
government. It is not just merely feeling so small and
insignificant among Douglas firs that are 800-1,000 years old and
nearly as tall as redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   It is the completeness of the forest, from the moss and lichens
hanging from the trees to the dense carpet of ferns and underbrush
at your feet. It is the deepest kind of green, a green that yielded
to sunglight in only the most miserly, scant beams, allowing almost
no details to be easily visible on the little brown wrens that
hopped along the branches.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the trail, the Salmon River gurgled, as clear as tap
water. The answer to its clarity lay benath my feet. The forest
floor of packed-down leaves and needles, ancient root systems, and
massive piles of decayed rubble from previous generations of
Douglas firs and western red cedars filters the mountain runoff,
and allows no soil to erode, even in the heaviest storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old growth is not essential to the functioning of the Earth,''
Jerry Franklin, the University of Washington ecologist and one of
the first environmentalists to study old growth, once said. ``I
view old growth somewhat like I view museums or libraries or
universities. They increase the richness of our life here. The
world could survive without them, but it would be a much poorer
place.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a richness and completeness that we have finally begun to
appreciate, whether it is the 25 million acres of federally managed
spotted owl habitat out here, or the mere 700 acres back here in
Massachusetts. In recent years, scientists who had long assumed
that the highly developed East Coast had long cut down all its
virgin forest, have been finding patches of uncut, wind-shortened
350-year-old birches and relatively undistinguished but ancient
oaks in places like Mount Wachusett and Mount Greylock.
</P>
<P>
   Our old growth may not be as spectacular as out west, and not
even as interesting to the eye as the precious strands of tall
virgin pine in the north woods in Wisconsin and Minnesota. But it
is still a living museum of what parts of this continent looked
like before the Europeans. When Robert Leverett, a Holyoke computer
worker who searches for old-growth, found the birches on Mount
Wachusett, he said, ``we had the discovery of the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Old growth is surely one of the ``discoveries'' of our time.
This year, a fund-raising drive among technology workers in the
Seattle area _ with a heavy focus on Microsoft _ raised $13.1
million to save old growth forest in Washington state. In suburban
Milwaukee, the Ozaukee Land Trust has been buying up tracts of
woods and forests that go back to the 1800s. ``Saving land should
be a concern of everyone,'' said trust founder George Row.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pacific Northwest, where divisions between loggers and
environmentalists are at their most bitter, so acrid that a tree
hugger scribbled over the map at the Salmon River trailhead ``This
area will not be logged,'' there are signs that saving the land has
become a significant priority. High-tech jobs now outnumber timber
jobs. Tourism has grown. Tourists do not want clear cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Judge Dwyer, at least until he is convinced that
cutting will not wipe out whole swaths of ecosystems. Here, the
fights are not so nasty, but Leverett said, ``Most of us really
have a feeling somewhere inside of us that these places are
important and we shouldn't let them slip away.'' Whether it is the
dim emerald of the western giants or the near cadavers of birches
that went undetected until recently, the old-growth forest is one
of our last chances to slip back into time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
