<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-PROFILE-FOSTER-BOS &LR;      09-01 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-FOSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S FOSTERING CHILDREN'S LITERATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The faintest look of pride crosses Frances Foster's
face as she holds up the cast on her left hand. A missed
dining-room step resulted in a broken finger, she confides. ``I set
it myself. I didn't think that was anything unusual (it hurt less
that way, actually), but they were somewhat surprised in the
emergency room.''
</P>
<P>
   Gracious women of a certain age (Foster is 68) are generally not
thought of as setters of broken bones _ theirs or anyone else's. If
anything, it's even more implausible when the lady in question is
one of the doyennes of children's books, that ostensibly sunniest
of corners on Publishers Row.
</P>
<P>
   But Foster has a knack for going against type. From serving as
her own paramedic to remaking her career when an employer tried to
force her into early retirement five years ago, she displays a
demure unflappability that has made her one of the most admired
editors in publishing and helped her see into print some of the
most admired children's books of the last few decades. ``When I see
her imprint on a book, it makes me want to read it,'' says Roger
Sutton, editor of The Horn Book magazine, the leading review of
children's books.
</P>
<P>
   She tinkles with laughter when asked if, beneath her quiet chic
and Seven Sister-ish manner, there lurks a touch of feistiness.
``I've heard myself described more times than I like to remember as
`gentle' or `ladylike.' . . . I can't deny that part of myself, but
I'm the other one, too!''
</P>
<P>
   Foster comes by her strength of character naturally. ``My
father's ancestors were Nantucket whalers named Starbuck (not
Starbucks coffee). When I married, and gave up Starbuck for Foster,
a number of Boston librarians, especially, were a little upset that
I was giving up that good New England name.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster's husband is a retired Bell Laboratories researcher. They
live three hours north of New York. She comes into the city on
Mondays to spend time with her grandchildren (she has three) and
most weeks comes into her office at Farrar, Straus and Giroux on
Tuesdays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   One of her authors, Peter Sis, was so appalled by the first
sight of her office at the firm's legendarily seedy Union Square
quarters that he offered to paint a view for her windowless office.
Sis, a Czech emigre, was heard to mutter, ``I haven't seen anything
like this since coming through immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   Amenities apart, Foster has found a happy home at FSG. She
annually publishes a dozen or so titles under her own imprint,
Frances Foster Books. Last year, a sixth of her list _ Louis
Sachar's young-adult novel ``Holes'' and Sis's ``Tibet: Through the
Red Box'' _ accounted for a Newbery Medal (one of the two most
prestigious prizes in children's publishing), a National Book
Award, two Boston Globe-Horn Book awards, and a Caldecott Honor.
And as proof that mass can honor class, ``Holes'' is the
best-selling title Foster has published, with some 200,000 copies
in print.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, by ``Harry Potter'' standards, sales of which are
somewhere in the vicinity of 800,000 copies, that's merely
impressive. Yet thanks in large part to the ``Potter'' phenomenon,
there's a renewed interest in children's books _ and anyone
interested in the subject is likely to become interested in Foster.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's almost from some different time,'' marvels Sis. ``It's
easier to say what other editors do wrong than what she does
right.'' Trying to explain what makes Foster special, Sis summons
up an image magical enough for one of his books.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are these boats somewhere in Iran, I believe, on these
lakes with flowers? You go on the boats very slowly, with a pole
sort of sliding on the water. Working with Frances for me is like
that: When her boat bumps into mine, it does it so very gently.
Other editors are like speedboats and try to roll over you or
completely change your direction. She's very peaceful and
coexisting.''
</P>
<P>
   When Foster started in publishing, 45 years ago, it was in
children's books, and she's never strayed. She's worked with such
classic children's authors as Leo Lionni (Foster is one of his
memoirs' dedicatees) and Roald Dahl (``He could be charming _ and
then something little could happen that would just set him off: He
was a bomb ready to explode''). Those were authors she inherited,
though. More important are the ones whose careers she's helped
discover and/or nurture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Besides Sis and Sachar, they include Kate Banks, Mordicai
Gerstein, Suzanne Fisher Staples, Ann Cameron, Claire Nivola,
Elizabeth Spires, and Jonathan Frost. Foster grimaces when asked
what makes for a Frances Foster book. Lacking ``a neat or succinct
answer,'' she proceeds to give just that _ albeit one that begs the
question _ ``I look for a book I just like so much I absolutely
have to publish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two things do stand out, though: quality and an unwillingness to
underestimate young readers. Foster's authors have tacked subjects
that are diverse, distinctive, and _ for those expecting the same
old kids' stuff _ not a little daunting. They include coming of age
on the Indian subcontinent (Staples's ``Shabanu''), the wild boy of
Aveyron (Gerstein's ``Victor'' and ``The Wild Boy''), Galileo and
Tibetan mysticism (Sis's ``Starry Messenger'' and ``Tibet: Through
the Red Box''), Emily Dickinson (Spires's ``The Mouse of
Amherst''), the Holocaust (Nivola's ``Elisabeth''), and
homelessness (Frost's ``Gowanus Dogs'').
</P>
<P>
   ``People think children's publishing is play,'' Foster says.
``It's not taken quite seriously. I think people take it more
seriously now than they used to, partly because it's a money-making
end of the business. You know, people say when they hear you're in
children's publishing, `Oh, that must be so much fun!' Well, it is
fun, but it's also work.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster grew up in comfortable circumstances in Berkeley, Calif.
(her father was a banker), and came east _ or at least midwest _ to
attend Denison University. What is it that makes people go west?
``I think it's the same thing that makes people come east. At the
time, I thought Ohio was pretty far east.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, she spent a year in Rome doing office work.
She got her first publishing job as assistant to Alice Dalgliesh,
an important figure in children's books as both editor and writer.
Later, she worked as a freelance editor while raising her two
children, then joined Knopf (that's where she edited Lionni and
Dahl).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The manner in which Foster shifted employers five years ago at
once belied and underscored her growing eminence in the field. That
Knopf wanted her to retire was a shock (and not just to her), but
even more of a shock (at least to her) was what came of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was offered early retirement, and for maybe 12 hours I
thought, `Well, maybe this is as good a time as any.' I was
expecting a first grandchild and had an image of me pushing a
stroller again and thought there was a nice symmetry in it. Then by
the next morning I began getting phone calls from other publishers
asking what I was going to do. The first one was the one that
interested me most: FSG.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster has a near-unique perspective on children's books: from
prewar (when she was a consumer) to ``Harry Potter'' (her books now
compete against J. K. Rowling's). She spent her childhood reading
A. A. Milne, ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland,'' and the ``Dr.
Dolittle'' books; and now navigates a marketplace in which
multimedia tie-ins are more important than story values at most
publishing houses. She believes the shift in the industry to a more
profit-oriented model took place when she was still a relatively
young editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big change in children's publishing came in the '60s, when
all of a sudden there was a lot of federal funding that went to
schools and libraries and there was a lot of money that came into
the industry. At the same time, looking back, you can see that men
began to come in then, too. When it began to be bigger business and
more money, it began to attract men. . . . Before that, it was a
female ghetto.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy to go her own way, courtesy of FSG, Foster looks forward
to publishing books well into the next decade. The one predictable
thing about her imprint is that it will go its own way, and that
way won't be quite like anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   How unlike anyone else's? Asked to name the books she read with
her own children, Foster ticks off a list of usual suspects that
includes ``Make Way for Ducklings,'' ``Ferdinand the Bull,''
``Babar,'' ``Dolittle,'' the ``Mary Poppins'' series, Dahl's books,
and C. S. Lewis's. ``Conspicuously absent was Dr. Seuss,'' she
notes (with the slightest hint of glee?).
</P>
<P>
   ``Though he is universally appreciated, his books didn't appeal
to me; they wouldn't be Frances Foster Books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
