<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-WOM-HAGERMANS-ART-BOS     09-01 1786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-HAGERMANS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTERS OF THE REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA MATSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dave and Parnie Hagerman's four children, all girls, all
athletes, have unconventional names and unusual talents.
</P>
<P>
   The parents, private school educators, have lived their lives in
the sheltering circle of boarding schools. The world outside spun
around them, while the Hagermans were tucked safely on quiet, leafy
campuses, raising daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The Hagerman girls arrived at five- and six-year intervals, and
Dave and Parnie's child-rearing odyssey paralleled the evolution of
girls' sports. Ironically, the confines of conservative prep
schools gave their girls the freedom to be athletes long before the
rest of the world caught up.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hagerman sisters have jaw-dropping athletic credentials:
Casey, 29, good enough to be named to the Junior Olympic field
hockey squad as a high school senior, was one of the first ice
hockey recruits to Dartmouth College. Kulin, 23, graduated from
Middlebury College in June with three Division 3 national
championship titles, two in lacrosse and one in field hockey.
Jamison, 18, swept through Deerfield (Mass.) Academy starring on
the soccer, hockey, and lacrosse teams; spent a week this summer at
the USA Hockey Women's Hockey Festival in Lake Placid, N.Y.; and
joins the defending national champion hockey team as a freshman at
Harvard this year. And Whitaker, 11, is a seventh-grader in Wenham,
Mass. who plays hockey, soccer, field hockey, basketball, and
lacrosse, and who beats her sisters at tennis.
</P>
<P>
   The Hagermans know all about the rapid changes in girls' and
women's sports spawned by the passage of Title IX in 1972; they
have lived through them, year by year, season by season, with their
own kids. They had to work to find opportunities for Casey, and
now, nearly 20 years later, they are trying to limit them for Whit.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hagerman was a goalie for the University of New Hampshire
hockey team in the 1960s, and Parnie Hagerman was named most
athletic girl at her high school in Manhasset, N.Y. So it was
natural that the Hagermans would introduce their children to
sports. They took their kids to the Y to swim, to the rink to
skate, to the tennis court near their summer cottage on Bailey
Island, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   At the prep schools where the Hagermans lived and worked _ first
Deerfield, then Hotchkiss, then Pingree _ the campuses were filled
with kids doing things: lacrosse and hockey and soccer, as well as
drama and art and academics. Everyone did everything: boys, girls,
teachers, faculty kids. So first Casey, then Kully, Jamie, and Whit
simply walked out the door of their campus house and joined in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started by following,'' said Casey, who grew up at
Deerfield. ``I got involved because my dad was coaching hockey. All
I looked forward to in the world was being a stick girl and
standing on the bench with my Dad (at games) on Saturday
afternoons.''
</P>
<P>
   But when they wanted to introduce Casey to organized sports
outside the cocoon of family and Deerfield, the Hagermans had to
knock down doors to find teams that would let her play.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Greenfield, Mass., youth hockey organization) wouldn't
let me play hockey because there was no accommodation for girls,''
said Casey, now married, the mother of a 1-year-old son, Jake, and
an educator herself in Dallas. ``And they didn't want me to get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   After newspaper stories began to appear throughout the nation
about sports programs starting to open to girls, Casey finally got
a chance to play youth hockey in fourth grade. She loved hockey,
but it was a lonely experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember boys scoring goals and hugging their friends, and
they wouldn't come near me,'' she said. ``In sixth grade, I had to
change into my hockey stuff in the handicapped stall of the women's
room. I was the only girl . . . it was hard. It was lonely to get
changed in that bathroom by myself, knowing my friends were all
together in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Kully, six years younger, watched as her sister pushed open
doors. But Kully, a very social person, didn't like what she saw in
the little rooms behind those doors. She didn't want to be the only
girl on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey started playing hockey and swimming, and I just
followed,'' said Kully. ``She liked hockey more, but I stuck with
swimming. I saw her having to change in the bathroom, and I saw she
was the only girl. That wasn't very attractive to me at that
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kully stayed with the traditional girls' sports of field hockey
and lacrosse and the separate but equal world of swimming, with
co-ed meets but competition restricted to same-sex races.
</P>
<P>
   And Kully participated in another era in the growth of women's
sports. She chose to go to Division 3 Middlebury College, in part
because she wanted the opportunity to be one of the last of the
three-sport athletes. For her first two years, she swam and played
field hockey and lacrosse. As the demands of playing for two
nationally-ranked teams grew, she dropped swimming for the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to college, I really didn't know which sports I
wanted to do, and the last thing I wanted to do was give up
swimming, which was the sport I'd been doing the longest,'' said
Kully, newly appointed assistant coach for field hockey and
lacrosse at Wesleyan. ``It's so difficult to manage, even with two
sports. Everyone is just specializing so much now, even coaches.
Middlebury was perfect timing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jamie began taking part in sports, the doors had all swung
wide open. Living at Hotchkiss School in Lakeville, Conn., Jamie
began youth hockey at age 4. It was a small town, and the rest of
the players on her team were boys, but that was not a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really, honestly thought I was a boy until I was 6 years
old,'' Jamie said. ``We were all best friends, and we did
everything together.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamie also skated with the girls' team at Hotchkiss, climbing
off the school bus from elementary school and running to the rink.
She didn't run into any doors until junior high _ but then she
found there were some people who were slamming them in her face.
</P>
<P>
   When Casey was young, the boys who didn't want her on the ice
had tried to flatten her. ``I remember one time a boy just teed me
up and pummeled me behind the net,'' Casey said. ``I felt my
collarbone snap. But there was no way I was getting off the ice. I
got to the bench and said to my father, `something's wrong with my
arm.' He got the biggest kick that I finished the game and shook
hands. But he never said `tough it out' to me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jamie hit eighth grade and the boys began to resent her
presence, she was too good, too strong a skater: They couldn't
flatten what they couldn't catch. So they threw words.
</P>
<P>
   ``At an Avon-Salisbury youth hockey game, a kid said, `why don't
you just go home to your boyfriend?' '' Jamie said. ``It was the
first time I heard that stuff. They said, `you suck, you're a girl'
and `your boobs are getting in the way,' and stronger stuff. I
didn't talk to my mom right away, but I told Kully (then a junior
in high school), and she was outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnie and Dave decided to move Jamie to the Polar Bears girls'
hockey program, a 90-minute drive each way for practice, but one of
the nation's strongest girls' teams and enough of a challenge for
the talented Jamie.
</P>
<P>
   Five years younger than Kully, Jamie won't even try to be a
three-sport athlete at Division 1 Harvard. She hopes she can play
lacrosse along with hockey, but she isn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie, you see, spent much of her senior year in high school
answering the phone. College recruiting for women athletes had
arrived. In the 10 years between the flattering attention
Dartmouth's George Crowe gave to Casey and the constant cajoling
and convincing that a host of coaches rained down on Jamie, the
scene had changed. The Hagermans had realized that ice hocky
prowess was a powerful addition to the college admissions folder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recruiting is tough because there weren't a lot of girls
before me that could tell me what to expect,'' Jamie said. ``It was
intense for a month, then I made my decision in November. And it
was hard because hockey was always my safe place to go. Then when
the calls from coaches were coming, three or four a day, it wasn't
as much fun as it used to be. I had to sit back and think (about
where to go.)''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to train constantly and to specialize in one sport
has begun to reach down to girls in Whit's age group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be more vigilant with Whit than with either Casey,
Kully, or Jimmer because there's so much overemphasis now,'' Parnie
said. ``You have to keep it balanced. Now there's so much
attention, so much year-round stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Whit, who plays youth hockey with a co-ed town team, has had the
opportunity to play with Assabet Valley, a challenging girls'
program, right from the start of her hockey career.
</P>
<P>
   But she has also been pressured by the coach of the all-star
soccer team to participate year-round. Already tall, she has drawn
the attention of the rec league basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a `be careful what you wish for' situation for women,''
said Parnie.
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, Parnie who was the first chapter in this
story. Born with athletic talent and a desire to play, Parnie had
no opportunities. When she went to UNH in the 1960s, there was no
women's sports program. None.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kid with the girls that I was born too soon,'' Parnie said,
``but it wasn't a few years too soon, it was 30 years too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Parnie is not envious of the opportunities her children
have had that she did not. And her older daughters do not envy
their younger sisters. Each enjoys the next one's success, so much
so that Casey, once an ice hockey star herself, said she gets
goosebumps on her arms just talking about Jamie's extraordinary
physical gifts and her success in hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you can say your kids have things you didn't,
your life is a success,'' said Parnie. ``I don't know if I could _
even now _ do an athletic career and have these four beautiful
children. If I'd had to choose, there's no question what I'd do.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnie, sitting on a bench next to Whit and Jamie, smiles
broadly at her two youngest children.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, she says, Jamie, or perhaps it will be Whit, won't have
to make that choice between building a career as an athlete and
building a family. Maybe with all the doors open, there will be
room to move about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
