<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASKETBALL-AMBASSADORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BELGRADE BOMBINGS, BASKETBALL DIPLOMACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ They were here to play basketball for an Italian
team, here to compete in a preseason tournament, three games packed
into four days.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a little twist of fate: Sydney Johnson and Lee
Nailon are Americans _ among the first Americans other than
journalists to come to Belgrade since the end of the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   Whose idea was this, anyway? Americans shooting hoops in
Belgrade, two months after US pilots were dropping bombs on the
city? Doesn't more time need to pass between bombs and basketball
games?
</P>
<P>
   The players were wondering just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit I was really nervous about coming,'' said
Johnson, 25, a Princeton University graduate, a few hours after his
arrival last week. He was sitting in the opulent Hyatt Regency
hotel lobby that swarmed with other basketball players on his team,
Milano Olympia. ``I called my girlfriend, called my brother. He
told me to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who graduated with a degree in history, looked around
the lobby, anchored on one end by a statue of the Greek god Zeus
lifting a brass clock above his head. ``It is kind of weird to be
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nailon, 24, who played well enough at Texas Christian University
to be a second-round draft pick this year of the National
Basketball Association's Charlotte Hornets, spread his 6-foot-8
frame across a plush maroon couch, his feet hanging off the edge.
He admitted he hadn't known what he was getting into.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know nothing about Belgrade being bombed,'' he said.
``I mean, I knew that we bombed somewhere over here, but I didn't
know it was here. I just found out a few days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the first game against the Yugoslav Red Stars, Milano
coach Marco Crespi gathered his team together. ``This is the first
tournament after the war,'' he told them. ``It's not just an
ordinary basketball tournament, it's a tournament that shows people
in Belgrade that life can go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Crespi also preached caution. Later, he told a reporter, ``I
said to them, maybe the situation in Belgrade is OK, maybe it
isn't. Maybe going out at night isn't the best thing to do, and
maybe it's best not to drink more than Coke in the pub. And in the
games, behave like gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   At the tipoff, which Nailon failed to control, most of the 3,000
fans cheered loudly for the home team. When Johnson dribbled up
court for the first time, scattered boos rang out.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, with NBA-like cheerleaders dressed in skimpy
Spandex dancing to ``Hit the Road, Jack,'' Serb fans, extremely
knowledgeable about the game, assessed the two Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The playmaker, Johnson, he plays for the team, not for
himself,'' said Nikola Bozic, 18. ``Nailon, he can play better than
this, you can tell. He can score.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very stylish players,'' said Dragan Kopribic, 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad the Americans are here,'' said Zoran Jevremcebic,
19. ``We have nothing against players. Sports has nothing to do
with politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Johnson stepped out of the dressing room. ``It was
fun,'' he said. ``Just a basketball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladmir Momcholeich, 15, approached him. ``Can I have your
autograph?'' he asked. As Johnson scribbled his name, Momcholeich
said, ``I like your game.''
</P>
<P>
   The games went on. A Greek team blew out Milano by 20 points in
the second game. In Milano's final game, they beat another Yugoslav
team and finished fifth in the six-team tournament. Nailon turned
into one of the top players, scoring more than 20 points in each of
the last two games. Johnson hurt his ankle in the second game, and
sat out the final contest.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, the games became just games. And
Belgrade became less fearsome.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon, the team ate lunch at the downtown American
Sports Cafe and then walked around the city. Nailon took out his
video camera and started taping some youngsters stretching at a
basketball camp. When the youngsters saw the players, they stood
up. Some saluted, some waved, some yelled ``Hello! Hello!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was neat,'' said Nailon, a South Bend, Ind., native who
hopes to play in the NBA next year. ``I just wanted to show
everybody back home that they have parks, too, and they play
basketball. Now, I'm not saying this is like home. I mean, the ice
cream is different, the chicken wings are not chicken wings. No
way. And they smoke in the gym. Can you believe that? They don't do
that back home. I walked into the gym, and said, `Hey, it's smoky
in here.' I was choking.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know, it's pretty wild you're actually in the town
that got bombed, sitting with people that went through the
bombing,'' Nailon said. ``I feel like I was part of history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RUINED-FARM-ART-BOS &LR;      09-01 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUINED-FARM-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WAY OF LIFE GOES UP IN SMOKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAFFREY, N.H. _ For the last three days, Peter Sawyer has
awakened at 2:45 a.m. to milk his cows.
</P>
<P>
   It takes him a minute to remember.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, with the smell of carbon still hanging in the air,
Sawyer remarked that he had 18 cows to dehorn, and then he
remembered they were dead. Ann Sawyer asked her daughter the time,
and her daughter responded gently, ``4:20. You'd be doing chores.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day for 31 years the Sawyers' lives have revolved around
their cows, and three days after 120 burned to death family members
wander around ``floppy-headed,'' as Peter puts it, stunned with
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time means nothing anymore,'' he said slowly, from a folding
chair set up by the barn's charred foundation.
</P>
<P>
   When Peter Sawyer was born, almost 62 years ago, there were 15
family dairy farms in Jaffrey. As of this week, there are none.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, when Fire Chief Jack White arrived at Sawyer Farm at
2:15 a.m., the barn was ``80 percent involved,'' the yard lit
nightmarishly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew all the cows would be in there,'' White said. ``I
didn't see Peter, but I had a feeling I knew where he was.''
</P>
<P>
   He found Sawyer in the blazing milkroom, the hayloft in danger
of crashing down on his head, trying to drive his cows from their
stalls out into the yard before the smoke knocked him out. White
had to scream at Sawyer to get him out, the way he would have to
scream at a long line of people that night who took too many risks
trying to save Sawyer Farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw things the other night that I just can't allow,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle with the panicked animals went on crazily, for
hours. Cows will run right back into a burning barn; the barn is
where they feel safe, White said. Several times he and his team
drove cows to safety and watched them race back into the fire. The
animals screamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget it,'' White said. ``You could hear them, and
you can see them, and it's not like seeing people, but if it
doesn't bother you, something's wrong with you.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Sawyer fire, Jaffrey lost the last remnant of a way of
life that has been draining away for years. Peter Sawyer can't
supply the date when he started working the 400-acre farm, but it
was sometime after his older brother vowed that he'd be ``damned if
he pulled teats for a living'' and sometime before he brought Ann
up to the mountain pasture to make sure she liked cows, a family
courtship ritual.
</P>
<P>
   It was he _ the second-youngest of six boys _ who carried on the
legacy of Josiah Sawyer, who settled over the hill in 1800, and
Alfred Sawyer, and Clifton Sawyer, and Jason Clifton Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   When Peter and his brothers were growing up there were 15 dairy
farms active in Jaffrey. But by the time he returned from college,
only five remained. In the years the Sawyers farmed here, the small
dairy farm became an increasingly tenuous proposition. During the
1980s and 1990s, the number of dairy farms in New Hampshire was
reduced by two-thirds. However, milk production remained steady _
those farmers who hung on typically doubled or tripled the size of
their herds, moving to high-volume, mechanized milking techniques.
</P>
<P>
   That line of reasoning never took hold with Peter Sawyer, who
has a lasting, vocal contempt for the modern farmer's longing for
``lifestyle.'' With the exception of three vacations _ ``less than
21 days, and all spent on his friend's dairy farm in New York
State,'' Ann Sawyer said _ the two have never left the farm.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:45 a.m. every morning, Peter milked 107 cows and spent the
hours before an 8 a.m. breakfast doing ``chores'' such as cleaning
and feeding the herd. The peak hours of the day went to outdoor
``work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmers have chores, and then they have work, and the chores
don't count,'' Sawyer explained.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first disaster to hit Sawyer Farm. In the
mid-1980s, one of the Sawyers' silos toppled over, crushing part of
the barn and mobilizing such a massive neighborhood relief effort
that the reconstructed silo has borne a huge ``THANK YOU'' painted
on it for the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   But although a collection can at Coll's Farm Stand had $20 bills
in it, this time the farm has sustained damage beyond the good will
of its neighbors. Lost in the fire was two-thirds of the Sawyers'
herd _ 120 cows worth up to $1,500 apiece who are now buried in one
of their fields. Although the family has insurance on the farm,
only half of the cows were covered.
</P>
<P>
   As the cleanup dragged into its third day, one of the barn cats
wandered around with her whiskers singed into corkscrews. Ann
Sawyer nursed two burned calves that stayed behind when the rest of
the survivors were shipped to a relative's farm.
</P>
<P>
   Friends called again and again, and she tried, not very
persuasively, to be cheerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' she told one, ``It's a whole lifetime, and it goes
in about 15 minutes, and you clean it up in a day and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the firefighters _ who went home to their own lives after
18 hours at the scene _ have had trouble getting this fire out of
their heads, White said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone found a cow in the bushes, a small one, and he said,
`Hey, there's a cow there,' and (Ann Sawyer) knew the cow's name,''
White said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was just a whole bunch of cows,'' he said. ``But she
knew their names. You realize this was a way of life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
