<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS INVADE GOP TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Monday, when I got to the building where First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and her husband were to speak to 500 of
Carl McCall's most intimate friends, a 25-foot-high Elvis Presley
balloon was bouncing in the breeze outside the place.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? Well, that's what they would like you to think, I'm
sure.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was the luncheon the state comptroller throws annually
at the New York State Fair. Diners are central New York business
and union leaders and local politicians of both parties. Generally,
Comptroller Carl McCall fills them with light food and heavy talk
of public money. This year, he was only the warm up act.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons had just flown in for a few days of what's billed
as vacation. It's actually a conspicuous bit of campaigning on the
first lady's part. She wants to be seen in a section of New York
where Democrats are badly outnumbered.
</P>
<P>
   The first family was occupying the lavish home of a real estate
developer on the east side of Skaneateles Lake. The decor of every
room is identical _ gigantic. The place is 8,200 square feet,
complete with pool, Jacuzzi and tennis courts. Skaneateles, by the
way, is an Iroquois word that translates to ``Land of Many
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite what New York Republican bosses like to believe is
serious hostility, especially upstate, toward the first lady as she
moves ever closer to a run for the U.S. Senate next year, the
Clintons received a conspicuously warm welcome from the politically
mixed crowd McCall had brought together. Mrs. Clinton was granted
hearty applause after a brief and eminently forgettable talk about
how much she likes New York. And the president brought down the
house with feigned complaints about arriving too late to eat and
recalling other fairs he has known and loved.
</P>
<P>
   As the Clintons were finishing up making nice with the people
McCall had brought together, I headed for Skaneateles. That's the
169-year-old village of 2,700 where the Clintons were staying. It's
a ritzy Syracuse suburb, the most dependably Republican community
in Onondaga County, a little gem of a town at the northern tip of a
glittering, 16-mile-long lake nestled between elegant, rolling,
tree-studded hills.
</P>
<P>
   All along the route the Clinton motorcade was to take from the
state fairgrounds to Skaneateles, hundreds of people sat in their
front yards with welcoming signs. One house with a ``For Sale by
Owner'' sign in the front yard sported a second sign that read,
``Will Hold Mortgage for First Family.''
</P>
<P>
   The center of Skaneateles, Genesee and Jordan Streets, was alive
with people hoping to catch a glimpse of the motorcade as it
flashed through the village. I parked and went looking for Doug
Clark and John Angyal. Clark is a white-bearded guy in a seafarer's
hat who operates a popular seafood joint on Jordan Street. Angyal
operates a flashy burger joint called Johnny Angel's a few doors
away. Angyal looks like a retired state trooper. That's because he
is a retired state trooper.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he wouldn't serve the Clintons if they entered Doug's
Fish Fry. Clark says he loves America and hates liars, and it's his
joint, and that's that.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Angyal says he's a devoted right-winger, but he'd
be delighted to serve the Clintons. The guy is president, after
all, even if he's not a president that Angyal thinks highly of.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Angel's has even named a sandwich after Hillary. It's
baloney and cheese on a hard roll _ mostly baloney. In just a few
weeks, Angyal has gone through 400 pounds of baloney. He's not sure
what that means for Mrs. Clinton's run for the Senate next year. He
knows what it means for the burger business, though.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
