<SLUG> BC-WOM-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TOUGH SITTING OUT THIS ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carolyn Jones-Young was drafted by the New York Liberty last
spring, but she hasn't seen a minute of action. So now the team is
in the playoffs, and Young is seeing them from her least favorite
position _ on TV at her new home in Attleboro, Mass. That's because
the former New England Blizzard guard tore her anterior cruciate
ligament in a game last November, after averaging 20 points per
game in five games.
</P>
<P>
   More bad luck came when the Blizzard's American Basketball
League folded just before Christmas. The players were left
league-less and jobless until the WNBA agreed to open its draft to
former ABL players.
</P>
<P>
   And it seemed to make no difference to the New York Liberty that
Young would join the team on the disabled list. The Liberty took a
look at her resume _ 1992 Olympic team, 1997 ABL scoring leader,
back-to-back SEC Player of the Year when at Auburn _ and in May
drafted the 5-foot-9-inch guard in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Now the team is in the WNBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty beat the Detroit Shock in the first round of the
playoffs, then beat the Charlotte Sting last Monday, and will now
face the Houston Comets, the two-time defending champion, in a
series starting Thursday (8 p.m., Lifetime TV).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching all the games and biting my nails,'' Young
said Tuesday, surrounded by unpacked boxes in her new home. She
just moved from Florida last week, because her husband, Charlton,
has begun work as an assistant coach for the men's basketball team
at Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   Young, 30, (still known as ``CJ,'' from her pre-married days at
the Blizzard) said she is doing rehab exercises for her knee three
days a week, but that recovery might take longer than expected
because a very significant extinuating circumstance _ she's
pregnant with her first child, due in November.
</P>
<P>
   But she said she'll be ready to go when the team starts training
next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got five, six months to whip myself into shape,'' she
said. ``I miss it so much.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Great expectation
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Framingham (Mass.) State soccer player Nicole Abbott will have
two new titles when the team reconvenes this fall. One is captain;
the other is mom. Abbott, 26, who gave birth to Leah last May,
obviously didn't let pregnancy get in the way of her playing.
</P>
<P>
   The native of Switzerland was Player of the Year for the
Massachusetts State College Athletic Conference (MASCAC), as she
scored 20 goals and had 13 assists. The junior was 29th in the
nation among NCAA Division 3 scoring leaders, averaging 2.79 points
a game.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, who said she knew she was pregnant right after the
season, said she got the OK from her doctor to keep playing. ``I
never had morning sickness, and I never worried when I fell,'' said
Abbott, who plays wing. ``The only problem was I had to go to the
bathroom a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Katy Delaney, the assistant women's basketball coach at
Stonehill, is taking a one-year sabbatical to _ what else? _ coach
basketball. Delaney will be the assistant coach with the Irish
women's national team, and will also be head coach for the
Waterford team in the Irish women's national league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
