u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-RAMON-BOS &LR;      09-01 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RAMON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON SET FOR TEST; PEDRO MERELY TESTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Enough of this nonsense, Pedro Martinez decided.
</P>
<P>
   He had sat and seethed as an ever-growing media gaggle
encroached on his locker space in the Red Sox clubhouse at Fenway
Park Tuesday. He had tried to shoo away the nuisances _ ``Out! Out!
Out!'' _ but the mass merely shifted as the questions persisted:
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you feel approaching your start Thursday?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever doubt you could come back?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it make a difference that you'll be returning in the heat
of a playoff race?''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Pedro lashed out on behalf of his older brother Ramon,
to whom all the questions had been addressed at the adjoining stall
and who was answering them with polite, subdued grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' Pedro snapped at the infidels. ``He's not saying
no more until after he pitches. He's been talking to you guys the
last four days. It's too much. Leave him alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Some teammates reclining on a nearby lounge were noticeably
enjoying the sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' said fellow pitcher Tim Wakefield indignantly, ``how
come you don't say anything when they're all over me?''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro's reply was brief and emphatic: ``I've got to take care of
my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As noble as Pedro's sense of sibling protection might be, the
27-year-old Cy Young cinch will be nothing more than a helpless and
nervous bystander Thurdsay when his 31-year-old brother makes his
Boston debut _ and first major league start since undergoing
extensive right rotator cuff surgery 14 months ago _ against the
Kansas City Royals at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   This will mark an official reunion for the brothers from Santo
Domingo in the Dominican Republic. But in a pitching sense, their
roles will be reversed. When Pedro broke in with the Dodgers in
1993, Ramon was entrenched as Los Angeles's ace, a two-time
All-Star and one-time 20-game winner who was on his way to racking
up 123 victories in 11 seasons. Now Pedro rules the American
League, if not all baseball, with his 19-4 record, and Ramon is the
test case. When he takes the mound, it will mark the first time in
the Sox' 99-year history that brothers have pitched for them.
</P>
<P>
   But general manager Dan Duquette was interested in more than a
historical footnote when he signed Ramon in March after the Dodgers
declined to exercise their option on his services for 1999.
Duquette was taking another of his famous fliers. He was banking _
reportedly to the tune of some $8 million guaranteed on a two-year
contract _ that he could salvage yet another discard. Now, after 10
rehabilitation starts, the results of this reclamation project will
be on display.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his brother, Ramon isn't making more of this trial run
than is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his attitude was as the experiment reaches its final,
make-or-break stage, Ramon said, ``Confident.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't expect any flashbacks to his major league debut in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm going to go through that again,'' he said.
``I just consider it another start. It's a long time since I've
been out there, but I just look at it as another game.''
</P>
<P>
   He claims he considered this venture inevitable, not
implausible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been very confident,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there were doubts, but they lasted less than a day. Having
first experienced pain in his shoulder in 1997, Ramon shrugged it
off while building a 7-3 record through May 1998. ``But I found it
was getting worse,'' he said, ``and that's when I shut it down.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgeons opened him up on June 30. They hoped a mere
arthroscopy would repair the tear they had discovered, ``but if
that didn't work, they'd have to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario occurred, an invasive procedure that
left Ramon with great discomfort and misgivings the morning after.
``That's when it got most negative,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he exorcised that thought process and proceeded vigorously
with rehab under new auspices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always doubts when someone has a major injury,''
said Red Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, who will hold his newest
starter to an 85-pitch limit. ``But knowing the character of the
man, I believed he could do it. We've created a spot for him in the
rotation. That's how much we think of him. But after this start,
we'll have to evaluate and see how he feels.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no mistaking how the Martinezes feel about each other.
Even by the standards of family, they are especially close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very confident with Pedro here,'' said Ramon, ``because
he trusts me. I know he's going to be 100 percent behind me. He's
going to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pedro's unsolicited censorship represented role reversal
of another sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon is truly the big brother,'' said Jason Varitek, who will
catch the elder Martinez for the first time Thursday and is an old
hand at handling Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon concurred: ``I'm taller than him. I'm older than him.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is far more cooperation that conflict in this
relationship. They would fight as youngsters, Ramon recalled, but
it never escalated to fisticuffs. ``Just arguments,'' he said.
``Brother things.''
</P>
<P>
   And it seemed that justice generally would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever had the reason would win,'' said Ramon. ``If he was
wrong, I won. If I was wrong, he won.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears their latest association is a win-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They trust each other reciprocally,'' said Varitek. ``They
bounce stuff off each other. Both have such a high knowledge of the
game that they help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ramon has spent most of the season touring various minor
league convalescence stops, the old order seems to assert itself
when the brothers get together.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ramon is here, he helps Pedro,'' said Kerrigan. ``As the
big brother, Pedro has a lot of respect for him. He's almost like a
father figure to Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then what in the world was Tuesday night's little tantrum all
about?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's just Pedro,'' assured Ramon. ``He's always like
that. It's nothing serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Then surely Pedro would be willing to talk about his big
brother, say, on the eve of his grand return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you, I'm not talking,'' Pedro snarled as he headed to
the sanctuary of the trainer's room. ``I pitched yesterday
(Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon merely shook his head knowingly. These kids today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
