<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7174 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-01 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEAR SAILING IN THE PACIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first consequences from the rash of injuries in the handicap
ranks were apparent when General Challenge, the only 3-year-old in
the race, won the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most prominent victims of the injuries incurred by
older horses this year were Victory Gallop and Real Quiet, who were
hurt while training for the Pacific Classic. If those two had
stayed healthy, General Challenge, a very good but not great
sophomore, would have been an afterthought. Instead, he dominated
the proceedings, winning by a comfortable 3 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that Bob Baffert, who is both
lucky and good, was the first trainer to benefit from the lack of
talent in what remains of the handicap ranks. He not only saddled
General Challenge to victory, but another one of his charges, River
Keen, a reformed claimer, finished second.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge, who was bred in California, won the Santa
Anita Derby but had a horrible trip in the Kentucky Derby and
finished 10th. He came back to win the Affirmed but was beaten by
Cat Thief in the Swaps. In the Pacific Classic, he was 5-2 ($7.20
to win), while Malek was 6-5. But Malek is old, tired, and has
chronic back problems. General Challenge simply stalked the pace
under David Flores, took over around the far turn and drew away.
Malek never fired, and finished fifth, beaten a dozen lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had confidence in him,'' said Flores. ``When we hit the
backside, I let him open up some. Then, at the three-eighths pole,
I let him roll. Turning for home, I didn't think anybody was going
to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory by General Challenge came as a boost to owners John
and Betty Mabee, who had just learned that their top filly,
Excellent Meeting, suffered a bone chip in her ankle that required
season-ending surgery. Excellent Meeting is by General Meeting, the
same sire as General Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mabees needed that,'' said Baffert. ``This horse has so
much talent. What you saw today is just the tip of the iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the injuries, which also claimed Silver Charm, Free
House, and Mazel Trick, only Behrens, the last prominent older
horse left standing, can stop the 3-year-olds from dominating the
big handicap races this fall. First up might be Lemon Drop Kid, who
won the $1 million Travers at Saratoga Saturday. Trainer Scotty
Schulhofer said that the $500,000 Woodward at Belmont Sept. 18 is a
possibility for his promising colt. The Woodward is expected to
draw Almutawkel, the Godolphin Stable horse who won the $5 million
Dubai World Cup March 28, and Running Stag, who took the Saratoga
Breeders' Cup on Sunday. Behrens reportedly is waiting for the $1
million Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Can Lemon Drop Kid win the Woodward? Well, his chances are a lot
better than they'd be if Silver Charm, Real Quiet, and Victory
Gallop were in the race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chilukki still perfect
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baffert turned loose Chilukki, his rapid 2-year-old filly, on
the Pacific Classic undercard, and she did not disappoint, winning
the $250,000 Del Mar Debutante to remain undefeated at 5 for 5.
However, for the first time, Chilukki, who was off at 1-5 ($2.40 to
win) did not blow her opposition away, winning by ``only'' a
length. It also marked the first time that Chilukki had run as far
as 7 furlongs, but Flores denied that she was getting tired. ``She
was playing around in the stretch,'' said Flores. ``I know she
looked like she was tired, but she wasn't. She just didn't have any
competition. When that other filly came to her, she went again.''
``That other filly'' was Spain, off at 16-1 and ridden by Gary
Stevens. Spain gave the chalk players an anxious moment when she
ran at Chilukki through the stretch. ``Going into the race, it
didn't look like there was any way we were going to beat
Chilukki,'' said Stevens. ``Spain's people said they'd just be
happy with a placing. Then, at the eighth-pole, I thought I was
going to win it.'' Said Baffert, ``I was scared to death when I saw
:22 1/5 (for a quarter) and :44 3/5 (for a half). They're
vulnerable at 7 furlongs. I hope she never has to go :44 3/5 again.
The race set up for a horse to come off the pace.'' Chilukki's
sire, Cherokee Run, was an outstanding racehorse, but he was a
miler at best. Questions about Chilukki's ability to handle a
distance of ground will remain until she proves otherwise . . . The
Pacific Classic was the final event in the 11-race NTRA Champions
series, which began when Malek won the Donn Handicap at Gulfstream
Jan. 30. Partly because of the injury problem, and partly because
the bonus system is convoluted and ill-concieved, the series went
out with a whimper. Behrens, the only one to win two events (the
Oaklawn Handicap and the MassCap at Suffolk), took the series with
46 points, but he did not earn any bonus money because a horse has
to run in the Pacific Classic to get a bonus. The Behrens camp
declined to ship their horse cross-country. By contrast, General
Challenge, who had 20 points, earned a $100,000 bonus in his series
debut. The farther along the series went, the less it seemed to
matter. Changes are needed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Ready' is willing
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More Than Ready, the crack 2-year-old colt who is unbeaten in
five starts, worked 5 furlongs in 1:03 4/5 over the Oklahoma
training track Sunday as he prepares for the Hopeful Stakes at
Saratoga Saturday. ``He had a solid work last week, this was more
of a maintenance work,'' said trainer Todd Pletcher. ``I've got the
horse to beat. I respect all the horses that go up against him,
though.'' A son of Southern Halo, More Than Ready captured the
Tremont at Belmont and the Sanford at The Spa, and could be the
real deal. He finishes strong, and there are fewer questions about
his ability to run long than there are concerning Chilukki . . .
Rudy Baez continues his rehabilitation at the Kessler Institute.
Baez suffered paralysis in a spill at Rockingham Park Aug. 4. Cards
and letters can be sent to: Kessler West, 1199 Pleasant Valley Way,
West Orange, N.J., 07052.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks and from
the Daily Racing Form was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
