<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GENZYME-GENETICS-ART-     09-01 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENZYME-GENETICS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENZYME'S RARE STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Most pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies strive to
develop drugs to treat patients who suffer from such widespread
diseases as cancer, diabetes, or arthritis. The goal is to reach as
many people as possible and create the kinds of treatments that can
generate steady profits for years.
</P>
<P>
   But Genzyme Corp. of Cambridge, Mass. is taking a different tack
_ and in the process is proving that drug companies do not have to
focus primarily on major illnesses to make big returns.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme's decision to concentrate on lesser-known illnesses
started in 1991 when it received government approval to market its
first drug, Ceredase, which treats Gaucher disease, a rare disorder
of the spleen and liver. The company expected that between 1,000 to
1,500 patients would use the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we had, at best, a $200-million-a-year drug,'' said
Genzyme president Henri Termeer. But sales have more than doubled,
hitting $411 million in 1998, while the number of patients
suffering from the disease has almost tripled this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of patients using the drug is still very small,
but a year's supply of Ceredase can run $170,000, nearly all of
which is covered by medical insurance programs.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Ceredase prompted Genzyme to begin work on six
more drugs to treat other rare genetic disorders. Termeer declined
to discuss the pricing of the drugs, two of which are expected to
gain US Food and Drug Administration approval next year.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, a Wall Street investment firm that tracks
drug and biotech companies, believes that the new drugs will be
priced between $50,000 and $100,000 a year per patient. It bases
those estimates on the amounts its says Genzyme will have to charge
to cover the high costs of developing drugs for rare diseases while
maintaining industry profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the unusually high cost of Ceredase and
expectations that the company's new medications will be equally
expensive are raising concerns about placing new burdens on a
health care system already under pressure to keep down costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No insurer will be bankrupted by an item that is
extraordinarily expensive and applies to very few people,'' said
Dr. Joseph Gerstein, medical director of Tufts Health Plan in
Waltham, Mass.. ``But as more rare diseases get major treatments
that are expensive, just who pays will become a societal issue.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Gerstein said, the federal government may have to
help subsidize the cost of such drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme came under attack for its high pricing from some members
of Congress when Ceredase was approved by the FDA. The company has
countered by arguing that while the drug is very expensive, it has
allowed many patients with Gaucher disease to lead normal lives,
eliminating expensive hospital stays.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company says, Ceredase has opened the door
to creating drugs for treating other genetic diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``These treatments for these rare diseases would not have been
developed were it not for our success with Gaucher disease,'' said
Dr. David P. Meeker, Genzyme's senior vice president of medical
affairs. Wall Street expects sales of the successor to Ceredase to
climb to $480 million this year, with nearly 2,700 patients using
the drug worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Some inherited diseases, including Gaucher, are caused by the
lack of a naturally occurring body enzyme, and can lead to
disfigurement and death. Children born with Pompe, for example, a
muscle degeneration disorder, often die within two years, because
no medical treatment is available. Genzyme is working with a
pharmaceutical company in the Netherlands that has developed a
replacement enzyme using rabbit's milk.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Genzyme acquired Peptimmune Inc., a small Cambridge
company that has developed a treatment for the estimated 5,000 to
10,000 people worldwide afflicted with an inherited disease called
Pemphigus Vulgaris, fatal blistering on gums and skin.
</P>
<P>
   One of the rarest diseases Genzyme is targeting is Fabry, which
affects about 2,000 men whose bodies cannot produce an enzyme
called alpha-galactosidase. Without it, fatty deposits build up in
blood vessel walls, causing intense pains in the hands and feet.
Left untreated, Fabry can lead to kidney failure and, in some
cases, heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Like his grandfather, Jack C. Johnson, a 36-year-old computer
programmer in Kansas City, Mo., has Fabry disease, and remembers
the worst pain attacks came as a teenager. He still gets periodic
pains in his legs and arms if he sweats from overexertion or stays
in the sun too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I generally stay indoors, which means I don't get to watch my
5- and 8-year-old sons practice baseball or do other outdoors
sports, so I all I can do is take them and drop them off _ I miss
that,'' said Johnson, who runs the Fabry Support and Information
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme has developed a replacement enzyme and is midway through
pivotal phase III clinical testing. It hopes to gain FDA approval
next year. Termeer would not discuss details of the clinical trials
because Genzyme is competing with Transkaryotic Therapies Inc. of
Cambridge, which has developed a comparable drug.
</P>
<P>
   Both will be seeking so-called Orphan Drug status, which would
give the company that obtains FDA approval first a seven-year
period of US market exclusivity.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a participant in Genzyme's phase II clinical trial,
said he felt better after taking the experimental drug twice a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel positive about the Genzyme drug, although I'm concerned
about how insurers will deal with this,'' he said. ``There is
always the possibility of not being able to get insurance or being
dropped by insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts believe that Genzyme is on the right track and that
its strategy of developing drugs for rare diseases will win the
support of most insurers, since the affected patient groups are
small.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the severity of the diseases, such expensive
treatments may be justified from a cost effectiveness standpoint,''
said Meg Malloy, senior biotech analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
