<HEADLINE>
STOCK DARLINGS DON'T DARE TO DISAPPOINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shoot first, ask questions later.
</P>
<P>
   That investment mentality has croaked hundreds of little public
companies with big ambitions but a whiff of disappointment. These
days, even much larger growth stocks are facing a similar threat in
a changing stock market.
</P>
<P>
   What's new? Investors who worry over the direction of interest
rates don't want to be around any company that might disappoint on
the market's other key priority: profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an earnings-driven market now,'' said Sly Marquardt,
research director at John Hancock Funds. ``Investors can't rely on
interest rate declines. They're looking for good earnings plays and
when they're disappointed they are very unforgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it hurts even when investors believe a company could
disappoint them.
</P>
<P>
   Two cases in point: State Street Corp. of Boston, the banking
company that makes its money as recordkeeper to the investment
world, and Staples Inc. of Westborough, Mass., the famed
office-supply retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have spectacular long-term track records but are
getting hammered in the stock market. Staples stock is down 31
percent since July 2. State Street shares are down by the same
percentage since July 6.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts of a possible slowdown ahead, not any actual business
screwups, are behind the slumps.
</P>
<P>
   Staples was the second most actively traded stock on Wall Street
Tuesday, trailing only Dell Computer Corp. The news: competitor
Office Depot Inc. had warned the day before that
slower-than-expected sales were going to translate into earnings
significantly below forecasts. Staples shares fell a further 3/16,
closing at 21 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Aram Rubinson of PaineWebber cut his recommendation on
Staples stock from ``buy'' to ``attractive'' Tuesday, reflecting a
broad stock market perception that Office Depot's problems could
spill into Staples stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all association, but some of it is founded,''
Rubinson said of the Staples stock slump. ``Staples on its own is
doing nothing but executing its business to a tee, but there are
some other dynamics that may eventually affect the industry as a
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The argument: Office Depot is pushing to open too many new
stores to revive sales in an industry that arguably suffers from
too much competition already.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means more new stores we don't need,'' said Rubinson.
``That's not good for anybody.'' He worries Office Depot's
expansion may hurt Staples's business beginning this fall, then
more forecfully next year.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a new argument, simply one fueled with an additional
jolt of reality Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, a report by analysts at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette fretted over much the same thing. They identified Office
Depot and OfficeMax Inc. as industry weak spots but also warned a
malaise could spread to Staples's stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that continued sluggish performance at the
other two chains will keep Staples's relative (stock
price-to-earnings) multiple from expanding,'' the DLJ report said.
</P>
<P>
   Staples executives insist their growth strategy has legs. They
point to expansion of services in existing stores, continued growth
of their small-business customer base, and the company's growing
franchise in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As for actual performance, they will tell you to check out
Staples's 8 percent same-store sales growth in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   State Street stock has been under pressure ever since the
company reported quarterly profits that rose, but not by as much as
expected, in mid-July. The second-quarter profits, up 14 percent,
prompted a notable stock-rating reduction by PaineWebber analyst
Ruchi Madan and sent State Street shares tumbling that day.
</P>
<P>
   The decline, which seemed to level off through August, resumed
last week and has trimmed more than $11 per share from State
Street's stock in just over a week. The stock finished at 59 7/8
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling it may not be an aberration and we may have
soft numbers in the third and fourth quarters,'' said analyst
Gerard Cassidy of Tucker Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   State Street stock was hurt several different ways by interest
rate concerns. Besides the usual impact on fast-growth stocks, rate
worries hit State Street because a weaker market would hurt its
investment management clientele.
</P>
<P>
   ``In good times when markets are roaring, they have the benefit.
Now it's vice versa,'' said Cassidy.
</P>
<P>
   State Street executives insist the impact of a stock market
decline on its business is usually overestimated. They said an
internal review conducted in 1997 suggested a 10 percent decline in
stock market values would depress State Street's revenues by about
2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time there's any bad news around a growth stock, people
take that information and magnify it many times over,'' said Ron
O'Kelley, State Street's chief financial officer. ``The fundamental
factors for our growth are still there and we continue to execute
well.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Kelley was in New York Tuesday visiting with institutional
investors who own State Street stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are asking us what's changed,'' he said.
``Frankly, we have a lot of diffculty telling them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. preparing to become a former
Gillette Co. shareholder? Gillette has filed registration documents
for KKR's 51.3 million shares, a process that will make it eligible
for sale without further regulatory action. KKR, which acquired the
stock when Duracell International was sold to Gillette in 1997, is
said to have no interest in selling at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
