<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BIOTECH-INVEST-ART-BO     09-01 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-INVEST-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH TRANSFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once not so long ago, before the Internet created a flood of
investments in high-tech companies, another sector was all the
rage.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1991, and young biotechnology firms were attracting
millions from venture capitalists who rushed to back the startups,
betting that the therapeutic drugs they were developing would one
day generate huge profits.
</P>
<P>
   But many companies, founded on one or two research ideas, were
crippled after their products failed to win government approvals.
The boom became a bust.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly a decade later, the biotech industry, after a period
of intense and often painful consolidation, is slowly making a
comeback on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices of established firms like Biogen have nearly
doubled since January. And shares in younger firms with promising
products, including LeukoSite Inc. and Cubist Pharmaceuticals Inc.,
have soared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks in the top-tier biotech companies are red hot, because
at the end of the day, investors are beginning to see pipelines of
promising new health care products that are safe, will improve
people lives, and make a profit,'' said Richard A. van den Broek,
senior biotechnology analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical giants, which are under pressure to create
breakthrough drugs rather than new versions of old therapies, are
acquiring biotech firms or striking development and distribution
deals with them. That strategy has also pushed up biotech stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Johnson &AMP; Johnson agreed to pay $4.9 billion for
Centocor Inc., the maker of heart drug ReoPro. In June, Alza Corp.,
the largest maker of sustained-release drugs, fetched a whopping
$7.3 billion from Abbott Laboratories. In May, Warner-Lambert paid
$1.9 billion for Agouron Pharmaceuticals Inc., a maker of the AIDS
drug Viracept.
</P>
<P>
   ``These and other recent investments by pharmaceutical companies
seemed to be triggers for investors figuring that if drug companies
think there is value here, than we should take a look and rotate
money into the biotech sector,'' said David K. Stone, managing
director of Liberty Tree Advisors LLC of Acton, Mass., a biotech
consulting firm, who expects the biotech rally to contine for at
least six month to a year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the new interest in biotech companies is not expected to
come close to 1991 levels. In the first half of this year, a total
of $58.5 million was invested in 13 New England biotech companies _
the second lowest amount in five years, according to The Boston
Globe/Pricewaterhouse Coopers Money Tree survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 1991, I am not sure whether the venture capital
community should be ashamed or proud for having created so many
companies, most of which did not do well,'' said Jean-Francois
Formela, general partner at Atlas Ventures of Boston. ``We still
see opportunities for new biotech companies, but investing in the
Internet is more appealing because it requires far less money and
there is strong investor interest on Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least Wall Street has stopped ignoring biotech. In recent
years, many investors have avoided the industry altogether because
of the inherent risk in determining which firms would be successful
in bringing new drugs to market.
</P>
<P>
   Often, drugs that showed promise in animal testing either failed
or proved no better than existing drugs in pivotal clinical trials
that involved patients across the country. One clear sign of the
perilous nature of biotech is that of the 350 publicly traded
biotech companies, only 20 are profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many Internet companies don't make any money either.
Indeed, the Internet investment boom is similar to the biotech
frenzy of 1991: lots of ``me-too'' companies with no signs of
profitability rushing to Wall Street to cash in on the the on-line
mystique that has created overnight sensations like Amzaon.com, the
Internet bookseller.
</P>
<P>
   But biotech remains a riskier investment than the Internet,
since most companies need six to 10 years to develop and thoroughly
test therapeutic drugs before seeking FDA approval, a process that
can cost hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was acquired by American Home Products Corp.,
Cambridge-based Genetics Institute Inc. reportedly spent $200
million during the 10 years it took to market its first
FDA-approved product, a genetically engineered drug used to replace
the missing blood clotting element for men with hemophilia.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-based companies, by contrast, face few government
restrictions, a product cycle as short as six months, and a smaller
cash requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the failure of many biotech firms has led to an
industry-wide consoldiation.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen Massachusetts biotech companies have
disappeared over the last five years. Some, including Alpha-Beta
Technology Inc. and Ergo Science Corp., closed after their only
products failed to win FDA approval. Others, such as OraVax Inc.,
simply ran out of money after their first products failed and were
acquired for their promising technology or for other drugs under
development.
</P>
<P>
   In August one of the biggest biotech failures, ImmuLogic
Pharmaceutical Corp., a 12-year-old developer of allergy vaccines,
was dissolved. Stockholders divided $40 million in remaining cash,
each receiving $1.94 per share _ a fraction of the more than $23 a
share the company traded at 7 1/2 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation has left investors able to focus on the
healthy survivors, mature and well-managed companies, including
industry leaders Amgen, Genentech, Genzyme, Biogen, Immunex, and
Cephalon, all with product pipelines and profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past six months, we've seen a renewed focus by Wall
Street on biotech and how it fits in with the pharmaceutical
industry,'' said Henri Termeer, president of Cambridge-based
Genzyme Corp., which hit a 52-week high of 62 1/16 last Tuesday,
one day after Biogen reached an all-time high of 80 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, investors are running up the prices of smaller
companies that are poised to introduce drugs or to be acquired.
Last week, shares of Vertex Pharmaceuticals Inc., which developed
Agenerase, an AIDS drug, climbed 30 percent in one day to nearly
33, amid speculation that it might be acquired. The Cambridge
company's extensive pipeline of promising drugs, along with
financial deals with major pharmaceutical companies, has made it
one of the most cash-rich biotech firms in New England.
</P>
<P>
   For smaller companies, such as Cubist Pharmaceuticals and
LeukoSite, investor interest is a recent phenomenon. Both have
promising products headed for FDA review, and extensive agreements
with major pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors and management are trying to focus biotech companies
on delivering products and revenue, not just sexy technology,''
said Scott M. Rocklage, Cubist president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Cubist shares have nearly tripled since January, a result of its
research collaboration with Merck &AMP; Co., Novartis Pharma AG, and
Bristol-Myers Squibb Co., to develop drugs to treat bacterial and
fungal infections, which affect over 30 million Americans and are
the third leading cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Cubist is also in the final stage of testing Daptomycin, its
internally developed antibiotic for use against bacteria that is
resistant to the strongest available drugs. Cubist developed
Daptomycin in response to the deaths of four children in Minnesota
and North Dakota from a drug-resistant strain of the staphylococcus
aureus germ.
</P>
<P>
   LeukoSite has signed a $30 million agreement with German drug
distributor Schering AG to market its drug Campath, which treats
patients with chronic lymphocytic leukemia, the most prevalent form
of adult leukemia, which affects about 120,000 patients in the
United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Campath, which the FDA is expected to review next year, is part
of a series of therapeutics LeukoSite is developing. Part of its
drug pipeline comes from a pair of Cambridge biotech companies _
ProScript Inc. and CytoMed Inc. _ that LeukoSite acquired earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seem to like the acquisition strategy: LeukoSite
shares have doubled this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``LeukoSite would not have made it to the radar screen of most
investors three years ago,'' said van den Broek of Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist. ``But it does now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
