<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLUG-POWER-IPO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL CELL COMPANY PLANS PUBLIC STOCK OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLAIRE HUGHES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATHAM, N.Y. _ Plug Power, a developer of an alternative energy
source, has decided to fuel its next stage of development with the
sale of stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The Latham-based start-up company has asked the Securities and
Exchange Commission for permission to sell as much as $117.3
million in stock. The company intends to trade on the Nasdaq
exchange under the symbol ``PLUG.''
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the sale will used in development of fuel cells
that use hydrogen to make electricity in a process that promises to
be cleaner and safer than current energy sources. Fuel cells have
generated interest as the country undergoes deregulation of its
electricity industry, opening up markets for nonutility companies
trying to deliver power to homes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it remains to be seen how consumers will ultimately
respond to fuel cells, said Peter Tertzakian, senior energy analyst
for Canadian investment banking firm Goepel McDermid.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to drive a stock like Plug Power? Deregulation,
technology change and then on top of that, there has to be customer
acceptance of a new way of generating power in your house,''
Tertzakian said.
</P>
<P>
   Two-year-old Plug Power plans to have a dishwasher-size,
$3,000-$5,000 fuel cell unit for use in homes on the market by
2001. Plug Power officials have said the worldwide fuel cell market
is expected to grow from $500 million a year in 2001 to $3 billion
in the span of a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power's preliminary filing with the SEC does not state how
many shares it wants to sell or the expected price range per share.
That information is expected to be included in a later filing.
Company President Gary Mittleman declined comment on the stock
offering, citing securities regulations that silence company
officers during a so-called ``quiet period'' before a stock
offering hits the street.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Plug Power stock has been available only through
private offerings, not to the general public. In addition to the
$117.3 million the company could raise through the offering, it
will get another $88.9 million boost from current stockholders who
have agreed to exercise various purchase agreements for company
stock at set prices, prior to the public offering. Those
stockholders include the companies that founded Plug Power _
Colonie-based Mechanical Technology Inc. and Edison Development
Corp., an affiliate of the Michigan utility Detroit Edison. Edison
Development owns 38.2 percent of Plug Power, and MTI owns 37.8
percent. Their stakes are bound to be diluted after more investors
purchase shares in the company.
</P>
<P>
   The third largest shareholder of Plug Power is now the General
Electric Co., with a 14.5 percent stake. Plug Power and
Schenectady-based GE Power Systems have formed a joint venture, GE
Fuel Cell Systems, to market the company's fuel cells. GE Power
Systems owns 75 percent of the company, and Plug Power owns 25
percent. GE Power Systems President Robert Nardelli has agreed to
join Plug Power's board of directors after the stock offering is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its SEC filing, the company notes some potential risks for
investors. Among them are lack of a product until 2001, anticipated
losses through 2003, dependence on GE Fuel Cell Systems for
marketing, intense competition and an inability to predict the
actual market for fuel cells.
</P>
<P>
   As a development-stage company with no product yet on the
market, Plug Power has lost $30.3 million since its startup in June
1997. Still, Tertzakian said, investors have shown interest in fuel
cells, at least in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that stock in Ballard Power Systems of Vancouver,
British Columbia, a Plug Power competitor that offered stock to the
public several years ago, is now trading at $30.31 (U.S.) per
share.
</P>
<P>
   The price reflects a slight decline in recent months, due to a
downward trend among technology stocks, but overall Ballard's stock
has done well for shareholders, Tertzakian said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of momentum behind fuel cells, and you'll be
seeing more and more of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power's potential has already buoyed the stock price of
MTI, even though MTI has taken hits on its earnings due to the
investment. MTI's stock was trading for under $2 a share before
launching the Plug Power venture in June 1997; Monday, its stock
closed at $29.75 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. is the lead underwriter for Plug Power's
offering. Other underwriters are Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co., and FAC/Equities, a division of First Albany Corp.
FAC/Equities owns 34 percent of MTI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
