<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIN'S WINNING DISCS; AGAINST SPECIESISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The September Spin offers up an early entry in what will soon be
a mad glut of best-of lists _ best of the year, best of the decade,
best of the century, best of the millennium. Sure, these honor
rolls are subjective, incendiary little beasts, but they do have a
valuable purpose in our age of too much information: They give a
sense of order to the increasingly chaotic world of entertainment,
to the zillions of albums, music genres, Hollywood and indie films,
TV shows, Internet sites, and celebrity ``moments'' that just keep
rolling on by.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine presents us with the 90 greatest albums of the
'90s, which is either an honest attempt to map out the decade or
just another excuse to put Kurt Cobain on the cover and pull out
the voice-of-a-generation lingo. Naturally, ``Nevermind'' tops the
pile, with Public Enemy's ``Fear of a Black Planet'' at No. 2, PJ
Harvey's ``To Bring You My Love'' at No. 3, and Beck's ``Odelay''
at No. 4. It does seem a little misguided to rate albums as the
greatest without allowing time to pass, for time is the greatest
test. But in the meantime, what's your everyday average
Zeitgeist-chasing magazine to do?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harper's asked five poets to bring a poem to dinner at the
Algonquin Hotel in New York. A transcipt of the conversation and
the poems is featured in the September issue, in a rich piece
called ``How to Peel a Poem.'' For offhand philosophies and
profound asides, you can't do better than listening to poets talk
about the minuscule details of poems, especially this clever crew _
Heather McHugh, Donald Hall, Paul Muldoon, Cynthia Huntington, and
Charles Simic, who says he chose a plain poem, ``the kind of poem
cats and dogs could understand.'' There's lots of celebration of
what Hall calls the ``mouth-joy'' of poetry, as well as plenty of
terrific, specific explication of the five poets' choices _
``During Wind and Rain'' by Thomas Hardy, ``The Taxis'' by Louis
McNeice, ``Music'' by Frank O'Hara, ``Traveling Through the Dark''
by William Stafford, and ``The Lake Isle'' by Ezra Pound. The most
interesting analysis may be of the O'Hara poem, during which Simic
notes, ``All lyric poems are narcissistic. They are the earliest
form of personal ad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Readings section of Harper's features a poetry-minded
transcipt, too, this one from a July 1 broadcast of ``The
Connection,'' our own Christopher Lydon's radio talk show. Callers
were invited to read their haikus on the air and process them with
poet Robert Hass, and the Harper's snippet follows Hass's
interpretation of this image: ``Terrible lizard made of tiny
plastic parts. He is broken. Drats.'' An homage to ``Jurassic
Park,'' perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't heard about Peter Singer, The New Yorker for
Sept. 6 profiles the controversial Australian ethicist who is
joining the faculty of Princeton University this month. Singer
believes that our ethics about the sacredness of human life in
regard to euthanasia and infanticide is outdated, and that our
common view of animal rights is ``speciesist.'' He believes, in the
words of writer Michael Specter, ``that a human's life is not
necessaily more sacred than a dog's, and that it might be more
compassionate to carry out medical experiments on hopelessly
disabled, unconscious orphans than on perfectly healthy rats. . . .
When Singer says that you are more likely to do moral harm by
killing a healthy cow than by killing a severely handicapped
infant, he means that the cow is more likely to anticipate pain and
suffer from it than would the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Princeton is under attack by a number of different
factions for hiring Singer (the university has had to take
``elaborate measures to insure Singer's safety''), and picketing by
a group called Not Dead Yet is expected to resume with the fall
semester.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
