<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CHILL-BOS &LR;      09-01 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CHILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `CHILL FACTOR,' GOODING IS GOING FROM BAD TO WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
CHILL FACTOR 
Directed by: Hugh Johnson 
Screenplay by: Drew Gitlin and Mike Cheda 
Starring: Cuba Gooding Jr., Skeet Ulrich, Peter Firth, David
Paymer, Hudson Lieck, Kevin J. O'Connor, Daniel Hugh Kelly 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and language) 
Star rating ! 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is at least one thing to be said for ``Chill Factor,'' the
new so-called action thriller starring Cuba Gooding Jr. It's where
Gooding's recent string of bad script choices bottoms out. With
``Chill Factor,'' Gooding arrives at the coveted
nowhere-to-go-but-up mode. One can understand that he chose to do
the gorgeous-looking but dramatically pallid ``What Dreams May
Come'' to work with Robin Williams and followed that up with
another misfire, ``Instinct,'' to work alongside Anthony Hopkins.
But why he chose to do ``Chill Factor,'' where he stars opposite a
cannister of frozen toxic chemicals, is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick _ and in ``Chill Factor'' whatever isn't a gimmick
is a cliche _ is a lethal scientific six-pack, code-named Elvis,
presumably so the characters can make bad jokes about Elvis leaving
the building. It contains a super-defoliant that will shrivel
anything within a 500-mile radius if it heats up beyond 50 degrees.
It did once, in 1987, during a test on a remote island. The ensuing
carnage resulted in an army troop commander being jailed for 10
years and David Paymer's scientist in charge, the real culprit,
walking because the army needed him. At the end of the 10 years,
Peter Firth's just-released colonel is not filled with love for his
fellow man.
</P>
<P>
   He's focused and he means to get even not only with the
scientist, but with the country he feels betrayed him. So he and
his minions start chasing Elvis, which the scientist passes off to
his fishing buddy, Skeet Ulrich's short-order cook. He, in turn,
enlists the aid of Gooding's thief, who just happens to show up in
the neighborhood with a stolen but refrigerated ice cream truck
they need to keep Elvis cool until they can return it to the army.
What ensues is mostly chase stuff, as the angry colonel and his
ninja commandos chase the two guys in the ice cream truck through
some spectacular Utah topography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chill Factor'' would be easier to take if it was anything more
than a bunch of dumb and dumber chase stuff. Ulrich plays a
watered-down James Dean rebel, the kind of loner nobody
understands, especially the local cops, but who's loaded with
integrity all the same.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding plays the worst role I've ever seen him play in a movie.
His larcenous hero named Arlo spends most of his time driving the
truck and overreacting to the stuff Ulrich's character is cool
about.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he perpetuates a kind of black stereotype that
should have become history years ago, but which, to judge by
Gooding's character in this movie and LL Cool J's easily flustered
kitchen worker in ``Deep Blue Sea,'' is as hard to kill as any
cinematic shark.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding has nobody to blame but himself for this one. What can
he have seen in a role whose every other line consists of him
saying, ``Oh, (expletive deleted)!'' while the white guys have all
the fun blowing stuff up?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
