<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7187 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CELLULAR-TRANSCEPT-AR     09-01 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLULAR-TRANSCEPT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH HOPES OF DOING AWAY WITH CELL TOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Millions of Americans want to be able to make
wireless phone calls anytime, anywhere. But even more Americans
hate living near or even looking at cellular phone antennas.
</P>
<P>
   Taking on that paradox, a small company here called Transcept
Inc. thinks it could make $100 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Transcept, spun off from Lockheed Martin Co. in late July with a
$17 million infusion from a New York investment house, sells
systems that replace 100-foot cell towers with devices about the
size of a toolbox that hang off telephone and utility lines.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 or 12 of the boxes, connected to upgraded cable
television lines or fiber-optic cables, can replace a cell tower
that might cost $350,000 or more to install, but at a 20 to 30
percent lower cost both for installation and maintenance, according
to Transcept president Steven J. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a $100 million business five years out. We
are selling a revolutionary product,'' said Johnson, who thinks
doubling sales every year in that time is a realistic goal.
Privately held Transcept does not release revenue figures, but
industry analysts estimate current annual sales at less than $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated 70 million Americans using cell phones and
33,000 more signing up every day, wireless companies are under
intense pressure to fill coverage gaps and add service to meet
demand in heavily traveled areas. The extraordinary value attached
to cell towers was underlined last month when Boston-based American
Tower paid more than $380,000 apiece for 2,100 Vodafone AirTouch
PLC towers around the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout New England and elsewhere, a backlash against
unsightly cell towers _ and largely unproven but hard-to-quash
fears they are a health risk _ has led zoning authorities to
sharply tighten siting rules.
</P>
<P>
   Transcept's devices include a box of electronics and three
antennas about the size and shape of a '60s lava lamp, which can
serve wireless phones in a radius of about 1,800 to 3,500 feet.
Each unit connects by wire _ or in one version by microwave _ to a
base station that handles call connections and the handoff of calls
from one cell site to another to maximize reception.
</P>
<P>
   So far Transcept has sold its devices to Sprint PCS for a system
serving Greater San Diego and to WirelessNorth for systems in
Duluth, Minn., and Superior, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The company is doing field trials in a Midwestern city it
declines to identify, and is also developing a system by which one
base station would serve multiple roadside towers by microwave
links. That reduces the need for rain-tight sheds with
$200,000-plus of electronics at every tower site.
</P>
<P>
   Transcept's devices can hook into fiber-optic cables strung
along poles or laid underground, or they can be connected to cable
TV networks that have been upgraded to 750 megahertz service, such
as MediaOne systems with RoadRunner fast Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   But the 50-person firm, located near the Manchester airport, is
facing an uphill fight persuading traditionally tower-oriented
wireless companies to give its technology a shot.
</P>
<P>
   One key hurdle, Johnson acknowledges, is that unless the
wireless franchise owner is a cable TV or phone company that owns
its own wires, companies using the product need to strike a deal
with another company to carry part of their network. Wireless
companies commonly lease fiber connections, but are reluctant to
become overly dependent on third parties.
</P>
<P>
   In linking to cable or wireline companies, ``Not only is it a
different party, it's a different industry,'' said Transcept
marketing director Christopher F. Cole.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of opposition to erecting towers, wireless companies
increasingly are striking deals to hide their antennas inside
church steeples or atop water towers. But among wireless engineers,
erecting towers, rather than using Transcept's system, is ``a very
strong paradigm that we are up against,'' said Cole, not to mention
the the usual ``try-it-before-you-buy mentality'' that greets many
new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   All three Transcept installations to date have involved wireless
systems backed by cable TV owners willing to share typically about
1.5 percent of their transmission capacity (after lines were
upgraded) to cover cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anything at the moment going for us in New
England,'' Johnson said. ``That's unfortunate for us, because there
are certainly major opportunities here.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being an alternative to towers for new wireless
franchises, Transcept officials see their products being used to
fill in coverage gaps or to overlay an area already covered by
towers where calling demand is so heavy that subscribers' calls get
dropped or fail to go through.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless analyst Mark Zohar of Forrester Research in Cambridge,
who has studied Transcept, said: ``They're not going to take over
the world with this product, but their basic business model makes a
lot of sense as a niche market.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that many US cell networks are nearly built out, Zohar
said, ``The majority of their business will probably be coming from
outside the US, such as in Latin America. A lot of the (domestic)
carriers aren't, frankly speaking, very interested at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Plating, executive vice president and chief operating
officer with Bell Atlantic Mobile, said he was not specifically
familiar with Transcept's products, but said his company has
already made heavy use of ``microcells'' to fill in coverage in
tunnels, shopping malls, and airports.
</P>
<P>
   In tunnels, including those under Boston Harbor and the
Prudential Center, wireless companies have installed what is called
``leaky coax'' _ a coaxial cable that works like a garden soaker
hose to provide coverage over a very short range. Inside, companies
use miniature cells whose ceiling-mounted antennas look like smoke
detectors.
</P>
<P>
   Plating said he was not specifically familiar with Transcept's
products. As far as using dozens of small transmitters as a widely
applied alternative to towers, Plating said: ``It's going to take a
while to get the electronics into play, but if this would do it, we
would be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Transcept was formerly part of Lockheed Martin's Sanders
telecommunications unit. After concluding wireless telephony did
not fit with its predominantly defense business, Lockheed spun off
the unit as Transcept last month.
</P>
<P>
   New York technology investment firm Spencer Trask &AMP; Co. put up
$17 million for a majority ownership stake, while Lockheed
continues to own a minority share, Johnson said. In time the
company may consider going public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
