<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERFAITH GROUP ASSAILS `INFLAMMATORY' VIEW OF HOMOSEXUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of religious leaders that supports gays and lesbians has
accused James Dobson, president of the conservative Focus on the
Family, of disseminating ``false and inflammatory rhetoric'' about
homosexuals through his print ministry and worldwide broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   The National Religious Leadership Roundtable made the charges in
a letter delivered last week to the powerful evangelical Christian
ministry based in Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   An interfaith organization of about 40 people that formed last
year, the roundtable drafted the letter during a two-day conference
held in Colorado Springs. The group chose the city, which is home
to several conservative Christian organizations, because it wanted
to present a different view of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Homosexuality and the role of gays and lesbians in different
faiths has emerged as one of the most contentious issues on
America's religious landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The roundtable's letter states Focus on the Family's
``anti-homosexual campaign leads directly and indirectly to broken
families, to divided churches, and to sufferring and death to God's
lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgendered people.''
</P>
<P>
   The group sought a meeting with Dobson so he could ``hear our
case, and together begin a process of seeking truth about
homosexuality and homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobson was on vacation and unavailable for comment. But Amy
Tracy, a spokeswoman for Focus on the Family, said it was unlikely
he would meet with the group because the letter's authors ``have
bashed him all over'' in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say homosexuality is a sin . . . that's not Dr. Dobson _
that's God,'' Tracy told reporters. ``They should take it up with
God because the Bible is very clear that homosexuality is a sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Roundtable leaders said they would not try to persuade Dobson to
change his views on homosexuality, but simply wanted to start a
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we really want is to have a dialogue about this,'' said
the Rev. Nori Rost of Pikes Peak Metropolitan Community Church in
Colorado Springs. ``It's OK if they disagree. No one's asking them
to embrace gays and lesbians or advocate for same-sex marriages.
What we want to see stopped is the dangerous rhetoric that portrays
gays and lesbians as monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Paulk, who says he is a former homosexual and who works
on gay issues for Focus on the Family, challenged Rost's view,
saying the ministry's beliefs are neither incendiary nor false. The
ministry is just trying to counter what Paulk described as an
``aggressive homosexual agenda'' being promoted across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not assaulting the gay community,'' he said. ``We don't
have a campaign against anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Seeking to calm fears about possible Year 2000 computer
disasters, the American Bankers Association is distributing sample
sermons to ministers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers are trying to urge clergy to allay fears that Y2K
computer glitches will cripple the country's banking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to reach out to the religious community,'' said John
Hall, a spokesman for the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   So the group is distributing the four-page sermon to bankers
who, in turn, can give them to their ministers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go into the new millennium with hope, eagerness and
faith in this new century of promise,'' the sermon states. ``We
don't want to be crouched in our basements with candles, matches
and guns.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one minister said he has no plans on using the
sermon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're treading where angels fear to tread,'' the Rev. Paul
Goodland, an Episcopal priest in Arizona, told reporters. ``Faith
and trust in God is really where it belongs, not in banks.''
</P>
<P>
   --Raising fears of tourist gridlock, Israeli officials say it's
not likely that a second entrance and exit to the crowded Church of
the Holy Sepulcher can be built in time to accommodate the millions
of pilgrims expected to flood Jerusalem to mark the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   While the government wants a second exit for safety reasons, the
Christian denominations that control the church's interior have not
been able to agree on where that exit should be.
</P>
<P>
   Located in Jerusalem's Old City, the church is believed to cover
the sites of Jesus's crucifixion, burial, and resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   --Archbishop Demetrios, who was named this month to replace
Archbishop Spyridon as leader of the Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of
America, will be installed Sept. 18 at Holy Trinity Cathedral in
New York City. Spyridon was forced to resign following a two-year
campaign by dissidents who criticized what they described as
Spyridon's authoritarian management style.
</P>
<P>
   --Robert Waldron, who has taught English at Boston Latin School
for 30 years, has recently published two books: ``The Hound of
Heaven at My Heels'' and ``Poetry as Prayer: The Hound of Heaven.''
The first is a reconstruction in diary form of the life of Francis
Thompson, the Victorian poet famous for his poem, ``The Hound of
Heaven.'' The second book explores the relationship between poetry
and prayer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego Ribadeneira,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
