<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-GUIDES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF FINDING WHAT'S NEW IN PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The capital of France spawned styles from Gothic to
Cubism, but after World War II it ceded its preeminence in the
contemporary field to New York, and today there are a dozen cities
worldwide that have surpassed Paris in adventurous art. Not that
there isn't plenty of recent work woven into the fabric of this
art-rich city. Finding it, though, was a challenge until the
publication this year of ``France: Contemporary Art (plus)
Architecture Handbook'' (art(bullet)SITES, $19.95) by the San
Francisco-based curator and art historian Sidra Stich.
</P>
<P>
   Without Stich's book, I wouldn't have known that amid the more
conventionally somber sculpture in the Montparnasse Cemetery is
Niki de Saint-Phalle's irreverent tomb statue of a human-sized,
grinning cat, her tribute to a deceased, feline-loving friend. Or
that the blue-on-blue dining room beyond the bar in the Cafe
Richelieu in the Louvre is filled with new art, including
Jean-Pierre Raynaud's frieze of moody indigo photographs of the
stone sculptures of the great and the good on the museum facade.
You can see the real thing out the dining room window, a spooky
effect, especially given that Raynaud's close-up photos make these
cardinals, architects, and scientists look about to start
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris last week, I ran around the city with Stich's book in
hand, appreciating not only her impeccable directions to obscure
locations, but also her forthright opinions. She's got far more
expertise than your typical guidebook writer, and it shows. On the
subject of the Jeu de Paume, for instance, that long, skinny, 19th
century building just off the Place de la Concorde, originally home
to a ``real'' tennis court, Stich says it's gone downhill. When the
national collection of Impressionist paintings it housed until the
mid-1980s was transferred to the Musee d'Orsay, the Jeu de Paume
became a kunsthalle devoted to daring contemporary shows. But now,
Stich laments, ``the pulse has changed to a more conservative
selection and historic orientation.'' That was certainly true of
the Richard Meier show I saw there, drawings and models of the
white-on-white buildings the famous architect has done worldwide,
its centerpiece a vast model of the Getty Center in Los Angeles.
The model makes the Getty look even bigger than it actually is _
like an entire city.
</P>
<P>
   The French are big on national collections; they see a kind of
glory, patriotism, and pride in forming and housing them in
splendor, an attitude the American government doesn't share. The
stated goal of the National Museum of Modern Art in Paris's
Pompidou Center is typically ambitious: ``to show every art form
that has existed since the beginning of the 20th century in France
and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pompidou, Renzo Piano and Richard Rogers's controversial
``inside-out'' building with the color-coded pipes, tubes,
elevators, and walkways on the exterior, is closed for renovations
until New Year's Eve. What isn't closed, and is well worth a visit,
is the Atelier Brancusi next door. Sculptor Constantin Brancusi
bequeathed his Paris studio and its entire contents to the French
nation, on condition the four rooms be reconstituted just as they
were at his death, in 1957. They were re-created at a couple of
other sites before the Piano-designed building to house them opened
in 1997. It's essentially a glass-walled corridor through which you
see the studio, crammed with sensuous sculptures in marble, wood,
onyx, and polished bronze, soaring birds and saw-toothed totems. To
anyone accustomed to seeing Brancusis one by one, this dense,
forestlike installation comes as a shock. But period photos of the
studio confirm it's the way he wanted his work displayed. His tools
are there, too: pulleys, saws, drills, and sanders, hinting at the
physicality of his process. There's even the guitar he used when
jamming with his pal, composer Erik Satie.
</P>
<P>
   France is fond of single-artist museums, a relatively new
phenomenon in the United States. Paris boasts museums dedicated to
Picasso, Rodin, Delacroix, and others; the Atelier Brancusi is one
of the most idiosyncratic and satisfying, despite Stich's
justifiable complaint that Piano's glass walls sanitize the studio
and distance you from work you yearn to get close to.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Pompidou, Paris's City Museum of Modern Art covers the
20th century. The cavernous spaces of this rather gloomy 1930s
neoclassical pavilion can accommodate the most sprawling works,
including a magisterial version of Matisse's ``La Danse,'' and
Raoul Dufy's giant murals ``La Fee Electricite,'' commissioned by
the Paris Electric Co. for the 1937 International Exposition.
</P>
<P>
   The City Museum's contemporary programming is particularly bold.
Parisian-based Martine Aballea has created an entire hotel in the
galleries, on view through Sept. 19. The doors to some rooms open;
others are locked; all are furnished as sparsely as monks' cells,
and for some reason, the furniture is gilded. It all reads like a
set for a surreal French film.
</P>
<P>
   There's a mysterious, disconcerting emptiness about Aballea's
``Hotel Passager.'' Pipilotti Rist's installation ``Remake of the
Weekend,'' also in the City Museum through Sept. 19, is anything
but empty. It's the apartment of someone who can't throw anything
out, and although the owner isn't there, the place is brought alive
by video images flickering over kitchen cabinets, lampshades, and
sofas.
</P>
<P>
   The most exciting contemporary art I saw, though, was at the
Cartier Foundation for Contemporary Art in Montparnasse, which,
since 1994, has occupied a glass building designed by Jean Nouvel,
as radical in its way as the Pompidou Center. Transparent and
ambiguous, thanks to layers of glass panels that make it seem to
dematerialize, the building is home, through Nov. 14, to a big
millennial show, ``1 Real World.'' Its science fiction theme is
introduced by Rolf Fehlbaum's spectacular collection of toy robots
whizzing along conveyor belts. Continuing in this vein, the Antwerp
artist Panamarenko, a latter-day Leonardo, offers a fantasy flying
machine involving clusters of propellors rising from the shoulders
of a mannequin attired as a pioneer aviator.
</P>
<P>
   Zaire artist Bodys Isek Kingelez creates a utopian city in
``Project for Kinshasa in the Third Millennium,'' a brightly
colored, oddly shaped, exuberant series of buildings constructed of
cardboard and soda cans. And Boston-born, Los Angeles-based Chris
Burden presents a globe gone awry in ``Medusa's Head,'' a huge,
lumpy, suspended ball with railroad tracks and bridges
crisscrossing the surface, sometimes upside down, the disarray
looking like the result of a cataclysmic earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Paris hasn't been particularly aggressive or adventurous about
public art _ perhaps because the city already has more than its
fair share of monuments _ but one fine example that pays homage to
its stately surroundings is French artist Daniel Buren's ``Les Deux
Plateaux,'' in the column-ringed courtyard of the Palais-Royale.
Buren has added 460 more columns, all in his signature stripes,
black and white in this case. They're fragments, in all different
heights, some reaching underground and viewable through glass.
People walk among them, sit on them, play hopscotch over them.
They're like pieces of a giant board game, or remnants of some
ancient structure that predates the 17th century palace.
</P>
<P>
   I'd visited Notre Dame dozens of times, but, until latching onto
Stich's book, never realized that since 1962 there has been a
Holocaust memorial behind the cathedral. Georges-Henri Pingusson's
``Crypte de la Deportation,'' which commemorates the 200,000 French
Jews deported to Nazi camps, is a sunken, rugged stone prison whose
claustrophobic interior contains little locked cells and, behind
more bars, a long chamber with a coffin shape bearing the
inscription ``here rests an unknown deported.'' The coffin looks
about to slide down the narrow corridor toward a tiny light at the
end, a glimmer of hope. Outside, though, all is bleak. The
memorial, at the east end of the Ile de la Cite, culminates in a
lethal-looking, swordlike sculpture and an iron portal, with a view
of the waters of the Seine beyond. You sense this is where the
prisoners exited, never to return. Like Jerusalem's Yad Vashem or,
for that matter, Boston's Holocaust Memorial, the ``Crypte de la
Deportation'' abstracts an unspeakably horrible subject that
literal treatment might trivialize. It permits an emotional
response rather than dictating one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7205 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-PROVIDENCE-BOS &LR;      09-01 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PROVIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURPRISE FROM THE FARRELLY BROTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
OUTSIDE PROVIDENCE 
Directed by: Michael Corrente 
Screenplay by: Peter Farrelly, Corrente, Bobby Farrelly (based on
Peter Farrelly's novel) 
Starring: Shawn Hatosy, Amy Smart, Alec Baldwin, Jon Abrahams,
Tommy Bone, Jonathan Brandis, Jack Ferver, Adam Lavorgna, Jesse
Leach, Gabriel Mann, Kristen Shorten, Alex Toma, George Wendt 
Rated: R (pervasive teen drug use and strong language, including
sexual references) 
Star Rating: !!! 1/2 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although ``Outside Providence'' comes on the heels of ``Dumb and
Dumber'' and ``There's Something About Mary,'' it predates the
films that made Rhode Island's Farrelly brothers, Peter and Bobby,
their reputation as the kings of zany low-ball comedy. It in fact
stems from a semi-autobiographical coming-of-age novel Peter
Farrelly wrote, and while there's certainly no shortage of comedy
in its story of a working-class kid from Pawtucket packed off to a
tony Connecticut prep school to keep him out of trouble, it's a
sweet and ultimately touching film with more straightforward
humanity and realism than anything else we have seen so far with
the Farrelly name on it. It's a film of modest but solid and
heartfelt attainments.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is that it also bears the name of Michael
Corrente as director and co-screenwriter. Corrente not only has
made a reputation for affecting and handsomely crafted filmmaking
with ``Federal Hill'' and ``American Buffalo,'' but has shown that
he imaginatively moves beyond generic realism to a more
individualized and impassioned brand. If his films are red-blooded,
they're also full-hearted, which is another way of saying that
there's no dumbing down here, no succumbing to teen movie formula.
A tender, gritty honesty pervades ``Outside Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet while you could make a case for regarding it as the
anti-``American Pie,'' it's also cognizant of the fact that, like
real estate, which is driven by location, location, location, teen
comedies are driven by hormones, hormones, hormones. It's those
first surges of testosterone that get Shawn Hatosy's Tim Dunphy
into trouble. When they lead to show-offy drug use and a subsequent
collision with the back end of a police car, Tim's tough
blue-collar father packs him off to boarding school. Nothing much
is said about it, but it's obvious from their less-than-affluent
neighborhood and house, that some sacrifice is involved in sending
Tim there.
</P>
<P>
   And yet he regards it as a prison, with its school blazers and
its rules and class consciousness. Just as service comedies are
about the eternal war between enlisted men and brass, school films
are about the perpetual conflict between students and the adult
authority figures of the faculty and administration. Certainly,
this is played for all it's worth when Tim finds a few ways to
successfully cross the vicious cold fish (Tim Crowe) in charge of
discipline. But the pleasures of ``Outside Providence'' come from
the ways it deviates from genre cliche and supplies freshness and
surprises. It's much closer to a European film in sensibility than
to one of Hollywood's factory products.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Tim isn't a miserable misfit at all, but
integrates quite harmoniously and even serves as a role model for
the obligatory nerd roommate (a convincing Jack Ferver). Even
better, Tim is forced to admit to himself that there's no real
snobbery to contend with, and that the real problem is his own
reverse snobbery, a product of defensiveness. His glorying in this
unexpected egalitarianism peaks when he finds that the patrician
girl who caught his eye (a freshly ingratiating Amy Smart) in fact
reciprocates his feelings. ``Outside Providence'' doesn't tell a
notably original story, but it reinvents a familiar one in very
engaging ways.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a triumph of pitfalls avoided. There's never anything
maudlin about Tim's disabled brother, played by Tommy Bone, nor is
there any attempt to wring pathos from the fact that the boys'
mother is dead. Hatosy fills the role with unforced conviction and
Alec Baldwin is terrific as the boys' clenched and in many ways
narrow but ultimately tender father. Never once does he slip into
an Archie Bunker mode, even though a lesser actor might have;
that's how dangerously close the role veers toward it. The film's
most moving moment doesn't involve any kind of big but overdrawn
emotional scene, but unfolds simply, when the father shows his son
how to knot a tie. Corrente delivers the goods in this film that
shows a hitherto unrevealed side of the Farrelly brothers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
