<HEADER>
A7216 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-BEST-BUY-MUSIC-HNS &LR;      09-01 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEST-BUY-MUSIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST BUY HELPING MUSIC NEWCOMERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG HASSELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When Mary Cutrufello was still earning her paycheck
playing guitar in Jimmy Dale Gilmore's band, a fan approached her
after a show in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   He'd heard her solo set and was impressed. It just so happened
this guy worked at the Minneapolis-based retail giant Best Buy. He
was cooking up a marketing program to promote young artists in
danger of being overlooked by the music industry's hit machine.
</P>
<P>
   Record companies are notorious for spending all their
advertising bucks to boost established stars like Garth Brooks.
Most newcomers have little chance of getting serious promotional
support. But Best Buy's Tom Overby &UR;  &LR; wanted to change that with an
innovative program called Find 'Em First.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even have a record deal at that time, but I
appreciated his enthusiasm,'' said Cutrufello, the Yale-educated
guitar slinger who moved to Houston to hone her craft in Texas
honky-tonks.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, Cutrufello released her first CD, ``When the
Night is Through.'' Overby sent her an e-mail asking if she'd like
to be involved in his marketing brainchild. A week after she
endorsed the plan, Best Buy sent a film crew to a Houston nightclub
and filmed a Cutrufello show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ESTABLISHING RECOGNITION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The commercial cut in Houston premiered on the MTV Video Music
Awards and established a regular presence on VH-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Find 'Em First commercial has given me tremendous
national exposure,'' Cutrufello said. ``People immediately began
coming up to me in public in places I'd never even been to before
and saying, `Hey, weren't you in that Best Buy commercial?' When
you're a young artist just trying to get people to match a name
with a face with a sound, you can't imagine how far that sort of
thing goes.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to TV advertising, Find 'Em First has promoted
musicians' careers with promotional billboards, advertising
circulars and big in-store displays. The Best Buy Web site
(www.bestbuy.com) gives updates on Find 'Em First artists,
including biographies, tour dates and free audio downloads. Total
budget for the effort is estimated to be $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Texas artists have gotten a big boost from Best
Buy. At one point this past year, one out of four CDs by Austin,
Texas-based Kelly Willis were sold at Best Buy. The retailer
estimates sales of David Garza's ``This Euphoria'' spiked 1,500
percent after he was featured in Find 'Em First. Just don't asked
Garza to verify the math.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea. I write rock 'n' roll songs,'' he quipped.
``But I can tell you it's a big help. It puts your face on TV until
people get sick of seeing it. When they get sick of seeing it, they
buy the CD. That's how it works in America.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a coincidence, Overby said, but there have been a
disproportionately large number of Texans featured on Find 'Em
First.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has always had a lot of great artists, but they don't
get played because they don't fit a demographic or a particular
radio format,'' Overby said. ``They are too rock, or too blues or
too country for the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been a problem for decades, nagging at Texas twangers as
prominent as Willie Nelson, who had to battle Nashville to release
his landmark concept album, ``Red Headed Stranger.'' He had to
battle the record company again when he wanted to release a record
of old standards. The brilliant ``Stardust'' proved him right by
setting sales records.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEW ARTISTS NEED A PUSH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story is so familiar and has been relived by so many others
_ especially country artists playing in the traditional vein of Bob
Wills, Jimmie Rodgers or Lefty Frizzell _ that it's news when they
aren't ignored by the mainstream recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new artists are the lifeblood of the industry,'' Overby
said. ``They need an extra push. We do it because we are passionate
about music ... We want to send a message to new artists that Best
Buy is your friend.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the retailer hopes to convince the public that
Best Buy is the best place to find great music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings people into the store,'' he said. ``Our customers
have responded well to this and told us they love it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubting that Find 'Em First has the grateful
support of the musicians who are enjoying their turn in the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a pretty amazing thing they are doing. They
aren't asking the record companies to pitch in,'' said Willis,
whose latest record is appropriately titled ``What I Deserve.''
``This is a huge company that could keep its money, but it wants to
help. It is so surprising you ask yourself, `What have I done to
deserve this?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
