<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7227 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-CASUAL-APPETIZERS-2TA     09-01 2032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASUAL-APPETIZERS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUNCHIES THAT LOOK, TASTE FABULOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
HAS ART  
By NATALIE HAUGHTON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; When it's time to gather friends for some hanging
out, keep the festivities casual _ and razzle-dazzle guests with
tasty nibbles and cool libations galore. Nothing formal or fancy,
just some fabulous easy appetizers and hors d'oeuvres to tease the
taste buds, stave off hunger _ and even suffice as a light and
informal meal by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of little bites to spark the appetite and greet
party guests, from endless combinations of dips and chips to more
chic fare such as cheese and salmon balls, appetizer cheesecake,
sesame chicken strips, tomato and olive tapenade, brie torte, corn
and shrimp cakes, stuffed mushrooms, Cajun-seasoned pecans, roasted
red pepper spread, hot crab and artichoke spread, tapenade and
more.
</P>
<P>
   We've culled a few tried-and-true favorites, along with
interesting in-vogue ideas that span the globe from some of the
latest cookbooks. Use the ideas included as guidelines and add your
own special creative touches and flavors. If you have the time and
inclination, explore ethnic markets for interesting and different
chips and crackers, or novelties to serve as conversation pieces.
Something like the Taiwanese chips embedded with black sesame
seeds, sampled recently at a Chinese restaurant, would make a tasty
dip accompaniment (available at the 99 Ranch Market on Sepulveda
Boulevard in Van Nuys).
</P>
<P>
   ``Appetizers that taste as good as they look don't have to be
complicated,'' writes Paula Hamilton in ``The 5 in 10 Appetizer
Cookbook.'' In her cookbook, ``A Little Something,'' Susan Epstein
writes that we can indulge in versatile appetizers or nibbles
midmorning or afternoon, at formal or informal cocktail parties,
poolside, in the park, at tea time or early or late in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Design and gear your appetizer menu to suit the hour of the
party, the appetites of the guests (are they hearty eaters, or do
they prefer lighter fare?), the number expected and your budget.
``Serve gourmet food to gourmets and updated traditional tidbits to
the less adventurous,'' advises Epstein, who was once asked by a
guest _ when she set out a spread of gourmet tidbits _ if she had
any onion soup dip. ``Plan an eating adventure, but have one or two
`life jackets' on hand just in case.''
</P>
<P>
   Strive for balance and variety as well as both cold and hot
appetizers with varied colors, textures and flavors. Consider your
schedule when selecting an assortment of recipes. If you have
limited time to spend, pick the fastest recipes you can find _ and
make them in between appointments or whatever. Or let convenience
or already-prepared foods assist you. Whatever you decide, be sure
you have plenty of eats. Get organized and assemble as many of the
appetizers in advance as possible so you can enjoy your own party.
Fortunately, most appetizers can be prepared in advance and kept
refrigerated a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   If hearty fare is in order, offer items like shelled and
deveined shrimp, thin pizza slices, meatballs, cut-up chicken
pieces or other more substantial finger foods that are easy to eat.
Crab meat on a cucumber or cracker, cut-up bites of cooked fillet
of beef with a mustard dipping sauce, mushrooms filled with pesto
or rolled-up tortilla slices filled with meat, cream cheese and
veggies are other ideas. Even bruschetta on toasted mini cocktail
breads or a platter of shrimp nachos with pineapple salsa are good
options.
</P>
<P>
   Remember _ you don't have to make everything yourself from
scratch. Supermarkets, delis and Trader Joe's offer busy hosts and
hostesses such ready-to-use items as peeled and cut-up fresh fruits
and vegetables, baked pizzas, egg rolls, hummus, cheeses, sliced
salamis, interesting breads and mini rolls, savory pates, cooked
chicken, ribs, smoked or cooked salmon, dips, crackers, chips,
pretzels and much more. Establishments like Smart &AMP; Final and
Costco carry items like jalapeno poppers, mini tacos, mini
burritos, mini quesadillas, mini sausage links, teriyaki skewers,
stuffed eggs, mini quiches, prepared tuna salad, prepared crab
filling, popcorn shrimp, chicken nuggets, mozzarella marinara
sticks, fresh refrigerated salsas, guacamole, baby pizzas, nuts _
and even some sweet things like baby cream puffs and baby eclairs.
</P>
<P>
   If your event is a last-minute affair, pick up platters of
assorted sushi along with shrimp, assorted meats and cheeses,
vegetables, assorted wraps and roll-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you can whip up creations with mostly premade items _ like
turning a wheel of plain brie into a torte with store-bought pesto
and pine nuts _ or wrapping up a dip or spread in a tortilla with
thin sliced sandwich meats and some lettuce leaves and roasted red
peppers. Antipasto platters with roasted peppers, an assortment of
imported green and black olives, marinated artichoke hearts, cherry
tomatoes, salami cornucopias filled with flavored cream cheeses,
caponata and stuffed mini grape leaves topped with a squeeze of
fresh lemon look great on a buffet table, too. It's also feasible
to create cheese straws with cut-up sheets of frozen store-bought
puff pastry dough topped with Parmesan cheese, then twisted and
baked until golden.
</P>
<P>
   Be creative with presentations and offer even the easiest
appetizers with style. Select colorful trays and platters _ even
plastic _ for serving the food poolside. Intersperse fancy and not
so fancy as well as colorful foods with those not as colorful on
the table.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger is usually better when it comes to food displays. You
want fresh fruits and veggies to look impressive. Brightly colored
vegetables can be piled in big lettuce-, kale-, fabric- or
napkin-lined baskets with a bowl or container (use hollowed-out red
or green bell peppers or cabbages or large tomatoes) of dip tucked
in the center or at the side. Also, consider doing food
arrangements on wooden cutting boards or using plastic
wrapped-lined flowerpots (plug the hole in the bottom) _ a large
one for chips and a smaller one for salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to keep food out of the sun. And replenish often to keep
things fresh-looking. When passing appetizers, serve only one type
at a time to avoid interrupting guests' conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Though a party of appetizers and hors d'oeuvres means finger
foods, provide a stack of little plates and even some forks. And
have plenty of napkins handy _ the more festive the better. Look
for something fun, colorful and decorative at gift and party shops.
</P>
<P>
   Also don't forget to have plenty of trash receptacles, kept as
neat as possible and handy.
</P>
<P>
   Impress your guests with a selection of these creations at your
next gathering. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
CUTLINE: &QL; 
Michael Owen Baker/Daily News Staff Photographer &QL; 
Keep party festivities casual with a variety of nibbles and
drinks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER CHEESECAKE &QL; 
1/4 cup margarine OR butter, melted &QL; 
6 sheets frozen filo dough (18x14-inch sheets), thawed &QL; 
1/2 of a 6-ounce jar marinated artichoke hearts &QL; 
3 packages (8 ounces EACH) cream cheese, softened &QL; 
1 1/4 cups crumbled feta cheese &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon dried oregano, crushed &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon garlic powder &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
1/4 cup sliced green onions &QL; 
Plum tomato slices (optional) &QL; 
Whole Greek OR ripe olives (optional) &QL; 
Fresh basil leaves (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Brush bottom and sides of a 9-inch springform pan with some of
margarine. Cut sheets of filo into 13-inch rounds. Ease 1 sheet in
pan off-center so that filo extends 3 inches up sides of pan. Brush
with margarine. Repeat with remaining filo and margarine, placing
sheets off-center to cover bottom and sides of pan. Make 2 slits in
center of filo for steam to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 400-degree oven 9 to 10 minutes, or until
lightly golden. Cool on a wire rack. Reduce oven temperature to 325
degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Drain and chop artichokes, reserving 2 tablespoons marinade. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixer bowl, beat cream cheese until smooth. Add feta,
oregano and garlic powder. Beat well. Add eggs; beat just until
blended. Do not overbeat. Stir in artichoke hearts, reserved
marinade and onions. Pour into crust.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 325 degrees F for 35 to 40 minutes, or until center is
soft-set and sides stay firm when gently shaken. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Cover; chill 2 hours or up to 24 hours. Serve slightly chilled
or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, remove from pan; top with plum tomato slices, whole
olives and basil leaves. Cut into wedges. Makes 14 appetizer
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Better Homes and Gardens, November 1993.
</P>
<P>
   SESAME CHICKEN STRIPS
</P>
<P>
   Chinese hoisin sauce makes a terrific basting sauce for grilled
chicken. Keep a careful eye on these kebabs as they cook. &QL; 
1 pound skinless, boneless chicken breasts &QL; 
3 tablespoons bottled hoisin sauce &QL; 
1 tablespoon cider vinegar &QL; 
1 teaspoon chopped garlic &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   Light a medium-hot fire in barbecue grill, or preheat broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Cut chicken lengthwise into 3/4-inch-wide strips. Thread strips
onto small metal or soaked bamboo skewers.
</P>
<P>
   Combine hoisin sauce, vinegar and garlic. Brush sauce over
chicken. Then sprinkle on sesame seeds, pressing into sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Grill or broil 3 to 4 inches from heat for 3 minutes. Turn
chicken over and grill about 3 minutes longer, until chicken is
white throughout but still moist in center. Serve hot. Makes about
12.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The 5 in 10 Appetizer Cookbook'' by Paula J. Hamilton
(Hearst Books).
</P>
<P>
   BRIE TORTE
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick way to dress up a large wheel of Brie for a
party. You can also use pesto made with basil or cilantro, or even
tapenade (olive paste). If you have a few nasturtiums or other
edible flowers, use them to garnish the serving platter. &QL; 
1 wheel (2.2 pounds) Brie cheese &QL; 
1 1/2 cups sun-dried tomato pesto &QL; 
2/3 cup pine nuts OR slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   With a long, sharp knife, cut wedge of Brie in half horizontally
and separate two halves. Spread 1/2 of pesto on top of bottom half
of cheese. Cover with other wedge of cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Spread remaining pesto on top and sprinkle on pine nuts,
pressing in slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with crackers or thin slices of toasted country-style
bread. Makes 20 to 24 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The 5 in 10 Appetizer Cookbook'' by Paula J. Hamilton
(Hearst Books).
</P>
<P>
   SWEET CORN AND SHRIMP CAKES
</P>
<P>
   Of all the recipes for corn cakes that I've read or tasted, this
is the easiest _ and one of the tastiest. Serve them plain or, if
you like, garnish with a dollop of tart green salsa made from
tomatillos. Thawed frozen corn works well in this recipe. &QL; 
3 cups corn kernels (fresh OR thawed frozen) &QL; 
2 tablespoons flour &QL; 
1 egg &QL; 
1/4 cup whipping cream OR milk &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 cup cooked shelled baby shrimp
</P>
<P>
   Puree 2 cups corn in a food processor. Add flour, egg, cream and
salt, pulse several times to combine. Stir in remaining 1 cup corn
and shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a nonstick or lightly oiled griddle. Make corn cakes using
1 tablespoon batter for each. Cook in batches over medium-high heat
until bottoms are nicely browned, about 2 minutes. Turn over and
cook other sides until lightly browned, 1 1/2 to 2 minutes longer.
Serve immediately. Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The 5 in 10 Appetizer Cookbook'' by Paula J. Hamilton
(Hearst Books).
</P>
<P>
   SWEET AND SPICY PECANS
</P>
<P>
   These crisp bites are irresistible and will disappear when
served as a nibble with cocktails. Don't salt until after tasting,
because each brand of Cajun seasoning includes different amounts of
salt. &QL; 
2 tablespoons butter &QL; 
2 cups pecan halves &QL; 
2 teaspoons Cajun seasoning &QL; 
2 teaspoons sugar &QL; 
Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a medium nonstick skillet, melt butter over medium heat. Add
pecans and cook, stirring often, 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle Cajun seasoning and sugar over nuts and cook, stirring
constantly, until sugar has melted and nuts are glazed, about 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer pecans to a plate and cool slightly. Taste and season
with salt, if needed. Serve warm or at room temperature. Makes 6 to
8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The 5 in 10 Appetizer Cookbook'' by Paula J. Hamilton
(Hearst Books).
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   SWEET AND SPICY PECANS
</P>
<P>
   These crisp bites are irresistible and will disappear when
served as a nibble with cocktails. Don't salt until after tasting,
because each brand of Cajun seasoning includes different amounts of
salt. &QL; 
2 tablespoons butter &QL; 
2 cups pecan halves &QL; 
2 teaspoons Cajun seasoning &QL; 
2 teaspoons sugar &QL; 
Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a medium nonstick skillet, melt butter over medium heat. Add
pecans and cook, stirring often, 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle Cajun seasoning and sugar over nuts and cook, stirring
constantly, until sugar has melted and nuts are glazed, about 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer pecans to a plate and cool slightly. Taste and season
with salt, if needed. Serve warm or at room temperature. Makes 6 to
8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The 5 in 10 Appetizer Cookbook'' by Paula J. Hamilton
(Hearst Books).
</P>
<P>
   STUFFED MUSHROOMS &QL; 
2 pounds medium mushrooms &QL; 
6 tablespoons butter &QL; 
1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese, softened &QL; 
1/2 cup (2 ounces) crumbled blue cheese &QL; 
2 tablespoons chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   Remove mushroom stems; chop enough stems to measure 1/2 cup.
Cook 1/2 of mushroom caps in 3 tablespoons butter over medium heat
for 5 minutes; drain. Repeat with remaining mushroom caps and
butter.
</P>
<P>
   Combine cream cheese and blue cheese, mixing until well blended.
Stir in chopped stems and onion; fill mushroom caps. Place on
baking sheet; broil until golden brown. Makes about 2 1/2 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Kraft Philadelphia Cream Cheese Cookbook,'' Publication
International Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP SPREAD &QL; 
1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese, softened &QL; 
1/2 cup margarine, softened &QL; 
1/4 cup chili sauce &QL; 
2 teaspoons prepared horseradish &QL; 
2 cans (4 1/4 ounces EACH) small shrimp, drained and finely chopped
OR 1/2 pound cleaned, cooked shrimp
</P>
<P>
   Combine cream cheese and margarine, mixing until well blended.
Add chili sauce and horseradish to cream cheese mixture, mixing
until well blended. Add shrimp; mix well. Chill. Makes about 2 1/2
cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Kraft Philadelphia Cream Cheese Cookbook,'' Publication
International, Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   ROQUEFORT BALL
</P>
<P>
   The sharp combination of blue cheese and walnuts is equally good
on bread, piped onto pears or stuffed into cherry tomatoes or
mushroom caps. &QL; 
1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese, at room temperature &QL; 
4 ounces crumbled Roquefort cheese &QL; 
2 tablespoons whipping cream &QL; 
1/2 cup finely chopped walnuts &QL; 
1/4 cup plump raisins
</P>
<P>
   Place cream cheese, Roquefort and cream in a food processor.
Pulse, using on/off turns, until thoroughly combined, and transfer
to a bowl. Stir in 1/4 cup nuts. Shape into a ball, wrap and
refrigerate at least 3 hours, until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Combine remaining 1/4 cup nuts and raisins. Roll cheese ball in
nut mixture, lightly pressing to adhere. Serve at room temperature.
Makes about 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``A Little Something'' by Susan Epstein, William Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO CHICKEN WINGS
</P>
<P>
   You'll need a good blue cheese dressing for dipping and plenty
of drinks to put out the fire. &QL; 
3 pounds chicken wings, tips removed, rinsed and patted dry &QL; 
Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste &QL; 
1/2 to 1 cup Frank's Original Red Hot sauce OR your favorite hot
pepper sauce &QL; 
1/3 cup butter, melted &QL; 
Vegetable oil for frying &QL; 
2 cups celery sticks, trimmed and cut into thin strips &QL; 
1 package (1 pound) baby carrots &QL; 
1 bottle (8 ounces) of your favorite blue cheese dressing
</P>
<P>
   Season chicken with salt and pepper. Combine hot sauce and
butter in a large metal bowl and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Pour about 2 inches of oil into a large, heavy saucepan. Heat to
375 degrees F. Cook chicken thoroughly, in batches, in oil until
golden and crisp, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly place hot chicken wings into hot sauce mixture and toss
to coat. Serve with celery, carrots and blue cheese dressing. Makes
6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``A Little Something'' by Susan Epstein, William Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   CHUTNEY HAM SPREAD &QL; 
1/2 pound honey-style baked ham &QL; 
3 tablespoons mango chutney &QL; 
2 tablespoons unsalted butter, softened &QL; 
1 tablespoon Cognac OR brandy (optional) &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons powdered mustard &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   Trim any excess fat from ham and cut meat into 1-inch dice.
Place ham in a food processor and pulse until chopped.
</P>
<P>
   Add chutney, butter, Cognac, mustard and hot sauce. Pulse
briefly to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Serve slightly chilled or at room temperature with rye or
whole-grain bread slices or mini corn muffins. Makes 1 1/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``50 Best Salsas &AMP; Dips'' by Jane Kirby, Broadway Books.
</P>
<P>
   HOT CRAB AND ARTICHOKE SPREAD
</P>
<P>
   1 can (14 ounces) artichoke hearts &QL; 
1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese &QL; 
1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese, softened &QL; 
1/4 cup mayonnaise &QL; 
2 small garlic cloves, minced &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper &QL; 
1/2 pound fresh OR thawed frozen crab meat, well drained and patted
dry &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Drain artichoke hearts. Squeeze in paper towels to remove as
much liquid as possible. Reserve 1 tablespoon Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor, combine remaining Parmesan cheese with
artichoke hearts, cream cheese, mayonnaise, garlic, black pepper,
Worcestershire sauce and cayenne. Puree until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pick over crab meat to remove any bits of shell or cartilage.
Add crab meat and lemon juice to artichoke puree and pulse just
until mixed. Turn into a 1 1/2-quart gratin or shallow baking dish.
Sprinkle reserved 1 tablespoon Parmesan cheese over top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 400-degree oven 20 to 25 minutes or until top
is golden. Let stand about 10 minutes to cool and set slightly.
Serve warm with crackers or toast points. Makes about 3 1/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``50 Best Salsas &AMP; Dips'' by Jane Kirby, Broadway Books.
</P>
<P>
   CAVIAR CREAM CHEESE SPREAD &QL; 
1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese &QL; 
2 hard-cooked eggs, finely chopped &QL; 
3 green onions, thinly sliced &QL; 
1 teaspoon capers &QL; 
1 cup dairy sour cream &QL; 
2 ounces red caviar, drained in a fine sieve
</P>
<P>
   Spread cream cheese on a dinner-size serving plate. Sprinkle
with eggs, then onions, capers and sour cream. At this point,
spread can be covered and chilled a few hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, top with caviar. Serve with water crackers.
Makes about 2 1/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Chips, Dips &AMP; Salsas'' by Judy Walker and Kim MacEachern,
Northland.
</P>
<P>
   MEDITERRANEAN OLIVE SALSA &QL; 
8 ounces Greek OR Kalamata olives, pitted and chopped &QL; 
1 large tomato, chopped &QL; 
4 ounces feta cheese, crumbled &QL; 
3 to 4 green onions, chopped &QL; 
2 tablespoons olive oil (OR less) &QL; 
2 tablespoons white wine vinegar &QL; 
Combine all ingredients in a medium bowl. Store in refrigerator.
Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with pita or bagel chips. Makes about 2 1/2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Chips, Dips &AMP; Salsas'' by Judy Walker and Kim MacEachern,
Northland.
</P>
<P>
   FRUIT DIP
</P>
<P>
   A bowl filled with this dip surrounded by mixed fruit pieces
makes a beautiful presentation. &QL; 
2 cups dairy sour cream &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
3/4 cup apricot OR peach preserves &QL; 
Sugar to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine first 3 ingredients in a medium bowl and blend. Sweeten
with sugar and stir to combine. Chill.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with fresh fruit pieces. Makes about 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Chips, Dips &AMP; Salsas'' by Judy Walker and Kim MacEachern,
Northland.
</P>
<P>
   EASY PIZZA DIP &QL; 
1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese, softened &QL; 
1/2 cup dairy sour cream &QL; 
2 teaspoons dried basil &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon garlic pepper &QL; 
1/2 cup pizza OR spaghetti sauce &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped green bell pepper &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped green onions &QL; 
1/2 cup sliced ripe olives &QL; 
1 to 1 1/2 cups shredded mozzarella cheese
</P>
<P>
   In a mixing bowl, beat together cream cheese, sour cream, basil
and garlic pepper. Spread evenly in a 9- or 10-inch quiche dish or
pie plate. Spread pizza sauce over top. Sprinkle with green pepper,
green onions and olives.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 10 minutes. Top with
mozzarella cheese and bake an additional 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot with pita, bagel or nacho chips. Makes 6 to 8
appetizer servings.
</P>
<P>
   COCKTAIL FRANKS &QL; 
1 jar (6 ounces) prepared mustard &QL; 
1 jar (10 ounces) red currant jelly &QL; 
1/3 cup chopped white or green onions (optional) &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds cocktail franks OR miniature smoked link sausages
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan, heat mustard, jelly and onion until well blended
and hot, stirring often. Add franks and heat until very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a chafing dish and keep hot. Makes 10 or more
servings.
</P>
<P>
   TACO DIP &QL; 
1 can (17 ounces) refried beans (use hot and spicy beans, if
desired) &QL; 
Bottled taco sauce &QL; 
Guacamole Dip &QL; 
1 pint dairy sour cream &QL; 
1 package (1 1/2 ounces) taco seasoning mix &QL; 
2 to 3 cups shredded Cheddar cheese &QL; 
4 green onions, chopped &QL; 
3 tomatoes, chopped &QL; 
1 can (2.2 ounces) sliced ripe olives, drained &QL; 
Tortilla chips
</P>
<P>
   Mix refried beans and 1/4 cup taco sauce. Spread bean mixture in
bottom of a 10-inch fluted quiche dish or pie plate. Top with
Guacamole Dip, spreading evenly. Mix together sour cream and taco
seasoning mix. Spread carefully over guacamole.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle with cheese, green onions, tomatoes and ripe olives.
Refrigerate until serving time.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, stand tortilla chips up around sides of
serving dish. Serve with additional tortilla chips. Makes 8 to 10
servings.
</P>
<P>
   GUACAMOLE DIP: Mash together 2 to 3 ripe avocados, peeled and
seeded. Mix in 2 tablespoons lemon juice; 2 tomatoes, chopped; 3 to
4 tablespoons diced green chiles; dash Tabasco sauce and garlic
salt and seasoned salt to taste. Adjust seasonings as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY SALMON BALL &QL; 
1 can (1 pound) salmon &QL; 
1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese, softened &QL; 
1 tablespoon lemon juice &QL; 
2 teaspoons grated onion &QL; 
1 teaspoon horseradish &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/4 to 1/2 teaspoon liquid smoke OR more to taste &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped pecans &QL; 
3 tablespoons snipped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Drain and flake salmon; remove skin and bones. Mix thoroughly
with cream cheese, lemon juice, grated onion, horseradish, salt and
liquid smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Chill several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Combine pecans with parsley. Shape salmon mixture into ball and
roll in nut-parsley mixture. Chill well. Serve with assorted
crackers.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Freezes well. Salmon mixture also can be placed in a
serving dish and topped with nut mixture, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   SUN-DRIED TOMATO AND OLIVE TAPENADE &QL; 
3 ounces dry-packed sun-dried tomatoes, softened in very hot water,
squeezed dry and coarsely chopped &QL; 
1 tablespoon small capers, rinsed, drained and patted dry &QL; 
5 ounces pitted Nicoise olives &QL; 
1 clove garlic, finely chopped &QL; 
1 teaspoon grated lemon peel &QL; 
1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon dried herbes de Provence, thyme OR rosemary &QL; 
3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil &QL; 
Salt
</P>
<P>
   In bowl of a food processor fitted with a metal blade, combine
all ingredients except salt and process to a coarse puree. Season
to taste with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a bowl and serve at room temperature or store in a
tightly covered food container in refrigerator or freezer. Serve
with fresh country-style bread or baguette slices. Makes about 1
cup.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Spreads, Toppers &AMP; Dips'' by Diane Rozas, Macmillan.
</P>
<P>
   CHUNKY ARTICHOKE AND BRIE PATE &QL; 
1 shallot, finely chopped &QL; 
1 pound French OR domestic Brie cheese, roughly chopped &QL; 
1/4 cup finely chopped flat-leafed parsley &QL; 
1/2 cup marinated artichoke hearts, well drained and roughly
chopped &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon grated lemon peel OR well-rinsed and drained small
capers &QL; 
2 tablespoons dry sherry OR to taste &QL; 
Salt &QL; 
Freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   In bowl of a food processor fitted with a metal blade, combine
shallot, Brie, parsley, artichoke hearts, lemon peel and 1
tablespoon sherry. Process to a coarse consistency. Artichoke
pieces will make texture slightly chunky.
</P>
<P>
   Add remaining 1 tablespoon sherry and season to taste with salt
and white pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Press into a crock or terrine and serve at room temperature.
Makes about 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Spreads, Toppers &AMP; Dips'' by Diane Rozas, Macmillan. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
