<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PBJSIDE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEANUT BUTTER RECIPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peanut butter hummus
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 (19-ounce) can chickpeas, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor fitted with a steel blade, combine all
ingredients. Process until smooth and creamy, scraping down the
sides of bowl as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Per (1-tablespoon) serving: 41 calories (48 percent from fat), 2
grams total fat (less than 1 gram saturated), no cholesterol, 4
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 91 milligrams sodium, 1 gram
dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ The World's Greatest Peanut Butter Cookbook
</P>
<P>
   Honey-Gorgonzola crostini
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 9 servings
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces sweet Gorgonzola cheese, rind removed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup raw honey (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped unsalted dry-roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   18 parsley leaves, to garnish
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place bread on baking sheet. Bake 15 minutes or until golden,
turning once.
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, combine cheese, peanut butter and parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Spread thin layer of honey on each slice of bread, followed by a
layer of cheese mixture. Sprinkle lightly with nuts. Place 1
parsley leaf on each slice. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving, based on 6, topping only: 174 calories (52 percent
from fat), 10 grams total fat (5 grams saturated), 25 milligrams
cholesterol, 14 grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 144
milligrams sodium, 1 gram dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ The World's Greatest Peanut Butter Cookbook
</P>
<P>
   Peanut butter-chutney Monte Cristo sandwiches \
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup crunchy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fruit chutney, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   4 slices sandwich bread, crusts removed
</P>
<P>
   4 small or 2 large slices (about 4 ounces) cooked turkey
</P>
<P>
   2 small or 1 large slice (about 2 ounces) cooked ham
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten slightly
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine peanut butter, chutney and mustard.
Spread on one side of each bread slice. Arrange turkey and ham on
peanut butter mixture side of 2 bread slices. Top with remaining 2
slices bread, peanut butter mixture side down. Secure with wooden
picks.
</P>
<P>
   In a shallow bowl, combine eggs, milk and salt. Heat oil in a
10-inch skillet over medium heat. Dip both sides of each sandwich
into egg mixture. Cook until underside is golden, turn and cook
remaining side until golden. Remove toothpicks. Cut each sandwich
diagonally into 2 triangles. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 676 calories (52 percent from fat), 36 grams total
fat (8 grams saturated), 226 milligrams cholesterol, 39 grams
carbohydrates, 36 grams protein, 1,892 milligrams sodium, 4 grams
dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate peanut butter roll ups
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup creamy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 (3-ounce) package cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup heavy cream, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound good-quality bittersweet or semisweet chocolate,
finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Six (8-inch) flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons (1/2 stick) unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   In the bowl of an electric mixer, cream the peanut butter and
sugar until light and fluffy at medium speed. Add the cream cheese
and vanilla, and beat well. Whip 1/3 cup heavy cream until
medium-soft peaks form, and fold the cream into the peanut butter
mixture until thoroughly combined. Refrigerate 30 minutes or until
slightly firm.
</P>
<P>
   While the mousse is chilling, place the chopped chocolate in a
small mixing bowl. Bring the remaining 1/3 cup cream to a boil in
small saucepan or in a glass measuring cup in a microwave at full
power, and pour it over the chocolate. Stir until melted and
thoroughly combined. Set mixture aside until it is firm enough to
spread; it should have the consistency of cream cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the mousse from the refrigerator. Beat on the lowest
speed of the mixer at least 5 minutes, preferably longer, until
mousse is light and fluffy.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven broiler. Cover a baking sheet with heavy-duty
aluminum foil. Place the tortillas on a counter, and spread a thick
layer of chocolate 3 inches wide in the center of each tortilla,
leaving a 11/2-inch margin on both sides. Place a portion of mousse
at the bottom of each tortilla, below the chocolate. Tuck the sides
in to enclose the filling, and gently roll the tortillas into a
cylinder. Place the tortillas, seam side down, on the baking sheet.
Brush the rolls with melted butter. Combine the sugar and cocoa
powder, and sprinkle the mixture heavily over the rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Broil the rolls 6 inches from the broiler unit 1 to 2 minutes,
or until the sugar on top has melted. Remove the pan from the
broiler, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Note: The peanut butter and chocolate mixtures can be prepared
up to 1 day in advance and refrigerated, tightly covered. Allow the
chocolate to reach a spreadable consistency before assembling the
dessert. Or the rolls can be prepared for final broiling up to 2
hours in advance and refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 571 calories (58 percent from fat), 39 grams total
fat (18 grams saturated), 74 milligrams cholesterol, 51 grams
carbohydrates, 11 grams protein, 325 milligrams sodium, 4 grams
dietary fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _ All Wrapped Up by Ellen Brown
</P>
<P>
   Homemade peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   Makes 11/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   Place peanuts in a blender or food processor. Add peanut oil.
Cover and blend on high, scraping the sides and bottom
occasionally. Blend until you have the desired consistency, smooth
or crunchy.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate any unused portion to keep the nut oils from going
stale. For easier spreading, remove from refrigerator a few minutes
before using. If the oil has separated, just stir the peanut
butter.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Before measuring peanut butter for a recipe, coat your
measuring spoon or spoon lightly in oil.
</P>
<P>
   Per (1-tablespoon) serving: 74 calories (74 percent from fat), 7
grams total fat (1 gram saturated), no cholesterol, 2 grams
carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 2 milligrams sodium, 1 gram dietary
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   _The Brown Bag Cookbook (Williamson) by Sara Sloan
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7241 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FOOD-PBJ-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      09-01 1768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PBJ-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOURMET PB&AMP;J 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's practically an American icon, so just how much liberty can
you take with a PB&AMP;J?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is it written that this kid's classic must consist of
peanut butter and grape jelly on white bread.
</P>
<P>
   Brad VanAuken, 42, still eats a peanut butter sandwich at least
once a week, but, he says, ``My tastes have become a little more
refined since I was a child.''
</P>
<P>
   VanAuken enthusiastically ticks off a few of his more
adventurous peanut butter pairings: peanut butter and guava jelly.
Peanut butter and lemon curd. Peanut butter and Nutella, a creamy
European-style, chocolate-hazelnut spread. Peanut butter and
chutney. Peanut butter and pitted dates. Peanut butter and fresh
pineapple slices. Peanut butter and candied ginger.
</P>
<P>
   Some of VanAuken's combinations came together after tasting new
foods on travels to such exotic locales as Belize or Tanzania.
Others spawned from an empty jelly jar.
</P>
<P>
   ``What usually happens is, I have all these snack things around
and just end up mixing them in the peanut butter,'' the Brookside
resident says.
</P>
<P>
   It's that same spirit of innovation that led 26-year-old Lee
Zalben to open Peanut Butter &AMP; Co. His Greenwich Village restaurant
serves 13 different peanut butter sandwiches for $5 to $6 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically I ate a lot of peanut butter as a kid,'' Zalben
says. As a college student at Vassar, Zalben and his friends' study
breaks often included contests to create a PB&AMP;J that could be
considered ``gourmet but not too out there.''
</P>
<P>
   At Peanut Butter &AMP; Co., Jif gets one-upped by freshly ground
peanut butters available in a mix of textures and flavors _ crunch
or smooth, spicy or cinnamon-raisin, chocolate chip or white
chocolate chip. Artisanal breads from a bakery stand in for spongy
mass-produced Wonder Bread. In addition to grape jelly, customers
can choose blueberry or cherry jam, raspberry or apricot preserves,
orange marmalade or lemon curd.
</P>
<P>
   On the menu are such classics as the Lunchbox Special, peanut
butter spread with a thick layer of strawberry or grape jam, or the
Fluffernutter, a gooey marriage of peanut butter and Marshmallow
Fluff.
</P>
<P>
   For the more exotic palate there's a spicy peanut butter
sandwich with chilled, grilled chicken and a dab of pineapple jam,
or a Creamsiclelike sandwich of white chocolate peanut butter and
orange marmalade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to stick to the universally accepted with some
gourmet twists,'' Zalben says.
</P>
<P>
   PB &AMP; crayons
</P>
<P>
   Peanut butter and pickles?
</P>
<P>
   Peanut butter and jalapenos?
</P>
<P>
   Peanut butter, yellow mustard and green peppers?
</P>
<P>
   Ahem. Tom Johnson has learned not to pass judgment on
odd-sounding peanut butter combinations.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year ago Johnson began researching concepts for the
new 122-seat Crayola Cafe, which is scheduled to open in Crown
Center in November. While visiting the Crayola home page at
crayola.com, he uncovered an interesting bit of trivia: the 18th
most-recognized smell in the world is the waxy, paraffin smell of a
crayon. The second most recognized smell is peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I envision Crayola, it's kind of nostalgic and
family-friendly,'' says Johnson, a managing director for Culinary
Concepts, which is owned by Hallmark. ``Then I thought, `Wow!
Peanut butter has that same kind of appeal.' It was a natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Smith and Debbie Gold, James Beard Award-winning chefs
for the American Restaurant, are known for sophisticated menus that
include such gourmet delicacies as kobe beef and foie gras.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last several months the chefs have been dreaming up
creative PB&AMP;J combos that will appear on the Crayola Cafe menu.
Their renditions include crustless rounds of white bread spread
with peanut butter served with ramekins of jelly, a side of M&AMP;Ms
and raisins plus small skewers of banana and apples; a
double-decker, club-style sandwich with peanut butter, grape jelly,
apple slices and crispy bacon; a chunky peanut butter sandwich with
generous layers of colored mini marshmallows, M&AMP;Ms, sliced bananas,
chopped cashews and peanuts topped off by a smear of apricot jelly.
</P>
<P>
   The nut butters will be ground fresh-to-order at the restaurant,
and children will be able to create a flavor and label their own
``brand'' of peanut butter. The personal peanut butter will be
served with their order or packaged for home use.
</P>
<P>
   Any kid's PB&AMP;J dream come true, right? Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, ``a lot of this is frankly appealing to the whims of
the adults,'' Smith says. ``We want to be a little bit gourmet and
have fun with it without getting too wacky.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just for kids anymore
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Swartz has been eating PB&AMP;J since she was ``old enough to
eat real food.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love peanut butter and jelly! It's my favorite meal and it's
sooo American,'' the 16-year-old Blue Valley Northwest High School
student says.
</P>
<P>
   Over the Fourth of July, Swartz was staying in Berlin as part of
an exchange program. To celebrate this most American of holidays,
Swartz decided to serve her new German friends ``the most American
dinner'' she could think of _ macaroni and cheese from a box,
peanut butter and jelly sandwiches and store-bought chocolate chip
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big hit,'' she says of the meal.
</P>
<P>
   An audio engineer for KMBC, Channel 9, Dolores Burke-King also
has fond memories of peanut butter as patriotic ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Burke-King had just graduated from college in 1982 and was
living in Ireland when she introduced her housemates to the joys of
a PB&AMP;J. For an entire summer they ate homemade rhubarb-date jam and
imported Australian peanut butter slathered on Irish soda bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was far from home for the first time in my life, traveling
and living by myself. Peanut butter and jelly helped with the
homesickness,'' says Burke-King, whose family of eight children
went ``through tubs of peanut butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Most American children are reared on PB&AMP;J, but it's not
just for kids anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have seen it as a very sweet kiddie food,'' the
Peanut Butter &AMP; Co.'s Zalben says. ``But peanut butter is a savory
taste and goes very well with savory food or as a complement to
more neutral foods.''
</P>
<P>
   Peanut butter also is age-neutral. ``Everyone has great memories
of their first peanut butter and jelly sandwich. They remind us of
simpler, happier times,'' Zalben says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have a mom and her child come in and have them end up
sitting next to a middle-aged couple wearing suits who are eating
on their lunch hour. They still get the same glint in their eye as
they prepare to take that first bite,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But are people willing to pay $5 for a sandwich they can make at
home?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently so.
</P>
<P>
   Open since February, Peanut Butter &AMP; Co.'s Zalben already is
making expansion plans. He's betting peanut butter is where coffee
was 10 years ago, before there was a Starbuck's on every corner.
</P>
<P>
   Replace the `J' in PB&AMP;J with _ anything
</P>
<P>
   The average American child will eat 1,500 peanut butter
sandwiches by high school graduation, according to The Great Food
Almanac by Irena Chalmers. So in the interest of variety, here are
some combos to consider:
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; cream cheese, raisins, carrot shreds and a
sprinkle of cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; apple butter
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; dried apple rings
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; honey with toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; date sugar
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; bacon with avocado
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; BLT (bacon, lettuce and tomato)
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; tofu with tomato and alfalfa sprouts
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; fresh pear slices
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; cream cheese with jelly
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; apricot jam with green chilies and hot mustard
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; ham with mandarin oranges
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; apple slices with honey
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; crushed potato chips
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; brown sugar (toasted)
</P>
<P>
   - Peanut butter &AMP; brown sugar with mini-marshmallows and
chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Other nut butters:
</P>
<P>
   - Sesame butter
</P>
<P>
   - Almond butter
</P>
<P>
   - Macadamia nut butter
</P>
<P>
   - Pecan butter
</P>
<P>
   - Hazelnut butter
</P>
<P>
   Other breads:
</P>
<P>
   - French toast
</P>
<P>
   - Pita
</P>
<P>
   - Sourdough
</P>
<P>
   - Sunflower
</P>
<P>
   - Whole-wheat
</P>
<P>
   - Banana bread
</P>
<P>
   - Raisin bread
</P>
<P>
   - Date-nut bread
</P>
<P>
   - Tortillas
</P>
<P>
   PB&AMP;J innovations
</P>
<P>
   In search of innovative PB&AMP;J combinations straight from the jar?
</P>
<P>
   Look no further than your supermarket where you'll find an array
of flavored spreads to go with, or substitute for, peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   - Nutella _ Created by an Italian pastry chef in the 1940s, the
product became so popular that Italian food stores began offering
``smears.'' Children would go to the stores with a slice of bread
and, for roughly a penny, buy a smear of this chocolate-hazelnut
spread. Originally known as Supercrema Gianduja, the spread was
renamed in 1964. A press release boasts that Nutella, the No. 1
selling nut spread in Italy and Germany, has sales greater than
those of all peanut butter brands combined. Look for it in gourmet
stores and supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   - Twist _ This sweet and creamy banana-flavored, milk chocolate
spread hails from Holland. The contents come piped in twisty
stripes. The glass jar bears a whimsical label with what may be an
alligator chasing a sprinting banana. Unfortunately it does not
come with subtitles. We found Twist at Hy-Vee.
</P>
<P>
   - Jif Smooth Sensations _ In July, Jif introduced three flavored
peanut butter spreads: Chocolate Silk, Apple Cinnamon and Berry
Blend. While many adult colleagues first frowned at the idea, after
an informal taste test, most conceded that, in small doses, the
folks at Jif might be onto something. A spokesman agrees it might
be too sweet for some on sandwiches but suggests using it on fruit,
crackers, pretzels and waffles. We agree.
</P>
<P>
   - Smucker's Snackers PB&AMP;J _ Who needs bread to make a PB&AMP;J? Try
crackers instead. Smucker's is touting the Snackers as a ``whole
new way to PB&AMP;J.'' You'll probably recognize it as a Lunchables
spinoff. They've prepackaged a spatula to spread small amounts of
peanut butter and grape or strawberry jelly on eight crackers.
Because it doesn't require refrigeration, it's easy to throw in a
backpack as the kids head off to school.
</P>
<P>
   - Smucker's Goober Grape _ Parents have never been able to
figure this one out, but kids love the novelty of PB&AMP;J ``stripes''
in Smucker's Goober Grape, a peanut butter and jelly blend in a
single jar.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jill Wendholt Silva
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
