<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7244 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-TV-TELETHON-KANSAS-KA     09-01 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TELETHON-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVER OR GOOFBALL? JERRY LEWIS IS BOTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN McTAVISH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   It's time again for the Jerry Lewis
Show.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forgive me _ ``The Jerry Lewis MDA Telethon.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a trademark Lewis pratfall, it's a seemingly easy slip to
make.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 8 p.m. Sunday the 34th annual Labor Day fund-raiser
for the Muscular Dystrophy Association returns with the serious
task of treating and finding a cure for 40 neuromuscular diseases
that most tragically ravage the bodies of children.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's the patently zany Lewis who remains the show's
singularly captivating draw.
</P>
<P>
   Love him or hate him _ and it's fair to speculate that even
detractors of the slapstick icon tune in just to shake their heads
in amazement at his audience-pandering antics _ Lewis is the
telethon.
</P>
<P>
   Whether people watch to see a great humanitarian at work or
their favorite idiot on display, 75 million in North America are
expected to view the 211/2-hour extravaganza on television (locally
KMBC, Channel 9). Millions more will be able to see streaming video
on the Internet in the world's first live multilingual Webcast in
English, Spanish and Japanese (www.mdausa.org).
</P>
<P>
   May I make a suggestion? Take the time to look very closely at
Lewis this holiday weekend on your TV or computer screen. Because
every star, no matter how festive in the firmament, eventually
burns out.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis may act like he's only 9 years old. In reality he's 73 and
recovering from a near-fatal attack of viral meningitis, which cut
short an August concert tour of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he takes the stage his energy returns,'' said Jim Brown,
director of public affairs for the Muscular Dystrophy Association,
of which Lewis is the national chairman. ``You see the magic come
back. But behind the scenes you see how he struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the TV audience is going to see vintage Jerry, but
we'll still have to play it by ear as the show unfolds. He isn't
100 percent yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As a recent guest on CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' a frank Lewis
revealed that he was advised to not be host of the telethon this
year because of the risk of another attack.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis: ``So I'll establish to the audience I may get the attack.
And if I get a bad attack, I'll walk off the stage, I'll get some
chicken soup and I'll come back ... I will take care of myself. I'm
going to have the best neurologists backstage ... ''
</P>
<P>
   King: ``Can you do the physical shtick?''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis: ``No, I can't do anything physically.''
</P>
<P>
   King: ``You can't jump around the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis: ``No, but I can make noise ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Host with the most
</P>
<P>
   Hear this, America: In more than 700 broadcast hours since 1966,
the annual MDA telethon has raised $953,673,793 _ that's right,
nearly $1 billion _ including a record-setting $51.5 million in
pledges and contributions in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Try imagining that arduous achievement without Lewis creatively
clowning, crying, begging and even bullying viewers for precious
pledge money to help his ``kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed McMahon can't. Lewis' longtime traffic cop and second banana
on the telethon views the event as inseparable from its
ultra-dedicated star, who is expected to sit on a high stool for
much of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``But knowing him, he'll be jumping off that stool and getting
involved,'' McMahon said in a teleconference with reporters to
discuss the telethon. ``He'll be in there with the blacked-out
teeth singing a song.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as always, he'll have lots of help. Recalling the golden
era of ``Ed Sullivan'' and other bygone TV variety shows, the MDA
telethon offers modern audiences a rare opportunity to be
entertained by a little bit of everything in one sitting _ from
comedians, dancers and magicians to Hollywood stars, sports figures
and popular musicians.
</P>
<P>
   This year's massive and diverse guest list includes Jason
Alexander, Brandy, Mariah Carey, Carrot Top, Cher, Charo, Norm
Crosby, Sheryl Crow, Celine Dion, Laura Dern, Brendan Fraser, the
Goo Goo Dolls, Whitney Houston, Judge Judy, Lucy Lawless, Bill
Maher, Marcel Marceau, Kevin Meaney, Tom Petty and the
Heartbreakers, Cathy Rigby, LeAnn Rimes, Gen. H. Norman
Schwarzkopf, Martin Short, Martha Stewart and Christopher Walken.
</P>
<P>
   Cast members from Broadway's ``Fosse'' and ``Annie Get Your
Gun'' also will perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say, `Look, we're going to entertain the hell out of you.
Then we're going to get your money,' '' McMahon said. ``We can
present Ray Charles and a 30-piece orchestra and strike them, and 2
minutes later bring out an acrobatic team. We're putting on one of
the best shows on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis isn't too bad, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing a guy who really knows physical comedy. Some of
those close-up shots of him being silly, but being silly on a
worldwide stage, are quite a phenomenal thing to witness. And it's
great for people to see that and understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Assessing a legend
</P>
<P>
   But does anyone really understand Lewis? (Besides the French,
that is, who have long hailed him as a comic auteur misunderstood
and underappreciated in his own country.) Does the man himself?
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' storied, up-and-down career suggests a perfectionist
performer making do in an imperfect show-biz world, a talent
tormented by his need to make people laugh and also triumphant
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   An eager performer since age 5, Lewis was a high-school dropout
(with a genius IQ) struggling as a solo act in New York's Borscht
Belt, when he partnered with then-toiling singer Dean Martin in
1946 in Atlantic City. The comedy team's onstage chemistry was
immediate _ Martin was civilized, Lewis was a lunatic _ and the two
rocketed to fame. For the next 10 years the duo reigned supreme in
movies, radio, television, nightclubs _ and fund-raisers, including
those that benefited the fight against muscular dystrophy.
</P>
<P>
   In later years Lewis would be repeatedly asked why he chose MD
over any other malady to so publicly battle. He has typically
refused to answer, saying in 1973, ``That's the only secret I
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The historic split between Martin and Lewis came with plenty of
hard feelings in 1956, although 20 years later the duo would be
briefly reunited onstage by Frank Sinatra in a memorable hug on the
1976 Lewis telethon. (Martin died at age 78 in 1995.)
</P>
<P>
   On his own, Lewis continued starring in popular movies,
eventually taking on the additional mantles of directing, writing
and producing. It seemed the harder he worked, the more he wanted
to know what others thought of him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1957 Bob Thomas of The Associated Press wrote that Lewis was
``an extremely sensitive fellow,'' who personally subscribed to
four clipping services. ``Criticisms sting him deeply and he
overlooks none of them ...,'' Thomas reported. ``He reads every
item and broods over the knocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Although such visually inventive Lewis films as 1960's ``The
Bell Boy'' garnered strong European favor, they were ignored or
belittled by most critics at home as trivial and infantile.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, perhaps buoyed by his overseas acceptance, Lewis
announced he was giving up TV appearances to devote himself to
movies. ``A film is foreverness, TV for a moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963 Lewis returned to TV in a live two-hour weekly variety
show on ABC. The network soon canceled the show _ a disaster by all
accounts _ buying out Lewis' contract for $4 million. He returned
to making movies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, as his old partner Martin scored big on television,
Lewis again vowed to be through with the small screen, saying
``it's dull, it's canned, it's tasteless.'' Despite his put-downs,
a year later he again tried TV, starring in his own short-lived
series on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   As the '60s passed into the '70s and beyond, the public's once
avid interest in Lewis was mostly a memory, except when it came to
his telethons for muscular dystrophy. Still, Lewis has made
attempts to be relevant in show business outside of his
high-profile charity work.
</P>
<P>
   Although never released, his 1971 film ``The Day the Clown
Cried'' _ about a German clown arrested by the Gestapo and used to
march Jewish children into the ovens of a concentration camp _
almost seems a sacrificial precursor to last year's controversial
Oscar-winner ``Life Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 he finally won concerted praise from American movie
critics for his straight role as a Johnny Carson-style talk-show
host kidnapped by an obsessed fan (played by Robert De Niro) in
Martin Scorsese's ``The King of Comedy.'' And in 1995, Lewis
realized his lifelong dream of appearing on Broadway when he played
the devil in a revival of ``Damn Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet today, ask anyone to tell you the last time they saw Jerry
Lewis perform, outside of an old movie, and the likely response is
on the MDA telethon. Perhaps that's why occasional attacks on the
telethon through the years by groups questioning its financial
integrity and ``pity party'' approach to raising money hurt him so
deeply.
</P>
<P>
   But then maybe Lewis has already gotten his reward for his
decades of telethon work. After performing emergency open heart
surgery on Lewis in 1982, Michael DeBakey, who is still Lewis'
primary physician, said that the millions of dollars raised by MDA
telethons contributed to scientific research on muscle function
that probably helped save his life.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewis, still on the mend from his life-threatening bout
with viral meningitis, sings ``You'll Never Walk Alone'' at the
close of this year's telethon _ perhaps tearfully, perhaps breaking
down _ millions of viewers will be rooting for ``Jerry's Kids.''
But this time, they may be pulling for Jerry, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
