<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-BEAUJOLAIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUJOLAIS: A WINE FOR DRINKING, NOT SIPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although wine marketing wizards would have us believe otherwise,
you don't have to wait until the third Thursday in November to
drink Beaujolais. You simply have to locate Beaujolais bottles that
don't have the word ``nouveau'' printed on the label.
</P>
<P>
   A task that, although not the easiest, isn't impossible. Like
the nouveau wines we've become accustomed to having during the
holidays, non-nouveau Beaujolais are light, fruity and easy to
drink. In fact, in the Beaujolais region of France, the slang for
these wines is gouleyant, which literally translated means
``gulpable,'' writes Michael Schuster in the ``Beginner's Guide to
Understanding Wine'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   New or not, Beaujolais is quaffing wine, meant to be drunk, not
sipped. But therein lies the danger. Thanks to their lighter,
fruitier, more friendly style, it is easy to overindulge.
Beaujolais wines are generally deep red in color with a distinctly
blue tinge making them appear violet. Low in tannins, they lack the
cheek-rattlng qualities of heavier reds such as cabernet sauvignon
and zinfandel and served slightly chilled, they are as close to a
white wine as a red wine can get.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUJOLAIS: THE REGION
</P>
<P>
   Unlike American and Australian wines, French wines are named for
the area in which they are made instead of the grapes from which
they are produced. Beaujolais, generally made from gamay grapes, is
produced in France's Beaujolais appellation; a strip of land, 30
miles long by roughly 8 miles wide in the lower area of the
country's famed Burgundy wine region. Beaujolais itself is divided
into two sections: Haut-Beaujolais and Bas-Beaujolais. The
Bas-Beaujolais, is the southernmost area where the soil is rich and
mostly limestone and clay. It's known for producing great quantity
more than quality. Usually, if you see a bottle labeled simply
Beaujolais, it was made here. These are flowery, fruity, simple
wines that must be drunk young. They are not intended for keeping.
Buy them, drink them. Serve slightly chilled (52 degrees) with all
types of food.
</P>
<P>
   THE VILLAGES
</P>
<P>
   The second area, the Haut-Beaujolais, is to the north and is the
source of better wines. Here you'll find the production of
Beaujolais-Villages (a step up from Beaujolais) and the 10 crus of
the Beaujolais region.
</P>
<P>
   Beaujolais-Villages wines contain a minimum of 10 percent
alcohol. These wines have more complexity and depth than Beaujolais
wines. Cherry red in color, Beaujolais-Villages can be kept one to
three years. Serve at 52-54 degrees with grilled and roasted meat,
poultry, cold cuts and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike American wines that are frequently grown, pressed,
fermented, bottled and sold by the winery, the grapes used in
Beaujolais are grown on small vineyards by hundreds of farmers who
then sell their crop to negociants (nah-GO-SEE-ahn). The
negociants, such as George DeBouef and Louis Jadot, make and sell
the wine under their own label. In some instances, when the grapes
are from a particularly respected, and highly rated vineyard, the
wine will be labeled for the vineyard in addition to the village.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where in France your Beaujolais comes from, you're
going to be hard pressed to find a bottle that costs more than $20.
</P>
<P>
   THE CRUS
</P>
<P>
   The northern part of Hapt-Beaujolais is divided into 10 crus, or
designated growing regions:
</P>
<P>
   Chiroubles (shee-ROOB-luh) _ Light bodied and the most balanced
of the cru wines. Serve at 54 degrees with roasted poultry and
white meats.
</P>
<P>
   Fleurie (FLUR-ee) _ Light bodied with the aroma of violets, the
Flurie area is called ``The Queen of the Beaujolaise.'' Serve at 54
degrees with lamb, grilled beef, roasts and poultry.
</P>
<P>
   Saint-Amour (sant ah-moor) _ Light bodied with the aroma of
stone fruits such as peaches, nectarines or apricots. Serve at 55
degrees with grilled meats, lightly seasoned stews, poultry and
pate.
</P>
<P>
   Brouilly (BREW-yee) _ The largest of the crus, wines from
Brouilly are generally known for being grapy tasting with red fruit
or blueberry aromas. Grown on the plains surrounding Mont Brouilly.
Serve at 54 degrees with poultry and red meat.
</P>
<P>
   Cote de Brouilly (coat duh BREW-yee) _ Grown on the hillsides of
Mont Brouilly, wines of this cru have similar flavors and aromas as
the Brouilly wines but with more depth and character. Serve at 55
degrees with meat stews, poultry, roasts or game.
</P>
<P>
   Regnie (ren-N'YAY) _ Usually, these wines have more concentrated
flavors than those from Brouilly. Regnie is the newest cru,
designated as such in 1988. Serve these at 54 degrees with
terrines, meats and light appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   Morgon (more-GOH) _ Medium bodied wines with the aroma of
cherries and plums. Serve at 54 degrees with hearty meat stews,
game, roast duck and seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Julienas (ZJOO-lee-ay-nah) _ Medium bodied with the aroma of
cherries and raspberries. Serve at 54 degrees with coq au vin,
game, red meats and cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   Chenas (shay-NAH) _ The rarest of the 10 crus, these wines are
medium bodied with the floral aromas of peonies. Chenas usually
have more aroma than Julienas, making them better for longer
storage. Serve at 57 degrees, with red meats, stews, strong cheeses
and big spicy dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Moulin-A-Vent (MOO-lan ah vahn) _ Named for a 300-year-old
windmill in the area, these wines have more weight and depth than
the other crus. When young, they have a rose, violet and red-fruit
aroma. With age, the scent develops into a mushroom-gamy smell.
They have great aging potential, usually keeping for seven to 10
years. Serve at 57 degrees with red meats, game, robust cheeses and
hearty dishes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sources: ``Wine Lover's Companion'' by Ron Herbst and Sharon
Tyler Herbst (Barron's, 1995); ``Beginner's Guide to Understanding
Wine'' by Michael Schuster (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1989); ``Tasting
Pleasure: Confessions of a Wine Lover'' by Jancis Robinson
(Penguin, 1997); ``Exploring Wine: The Culinary Institute of
America's Complete Guide to Wines of the World'' (Wiley, 1996);
``Wine Spectator's Ultimate Guide to Buying Wine'' (Wine Spectator,
1998) and the Georges Deboeuf Web site at
www.deboeuf-beaujolais.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
