u a BC-DAUGHTER-DEATH-ART-SP     09-01 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAUGHTER-DEATH-ART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS OF A DAUGHTER'S TORMENTED LIFE MAY OFFER HOPE TO OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHUONG LE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Carolyn Higgins remains puzzled when she looks at the
photograph of her daughter taken two weeks before her death.
</P>
<P>
   In the picture, Lexi Higgins is 19, bright-eyed and beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   But she also appears sad and troubled, her strained smile
revealing how she struggled for years with a personality disorder
few people understand and one she ultimately could not control.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 17, Lexi Higgins went to the Rite Aid in downtown
Seattle and bought lipstick, mascara and a large bottle of
extra-strength Tylenol. After sending an e-mail message to her
lawyer promising not to kill herself, she took 375 pills and ended
her life, alone in the room she rented for the summer at the YWCA.
</P>
<P>
   When the daughter's struggle with borderline personality
disorder ended, the mother's search for answers began.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not enough understanding about this disorder,''
Carolyn Higgins said from her home in Seattle's Lake City
neighborhood a day after Lexi's memorial service. Bouquets of
flowers sent from friends and family still crowded the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of how hard Lexi fought to get through the days and hoping
to help others, her parents have started a fund at Washington
Mutual to benefit those who suffer from personality disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our dream is to establish some sort of hospice where young
girls like Lexi could go,'' Carolyn Higgins said. ``There was no
place that was suitable for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Lexi's parents are also trying to piece together what happened
to her and what they can do to help others who suffered as she did.
</P>
<P>
   Even after her death, they continue to search the Internet and
libraries for answers: What is this disorder that tormented their
daughter? Why is so little known about it, even though it affects
about 2 percent of the population?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complex disorder,'' said Dr. Marsha Linehan, a
leading researcher of borderline personality disorder and
University of Washington professor. ``It's exceptionally difficult
to treat.''
</P>
<P>
   Research on the subject is relatively scant given that the
disorder has only been included in the American Psychiatric
Association's Diagnostic and Statistical Manual, the bible of the
profession, since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Its exact causes are unclear. It is characterized by instability
in mood, self-image and personal relationships.
</P>
<P>
   People with borderline personality disorders have a severe
inability to regulate their emotions and, therefore, control their
behavior, Linehan said.
</P>
<P>
   They have problems controlling emotions such as anxiety, fear,
love, depression and sadness, which can lead to drug use and
impulsive actions and cause sufferers to harm themselves.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of sufferers commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Lexi Higgins may have seen suicide as an escape from her endless
battles with low self-esteem, severe mood swings, intense anger,
fears of abandonment and other emotions that she was not able to
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something inside of her was causing her horrible agony,''
Lexi's mother said. ``I could see that she was just tormented.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when she could see clearly and try to get
herself back on track, and for some reason she would become lost in
this other space and not be able to control her behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Lexi Higgins' life embodied the sentiments of the popular book
on borderline personality disorder entitled ``I Hate You, Don't
Leave Me,'' those who knew her said.
</P>
<P>
   Hers was a life of extremes, of intense feelings of emptiness
and of unstable, intense personal relationships.
</P>
<P>
   She was a loyal friend who sent birthday cards even from her
hospital bed and tried to cheer others up even when she was
depressed. She was a sorority sister who loved games and going out,
yet often felt alone or unloved. She was a talented student who
swam and competed in gymnastics at Nathan Hale High School and
earned several scholarships to study at Washington State University
in Pullman.
</P>
<P>
   But she also did things that frustrated her friends and family
and baffled those who tried to help her.
</P>
<P>
   She told strange stories about her life, lied about things such
as her birthdate and became enraged over what most people consider
tiny problems, such as not being able to return a library book on
time.
</P>
<P>
   She erupted in fury over minor incidents and viewed every slight
against her as if it were the worst. She became furious once when
she wasn't offered a cup of coffee, even when she didn't drink
coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, she stole $4,000 from the Bon Marche store when she
worked as a retail clerk. She pleaded guilty to one count of
second-degree theft the day before she died.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were the suicidal tendencies and attempts to harm
herself with razor blades, both common signs of sufferers. She
tried several times to kill herself, the first serious attempt
coming in November at Washington State University.
</P>
<P>
   But with ``the courage of Napoleon,'' Lexi Higgins fought back
and tried to find help, her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Lexi often sought help at the emergency rooms of hospitals such
as Seattle's Harborview Medical Center, telling nurses and doctors
that she wanted to kill herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she let people know what was going on,'' said
childhood friend Jessica Coulson, who met Lexi when she was 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a brilliant girl, humorous and effervescent. She took
things hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friends and family wanted to know why she did what she did.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her uncontrollable behavioral problems, she still
managed to draw people to her with her sense of humor and quick
wit, her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Ellis, a Seattle public defender who represented Lexi in
her theft case and to whom she sent perhaps the last correspondence
before her death, remembers how she constantly reached out to
others even when she was down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is what was going on with this very bright
and wonderful person who was very troubled as well,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . I hope Lexi's life can help us take a step forward to
deal with this population.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, her mother said in her eulogy, ``the tragedy of her
life is that she alone was unable to see her own exquisite
loveliness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
