<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHILL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHILL FACTOR' SUFFERS FROM NEVER DECIDING WHAT IT WANTS TO BE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone in the market for a late-summer action movie could do
worse than ``Chill Factor,'' but it's certainly nothing special:
Its star chemistry is unusually lukewarm and its non-stop action
sequences all seem derivative of other movies.
</P>
<P>
   It's Hollywood's latest effort to capture the particular magic
of ``Speed'' _ a race to prevent an internal explosion _ and a
disjointed and often wacky effort it is at that, with an endlessly
bickering Skeet Ulrich and Cuba Gooding Jr. in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich plays a small-town Montana slacker and Gooding is the
thief of an ice cream truck, who are forced into mismatched
buddyhood when a canister of a highly volatile, frozen chemical
substance falls into their hands. If it melts, it could wipe out
most of Montana ``and maybe Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   So they have to throw it in the ice cream truck and keep it from
hitting the critical temperature of 50 degrees, while running from
the deadly band of paramilitary terrorists who originally stole the
bomb, and the slow-witted and trigger-happy Montana police who
think our heroes are responsible for the theft.
</P>
<P>
   As they race through the desert, dodging the pursuing
motorcycles, helicopters and mini-vans filled with high-tech
equipment, there's a thrill or two. And it's fun to try to spot the
movies that director Hugh Johnson is ripping off: not just
``Speed,'' but ``The Wages of Fear,'' ``The Satan Bug'' and
``Daylight'' all seem to have been major inspirations.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to stay hooked because the film can never quite
decide what it wants to be. It starts with a 15-minute prologue
that establishes a morbidly serious mood, then gets progressively
lighter as it goes along until it suddenly turns slapsticky and
silly, and begins to resemble a Road Runner cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chill Factor'' also suffers from the low-voltage casting of
Ulrich and Gooding. Both have been effective in other roles in
other movies, but neither has the distinctive spark of an action
hero, and their Butch-and-Sundance repartee falls so consistently
flat that you end up feeling a little embarrassed for them.
</P>
<P>
   Chill Factor. Directed by Hugh Johnson. Screenplay by Drew
Gitlin and Mike Cheda. Cast: Cuba Gooding Jr., Skeet Ulrich, Peter
Firth, David Paymer, Hudson Leick. Warner Bros. 105 minutes. Rated
R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0156 </DOCNO>
