A7274 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-PROVIDENCE-SPI &LR;      09-01 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROVIDENCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MUCH ENLIGHTENING IN COMING-OF AGE MOVIE, `OUTSIDE
PROVIDENCE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coming-of-age film has been a staple in the cinema for eons.
``The Graduate'' was perhaps a quintessential film of the '60s and,
on recent viewing, it still holds up well.
</P>
<P>
   But the deluge from young indie filmmakers _ the recent release
``Desert Blue'' and the upcoming ``The Adventures of Sebastian
Cole'' instantly leap to mind _ have glutted the market with
memoirs of personal rites of passage. ``Outside Providence''
nestles nicely into this niche.
</P>
<P>
   Its selling point is that it boasts the talent of those raucous
bad-boy brothers, the Farrellys, who directed ``Dumb and Dumber,''
``Kingpin'' and last year's big smash, ``There's Something About
Mary.'' ``Outside Providence'' has been adapted by the brothers
from an early novel by Peter Farrelly.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly a loving, bawdy view of a young man's coming to
terms with a blue-collar family, love and life in the small city of
Pawtucket, Conn. But outside of a smart performance by Shawn Hatosy
as Tim Dunphy, there just isn't much that's enlightening or new in
this intimate recollection.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it follows a formula that has been around for decades:
boarding school, first love and the search for individuality and
expression that is elusive but necessary in order to avoid becoming
stuck in a rut like the protagonist's parents.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Outside Providence,'' the younger actors bear up better
than the adults. Alec Baldwin plays pop to Tim, a young screw-up
who is sent away to school after smashing up a police car. Tim's
friends are all drunks and druggies and his little brother is
confined to a wheelchair. Even the family dog wears a patch on its
eye and has only three legs.
</P>
<P>
   At his new school, Tim collides with the usual woes: the
housemaster is itching to expel him; his friends are the requisite
outcasts and the girl he has his eye on, smart, rich and gorgeous
Jane Weston (Amy Smart), is way out of his league. But school
slowly provides an antidote to the real hardships in Tim's life and
he discovers who he is as well as embarking on the quest toward
taking control (and responsibility) for his life and actions.
</P>
<P>
   In that, ``Outside Providence'' is just fine. But it meanders
into dad's poker parties and some weird gay segues that throw the
film out of whack. Worse, Baldwin seems so intent upon replicating
Jack Nicholson's mob thug performance in ``Prizzi's Honor'' that we
wind up watching his overactive technique instead of engaging with
the quiet subplots that have taken shape.
</P>
<P>
   Like life, ``Outside Providence'' belongs to the kids. Hatosy
and Smart have a keen chemistry and they are both engaging,
attractive and natural actors. They make the characters real
despite the glorification and ridiculous romanticizing of the
uneventful, common story line that surrounds them.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Providence. Directed by Michael Corrente. Written by
Peter Farrelly, Bobby Farrelly, Michael Corrente. Cast: Shawn
Hatosy, Amy Smart, Alec Baldwin. Miramax Films. 102 minutes. Rated
R for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
