<P>
   FALL BOOKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ This fall, nonfiction dominates new books. Publishers
believe that it is easier to target nonfiction audiences, and that,
during the winter months, readers are more willing to curl up with
weighty, 500-page tomes. Accordingly, most of the sure-fire fall
bestsellers are nonfiction, from Frank McCourt's ``Angela's Ashes''
sequel to pop singer Jewel's printed prattlings about her life. By
JEFF GUINN. (Accompanied by FALL BOOKS-OTHERS). Story will move in
``e'' entertainment category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PROVIDENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Although ``Outside Providence'' comes from the
Farrelly brothers, the minds behind the gross-out hit ``There's
Something About Mary,'' there's a lot more to this film than
politically incorrect humor. It's unusually perceptive and even
charming, and it's the year's best coming-of-age film. By ROBERT
PHILPOT. Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CHILL FACTOR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Hey, Cuba Gooding Jr., the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts &AMP; Sciences called and they want their Oscar back. Well, not
really, but they might if you keep doing crummy films like ``What
Dreams May Come, Instinct'' and the predictible action ``thriller''
``Chill Factor.'' It's about a defoliant bomb that will explode if
its temperature reaches 50 degrees. Gosh, Cuba, seems like you'd be
tired of bombs by now. By TODD CAMP. Story will move in ``e''
