<P>
   NY-NORTH-SHORE-HOUSE (Undated) _ This was a summer of roses for
Carol and Millard Prisant, a Long Island couple who vacationed at
home by simply stepping through the screen doors onto their
rose-bedecked wraparound porch and drinking in a view of the long
harbor in their backyard. Maybe their part of the North Shore had a
faster social engine when Gatsby partied in the Eggs along with the
Fricks and the Morgans, but time is surprisingly slow even in 1999.
If the house and setting seem like a pocket of perfection suspended
in time, there are two reasons, separated by over a hundred years.
First, the house was conceived in 1862 as the country house of the
future. The second reason the house seems perfect is that the
Prisants _ he is a former rocket scientist who now owns an
aerospace hardware company; she is the New York editor of World of
Interiors magazine _ have restored it to the ideal from which it
had sadly lapsed. By Joseph Giovannini.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ESTHER-WILLIAMS-BOOK (Beverly Hills, Calif.) _ On the spreading
terrace of the hilltop house, there's a pretty blue pool and an
Esther Williams-brand whirlpool spa. There's a panoramic view to
the Pacific Ocean and a custom-made Esther Williams kick board
propped on the lawn. But nothing quite prepares a visitor for the
sight of Esther Williams herself, in short white shorts, black
flats, black tube top and white cotton blouse adorned with a
rhinestone-speckled applique of a top hat and gloves on the front.
She emerges from the shade of her living room in full-body makeup,
legs firm and posture perfect, smiling that 1,000-watt waterproof
smile, and asks politely, ``Would you like to take a swim?'' The
offer is tempting, but there are no trunks and the task at hand is
talk. The topic is Miss Williams's new memoir, ``The Million Dollar
Mermaid'' a ribald account of her years as MGM's aquatic sensation,
the godmother of synchronized swimming and one of the top 10 box
office stars in the world. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
