<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Partial-Shade Bonanza
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently moved into a home on the Connecticut shore that
has beautiful gardens. One area, however, gets a fair amount of
shade. Mums, bee balm, parsley and marigolds are doing well in the
less-shaded part of this section, and I would like to plant a few
more perennials that will bloom in July and August. It has a
southeastern exposure.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Since you say the gardens are lovely already and don't
mention major trees, I'll assume your soil is relatively free of
roots and in good health, and by southeastern exposure, you mean
the garden gets sunlight for most of the morning. If these
assumptions are correct, your only problem will be leaving room for
later bloomers after you fill up the joint with spring delights
like columbines, violas, bleeding hearts, trout lilies, primroses
and bluebells.
</P>
<P>
   Most partial-shade gardeners fall heavily for coral bells
(Heuchera sanguinea), because they are such hard workers. Though
they start putting out airy stalks of little red, pink or white
bells in late spring, heucheras often repeat right through the
season and, if deadheaded, can usually be counted on to rebloom at
summer's end. As an added bonus, the leaves are lovely, basically
round, but sometimes also attractively scalloped and cut. Several
varieties, including Palace Purple and Pewter Moon, are grown
primarily for their deep maroon or maroon and silver foliage. These
darklings are prettiest when backed by something bright, like the
chartreuse blades of golden sedge, which also does well in partial
shade.
</P>
<P>
   Many hostas have lovely midsummer flowers. Don't forget the
puffy spires of astilibes or the taller, more delicate meadow rue
(Thalictrum ), which comes in yellow as well as pink and white.
There's great blue lobelia (Lobelia siphilitica), and all the
wonderful, intense purples of monkshood (Aconitum). For
architectural drama consider black snake root (Cimicifuga racemosa)
or, as fall comes on in earnest, the exquisite blossoms of Japanese
anemones.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking Big Girl Tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Q. When we started to garden 30 years ago, we experimented with
many varieties of tomatoes. It didn't take long to settle on Big
Girl; we thought it stood up to bugs and disease better than
others, and we loved the flavor. After a time, we found it hard to
find seedlings, and now it is almost impossible to get them. Why?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Take a stroll through the supermarket, looking at how many
products say ``New!'' and you'll have a good part of your answer.
The W. Atlee Burpee Company introduced Big Girl in 1976, and
although they continue to offer it, they also continue to keep
introducing other tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early Girl has taken over the girl spot,'' said David Seitz,
the director of research and product development for Burpee. He
also pointed out that commercial growers ``can only grow so many.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Big Girl just got squeezed out'' by newer
introductions, he said. It may also be feeling the pinch from the
other direction. As heirloom varieties become more and more
popular, they, too, are starting to take up space on nurseries'
seedling shelves.
</P>
<P>
   To cover your bets, ask your local garden centers about their
tomato plans well before planting time. Then, if you have to, you
can order small seedlings of Big Girl directly from Burpee. (Orders
must be placed between Jan. 1 and April 30; 800-888-1447).
</P>
<P>
   But please don't stop experimenting; there have been some pretty
spiffy developments. The new Juliette, for instance, is a wonderful
little (two inch) tomato _ sweet, firm, crack-resistant and
extremely productive.
</P>
<P>
   To get a good idea of what's out there, consult the catalogs
from Totally Tomatoes (P.O. Box 1626, Augusta, Ga. 30903;
803-663-0016; free catalog) and the Tomato Growers Supply Company
(P.O. Box 2237, Fort Myers, Fla. 33902; 888-478-7333; free
catalog), both of which offer hundreds of choices.
</P>
<P>
   A Yew Run Amok
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've got a seriously overgrown yew, which I've chopped back,
so it's about eight feet tall and nearly as wide. Nothing but a few
straggly weeds grows under there now. Can I surround it with day
lilies, both for the flowers and to fill in the gap?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You can, if by surround you mean plant in a ring six to 10
feet away from the trunk. As you have noticed, even weeds are
having trouble in the deep shade under that yew, which in its years
of overgrowing has undoubtedly set down a mat of roots that would
give pause to anything but the most tenacious ground cover. If I
were you, I'd go for a nice smooth mulch of pine needles.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
