<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7308 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     09-01 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL FINANCE SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his stage play ``Millennium Bug,'' the economist and
performance artist Steven Tomlinson describes a new software
package called Veritas 2000 that not only manages your personal
finances, but also your soul. Veritas 2000 promises to lead
consumers out of debt and into affluence, but it does so by
tracking the user's spending and savings down to the most minute
level, spewing alerts and threats if a penny is spent
unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Quicken 2000 Deluxe ($59.95, or $39.95 for previous
Quicken users) nor its archrival Microsoft Money 2000 Deluxe
($44.95 until Nov. 30, $64.95 afterward) dare to intrude so deeply
into personal spending habits, but they do take the idea of
personal financial management to new levels, especially with the
aid of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these new programs jingle with features that help the
user manage daily finances, plan and invest, prepare for taxes, do
online banking, shop for insurance, and even tap into financial
information round the clock, and round the world, through
affiliated Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   These Year 2000 deluxe versions use the Internet for everything
from ferreting out information on investments to tracking down the
best financing options for major purchases. In a sign of the times,
both Quicken and Money provide detailed guidance on employee stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   Quicken and Money have been slugging it out for years, and their
epic rivalry is similar to that of baseball's Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa. Both are in a league by themselves, and both continue
to hit home runs at a hectic pace. Quicken scored with its
checkbook interface, Money countered with its better online
integration, Quicken took the lead with tax integration, Money
fired back with better planning tools, Quicken added easier data
entry, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   This year, both programs sport improved interfaces, and both
programs are swinging for the virtual fences with their Internet
links.
</P>
<P>
   There is not enough space here to list all of the features of
the deluxe versions of both of these programs and their respective
Web sites, www.quicken.com and www.moneycentral.com. The big news
is that Microsoft has scrapped its former $9.95 a month access fee
for MSN Money Central, which is now free. Quicken.com remains free.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other major features include the ability to track
bank accounts and credit cards, balance multiple checkbooks,
customize a budget, spew out endless graphs and charts in a
pathetic effort to impress ones spouse, plan for retirement or
college or other major events, grab current financial news and
stock quotes off the Web, analyze thousands of stocks and mutual
funds, track investment performance, pay bills on line, and even
enter data without having to wait to load the actual program.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, users will probably spend 80 percent of their time just
balancing the checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   The fictitious Veritas 2000 program also bristles with features,
but in the end they function mainly to highlight the risk that
focusing too much on numbers and data can cause the user to
overlook the more important things in life, like happiness. Both
Intuit (the maker of Quicken) and Microsoft have tried to program a
warmer and fuzzier feeling into the software. Both programs seem
determined to help the user plan for future happiness, and both get
fairly personal. Quicken will tell you how much your car is worth
and will scour the Internet to tell you how much your neighbor paid
for his or her house. Money will help you find the best way to pay
for your new refrigerator and will help you plan ``what if''
scenarios ranging from winning the lottery to getting hit by a bus.
I'm surprised neither program offered to lend me $20 until next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing for this version of its Money program, Microsoft
determined that nearly two-thirds of all the families that owned a
personal computer already have some sort of personal financial
management software. This is not surprising, considering that many
computer manufacturers sell PC's with such software already loaded
(some include both Quicken and Money.)
</P>
<P>
   Even though the software is already installed, only half of the
PC owners actually try the programs, and of those, Microsoft found,
only one of three used it on a continuing basis.
</P>
<P>
   One could make several inferences from these findings. One
supposition is that most PC owners do not need financial software
because they are natural wizards at managing their finances using
conventional analog techniques like checkbook registers and shoebox
receipt bins.
</P>
<P>
   No, I didn't think so, either. More likely, they have watched
their computers lose, mangle or hold their other data captive, and
they would rather entrust their important financial data to a
hardened criminal than to a hard drive. Or, they have come to
believe that using a personal finance program is more trouble than
it is worth.
</P>
<P>
   That may have been true when entering data into the older
programs, but consumers now have the ability to transfer data
directly into the program from their bank accounts, investment
portfolios and credit card statements. Each program has
relationships with more than 600 banks, and downloading bank
statements sure beats plugging each check into the electronic
register one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   If you are already using one program or the other, there are no
features in the new versions that are so dazzling as to warrant
switching.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using an ancient version of either program _ more
than a few years old _ and are happy with it, you ought to upgrade
anyway if only to avoid any potential problems with Y2K
compatibility. The 2000 versions of Money and Quicken are fully
Year 2000-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   For people just starting out with a personal financial manager,
Money 2000, with its impressive Setup Assistant, clean design and
use of audio and video coaching, is the easier program to learn.
Although I had better not explain why, I was grateful that the
program offered to send me reminders by e-mail when it comes time
to pay bills and file my expense reports.
</P>
<P>
   For Macintosh users the choice is easy, as Microsoft has no
plans to create a version of Money for Macs. (Intuit dismayed the
Apple community in 1998 by announcing that it would no longer
support the Macintosh, but it relented under pressure.) Canadians
will want to take advantage of Quicken's north-of-the-border
version.
</P>
<P>
   If tax preparation is a major concern, Quicken gets the edge
because of its close integration with the Turbotax and Macintax
programs, also made by Intuit. However, Microsoft plans to
introduce its own tax-prep program, Taxsaver, in December, and one
can expect it to work closely with Money 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: The intense rivalry between Quicken and Money
has resulted in a steady improvement in both programs, and the 2000
deluxe versions of both are excellent. Quicken has been around for
15 years and is by far the more popular program, but Money has
closed the gap and deserves serious consideration, especially by
those who are just now making the commitment to manage their
finances by computer.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson's fictitious Veritas 2000 program, which he describes
in a play currently showing in Austin, Texas, would advise the user
to skip lunch for a couple of weeks to pay for the new software,
noting that the $50 saved will grow to $100,000 in just a few short
decades thanks to the miracle of compound interest. I'd say, go
ahead, splurge now. You and your finances deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
