<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-EGYPT-0902-CO     09-01 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-EGYPT-0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A WARY EGYPT HOSTS PEACE TALKS AS SPECTRE OF CAMP DAVID LOOMS
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-PEACE-0902.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Egyptian Yasmin Mahdy remembers the hope she felt
as a teenager when she watched and videotaped the signing of the
Oslo Accords between Israel and the Palestinians in 1993. Now, that
peace process has stalled and she's wary as her country hosts the
latest attempt Thursday(Sept. 2) to revive it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody will be glued to the television for
this,'' says Mahdy, 22, a member of the American University of
Cairo's Model Arab League, a diplomatic club similar to a model
United Nations program. ``Ink on paper is good, but it has to be
implemented ... It might be only by the time we're almost dead that
we see something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   This amateur diplomat looks on skeptically as the old pro
diplomats, including U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
meet here Thursday with the chance of signing a new memorandum
outlining the next steps in the long-delayed Oslo process.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting comes in the same month 21 years ago that President
Jimmy Carter hosted the Camp David negotiations, in which Egypt,
the largest Arab country with 66 million people, became the first
Arab nation to make peace with Israel. The agreement returned the
Sinai Peninsula to Egypt, but the legacy of Camp David looms large
over Thursday's meeting and a peace process many Egyptians feel has
let them down, mainly because Palestinians, who many Egyptians call
``Arab brothers,'' are still without a state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Egypt's status in the world is very much determined by its
ability to influence the peace process,'' said political columnist
Mohamed Sid-Ahmed. ``Egypt wants to prove that it was right to
follow the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many call the peace treaty with Israel the ``pharaoh's
peace,'' a reference to former President Anwar Sadat, who made the
deal in 1979. He sprung it on his people and fellow Arab leaders
shunned him. Barely any Arab leaders attended Sadat's funeral after
he was slain by a militant group opposed to the peace process in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   His successor, Hosni Mubarak will host Albright Thursday.
Mubarak has stressed that Arabs need to be patient with Israel's
new Prime Minister Ehud Barak. He has pressured fellow Arab leader
Yasser Arafat to be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak is sure to win his fourth term in office later in
September in a referendum vote, but a signing ceremony Thursday
could inject some enthusiasm into the vote.
</P>
<P>
   It is an indication of the Egyptian anxiety over Israel that
Mubarak, now in office 18 years, has only gone next door to visit
Israel once, to attend the funeral of slain Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian press regularly warns of Israeli conspiracies. The
latest accused the Egyptian agriculture minister of being an
Israeli agent because he was letting Egyptian farmers train in
Israel and use Israeli seeds.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   A popular movie in Cairo is, ``The Girl from Israel,'' the story
of a seductress sent to undermine Egyptian values. Though many
Israelis vacation at Sinai beach resorts, few Egyptians venture
into Israel and many that do face scrutiny and harassment from
Egyptian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Trade between Egypt and Israel is minimal and Egypt still lags
behind in key indicators _ per capita income in Egypt in 1997 was
about $4,400 compared to $17,500 in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian newspapers Wednesday warned that hope of a signing
Thursday should be tempered with the consideration, as one
columnist noted, that ``even Albright herself cannot guarantee that
Barak will keep his commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy and educated students at AUC are not typical of all
Egyptians, most of whom are preoccupied with making a living. But,
Mahdy is typical of many who feel that the principles their country
envisioned in peace have not been fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, the Camp David agreement called for a five-year
period before autonomy would be granted to Palestinians. That
autonomy has developed slowly and fallen short of the statehood
they still seek.
</P>
<P>
   When Mahdy hears Albright and other diplomats speak of their
goal for a ``comprehensive peace'' in the region within a couple
years, she worries it will be just a forced deal favoring Israel
and papering over the injustices to the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in her Model Arab League training she learns that
countries act for their interests and, ultimately, peace is in the
interest of all the parties. She thinks it might take a generation,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as optimistic as you're going to get,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
