<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indecisive? Printing 101
</P>
<P>
   Q. If I've sent files from my Mac to the printer, how do I stop
one from printing?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you have the Background Printing feature enabled on your
Macintosh (it's the default setting for the printer drivers in
newer versions of the operating system), all the files wait their
turn for the printer. The printer keeps these jobs in its buffer
until it is ready to deal with them. That is sometimes called
spooling. (Spool is short for simultaneous peripheral operations on
line.
</P>
<P>
   To get to the files waiting to print, double-click on the
printer icon on your desktop (if you have a version of the Mac OS
that uses the Desktop Printers function). A window will pop up and
show you the documents waiting to be printed. You can click on the
job you do not want to print and then click on the trash-can icon
to delete the file from the printer's to-do list. (This doesn't
delete the actual file.) If you have a Mac with older system
software that doesn't use Desktop Printers, you can delete jobs
with the system's Print Monitor utility, found in the Applications
menu (on the right side of the menu bar) when you are printing.
</P>
<P>
   For Windows users, click on the Printer icon in the lower right
corner of your Taskbar. A list of all files that are waiting to
print should pop up. Highlight the file you wish to stop and click
on Cancel Printing from the Document menu.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
