<HEADLINE>
ELECTRIC `GOLF CART' MAKES IT'S DEBUT ON STREETS OF SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco store is marketing a
neighborhood electric vehicle, or NEV, part of a fleet of electric
bikes, scooters and skateboards being billed as clean and efficient
way to get around town.
</P>
<P>
   The NEVs, manufactured in Fargo, N.D., are allowed on the
streets because of recent federal regulations that allow low-speed
electric vehicles to travel any city street that has a 35 mph or
slower speed limit, said Gary Starr, the managing director of the
ZAPworld.com store in the Fisherman's Wharf section of the city.
ZAP stands for zero air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't be cruising the Golden Gate Bridge with them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco City Administrator Bill Lee, who has been testing
electric and compressed cars for use by city workers, said he was
taking a ``wait and see'' approach before encouraging the
widespread use and rental of the three electric cars that can best
be described as beefed-up golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some issues with how long they can go between
charges, rental costs and other things,'' Lee said. ``But I think,
all in all, they're a good thing for San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said the cars, which were tested for the last two weeks on
city streets, have been a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were trying to rent them while we were just setting
them up on the street,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The open-air cars, which cost $100 per day to rent, offer a
double tour of San Francisco, Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to see a great city while meeting its people,'' Starr
said. ``That's because they're real people magnets.''
</P>
<P>
   The car has a top speed of 30 mph and has a 30-mile range with
each charge. The four-seat NEV sells for $9,500.
</P>
</TEXT>
