<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIPPING AWAY WITH COLD CHISELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cold chisels are used to cut through hard materials like metal
or masonry. They are often used to cut or shape metal when the
stock is thick and where other tools, like a hacksaw or tin snips,
would be unsuitable. The striking end of the cold chisel is
chamfered to reduce mushrooming and burring caused by constant
hammering.
</P>
<P>
   Cold chisels are designed to be struck with a hammer; either a
machinist's hammer (often called a ball-peen hammer) or a small
sledgehammer (sometimes called a club hammer). Always wear heavy
gloves and safety goggles when working with cold chisels.
</P>
<P>
   The four most useful shapes for cold chisels are the flat
chisel, cape chisel, round-nose chisel and the diamond-point
chisel.
</P>
<P>
   The flat chisel has a flat, wedge-shaped cutting edge that is
ground on both sides to a 60-degree angle. The chisel is hand held
by wrapping the fingers around the shaft with the thumb overlapping
the index finger. To cut sheet or plate metal with a flat cold
chisel, first clamp the work in a vise. Hold the chisel at a
45-degree angle from the face of the metal, with the bottom bevel
of the cutting edge resting on the top of the vise. Drive the
chisel with a hammer, using a series of even blows, to cut through
the metal. The cut should be made close to the vise jaws. Smooth
the cut edge with a metal file.
</P>
<P>
   To cut round stock, like a rod or a chain link, place the work
on a firm, hard support, like an anvil or a thick piece of flat
steel. If possible, secure the work with a clamp to keep it from
flying away should you direct a glancing blow. Use a triangular
file to mark the cutting line on the stock. Hold the chisel
vertically on the line and strike it with a hammer. Cut halfway
through the piece, then flip it over and cut from the other side.
</P>
<P>
   To make cutouts in sheet metal, first scribe the perimeter of
the cutout on the surface. Then drill a series of overlapping holes
within the outline. The holes should remove enough material from
inside the cutout so you can clean up the edges with a chisel. To
do this, hold the chisel vertically and strike it with a hammer.
Smooth the edges with a file.
</P>
<P>
   You can also use a flat cold chisel to shear off rivets.
Position the chisel at a 45-degree angle against the rivet head.
The bottom bevel of the cutting edge should rest on surface of the
surrounding material. Drive the chisel against the rivet with a
hammer.
</P>
<P>
   The same technique works well with small bolts. For thick bolts,
it may be easier to first split the bolt head. Hold the chisel
vertically over the center of the head and strike with the hammer.
Then shear off each side with the technique just described.
</P>
<P>
   The cape chisel has a thin cutting edge on a wedge-shaped head.
The wedge shape provides extra support for the narrow cutting bit.
Cape chisels are used to cut narrow slots in metal or masonry.
Machinists also use the cape chisel to lock nuts and bolts so they
will not loosen. The technique is simple: the nut is threaded onto
the bolt and tightened with a wrench. The machinist uses the cape
chisel to strike the threads above the nut. This distorts the
threads so the nut cannot work loose. The only way to remove the
nut is by splitting it with a flat chisel.
</P>
<P>
   The round-nose chisel is similar to the cape chisel, but the
cutting edge has a semicircular shape. It is used to cut round
grooves. Round grooves are often cut in bearings for oil channels.
The diamond point chisel has a tapered four-sided cutting bit. It
is used to clear out material in corners and for cutting
V-channels.
</P>
<P>
   While you can use a cold chisel for masonry work, it is easier
to cut into stone, concrete or brick with chisels especially
designed for that purpose. Some mason's chisels, like the brick
chisel (also called a brick bolster), have wide spade bits so you
can chop a brick evenly in half. Another chisel similar in
appearance to the brick chisel is a mason's bolster. It has a wide
flat head and a long handle. Use this chisel to smooth flat stone
surfaces and remove peaks.
</P>
<P>
   For making round holes in concrete or stone, use a star drill.
This tool has a long hexagonal handle, and a cutting bit is in the
shape of a cross or four- pointed star. To drill a hole, hold the
tool vertically and strike with a small sledgehammer. Turn the
drill a quarter turn with each blow, and occasionally stop to blow
the dust and debris from the hole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
