<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7332 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FALLBOOKS-1000(3Takes     09-01 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLBOOKS-1000(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`'TIS' THE SEASON OF NONFICTION AS THE FINAL CHAPTER OF THE 1900S
DRAWS NEAR
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by FALL BOOKS-OTHERS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   'Tis the season when the so-called fall books begin arriving on
bookstore shelves, which this year means essentially that 'tis the
season of `` 'Tis.''
</P>
<P>
   The second installment of New York City
schoolteacher-turned-memoirist Frank McCourt's life story, ``
'Tis'' (Scribner, $28), will go on sale late this month. When it
does, it will instantly rocket to the top of the nonfiction
bestseller list, with just about every one of its 500,000
first-printing copies snapped up by the same readers who made
McCourt's ``Angela's Ashes'' an unexpected, runaway bestseller two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then about a month into 2000, `` 'Tis'' probably will be
nominated for all the same prizes ``Angela's Ashes'' vied for, and
might even equal its predecessor by copping the Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the literary smoke clears by the end of the Christmas
shopping season, `` 'Tis'' will probably be the book that was most
talked about, sought and bought.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Tis'' is the centerpiece of a fall that features nonfiction.
Fans of novels will get their literary fix, but overwhelmingly _ in
number and promotional dollars _ publishers are betting that more
bookstore browsers will prefer real to made-up. It comes down to
the kind of book that publishers believe will sell the best, and
nonfiction wins handily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fall is the toughest, most competitive season,'' says Sally
Richardson, a senior editor at St. Martin's Press. ``We publishers
all try to put our biggest books by our biggest names out there,
and, in fiction, there just aren't that many big names.''
</P>
<P>
   The publishers' preference for nonfiction is obvious to Michael
Rosenberg, who operates a literary agency in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishers believe nonfiction has a clearly defined potential
market,'' he says. ``The subject of a nonfiction book tells them
exactly who they will be selling it to. The market for literary
fiction is much less defined.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishers are more likely to offer fiction during the summer,
when consumers want light fare suitable for reading on airplanes
and under beach umbrellas. Novels generally cost consumers less,
too, because publishers often have to pay heftier advances to
nonfiction writers who require money for extensive research.
</P>
<P>
   But during the Christmas season, publishers believe, the price
of a book is not as important to shoppers. In July, an adult
already paying a significant amount for the family vacation may
consider $25 to be his or her maximum price for a 200-page,
read-on-the-run thriller. But in November, spending $35 for a
weighty, 600-page nonfiction tome to be savored during the winter
months or to be given as a gift does not seem as extravagant.
</P>
<P>
   Famous novelists are represented on the fall '99 list. But with
Patricia Cornwell, Thomas Harris, John Grisham and Mary Higgins
Clark just published this summer, there aren't many left to offer
new titles from September through December.
</P>
<P>
   About 20,000 books will be published between now and Christmas.
Because no list can adequately catalog all of them, we look at 20
titles that are of special interest.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1. `` 'Tis: A Memoir'' by Frank McCourt (Scribner, $28,
September) _ The subject matter: This picks up where ``Angela's
Ashes'' left off, mostly chronicling McCourt's experiences as a New
York schoolteacher and including some outrageous tales of his
misadventures after marriage. The buzz: No one wonders whether this
book will be a bestseller, especially since it is not necessary to
have first read ``Angela's Ashes'' before diving into this second
installment. The prediction: Pulitzer judges may honor McCourt a
second time. He is a bard in the finest tradition of engaging,
roguish Irish storytellers.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Daughter of Fortune,'' by Isabelle Allende (HarperCollins,
$26, October) _ The plot: A young Chilean woman finds and loses
love during the California gold rush, but this novel focuses more
on fiction than fact. Think of ``Gone With the Wind,'' which used
the Civil War as a backdrop for made-up characters. The buzz: Early
reviews are mixed; Allende has been praised in the past for the
complexity of her stories, but she may have burned out her audience
in the process. The prediction: The book will prove to be a
critical and sales disappointment, although Allende's hard-core
fans will probably love it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Hitler's Pope: The Secret History of Pius XII,'' by John
Cornwell (Viking, $29.95, October) _ The subject matter: Historian
Cornwell argues that, during World War II, the Vatican was a covert
ally of Hitler. The buzz: Some publishers have shied away from
similar books, fearing a backlash from Catholics and/or the Holy
See. That means Cornwell has to present a solid, near-unshakable
case. The prediction: Modest but respectable sales that might reach
the lower rungs of the bestseller lists. Critical acclaim is almost
a given.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban,'' by J.K. Rowling
(Scholastic, $19.95, September) _ The plot: The third installment
of this wildly successful children's series finds gawky apprentice
Harry hanging around incarcerated wizards. The buzz: A month before
publication, ``Prisoner'' is No. 1 on Amazon.com's sales list
(ordered in advance). But the first two books had a certain
sameness, and it seems unlikely that Harry's momentum can sustain
many more runaway bestsellers. The prediction: Pottermania will
wane in 2000; but ``Prisoner'' is being published in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' by Edmund Morris
(Random House, $35, September) _ The subject matter: Random House
promises the definitive life of our former president. The buzz:
Morris has been working on this book for 13 years, so Random House
expects that it's going to be really good. It better be. The
prediction: ``Dutch'' will be a critical and sales success, and may
edge `` 'Tis'' for the various nonfiction awards.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   6. ``A Little More About Me,'' by Pam Houston (Norton, $23.95,
October) _ The plot: Norton gathers a dozen first-person Houston
stories that previously appeared in magazines. The buzz: Houston's
first two books, also collections of short stories, got critical
raves but didn't sell. Now Norton is promoting ``A Little More
About Me'' as the ``real'' Pam Houston, although she prefers the
promotional emphasis to be on her fiction. The prediction: Even
Houston's laundry lists would be interesting to read. ``A Little
More About Me'' may hook the public into reading more of her short
stories.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   7. ``The Alibi,'' by Sandra Brown (Warner, $25.95, due in stores
Wednesday) _ The plot: A prosecuting attorney tries to solve the
murder of a local businessman. The prime suspect is a woman whom
the prosecutor met and slept with on the night of the murder. The
buzz: Fort Worth homegirl Brown has written more than 60 books, and
more than half of those have made bestseller lists. Her legions of
readers are devoted. The prediction: After ``The Alibi'' is a
bestseller, it'll be turned into a TV miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Hillary's Choice,'' by Gail Sheehy (Morrow, $21.95,
September) _ The subject matter: Why the first lady stays with her
husband. The buzz: Sheehy's understanding of, if not sympathy for,
Hillary is said to drip from every page. Hillary-haters will
probably call it propaganda. The prediction: The author of
``Passages'' has enough fans to make this a bestseller.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Eddie's Bastard,'' by William Kowalski (HarperCollins, $24,
October) _ The plot: A grieving father finds a baby abandoned on
his doorstep; the child turns out to be his grandchild. The buzz:
If HarperCollins is publishing a first novel in the fall, the
company's brain trust must believe it is special. It will promote
``Eddie's Bastard'' for all it's worth. The prediction: Remember
Charles Frazier and ``Cold Mountain''? Karla Kuban and
``Marchlands''? Every once in a while a new novelist emerges from
obscurity, and this may be Kowalski's turn.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Walter Benjamin at the Dairy Queen: Reflections at Sixty
and Beyond,'' by Larry McMurtry (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $21, November) _
The subject matter: McMurtry offers essays on middle, maybe even
old, age. The buzz: The author is rumored to be tired of fiction;
his heart bypass surgery made him more conscious of his mortality;
and he is determined to write about his life. The prediction:
Readers love McMurtry, but they love Gus and Call and Danny Deck
and his fictional casts so much more. Self-indulgence may be
tolerated this once, but 2000 will see McMurtry back writing
novels.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   11. ``Big Trouble,'' by Dave Barry (Putnam, $23.95, September) _
The plot: It's far too convoluted to recount. All sorts of wacky
bad guys have weird things happen to them when hit men invade
Coconut Grove. The buzz: This is Barry's first attempt at a
full-length book. His last few collections of humorous columns have
not sold very well, so ``Big Trouble'' is an attempt to freshen his
approach and recapture his audience. The prediction: The book ought
to be successful; book-length Barry is much better and funnier than
most would have expected.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   12. ``Joe DiMaggio: The Hero's Life,'' by Richard Ben Cramer
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $27.50, September) _ The subject matter: For the
first time, an eminent historian tries to recount the life of the
intensely private, recently deceased Yankee Clipper. The buzz:
Cramer's ``What It Takes'' is still considered by many the
definitive recounting of a modern presidential campaign. This book
will be reviewed by every major print publication, and you won't be
able to read any mainstream magazines without finding it mentioned
somewhere. The prediction: If ``The Hero's Life'' is half as good
as ``What It Takes,'' it will be one of the best books published
this year.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   13. ``A Star Called Henry,'' by Roddy Doyle (Viking, $23.95,
September) _ The plot: A fictional Irish boy experiences his
nation's upheavals in the 1910s and '20s. The buzz: Doyle has been
a novelist with a gold-plated reputation and mediocre sales. Viking
must be wondering what it will take to make him a bestseller. The
prediction: ``A Star Called Henry'' may inch onto the bestseller
list, riding the coattails of `` 'Tis'' in an Irish-themed fall.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   14. ``The Roots Run Deep,'' by J.C. Watts (HarperCollins, $25,
October) _ The subject matter: The University of Oklahoma
quarterback-turned-Republican-congressman tells his life story. The
buzz: Political conservatives buy books in droves; witness the
sales, if not literary success, of Dan Quayle, Newt Gingrich and
Rush Limbaugh. Watts will appeal to that market. The prediction:
Solid sales that will reach bestseller proportions if Watts emerges
as a possible vice-presidential nominee on the 2000 Republican
national ticket.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   15. ``The Way We Lived Then: Recollections of a Well-Known
Name-Dropper,'' by Dominick Dunne (Crown, $27.50, September) _ The
subject matter: Dunne dishes on his experiences as a Hollywood
producer, with humorous emphasis on the downs instead of the ups.
The buzz: Stars love being mentioned in print by Dunne, and he
loves mentioning them. From People to Newsweek, all the slick
magazines will plug ``The Way We Lived Then.'' The prediction: Good
sales and good gossip from the man everybody wants sitting next to
them at a dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   16. ``Life Stories,'' by Jewel (HarperCollins, $23.95,
September) _ The subject matter: The waifish singer tells about her
short, eventful life. The buzz: It's awful, embarrassing and poorly
written, but so was ``Night Without Armor,'' Jewel's collection of
poetry, and that was a bestseller. The prediction: Around
Christmas, when excellent-but-relatively-unknown writers gripe
about talentless celebrities hogging the bestseller limelight with
their self-indulgent tripe, they'll be talking about Jewel and
``Life Stories.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   17. ``The Voyage,'' by Philip Caputo (Knopf, $26, November) _
The plot: As the 1900s draw to a close, the Braithwaite family of
Maine struggles to understand the events at the start of the
century. The buzz: Caputo is regarded by critics as one of
America's finest novelists. His Vietnam epic, ``A Rumor of War,''
is especially admired. But mainstream readers have never caught on,
and ``The Voyage'' is expected to be another of his books that is
critically acclaimed but doesn't sell well. The prediction: Better
late than never. With so little to entice devotees of fiction this
fall, ``The Voyage'' just might get Caputo the attention he
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   18. ``Peel My Love Like an Onion,'' by Ana Castillo (Doubleday,
$23.95, October) _ The plot: ``La Coja,'' a famous flamenco dancer
in Chicago, has succeeded despite a crippled leg, the result of a
childhood bout with polio. She suddenly finds herself at the center
of a romantic triangle, with her troupe director and his grandson.
The buzz: Castillo gained national attention for ``So Far From
God,'' her last novel. Doubleday is launching a huge national
publicity campaign to make ``Peel My Love'' a bestseller. The
prediction: If Oprah comes calling with a Book Club selection,
everyone will know someone who bought ``Peel My Love.'' Otherwise,
Castillo remains a good writer with a small audience.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   19. ``The Great Shame,'' by Thomas Keneally (Doubleday, $35,
September) _ The subject matter: Eloquent nonfiction about
19th-century Ireland, when the embattled nation lost 50 percent of
its population. The buzz: This one's a slam-dunk; even if ``The
Great Shame'' were bad _ which it isn't _ it would ride
``Schindler's List's'' reputation onto the bestseller list. ``The
prediction: `` 'Tis,'' ``A Star Called Henry'' and ``The Great
Shame'' make the last book cycle of the 1900s an Irish-dominated
one.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   20. ``The Phantom of Manhattan,'' by Frederick Forsyth (St.
Martin's, $19.95, November) _ The plot: What happened to the
Phantom after that great opera house in Paris burned down? Did Erik
and Christine ever get back together, and where? The buzz:
Forsyth's usual publisher refused to print ``Phantom,'' claiming
fans of the author's spy novels wouldn't be interested in another
kind of story. If ``The Phantom of Manhattan'' flops, Forsyth
probably will never have a non-espionage novel published again. The
prediction: There are enough fans of the Andrew Lloyd Webber
musical to push this book onto the bestseller list, but probably
only to the lowest (15th to 25th) rungs. Jeff Guinn,(817) 390-7720
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can e-mail him at: jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
