<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHILLFACTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BOMB GETS A CHILLY RECEPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Cuba Gooding Jr. doesn't start making better movie choices,
he might just have to return that Best Supporting Actor Oscar
statue.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, those Pepsi One commercials alone were grounds enough
for disqualification, but after Gooding's forgettable turns in
celluloid stinkers such as ``What Dreams May Come, Instinct'' and
the direct-to-video ``A Murder of Crows,'' that statuette is
starting to look more and more like a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   His credibility gets no help from the lame actioner ``Chill
Factor.''
</P>
<P>
   As Arlo, an ice-cream-truck driver caught up in a web of murder,
terrorism and international arms dealing, Gooding returns to his
familiar bag of tricks: high-speed, high-volume jabbering at the
expense of actually saying anything.
</P>
<P>
   Not that his co-star offers much help. Skeet Ulrich _ think
Johnny Depp, except made out of wood _ is a sullen drifter who
finally settles down, slinging hash in a small-town greasy spoon.
His fishing buddy (David Paymer) is a secretive doctor who works at
the nearby military base. When the doc stumbles in, gut-shot and
bleeding, clutching a metal canister and raving about a lethal
defoliant that explodes once its temperature reaches 50 degrees,
Ulrich hijacks Gooding and his ice-cream truck before the shooters
track them down.
</P>
<P>
   Seems the stuff in the canister not only snuffs out all plant
life in a 100-mile radius, it also turns any humans in the area
into steaming piles of goo. In other words, it'd be a really nifty
weapon if it fell into the wrong hands. In this case, those hands
belong to Peter Firth as a disgraced Army major who crossed to the
dark side after being imprisoned when an early experiment with the
defoliant wiped out his entire platoon.
</P>
<P>
   All the standard action plot devices are here: The
character-flawed good guys barely tolerate each other but learn to
be friends; the bad guy's inherent evil outweighs his common sense;
the naughty henchmen are easily dispatched, despite being trained
killers; and the bomb comes close to detonating half a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   None of the performances is worth mentioning. Even Paymer, who's
always competent even in undemanding roles, walks through his bit
part as the guilt-ridden scientist. And Firth's performance is
steeped in such monotone villainy that Steven Seagal might as well
have played it.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness the bomb effects are cool, but it's too bad it
couldn't disintegrate more of this movie.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Chill Factor''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Hugh Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Cuba Gooding Jr., Skeet Ulrich
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ profanity, graphic violence and adult subject matter
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
