<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Video mini reviews
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera and Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Party Monster'' (unrated) _ New York, the club scene,
mid-'80s. Weird, man. How weird? These so-called club kids _ young,
partying, fame-seeking hedonists whose only talents were outsize
amounts of self-promotion and self-destruction _ became regulars on
``Geraldo.'' In this rivetingly grotesque documentary, Michael Alig
was the biggest no-reason star of all. A gay kid from small-town
Indiana, Alig fled to New York for his 15 minutes of fame and wound
up serving 10 to 20 for the bizarre murder of his roommate. ``Party
Monster,'' which first made waves at the Sundance Film Festival,
traces with a coolly intimate eye the steady, drug-happy unwinding
of Alig from gory ironist to gory killer. Alig and his flamboyantly
misfit crew were so self-absorbed they seemed to videotape and
record almost their every move, giving ``Party Monster'' an eerie,
home-movie air of macabre inevitability. When a fellow club kid
recounts the depths of Alig's awfulness and then giggles to an
unseen interviewer, ``Did I just destroy the whole point of your
documentary?'' he doesn't realize that he's only enhanced it.
Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _Drew Jubera
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dracula'' (unrated) _ This re-release of the classic 1931
Bela Lugosi film comes with a new sound: an original score by
Philip Glass, performed by the Kronos Quartet. Whether you like his
music or not, Glass' repetitive score lends a hypnotic urgency to
the movie that its earlier, creakily quiet incarnation lacked.
Sugested price, $14.98. Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   THE VIDEO COLLECTOR
</P>
