<HEADER>
A7344 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-ALTERNATIVE02-C     09-01 0297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ALTERNATIVE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flawless harmonies lift Ronstadt-Harris outing
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you bought February's ``Trio II,'' the superb CD that paired
Linda Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris with Dolly Parton, keep this in
mind: ``Western Wall'' isn't an encore performance. The songs here
are much more experimental and introspective, sparsely produced and
virtually country-free. Most are ballads featuring Ronstadt on lead
vocals, with Harris weaving in haunting harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Without Parton's smoky mountain soprano, however, Harris and
Ronstadt sound much more like a folkie, coffeehouse duo trying out
material on songwriter's night. They've drawn from a who's who of
tunesmiths _ Patty Griffin, Sinead O'Connor, Rosanne Cash, Bruce
Springsteen, Jackson Browne _ and almost self-consciously strive to
make sure nothing is predictable. ``Falling Down'' is layered over
the heart-monitor repetition of a thumping bass. There's a very
long and tedious story song called ``1917'' that's ``The Wreck of
the Edmund Fitzgerald'' on slow speed. Harris/Ronstadt's cover of
Leonard Cohen's ``Sister of Mercy'' is wrapped around a happy
sailor accordion straight out of an Old Spice jingle.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the vocals are flawless. The duo deserves extra
credit for being bold enough to experiment. But Dolly would have
made this often coldly ethereal outing a bit more down-to-earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Western Wall:
</P>
<P>
   The Tucson Sessions''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ronstadt and Emmylou
</P>
<P>
   Harris. Asylum Records. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris perform Oct. 3 at Symphony
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
