<HEADER>
A7345 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS02-COX     09-01 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Mock Tudor''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Thompson. Capital. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to take Richard Thompson for granted. From his days
with the early-1970s folk-rock troupe Fairport Convention through
his collaborations with former wife Linda Thompson and his solo
career, the London-born guitarist and vocalist has produced such a
consistently stellar body of work that critical praise has become
routine. That's a blessing and a curse _ fans expect him to be
brilliant, and as such he's lost the ability to surprise. ``Mock
Tudor,'' a top-notch collection of muscular, fervently delivered
tunes, will delight many but astonish no one familiar with
Thompson's melancholy-folkie croon, deft guitar playing and
pointed, pessimistic lyrics. As usual, Thompson paints vivid
portraits of fractured relationships (``Dry My Tears and Move
On''), emotional duplicity (``Two-Faced Love'') and wounded
romantics (``Crawl Back Under My Stone''). He's in fine form _ if
only we could listen with new ears.
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Violator: The Album''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Violator/Def Jam. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   What a shame that one of hip-hop's best summer songs arrives not
only at the tail end of the season, but amid such poor company.
Q-Tip's first single away from the oft-touted ``thinking fan's rap
group,'' A Tribe Called Quest, is a clever tale about a
relationship going right that glides along a rubbery bass and
cymbals. Even better, ``Vivrant Thing'' is the first track on this
big-name (LL Cool J, Busta Rhymes, Noreaga) compilation wrangled
together by the successful Violator Records/Management Company.
That means you don't have to bother with the rest of this
well-produced but spotty effort, which suffers from serious hook
deprivation.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton and Sonia Murray write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
