<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-WISHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THOSE WITH WANDERLUST, DRAW UP A WISH LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's on your travel wish list? If you're like me, you keep
such a list in the back of your mind, a roster of wanderlust
fantasies and yearnings.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago in this space, Tony Wheeler shared the
contents of his travel wish list. You may not have heard of
Wheeler, but you almost certainly use his books. Along with his
wife, Maureen, Wheeler is the founder of Lonely Planet, the
astonishingly successful guidebook series that has changed the way
we all travel. From its first book, produced on a kitchen table in
1972, Lonely Planet has grown to the point where it now covers
virtually every inch of the globe, with more than 400 titles in
print.
</P>
<P>
   As befits a man who, as a small boy, asked Santa Claus for a
globe and a filing cabinet, Wheeler doesn't keep his list in his
head. He used to carry it with him at all times in a small diary;
now he keeps it in a little electronic Palm Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler has the money, the freedom and the savviness to travel
just about anywhere he desires, for any length of time, in any
style. It was a little surprising, therefore, to see how
unpretentious and accessible his wish list was.
</P>
<P>
   What also impressed me was the way he was methodically ticking
off the items. There were 15 dream trips on Wheeler's list, and at
the time he'd done five of them.
</P>
<P>
   I ran into Wheeler in Corte Madera last weekend at the Book
Passage Travel Writing Conference and asked him how many more dream
trips he'd crossed off his list. In the two years he's done four
more _ so many that he'll finish them all well before his 60th
birthday. He's already composed a new list.
</P>
<P>
   These are the trips he's already crossed off his list:
</P>
<P>
   1. Visit Angkor Wat, the ancient temple complex in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   (1992).
</P>
<P>
   2. Drive the Birdsville Track, a four-wheel-drive trip across
the Simpson Desert in the Australian outback. (1993).
</P>
<P>
   3. Drive across America in a Cadillac. (1994).
</P>
<P>
   4. Walk Mont Blanc Circuit, a hiking trip around the highest
peak in the Alps. (1995).
</P>
<P>
   5. Buy a Ferrari. Not travel per se, but transportation. Hey,
the guy can afford it. (1993).
</P>
<P>
   6. Walk the Milford Track, a four-day journey on the South
Island of New Zealand. (1997).
</P>
<P>
   7. Visit Damascus, Syria. (1999).
</P>
<P>
   8. Visit Lhasa, Tibet. (1999).
</P>
<P>
   9. Walk around Mount Kailash, a sacred peak in Tibet that is the
goal of devout Buddhist pilgrims. (1999).
</P>
<P>
   The remaining trips on his original list:
</P>
<P>
   10. Dive the Truk Lagoon in Micronesia.
</P>
<P>
   11. Walk across Hinchinbrook Island, off east coast of
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   12. Drive the Karakorum Highway between Kashgar, in western
China and Islamabad, in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   13. Cross Russia on the Trans-Siberian Express.
</P>
<P>
   14. Walk the Annapurna Circuit, Nepal's most popular long trek.
</P>
<P>
   15. Drive the Gunbarrel Highway, west of Ayer's Rock in the
Australian outback.
</P>
<P>
   When he's finished the last of these, Wheeler has a new list
ready to go:
</P>
<P>
   1. Visit Alaska. (``I've never been there!'' he says, a little
surprised with himself. ``I'd love to do the Inside Passage.'')
</P>
<P>
   2. Visit the Marquesas aboard the Aranui freighter.
</P>
<P>
   3. Dive the Yongala shipwreck off Townsville, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   4. Drive across Spain.
</P>
<P>
   5. Visit the Falkand Islands.
</P>
<P>
   6. Tour Kakadu National Park at the top of Australia, where
``Crocodile Dundee'' was filmed.
</P>
<P>
   7. Take an opera tour to Verona, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   8. Venice. (``I've only been there on day trips. I'd really like
to spend a couple of nights.'')
</P>
<P>
   9. Timbuktu. (``The name alone conjures up all sorts of exotic
images.'')
</P>
<P>
   10. Ethiopia/Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   11. Yemen. (``With all those kidnapping stories recently, the
newspapers were calling me up for a comment, and it was
embarrassing to say I'd never been there. So I put it on the
list.'')
</P>
<P>
   12. Walk the pilgrimage route to Santiago de Compostela, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   13. Montana.
</P>
<P>
   14. Tour India by Enfield motorcycle. (``In India they're still
making new versions of this great mid-'50s British motorcycle, and
it would be great fun to tour the country on one.'')
</P>
<P>
   15. Visit Leptis Magna in Libya. (``They say it's the best Roman
ruins in the world.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
