<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ROCK02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Babe' invasion: Her voice gives Aguilera an edge
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fodder for the next ``X-Files'' episode: A top-secret ``babe''
factory where a vaguely sinister elite manufacture innocently cute
yet suspiciously sexy pubescent entertainers programmed to sell
millions of CDs. Guest stars: Dianne Warren and Carson Daly.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it could happen. Maybe it already has.
</P>
<P>
   The debut of 18-year-old Christina Aguilera, a former
Mouseketeer with a fashionable Hispanic surname and a hairdo
straight out of ``Melrose Place,'' points to such conspiracy. Heir
apparent to Britney Spears' chart dominance, this pouty nymphet
rose to MTV ubiquity touting herself as a ``Genie in a Bottle'' _
one whose vow of chastity could be repealed by someone who knows
how to ``rub me the right way.'' The tune's maybe-yes, maybe-no
tease and rap-tinged R&AMP;B pulse owes a big debt to TLC, the
Atlanta-based trio whose gift is projecting individuality within
clearly regulated formula.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an appealing voice that evokes ``How Will I Know?''-era
Whitney Houston, Aguilera hits the marks without conveying a unique
persona. But, as baby divas go, she's got promise. Vocally, she's
worth at least 2 1/2 Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christina Aguilera''
</P>
<P>
   Christina Aguilera. RCA/BMG. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
