A7351 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP02-COX     09-01 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vary flavors of liqueur in Mexico treat
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Melinda Gwitt ate a piece of Tres Leches dessert from a
Mexican grocery store in Atlanta, she wanted to try to duplicate it
at home and e-mailed a recipe request.
</P>
<P>
   This one is from Canyon Cafe, which baked it as a special
Mother's Day treat in May. The restaurant uses Captain Morgan
Spiced Rum as a flavoring and tops it with fresh berries. You can
vary the taste with almost any liqueur or extract (our tester liked
it with Kahlua) and other fresh fruits.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Tres Leches
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sweetened condensed milk, chilled
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup whole evaporated milk, chilled
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Captain Morgan Spiced Rum or a flavored liqueur such as
banana, orange or coffee
</P>
<P>
   6 cups fresh berries
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Beat egg whites in large bowl until
soft peaks form. With a mixer, beat egg yolks and sugar until light
and lemony in color. Add oil to yolks and slowly mix in the flour
until all is incorporated. Lighten the yolk batter by mixing in a
scoop of egg whites. Fold the lightened batter into the remaining
egg whites, taking care not to overmix and deflate them. Butter a
9-by-9-inch glass baking dish and add the batter to the pan. Bake
until lightly browned on top, about 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the oven and allow to cool thoroughly on a rack. Do
not remove cake from this pan unless you are going to serve it from
a different dish.
</P>
<P>
   When cooled, punch holes with a fork all over the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the tres leches (three kinds of milk) with rum or liqueur
and pour over cake. Refrigerate for at least two hours or until the
tres leches have saturated the cake and it is chilled throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Using a large ice cream scoop or serving spoon, scoop and serve
in a wide martini glass or bowl and garnish each portion with some
of the sauce from the pan and half a cup of fresh berries.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Per serving: 395 calories, 8 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 47 grams carbohydrates, 138
milligrams cholesterol, 83 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ellen Hastie of Johnson City, Tenn., wants to replace a lost
recipe for Sloppy Joes that included browned ground beef and a
sauce made of Heinz chile sauce, yellow mustard and Karo syrup. Her
children enjoyed it 25 years ago and now she'd like to make it for
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June Henderson of Alpharetta wants the recipe for meringue
cookies with a beaten egg white base that her family used to call
``white puffy cookies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Barbara Roberts of Atlanta would like a recipe for Punch Bowl
Cake.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shirley Barker of Morrow lost her recipe for Hawaiian Banana
Bread and hopes another reader has one.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mrs. Jessie P. Swain of Decatur wants a recipe for Railroad
Pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
