<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7352 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-WRAPS-RECIPES02-     09-01 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-WRAPS-RECIPES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On a roll: Wrap up a quick, tasty, nutritious meal anytime
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most supermarkets stock tortillas and a few egg roll wrappers _
the basics for wraps. But if you want more exotic selections, check
out Hispanic and Asian markets. There you'll find different sizes
of tortillas as well as myriad spring roll wrappers that range from
about 8 to more than 30 inches in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   While some chain grocery stores occasionally stock flavored
tortillas, they're often difficult to find. We purchased our
sun-dried tomato and spinach tortillas from Bajarito's on Peachtree
Road.
</P>
<P>
   The Hye Rollers were found in the deli department at Kroger in
Crabapple. They're also available at Harry's Farmers' Markets.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Tequila Shrimp Wrap
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings; about 1 cup guacamole
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Set out the tequila shrimp filling and guacamole and let guests
make their own wraps.
</P>
<P>
   For the shrimp filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 orange bell peppers, cut in strips
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons tequila
</P>
<P>
   1 pound small shrimp, peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   For the quick guacamole:
</P>
<P>
   2 Haas avocados, cut in large chunks
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   Few drops green habanero hot sauce
</P>
<P>
   For the shrimp filling: In a medium skillet, heat olive oil over
medium heat. Add the peppers and saute for about 2 minutes, then
add garlic, lime juice and tequila. Saute for 1 minute, then add
shrimp and cook until they turn pink and most of the liquid
evaporates. Remove from heat, season with salt and pepper, then add
cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   For the quick guacamole: Place avocados, lime juice, cilantro,
garlic, salt and hot sauce in the bowl of a food processor. Process
until almost smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without guacamole): 112 calories, 16 grams protein,
4 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 29), 3 grams carbohydrates,
115 milligrams cholesterol, 112 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Guacamole (per tablespoon): 33 calories, less than 1 gram
protein, 3 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 70), 3 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 16 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Sauteed Veggie Wrap
</P>
<P>
   With Yogurt Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings, 1 cup yogurt sauce
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large portobello mushrooms, cut in strips
</P>
<P>
   1 large zucchini, cut in 3-inch-long strips
</P>
<P>
   1 green bell pepper, cut in strips
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, cut in strips
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, thinly sliced lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Pinch dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   Pinch dried dill
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 sun-dried tomato tortillas
</P>
<P>
   For the yogurt sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cucumber, some skin left on, grated
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   For the wraps: In a medium skillet, heat olive oil. Add
mushrooms, zucchini, peppers, onion, garlic, dried herbs and wine.
Saute until vegetables are slightly soft but not mushy, about 5
minutes. Add salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Wrap in sun-dried tomato tortilla and serve with Yogurt Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   For the Yogurt Sauce: Wring grated cucumber in a clean, dry dish
towel to remove excess moisture. In a small bowl, combine cucumber,
yogurt, garlic and lemon juice. Chill about 1 hour before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without yogurt sauce): 221 calories, 6 grams
protein, 6 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 26), 36 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 347 milligrams sodium, 3 grams
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Yogurt sauce (per tablespoon): 10 calories, 1 gram protein, less
than 1 gram fat (percent calories from fat, 42), 1 gram
carbohydrates, 2 milligrams cholesterol, 7 milligrams sodium, trace
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Roll Wrappers With Glazed Chicken and
</P>
<P>
   Shredded Cabbage Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 2 to 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   These rolls can be made earlier in the day or the night before
and kept in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   For the glazed chicken:
</P>
<P>
   2 boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons bottled teriyaki glaze
</P>
<P>
   For the cabbage salad:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon crunchy or plain peanut butter (warm in the
microwave for a few seconds to soften)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup plus 1 tablespoon rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup peanut or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   Few drops hot chile oil, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups finely shredded cabbage
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon toasted slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   For the spring rolls:
</P>
<P>
   8 round spring roll wrappers (soak for a minute or so in warm
water to soften)
</P>
<P>
   1 orange, peeled and cut in sections
</P>
<P>
   16 large Thai basil leaves (available at Asian supermarkets) or
other fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   For the chicken: Brown chicken breasts in oil and cook for about
10 minutes. Lower heat. Add teriyaki glaze and coat chicken,
cooking for about 1 minute more on each side. Remove from heat and
let cool. Slice chicken lengthwise and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the cabbage salad: In a small bowl, whisk together peanut
butter, rice vinegar, orange juice, soy sauce and salt. When
combined, dribble in oils, whisking constantly. Check seasonings.
Place cabbage and almonds in medium bowl. Pour dressing over the
mixture and chill for 2 to 3 hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble rolls: Place a soft wrapper on a clean dish towel
and pat dry. Lay two orange segments lengthwise in the center of
the wrapper, leaving a couple of inches clear on the top and
bottom. Top with a mounded tablespoon of cabbage salad, then place
a strip of chicken and top it with two basil leaves. Fold the top
and bottom flaps first, then fold the right side over and roll
snugly. Chill rolls until serving time.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 264 calories, 17 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 21 grams carbohydrates, 36
milligrams cholesterol, 362 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Hye Roller With Roast Beef
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   These wraps are easily prepared the day before and cut just
before serving. Vary the ingredients by substituting sliced turkey
for the beef or adding grated cheese.
</P>
<P>
   1 sheet Hye Roller Armenian wrap
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces softened cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons horseradish
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces thinly sliced deli roast beef
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh spinach leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 small jar marinated artichoke hearts, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mild pepper rings
</P>
<P>
   1 cup radish sprouts or alfalfa sprouts
</P>
<P>
   Lightly moisten both sides of wrap by sprinkling with a little
water and rubbing it in with your hand. In a small bowl, mix cream
cheese and horseradish. Spread on the wrap. Leaving about a 2-inch
strip on one edge with only the cream cheese mixture to seal it,
layer on the roast beef, spinach, artichoke hearts, peppers and
sprouts. Roll as you would a jellyroll. Wrap in plastic and
refrigerate until serving time. Slice into 1- or 2-inch rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 147 calories, 9 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 43), 14 grams carbohydrates, 28 milligrams
cholesterol, 143 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Hye Roller With Dried Fruit
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 sheet Hye Roller wrap
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces softened cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped mixed dried fruit
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   Lightly moisten both sides of the wrap by sprinkling with a
little water and rubbing it in with your hand. In a small bowl, mix
cream cheese and cinnamon. Spread on the wrap. Leaving about a
2-inch strip on one edge with only the cream cheese mixture on it
to seal, layer on the fruit and nuts. Roll as you would a
jellyroll. Slice into 1- or 2-inch servings.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 213 calories, 5 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 21 grams carbohydrates, 25
milligrams cholesterol, 145 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
