<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7353 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-WRAPS02-COX     09-01 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-WRAPS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let the good times roll with mix-and-match fillings and
tortillas
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While wraps have been the culinary buzz word for several years,
the concept itself is an ancient one. The Chinese have been
wrapping and rolling for centuries _ utilizing everything from
lettuce leaves to rice flour wrappers.
</P>
<P>
   And the French can encase the most pedestrian ingredients in a
lacy crepe, and we call it gourmet. For the Hispanic worker who
carries his midday meal, no utensils are needed. He makes mini
wraps by tearing bite-size bits of tortilla and scooping up rice,
beans and chunks of spicy meats.
</P>
<P>
   Why have we gone wrap crazy? Probably because they provide a
quick meal for those on the go and the combination of fillings _
from the healthy to the decadent _ is limitless. At Bajarito's on
Peachtree Road in Brookhaven, wraps come stuffed with everything
from Thai curry chicken to blackened salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Even kids can join a wrap session. To spice up those school
lunch boxes, consider spreading peanut butter on a flour tortilla,
cut it in half so it's easy to handle, then put some jam in a small
container and let them dip their wrap. Instead of the same old
bread for that tuna salad, give them a tuna wrap using a
whole-wheat tortilla.
</P>
<P>
   Adults might consider throwing a wrap party as a simple,
stress-free way to entertain. Guests help themselves and even fill
their own wraps.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a great way to provide a wide array of flavors for
your company. Even the most finicky diner _ from the vegetarian to
one on a restricted diet _ can combine ingredients to satisfy. Plus
they're easy to handle and leave the host with little mess.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing some of the pre-wrapped selections ahead of time makes
a wrap party even easier.
</P>
<P>
   The Spring Roll Wrappers with Glazed Chicken and Shredded
Cabbage Salad has several steps, but they're still relatively
hassle-free to prepare early in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Hye Rollers, also called caravan sand-
</P>
<P>
   wiches, feature a large, round, flat Armenian bread developed in
a California bakery specifically for rolled or wrapped sandwiches.
In fact, they taste better if made ahead of time so the flavors of
the horseradish-spiked cream cheese, peppers and marinated
artichoke hearts have time to meld. Slice them just before your
guests arrive so they won't dry out.
</P>
<P>
   Tequila Shrimp and Sauteed Veggie fillings use a handful of
ingredients, which can be assembled ahead of time, then quickly
sauteed and set out while your guests mingle. You can make the
accompanying guacamole and yogurt sauce a few hours in advance.
</P>
<P>
   There are no strict rules here, so feel free to mix and match
fillings and wraps. For instance, extra Shredded Cabbage Salad
makes an excellent filling for the flavored tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Note that some of those colorful tortillas are pretty large and
you want your guests to sample a variety of stuffings and wraps. If
you cut them in half, they can be fashioned into cones that provide
perfect containers for those fillings.
</P>
<P>
   So, just set out your favorite beverages, relax and call that
party a wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
