<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7386 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE02-COX     09-01 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bust those blahs by going abroad
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a tough season. Somewhere between summer and fall. Maybe
we should call it ``stall.'' The relentless summer heat and
humidity have taken their toll, leaving us wilted and drained.
Battle weary, we crawl out of air-conditioned bunkers trying to
discern the first taste of cool air that will bring the
invigorating energy of autumn _ and not a moment too soon.
</P>
<P>
   We who cook are called upon to help Mother Nature herald the new
season by infusing our fare with an enthusiasm that brings a
renewed taste for life. It's a culinary challenge though, this
``stall.'' Outdoor fare, barbecue, grilling and salads that were so
fresh and exciting just a short while ago are becoming tiresome and
old, yet it's hardly the time for soups and stews.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps now is the perfect time to consider venturing forth into
uncharted territory, seeing the big picture, going global for an
exciting, positive change.
</P>
<P>
   Surfing the Web for recipes, we know, is a fun and somewhat
addicting pastime. But to zero in on the cuisine of far-flung
places, as we imagine what tastes will emerge from unusual
combinations of foods and spices, might be the most fun of all.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start your quest by visiting the Global Gastronomer at www.cs
</P>
<P>
   .yale.edu/(tilde)hupfer/global/gastronomer.html, just for this
opening quote alone. ``To read ... about a country's cuisine isn't
simply to go looking for `good things'; it is also to better know _
by means of the recipes _ the customs and the richness or poverty
of a place, and the spirit of those who inhabit it. It is, above
all, to participate in the symbolic celebration of the shared
repast.''
</P>
<P>
   What follows, though, is a tad disappointing because some of the
links don't work. The map, which asks you to click on any region of
the world and then doesn't take you there, is especially
disappointing. Still, there are some treasures to be found, like an
Egyptian snack called Foul, which mixes mashed fava beans,
tomatoes, green peppers, green onions, olives (green or black)
salt, pepper and cumin lemon, vinegar and olive oil _ all in
amounts to taste.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Culinary World Tour at www.gumbopages.com
</P>
<P>
   /world-food.html is straightforward, easy to navigate and
delivers authentic recipes from more than a dozen countries.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that Swedes love crawfish? Their signature crawfish
dish, which incidentally contains not a bit of hot stuff, is called
Kraftor and is flavored with dill crowns and anise. For spice you
might consider matching the Kraftor with Lobio, which are the
spice-laden red beans from the republic of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sue's Recipe Server'' at www.hubcom.com/cgi-win
</P>
<P>
   /recipe.exe/1$1$1 serves up recipes from about four times as
many countries as the previous site. There is Prawn Palava made
with onions, tomatoes, ground peanuts, spinach and thyme, from
Sierra Leone; duckling made with rum from Guadalupe; Tomato Tambal,
a dish that pairs tomatoes with cinnamon from Sri Lanka; and from
Portugal, cold stuffed crab made with hard boiled eggs, brandy and
mustard.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The World in Your Kitchen'' at creative-homeliving
</P>
<P>
   .com/worldkitchen/home.stm takes you on a cook's tour of the
world with profiles of cuisines, recipes and links to related
cultural sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Once you figure out how to get around ``International Recipes
on Line'' at eden-backend.rutgers.edu/(tilde)davidg you will be
treated to more than 18,000 submitted by people from all over the
world. Under the heading of appetizers alone, we found 132, from
Afghan kofta (meatballs) to the Neapolitan treat Zeppoli
(doughnuts).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And don't forget to check the mother lode of ethnic recipes at
soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For your reading pleasure see ``The Global Gourmet'' at
www.iagora.com/pages/html/articles/gourmet/index.html for an index
of articles by ``Food Historian-cum-Hedonist'' Corey O'Hara, who
delivers weekly bits of international culinary wisdom and includes
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For an in-depth look at Mediterranean cuisine with some great
recipes, stop by Incredible Edibles at www1.sympatico.ca
</P>
<P>
   /healthyway/HEALTHYWAY/recopa.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  We saved the best for last. You will want to bookmark ``World
Wide Recipes'' at wwrecipes.com, a site that not only puts together
entire themed, gourmet, international menus but will e-mail you an
international recipe a day if you sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Bon voyage.
</P>
<P>
   Eggplant Caviar
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 10-15 minutes
Chilling time: several hours or overnight
</P>
<P>
   This Mediterranean spread can be as bland or as spicy as you
like. Serve it with crackers or bread.
</P>
<P>
   2 medium eggplants (about 2 1/4 pounds), peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canned crushed tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon balsamic vinegar, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers
</P>
<P>
   Few drops hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   In a medium Dutch oven, combine eggplant and water. Cook over
medium heat until tender, 10 to 15 minutes. Drain and mash. Place
in a large mixing bowl. Add tomatoes, paste, garlic, lemon juice,
vinegar, oil, capers, hot sauce, onion and sugar. Chill several
hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4-cup serving: 41 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 3
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 77), 2 grams carbohydrates,
no cholesterol, 36 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
