<HEADER>
A7390 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-POKEMON-NYT &LR;      09-01 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-POKEMON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL THEME PARK WHERE POKEMON ROAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After imitating the Magic Kingdom for years, Nintendo has
finally out-Disneyed Disney. With Pokemon Island, the Japanese
software company has taken the idea of a synthetic, self-contained
tourist environment to its logical extreme.
</P>
<P>
   As the setting for Nintendo's best-selling Pokemon Snap game,
Pokemon Island is a digital theme park where ``wild'' Pokemon roam
``free'' in their ``natural'' habitat. As a young photographer
employed by Professor Oak (who appears elsewhere in Nintendo's
ever-expanding Pokemon universe), it is your job to capture all of
the island's Pokemon species on film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of asking Pokemon trainers to help me,'' he writes
in an introductory letter. ``But I am afraid they would become too
interested in catching the Pokemon on the island. If that happened,
the number of Pokemon on the island would decrease, and Pokemon
Island would lose its value.''
</P>
<P>
   As a precious natural resource, Pokemon biodiversity must be
preserved (as we all know, the creatures are teetering on the brink
of extinction). And because Pokemon Island is such a fragile
ecosystem, you can't really roam around _ your vehicle is either on
rails or floating slowly down a river.
</P>
<P>
   It's less like a National Geographic safari than like a visit to
Pirates of the Caribbean at Disney World, since Pokemon are more or
less animatronic. Strategically planted along a predetermined
route, they are timed to behave adorably within eyeshot of your
hover-buggy.
</P>
<P>
   They're there to pose for you, and they are staggeringly good at
it. Like well-trained babies in television commercials, Pokemon are
hyperbolically cute. As the virtual shutter fires and the motor
drive sound effect kicks in, their antics seem to intensify. You
feel like Austin Powers at a Teletubbies fashion shoot. (``Peek out
from behind the rock. Gorgeous! Show me paws! Yeah, baby!'')
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon Snap may be the first video game whose object is to
document a virtual environment. Instead of accumulating objects,
you accumulate images that are evaluated later, back at the lab,
where Professor Oak rates them for content and composition.
</P>
<P>
   If the subject takes up most of the frame, you get more points.
If it's striking an active pose, you get more points. If it's
centered, the image score doubles. The professor's Pokemon index
has room for only one image of each species, so the cumulative
score rises as you substitute larger, more perfectly centered
photos for inferior images.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you happen to like a snapshot in which the subject
does not dominate the center of the frame, you can save it in a
personal album, along with your personal comments.
</P>
<P>
   And for $3, you can buy a smart card at your local Blockbuster
video store and print that image on a sheet of 16 stickers that you
can trade with your friends. There are five smart cards with
different pictures on them, and naturally these are also
collectible objects. (The Pokemon marketing machine rolls along
with Borg-like momentum.)
</P>
<P>
   Because it's a Pokemon product, the cartridge sells things, of
course. But what's really provocative is its near-perfect
simulation of the modern tourist experience. Pokemon Snap is media
filtered through media. It's a trip you take through a photographic
viewfinder, with a game controller, on your television. Your score
depends entirely on what you record. None of your experiences count
unless you get them on camera, and the end product _ the ultimate
goal _ is hard evidence of your excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's on rails. But so are most package tours. Sure, it's
an on-screen experience. But go to any popular tourist destination
and you'll see squads of people with camcorders, and for them the
trip is also an on-screen experience. And to many of them, it's
worth more as a set of videotapes or photographs that can be
experienced by their friends and family, as images that can be
printed out, posted and sent via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon Island is a fantasy environment. But so is Universal
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Pokemon Snap feels like a more authentic experience,
perhaps because what you see is really what you get. The simulation
that has been engineered for you, the illusion that theme parks
strive so hard to achieve, is uncluttered by the artifacts they
strive so hard to eliminate: trash, bad weather, broken rides, long
lines and the chance that anything untoward will happen before you
get home to process your film. As a theme experience, Pokemon
Island is pure signal, zero noise.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the environment is a simulation of nature. But
the San Diego Wild Animal Park is also a simulation of nature.
Nintendo's creatures are marketing mascots. But so are lions and
tigers. Like Pokemon, lions and tigers belong to institutions that
make money because people want to see charismatic fauna. The
difference, from a business standpoint, is that no one owns the
idea of a zebra, whereas Pokemon are the intellectual property of
Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   Most kids would be more upset about the disappearance of Pokemon
than by the disappearance of zebras. Pokemon are a part of their
lives in a way that zebras are not. Pokemon Island is more real to
them than Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the only way for a child to experience Pokemon
Island's wild animals is through media. But for most children,
that's the case for African highland gorillas as well. Practically
speaking, gorillas are a media experience, no less than the
jigglypuffs and charmanders and metapods that populate Pokemon
Island. As a kid, you experience gorillas when your mom buys a
National Geographic special at Blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   I'll bet that Pokemon outlast gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon Snap, published by Nintendo for Nintendo 64; $59.95; for
all ages. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
