<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-NORTH-SHORE-HOUSE-     09-01 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NORTH-SHORE-HOUSE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORING THE FUTURE, 1862 STYLE, ON LONG ISLAND'S NORTH SHORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOSEPH GIOVANNINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was a summer of roses for Carol and Millard Prisant, a
couple on New York's Long Island who vacationed at home by simply
stepping through the screen doors onto their rose-bedecked
wraparound porch and drinking in a view of the long harbor in their
backyard. Maybe their part of the North Shore had a faster social
engine when Gatsby partied in the Eggs along with the Fricks and
the Morgans, but time is surprisingly slow even in 1999.
Butterflies flirt with the phlox. Canada geese groom themselves on
a rolling lawn swept by weeping willows. There are spired chairs in
the Gothic-style dining room, a dinghy in the boathouse, and a
lavender 1950s kitchen waiting for Loretta Young to pour pink
lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   If the house and setting seem like a pocket of perfection
suspended in time, there are two reasons, separated by more than a
hundred years. First, the house was conceived in 1862 as the
country house of the future. Designed by Staten Island architect
Frederick S. Copley, it was published in ``Woodward's Country
Houses'' with plans and lengthy descriptions of its many
innovations, including its picture windows and geometrically
patterned tile floors.
</P>
<P>
   The three-story structure with curved Flemish gables was a model
of Romantic architecture in New York's emerging steamboat suburbs
in the mid-19th century. Cast-iron birdhouses, now collectors'
items, were copied from published plans for the house, and a
succession of residents, including Rear Adm. William Emory, Gen.
John Pershing and John Demarest, the developer of Forest Hills
Gardens, hung their hats in the central hall. (Emory's sea chest is
still lodged in the attic.)
</P>
<P>
   The second reason the house seems perfect is that the Prisants _
he is a former rocket scientist who now owns an aerospace hardware
company; she is the New York editor of World of Interiors magazine
_ have restored it to the ideal from which it had sadly lapsed. Its
documentation gave the Prisants an unusually clear road map.
</P>
<P>
   They thought it would take a great deal of money to restore the
14-room house. ``It didn't,'' Mrs. Prisant said, ``because we did
most of the work ourselves. I say `most' because I don't lay
tile.'' Over seven years, they spent $125,000 painting the exterior
and interior, scraping and staining mahogany floors, replastering
ceilings, bleaching marble mantles, adding moldings. But her
husband was initially reluctant. ``Actually, the poor man had just
finished the other house when I dragged him kicking and screaming
to this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other house'' was a small Greek Revival they had spent
years of weekends restoring in the same North Shore town. But one
evening, a fellow preservationist whispered to Mrs. Prisant that
the owner of the neighborhood landmark was selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me, `But don't go now, you don't want to see it in
the dark,''' said Mrs. Prisant, who answered, `` `Oh yes I do.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, I'd been in the house and I already knew I was going
to buy it before I drove down the driveway.'' She paused.
``Millard, however, didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   This down-at-the-heels architectural dowager was threatened by a
developer who planned to subdivide the property and build a couple
of ranch houses. ``We bought it to save the house, yes, but also
because it was beautiful,'' she said, serving iced tea on the north
porch, within earshot of a Victorian cast-iron fountain the
Prisants have just erected from parts found on antiquing forays.
</P>
<P>
   The quietly eccentric Mrs. Prisant liked the many-gabled
profile, and she admired the 11-foot ceilings and the proportions.
She could see the charms of the property even though the
landscaping, done by the Olmsted Brothers, sons of the designer of
Manhattan's Central Park, was threadbare. ``It seems it had been on
the market for some time because most women loved it, and most
husbands went ashen _ as did mine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Prisant said: ``My wife looks for trouble and I don't. I like to
repair things and put them to bed and then enjoy them. If she's not
fixing something, she's not happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Prisants _ and their Jack Russell terrier, Cosi Fan Tutti _
moved in right away even though the house wasn't really livable.
``Millard stopped talking to me for quite a while,'' she said.
Prisant only relented when, in a Keystone Cops scenario, the
plaster ceiling in the kitchen collapsed onto the canvas covering
placed overhead. ``It was the first time he laughed in months,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Prisant presides over what may be one of the best-equipped
private tool rooms on Long Island, arranged by department, as in a
hardware store: plumbing, carpentry, electricity. ``Millard and I
have a division of labor,'' she said. ``I do `pretty' and he does
`functional.' He's the engineer and I'm the artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Prisant summarized: ``It's been a cementing experience for
my husband and me, because we complement each other's talents. We
really have the house in common. Your only child is grown and gone,
so you adopt and dress this house and educate yourself about it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Prisant jacked up the porch and secured failing beams, she
focused on the faux finishes, reading a book called ``Parry's
Graining and Marbling'' to teach herself marbleizing techniques.
``It didn't take patience, it was therapy,'' she said. ``But it
took years before my knees got over it.''
</P>
<P>
   They had some helpers. ``An illegal Irishman, that was the
extent of our work force,'' she said. Prisant, who acted as foreman
and engineer as well as laborer, noted, ``Hiring someone who could
learn skills was much less expensive than using a trained carpenter
at $20 an hour.'' They also hired a painter for the exterior, and
their grown son, Barden, an art appraiser in New York, often
pitched in. The idiosyncratic nature of the house, as well as the
cost, dissuaded Prisant from working with a contractor.
``Contractors know it all,'' he said. ``They won't listen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
