<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-NORTH-SHORE-ART-2N     09-01 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NORTH-SHORE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: to you.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead, Prisant restored old plaster (he recommends a roll-on
wallpaper paste called Glidewall to stabilize things) and literally
jumped on the restored porch to tamp it down to the right level.
Luckily, the plumbing was sound. ``It's wonderful what you can do
when you don't have to put in new kitchens and bathrooms,'' Mrs.
Prisant said. ``The seven bathrooms were old but perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair chose their battles, focusing on restoring only the
dining room, front parlor and hallway _ ``as it would have been
furnished in the 1860s by someone who was nouveau riche,'' Mrs.
Prisant said wryly. ``People who come here are appalled. I'm
careful to explain this is not my taste.'' She really favors spare,
disciplined Greek Revival, but the couple resolved to respect the
house, which merited a historically correct treatment. ``We did a
lot of research on the period in order to do a really accurate
job,'' she continued. ``That was the greatest fun, and that's what
took so long.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple studied Lyndhurst, a Gothic Revival house of the same
period on the Hudson, and consulted with the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, through which they located H.&AMP; R. Johnson Tiles Ltd., a
manufacturer in Stoke-on-Trent, England, that was still producing
the encaustic floors made of durable integrally colored
brown-mustard-and-rust ceramic tiles first fabricated in the 19th
century. ``You send measurements, and they send you the
computerized printouts of your floor in that pattern,'' Mrs.
Prisant said.
</P>
<P>
   Until her back gave out about two decades ago, Mrs. Prisant,
author of ``The Antiques Roadshow Primer'' (Workman Publishing, due
this Christmas), had been an antiques dealer and appraiser in
Locust Valley. Through her Rolodex and acumen, she found furniture
that evoked the eclectic Victorian period. The pointed arches over
the doorways in the dining room, though Tudor, suggested a
Gothic-style decor appropriate for the period.
</P>
<P>
   She collected an ensemble of dark, carved pieces _ chairs,
etageres and a four-pedestal mahogany table _ arranged under
plaster tracery bought from a catalog and screwed into place by
Prisant. The English Regency chaise in the front parlor and an
elaborate Victorian side cabinet (``meant to show how rich you
are,'' Mrs. Prisant said mischievously) establish a formality in
the front parlor that is daunting even to the homeowners, who never
use the room, ``which is how it would have been,'' she said,
adding, ``The front parlor was strictly for guests; the family
lived in the back parlor.''
</P>
<P>
   The carpet is based on a 19th-century pattern still produced by
the original English company, with only 6 colors instead of the
original 12. ``At every step I was limited by what was available,''
she said of a carpet without subtle color gradations. ``The carpet
is simpler than it should have been, and less lifelike as a
result.''
</P>
<P>
   The Prisants often improvised. The striped wallpaper, when it
arrived after a six-month wait, was the wrong color, so the couple
sent it back and painted their own camel stripes on yellow parlor
walls, using automobile masking tape. The couple designed the
monumental valances by cutting templates out of cardboard and
having a woodworker construct the actual valance.
</P>
<P>
   The couple left some rooms, like the specimen 1950s kitchen with
its 1954 Caloric stove, just as they found them, but for new paint.
The back parlor and bedrooms are comfortably furnished with roomy
chairs upholstered in floral fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th century French novelist Gustave Flaubert said that the
one unforgivable literary flaw is a lapse in tone, but Mrs. Prisant
deploys lapses as a design strategy. ``I didn't want people to be
intimidated by the house, even though it looks so museum-like,''
she said. ``I thought there should be some whimsy, some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   A cartoon about tag sales, in a period picture frame, a bronze
plaque on the front porch announcing ``Cave Canem'' (beware of the
dog), and a tin Christmas ornament, shaped like a dog, hanging from
a Gothic-style bronze chandelier in the hall, all imply a blithe
spirit.``I don't want to be taken as seriously as the house would
imply,'' Mrs. Prisant said. ``If you look carefully, you'd know
you're not in a stuffy house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
