<HEADER>
A7399 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-FISHING-BASS-MASTERS-     09-01 1905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-BASS-MASTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 FAST BOATS and BIG FLOPPING FISH  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By JAMES GORMAN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It is dawn in the delta, and the heat is already building. We're
just south of New Orleans on Lake Salvador, with the rising sun
behind us and the setting moon ahead, when it occurs to me that my
life could be in danger.
 &HT;    We're going 70 miles an hour in an open boat with no seat belts
and no helmets. Suppose I fly out of the boat and land on my head.
What will my life preserver do? Make my corpse float?
 &HT;    I take a quick look at Michael Iaconelli, who is driving the
boat. His hair and face are flattened by the wind. He looks as if
he has had a bad face lift. The noise is such that if I were to
shout, ``I don't want to die,'' he wouldn't hear me. I wouldn't
hear myself. And the request would be pointless anyway.
 &HT;    Iaconelli is a professional bass fisherman, this is the first
day of a three-day tournament and every minute between us and our
destination is another minute between him and $100,000. Maybe $1
million if you count endorsements.
 &HT;    This is the 29th annual Bass Masters Classic, a competition
billed by its organizers, the Bass Anglers Sportsman Society
(BASS), as the Super Bowl of bass fishing. Forty-five fishermen,
presumably the 45 best bass fishermen in the entire universe, have
come to Louisiana to spend three days racing around the networks of
canals, bayous and lakes of the Mississippi Delta catching
largemouth black bass and bringing them back to New Orleans so the
fish can be weighed - dripping wet and wriggling - under the lights
in the Louisiana Superdome to the cheers and whistles of the
faithful. Most pounds of fish over three days wins a hundred grand.
 &HT;    It is hard to find a sport comparable to professional bass
fishing. Nascar drivers probably have as many sponsor patches on
their shirts. But there are no fish. There are weigh-ins in boxing,
but again, no fish. There may well be fish in professional
wrestling, for all I know, but there is no boat racing.
 &HT;    Professional bass fishing _ the pursuit, for fame and money, of
Micropterus salmoides _ is sui generis. Or, as Denny Brauer, the
winner of last year's classic who got his face on a Wheaties box
for his achievements, says of his chosen sport, ``I think it kind
of sits there by itself.''
 &HT;    Here's how it works: In BASS tournaments, each competitor has an
observer in the boat with him (in this case, a member of the media,
which serves the dual purpose of preventing cheating and getting
publicity). The competitors have a set amount of time to fish each
day.
 &HT;    On the first day, we leave at 6:30 and have to be back by 2:30.
The goal is to come back with the five biggest bass you can catch,
using artificial lures - no worms, minnows or ducklings allowed.
Each boat, a brand-new top-of-the-line model provided for the
classic, is equipped with an aerated well, a kind of aquarium
without glass, to keep fish alive.
 &HT;    You can keep only five fish, but once you've got that many, you
can keep fishing to try to catch bigger fish. If you put a new one
in the well, you've got to let one go. At the end of the day, all
the fish are weighed and eventually taken back to the bayous and
released.
 &HT;    Over the last few decades, professional bass fishing has grown
in glitz and glory. BASS is a profit-making organization that
encompasses several magazines, a TV show, conservation
organizations, a network of fishing clubs and more than one
professional tour.
 &HT;    A competing organization, Operation Bass, runs another series of
tournaments, including the Wal-Mart FLW tour, which offers an even
bigger first prize than the classic, $250,000. It is the battle of
the marts: Kmart supports BASS, Wal-Mart supports Operation Bass.
The prize money is only part of it. Professional fishermen endorse
equipment, write books, act as hosts of fishing shows on
television.
 &HT;    Of course, those are the few at the top. Pete Gluszek, a young
New Jersey fisherman who left a job in engineering to fish, says
that successful full-time professionals are likely to earn,
depending on the year, something between $40,000 and $100,000.
 &HT;    The pros are just the tip of the iceberg, the ones who help sell
equipment to the weekend anglers, who support, according to BASS, a
$46 billion industry. (That probably includes all the
cheeseburgers, beer and nachos that anglers buy on their way to and
from the lake.)
 &HT;    Iaconelli, 27, has been gradually working his way up the
iceberg. He fished amateur tournaments for years and then started
on a professional tour, going from tournament to tournament, across
the country, in 1997. He won a major competition in May on the Red
River in Louisiana, which got him into the classic.
 &HT;    He is not one of the slow-talking Southerners who still dominate
the sport. He is a fast-talking, intense, summa cum laude graduate
of Rowan University, in New Jersey. When he is not fishing, he
manages the fishing-tackle department in a sports store. He leaves
as little as possible to chance. In a week's exploratory fishing a
month before the tournament, he picked one bend of the Orange Grove
Canal as the area he would fish. It is about 65 miles from the
launch.
 &HT;    Forty minutes into our trip, Iaconelli slows to an idle, and I
reach back to unscrew an aluminum light pole from the back of the
boat so we can fit under a low bridge. The pole won't come loose.
 &HT;    He turns off the motor, jumps back to the stern, gives the light
pole a twist, finds it won't yield to him either and breaks it off,
snapping the aluminum, tearing the wires and cutting his finger. We
pass under the bridge and immediately speed up again, although the
canal is narrower and we sometimes have to drop below 60 mph. We're
halfway there.
 &HT;    When we finally stop, the quiet is a shock, the cessation of
wind roar seems like a slap in the face. Suddenly there is no sound
other than the water lapping against the boat, the occasional frog
croaking and the all-but-imperceptible hum of the electric trolling
motor.
 &HT;    It is now 7:30. We are in a canal, with a few docks and
ramshackle fishing camps set out over the water. The banks are
clogged with water hyacinths, an invasive plant that obstructs
navigation but that the bass love.
 &HT;    Iaconelli doesn't talk as he fishes. He runs the trolling motor
with a foot pedal, easing the boat along while he uses underhand
casts to make a lure called a jig float an inch above the water for
20 or 30 feet and then slip through the surface without a splash.
 &HT;    He catches one bass just before 8 and then nothing except a gar
(only bass count) for the next hour and a half. If possible, the
swamp grows more quiet still. Occasionally we move. I watch a heron
fishing in the shallows. A big alligator swims by. Schools of
mullet leap into the air.
 &HT;    Iaconelli methodically pitches the jig to the edge of the weeds,
letting it bump on the bottom once or twice and retrieving it to
cast again. When he is done with the jig, he tries other lures in
the open water, an imitation minnow called a crankbait and a bit of
wire, flashing spoons and plastic skirt called a spinnerbait.
 &HT;    At 9:30 his luck changes. Off a point where one canal runs into
another, he catches one small fish and then quickly another larger
fish, about three pounds. Each is in the boat and in the live well
in seconds.
 &HT;    ``See the current come out of there,'' he says, excitement in
his voice. ``That is a good thing. That is a very good thing. That
is a great thing.''
 &HT;    By 9:45 he has five fish over 12 inches, all in the live well.
He has reached his limit, but he needs more weight. When he catches
a big-bellied four-pounder, he turns ecstatic. ``Thank you, Lord -
thank you, Lord,'' he says, pumping his fist on the bow of the boat
and shaking my hand. ``That's what I needed. Thank you, Jesus.''
 &HT;    As he starts fishing again, he is suddenly talkative. ``Remember
I was telling you about that buzz feeling,'' he says, referring to
the athlete's sense of being in the zone, of being able to do no
wrong, ``I got it now.''
 &HT;    By the time we head back, he estimates that he has a good 15
pounds, his goal for each day. He and other anglers are estimating
that 45 pounds will win the competition. He turns on the motor, and
we are off. I watch the speedometer carefully. When it edges over
75, I turn away and contemplate the unsung virtues of rowboats.
 &HT;    By 4 p.m. the show is beginning at the Superdome. The bass are
still in the live wells in each boat. The trucks that have pulled
the boats on their trailers to and from the launch are lined up
waiting to be washed and polished before they take a lap around the
Superdome stage, with each fisherman waving to the crowd like a
teen-age beauty queen. By the final day, BASS estimates 28,000
spectators are in the dome. Today, my guess is that the
sectioned-off stands are less than a quarter full.
 &HT;    Denny Brauer, last year's champion, comes in with 14 pounds 4
ounces. A few do better; most do worse. The fishermen pull their
fish out of the live wells and hold them up for the cameras. Then
they step up to the microphone, carrying the fish in a mesh bag,
and stand, sunburned after a day on the water, to name lure, rod
and line manufacturer and to praise the boat and motor the way
actors thank their parents when they win the Oscar.
 &HT;    Iaconelli's fish weigh in at 15 pounds 1 ounce. The hero of the
day, Jack Wade, has 16 pounds 13 ounces. But Iaconelli is one of
the Top 5, and the next day, BASS photo boats will follow him.
 &HT;    But the next day, a new leader, Davy Hite, comes in with 19
pounds 3 ounces, a huge haul. Iaconelli brings in 11 pounds 5
ounces, well short of his goal, and drops to eighth. And on the
final day, Hite scores again with 19 pounds 14 ounces and wins
handily.
 &HT;    Iaconelli comes in sixth, well ahead of many more experienced
fishermen. He had hoped for the Top 5, but he is pleased with his
showing and ready for the next tournament. He is not planning to
get rich yet. His winnings come to $6,000. ``If I can make a
living,'' he says, that will be good enough. ``This is what I love
to do.''
 &HT;    When the Top 5 fishermen are interviewed after the weigh-ins,
they explain how they caught their fish. Hite, from Prosperity,
S.C., credits the tackle he used, but he is refreshingly honest
about the real secret to his victory. It was a tip from a local, he
says, from the stage.
 &HT;    A Louisiana friend told him that a spot near Bayou Boeuf was a
good one. And that, as it turns out, is where the big ones were.
 &HT;     c.1999 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (James Gorman is editor of the weekly Circuits section of The
New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
