<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GAS-PUMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILLING UP ON GAS, AND WEB ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gas pumps are no strangers to advertising. Their nozzle handles
have long been adorned with junk food ads encased in clear plastic.
And their sheet metal bases often serve as tiny billboards.
</P>
<P>
   So it should come as no surprise that an evolution in gasoline
pump advertising will start making its way across the United States
this fall. The Internet-linked gasoline pump _ called, perhaps
predictably, the Millennium Series by one maker _ will turn those
pitches for salty foods and sugary drinks into multimedia
extravaganzas of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back at the history of the gasoline pump, you can
see a clear development of their technology from purely dispensing
gasoline to a number of other functions,'' said Douglas Pinner, the
chairman and chief executive of the Tokheim Corp., a gas pump maker
in Fort Wayne, Ind. ``At the same time you clearly see the advent
of utilizing the dispenser as a marketing device.''
</P>
<P>
   Tokheim's new Millennium pumps _ which BP Amoco will test this
fall before a broad rollout next year _ will be stuffed with
individual stripped-down computers and touch-screen controls. And
much like computers in, say, a law office, the pumps will be
connected into a local area network controlled by a more powerful
central computer that will make the link to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Pinner said most customers visiting Tokheim's Web browsing pumps
would see banner ads above the display's on-screen pump controls or
around weather forecasts, traffic reports or local hotel lists if
those options are selected. Ads will flood the pump's full screen
only when customers press on banner ads promoting discount coupons
for items in the station's convenience store. The coupons will be
produced by an in-pump printer.
</P>
<P>
   The browser will work only while gasoline is being pumped and
will not allow customers to check e-mail or search for Web pages of
their own choosing.
</P>
<P>
   Tokheim's basic technology, which it developed in conjunction
with Radiant Systems Inc., a provider of computer systems and
software for retailers in Alpharetta, Ga., is largely the same in
concept as a system now being field-tested in Kitchener, Ontario,
by the Time Line Media Corp., a small software maker for the
petroleum industry.
</P>
<P>
   At a Pioneer gasoline station currently testing a Time Line
system that retrofits existing pumps, consumers are treated, or
perhaps subjected, to full-motion video ads for things like cell
phone service and a local theme park. Time Line also mixes news
headlines, weather and traffic with the ads. Its president, John
Lowndes, said he hoped to make its sponsors' messages appealing by
using cameras to target specific ads to different vehicle types.
</P>
<P>
   Tokheim and Time Line vary when it comes to the issue of how
much advertising motorists will tolerate as they fill their tanks.
Pinner said the advertising on Tokheim pumps would be ``very
subtle'' because Tokheim's research showed that customers did not
want to be inundated with advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Lowndes said he hoped that pumps could also serve as electronic
commerce sites for a variety of services, accepting, for example,
orders for florists or payments for parking tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at a gas station as a community access point.'' He
acknowledged, however, that giving customers a reason to linger at
do-everything pumps could lead to congestion and could ultimately
undermine the station's ability to sell gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
