<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER KORESH PROBE UNNECESSARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not again. Not another investigation of the Branch Davidian
fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows what happened, or ought to: A homicidal/suicidal
nut case named David Koresh set himself and his goofball cult on
fire, and most of them burned to death.
</P>
<P>
   Case closed.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI did not start the fire that consumed Koresh, his idiot
followers and their unfortunate children. If federal law
enforcement officials lied about using pyrotechnic tear-gas
grenades hours before the fire broke out, well, shame on them.
</P>
<P>
   If the attorney general and Congress want to find out who lied
and why, let them conduct a brief, limited investigation that
focuses on the whys and wherefores of the lying. We do not need
another in-depth rehash of the entire, ill-fated showdown between
Koresh and the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have happily forgotten this pitiful 51-day chapter
in American history, here's a quick refresher course: On Feb. 28,
1993, the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms conducted
a raid on the Branch Davidians' headquarters near Waco after a
lengthy investigation turned up evidence that Koresh and his
bizarre band of misfits were illegally stockpiling weapons and
explosives for the purpose of waging violence against the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody apparently tipped off the Koreshians about the raid,
and so they had their considerable arsenal at the ready when ATF
agents approached the so-called compound in which Koresh and the
others resided in the finest tradition of cultification. The
shootout left four agents and at least two Davidians dead. Sixteen
agents were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   After the ATF retrieved its dead and wounded, the FBI assumed
command of the scene and settled in for a 51-day standoff that
ended with the lethal conflagration on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Arson investigators concluded that the fire was set by the
people inside the building, which came as no surprise to anyone who
had paid attention to the Koreshian rantings that emanated from the
place throughout the siege. It couldn't have been more obvious that
Koresh meant to end his life in what he considered a blaze of glory
_ and to take the others with him.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno OK'd the tank-and-tear-gas assault
on the Davidian compound that evidently provided the excuse that
Koresh was looking for to ``light it up.'' The critics say that the
government shouldn't have forced the issue after a mere 51 days,
that the FBI should have continued to negotiate with Koresh until a
peaceful resolution was achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Koresh had no intention of permitting a peaceful resolution. He
had promised his followers a fiery apocalypse, and he was hell-bent
on keeping his word.
</P>
<P>
   No, the FBI did not move too soon when it began poking holes in
the Davidians' happy little home and injecting tear gas. It acted
approximately 50 days too late.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the initial ATF raid was repelled by the combative
Davidians, the government should have regrouped and mounted a
second assault _ a serious assault, the kind of assault that would
have overwhelmed the cultists and forced their surrender.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake the government made was sitting there all those days
and weeks, giving Koresh an opportunity to promulgate his
preposterous preachings and prepare his followers for the
diabolical climax he was plotting.
</P>
<P>
   What about the children? Wasn't the government responsible for
the safety of young children inside the Davidian compound?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Koresh and the Davidian adults were responsible for the
safety of the children. The adults inside placed the children in
jeopardy. Koresh and whoever else set the fire murdered the
children. Blaming the government for any deaths that occurred
inside that building is an outrageous misallocation of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's newly revealed failure to be entirely forthcoming
about irrelevant details does not change the fundamental facts of
what happened that day: David Koresh perpetrated mass murder and
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   No further investigation is required.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
