<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
 (gm)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, Sept. 2, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Israel and the Palestinians
scheduled talks late into the night Wednesday in a race to seal a
deal on implementing their stalled Wye River peace accord. (Summary
from wires) By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ The Clinton administration said
Wednesday that it wants assurances that international financial aid
already sent to Russia has not been lost to corruption, but stopped
short of calling for a halt in future loans to Moscow from the
International Monetary Fund. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-INAUG (Panama City, Panama) _ Thirty-one years after her
husband was overthrown, Mireya Moscoso will be inaugurated as the
first female president of Panama on Wednesday, breaking from a
tradition of military regimes and populist strongmen.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ZEDILLO (Mexico City) _ President Zedillo gives
state-of-the-nation speech tonight.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WACO-INQUIRY (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno wants to
move quickly to open an independent investigation of the 1993
deadly siege in Waco, Texas, and plans to pick a leader for the
inquiry from a short list that includes two former Republican
Senators, law enforcement officials said today. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-TAXES (Washington) _ The White House chief of staff today
urged the Republican majority in Congress to send President Clinton
its $792 billion tax cut bill so that he can promptly veto it.
Congress passed the tax measure early last month but lawmakers have
refrained from forwarding it to the White House, where it faces
certain rejection. Republicans have been stumping across the
country for their tax plan during the current congressional recess.
Clinton and his aides have taken every opportunity to criticize the
proposal as an unwarranted windfall for the rich and a threat to
the booming American economy. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARCH (New York) _ An appeals court on Wednesday emphatically
rejected the city's final legal challenge to a Harlem youth rally,
and, in an unusual intrusion into the city's authority over public
safety, it ordered the Police Department not to monitor the event
with ``undue rigidity.'' By David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-BUSCH (New York) _ A profile of Gidone Busch, the
mentally disturbed man shot by the police Monday in Brooklyn. By
Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-SHOOTING (New York) _ Developments in the shooting of
a mentally disturbed man by the police. By Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-INVEST (Kuala Lumpur) _ Taking a major stride back into
the world's financial mainstream, Malaysia lifts a steep tax on the
repatriation of foreign capital. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SMART-MICE (Undated) _ In a major test of how learning works
at the level of nerve cells, a scientist has created a smarter
strain of mice by manipulating a gene involved in memory formation.
He believes his work lays the basis for eventually doing the same
in people, whether in helping patients with memory deficits,
counteracting the loss of memory in older people, and even in
making healthy individuals smarter. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-STEEL-DRUMS (New York) _ The scene and excitement in Brooklyn
as Len ``Boogsie'' Sharpe, Trinidad's master of the steel drum,
helps steel bands prepare for the Brooklyn Labor Day carnival. By
Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
