<HEADER>
A7442 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-STOCK-MANIA-HNS &LR;      09-01 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-MANIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET MAY FIND A LESSON IN THE TULIP 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Beneficial as it is in so many ways, prosperity
also brings out the worst in people _ the greed, the stupidity, the
criminal lust.
</P>
<P>
   For eight years, the stock market has been through the roof. Our
culture has changed, as a result, in subtle and not-so-subtle ways,
most of them awful. You can't listen to the radio without hearing
some boob pitch an utterly implausible get-rich-quick-scheme. But
people evidently buy into this gibberish; otherwise, the ads
wouldn't run.
</P>
<P>
   A major mental disorder gripped the Dutch between 1634 and 1637,
``tulipomania,'' the primary symptom of which was the investment of
one's life savings in the bulbs of a new kind of flower from Asia
Minor, the tulip. People didn't tiptoe into disaster; they dove in,
head first, and drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Are we different 360 years later? I think not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long bull market,'' said Securities and Exchange
Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt, ``has not only proven attractive
_ it's created a stampede.''
</P>
<P>
   It has gotten so bad today that some companies standing to
profit from the thundering herd's run for the riches have tried to
rein in the cattle, lest they themselves get trampled by the
ignorant greedheads who are their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab and Co. of San Francisco has identified 1,000
stocks it will no longer allow to be used as collateral for margin
buying.
</P>
<P>
   The latest issue of ``Fidelity Outlook,'' the big mutual-funds
company's magazine for ``preferred customers,'' cautions readers
against ``obsessive, compulsive'' investing behavior and
``overconfidence.'' It suggests that ``fear of losing'' may play a
useful role as a psychological ``ballast.''
</P>
<P>
   Some years ago, the SEC added to its San Francisco office. From
there, the feds could sneak a peak at the shamming and scamming in
Silicon Valley, much of it Internet-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody sees other people making a lot in the market,'' said
SEC attorney Mike Dicke, ``and they want to get in on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said assistant district administrator Helane Morrison: ``People
won't want to be left behind. Greed kicks in.''
</P>
<P>
   I was glad to hear the feds had nailed some of the alleged
idiots.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Henderson, 24, a securities analyst for Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter in Menlo Park, was accused Aug. 2 of civil and criminal
insider trading violations for allegedly participating with a buddy
in Ohio in a scheme that began last July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assume everything they say is true, it was a four-week piece
of stupidity by a young person'''' said Cris Arguedas, a lawyer
representing Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   The deal went like this, the feds allege: the two young men
split profits 60-40, with Henderson's Ohio pal taking the larger
share for providing the capital, while Henderson provided the
illegal insider information available to him even at his
entry-level position.
</P>
<P>
   Total take: an alleged $54,000, which strikes me as a pittance
given the risk _ maybe enough for a new BMW, but that's about all.
</P>
<P>
   Dicke said: ``In the '90s we have seen insider trading move from
Wall Street to Main Street, and now we're seeing a resurgence of it
in the brokerage industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Aug. 2, the feds filed civil charges against 15 people
for allegedly engaging in an illegal stock manipulation scheme
involving a cheap airline stock, PSA Inc., a name intended to evoke
memories of the long-defunct Pacific Southwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The case was part of a nationwide sweep targeting alleged fraud
involving microcap stocks _ the penny-ante offerings that often
escape regulatory oversight but provide scam artists with all sorts
of opportunities for big profits.
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC, the PSA group _ including Edward Durante
of Orinda, Thomas J. Donahue of Santa Rosa and Daniel C. Sanders of
Martinez _ artificially drove up the price of the stock from 50
cents a share to $5 in two weeks last year, then watched it
plummet.
</P>
<P>
   They made $1 million in illegal profits in the process, the SEC
alleges, by secretly controlling the supply of PSA stock on the
market and lying about it to investors in order to inflate the
value. Losers included retirees who were bilked of sums in the six
figures, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue's lawyer Peter Goodman of San Francisco, said his client
denies wrongdoing. Lawyers for the others did not return telephone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how it all shakes out, Dicke's warning to the
little folks who get caught in the stampede is a good one:
``Investors need to do their homework.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
