<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Depriving citizens of food has become a vicious tool of modern
warfare. And in Sudan, a poor country in East Africa, the
government is using hunger as a weapon. The Houston Chronicle, a
partner of the New York Times News Service, examines Sudan's
16-year-old civil war and the deaths of more than 2 million people,
more than any conflict since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   We have moved the following eight photos by Andrew Innerarity
for release on Sunday, Sept. 5, to go with The Chronicle's package
of stories slugged with the keyword ``SUDAN.''
</P>
<P>
   NYT101, Sacks of food are dropped from a C-130 Hercules cargo
plane, under contract to the United Nations, onto a field in
southern Sudan in April. Photo slugged: SUDAN AID 1 HNS
</P>
<P>
   NYT102, Sudanese women and children race to a site where bags
containing food where air-dropped in April. Photo slugged: SUDAN
AID 2 HNS
</P>
<P>
   NYT103, Ajou Deng hangs from a scale at a feeding center
sponsored by Doctors Without Borders in April. Photo slugged: SUDAN
AID 3 HNS
</P>
<P>
   NYT104, Abuk Garang, 12, scrabbles to collect grains of cereal
spilled on the ground after a food drop from an aircraft with the
United Nations relief effort. Photo slugged: SUDAN AID 4 HNS
</P>
<P>
   NYT105, A woman feeds a child at a feeding center run by Doctors
Without Borders in April. The facility is designed to provide
nourishment to children who are below 70 percent of their minimum
weight requirement. Photo slugged: SUDAN AID 5 HNS
</P>
<P>
   NYT106, Saleman Kuku, a Sudanese rebel, stands watch at an
airfield in an undisclosed area of the Nuba Mountains as sacks of
food are unloaded from an aircraft. Photo slugged: SUDAN NUBA
</P>
<P>
   NYT107, Cargo planes with various humanitarian aid groups are
parked in April on Lokichoggio's airfield, said to the the second
busiest airport in eastern Africa. Photo slugged: SUDAN AID WORKERS
HNS
</P>
<P>
   NYT108, Mohamed Tutu, 28, a father of four, inspects a house in
the village that was damaged by government forces in April. Photo
slugged: SUDAN-WAR
</P>
