<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-PERSONAL-ORGANIZE     09-01 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PERSONAL-ORGANIZERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'VE GOT THE WORLD IN THEIR PALMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: sidebar at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a summer of relative leisure, when jobs or camp ate up
most of the day, the new school year can ring in a head-spinning
array of classes, athletic practices and after-school lessons. How
does the beleaguered student make sense of it all, and still
remember to hand in a history project by its due date?
</P>
<P>
   Most school-age children write their schedules in notebooks,
scribble appointments on the refrigerator or just rely on their
parents to remind them. But some, like 10-year-old Alden Mathieson
of Atlanta, are turning to handheld electronic organizers to keep
track of their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have a paper planner on my desk in my room, but I'd
write something down one day and not look at it again until after
I'd missed the appointment,'' said Alden, who now records all his
homework assignments and appointments in his Palm III organizer. A
two-toned chime will sound on the Palm III in his back pocket 15
minutes before a friend is due to arrive or on the night before a
report is due.
</P>
<P>
   For many children, of course, Palm Pilots and similar handheld
organizers are attractive because of the many games that can be
played on them or because of the programs for things like
calculators or dictionaries that can be loaded onto them to help
with schoolwork. But increasingly, students are following their
parents' lead, using the devices to help schedule their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Does a child really need an electronic organizer? Many parents
would say no, that children often have too much to do and that an
organizer just encourages overscheduling. But other parents are
supporting the use of the devices by their children.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Elgan, who publishes a weekly online Palm newsletter, The
Palmreader (www.thepalreader.com), said he had given his Palm III
to his 10-year-old son, Kenny, when he upgraded to a Palm V.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been warming to it more and more and is starting to
record his friends' phone numbers and keep track of his own
schedule,'' said Elgan, of Elmont, N.Y. ``But the thing he uses it
the most for at this point is games. He likes chess and arcade
games like Pac-Man. It's good for long car trips or when we're
waiting for a table in a restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents, however, say they are a little perplexed by their
children's desire to use organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shannon of Los Angeles, who has boys 6 and 9 years old,
said that after his older son, Zachary, had expressed interest in
the To Do lists on Shannon's Palm III, they had set about creating
one for the boy. It included tasks like ``feed the dogs'' and
``help Mom with the dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon said that his son got satisfaction from checking off
completed items but that he himself could not remember wanting _ or
needing _ to keep track of daily functions when he was that age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of chores, but the only thing that mattered was
that I would have enough time afterward to go out and play,'' he
said. ``The same thing was true the next day and the day after
that. As for the rest of it, I didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   The process of scheduling appointments, which originated in the
workplace, has not only moved into the home but has also altered to
some extent how people structure their lives outside the office,
said Jan English-Lueck, an associate professor of anthropology at
San Jose State University. Dr. English-Lueck directs the Silicon
Valley Works Project, which studies technology's effects on work
and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people tend to schedule appointments at work in
hourly increments,'' Dr. English-Lueck said. ``Even when a meeting
might take only 20 minutes, they still set aside an hour block.
This approach seems to translate seamlessly to their kids, and it
fuels the way people handle schedules at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents with children who use electronic organizers say
they appreciate being relieved of the burden of insuring that their
children make their appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have to be reminded of things all the time,'' said Peter
Fiekowsky of Los Altos, Calif., whose 11-year-old son, Daniel, uses
his Palm III to keep track of homework assignments, piano lessons
and morning exercise routines. ``Now the Palm beeps, and I don't
have to be the bad guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason Daniel often has his Palm with him, however, is
because he is an avid fan of Sub Hunt and Hardball, two of the
hundreds of games available for the Palm that can be downloaded
from the Internet. Like many children, Daniel was initially
attracted to the games on the Palm, he started learning how to use
the scheduling features later.
</P>
<P>
   Some students do schoolwork on their organizers. Joe Malchow, a
14-year-old resident of Scotch Plains, N.J., who last year designed
a student scheduler for the Palm, writes book reports, short
stories and other English projects directly on his Palm III.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can input words into my Palm almost as fast as I can write
on paper,'' he said. ``About the only thing I can't do are math
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Joe cannot write out long equations for math
assignments on his Palm, dozens of numeric and scientific
calculator programs are available for Palms, as well as
applications that convert currencies, weights and other
measurements.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic organizers are not as ubiquitous among teen-agers as
cell phones or pagers. ``I'm still the only kid in my class with a
Palm,'' Joe Malchow said. ``But I think that will change,
especially because they've gotten a lot cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, Palm Computing, a division of 3Com, began selling a
less expensive version of its popular Palm III, the IIIe. And
several companies have recently introduced Palm-like organizers
that are even less expensive, including some in the $100 range.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are elementary, middle and high schools that
allow children to use the built-in calculators found in most
electronic organizers while in the classroom, many schools consider
them to be like Gameboys and other portable games.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many teachers also wonder about their value as an educational
tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with calculators, children can rely too much on technology
without learning the real skills,'' said Janice Levitan, an
elementary school teacher in Austin, Texas, who says she still
remembers the phone numbers of her childhood friends. ``I don't
think students should have a combination
Gameboy-calculator-organizer at a time when their lives should
still be relatively simple.''
</P>
<P>
   But most parents of children who use organizers say they help
children learn to keep track of their days.
</P>
<P>
   Alden Mathieson's mother, Wendy Shapiro, said: ``We think it
will help him in middle school, when he has to go to a different
classroom for every period. He has an incredible memory now, but
his organizer will come in handy when things get more
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE CHOICES
</P>
<P>
   By CATHERINE GREENMAN &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The following are some popular back-to-school software programs
for handheld electronic organizers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLASSPRO: www.developerone.com/ClassPro/home.htm
</P>
<P>
   A software application for Casio and other organizers that use
the Windows CE operating system, it helps students organize class
schedules, notes and assignments. Ten file templates also let
students enter notes into their CE devices while in class. Created
by Developer One, it can be downloaded for $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   GK IN POCKET:
www.palmix.itil.com/newpalmix/products/gkpockethome.htm
</P>
<P>
   A mini-encyclopedia that can be used on both Palm and Windows
CE-based organizers. The topics include geography, literature and
world records. Produced by the ITIL Corporation, it is available
for $5.
</P>
<P>
   STUDENTMATE: www.palmcentral.com or www.jet-ware.com
</P>
<P>
   A shareware application for Palm users that helps middle and
high school students store their class schedules and work
assignments. Created by Joe Malchow, a 14-year-old high school
student from Scotch Plains, N.J. The software is available for $13.
</P>
<P>
   IMAGIPROBE: www.imagiworks.com
</P>
<P>
   For earth science students, a software and hardware combination
that, when hooked to Palm devices, will take measurements of light,
soil and water temperature, and voltage. Sensors are sold
separately. It is $250 from Imagiworks.
</P>
<P>
   LOST IN DIVISION: www.palmcentral.com
</P>
<P>
   For 8- to 12-year-old Palm users, a division game and tutorial.
Players solve division problems to help a robot fuel a space ship.
It can be downloaded free from the math section at Palm Central.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
