<HEADER>
A7482 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-PROVIDENCE-TEX     09-01 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROVIDENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OUTSIDE PROVIDENCE' GETS THE '70S RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ads for ``Outside Providence'' trumpet its connection to
``There's Something About Mary's'' creators, the Farrelly brothers,
leading viewers to expect another politically incorrect, gross-out
comedy. The opening scenes don't dispel this notion; they're home
movies of a bike-riding teen-age boy towing his little brother
along on a paper route in his wheelchair, with their one-eyed,
three-legged dog running behind. Somehow, you expect the dog and
the kid in the wheelchair to suffer indignities inspiring guilty
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   They do, but not as graphically as you might expect, because
``Outside Providence'' isn't simply a Farrelly brothers movie. What
the ads don't say is that it's directed by Michael Corrente, who
gave 1994's ``Federal Hill'' a sense of grit. He layers ``Outside
Providence'' with unusual perception, charm and depth while not
slighting its laugh quotient. It's the best coming-of-age film in a
year that sometimes seems dedicated to the genre.
</P>
<P>
   That young man on the bike is dumb-but-sweet Tim Dunphy (Shawn
Hatosy, allowed to stand out rather than get lost in a teen
ensemble as he was in ``The Faculty''). It's 1974 in Pawtucket,
R.I., and ``Dunph'' does what most guys like him did back then _ he
hangs out. He loves his little brother, has a love-hate
relationship with his blue-collar single father, and spends most of
his free time getting high and talking about life with his buddies.
</P>
<P>
   That means mostly talking about sex, although there's no
evidence that Dunph or his buddies have any sexual experience. For
all their banter, they never seem to have any girls around. Even
when one pulls Dunph onto a disco floor, he's uncomfortable,
dancing with his arms folded as if he instinctively knows that this
incipient fad is a threat to his long-haired, field-jacket-clad way
of life.
</P>
<P>
   But he also suspects that he's a little different from his
friends, and he finds out more about himself when he's shipped to a
prep school after an unfortunate car accident.
</P>
<P>
   The prep school is a way of keeping Dunph out of jail, although
it has so many rules it doesn't seem like much of an alternative.
Naturally, Dunph hates it at first, but he soon discovers that
other students like to get high and talk about life; they're merely
smarter, better-dressed versions of his Pawtucket friends (one of
them owns a bong that would make Cheech and Chong bow in worship).
Dunph also discovers Jane ``(Varsity Blues''' Amy Smart), an
intelligent, fresh-faced blonde who just happens to like getting
stoned and hanging out, but who also has ambitions that begin to
rub off on Dunph.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of ``Outside Providence'' isn't particularly new;
what's different is the knowing observation that Corrente brings to
the story (he co-wrote the screenplay with Bobby and Peter
Farrelly, working from the latter's brief novel). Unlike the makers
of the likable but uneven ``Dick'' and the execrable ``Detroit Rock
City,'' Corrente actually appears to have lived in the '70s and
doesn't have to rely on celebrity impersonations or sharp set
design to evoke the period.
</P>
<P>
   You get the sense that he knew guys like Dunph and his buds, and
he brings as much poignancy to the teens' impromptu memorial
service for a friend as he brings humor to the prep school's very
formal dean reading of a stoned-out letter written by one of
Dunph's friends (despite all the pot-smoking in this movie, it
contains more than a few anti-drug messages).
</P>
<P>
   Corrente and the Farrellys deftly balance views of Dunph's two
cliques and his dad's poker-playing friends, who are merely
grown-up versions of male-bonders. Alec Baldwin gives his best
performance since 1992's ``Glengarry Glen Ross'' as Dunph's
none-too-bright dad, particularly in an emotional scene in which he
tells Dunph just why his mother left them. But his portrayal is
just one of many that give multiple dimensions to a character that,
in other hands, would be a mere stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   The '70s have done so poorly in movies lately that it's a wonder
people keep making films about the decade. Even the vibrant
``Boogie Nights'' was a box-office disappointment. But ``Outside
Providence'' gets it right, with astonishing tenderness for a movie
with such clueless characters. We've seen so many teen-age tales
this year that we're approaching burnout, and that leads to concern
about how well this movie will do as it kicks off the film biz's
off-season. With any luck, the Farrelly name will draw audiences,
and they'll be pleasantly surprised by a movie with considerable
humor, and even more heart.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Outside Providence''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Michael Corrente
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Shawn Hatosy, Alec Baldwin
</P>
<P>
   Length: 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ pervasive strong language and drug use
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
