<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN RESOLUTION DIVIDES ASIAN-AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ Behind the California Assembly's demand that
Japan apologize and pay for atrocities before and during World War
II is a tangle of politics and emotions that has divided many
Japanese-Americans and Chinese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the legislators approved a resolution sponsored by
Assemblyman Mike Honda, D-San Jose, that the Japanese government
formally acknowledge atrocities committed by the Japanese Imperial
military throughout Asia from 1931 to 1945 and provide unspecified
compensation for victims.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, it seems odd that California lawmakers would
step so directly into what appears to be a foreign policy issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Honda and his supporters (mainly Chinese-Americans) don't
think it's odd at all. They view the matter as one of human rights
that transcends national boundaries and ethnic considerations.
</P>
<P>
   That Honda, 58, is a third-generation Japanese-American makes
his leadership on this touchy issue all the more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   The nuances and ironies in this case are a fascinating study of
the richly complex political development of the diverse
Asian-American communities here in California and nationally. Those
promoting the issue are affluent Chinese immigrants living in
Silicon Valley who carry direct or indirect memories of the
horrendous Asian chaos two generations ago. They pushed for a
similar congressional resolution last year, but didn't succeed. It
is the depth of their emotions that has propelled this issue into
the public's consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Other Chinese-American activists, however, have concentrated on
a different political agenda. It includes, among other issues,
getting Bill Lann Lee confirmed by the Senate as an assistant
attorney general; favoring a statistical sampling method in the
next Census; opposing immigration restrictions and welfare cuts
against legal immigrants; and supporting stronger hate-crime laws.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the campaign financing scandal involving some Asians
and Asian-Americans and the spying allegations against a
Chinese-American scientist, these latter activists have worked
strenuously to get Congress and the news media to make distinctions
between Asian-Americans and Asian nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Honda resolution is not a domestic issue. It does not
belong in the California Legislature. It perpetuates the myth we
are foreign,'' said one Asian-American political activist, who
asked for anonymity. ``It compromises the battle that
Asian-Americans are fighting, that we are loyal to our root Asian
homelands.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Japanese-Americans are upset with Honda because they fear
backlash from Americans who may consider them more Japanese than
American. For many Japanese-Americans, especially those who were
interned in camps during World War II, the matter of a distinct
American identity has been crucial to their efforts to persuade
Americans they aren't loyal to Japan. Ironically, according to some
sources, Japanese-Americans who oppose the Honda resolution won't
speak out publicly for fear their opposition will be interpreted as
endorsing Japan's heinous acts half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Honda's assertiveness on this issue demonstrates that there
should be no confusion between Japanese-Americans and Japanese
nationals.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some Japanese-Americans support Honda. One is Dr.
Clifford Uyeda, former national president of the Japanese-American
Citizens League.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not betraying the country of your parents or
grandparents by criticizing it,'' the retired pediatrician said.
``We Americans criticize the U.S. government all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Another irony is the fact that a decade ago, when Japanese
companies were buying up American icons like the Rockefeller
Center, some Americans engaged in unfettered Japan-bashing.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese-Americans and other Asian-Americans protested. Now we
have a Japanese-American politician unapologetically bashing Japan,
in the estimation of some other Japanese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   This dust-up certainly disabuses those naive enough to believe
Asian-Americans are of one mind politically and emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
