<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7495 &Cx1f; tad-z
s a BC-SEA-FAMILY-0905-COX     09-01 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEA-FAMILY-0905-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MISSING AT SEA: A FAMILY'S STORY OF STRUGGLE AND SURVIVAL
 &HT;    With Photos
 &HT;    Advance for Sunday, Sept. 5
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEAN CITY, Md. _ The Stewarts of southwestern Ohio had been at
sea for 11 days when they made this notation in the log they'd been
keeping: ``readying to abandon ship if nec (necessary).''
</P>
<P>
   The Jolly Joyce departed Newport, R. I., uneventfully on July
26, heading for Fort Lauderdale to see a marine mechanic they
trusted with the twin diesels in their 65-foot boat.
</P>
<P>
   Under sail, Rick and Deb Stewart, with their 16-year-old son and
12-year-old daughter, were making a few knots of headway with a
light breeze pulling the heavy, wooden hull through a small chop in
the Atlantic Ocean. The freedom of being underway was a release.
</P>
<P>
   For the Stewarts, the past year had been a rocky one filled with
high excitement and deadening frustration. Last Tuesday, in Ocean
City, Md., where the U.S. Coast Guard towed their boat several days
earlier and ended reports that they had been missing, the Stewarts
discussed their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   They were supposed to have made a dramatic leap from suburban
family in Ludlow Falls, Ohio, to vagabond sailors of the world last
November, but the transition was coming in halting spurts.
</P>
<P>
   The day they emptied their house in Ohio and put it on the
market last fall, they thought they'd never see it again. The boat
was in Fort Lauderdale, waiting, and they were eager to begin a few
years of exotic ports of call and home-schooling for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jolly Joyce wasn't ready as expected, and the Stewarts
did see their house again. At Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit of a downer,'' Deb, 47, said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest setback had been Newport itself, where a conspiracy
of more mechanical trouble and a local lack of necessary parts kept
them trapped at the dock for six long weeks. When the Stewarts
chose to depart, they promptly headed off shore to avoid the
powerful northward sweep of the Gulf Stream, and soon had sailed
out of contact with everyone on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Stewarts finally were at sea, bravely living a private
adventure they'd chosen as their mission only three years before.
But after days of radio silence, their family, friends and the
Coast Guard began thinking they'd been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have been the least worried of anybody,'' Rick Stewart
says now, with the Jolly Joyce pinned to a dock in Ocean City by
the peripheral winds of Hurricane Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   An air search turned up nothing because the Stewart's strategy
of dodging the Gulf Stream wasn't working. They'd taken off without
the use of the port engine, which needed to be rebuilt, and with
only emergency use of the starboard engine, which had a major oil
leak. The plan to sail all the way to Florida was meeting
significant resistance from the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Although the first days went well and Stewart laced his log book
entries with commentary on their progress that included words such
as ``nice'' and ``perfect direction,'' circumstances soon would
change.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, a series of violent thunderstorms halted their
southward progress and planted them in the Gulf Stream's path.
Their tenth night at sea was spent engulfed in a thunderstorm
``which refused to move and refused to release the boat. Both bilge
pumps failed forcing us to hand bail the bilge. (200 gals.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's on edge; need some sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   And the trouble wasn't behind them. More storms drove them
backward (``sure will be glad to get engines back!'') and tore the
sail on the mizzenmast, the smaller of the two at the back of the
boat. The bilge pump, which pulls water from the inner cavity of
the hull and pumps it overboard, still wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   And so they considered the possibility that they'd have to
abandon the boat. But the dire moments passed, if only to return,
and the Jolly Joyce plunged on against the sea. In the weeks that
followed, as the 10-day sailboat ride down to Florida stretched
into 34 days on the ocean, trouble plagued the Stewarts.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the mizzen, another storm kicked up and tore the
main sail at the corner point, called the clew, where the sail is
attached to lines that stretch it back. Using scraps of string they
pieced the sail together, only to see it break again. Three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, `Oh, the clew tore, OK let's put it back,''' said
Chad Stewart, 16.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a combination of heavy fishing line and nylon straps
provided a repair that withstood the elements.
</P>
<P>
   But on day 15, still less than halfway through their time at
sea, another storm (``lightning in all quadrants'') dealt a
crippling blow that ultimately helped determine that the Stewarts
wouldn't be going to Florida and would instead need to seek a port
where they could find it.
</P>
<P>
   The rudder broke.
</P>
<P>
   Riding six-foot seas in gale-force winds of 30 knots and more,
the wheel of the Jolly Joyce suddenly went dead. The autopilot
wouldn't hold coordinates and when Deb Stewart grabbed the wheel,
it spun freely.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, they discovered that the hydraulic system that connects
the wheel to the rudder had broken. And soon after that the
emergency tiller _ a metal pipe that fits on a peg atop the rudder
itself _ had broken, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbing in a tumultuous sea, the Stewarts began sailing and
drifting and sailing and drifting, steering their 60-ton ketch with
a screw driver jammed into the hole at the top of the rudder.
</P>
<P>
   When they had been back in port, where there had been nothing to
do for days on end, the Stewarts had begun reading the Bible. Not
in any serious, religious way, but simply as another valuable way
to spend time together. After watching the reruns of Seinfeld and
Jeopardy they could pick up on their small television, they read
passages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out OK,'' Deb said about goading the kids into
taking turns reading from the Bible, ``we had a lot of fun doing
it, and a lot of knowledge gained.''
</P>
<P>
   But at sea, who has time? Once, 12-year-old Mischa raced for the
Bible and began leafing through it for inspiration to a prayer when
the winch on the anchor pulled out of the deck and she was scared
to death. But that was months ago, in the Florida Keys on a short
trip designed to get them and their boat ready for a long cruise up
the eastern seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   Now, off in the Atlantic, the Stewarts were accustomed to their
roles and went about their business. They took turns trying to
steer with the screwdriver as they sought to raise a passing boat
for a radio check.
</P>
<P>
   For Rick Stewart, none of the strain that had enveloped them in
the weeks at sea was dampening his enthusiasm for the new life he'd
chosen for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the dock last week, he admitted he's a man who plunges
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere along in my life I decided I was going to do what I
want to do,'' Rick Stewart, 50, said. ``Money has never been that
important to me. I've made a lot and I've spent a fair amount.''
</P>
<P>
   When he wanted to be a pilot he went to an airfield, started
lessons and in due time had his license. Then he bought a plane,
then he bought more.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up all over the place, as his family moved with his
father's job as an executive with a national chain of bakeries that
operated under a variety of names, among them Colonial Bakery. When
the Anheuser-Busch Co. bought the bakery, one of its largest yeast
customers, the Stewart family ended up being large shareholder's in
the beer giant, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Stewart struck another stock deal when the Dayton, Ohio,
company where he was vice president and general counsel was bought
out. Allied Paper had been a division of Smith Corona Corp., and
specialized in making office forms and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Stewart has been in the video business, owning a pair of
Video Vault stores in southwestern Ohio. But he fantasizes about
owning a bar on an island somewhere, schmoozing with the customers,
and shoving off when he gets tired of it.
</P>
<P>
   Money isn't important. But Control is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't discouraging,'' Stewart said of their string or
problems at sea, ``because we were in control of our fate.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Coast Guard greeted them about 15 miles off the coast
of Maryland, Stewart declined an offer to be towed. Later that
night the Coast Guard returned and insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder,'' Deb said as her husband spoke, ``if we should be
doing this with the kids. If we should have waited until they were
18 to go do this ourselves because you feel guilty, you know, about
how much peril you're putting them in.''
</P>
<P>
   But Deb and Rick Stewart both said they like the way the kids
have responded to their trials at sea. They're more confident, and
more responsible. More familiar with the power of teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for them when it's all said and done,'' she said.
``The surprise is they're as far along as they are in this short
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
