<HEADLINE>
JACK LORD WASN'T MUCH FOR WRITING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Did the guy who used to star in ``Hawaii Five-O,'' Jack
Lord, ever write an autobiography? _ G.S., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ The fiercely private actor, who died in 1998 at age 77,
does not appear to have written any books. The closest he came to
revealing anything personal in print may have been Jack's Favorite
Watercress Soup, a recipe he and wife Marie Lord contributed to the
1974 ``Hawaiian Celebrities Cookbook''.
</P>
<P>
   A 1971 ``TV Guide'' article states that Jack Lord was planning a
book on Hawaii, but none turned up in a Library of Congress search.
</P>
<P>
   The article, which details Lord's efforts to control how he was
portrayed in the news media, quotes several things the actor added
to his network biography. Lord wrote that he was ``a highly
disciplined product of the theater, steeped in the art of acting''
and that he possessed ``a striking facial bone structure for which
the cameras have an affinity.''
</P>
<P>
   During his acting career, Lord also claimed to be born in 1930
rather than 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ What does it mean when the announcers on ESPN and other
channels say ``come join us, we are a part of the GO Network''? _
A.B., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ On Jan. 12, Disney and Infoseek launched the GO
Network, a World Wide Web site that combined Infoseek with several
successful Disney Internet properties: ABC, ABC News, Disney, ESPN,
Family.Com and Mr. Showbiz.
</P>
<P>
   The combined Web site attracts more than 20 million visitors
each month and is the fourth-most-visited ``portal'' on the
Internet, according to the technology news service CNET.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which is published at www.go.com, is mentioned
whenever a Disney TV channel's Web site is referred to on the air.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, Disney purchased 43 percent of Infoseek in
exchange for $70 million in cash and its ownership stake in
Starwave, a Web design company.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Is Turkish Taffy by Bonomo still being made? _ T.B.,
Whitinsville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ Turkish Taffy is no longer available, but Sweety's
Candies sells a similar-tasting product called ``DORK
double-flavored taffy.''
</P>
<P>
   The candy comes in chocolate/banana, blue raspberry/marshmallow,
strawberry/banana, and chocolate/cherry flavors, and sells for
$5.40 per carton of 36.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (888) 793-3897 or visit the World Wide Web site
mall0.register.com/sweetys.
</P>
<P>
   Sweety's sells dozens of unusual candies, including Candy
Flipstick taffy lipstick, Delfa Rolls, Squirrel Nut Zippers, Wax
Fangs and Wax Lips.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
