<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Stay Christian in College''
</P>
<P>
   By J. Budziszewski
</P>
<P>
   NavPress, $8
</P>
<P>
   J. Budziszewski's resume reads (in part): ``Former atheist, Yale
Ph.D. and 18-year faculty veteran of the University of Texas at
Austin.'' So his credentials for writing a book on retaining faith
while gaining a degree are about as good as those of any and better
than those of many.
</P>
<P>
   The university experience, Budziszewski observes in ``How to
Stay Christian in College,'' ``can be like moving to Mars.'' The
author sets his stage by discussing two views of the non-Christian
world _ its own and God's _ and then moves on to tackle common
myths and how to cope with campus social, religious and classroom
life.
</P>
<P>
   Budziszewski's style is blunt and common-sensical. Particularly
worthwhile are his observations on love and sex (''on guy myths my
comments will be about fifty percent longer because guys take more
convincing'') and discussing beliefs with others (''challenge the
ridicule _ but do so calmly, concisely and politely'').
</P>
<P>
   You may not agree with all of this academician's lecture, but
his class is worth the minimal tuition.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Back to My Roots''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Womack
</P>
<P>
   The Right Stuff
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Womack is best known for his R&AMP;B hits _ including
``Lookin' for a Love'' and ``It's All Over Now,'' the latter a hit
single for the Rolling Stones _ even though he started off singing
gospel as part of the Womack Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly enough, the new ``Back to My Roots'' is Womack's
first gospel CD, and it's a gem. R&AMP;B always stemed largely from
gospel, and the 17 tracks find Womack, 55, fusing the two and
putting his own stamp on a variety of standards, such as ``Jesus Be
a Fence Around Me,'' as well as Paul Simon's ``Bridge Over Troubled
Water.''
</P>
<P>
   Womack's grainy, gritty voice is still excellent, and he knows
just how to shape the favorites he has chosen. He rewrites Sam
Cooke's ``Stand by Me'' to include some overtly religious lyrics,
strolls through ``What a Friend We Have in Jesus,'' and imbues ``Oh
Happy Day'' with all the joy one could ask for.
</P>
<P>
   Womack has certainly been through his own problems (he's
admitted to past drug use), and to hear him praising Jesus and
doing so well is a real treat. He sounds like a survivor who
realizes how much he nearly lost, and how much he has to live for.
Any Womack fan _ and indeed, any gospel fan _ should add this to
his or her collection.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   .MDBR/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
