<HEADLINE>
INTERNET NOT YET A THREAT TO THE CAMPUS BOOKSTORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DANIELLE FURFARO   
 c.1999 Albany Times Union   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ College bookstores have enjoyed a virtual
monopoly on textbook sales for years. The Internet promised to
change that.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, it's just a promise. A spot check of textbook Web
sites indicates that e-commerce prices are not always cheaper, some
take weeks for delivery and choice is limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to look around in a bookstore where you know you
can find the books you need,'' said Mark Simmons, a junior at the
State University of New York at Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, professors at SUNY-Albany have given a list of
required and recommended books for each course to the school
bookstore, which is owned by the national retailer Barnes and
Noble. The store then makes sure that it has enough of each book
for all students taking a class.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY-Albany's only competitor for textbooks is Mary Jane Books,
a downtown retailer. However, since the independent textbook store
opened before the spring 1998 semester, most professors have
ignored the store's requests for book lists, making it difficult
for Mary Jane Books to compete with Barnes and Noble. The store has
sent Freedom of Information Act requests to both the administration
and the professors seeking the lists, according to Mary Jane Books
owner Adam Militello.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is still the university that is responsible,''
Militello said. ``It'll be a cold day in hell before I sue a
faculty member.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, several textbook stores and distributors opened
e-commerce sites, with inventories that cover the reading lists of
several courses offered at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Although these sites advertise prices discounted as much as 60
percent, many on-line sites charge higher prices than the Barnes
and Noble store at SUNY-Albany.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``Science of Ecology,'' which is required for a
biology course, costs $89 at the university's bookstore. At
efollett.com, a wholesale bookseller in Illinois, the book costs
$97. The company also charges a minimum shipping fee of $3.95 for
the first book and 95 cents for each additional book in the same
order. It also takes two to three weeks to ship.
</P>
<P>
   There were many books in a survey sample that were not available
from the site or only available new, even though the company bills
itself as the largest wholesaler of used books in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of prices of randomly selected textbooks required
for courses at SUNY-Albany, only one on-line site offered lower
prices than those of Barnes and Noble.
</P>
<P>
   That site is bigwords.com, a startup Internet company in San
Francisco that compiles the reading lists of classes across the
country by contacting professors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bookstores of public institutions have to give you the
reading list information, but it usually gets changed after you
receive it,'' said the company's co-founder, John Bates. ``If you
have a good relationship with the professors, they will give you
the updated information.''
</P>
<P>
   The company charges $78.12 for ``Science of Ecology.'' It does
not charge for regular three- to five-day shipping on orders of
more than $35, and there is no state sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-01-99 1530EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
