<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7574 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DIGITAL-ORGANISMS     09-01 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DIGITAL-ORGANISMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVOLVING DIGITALLY INTO RESPECTABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Michigan, California)  (dal) 
 By SARA ROBINSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Lenski, a biologist at Michigan State University, used
to study evolution by allowing bacteria to reproduce, generation
after generation, in a laboratory dish. Now he just lets digital
organisms run rampant in a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual organisms are small programs that, like computer
viruses, are capable of replicating over and over. But unlike
computer viruses, digital organisms can help, not harm: they can be
a tool for studying how real organisms change and adapt, an area
that has long stymied researchers because the evolutionary process
is slow.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper published last month in the journal Nature, Lenski
collaborated with Chris Adami, a physicist at the California
Institute of Technology, and others to create an artificial world
to study populations of digital organisms that replicate, mutate
and compete for resources. The researchers used a software program
called Avida, which was designed by Adami and one of his students,
Charles Ofria.
</P>
<P>
   ``The novelty for me is that here we have completely distinct
organisms that we can do genetics with,'' Lenski said. ``This is
throwing in a whole new class of organisms not derived from that
common ancestor on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of life-like creatures created by computer programs as a
tool for biological research is one aspect of a growing field of
research known as artificial life. While the field has existed for
decades, it has long been viewed with skepticism by some computer
scientists who dismiss it as eccentric and by some biologists who
believe that the study of artificial organisms does not have much
relevance to actual life forms.
</P>
<P>
   But Chris Langton, editor of the journal Artificial Life, said
the field was undergoing a quiet renaissance. The study by Lenski
and Adami is significant, he said, not so much because the
techniques are new or the conclusions startling. Rather, he said,
it represents an ``interesting collaboration'' between an
artificial life researcher and a well-respected biologist. And even
more significant, the study was published in Nature, one of the
world's premier research journals for biologists.
</P>
<P>
   Inman Harvey, a scientist at the University of Sussex in England
who wrote an article accompanying the paper in Nature, said he
concurred with Langton's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Lenski paper may well be a first in explicitly mentioning
artificial life techniques in such a prestigious journal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, each organism contained a command to copy itself
one line at a time before dividing in half and spawning another
organism. The copying process was intentionally made imperfect to
simulate the naturally occurring mutations of genes in living
organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Digital organisms that could perform certain simple mathematical
computations were rewarded with extra computer processing time _
the equivalent of the energy and nutrients for which real organisms
compete. That extra processing time, in turn, enabled the fittest
organisms to replicate more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers used their artificial world to study the effects
of mutations on evolution. The Avida program allowed them to
systematically mutate the genes of these creatures one at a time
and then study the effects thousands of generations later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can turn off and on any mechanism we want to study, which
is quite hard to do with living organisms,'' Adami said. ``It opens
up all kinds of avenues that you can go down. We can study 10,000
generations of these organisms then go back and change one thing
and then study 10,000 generations again.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lenski said he believed the method and philosophy of the
experiment was at least as interesting as the specific results of
the experiments, there were two findings he highlighted.
</P>
<P>
   The first was that the combined effect of multiple mutations was
greater than the sum of the effects of individual mutations.
Studies of evolution, Lenski explained, have often focused on the
effect of mutations of a single gene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we can generalize single-gene studies depends on
whether the interactions of multiple mutations have a big effect or
not,'' he said. In these digital organisms, interactions of
multiple mutations proved to be very significant, supporting the
conclusions of less exhaustive studies with real organisms.
</P>
<P>
   The second result was the finding that size and complexity _ in
this case the length and computational power of the digital
organism _ protects organisms against the harmful effects of
mutations. ``I don't know if people have asked that question _
whether complexity protects against mutations _ in real
organisms,'' Lenski said. ``It's a very rare lab that even works on
multiple organisms.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear whether digital organisms will become widely
accepted as research subjects among biologists in the future, but
Adami said that since the Nature article had appeared, other
biological researchers had expressed strong interest in his
software.
</P>
<P>
   While his software used to be downloaded fewer than 10 times
each week, Adami said, it has been downloaded 4,000 to 5,000 times
since the Nature article appeared on Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biologists haven't been able to make sweeping studies on life
as a whole,'' he said. ``We think this has created a new avenue of
research.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
