<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7579 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-WEBCAMS-ART-1000&AMP;     09-01 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEBCAMS-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURING NOT-SO-STILL LIFE: WEBCAMS IN MANY FLAVORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and NYT
graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By JENNIFER 8. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spam decomposing on a plate, penguins falling on their faces and
a cubicle dweller coping with day-to-day office life: Webcams have
brought out an odd combination of the voyeur and exhibitionist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cam,'' like .com, has become a trendy technological suffix for
sites like the Spam Cam (www.fright.com/spam/spamcam.html), the
Penguincam (www.discovery.com/cams/penguin/penguinmain.html) and
the Davecam (ranier.oact.hq.nasa.gov/staff/davecam.shtm).
</P>
<P>
   There is Kremlinkam, Fogcam, Trafficam. Animals, in particular,
seem to draw large Internet audiences to sites like Puppy Cam,
Catcam, Sharkcam. They are overshadowed only by webcams that cater
to voyeurs, like the well-known Jennicam. Last year there was
Monicacam, which surveyed the building office doors of Monica
Lewinsky's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for Webcams have become reasonable; rebates and discounts
available for many models can bring the cost of Webcams down
sharply from list prices. For less than $100 and a dial-up Internet
connection, home computer users can set up their own cameras, hook
them up to the World Wide Web and become one-person broadcast
studios.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Ringley, of Jennicam fame, uses four Webcams for her
broadcasts, including a Connectix Quickcam Pro, a model now sold
under the Logitech name. That model was also featured in a pivotal
scene in the recent movie ``American Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 Webcams are sold each day, according to NPD
Intelect, a market tracking firm in Port Washington, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   All Webcams on the market can take single shots and can record
digital video. Single shots can be used to update Web pages, can be
sent via e-mail to friends and relatives or can be manipulated in
photo editing programs.
</P>
<P>
   Digital video feeds allow business executives and families to
talk over the Internet, emulating the futuristic videophones in the
``Jetsons'' cartoons. Webcams with motion sensor capabilities have
also found a niche as security devices for computers _ you leave it
on and if someone moves nearby it captures the image.
</P>
<P>
   The market leader for home Webcams is Logitech, which has models
compatible with Macs and PCs. Other large manufacturers are
Panasonic, Creative Labs, Intel and Kodak; all of them sell Webcams
in the $80-to-$130 price range, mostly for PCs. The brand-name
companies are popular because of their warranties and level of
technical support, but low-cost cameras can also succeed. Ezonics
has carved out a niche with its Ezcam, which costs less than $50
after a rebate.
</P>
<P>
   A Webcam consists of a digital camera and software, which are
sold as a package. When selecting the camera, the most important
things to consider are picture quality, the maneuverability of the
camera (how well it pans or tilts) and the cost. In the last two
years, Webcams have improved in quality while dropping in price.
</P>
<P>
   But home digital studios still have a long way to go; the
quality of the pictures is far from that seen on television or in
camcorder shots. Lighting in the Webcam world is seldom flattering,
the pictures are jerky, and the resolution is poor. Nonetheless,
users still find it a great novelty to see their own movements
captured on computer monitors for the very first time.
</P>
<P>
   The installation of Webcams has been standardized. Almost all
manufacturers sell PC models that feature Universal Serial Bus, or
USB, ports, and some still sell versions with parallel and serial
port connections.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, installing a Webcam meant digging into the
innards of the computer to put in a video capture card. USB
connections mean that users are ready to go after plugging in the
camera and popping in a software CD _ barring any software
glitches, which can be a nightmare to solve.
</P>
<P>
   Computers manufactured after 1996 probably have USB ports. For
earlier models, USB cards can be purchased for $30 to $150 to plug
into the PCI slot. (A computer that is too old for a PCI slot is
probably not powerful enough to handle a Webcam's video feed.)
</P>
<P>
   The minimum system requirements for a PC are: Windows 95 or
later, a Pentium 100-megahertz chip or faster and 16 megabytes of
RAM and 10 megabytes of free hard-disk space.
</P>
<P>
   The main components of Webcams are analogous to those in the
human eye. A Webcam has a lens; a sensor, which captures images
like a retina, and a computer chip, which acts like a brain to
translate the light patterns into data.
</P>
<P>
   Glass lenses generally produce better pictures than plastic
ones. But glass lenses are also up to three times as expensive so
the Webcams designed for home users tend to have plastic lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Two types of resolution are available for sensors. Common
Interchange Format, or CIF, sensors cost a lot less than Video
Graphics Array, or VGA, sensors but have only one-third the
resolution. The greatest resolution for home Webcams is 640 by 480
pixels, the VGA resolution. Any resolution higher than that has
been augmented by software.
</P>
<P>
   VGA Webcams have sold for $140 and up, but prices recently
dipped below the $100 mark. Creative Labs recently came out with a
VGA Webcam III priced at $80.
</P>
<P>
   There are two competing technologies for image sensors:
Complementary Metal Oxide Silicon, or CMOS, and Charged-Coupled
Devices, or CCD. While CMOS is less expensive, smaller and uses
less power, it is not as efficient as CCD in very low light.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, bright light causes CCD sensors to produce a
halo-like effect known as light bloom. But in most lighting
situations, both types perform comparably. All cameras work best
with soft diffused lighting hitting the face.
</P>
<P>
   An important, but not critical distinction between home Webcams
is in how fast they can capture images. Webcams, like film, create
moving images by capturing a succession of still images, or frames.
The higher the number of frames per second, the higher the quality.
</P>
<P>
   The recommended minimum frame rate is 12 to 15 frames per
second. A rate of 30 is good, and 40 will give very smooth quality.
The maximum rate is usually possible for only the smallest picture
sizes on the computer. As the size of the picture goes up, the
frame speed goes down. For videoconferencing, however, the speed of
the connection rather than the speed of the camera is usually the
limiting factor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some optional features to consider include shutter buttons,
microphones and the length of the cord. Shutter buttons allow the
user to snap pictures manually instead of having the software
solely in charge. Built-in microphones are not vital because
microphones and sound cards are often installed separately.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the ideal position for microphones is not the same
as the ideal position for cameras. Long cords give the user more
freedom in deciding where to place a Webcam. The Kodak DVC323, for
example, has a generous 10-foot cord.
</P>
<P>
   All Webcams come with basic photograph and video capturing
software. The more expensive models come with high-end photo
editing programs like Adobe Photodeluxe, a lower-end version of
Adobe's well-known Photoshop software.
</P>
<P>
   Webcams intended for a more sophisticated audience also include
videoconferencing software, like Microsoft's Netmeeting. Other
popular programs allow for automatic Web page updating and security
functions. Most software can be mixed and matched with different
cameras, and many shareware programs are also available for
downloading from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Parents should be aware that the Net teleconferencing software
has opened up a new level of prank calls. ``The plain fact is that
there are people who are very into being exhibitionist,'' said Jim
Carlton, a senior brand manager for Creative Labs. ``Every once in
a while,'' he said, ``people call up to show me their private
bits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7581 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DISTANCE-LEARNING     09-01 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DISTANCE-LEARNING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLICK HERE FOR THE IVORY TOWER: ELITE SCHOOLS AND ONLINE LEARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa., Calif., N.Y., Ariz., N.C.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For almost as long as students have been going off to college,
educators have been trying to bring college home to them. More than
100 years ago at Cornell University, professors traveled to rural
areas on horseback to teach farmers about the latest agricultural
research. Correspondence courses have been available for decades,
through the mail at first, and then through television and video.
</P>
<P>
   But the development of the Internet has created new excitement
around what has become known as distance learning. This summer a
startup company called UNext.Com, based in Deerfield, Ill.,
announced a venture that is one of the most ambitious yet:
delivering executive training and, eventually, a full M.B.A. over
the Internet. This summer, UNext.com christened its virtual school
Cardean University after the Roman goddess who could, ``open what
is shut, and shut what is open,'' in the words of a company press
release, quoting Ovid.
</P>
<P>
   The plan attracted attention not only because one of the initial
investors was former junk-bond king Michael Milken, but because of
the five prestigious institutions the company had brought on board
_ the University of Chicago, Columbia University, Carnegie Mellon
University, Stanford University, and the London School of Economics
and Political Science _ a veritable all-star team of elite
universities.
</P>
<P>
   According to the proposed plan, UNext.Com would produce, market,
and distribute the courses _ as well as hiring a corps of employees
to serve as mentors and e-mail correspondents for UNext.Com's
students. The universities would provide the curriculum and the
impressive credentials, without risking their endowments on untried
technology. Some of them have projected that they will earn at
least $20 million in royalties from UNext.Com within five to eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way to embark on distance education by using what
others bring to it,'' said John Preis, associate dean for finance
and administration at Columbia University's School of Business.
``We think this is a home run.'' Distance learning, it seems, has
come of age.
</P>
<P>
   But has it? Since the dawn of the Web in the mid-1990s, the
concept of earning degrees entirely online has become a rallying
point for university presidents, politicians and profit-seekers
alike. Yet while millions of people are diving into online shopping
malls and chat rooms, virtual universities have been something of a
bust.
</P>
<P>
   Western Governors University, a venture started by 17 states and
Guam, opened its online doors to much fanfare last year but has
only enrolled 120 students, far below its projections. California
Virtual University, a project initiated by California Board of
Regents in 1997, folded this spring, citing financial problems.
Many other virtual university projects have appeared to be nothing
more than online catalogs of courses that can only be taken for
credit by students who are already on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be the joke of the 21st century,'' said
Carole Fungaroli, a lecturer in English at Georgetown University
who is writing a book about the value of university degrees. ``I
don't see anything that these people are offering that you can't
get better on campus.''
</P>
<P>
   One place that the distance education concept has been
successful is Wall Street, where analysts' reports are thick with
data on the rapidly growing adult-student market. The Apollo Group,
the company that runs the University of Phoenix, an accredited
institution that offers online degrees, has seen its stock soar
more than 1,500 percent since 1994. Apollo, which also operates
other educational programs, now has a market capitalization of $1.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at the universities that have signed up with
UNext.com readily admit that the possibility of becoming part
owners of a publicly traded Internet company was a part of
UNext.Com's attraction. ``I was less interested in the income
stream than in the market capitalization of UNext.Com,'' Columbia
business school dean Meyer Feldberg told The Wall Street Journal.
``The huge upside essentially is the value of the equity in the
IPO.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been other concerns raised about UNext.com. The
management of the company is made up of several Chicago professors,
including John P. Gould, a former dean of the university's business
school, and two Nobel laureates, Gary Becker and Merton H. Miller.
Several other members of the Chicago faculty have publicly raised
questions about conflicts of interest. Whose interests will be
served, the company's or the institutions who need to protect their
good names and academic integrity?
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneur behind UNext.com is Andrew Rosenfield, a
business consultant and University of Chicago alumnus who was
running Lexecon, a company that employed many of the same people
who are now involved in UNext.Com. Over the last decade, he has
also served as a part-time law professor and trustee for the
university, remaining immersed in the culture of an institution
known not only for breeding free-market intellectuals but also for
being strongly resistant to change.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, Rosenfield started thinking about about
creating an Internet-based education company that would be both a
radical departure and a continuation of the values of his alma
mater. He wanted to create an online environment that would be
``the technological equivalent of the small break-out session or
the evening at the coffee shop, where students really teach each
other.'' He also wanted to reach students outside the United States
who want access to education delivered by American universities but
who cannot travel to get it.
</P>
<P>
   He mulled the idea over with Becker _ his former professor and
now longtime friend, who had won his Nobel prize for his theories
about human capital. The two brainstormed over lunch at the
University of Chicago's faculty club and while watching Chicago
Bulls games.
</P>
<P>
   The first investor for the company, which was founded in
December, 1997, was Knowledge Universe, a company owned in part by
Milken. His involvement stirred gossip throughout the
higher-education community last year, when Rosenfield started to
shop his idea around to select universities. By the time Rosenfield
has signed up his first partner _ Columbia University, in March
1999 _ the contracts included the condition that Milken's
investment would never exceed a 20 percent ownership stake and that
he would have no voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four months, four more universities signed on, the
last being Carnegie Mellon, which struck a deal in July. Other
universities, like Cornell, were approached by UNext.com to be
pioneering members but declined. Cornell has already developed its
own distance-education technology, said Jonathon Levy, executive
director of Cornell's distance-education office.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that the partnership could damage the universities'
academic credibility. The quality associated with getting a degree
from these schools cannot be replicated on the Internet, said John
K. Wilson, an outspoken graduate student at the University of
Chicago who has written columns accusing administrators of jumping
in blindly with ``dollar signs in their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   University administrators have responded vaguely to questions
about how much the deals may be worth. Preis, at Columbia
University, confirmed reports that his institution expects to make
at least $20 million in five to eight years. Other university
administrators said that they expected the same return.
</P>
<P>
   But UNext.com would not confirm the $20-million figure. ``That's
the universities' expectation,'' said Edwin Eisendrath, UNext.com's
spokesman. Eisendrath added that not every university signed the
same deal. He would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Within the faculties themselves, the reaction to the announced
deals has also ranged from approval to confusion. Administrators at
some of the participating schools have pleaded ignorance about
exactly what the deal means and who will be affected. At Chicago, a
committee was formed to talk about UNext.com before the deal was
struck, but at Columbia University most professors awoke to an
announcement of the deal without any prior consultation. In
Carnegie Mellon's case, a Chicago public-relations firm sent out an
announcement about the university's involvement before the
university's press office had a chance to see the release and fix
several errors in it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some professors are wondering what involvement with
UNext.com will mean to their scholarly reputations, the coin of the
realm in the academic world? Robert Connolly, a professor in the
business school at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill,
has worked with another distance-education company, called
University Access, to create several economics courses using the
Web and videotape. The experience, he said, has improved his
teaching skills but hurt his standing in his department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get people in my own school to talk to me about it,''
Connolly said. Colleagues who have been willing to acknowledge his
distance-education work expect that his research _ a professor's
ticket to tenure _ must be suffering, he said. ``They look at it
and say, `If you are spending time on that, that takes time away
from your research and publishing.'''
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of University Professors has also asked
questions about teaching quality. Last spring, when an online
university called Jones International University became the first
completely Internet-based school to gain accreditation, the
association wrote a letter of protest to the accrediting agency.
The letter cited ``major worries about the denigration of quality''
that could come with online education.
</P>
<P>
   Most distance-education courses are not cheap, either. In the
spring of 1998, a Baltimore based company called the Caliber
Learning Network has persuaded three universities _ the University
of Pennsylvania, Johns Hopkins University, and the University of
Southern California _ to join it in offering business courses via
satellite television and the Internet. Tuition is high: Students
who take the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton Direct program
pay $2,500 each for six-week courses.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the students can afford to attend, according to Alison
Pierce, Wharton Direct's director, because they are already in
upper-income brackets and the companies for which they work pick up
most of the tab.
</P>
<P>
   While UNext.com expects to benefit from companies'
tuition-reimbursement programs as well, it will offer lower tuition
prices, Rosenfield said. The company has not yet set its prices,
but the cost of an Internet-based education, he said, should not be
more than that of attending schools in person.
</P>
<P>
   Still, critics ask, what will a degree from Cardean University
be worth? Ms. Fungaroli has called such online programs ``a new
version of a trade school.''
</P>
<P>
   And students who enroll in M.B.A. programs from Stanford or the
University of Chicago, argued Wilson, are doing so to build
networks of contacts. ``There is a real question about whether the
`good-old boy's network,''' he said, ``can be created in the same
way it is created in elite business schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But IBM, UNext.Com's first customer, is willing to to give the
concept a try as a way to encourage their employees to learn
without losing them to on-campus business schools. The computer
company will offer its employees a course in finance this year. IBM
is also a partner in the UNext.Com venture; the courses are being
delivered through Lotus Learning Space, a piece of software
developed by Lotus, an IBM subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield admits that UNext.com does not plan to offer a full
M.B.A. online for years. Until then, the company will focus on
executive training. UNext.Com is not being structured, Rosenfield
stressed, to attempt to compete with what universities are already
offering on campus.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Rosenfield himself thinks that on-campus education is
the best way to learn. ``Replication is probably too high a
standard,'' Rosenfield said. ``For people who have the ability to
attend facilities-based schools, we recommend it.'' But, he asked,
why not also attempt to create a worthwhile experience for people
who cannot attend those schools?
</P>
<P>
   ``They will not have direct interaction,'' he continued, ``but
what they will have is the wisdom of professors and pieces of their
knowledge that are captured and scalable. And they will have
supporting resources and mentors who are their guides.''
</P>
<P>
   So would Rosenfield take these courses? ``Absolutely,'' he said.
``The days when you ended your education at college, or graduate
school, are truly over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
