<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRISCOE-SLAVERY-ART-8     09-01 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRISCOE-SLAVERY-ART-830WORDS(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOVELIST FILLS IN SLAVERY'S BLANKS WITH IMAGINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New York, Virginia)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All the family photographs of the writer Connie
Briscoe recently displayed in the HarperCollins lobby in midtown
Manhattan burst with tales to be told. One in particular, though,
captured at once the complexity of her family, American history and
Ms. Briscoe's latest novel.
</P>
<P>
   The caption for the sepia-toned photograph of three young male
ancestors, whose mother was a slave, notes that as an adult one
disappeared for some years. The family believed that he was
``passing'' for white. He resurfaced in Boston years later, with a
white wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Briscoe, who has sold over a million copies of her two
novels about the romantic travails of buppies, or black urban
professionals, has ventured into her past and into slavery for her
new book, ``A Long Way From Home,'' released last month. It is the
story of two of Ms. Briscoe's ancestors, Susan and Ellen, who were
born as slaves on the Montpelier, Va., plantation of President
James Madison. It was Susan's son Oliver Jr. who ostensibly decided
to take advantage of his white ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Both Susan, Ms. Briscoe's great-great-grandmother, and Susan's
sister, Ellen, were light enough in color to appear to be white. As
a child, Ms. Briscoe recalled looking at their photographs and
asking her family why they looked white and wondering what their
lives were like. As an adult, Ms. Briscoe began researching her
ancestry and filled the rest in with fiction.
</P>
<P>
   What results is a book that Ms. Briscoe counts as her first with
wide appeal beyond her core readers, black women, who put ``Sisters
and Lovers'' and ``Big Girls Don't Cry'' on best-seller lists. Like
those two novels, the new book is more in the category of popular
commercial fiction, rather than literary fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ms. Briscoe said, white readers come to her book readings
and ask about the dual racial heritage of many black families as
well as some of their own presumably white ones. On the West Coast
some of her audiences have been predominantly white. At the same
time, she said, her faithful fans of the stories of the lives and
loves of the black middle class have thanked her for telling ``our
story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As I did the book tour, I met many black women who had the
same experience,'' Ms. Briscoe said. ``It's a side of slavery and
that era we don't talk about, but it's an open secret. There are a
lot of us walking around who don't know who our great-grandfather
was or hear stories about white ancestors.''
</P>
<P>
   While the news releases put out by HarperCollins describe Ms.
Briscoe as ``the descendant of the slaves on the Madison family
plantation,'' her novel leaves hints rather than giving direct
answers about the paternity of Susan and Ellen. Ms. Briscoe never
answered the question herself, after wading through her old family
Bibles, letters, photographs and documents in various libraries and
archives. Many records were lost, destroyed or simply badly kept.
It was common for slaves not to know their birth date or even the
names of both parents.
</P>
<P>
   Family lore has it, though, that Susan and Ellen's father was a
white plantation master. In the novel he buys his own enslaved
daughter to be a nursemaid to the children of his ``legitimate''
white daughter. In the novel, as in real life, Susan's husband,
Oliver Armistead, was negotiating her freedom with her putative
father when the Civil War erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, when a slave had a white father, they kept it hidden
from the white family to protect the child,'' said Ms. Briscoe, who
did extensive research of the plight of female slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up hearing that Susan and Ellen's father was the master
of the plantation,'' Ms. Briscoe said. ``It was never said James
Madison was the father but that it was the master, and that he
would come into the room at night and give the children a penny.
All I knew was that Susan was sold between the ages of 12 and 14 to
be a nursemaid. And she was bought by her father.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Long Way From Home'' opens in the 1830s. The story is
initially told through the eyes of Clara, a 10-year-old house
slave. As a young woman she becomes pregnant but refuses to reveals
the identify of the child's father, who is white. She has two
children: Ellen and then Susan. The girls wonder who their father
is and why their mother refuses to talk about him. They know only
that he is ``a real important white man from Richmond.''
</P>
<P>
   When plans are made to sell Ellen off the plantation, her family
hides her. Instead of Ellen, the plantation owners sell Susan, who
is torn from the arms of her wailing mother. When Susan arrives at
the home of Willard Montgomery, or Mass Willard, her new master in
Richmond, she recognizes him as the man who gave her and her sister
a penny every night as children. She wonders if he is her father.
She continues to wonder, even as the Civil War breaks out. She
marries and dreams of being reunited with her sister and mother.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   As the fortunes of the South crumble and Susan prepares to flee
Richmond with her new husband (moments before, the white family had
tried to persuade her to stay), Mass Willard hands her a velvet
sack of coins.
</P>
<P>
   ``But just like back then, he wasn't prepared to give her what
he'd denied her all these years, what she wanted most. An identity.
A real family. So she wanted nothing else from him.''
</P>
<P>
   The topic of so-called miscegenation has been in the news lately
because of the DNA tests indicating that Thomas Jefferson probably
fathered at least one child with Sally Hemings, a woman he owned.
The efforts of the black branch of the Jefferson family to be
recognized have also made headlines and generated lively debates
about identity and the inherent contradictions of slavery in a
nation whose founders spoke so eloquently of personal freedom as
the cornerstone of the new republic.
</P>
<P>
   James Madison, the fourth President, was a slave owner and
master of a 2,700-acre Virginia plantation. He was also the chief
proponent of the federal bill of rights. He and his wife, Dolley,
had no children.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago at the invitation of the staff at the Montpelier
estate, Ms. Briscoe visited and gave a talk about her research for
the novel. She said she met other descendants of Madison slaves.
When it comes to the white Madisons, ``I feel no sense of kinship
or entitlement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Briscoe, 46, who lives in Virginia and grew up in
Washington, is thin and sandy-haired. She wears a diamond
engagement ring, given to her by a man she met on the Internet. She
says she spends no time feeling sorry for herself or other black
people and says that awareness of the wrenching abuses that black
people historically endured can put steel in the spine of
African-Americans today.
</P>
<P>
   She herself is an example of graciousness meeting adversity. Ms.
Briscoe was born with a mild hearing loss resulting from a genetic
abnormality, but in her late 20s she went from a 20 percent hearing
loss to an 80 percent loss. She can read lips and uses a
sign-language interpreter. She also speaks, although her diction is
somewhat muffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a rather difficult period,'' she said of her
hearing loss. ``I was going through a divorce, too.'' The hearing
loss took place over several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you can't hear things on the phone,'' she said. ``Then
you can't hear it ring. You make excuses for what's happening. Then
you get to the point you can't ignore it anymore. I went though the
period of the doctors, the emotional adjustment, but I'm lucky I
have a supportive family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up to think that you don't let things hold you
back,'' Ms. Briscoe said. ``My parents never allowed me to think I
was handicapped or this was an excuse so I couldn't do all the
things I dreamed of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Briscoe found her own measure of freedom in 1994 when she
left a job as managing editor of The American Annals of the Deaf at
Gallaudet University to pursue a writing career. She uses index
cards and character sketches to develop her main characters. It was
a challenge, she said, to write a novel about slavery that would
appeal to her contemporary readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``By not looking into our history and our past in a realistic
way, we are depriving our young people,'' Ms. Briscoe said. ``We
are too accepting of the history of ourselves that has been handed
down and written about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
