<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LA-EXHIBIT-NYT &LR;      09-01 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG-AGO CELEBRITY GRABS THE LOS ANGELES SPOTLIGHT ONCE MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ She sits on a rustic throne like Britannia
herself, clothed in a richly embroidered gown, with an enormous
pearl necklace around her swan's neck. In striking half-profile
this imposing figure stares upward as if transported to some
far-off world. The woman is Sarah Siddons (1755-1831), the English
tragedienne, and the view is that of Sir Joshua Reynolds, in his
painting ``Sarah Siddons as the Tragic Muse'' (1784).
</P>
<P>
   The portrait, arguably Reynolds' finest, normally hangs at the
Huntington Art Collections in San Marino, a Los Angeles suburb. But
until Sept. 19 it can be viewed some 25 miles from its home, at the
J. Paul Getty Museum in the Brentwood section of Los Angeles. The
painting is the centerpiece of a small exhibit, ``A Passion for
Performance: Sarah Siddons and Her Portraitists.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which features 10 works in oil by esteemed artists
like Thomas Lawrence, George Romney, Gilbert Stuart and Thomas
Gainsborough, examines the nature of 18th-century fame through the
prism of the current era's infatuation with celebrity. Though
Siddons was primarily a subject of fascination for British
audiences, she also enjoyed renown in America.
</P>
<P>
   Few outside academic circles recognize Siddons today. If she is
known at all, aside from her portraits, it is because of the film
``All About Eve,'' in which the characters played by Bette Davis
and Anne Baxter vie for a fictitious Sarah Siddons Award. Yet the
real Sarah Siddons was an actress of legendary talent and
following. An unconventional beauty acclaimed for her portrayal of
Lady Macbeth (she was also a sensation in such now-neglected works
of her day as ``The Tragedy of Isabella'' and ``The Tragedy of Jane
Shore''), Siddons possessed the most famous profile of any actor
until perhaps John Barrymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 18th century actors were the most celebrated figures
after royalty,'' said Robyn Asleson, a research associate for
British art at the Huntington and the curator of ``A Passion for
Performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Siddons reveled in that celebrity, and she took it to new
heights, paving the way for actors like Henry Irving and Sarah
Bernhardt in the 19th century and Ralph Richardson, John Gielgud
and Laurence Olivier in the 20th. Hollywood, too, owes Siddons a
great debt. ``She certainly pioneered the whole notion of a star
culture for women,'' said Ms. Asleson.
</P>
<P>
   It is in that spirit that the Getty exhibition and a companion
show at the Huntington, ``Cultivating Celebrity: Portraiture as
Publicity in the Career of Sarah Siddons,'' have been assembled.
The Huntington exhibition, which Ms. Asleson also supervised,
comprises a host of smaller portraits and ephemera related to the
actress and closes on the same day as the Getty show.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was famous so young that practically every scrap of paper
she ever touched has been preserved,'' said Ms. Asleson, noting
that hundreds of Siddons relics survive.
</P>
<P>
   The Huntington show features only a selection of the cache, but
among the etchings and chalk drawings on display are watercolor
caricatures mocking her elaborate costumes, wax heads of Siddons
and her brother, the actor John Philip Kemble, and a battered
manuscript copy of Thomas Campbell's ``De Montfort: A Tragedy''
filled with Siddons' editorial comments. In a nod to the present
the show also includes a movie prop that once belonged to Bette
Davis, her Sarah Siddons award from ``All About Eve,'' inscribed to
``Miss Margo Channing.''
</P>
<P>
   A chance encounter at the Dulwich Picture Gallery in London in
1995 inspired these shows. Mark Leonard, the conservator of
paintings at the Getty, was visiting the gallery when he glimpsed a
well-known copy, credited to Reynolds, of the famous Siddons
portrait. The Dulwich painting, which dates from 1789, seemed an
ideal candidate for restoration, and so discussions began about
flying it to California, where it would be cleaned and compared
with its inspiration, the Huntington's ``Sarah Siddons as the
Tragic Muse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Getty does not charge for restoration but reserves the right
to display works for six months after the conservation effort.
Leonard said he felt that placing the Dulwich copy of the Reynolds
portrait alongside the Huntington painting could prove the basis
for a show. After all, the paintings had not been in the same room
for more than 200 years. He asked Shelley Bennett, the Huntington's
curator of British and European art, if she would sanction such a
show, and she agreed, releasing Reynolds' portrait from the
Huntington for the first time since its acquisition in 1921.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Dulwich and Huntington portraits were X-rayed as part
of the Getty's study and restoration process. The X-rays revealed
that the Dulwich picture was not painted by Reynolds but rather by
an unidentified studio assistant. By contrast the Huntington's
painting was confirmed to be entirely Reynolds' work, an unexpected
finding given that artists of his stature frequently delegated some
details to underlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big surprise,'' said Ms. Asleson. ``Up until that
point, we didn't know how we would handle this aspect of the
exhibit, because we didn't know what the study would turn up.''
</P>
<P>
   But more than questions of provenance were illuminated by the
X-rays. They demonstrated that the striking composition and elegant
sense of proportion in Reynolds' portrait (and the inferior Dulwich
copy) were not achieved effortlessly. The X-rays proved that
Reynolds made several substantial changes to his canvas before
pronouncing it completed.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said a putto, or cherub, once knelt at Siddons' feet,
and her dress, now brownish-gold, was originally blue. More
significant, one of the shadowy allegorical figures that flank
Siddons was different. In the finished painting, she is framed by
Pity on her right and Terror on her left, a nod to Aristotle's
conception of tragedy. But Terror, as the X-rays show, replaced
Melancholy, a kind of Hamlet-like figure with chin resting on fist.
Photographs of the X-rays are displayed at the entrance to the
Getty's Siddons exhibition. In an effort to surpass traditional
expectations for museum exhibitions, the Getty also commissioned a
play, hoping it would shed light Siddons' career and her continuing
impact on the theater. ``The Affliction of Glory: A Comedy About
Tragedy,'' by Frank Dwyer, was produced in association with the
Mark Taper Forum and runs at the Getty through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for an accompanying play was Leonard's. Dwyer, whose
play jumps through time to mix modern fictional characters with
18th-century figures like Siddons, Reynolds and George III, said,
``I found myself challenged writing about a woman who made men weep
and women hysterical.''
</P>
<P>
   A relentless self-promoter who took up sculpture because she was
so dissatisfied with the plaster busts made in her image, Siddons
would undoubtedly applaud the tributes at the Getty and Huntington.
And how could she not? At these exhibits, and in Dwyer's play, she
is a star once more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
