<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGINIA-RETREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOT THE EXPRESSWAY BLUES? GO SOUTH, YOUNG GARDENER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MARTHA BAKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Come the weekend, when half of Manhattan is packing
shorts and cell phones for a mass migration to the beach, two of
its number are making a beeline for the South.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour's plane ride later (even as others, sustained by a
kind of grim fatalism, are still inching along the Long Island
Expressway), these same two are already enjoying the amenities of
their weekend retreat in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   But for Garren, of the Garren New York hair salon at Henri
Bendel, and a fellow Bendel's hair stylist, Thom Priano, time and
traffic weren't the sole reasons for making Richmond their getaway
of choice.
</P>
<P>
   While visiting friends there in 1980, they were charmed by the
leisurely pace, the old plantations along the James River and the
city's obvious reverence for the past. (In Richmond, history is
taken seriously, as the Confederate memorials lining Monument
Avenue reflect.)
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate lure, however, was a house they had seen on that
initial trip: a property so impressive that in 1990, when it
finally came on the market, they snapped it up in a New York
nanosecond.
</P>
<P>
   No prizes for guessing why. Located in a 300-acre enclave of
trees and lakes known as Byrd Park, the Mediterranean-style villa
sits on Mansion Row, the park's only residential block, alongside
similar European-inspired estates developed there in the 1920s and
'30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in our own little world here, walled in, away from
everything,'' Garren said. ``It's so solitary, it's like
floating.'' For two men whose talents are in constant demand by
salon patrons and magazine editors (Priano is also overseeing the
development of a line of hair-care products that will be sold at
the Garren New York salon this fall), solitude is an alluring
prospect at the end of a workweek.
</P>
<P>
   And the price was right. Ten years ago, Mansion Row was in a
state of genteel dilapidation. Garren and Priano, who wouldn't
divulge the price of the property, figure that the renovations on
their garden were paid for by what they saved on the house, had
they settled in, say, the Hamptons or Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The house was built in 1934 for Webster Rhodes, an owner of the
Miller &AMP; Rhodes department stores. After several years in
residence, Rhodes married and traded his Mediterranean bachelor
digs for more traditional Virginia brick, and other owners
succeeded him. By the time Garren and Priano bought the house, it
was more than a half-century old, and restorative measures had
become imperative.
</P>
<P>
   First on their to-do list was the badly needed repair of the
stucco walls that had been damaged by tenacious blankets of ivy.
Then came a bit of remodeling, including the striking conversion of
a dark, screened-in back porch into an airy loggia with
ceiling-high glass doors that open onto the terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently located near the kitchen, the loggia and terrace
were to be living room and focal point for outdoor entertaining,
which, given the Virginia climate, can extend all the way from
early March to late December. But the garden it overlooked _ in
fact, the entire property _ was such a jungle of bamboo plants and
other rampant growth that even the swimming pool was hidden from
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Although the identity of the garden's original designer isn't
entirely certain, strong evidence points to the landscape architect
Charles Gillette, famed for his classic Virginia gardens.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Gillette is known to have been a friend of
Webster Rhodes; for another, the garden's distinctive formal style,
complete with pool, parterre and pergola, is typical of Gillette's
work in the region. So, five years ago, when the new owners hired
Doug Wood, a Richmond-based landscape designer, to return their
garden to its former glory, Charles Gillette was the inspiration
for his design.
</P>
<P>
   After the jungle was conquered and the pool repaired, the real
landscaping began. Part of the restoration involved accommodating
original plantings, like the 70-year-old beech tree that rises from
a mossy bed on the front lawn. To prevent the moss from browning in
winter, Wood devised a special sprinkler system to keep it
constantly watered.
</P>
<P>
   Wood also introduced new plants to complement the old ones. He
mixed traditional Southern-zone favorites (Cornus florida dogwoods,
magnolias and cypress) with a selection of northern varieties,
which, with some exceptions (lilacs, for example), do very well in
this temperate climate. What resulted were three separate gardens,
lovely enough to have pleased the great Gillette himself.
</P>
<P>
   Lying in direct view of the loggia and terrace is the pool
garden, which consists of a formal parterre with corner beds of
white impatiens, the pool area itself and, at the far end, a stucco
pergola, its roof thick with wisteria vines.
</P>
<P>
   Framed by paths of herringbone brick, the garden has walls of
towering azaleas: giant-flowered, free-form varieties like the pink
George Tabor and white Gigi Gerbing. Fragrant gardenias thrive
here, too, as do puffy hydrangeas, spiraling topiaries of juniper,
and crape myrtle shrubs that explode in a burst of coral blossoms
throughout July and August.
</P>
<P>
   To the left of the pool garden is the fountain garden, so named
to mark a pedimented wall fountain that was discovered only after
runaway growth was cleared. Now, it's the focus for a green garden
of impeccably mounded boxwood spheres, Southern magnolias (an
evergreen variety) and espaliered pear trees. In one inviting spot,
there is a teakwood bench, weathered to a warm coppery bronze,
shaded by a stand of tall paper mulberry trees.
</P>
<P>
   At the right of the center garden, there's a flagstone path with
a border of showy Casablanca lilies, zinnias and black-eyed Susans;
this is the cutting garden. In this case, though, the term is
purely a formality: the flowers are almost never cut.
</P>
<P>
   When the men need centerpieces for their dining tables, as they
often do for the lunches and dinners Priano is famous for, they
usually choose from the many varieties of orchids that flourish in
the nurturing light of the loggia.
</P>
<P>
   These days, it takes a full-time gardener to keep the property
in pristine shape, and with a climate as generally gentle as
Virginia's, full time means year round. Of course, even Virginia
can't escape winter entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many ice storms that we have to wrap the cypresses
and the topiaries in burlap,'' Garren said. ``It looks wonderfully
weird, like the movie `Orlando.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
