<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Sept. 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gales will persist along the Middle Atlantic Coast from Virginia
to North Carolina as the circulation associated with Dennis
continues to draw large quantities of moisture toward the
shoreline. Squalls will move inland across southeast Virginia and
eastern North Carolina. The center of lowest pressure will drift
close to the Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   As the storm unwinds like a tight spring, high and middle clouds
will spread farther away from it, reaching from southern Long
Island to the central Appalachians. Showers will slowly spread into
North Carolina during the next 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   A long ridge of high pressure stretching from southern New
England west to the Great Lakes and south to the Tennessee Valley
will promote dry, but increasingly warm weather. Sunshine will
dominate and after a comfortably cool morning, readings will rise
to above seasonal levels in many sections.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of an upper level disturbance and a tropical
wave in the Gulf of Mexico will bring thickening clouds and some
thundershowers from Louisiana to southwest Missouri. A wedge of
hot, sticky air will occupy the western Plains under sunny skies.
</P>
<P>
   Very cool air will surge into the northwest Plains and Montana
ahead of strengthening low pressure system. Thick clouds and rain
will dampen much of the region. Thunderstorms will erupt over the
central and eastern Rockies ahead of a slow-moving cold front.
Cooler weather will cover the Northwest while onshore winds bring
marine air into southern California with low clouds near the coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DEATH KNELL
</P>
<P>
   Like a dagger to the heart, a wedge of cool, dry air circulated
from the Middle Atlantic States into the center of what was
Hurricane Dennis on Wednesday. The chill was able to stymie the
development of new thunderstorms around the center of the storm
system, virtually eliminating the source of its energy. Record cool
temperatures were recorded on Wednesday morning from West Virginia
to northern Florida. Myrtle Beach, S.C., which had been soaked on
Monday as Hurricane Dennis approached, tied a record with a minimum
of 61 degrees.
</P>
</TEXT>
