<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7604 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-EXERCISE-ANDHEAT-TEX     09-01 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXERCISE-ANDHEAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXERCISE SMART, BECAUSE, BABY, IT'S HOT OUTSIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late summer, when the sun is burning a sizzling 100-degree
trail, is no time to take up jogging or biking in North Texas _ or
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Comic actor Martin Lawrence, 34, was in a coma for three days
and on a ventilator for most of a week after collapsing while
jogging in heavy clothing, in 100-degree heat, near Thousand Oaks,
Calif. He was reportedly trying to loose weight for a movie role.
</P>
<P>
   He is lucky to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, Lawrence suffered heatstroke _ a life-and-death
emergency that sends body temperature soaring and causes confusion,
amnesia, loss of balance, incoherent speech, dizziness, delirium,
convulsions and unconsciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Heatstroke kills approximately 4,000 Americans each year, says
Steve Farrell,
</P>
<P>
   an exercise physiologist and associate director of the Cooper
Institute for Aerobics Research in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence's temperature was 107 degrees when he reached Los
Robles Regional Medical Center, a hospital spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your temperature gets that high, a protein in the blood
begins to boil. It causes organ failure _ usually the kidneys or
liver first, then you go on from there. It can severely damage
vital organs,'' Farrell says.
</P>
<P>
   He is not encouraging anyone to give up exercise in the heat of
summer. Just use common sense.
</P>
<P>
   That means wearing light clothing, drinking plenty of fluids,
planning shorter, less intense early-morning or late-evening
workouts, and never, ever putting on one of those dark rubber suits
designed to help you sweat off pounds more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen people exercising in the heat with those stupid
black plastic or rubber suits,'' Farrell says. ``Their sweat can't
evaporate. They are cooking in their own juices. It increases the
risk of heatstroke by about 100 times. They are just asking for a
heatstroke.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``sweat suits,'' sold in sporting-goods stores, have become
popular with high-school and college wrestlers and boxers who need
to shed a couple of pounds overnight to compete in a particular
weight category.
</P>
<P>
   But Farrell says he's seen people walking, jogging and riding
bikes in the suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it a lot, but I am amazed to see it at all,''
Farrell says. ``Mostly you see overweight people trying to lose
weight quickly. When you lose the weight, it's water weight. You
put it right back on when you replace fluids. You need to think
about loss of fat, not water.''
</P>
<P>
   What about athletes in training? Farrell says that with the
right precautions, they should be OK and notes that highly
conditioned people tend to tolerate hot weather better than those
who are untrained.
</P>
<P>
   Farrell also says that a higher awareness among coaches of the
risks of heatstroke has led to improved conditions for high-school
and college football players struggling through ``two-a-day''
practices as they prepare to kick off the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death is much less common among high-school football
players,'' Farrell says. ``They used to not let them have any
fluids during workouts and give them salt tablets. Now they push
fluids and are very aware of warning signs of heat injury,
especially nausea and muscle cramping,''
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of us?
</P>
<P>
   The American Council on Science and Health warns that heat poses
a particular threat to the very old; the very young; people
susceptible to heart and vascular disease, diabetes or other
chronic illnesses; alcoholics; and drug abusers.
</P>
<P>
   Fitness experts say most people can exercise safely in hot
weather if they modify normal workouts, following common-sense
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you are a beginning exerciser and not very fit,
running is not a good choice, especially in the summer. It's too
strenuous. If you are highly fit, you can run _ even in the summer,
but you should stick to the recommendations: early morning or late
evening, white clothes, plenty of fluids and shorter runs.
</P>
<P>
   The key for everyone _ including those determined to shed pounds
quickly _ is to stick with moderate, not extreme, workouts in
loose, light clothing. ``Back in the '70s, we thought exercise had
to be vigorous and painful,'' Farrell says. ``Studies today all
point to moderate exercise being the most beneficial for most
people.''
</P>
<P>
   GUIDELINES FOR HOT-WEATHER TRAINING
</P>
<P>
   If you are going to train in the heat, it's a good idea to have
attained a high level of fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Acclimatization to heat takes approximately 10 to 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect peak performance during hot weather. (The heart
works harder to shunt some blood to the skin, and less is delivered
to the working muscles.)
</P>
<P>
   Don't take salt tablets unless a physician prescribes them.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing should be loose and absorbent, and light-colored to
reflect heat. Don't wear black. Don't layer on the clothes to sweat
more in the hope of losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   Drink before, during and after exercise, every 10 to 15 minutes.
Electrolyte replacement (sports drinks) are unnecessary for
short-term exercise sessions, but should be used during long-term
exercise when profuse sweating occurs. Over a longer time, you are
not losing just water, but also electrolytes. Salt needs to be put
back in the body, but not with salt tablets.
</P>
<P>
   Beware of sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid rubber or plastic suits at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Consider temperature and humidity. Humid air prevents the
evaporation of sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Do not use oil-based sunscreen or suntan oil. It can interfere
with normal sweating.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Cooper Institute for Aerobics Research
</P>
<P>
   HOW THE BODY DEALS WITH HEAT
</P>
<P>
   It takes 10 to 14 days of exercise in the heat to acclimatize
fully. With acclimatization:
</P>
<P>
   Sweating rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   Sweating begins earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Sweating becomes better distributed over the entire body.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat becomes hypotonic (less salty).
</P>
<P>
   Blood plasma volume increases.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
