<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7627 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX     09-01 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL HAIL TO CAPTAIN BEEFHEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From Cher's ``Believe'' to Carlos Santana having a Top 10 CD and
being appreciated by a whole new generation of rockers and
hip-hoppers to Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band being the
hot tour of the summer, 1999 has seen some amazing comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most impressive is by a guy who sold very few
records in the first place, made precisely one promotional video,
never came close to having a hit single and hasn't put out new
material since 1982, when he abandoned music altogether.
</P>
<P>
   I speak of Don Van Vliet, better known as Captain Beefheart, the
weird and wonderful singer/songwriter/band leader whose sometimes
surreal _ and often pun-filled _ mutant strain of blues and jazz is
being appreciated all over again.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, the summer of 1999 has seen an absolute
flood of the good Captain's work hitting the shelves. The most
accessible retrospective is the just-released ``The Dust Blows
Forward (An Anthology),'' a two-CD anthology from Rhino Records: 45
songs, from the stomping blues of his first single, 1966's ``Diddy
Wah Diddy,'' to three tracks from his final record, 1982's ``Ice
Cream for Crow.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all. Heck, no. His 1967 debut LP, ``Safe as
Milk'' and the later ``Mirror Man'' have been reissued on CD. And
for the hard-core fans there is ``Grow Fins,'' a massive five-CD
collection of live tracks, demos, radio broadcasts and more,
including a whole bunch of enhanced CD footage.
</P>
<P>
   Time has not changed this essential fact: Captain Beefheart is
one of those guys whom a very few people love very much, and the
rest of the world either A) can't stand to listen to for more than
about three minutes, or B) never heard and never will hear. Which
is probably best.
</P>
<P>
   Pal of Frank Zappa, blower of good 'n' greasy blues harmonica,
taskmaster band leader and definite eccentric, Beefheart took basic
Chicago blues and sort of, well, how to put it? ``Altered its
consciousness'' might be the best description.
</P>
<P>
   Full of surreal tales and stinging guitar work, the music of
Beefheart and his ever-changing Magic Band is one part Muddy
Waters, one part beat poetry, one part avant-garde jazz, one part
that ranting weirdo uncle whom nobody invites to family gatherings
anymore, one part tent preacher, one part _ heck, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Songs such as ``Big Eyed Beans From Venus'' and ``The Floppy
Boot Stomp'' may not make any sort of literal sense, but in a world
that's drowning in cookie-cutter music, they sound fresh and
twisted, adventurous and playful and human. You want alternative?
``Real'' alternative? Pick up the Rhino box and play just about any
track; what you'll find is much that's more challenging and just
plain fun than most anything by any current artist.
</P>
<P>
   Which may be because Beefheart's influence extends so widely.
Col. Bruce Hampton, the granddaddy of jam-band rock, was obviously
listening closely to Beefheart back in the '60s. Tom Waits' vocal
style is, at times, reminiscent of Beefheart's, and no small part
of Little Feat's oddball charm bears the Captain's mark.
</P>
<P>
   John Lydon _ who as Johnny Rotten led the Sex Pistols _ is an
avowed fan, and Pere Ubu (a very important proto-punk band from
Cleveland) was clearly touched by Beefheart's music. One can't
imagine the odd rants by vocalist David Thomas without Beefheart's
trailblazing work, which for my money was at its best on ``Milk,''
1969's ``Trout Mask Replica'' and 1980's ``Doc at the Radar
Station.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Captain Beefheart's music can still astonish and
captivate. You've gotta wonder what Van Vliet makes of all this as
he does his artwork somewhere out there in California, but he ain't
talking. He didn't even do an interview for the excellent booklet
that accompanies the Rhino box. But that, too, is somehow fitting:
Captain Beefheart said his piece, twisted as it often was, and then
exited. He doesn't need us, but listening to this stuff reminds me
just how much fans of adventurous music continue to need him.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7631 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA02-COX     09-01 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA: The Dr. Dolittle of the Rocky Mountains
 &HT;    (Eds: This is the first of a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.)
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TELLURIDE, Colo. _ Melissa Margetts will never forget the time
she sliced open the bulging stomach of a cow elk that had been
seriously injured by a car on top of Dallas Divide.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency roadside Caesarean yielded a calf in obvious
distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grabbed her by the back legs and spun her around so the
centrifugal force would get this fluid out of her lungs,'' explains
Margetts. ``I had given her mouth-to-mouth and it took four minutes
to get her going.''
</P>
<P>
   The calf, nicknamed Junebug, was nursed back to health and
released into the wild last December.
</P>
<P>
   Margetts is a modern-day Dr. Dolittle meets MacGyver.
</P>
<P>
   Take the time she rescued a baby porcupine from its mother's
womb using only her Swiss Army knife, cinnamon dental floss and a
little ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first C-section,'' says Margetts, laughing. ``I got
the uterus out and opened it up and got the baby out. The placenta
was attached to it and I thought with a human baby you tie off the
umbilical cord so they don't bleed to death, so I had cinnamon
dental floss in the car, and I thought, what the heck.''
</P>
<P>
   The baby, dubbed Stickers, was featured on a National Geographic
Explorer television special with Boyd Matson.
</P>
<P>
   Margetts, 43, heads up the Rocky Mountain Ark Wildlife
Rehabilitation Center on a 14-acre spread high in the San Juan
Mountains near Telluride. She jokingly refers to her wildlife
refuge as the ``Damn Nice Ranch'' because that's what she said to
herself when she spied the rugged plot of land off a dirt Forest
Service access road.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Margetts has rescued thousands of wild and
domestic animals. Current residents include Spike, an
African-crested porcupine; Wile E. Coyote; a homeless donkey dubbed
Jackson Browne; Elvis the mutt; and a sassy exotic parrot named
Diego who seems to have picked up a bit of office lingo from his
previous owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right!'' screeches the brilliant blue and yellow bird from his
perch next to the deck.
</P>
<P>
   It's just after 10 a.m. and Margetts and an intern, Ann Allen,
make the usual feeding rounds _ every four hours around the clock _
armed with containers of mealworms for the birds, a bucket of milk
for the fawns and roadkill for Ruby the mountain lion. Elvis and
Jackson Browne trail behind for company, occasionally chasing each
other. It seems one of them has forgotten that he is a donkey.
</P>
<P>
   A typical season at the Ark produces as many as 150 animals,
many considered hard-luck cases after tangling with the most
dangerous creature of all _ humans.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with Chaos, a great horned owl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This couple was driving from California to their home in
Arizona,'' begins Margetts, with Chaos perched on her gloved arm.
``They were driving at night and they hit him and thought he was
just stunned. They put him in a box and kept him overnight while
they continued to drive and their dog got into the box and totally
mangled him. The dog tore off his left foot and it was hanging by a
thread and his left wing was dangling. They put him back in the box
and thought he would be dead and continued to drive to Arizona. He
was still alive when they got there, so they thought the most
peaceful way to die was when you freeze to death. They stuck him in
the freezer and left him there for 30 hours and when they checked
on him, he was still alive. They finally called the sheriff's
department and asked what to do. The sheriff's department picked
him up and took him to Liberty Wildlife, where his left wing was
amputated and his left foot was sewn back on. This was good
intentions really gone awry.''
</P>
<P>
   Margetts is a woman on a mission. She's on call 24 hours a day
and can often be found behind the wheel of her old green-and-white
ambulance picking up wounded animals and bringing them back to the
Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary goal is wildlife rehab and reintroduction into the
wild,'' she says. ``All we are is a second chance for these guys to
be free. There's no guarantee. They die in the wild all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 63 percent survival rate, many of Margetts' animals are
too critically wounded to survive and must be euthanized. Those
that make it are released back into the wild if they are able.
</P>
<P>
   ``The animals that I get attached to are the ones that I don't
think are going to make it,'' says Margetts. ``I am down at the
incubator at 2 o'clock in the morning and I've got my fingers
crossed and I am prepping myself for the idea that this animal is
more than likely going to be dead. Those are the ones that bring
tears to your eyes when it finally comes time to open up the box
and you see them tear across the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Animals that are maimed or unable to survive in the wild for
various reasons are retained for adult and children's education
programs at schools and national parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can plant a seed in one kid, you never know what kind
of a difference they will make,'' says Margetts. ``If you inspire
one kid not to throw that plastic six-pack container in a bag
without cutting it up and he tells his son who becomes a
schoolteacher and tells more kids _ you never know how it is going
to steamroll.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her education programs, Margetts has been
featured in People magazine for her pet lending library, believed
to be the only one of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
   For 5 bucks, kids can get a library card and check out a
plethora of pets, including chinchillas, rabbits, guinea pigs,
hamsters, snakes, birds, pygmy goats _ even a tarantula spider in a
locked viewing box.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my favorite animal in the pet lending library,'' says
Margetts, while holding up what appears to be a gigantic New York
sewer rat. ``This,'' she says, ``is Howard Stern.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ark is also part of the International Placement Program, in
which animals are placed from all over the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   That's how she acquired a webbed-footed beaver named Wally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came from Montreal, Canada, and his dam had been blown
up,'' says Margetts. ``The parents were killed and the two babies
floated to the surface. A couple brought the babies home and they
tried to feed them but didn't do it properly, so they got metabolic
bone disease which caused their legs to break. They were taken to a
zoo, but the zoo didn't want them, so they were put on the
placement program list.''
</P>
<P>
   Those animals that can be released back into the wild undergo an
intensive ``demanning'' process where Margetts and her volunteer
assistants beat on pots and pans with silverware or bang on the
side of their pens three times a day in an effort to make the
animals afraid of humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is not to harass the animals,'' says Margetts, ``but
we want them to have negative human contact. That's the hardest
part of the job. These guys start to follow you around after a
while and you have to start scaring them, banging on pots and pans
and flipping blankets and yelling and screaming. You want them to
run from you every time they see you.''
</P>
<P>
   Margetts' compassion for critters began at an early age while
growing up in Telluride. Her father, a medical doctor, often
doubled as the town vet and would bring home animals for Margetts
and her half dozen brothers and sisters to nurse back to health.
</P>
<P>
   She gleaned much of her medical knowledge from Dr. Dad, who was
known to dissect the chicken before dinner while pointing out
things like tendons and joints to anyone who would listen.
</P>
<P>
   After a short stint in Minnesota as an engineer for Honeywell
designing laser eyepieces for anti-tank weapons, Margetts heard the
call of the wild and followed it back to her hometown of Telluride.
</P>
<P>
   Life hasn't always been easy for the auburn-haired animal lover
who firmly believes that one person can make a difference. In 1992,
she was diagnosed with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. The cancer went into
remission after several bouts of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Margetts is never short on animal stories. She remembers the
time a woman offered her $20 and told her to go to the grocery
store after she spotted Margetts tugging on a dead animal carcass
she was attempting to bring home to her animals. Then there was the
time she yelled at her son Jake to put his toys away only to find
out later that he had put his toys away before going to bed and it
was the baby beaver who was dragging them back out at night in an
attempt to build a dam across the doorway. Margetts and her
husband, Steve, once trapped an out-of-control badger inside a
Rubbermaid container. Taz, as the badger was affectionately called,
was making horrible noises and the container was flipping all over
the place as the two struggled to keep it intact. It was then that
Steve turned to Margetts and said with a straight face, ``Don't you
wish everything was made like Rubbermaid?'' And she still remembers
the time a couple from Norwood gave her a pair of milk goats but
neglected to tell her that they only produced milk if they got to
listen to the country radio station KKXK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them's country goats,'' she remembers the man telling her.
</P>
<P>
   Margetts takes a moment to reflect on her life as rain pours
from the dark storm clouds that have gathered overhead near the San
Juan Mountain range. After watching four otters gleefully swimming
in the enclosed otter pond outside her living room window, she
turns and says, ``If I won the lottery, I would still be doing this
on Monday. Even if I didn't have a dime to my name, I'd be doing
this on Monday. It's a fulfillment in my life that I would have a
hard time explaining to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   She just hopes she has many more Mondays. In November 1998,
Margetts' cancer returned. She underwent surgery to remove masses
from her pancreas and stomach. Since that time, she has lost 80
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it's the animals who are now keeping Margetts alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe the animals have had more to do with healing
me than I had to do with healing them,'' she says, quietly. ``I
feel that I have made a difference, not only in the lives of
thousands of animals, but also the kids. If I died tomorrow, that
would be perfectly fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The non-profit Rocky Mountain Ark Wildlife Rehabilitation Center
is funded through donations and grants. Donations can be sent to:
Rocky Mountain Ark, P.O. Box 865, Telluride, Colo. 81435.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Cumpston writes for The Daily Sentinel of Grand Junction,
Colo., and can be reached at lcumpston(at)gjds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
