<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BRAZIL-CULTURE01-COX     09-01 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-CULTURE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Land of samba is the latest rhythm in things culinary, otherwise
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bye-bye, Carmen Miranda. Celebrity chef Paul Luna has
stolen your punch.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Portuguese bombshell _ who moved to Brazil, put a bunch
of bananas on her head and became a kitsch classic _ Atlanta's
wackiest chef is putting on a show at Loca Luna, his new
Brazilian-inspired late-night hangout in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, as a whispery bossa nova band played jazz
standards, Luna was on the bar blowing bubbles and handing out
bright red rum drinks to a fawning crowd. A few nights later, he'd
strapped on the most outrageous Carnival outfit he could find _ a
revealing getup of leopard prints and pheasant feathers _ and was
ready to samba.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did we mention that he also cooks everything from pickled
pig's feet to guava flan?
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Like any number of trend-savvy entrepreneurs, Luna knows that
the biggest wave of the moment is Brazilian. Starbucks has been
promoting its Ipanema Bourbon bean in a fancy package with a
Carnival dancer on the label. Even the rock star Beck has recorded
``Tropicalia,'' a song based on the stylish '60s Brazilian sound.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Delta Air Lines has added nonstops to Brazil and
says it wants to offer flights from other U.S. cities. Emory
University says its Evening at Emory Portuguese classes are second
only to Spanish. Arts venue directors say that when a Brazilian
ensemble comes to town, the community of Brazilian expatriates _
estimated at 10,000 to 15,000 _ crawls out of the woodwork. Back on
the culinary front, Tierra, the new pan-Latin restaurant on
Piedmont Avenue, is seizing the moment by offering feijoada _ the
Brazilian national dish _ at a special, one-night-only dinner Sept.
7. Chef Ticha Krinsky, who lived in Brazil for seven years and
speaks Portuguese, says it's the first time an Atlanta restaurant
has offered the complicated dish of pork, black beans, rice and
numerous other accompaniments (reservations recommended:
404-874-5951).
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnival is what people want,'' says food industry
standard-bearer Michael Batterberry, founding editor of Food Arts
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnival history is what drives people into deliriums of
excess and happiness, and it's usually in places that are pretty
repressive. . . . It goes back to the Saturnalian rituals, when all
conventions were tossed out the window and you just got your cans
full of pebbles and jumped up and down.'' He's referring to
S.O.B.'s, Manhattan's hottest restaurant-cum-samba room, where
patrons get an aluminum can full of rocks so they can play
percussion and dance between bites (S.O.B., by the way, stands for
``Sounds of Brasil'').
</P>
<P>
   That's clearly the kind of revelry Luna has in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to get on the table, go for it,'' says the
35-year-old chef, who turned the town onto Spanish tapas at Eclipse
di Luna, his other Atlanta restaurant, in 1997. Luna's new place _
wedged between the popular gay nightspots Backstreet and the Armory
at the corner of 6th and Juniper streets _ is open until 1:30 a.m.
on Tuesdays through Thursdays and until 5:30 a.m. on Fridays and
Saturdays. Never mind that he's from the Dominican Republic and
doesn't speak Portuguese. Luna is so convinced of the trend that he
wants to do a cooking show _ in Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   Done up to look like a South American beach bar, Loca Luna is
painted in Starburst shades of purple, orange, red, yellow and
green. There's even a mural of Corcovado, the landmark Rio de
Janeiro mountain with the statue of Christ on top. But because
authentic Brazilian ingredients are hard to find, Luna has fudged a
bit on the menu. He says he'll soon be adding some authentic
dishes, including bolinho de bacalhau (fried codfish balls),
moquecas (coconut-milk-based fish stews) pao de queijo (cheese
rolls).
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like it,'' says Alessandra Lange, 24, an Atlanta
Ballet dancer from Curitiba, Brazil, who was at the restaurant on a
recent Saturday. ``I just wish it was more Brazilian. It's like the
first city I've lived in the United States where there is not a
Brazilian place.'' Lang says that Brazilians hang out at North Cafe
Diem (642 North Highland Ave. N.E.) on Monday nights and Voodoo
(3186 Roswell Road N.E., Buckhead) on Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   But restaurant-industry insiders say it's only a matter of time
before the rodizio craze, already big in New York, California and
Texas, hits Atlanta. After all, barbecue-loving Southerners ought
to go for the all-you-eat meat concept, in which roving waiters
carve slices of meat right onto your plate. ``It satisfies a lot of
hunger today for people in their 20s and 30s,'' says Batterberry.
``It suggests a place where you can cut lose and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Atlanta-Brazil business connection is booming.
Although Atlanta's Brazilian Consulate closed in June due to
government cuts back home, it wasn't for lack of interest on the
part of tourist and business travelers from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you easily that both the number of tourist and
business people going to Brazil increased threefold in the 3 1/2
years we were in Atlanta,'' says Mario Graca Roiter, Brazil's
former consul general in Atlanta, who has been re-assigned to
Tokyo. According to the Brazilian Embassy in Washington, 9,020
visas were issued by the Atlanta consulate in 1998, out of a total
of 148,321 nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil has been the best performing Latin American market,''
says Delta spokesman John Kennedy. ``Passenger loads have been
extremely high this summer.'' In 1997, Delta began offering
non-stops to Sao Paulo, with continuing service to Rio. Kennedy
says the airline is seeking permission to add non-stop flights from
other major U.S. cities. ``Europe is still the dominant market,
approximately 3 to 1, but we are seeing a burgeoning Latin American
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Stoffle, Emory's director of community education
services, says: ``We've been really amazed by the response to
Portuguese. We tried it as an experiment, and it just started going
like gangbusters. So there's definitely a market for it. Doing
business in Brazil has been one of the key motivators for people.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Rialto Center for the Performing Arts downtown and
Charleston's Spoleto Festival USA, Brazilian artists have been on
the program for the last several seaons _ and both presenters are
considering bringing back Bale Folclorico da Bahia, which sold out
two Rialto shows in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``In future seasons,'' says Rialto executive director Bill
Baites, ``I plan to include Brazilian music and dance as a regular
part of our programming, because the audiences are extremely loyal.
... We've documented the fact that in two performances of Bale
Folclorico da Bahia in a 900-seat hall, we have sold out with a
strong Brazilian presence in the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   So what about that Ipanema Bourbon bean?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ipanema is the name of the farm it comes from, and bourbon is
the type of coffee tree,'' says Starbucks spokesman Helen Chung,
pronouncing ``bourbon'' as ``bur-BONE.''
</P>
<P>
   And we thought Ipanema was a beach.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
