<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MTV-AWARDS-1225(TRIMS     09-01 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-AWARDS-1225(TRIMS)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT AT THE OPERA WITH MUSIC BY MTV 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ MTV and the Met? They may sound incompatible, but
next Thursday MTV plans to present its 16th annual Video Music
Awards in the elegant opera house at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   The award ceremony has taken place in New York before, but MTV
executives said they wanted to do something particularly majestic
this year in honor of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find a venue that fits the spirit of the show,
which is kind of like an awards show but twisted,'' said Judy
McGrath, the president of MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Radio City Music Hall, where the awards have been presented
before, is under renovation. MTV felt the Universal Amphitheater in
Los Angeles, site of last year's awards, was too cavernous. They
weighed the possibility of staging it in Central Park or on a barge
in the Hudson River. Then someone thought of the Met, suspecting it
would be like asking for the moon. Ms. McGrath likened the first
meeting between MTV and the Met to a U.N. conference, ``feeling
each other out.''
</P>
<P>
   But in short order the Met agreed.
</P>
<P>
   With the comedian Chris Rock as host, the show is to include
Madonna, Jennifer Lopez and Susan Sarandon as presenters, along
with performances by Ricky Martin, Lauryn Hill, the Backstreet Boys
and Britney Spears.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Met's first production of the season is a
double bill: ``Cavalleria Rusticana'' with Jose Cura and ``I
Pagliacci'' with Placido Domingo.
</P>
<P>
   Although one might expect such a collaboration to result in a
clash of high and low culture, instead, both MTV and the Met say,
so far so good. ``They've been unbelievably open-minded about this
as we have been respectful and flattered to be there,'' Ms. McGrath
said. ``They're not like geeks who've never understood anything
creative. In fact, their set for `Mephistopheles' could give
Marilyn Manson a lesson or two.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Joseph Volpe, thegeneral manager of the Met, he said MTV
was more than welcome, particularly since the opera season does not
begin until Sept. 27, and the stage would otherwise be unoccupied
at this time of year. ``The worst thing a theater can be is dark,''
Volpe said. ``Here is an opportunity for it to be alive again.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV may also have wanted to find something that would upgrade
the production, given past criticism. In The New York Times, Neil
Strauss called last year's ceremony ``a three-hour salute to
tastelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Met, which would not disclose what its rental fee, is not
entirely unfamiliar with unorthodox tenants, like Robin Williams,
who staged a comedy special there. Nevertheless, there have been a
few bumps in the creative process: like the time MTV reported that
one rapper, DMX, wanted to include pit bulls in his performance and
another wanted to drive a Bentley onto the stage. ``Since they're
accustomed to dealing with livestock, I think we'll figure that
out,'' Ms. McGrath said. ``And they're used to vehicles, but it's
usually a horse and a cart.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGrath said the Met has learned that opera divas have
nothing on rock divas. ``Opera stars don't have posses,'' she said.
``They're used to dealing with divas, but they don't have divas
that come with 40 friends.''
</P>
<P>
   On some issues, MTV said, the Met drew the line. Ruled out was
the standard method of operation for the production team that sets
up the show: camping out and ordering in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff that works on a show tends to move in and live
there,'' Ms. McGrath said. ``They said, `Absolutely no eating in
the hall. You can't have a tub of Pepsi in the aisle and a sandwich
at your right hand.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the opera house has been extremely
accommodating in other ways. For example MTV will be replacing the
opera costumes on display in the Met lobby with famous outfits worn
by various musicians at previous MTV music video awards, like a
pair of seatless yellow pants worn by Prince when he sang ``Get
Off'' in 1991 and a Marie Antoinette outfit worn by Madonna when
she sang ``Vogue'' in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   On the backs of seats, instead of the usual opera titles, the
lyrics of the featured performers will be displayed. (The featured
songs will not include profanities, MTV said.)
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody comes into the Metropolitan Opera, what's the
point of having them if you can't be hospitable?'' Volpe said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The auditorium, which usually holds 4,000, will also feel
different, with 500 seats removed to accommodate sets and cameras
and pits for dancing fans and a thrust that will allow musicians to
move out into the audience. The lobby will be transformed with DJ
Moby choosing tunes at the top of the grand staircase. The outside
plaza will be a spectacle including a live MTV News broadcast
featuring the band Smash Mouth and limousines dispensing
star-studded attendees onto a red carpet.
</P>
<P>
   MTV, in turn, has decided to pay tribute to its environs with
certain operatic touches. The awards are to open with ``Carmina
Burana,'' a cantata composed by Carl Orff in the 1930s that turns
up in the hip-hop works of NAS and Sean (Puffy) Combs. The
16-year-old Welsh opera singer Charlotte Church will present an
award with the heavy metal band Limp Bizkit. The ad campaign
depicts rock stars posing as opera characters: Chris Rock as
Rigoletto, David Bowie as Mephistopheles and Janet Jackson as
Cleopatra.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   To create its set MTV chose the Russian designer George Tsypin,
who has mostly worked on operas.
</P>
<P>
   Tsypin said he meant his set _ a looming steel and glass
structure that includes a rendering of the Statue of Liberty _ to
invoke an image of New York as a Tower of Babel. ``For me it's not
such a big departure because even though I design mostly opera, I
kind of go against operatic tradition,'' he said. ``All these
things kind of merge _ classical music and rock-and-roll _ in my
mind. I listen to all of it.'' (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGrath said the musicians scheduled to appear seemed
somewhat awed by the prospect of playing at the Met. ``A lot of
bands are starting to feel like, `Gosh, maybe this calls for more
layers of fabric than I was initially thinking about,''' she said.
``For musicians who care deeply about sound and acoustics, I think
this adds a layer of anxiety and energy to it.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it seems the featured musicians feel that the Met's
atmosphere is sufficiently attention getting. ``In the past, a lot
of people felt they had to come with huge production numbers,'' Ms.
McGrath said. ``I generally get millions of requests, `Can I hang
the neon sign behind me?' This time, almost everyone coming wants
to just stand there, enjoy the moment and the space and sing their
best.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As to whether or not the experience of being in the Met might
create some new operagoers, Volpe said he was optimistic. ``I think
once they're in the house, they might say, `I want to come back and
see what this opera thing is all about,''' he said. While one might
not expect Volpe himself to be jamming on an air guitar in the
aisles, he said he hoped to attend and added, ``You've never seen
me on the dance floor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FASTER-BOOK-REVIEW-AR     09-01 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASTER-BOOK-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FASTER': CAN YOU SPARE 7 MINUTES OF LIFE TO READ THIS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.)  
 Patricia Volk is a novelist and essayist who lives in New York.  
(editors: in last graf, replace (POUND SIGN) with the typographical
symbol) 
 (bl)  
 By PATRICIA VOLK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the old television show ``Beat the Clock,'' contestants were
given wacky tasks to do while a giant second hand ticked away. The
audience howled as grown men and women raced around in gorilla
suits with eggs on spoons. In ``Faster: The Acceleration of Just
About Everything,'' James Gleick says that is what we're doing now.
Life is a 33 rpm record spinning at 78. We are a culture of racing,
panicky white rabbits. Naturally, you've noticed.
</P>
<P>
   You don't just do one thing at a time anymore. You multi-task.
In the car you drink coffee, listen to self-improvement tapes, talk
on the cellular phone and floss. You wash your hair with J.F.
Lazartigue's ``sechage rapide,'' a shampoo with polymers that
hastens drying by 30 percent. In advanced cases of ``hurry
sickness'' you punch 88 on the microwave instead of 90 because it
takes less time to tap the same digit twice. There is a whole
generation of workers weaned on video games who function at
``twitch speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Can we get any faster than twitch? We're trying. The fastest
elevator in the world travels at ``a good climb rate for an
airplane.'' Not fast enough? Look forward to the pressurized sky
lobby, a room ``high inside a megaskyscraper, where passengers pass
through an airlock to repressurize before making a rapid descent to
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM promises to cut waiting at airport immigration checkpoints
to 15 seconds once you surrender your biometrics: fingerprints and
voiceprints. Politicians are coached to speak in 10-second sound
bites. A three-minute television news segment is considered ``long
form.'' We're even learning to hear faster. Telephone answering
machines speed up messages 25 percent in case your friends drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to real time. Gleick writes, ``If you can sign the
check, lick the stamp and toss the envelope onto the passing mail
room robot cart just as you tell your caller, `It's in the mail,'
you have at least part of your life running in real time.''
</P>
<P>
   And what is the price for all this speed? You can't keep up.
``Software product cycles, already short at 18 months to 2 years,
have begun to evaporate,'' Gleick says. ``Instead of distinct,
tested, shrink-wrapped versions of software, manufacturers
distribute upgrades and patches that change within months or even
days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Faster'' points to science writer James Burke, who predicts,
``We will need to reskill ourselves constantly every decade just to
keep a job.'' We are speeding cartoons, cloud puffs scuttling
behind our heels. There is no time for contemplation. We live life
in the crisis lane.
</P>
<P>
   A man who lives in real time, Jay Walljasper, an editor at large
at the Utne Reader magazine, is quoted: ``I can't stand small talk,
waiting in line or slow numbers on the dance floor. . . . It has
gotten to the point where my days, crammed with all sorts of
activities, feel like an Olympic endurance event: the
everydayathon. . . . I hear an invisible stopwatch ticking even
when I'm supposed to be having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Observing us glued to our cellular phones or our screens, or our
cell phones  &UR; and &LR;  our screens, Gleick, a frequent contributor to
The New York Times Magazine, looks for the why. ``It is the way of
keeping contact with someone, anyone, who will reassure you that
you are not alone. You may think you are checking on your
portfolio, but deep down you are checking on your existence.''
</P>
<P>
   So what are we doing with all this time we are saving? We're
having sex for an average of four minutes a day. Seven minutes are
lavished on the care of plants and pets. Internet users wait nine
minutes daily for their Web sites to materialize. Sixteen minutes
drop into the black hole of looking for lost objects. ``The
software industry alone leaves Americans waiting on hold for an
estimated 3 billion minutes a year,'' Gleick writes. Television
sucks up three hours a day. A strategy for bargaining power is
bragging about how little time you have: ``The more time you have
on your hands, the less important you must be.''
</P>
<P>
   In rat-a-tat yet elegant prose, Gleick hammers out precisely how
time-driven we are. Smell the roses? Fine, if you order them on the
Web and ship them overnight. I tried to think of things no one
could make faster. There's dawn. (Unless you jet past the
international date line.) There's pregnancy. (For the birth itself,
we have the drug Pitocin.) There is still the three-minute egg.
Gleick offers compost and souffles, but I bet you could do
something with a microwave. Not that we always opt for speed.
Pistachio nuts that have already been shelled are quicker, but
they're not nearly as great as pistachio nuts in the shell.
</P>
<P>
   In years to come, ``Faster'' will tell people what we were like
as clearly as Dickens or Tom Wolfe. It would help if you knew a
little high school physics. What on earth are Tetris blocks,
teraflops, parsecs and Mersenne primes? What does folding a piece
of paper in half  &UR; n &LR;  times mean? Precooked meals take up more space
in the supermarket than fresh fruits and vegetables? Not at my
market. And sorting stamps is boring? I'd kill to get my old stamp
collection back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, if we pay attention to our watches, they teach us
something even more valuable: that lived time is different from
clock time,'' Gleick writes. ``Our experience of time changes with
our moods, with our age, with our level of busyness, with the
complexity of our culture.'' Time, he writes, ``is a version of the
truth you wear on your wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer Mark Helprin says, ``Life is lived with the kind of
excitement that your forebears knew only in battle.'' So if you
don't have time to read ``Faster'' (it took me 412 minutes, or 103
days of sex), here is a time-saving hint: on your telephone,
pressing the (POUND SIGN) key lets you skip the automated prompts.
``f y cn rd ths, y cn ern mo py,'' the old bus advertisement used
to say. Speed is our destiny, speed is our fate. Gleick cites the
historian Stephen Kern: ``Human beings have never opted for
slower.'' Tell that to my friend who still makes toast in a
skillet.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FASTER: The Acceleration of Just About Everything'
</P>
<P>
   By James Gleick
</P>
<P>
   324 pages. Pantheon Books. $24
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
