<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MAGS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business Week tracks the launch of an IPO
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many a corporate executive thought a public stock
offering was the right way for a company to go, only to regret it
later. Business Week (Sept. 6) explains why in a step-by-step
profile of an initial stock offering, or IPO.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine follows an Internet mortgage company, E-Loan,
through this grueling process. It goes from making a pitch to
investors, includes a hectic national road show to visit money
managers and underwriters and culminates in the tension-filled
launch on the day the company begins trading, in this case on the
Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   E-Loan raised $56.3 million in a June 29 IPO and got to keep
$50.3 million after the underwriters, attorneys, accountants,
regulatory agencies and miscellaneous other individuals deducted
their fees.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the first day of trading made it seem worthwhile.
E-Loan's stock, which went on the market at $14 per share, rose 164
percent, giving the company a market value of $1.4 billion. The
stock continued to rise for several more days until it peaked on
July 6 at a closing price of $63 per share. After that, the stock
dipped into a trading range at about one-third its top price.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the experience, E-Loan Chief Executive Chris
Larsen said, ``If it wasn't for Prozac, I never would have gotten
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's bright future
</P>
<P>
   Economist A. Gary Shilling has a slightly different take on why
Atlanta-based Home Depot has become the giant of home improvement
retailing. It's U.S. tax policy, he says in Forbes (Sept. 6).
</P>
<P>
   In addition to overhead costs and the need for a profit margin,
the professional plumber, electrician or carpenter has to charge a
huge fee to cover the government's tax take _ a fee that may be
bigger than the cost of doing it yourself with products bought at
Home Depot, Lowe's or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   He says the outlook for these retailers is bright, since ``high
tax rates are not going away any time soon,'' nor will the yearning
of ``deskbound professionals'' for do-it-yourself, hands-on work.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Indexing is probably the most popular way to invest in mutual
funds these days, since the fund is guaranteed to do at least as
well as the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, or whatever it is indexed to.
But Bloomberg Personal Finance (September) says funds tracking the
S&AMP;P 500 may not be right for every investor. There are multiple
indices to choose from, and it will take some homework to find the
right one.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fortune (Sept. 6) continues its look at 20th century business
giants with profiles of pioneers in mass media: William Paley of
CBS, Henry Luce of Time and David Sarnoff of RCA. The ``B'' list
includes Ted Turner of CNN, newspaper mogul William Randolph Hearst
and Australian media magnate Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
