<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PEACE _ CAIRO, Egypt _ U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright begins delayed trip to the Middle East here amid positive
signs that Israeli and Palestinian leaders are making headway to
restarting the accords laid out in the Wye River Memorandum. That
agreement, hammered out over several days with President Bill
Clinton and Jordan's King Hussein meditating, has been stalled for
nearly a year. But this time the participants are more numerous and
more ambitious, as this is seen as a stepping stone to an emerging
regionwide effort _ spearheaded by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak. (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   w/MIDEAST-EGYPT _ CAIRO, Egypt _ Yasmin Mahdy remembers the hope
she felt when she watched and videotaped the signing ceremony of
the Oslo Accords between Israel and the Palestinians in 1993. Now,
it has stalled and she's wary as her country hosts the latest
attempt Thursday to revive the peace process. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Albright arrives in Cairo Wed. night. and main story may
have to be updated with news of progress on agreement.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CAUCASUS _ TBILISI, Georgia _ It may seem like a small
war. But looks are deceiving. Russia's latest military action in
its southern republic of Dagestan has far-reaching implications for
the stability of the former superpower and the well-being of the
oil-rich Caspian Sea region. Russia declared victory two weeks ago
when Russian forces managed to re-take several villages and push
many of the guerrillas out of Dagestan, back across the border into
the breakaway republic of Chechnya. But the Chechen warlords, now
back in Chechnya, vow they will regroup and return to challenge
Russian forces in Dagestan. It was a clear sign that Russia may
have won some battles, but it has not won the war. (Christie, Cox
News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/CAUCASUS-BOX-$ADV22 (MOVED PREVIOUSLY).
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA _ Robert Pastor, once a nominee for ambassador to Panama,
talks about Mireya Moscoso, the new Panama president being sworn in
today 31 years after her husband was overthrown. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CARE _ Two Australian CARE workers, convicted of spying during
the NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia, have been pardoned by
President Slobodan Milosevic and released. Steve Pratt and Peter
Wallace were en route Wednesday to Croatia. Pratt's wife, Samira,
is due to give birth soon, and she had recorded a two-minute video
message asking Milosevic for clemency. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AIRTRAN _ An AirTran airplane took off from Hartsfield for
Orlanda, reached 4,000 feet and then returned when the pilot
smelled smoke in the cockpit. No one was hurt. Passengers were
loaded onto another plane and flown away. (Hendricks, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFE-IN-AMERICA _ A series of reports on life in small-town
America _ the values, the stories and the characters _ at the end
of the millennium. This week: TELLURIDE, Colo. _ Melissa Margetts
will never forget the time she sliced open the bulging stomach of a
cow elk that had been seriously injured by a car on top of Dallas
Divide. The emergency roadside Caesarean yielded a calf in obvious
distress. ``We grabbed her by the back legs and spun her around so
the centrifugal force would get this fluid out of her lungs,''
explains Margetts. ``I had given her mouth-to-mouth and it took
four minutes to get her going.'' The calf, nicknamed Junebug, was
nursed back to health and released into the wild last December.
Margetts, a modern-day Dr. Dolittle meets MacGyver, heads up the
Rocky Mountain Ark Wildlife Rehabilitation Center on a 14-acre
spread high in the San Juan Mountains near Telluride. (Cumpston,
Grand Junction Daily Sentinel) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   MALCOLMX-DONATION _ATLANTA _Local guy has donated to Emory
University Library a horde of previously unseen correspondence from
Malcolm X. Experts of Malcolmology say they are quite significant
for scholarship, since many of his private papers were destroyed
after his assassination. ``Given how well-known and appropriately
celebrated Malcolm is, it's embarrassing that the historical
scholarship on him is so modest and spotty and incomplete,'' Garrow
says. ``This material shows what an immensely talented individual
he was, even when he was 20 years old. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EAGLE _ A federal judge has denied a Delray Beach man's request
to borrow an eagle feather for Native American religious
ceremonies. Harvey ``Fire Bird'' Gibson said he needs an eagle
feather for certain customs as a Creek Indian. Problem is, eagles
are protected by the government (even dead ones are kept at a
Colorado depository), and the govt doesn't recognize his branch of
the Creeks. Supposedly, Judge Hurley in his ruling did say he was
``troubled'' by the arbitrary manner by which the govt chooses to
recognize Indians; Gibson said he's disappointed, but he's
appealling the decision. (Hiaasen, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   POGO _ WASHINGTON _ A little-known whistleblower's lawsuit has
exposed what plaintiffs contend is a billion-dollar conspiracy by
the big oil companies to defraud taxpayers out of royalties on oil
and gas taken from public lands and offshore oil and gas fields.
And it has pushed a little-known public interest group, the Project
on Government Oversight, into a new world of wealth and
controversy. (Nesmith, Cox News Service)
</P>
