<HEADER>
A7652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-ART(T     09-01 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-ART(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL GANGS CLASH IN EAST TIMOR CAPITAL AS BALLOT COUNT BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ With a jumble of swords, slingshots and
automatic weapons, gangs of street toughs battled outside the
United Nations compound here Wednesday, killing at least one person
and trapping scores of U.N. officials and journalists inside for
several hours.
</P>
<P>
   One man was clubbed to the ground with a rifle butt, then hacked
to death with machetes a few yards from the U.N. gate.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian police, who have been criticized by the United
Nations for their ineffectiveness, were slow to arrive. And they
mostly stood aside during much of the fighting, failing to protect
either Indonesians or foreigners who were beaten by the thugs.
</P>
<P>
   The street battle, which ended in early evening, was part of a
surge of tension as U.N. officials began counting ballots
Wednesday, two days after a referendum to decide on whether this
tiny, disputed territory should become independent of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After Indonesian invasion and the 24 years of war that followed,
during which some 200,000 people died in this former Portuguese
colony, East Timor has become a symbol of the resistance of small
territories against foreign occupation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the United Nations, which conducted the referendum,
said it would be about a week before the process of counting and
validating the ballots is complete and the results are announced.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and analysts here said the period just before and
after the announcement holds a high potential for violence.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I am gravely concerned about the prospect of renewed violence
in this post-balloting stage,'' said the British ambassador to
Indonesia, Robin Christopher, a few hours before the fighting
erupted Wednesday. ``The situation is quite dire. In East Timor we
have really seen intimidation developed into a fine art.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's violence resembled a gang war between groups of
toughs supporting the two sides in the referendum. They taunted and
threatened one another, dancing, wiggling their behinds and making
rude gestures, then firing slingshots and homemade pistols,
accompanied by puffs of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unequal fight. The rulers of the street were the young
men who have been organized by the Indonesian military into ragtag
militias that have terrorized East Timor in an effort to derail the
referendum and block independence.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's strong turnout of nearly 99 percent of registered
voters was a defeat for their campaign of intimidation, and it
suggested the strong possibility of a victory for the
pro-independence side.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may see this as their last chance of reversing the
process,'' Damian Kingsbury, a professor at Monash University in
Australia, said of the pro-Indonesian gangs. ``It seems they really
have nowhere to go but to create havoc.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Donald Emmerson, a professor at the University of Wisconsin in
Madison, said the violence could be seen as a last attempt by the
militias to assert their importance against a tide that may have
turned against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many militias are more or less resigned to the momentum toward
independence,'' he said.``They have shifted to an assertive mode
in which you kill in order to maintain your place on the landscape.
People have to take you into account. You matter.''
</P>
<P>
   There is frustration evident in the gangs' anger against
foreigners, whom they see as favoring the pro-independence forces.
They seem particularly angry at foreign journalists, who keep
rushing to take their pictures when they become _ as one elderly
woman here put it _ ``naughty.''
</P>
<P>
   One reporter, Jonathan Head of the BBC, was beaten with a rifle
butt, although he was not seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's fighting also showed the role played by feuds among
local gangs. These have been heightened as the military has armed
some groups to act as their surrogate spoilers.
</P>
<P>
   With Dili, East Timor's capital, broken into a checkerboard of
pro- and anti-independence neighborhoods, the violence Wednesday
apparently began when a militia group attacked a market area near
the U.N. compound, burning several houses.
</P>
<P>
   Local ruffians fought back with their homemade weapons, and the
little street in front of the compound became a chaos of people
running back and forth with sticks, stones, hatchets and television
cameras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
