<HEADLINE>
TECHNO NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple Is Top Banana in the PC Speed Wars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer humbled the rest of the personal computer
industry this week by introducing a new desktop machine based on
the Motorola PowerPC G4 processor, which Apple calls ``a
supercomputer on a chip.'' Using the Intel Corp.'s own benchmark
software, a 500-megahertz G4 Macintosh simply smoked the fastest
chip in Intel's PC lineup, the Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   Intel countered by announcing that its long-awaited Coppermine
Pentium III processor, operating at a minimum speed of 700 MHz,
will be available in new personal computers by the end of October.
Coppermine is a code name for Intel's new submicron chip
manufacturing process that packs all the circuitry of a Pentium III
chip into a much smaller package, which makes the chip run faster.
</P>
<P>
   Intel itself needs to run faster to catch up to its competitors
in the PC world. The new Advanced Micro Devices Athlon (formerly
called K-7) processor, used by Compaq and several other PC makers,
outperforms the top Pentium III chips on benchmarking tests.
</P>
<P>
   But Apple, with the surprise announcement of its G4 chip family,
is now the top banana in the PC speed wars. Apple announced three
new, silver-and-gray Macintosh desktop models based on G4 chips, at
roughly same prices as Apple's current G3 models. The first,
available now, is a 400-MHz G4 that starts at $1,599.
</P>
<P>
   Power-hungry Mac users might be advised to wait, however. The
400-MHz model is based on an older Mac system design and is
considered the runt of the litter. The next two models will be
based on a new, high-performance Macintosh architecture called
Sawtooth. Apple said it would begin shipping the first of these
screamers, a 450-MHz G4 starting at $2,499, in a couple of weeks,
followed a few weeks later by a 500-MHz model that costs $3,499.
</P>
<P>
   And no desktop supercomputer would be complete without a
super-sized flat-panel monitor, so Apple also introduced a 22-inch
``Cinema Display'' for just $4,000 extra. The new systems are
expected to be popular among graphic arts and publishing
professionals, especially those on expense accounts.
</P>
<P>
   _ PETER H. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   New Receiver for PC's Sounds and Looks Good  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the growing popularity of large computer monitors,
high-fidelity sound cards and internal DVD-ROM and MP3 players, the
quality of personal computer speaker systems is beginning to share
the sort of cachet once only associated with the of the latest
microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   Now the PC audio ante is being upped yet again with the
introduction of a stereo receiver made specifically for home
computers. Packing 30 watts per channel, Yamaha's home
entertainment reeceiver called the (at)PET RP-U100 is designed to
stand between a computer's Central Processing Unit and its
speakers, amplifying and refining the resulting sound. The $500
receiver, which, of course, includes an AM-FM digital tuner, and
home theater enhancements to help create surround-like sounds,
looks very much like a CPU tower as it stands on its four little
feet next to the monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The Yamaha receiver uses a universal serial bus to connect to
computers, and features connectors that permit home stereo speakers
to be used, rather than the often tinny-sounding one frequently
included with personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, high-output, powered computer speakers with their own
built-in amplifiers will do much the same job, and perhaps better,
for less than half the price (even Yamaha makes an 80-watt
three-piece speaker system for PCs).
</P>
<P>
   But powered speakers don't have as many cool buttons and dials
as the beefy new desktop receiver has. And that should count for
something, right?
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   The High-End Camera Moves Up a Notch
</P>
<P>
   Just as digital cameras are dropping in price and consumers are
growing more eager to squint into the viewfinders of relatively
low-resolution, point-and-shoot cameras, some manufacturers are
preparing to offer a new, more highly evolved digital camera that
has much more in common with their professional-grade,
single-lens-reflex counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Electronics recently announced its Cyber-shot DSC-F505,
priced just below $1,000, a mega-pixel camera that looks like an
unlikely marriage between a digital point-and-shoot and the kind of
barrel-lensed still camera more commonly found in the hands of
fashion photographers. A closer look at this magnesium-skinned
machine reveals a rotating, Carl Zeiss Vario-Sonnar lens,
high-speed automatic focus and digital zoom.
</P>
<P>
   This camera also shoots in 2.1 million pixel, 1,600-by-1,200
resolution, meaning that prints made from this digital camera are
more likely to rival photographs taken with traditional
35-millimeter cameras. The Cyber-shot can also produce moving
picture and sound clips in MPEG movie mode.
</P>
<P>
   Sony has also introduced a $1,999 Cyber-Shot Pro that features
even higher image resolution and a sort of no-tech mode that
permits photographers to manually set their exposure settings and
focus. Canon USA is also offering its own version of a new
professional-class digital camera _ but with a twist. Called the
PowerShot S10 (price still undetermined), this 2.1 mega-pixel
camera with a zoom lens is the smallest and lightest of its kind,
Canon says.
</P>
<P>
   While the Sony Cyber-Shot camera uses only Memory Sticks for
removable storage, the PowerShot and Cyber-Shot Pro uses flash
memory cards.
</P>
<P>
   Yukiaki Hashimoto, vice president and general manager of the
photographic products group for Canon USA called the camera
``sophisticated and easier to use.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A New Reason Not to Curse at Your PC  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember the scene from ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' where the evil
computer Hal 9000 discovers the plot to disconnect him by reading
the astronauts lips? In a few years, your PC will use the same
technique to find out when you might pull the plug on it.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Waibel, a professor of computer science at Carnegie-Mellon
University in Pittsburgh and the University of Karlsruhe in
Germany, has been developing a speech-recognition software that
reads lips as part of a project to increase the accuracy of
recognition systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems with speech-recognition systems are they're not
good in a noisy environment and that they're not robust enough for
spontaneous speech,'' Dr. Waibel said. ``They basically don't know
what you're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   The software, Nlips, uses a video camera to observe the
speaker's lips, jaw and, when visible, tongue. Observed
lip-sequences, which Waibel playfully calls ``visemes,'' because
they are the visual equivalent of differentiated sounds called
phomenes, were then fed into a neural network. The software would
then take the phrase, for example, ``no new taxes'' and check the
lip sequences against the sound sequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were working with the interesting effect, first observed in
the 1970s, that when people are listening, they are also visually
tracking the movements of the lips.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nlips software only increases speech-recognition accuracy by
1 percent or 2 percent in a quiet environment. But when there's
background noise and the accuracy of speech-only recognition drops
to about 60 percent, Nlips can lift the figure back up to 85
percent. Dr. Waibel expects the technology will be commercial
applications in five to 10 years, when cameras on computers and
even in cars become more common.
</P>
<P>
   _ BRUCE HEADLAM
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
