<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POLAND-GERMANY-ART-47     09-01 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-GERMANY-ART-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
60 YEARS LATER, GERMANY SEEKS RECONCILIATION WITH POLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(EDS: Awkward quote at end of 16th graf is CQ.) 
(th) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Germany on Wednesday marked the 60th anniversary of its
invasion of Poland and the start of World War II by declaring that
its eastern neighbor should have a place in the European Union as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when most major newspapers chose to ignore the
anniversary _ a sign of a certain German weariness over such
commemorations _ President Johannes Rau traveled to Gdansk,
birthplace of the Solidarity labor movement, and thanked Poles for
igniting the resistance in the former Soviet bloc that ultimately
led to the collapse of communism in Europe and the unification of
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Solidarity, Rau said: ``This freedom movement made
the reunification of Germany possible. On this day and in this
place, I would like to pay tribute to that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   No such formal acknowledgment at the highest level had
previously been made, and Rau's visit clearly reflected the
continuing German attempt to overcome the bitter wounds of the war,
an effort that began when Willy Brandt fell to his knees in the
Warsaw ghetto in 1974 and has quickened since the Cold War's end.
</P>
<P>
   But although official ties have improved enormously, and the two
countries became NATO allies this year when Poland joined the
alliance, relations between Poles and Germans remain generally
cool. They are clouded by old suspicions, problems of illegal
immigration across the now porous border, and sometimes plain
prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trip over the border to a market is usually sufficient for
the German tourist who fears his car will be stolen if he goes
deeper into the country,'' The Berliner Morgenpost noted.
``Beautifully renovated cities like Gdansk and Wroclaw arouse
little curiosity among Germans.''
</P>
<P>
   With the German capital now back in Berlin, just 50 miles from a
border that was moved a long way westward at the end of World War
II, relations with Poland have become an important concern.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually forceful statement issued Wednesday, Joschka
Fischer, the German foreign minister, said that ``Germany believes
that measures must be taken to insure Poland's entry into the
European Union at the soonest possible date.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations on membership of the 15-member bloc have been
painstakingly slow. With Europe long focused on the introduction of
the single currency, the euro, and still concerned over competition
from former East bloc countries with cheaper labor, progress has
proved difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who shares a growing German desire
to look forward rather than back, chose to defer Wednesday to Rau,
whose role is mainly ceremonial. But in remarks to journalists, the
chancellor said it should be remembered that Berlin is the city
``where the most hideous crime ever began.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder is to travel to Poland on Friday for two days of
meetings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The chancellor has been criticized since taking office for
declining a French invitation last November to join World War I
armistice celebrations, for being absent from Parliament this
summer when a long-delayed project for a Berlin Holocaust memorial
was approved, and for not interrupting his summer vacation last
month to attend the burial in Israel of Ignatz Bubis, the leader of
the main German Jewish organization.
</P>
<P>
   But there can be little doubt that the chancellor's position _
acknowledgment and awareness of the past allied to a determination
to look beyond it _ reflects that of a large majority of Germans,
tired of being pilloried for crimes that took place before most of
them were born.
</P>
<P>
   Germany had hoped to reach a settlement by Wednesday for the
compensation of slave laborers and others forced to work by the
Nazis, but disagreements over the amount to be paid have stalled
the discussions. The issue is sensitive because many of the
laborers were Poles, and Rau said ``reconciliation'' would be
helped by an accord.
</P>
<P>
   Rau held a symbolic meeting with Aleksander Kwasniewski, the
Polish president, on the German-Polish border, before going on to
Gdansk, the city that was the object of the dawn barrage from the
battleship Schleswig-Holstein that started the war. Gdansk was then
Danzig, a port and free city populated largely by ethnic Germans.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gdansk ceremony, Kwasniewski recalled that six million
Polish citizens died in World War II _ about half of them were
Jews. ``Shalom!,'' he said. ``I turn to the Jews among you, to the
victims of the Holocaust, and descendants of a common fate. You
sentenced to death by Nazism _ the world must never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   In the light of frequent tensions between Catholic Poles and
Jews over the extent of their respective suffering in World War II,
Kwasniewski's allusion to ``a common fate'' appeared a significant
sign of Poland's determination to put such friction behind it.
</P>
<P>
   A German veteran of the Schleswig-Holstein, Martin Menzel, said,
``I now understand what the war was and I ask for forgiveness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-framing-art-2NDTAKE-N     09-01 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-framing-art-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Bull said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, before frames increased in price, Roger
Ward, the curator of European art at the Nelson-Atkins Museum, made
a list of the 20 most difficult to frame paintings in his
collection. ``The price I paid then for a period frame couldn't
even pay for a reproduction now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nelson-Atkins was one of the first museums to
comprehensively reframe major portions of its Old Masters and
European art collection.
</P>
<P>
   Ward said that 60 of his paintings now wear antique frames.
</P>
<P>
   One of his prized paintings, Caravaggio's ``St. John the
Baptist,'' had been framed in a spindly 18th-century tapestry
molding that had been cobbled together. Ward found a 16th-century
Italian altarpiece frame that was appropriate to the scale and
color of the painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this was originally stuck in a stone altar, this frame
is as close to the original as I could get,'' he said. When he
bought the frame in 1987 it cost just over $26,000. ``It would cost
a lot more now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward said he realized that he is luckier than most museum
curators: ``I had sympathetic trustees and a sympathetic director.
I have an endowment for my department, which includes expenses for
things such as frames, so I don't have to find a donor for every
frame I want to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Art Institute of Chicago, curators have been evaluating
the need to reframe gallery by gallery. With financial help from
the museum's Old Masters Society, a group of about 400 people, and
from the institute's director, curators have raised $125,000 for
the Dutch and Flemish galleries and are raising another $225,000
for reframing major works in the mid-19th-century galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The ``before and after'' presentations at the museum have
persuaded potential donors to help. To illustrate the difference an
appropriate frame can make, curators take Corot's ``Interrupted
Reading,'' an image of a woman looking up from her book. First they
show the painting in its original 17th-century Italian frame, which
had been stripped and painted a dull brown, presumably to match the
painting's background. Then they replace that frame with an 1870
Louis XIII-revival-style frame from Wiggins in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It restores the balance between the background and the flesh
tones in the figure,'' said Gloria Groom, a curator in the museum's
department of European paintings. ``This is a frame the artist
would have put on the painting for an exhibition in a salon in the
second half of the 19th century.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum started to think about reframing nearly 10 years ago,
with the exhibition ``Monet in the 90s.'' ``When we put paintings
of similar subjects together we could actually see what was
historically and esthetically pleasing,'' Ms. Groom said. Some of
the original frames on works the museum borrowed, she said, opened
curators' eyes. ``Ninety-nine percent of the time we try to figure
out what the artist put the picture in himself,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The reframing project has been ``a consciousness-raising
exercise,'' said Douglas Druick, the senior curator of European
paintings at the Art Institute of Chicago. ``A lot of the Dutch
paintings that had entered the collection at the same time were
suffering under the weight of the robber-baron frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Curators don't always have the luxury of spending years seeking
the right period frame when they make changes gallery by gallery.
The Chicago museum has often had reproductions made. Of the six
Monet haystack paintings in their collection, two have their
original frames. The others have frames made by Mitchell, all
different but all based on the classical vocabulary of the Louis
XVI style.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's star painting, Seurat's ``Sunday Afternoon on la
Grande Jatte,'' still doesn't have a frame that satisfies curators.
They consider it too big, too round and too white. ``We feel we
need to revisit this,'' Ms. Groom said.
</P>
<P>
   While the designers who made the frame in 1989 took the shape
from the artist's rendition (Seurat is famous for his
impossible-to-match white frames), what they considered
historically correct then does not do justice to the painting.
``Historically correct doesn't always work,'' Ms. Groom said.
``It's difficult to age white because there's a patina you can't
get. We just have to keep experimenting.''
</P>
<P>
   What may be considered historically accurate and what an artist
would have wanted are not always what the public likes. In 1986
curators at the Baltimore Museum of Art removed the ornately carved
wood-and-cast-plaster frames from the fabled collection of Matisses
that had belonged to Dr. Claribel Cone, a Baltimore pathologist,
and her sister, Etta Cone, who bequeathed their collection to the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   They replaced the Cones' elaborate frames with simple strip
frames and stored the originals. Scholars applauded the museum's
boldness, but some visitors criticized the move.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Doreen Bolger became the museum's new director,
one of her first decisions was to restore the Cone sisters' frames.
``We know that Matisse made comments about not liking elaborate
frames, but there have been strong feelings in Baltimore that the
Cones' frames should go back on the Matisses,'' she said. ``When I
first saw them in strip frames I wanted to see the paintings in the
more traditional frames.''
</P>
<P>
   Archival pictures of the artist's studio show that Matisse put
his paintings in flat-edged strip frames, and in a letter that he
wrote in 1916 he said he was ``very opposed to frames and
particularly heavy frames that surround the paintings with a yellow
color, stopping all expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``A modern painting has no need for a frame: it
should have a simple border at most.''
</P>
<P>
   So who is right? ``We have to acknowledge changes in tastes and
no doubt tastes will change again; it's cyclical,'' Ms. Bolger
said. ``Framing is definitely subject to interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason museums are saddled with frames that do not do
justice to their paintings is that many of the world's most famous
dealers during the last two centuries _ figures like Joseph Duveen
and Paul Durand-Ruel _ put paintings in imposing gilt frames to
impress their nouveau-riche clients.
</P>
<P>
   The scroll-shaped corners of a Durand-Ruel frame, for example,
can be instantly identified by any seasoned curator. Their
flourishes served a purpose. When a painting looked more impressive
framed in heavy gilt, it could command a higher price. Ornately
carved gilt frames were also used to tame what were considered wild
Impressionist paintings, and they went well with the fine
18th-century French furniture that was the decorating trend of the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 19th and early 20th centuries, however, artists
became involved in framing. Whistler refused to allow anyone to
design his frames and made simple ones himself. Some
Impressionists, particularly Pissarro and Degas, put their pictures
in plain white, gray, yellow and even purple frames of their own
design. Post-Impressionist artists like Seurat, van Gogh and
Gauguin made frames that in colors that complemented their
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are no rules for what makes an appropriate frame,
although curators are mindful of a painting's history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRAMING-ART-2TAKES-NY     09-01 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAMING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUMS LOOK AGAIN AT THEIR PICTURE FRAMES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a hushed gallery at the Brooklyn Museum of Art,
Elizabeth Easton, the curator of European paintings, and Jared
Bark, the founder of Bark Frameworks in SoHo, were huddled around a
Sisley landscape. The talk was not about the painting, but of its
Louis XV-style reproduction gilt frame festooned with intricately
carved flowers, swags and shells. ``Look how the frame overpowers
the painting,'' said Ms. Easton. ``It's just too Louie-Schmooie.''
</P>
<P>
   Dissatisfied with the frames on many of the pictures in their
collections, museum curators from Brooklyn to Kansas City, Mo., are
caught up in a flurry of costly reframing projects. At the
Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas City the curator of European
paintings has spent $500,000 to reframe 75 paintings. The National
Gallery of Art in Washington paid $60,000 to put a 17th-century
walnut frame on Rembrandt's ``Man in Oriental Costume,'' the most
it has ever paid for a frame. At the Art Institute of Chicago
curators do a special ``before and after'' presentation to
encourage benefactors to support the cost of reframing paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, as museums across the country expand, works that
have languished in storage are being re-evaluated. In today's
robust art market, curators can no longer afford to buy paintings
as often as they once could, so they try to make the best of what
they have. Sometimes a painting brought back into view has a frame
deemed hopelessly out of fashion; or a painting, framed to enhance
a donor's decor, just doesn't work in a museum. But scholarship
also plays a role. In recent years curators armed with new
information about how artworks were originally framed are becoming
fussier about authenticity
</P>
<P>
   So now, in addition to raising money for exhibitions,
acquisitions and expansions, curators are also trying to convince
donors that the right frame, which can cost tens of thousands of
dollars, is not just window dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Framing has always been a business,'' said Keith Christiansen,
a curator of European painting at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
``But now there's big money in it.'' Like the price of all
antiques, those of frames from the 17th through 19th centuries have
escalated in the last decade. The most expensive and hardest to
find are the simple, hand-carved 17th-century frames that curators
covet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, at the Bond Street gallery of Paul Mitchell, frames
of all ages, sizes and styles line every available inch of wall.
Mitchell's business is booming largely because of work from
American museums. ``It's a ripple effect,'' Mitchell said. ``Once a
curator changes a frame on one picture he wants to keep going.''
When one curator learns that a colleague at a competing museum is
reframing a collection, he suddenly wants to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   In art history books, pictures are shown, but rarely their
frames, Mitchell said. ``Famous paintings are cataloged from head
to toe, but about their frames you know nothing,'' he said.
``That's because art history books only show the picture. They
don't show the frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Some artists have had definite ideas about how their works
should be framed, but this information is also rarely documented.
</P>
<P>
   So framers like Mitchell compiled their own historical
references. He has systematically photographed pictures in their
frames and created an archive of more than 40,000 paintings from
museums, private collections, exhibitions and auctions worldwide.
He also uses computer imaging to show clients how one painting
might look with different frames.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few paintings have withstood the ravages of time in their
original frame,'' he said. ``Generally Old Masters have been
divorced from their frames, either because of change of ownership,
transport (it's easier to ship a painting without its frame) or
changing tastes in interior decoration.''
</P>
<P>
   Every artistic movement has produced its own style of frame. The
earliest frames, from the Renaissance, were merely protective edges
for religious paintings and were extensions of the painting. The
conception of frames as separate from the painting began in Italy
during the 16th century. By the 19th century frame making had
become a growth industry as the new middle class framed everything
from paintings to lithographs.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Gallery of Art in Washington, a frame committee
of four museum staff members _ David Bull, a senior consultant in
the conservation department; Philip Conisbee, senior curator of
European paintings; Mark Leithauser, chief of design, and Alan
Shestack, deputy director and chief curator _ was formed 10 years
ago to reduce the chances of choices based purely on personal
taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we change a frame all of us have to agree,'' Bull said.
Since 1990 the National Gallery has reframed some 200 paintings and
plans to do 200 more.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is so large, the museum has a growing computer
database that consists of some 3,000 frames in its collection.
Along with images and detailed descriptions of each frame are
conservators' reports. ``We look within our own collection first
whenever we decide to reframe something,'' Conisbee said.
</P>
<P>
   When the committee members decided to find a new frame for
Degas' ``Three Dancers,'' for instance, they discovered the perfect
one in their storeroom. It was designed by Degas and was originally
on the painting, which had been badly reframed by a dealer by the
time it came to the museum in the 1940s. Luckily the original frame
accompanied the painting. Because museum policy is never to throw
out a frame, conservators were able to restore the more restrained
Degas frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get rid of frames just in case 50 years from now
people think we've made a mistake,'' Leithauser said. ``This way
they can easily change something.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dutch Old Masters, reframing can be a challenge because
large 17th-century frames rarely exist. ``In the 19th century
dealers and collectors took off the original 17th-century black
frames believing they were too somber and devoid of decoration,''
Leithauser said. ``If you were a collector with a Rembrandt, you
wanted a frame that said, `I am a Rembrandt.' The older frames were
therefore scrapped or burned.''
</P>
<P>
   For van Eyck's ``Annunciation,'' which is 36{ inches by just
over 14] inches, the committee studied the original frames that
they found on paintings by the same artist. One in the National
Gallery of Art in London became the basis for a reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   But the gallery was able to find a perfect match for Rembrandt's
``Man in Oriental Costume,'' a 17th-century frame costing $60,000
from Guttman Frames. It replaced the overpowering gold frame that
was on the painting when the museum acquired it. The men have no
regrets. ``Compared to what the painting is worth, it's cheap,''
Bull said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
