<HEADER>
A7666 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-WORKERS-GORE-HNS &LR;      09-01 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKERS-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING AMERICANS SUPPORT BUSH OVER GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Embargoed for release until 12:01 a.m., Thursday, Sept. 2)   (FILED in ``p'' and ``w'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite his ardent courtship of organized labor and
his emphasis on workplace issues, Vice President Al Gore trails
Texas Gov. George W. Bush among working Americans, according to a
poll being released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey by Rutgers University in New Jersey and the
University of Connecticut found that in head-to-head competition
Bush beat Gore 49 percent to 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When other candidates were considered, Bush still had a solid
plurality, garnering 32 percent compared with 23 percent for Gore,
according to the poll, which surveyed 1,000 randomly selected
Americans who are employed or looking for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the frontrunners were Republican Elizabeth Dole with 10
percent, Democrat Bill Bradley with 6 percent and Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., with 3 percent. The survey was conducted between July 30
and Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``This definitely is something of a wake-up call for the Gore
campaign,'' said Carl E. Van Horn, a political science professor at
Rutgers and co-director of the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn said the main reason for Gore's deficit is that working
Americans have given him ``little credit'' for the booming economy
and low unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how much credit should be given to Gore for the
health of the economy, 8 percent responded ``a lot,'' 44 percent
said ``some'' and 31 percent said ``not at all.'' Asked about any
credit due Clinton, 25 percent said ``a lot'' and 44 percent said
``some.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Gore is remembered more as the man who supported
Clinton through impeachment than as an architect of the surging
economy,'' Van Horn said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Gore has been hindered by a common problem for vice
presidents who run for president: he is considered ``the weak
family member.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn added, ``Let's face it, the job of vice president is
not a glamorous position designed to make you look like you're the
one in charge. And that image takes time to shake.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll, the only groups of working Americans to
support Gore over Bush were minority workers, those making less
than $10,000 a year and those identifying themselves as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has won the endorsement of the Communications Workers of
America, the International Association of Firefighters and the
United Transportation Union, as well as several chapters of the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Workers.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki Moore, a Gore spokeswoman, downplayed the poll results,
saying the presidential campaign is in its ``early stages'' and
that most voters have yet to hear where the candidates stand on
issues important to working Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing these numbers reflect is the fact that most
voters are still learning what Al Gore and George Bush are saying
about things like health care coverage and education,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn said a ``silver lining'' in the poll for Gore was that
a large number of working Americans _ 27 percent _ said they were
unsure which candidate would handle the economy best. ``There is
still time for the vice president to turn this situation around,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll, the top issue for working Americans is
education. Ninety percent of those surveyed said improving the
nation's schools and increasing the number of programs to retrain
workers for high-tech jobs are the most important tasks facing the
next president.
</P>
<P>
   Poll respondents listed other critical issues as expanding
medical coverage, protecting retirement benefits and ensuring
economic security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike past elections, working people today are not terribly
worried about finding a job,'' Van Horn said. ``Instead, they're
worried about the future _ both their and their children's
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted by the Heldrich Center for Workforce
Development at Rutgers and the Center for Survey Research and
Analysis at the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
