<HEADER>
A7672 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BELL-THEFT-1STLD-WRIT     09-01 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-THEFT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH RECOVERS BELLS, A GIFT OF RUSSIAN CZAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Complete writethru to reflect that bells recovered; edits to
conform.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MALCOLM GLOVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three bells that were the gift of a 19th-century
Russian czar were returned to the Orthodox Holy Trinity Cathedral
on Wednesday, four days after they disappeared from the bell tower.
</P>
<P>
   They were among five bells that were given to the San Francisco
church _ the oldest Eastern Orthodox parish in the continental
United States _ in 1888 by Czar Alexander III.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Victor Sokolov said the bells were found on the front
steps of the church, at Van Ness Avenue and Green Street, at 8 a.m.
Wednesday by painters who were repairing damage from an arson fire
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sokolov said a man went to the church and said he had the bells,
``but emphasized that he hadn't stolen them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sokolov said the man told his daughter that he had bought the
bells from another man ``on the street'' for $250. He said he
didn't realize that they had been stolen until he read about it in
the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The man did not have the bells with him but said that he would
return them to the church. He apparently returned them sometime
late Tuesday night or early Wednesday morning, Sokolov said.
</P>
<P>
   The bells did not appear to be damaged, Sokolov said.
</P>
<P>
   Cast in Moscow, the heavy bells adorned with decorative
scrollwork are believed to be unique in the United States and rare
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Choir members noticed the bells missing when they prepared to
ring them before the 6 p.m. service on Saturday. At first they
thought painters might have moved them, but an extensive search of
the building failed to turn them up.
</P>
<P>
   After a call to the painting company confirmed that workers had
not moved the bells, church officials notified the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never imagined somebody actually stealing them,'' said
Robert A. Parent, the choir director of the church. ``Why would
anybody want to? I cannot imagine what kind of value they would
have to people other than to the church itself and to San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   A silver alloy was used to cast them, providing an unusually
pure, distinct tone not found in modern-day bells, Sokolov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an art form,'' he said. ``Nothing exists today of this
caliber anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The church and its bells are a popular attraction in the city.
Guides regularly begin their tours by listening to the bells every
Sunday at 10 a.m. at Van Ness Avenue and Green Street.
</P>
<P>
   The bell tower stands some 50 feet off the ground, and normally
is accessible only from inside the church. The doors of the church
are locked and protected by an alarm system.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 10 days, however, parts of the two-story wooden
church have been undergoing repairs needed after a fire on Easter
Day 1998. The unsolved arson destroyed parts of the church and
caused $20,000 in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials suspect the scaffolding surrounding the
building and covered by a dark green canvas provided easy access
and shelter to thieves.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the five Russian bells, two others cast in the
same time period in the United States make up the complete set of
seven bells.
</P>
<P>
   Each bell represents a different tone, the smallest bell of
about 10 inches in diameter providing the lighter sounds, while the
largest ``Great Bell'' provides deeper tones.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone absconding with a bell would need to cut or untie the
cables and clamps supporting it from the beams of the tower and
then either carry it down the narrow scaffolding or lower it,
perhaps with a rope.
</P>
<P>
   Sokolov said the theft would be an impossible feat for one
person, and a difficult task for two.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials have moved some of the bells inside but left
the two largest _ one of them weighing 5,765 pounds and presumably
too heavy to steal without heavy machinery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7674 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-DEADMEN-WRITING-TEX     09-01 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEADMEN-WRITING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECEASED AUTHORS CONTINUE TO PUBLISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their tombstones might read: ``Dead, but still being
published.'' Recent bestseller lists have included fiction by Ralph
Ellison and Ernest Hemingway. This summer, critics have raved about
a short-story collection from Dashiell Hammett.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most anticipated books of the fall are new titles from
Jack Kerouac and Sir Winston Churchill, with the latest John
Steinbeck title just a few years away.
</P>
<P>
   These authors have two things in common: Each was lionized in
life, and each has just been published or is about to be published
years after his death. Their modern-day publishers, from Knopf to
Random House to Scribner, are secure in the knowledge that there's
always a ready market for previously unavailable work by famous
deceased authors, and that the quality doesn't necessarily matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ranges from treasures to curiosities, just like what you
might come across in Grandmother's attic,'' says Charles Scribner,
whose company has published seven books by Hemingway since the
legendary ``Papa's'' death in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a story about a former president that is appropriate
here,'' Scribner says. ``The widow of Warren G. Harding said of her
late husband, `He was great in life and even greater in death.'
Sometimes that is true of authors, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that readers are always ready to snap up anything
``new'' by their favorite dead authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cases like Ellison and Hemingway and Hammett, there are
always fans out there who love them and must have any new books by
them,'' says Michael Millman, an editor at Penguin/Putnam, which
will publish a collection of Kerouac's early, previously
unpublished stories in November under its Viking imprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It often seems immaterial whether it's of high quality or just
any old thing pulled out of a shoe box by surviving family
members.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Juneteenth,'' gleaned from a 2,000-page work in progress by
Ellison when he died in 1994, received rave reviews when it was
published this summer. Hemingway's ``True at First Light,'' a
heavily edited retooling of a novel he began and discarded some 40
years ago, was savaged by critics but still made most bestseller
lists. Hammett's ``Nightmare Town'' is expected to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Random House senior editor Scott Moyers, who worked on Ellison's
``Juneteenth,'' says he felt ``responsibility to the author, the
author's estate and fans not to exploit his reputation. You want to
do right by the author, and also sell books to pay the light
bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Posthumous publishing is nothing new; a famous example is ``The
Mystery of Edwin Drood,'' cited by many as one of the earliest
``modern'' mystery stories. It was written by Charles Dickens, who
died in 1870 without completing the tale. His editors finished the
work on his behalf, and grieving fans rushed to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   But recent years have seen publishers intensify efforts to track
down anything from completed, hitherto-undiscovered manuscripts to
scraps of story ideas from famous authors. In many cases, family
members have come forward with material.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of Hemingway's sons comes to Scribner and says, `Here's
a book by my dad, do you want to publish it?' do you think Scribner
is going to turn him down?'' says an editor at a rival publishing
house who did not want his name used.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Tolkien, son of J.R.R. Tolkien, has edited nearly a
dozen new works by his father since the elder Tolkien's death in
1973. ``The Hobbit'' and the ``Lord of the Rings'' trilogy made
Tolkien a household name in the '60s and '70s, although these
eventually revered titles were published from the '30s through the
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   In death far more than in life, Tolkien has been prolific. His
post-1973 titles include ``The Book of Lost Tales,'' ``The Book of
Lost Tales, Part II,'' ``The Simarillion,'' and ``Morgoth's Ring:
The Later Simarillion,'' among others. All were welcomed by Tolkien
die-hards.
</P>
<P>
   Unfinished works by Edith Wharton and Dame Agatha Christie have
been resurrected, spruced up and published in recent years. Critics
were routinely unkind. But sometimes, books by dead writers have
been proclaimed classics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, a frustrated would-be writer named John Kennedy Toole
committed suicide at age 32. His novel-in-progress had been
rejected by a series of publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Toole's mother badgered anyone who she thought might help get
her late son's book into print. Finally, author Walker Percy agreed
to read the manuscript. Through his championing of the work, LSU
Press published ``A Confederacy of Dunces'' in 1980, working from
the manuscript Toole had considered finished but other, larger
publishing houses judged unsuitable. ``Dunces'' won the Pulitzer
Prize for fiction.
</P>
<P>
   For publishers, anniversaries are an opportune time to unveil
works by well-known deceased authors. ``True at First Light'' was
published, in part, to take advantage of publicity about
Hemingway's 100th birthday in July.
</P>
<P>
   Sources at Viking have confirmed what industry insiders have
suspected for months: that in 2002, the Steinbeck centenary will
probably feature a new collection of his nonfiction works, possibly
newspaper and magazine articles collected in hardcover for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   But industry insiders say this isn't a trend. ``It has been
going on for a long, long time,'' says Moyers of Random House,
whose current projects include the final editing of ``The Great
Republic: A History of the United States'' by Sir Winston
Churchill, which comprises material selected by Winston Spencer
Churchill from his grandfather's Nobel Prize-winning, four-volume
``A History of the English Speaking People.''
</P>
<P>
   ``''The Aeneid'' was published posthumously; Virgil left
explicit instructions that it should never be published. But aren't
we all glad it was?''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
