<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7675 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-POLITICAL-ACTIVIS     09-01 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-POLITICAL-ACTIVISM-ART-630WORDS(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY FINDS FERTILE GROUND ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
(Steven R. Knowlton is an associate professor of journalism at
Hofstra University.) 
 By STEVEN R. KNOWLTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a recent sweltering Monday evening, nearly 50 residents of
the Bay Ridge neighborhood in Brooklyn jammed into the living room
of a two-story brick row house to talk about problems like erosion
and rats in Owl's Head Park, 27 acres of trees and grass on the
Brooklyn waterfront. It was classic grass-roots organizing, more or
less the way it has been done for generations.
</P>
<P>
   But with every passing month, as more people go online,
community organizers are finding new ways to harness the power of
the Internet. The basics of organization _ using communication to
start a group or keep it together, and finding information that
will arm community organizers with data _ are, one by one, moving
into cyberspace. And individuals can also turn to those same
sources of information when they want to make their voices heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole notion of the Web is to try to get people
involved,'' said William Revelle, a psychology professor at
Northwestern University who says he maintains a page of links to
civic groups (pmc.psych.nwu.edu/civicpart99.html) because, well,
people with computers and civic interests should do that sort of
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Group members can stay in touch through a Web site or a
listserv, a kind of mass mailing possible through e-mail. Both
technologies have their advocates, but Web sites are indispensable
for gathering information. E-mail has also made it vastly easier to
get in touch with elected officials and civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   And because the Web shrinks both time and space, concerned
residents in places like Bay Ridge can turn to it for help,
regardless of whether they want a fenced dog run or Rudy Giuliani
or Hillary Clinton to be their next U.S. Senator.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP E-MAIL  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before each monthly meeting of his coalition of antipoverty
groups in Philadelphia, a veteran community organizer and advocacy
consultant, Edward Schwartz, sends out mass mailings through
ordinary mail and through e-mail. ``Overwhelmingly, the people who
show up are the people on the e-mail list, even though our print
mail goes out to a far larger number of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz began his work as a community organizer when he was
still a teen-ager, nearly 40 years ago. From his perspective, the
real innovation that the computer revolution has provided is what
he calls ``the overlooked technology'': group e-mail, or listservs,
which is ``where the bulk of organizing occurs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If a new group's members can tolerate the advertisements,
Schwartz recommends that the group start an e-mail group free
through www.egroups.com. (Egroups will let you set up a group
without the ads, but it charges $4.95 a month.) Setting up a group
takes 10 minutes or less.
</P>
<P>
   The other way for a group to make its mark in cyberspace is with
a Web site from an organization like Neighborhood Link, which is
free but also has ads (www.neighborhoodlink.com).
</P>
<P>
   A group does not need a computer expert to build a page. Leave
HTML for power users: setting up a page today is no harder than
following the recipe for cookies on the back of the chocolate chips
bag. Service for community groups is a fast-growing areas of the
Internet, and new companies are getting into it almost weekly.
Alternatives to Neighborhood Link include Geocities
(geocities.yahoo.com/home), recently bought by Yahoo, and the
community section of America Online (aol.com/community/home.html).
</P>
<P>
   Is a Web site necessary, or will a listserv suffice? Reading
one's e-mail takes virtually no effort, while going onto the Web
requires at least some. On the other hand, on some listservs that
urgent note about the litter problem in the park can get lost amid
the neighbors' vacation pictures. In the end, though, the two
routes are not exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   RELIABLE INFORMATION  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With thousands of Web sites out there talking politics, someone
seeking reliable political information is in the position
Archimedes described in the third century B.C.: ``Give me where to
stand and I will move the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding such a place on the Net is getting easier because some
people and groups are, in effect, beginning to catalog the
worthwhile stuff. The best sources to begin with are often
universities, which have access not just to libraries but to good
reference librarians.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly helpful site for citizen surfers is Grace A.
York, the federal documents librarian at the University of Michigan
(www.lib.umich.edu/libhome/Documents.center/federal.html). A
handful of the links from her page are to databases that cost money
and are available only at the university, but the list of free and
universally available sites is among the most comprehensive, and
comprehensible, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Another reference librarian, Gary Price, at George Washington
University in Washington maintains a number of Web sites, including
something called Direct Search
(gwis2.circ.gwu.edu/gprice/direct.htm), an eclectic almanac of
information that general search engines (Google, Alta Vista, etc.)
are apt to miss. And a linked state site,
(gwis2.circ.gwu.edu/gprice/state.htm), is also a good place to go
for local and state government sources.
</P>
<P>
   For reliable, meat-and-potatoes political information, research
experts nearly all recommend Project Vote Smart
(www.vote-smart.org). There's no place in the government sites to
find an easy assessment of the voting records of members of
Congress, but on this site, you can track 13,000 voting records,
for them as well as state officials. It's so good that even the
federal government's own congressional portal, Thomas, named for
Thomas Jefferson and his famous advocacy of the free flow of
government information (thomas.loc.gov), recommends it. Vote Smart
is paid for by foundation grants and individual memberships.
</P>
<P>
   Public Agenda, also paid for primarily by foundations rather
than ads, offers as serious and sober a look at public-policy
questions as one could ask for (publicagenda.org). On each of a
score of major issues like crime, the economy, education, Internet
speech and privacy, the site offers an overview, recent articles on
the topic and, especially useful, extended arguments for and
against the major positions on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   The other major plus to this site is its polling primer, which
is understandable because the organization's co-founder (along with
the former Secretary of State, Cyrus R. Vance) is Daniel
Yankelovich, the pollster. The site gives tells you how to figure
out if a poll is reliable, listing 20 things you should know about
a poll before making up your mind.
</P>
<P>
   Another site, politics1.com, is favored by academics and policy
wonks. It has hundreds of links to all manner of political sites.
(Be careful with the section that auctions political buttons. The
prices tend to be much higher than the same items go for on Ebay or
on specialized political collectors' auction sites.)
</P>
<P>
   Policy.com, has an impressive list of annotated links, and many
scholars point to it as an example of a good gateway, or portal, to
the world of politics and policy. A caveat: the annotations are
provided by the groups themselves. Thus, the descriptions of two
media watchdog groups, Accuracy in Media and Fairness and Accuracy
in Reporting, sound very similar. AIM says its goal is to ``combat
political and ideological bias in the news media'' while FAIR says
it ``offers well-documented criticism in an effort to correct media
bias.'' There's no hint until you go there that AIM is a
conservative organization, and only a fairly oblique hint in the
FAIR description that it is liberal.
</P>
<P>
   The Web also provides a fairly easy way for readers and viewers
to check up on the accuracy of the news stories they've been
watching and viewing, said John Coleman, a political science
professor at the University of Wisconsin at Madison. ``You can see
some of the data yourself,'' Coleman said. ``You can dig into the
numbers as minimally or as heavily as you want.'' Polling Report,
for one, provides a wealth of raw polling data (pollingreport.com).
</P>
<P>
   For the adventurous who want to surf for information on their
own, experts say sites offer a few clues to their nature and
reliability. A good site will say who owns it, who maintains it and
when it was last updated. Be suspicious of any site that doesn't
make these things clear.
</P>
<P>
   VIEWS LEFT AND RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century British politician and philosopher John Stuart
Mill recommended reading and hearing arguments counter to one's own
beliefs as the best way to keep one's own arguments sharp and
convictions keen. Otherwise, he said, beliefs degenerate into
``dead dogma.''
</P>
<P>
   For those people, or for those believers who want to hear the
righteous word redux, the Web offers two nice portals. On the left,
www.commondreams.org leads to a huge collection of straight wire
services (Associated Press, Agence France-Presse, Reuters, United
Press International, etc.), as well as progressive sources
(Alternet, Utne Reader, etc.) and liberal commentary ranging
(alphabetically, not politically) from Eric Alterman, a columnist
for The Nation and MSNBC, to Dave Zweifel, editor of The Capital
Times in Madison, Wis. There are also links to a flock of daily
newspapers and to various political sites in Washington, including
the home pages of both major political parties.
</P>
<P>
   On the right, www.rightnow.org has a list of links to
conservative news sources (it includes Fox News, calling it ``not
as liberal as CNN'') and to categories of conservative sites about
anti-abortion efforts, libertarians and the U.S. Taxpayers Party. A
category called Labor leads to links on how to break unions and how
union members can get out of paying for lobbying efforts for
pro-labor causes. An introduction to the news list explains that
its ``news sources either have a conservative slant, or at the very
least they are not as liberal as the majority of the major media.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the merits of the left and the right politically, the
right has generally had far better Web sites. Compare the visually
attractive, well-organized National Rifle Association's site
(nra.org) with, say, the League of Women Voters site (lwv.org). The
league site is, well, serviceable. Its new Webmaster, Jennifer
Recine, said she was working with Web designers to spiff up the
look.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
