<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7680 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-POLITICAL-ACTIVIS     09-01 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-POLITICAL-ACTIVISM-SLUG-2RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the look.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONGRESSIONAL DATA
</P>
<P>
   What is most remarkable about the Web is what's not available,
at least not easily. Guidance is especially needed for Web sleuths
heading in the direction of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   While Congress provides a wealth of valuable information, it
does not make available voting records for members of Congress, as
basic a piece of political information as a voter is apt to want.
Nor does it provide an easy way to get members' e-mail addresses,
although nearly all members of Congress now have them.
</P>
<P>
   The sites available through the Thomas site (thomas.loc.gov)
list roll call votes on individual bills, but nowhere on the
government's site is that information sliced the other way to show
how an individual member has voted across a career.
</P>
<P>
   The Thomas site contends that since many votes are voice votes,
any attempt to list the voting record of a senator or
representative would be incomplete. An e-mail question to the
Thomas Webmaster asking why this is so, since Thomas' own site
acknowledges that citizens want this kind of information, brought a
response citing the Thomas page with a link to Project Vote Smart
(www.vote-smart.org), which does have the information.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to use the government's own information to find out
your congressman's voting record, Thomas recommends that you call
up vote after vote after vote and make manual notes on how that
person voted until you have a complete record. Thanks, Tom.
</P>
<P>
   Those outside government service suspect that this is not an
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was done on purpose,'' said Bruce Maxwell, who has
written or edited more than a dozen books on Internet
information-gathering. ``It took years for Congress to put any type
of voting data online. It has only become available recently, long
after all the other congressional stuff was posted. Congress now
has the best of all worlds: it can proudly crow that the voting
data is online for all Americans, while at the same time making it
inaccessible for all practical purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing peek-a-boo with voting records, of course, makes it
tough for voters to tell if a representative or senator's
contentions in re-election speeches are strictly legitimate.
Committee votes are also not recorded on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Until relatively recently, members of Congress did not even have
their e-mail addresses and phone numbers listed on the Web. They're
still not in one place, to reduce unwanted mass mailings, said
Grace A. York, the federal documents librarian at the University of
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. York prides herself on having perhaps the nation's most
current list of Congressional e-mail addresses. For years, she
said, Congress had no such lists at all. Even after the House put
up its own list, she said, ``It didn't maintain it very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Democracy and Technology, a Washington
organization that pressures Congress to release more information,
has a couple of interesting pages, one a quick guide to locating
federal government data (but not as comprehensive or attractive as
the Michigan site), the other a list, generated by write-in
suggestions from the public, of federal information that is public
record but not on the Web (www.cdt.org/righttoknow/10mostwanted).
The list reminds us that it will still be awhile before citizen
surfers can find everything they want to know online.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
