<HEADER>
A7682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-DIVERSITY-2TAKES-N     09-01 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DIVERSITY-2TAKES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOR TV? IT COULD LOOK MOSTLY WHITE THIS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Turn on your television during most times of
the day, and you're likely to find a diverse world of people, from
white talk-show hosts to black newscasters and Hispanic soap stars.
</P>
<P>
   But when the new prime-time TV season begins in September, the
color will look a little bland.
</P>
<P>
   The six broadcast networks _ ABC, CBS, Fox, NBC, UPN and The WB
_ are introducing 38 new series this fall, but 29 of them have no
minority characters in the pilots. Only two of the shows are built
around minority characters (``The Parkers'' and ``Grown Ups'').
</P>
<P>
   Remove UPN and The WB from the mix and the results are even more
distressing.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The 26 new shows on ABC, CBS, Fox and NBC amount to a
whitewashing of television.
</P>
<P>
   Network executives say it's an unfortunate coincidence of
timing. Producers claim they cast the best people they can find,
regardless of ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people aren't buying the excuses, least of all the
NAACP, which lodged a formal complaint and challenge in mid-July,
days before TV critics began their annual summer network press tour
in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Kweise Mfume, president of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, said that his organization would
open an office in Hollywood to monitor the progress toward
integrating TV series, an effort that could lead to a boycott of
programs and sponsors that remain segregated. He also called for
meetings with network leaders that eventually were held earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP challenge was a main topic during three weeks of
Television Critics Association news conferences with network
executives, show creators, writers and stars. Early on, some
participants seemed shocked by the tone and frequency of the
questions, but by the end, executives were prepared with press
release-style answers of all that they're doing to counteract the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   No person or group, including the NAACP, will claim that every
show has to feature multiracial casts (that would certainly wipe
out many of the mostly black shows that have made UPN and The WB
popular among African-American viewers). But something clearly must
change if network television is going to resemble more closely the
diversity of the nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   You'll still find Bill Cosby, Della Reese, D.L. Hughley, Brandy,
Hector Elizando and other actors of color on returning shows. And
NBC has Jesse L. Martin (Ally McBeal's former boyfriend) on the new
spinoff, ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit.'' But in a surprise
twist, gay characters seem to have a stronger presence this fall
than blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   You might forgive some producers or creators if their shows are
all-white, like ``Friends.'' We are, after all, a society that is
still segregated, although it is difficult to understand how
attractive, white professionals in a big city like New York can
live without ever encountering ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But how can you overlook what Aaron Sorkin has done in the pilot
for one of the season's best new dramas, ``The West Wing''? He has
created a show in a modern-day White House without any leading
black characters. That's unfathomable in this day and age. It's
difficult to imagine a president of any party or political bent not
being savvy enough to have an ethnically diverse staff.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be, as some claim, that network executives believe that
the majority of white viewers won't watch shows with black lead
characters? If so, how would you explain the success of ``The Cosby
Show'' or ``The Jeffersons'' in years past?
</P>
<P>
   Day after day at the press tour, critics were told that minority
characters were planned all along, but they just didn't make it
into pilots, some of which, admittedly, will be altered before you
get to see them.
</P>
<P>
   It got to the point that one of the critics won big laughs for
asking, ``Which character are you going to tell us you meant to
show all along that just didn't make it into the pilot?''
</P>
<P>
   Network executives took their turns offering mea culpas for the
lack of diversity, each offering his or her variation on comments
made by Fox Entertainment President Doug Herzog: ``I do believe we
want to put on the best shows possible, and I don't care if the
casts are blue, green, yellow, orange. I want to put on the best
shows....Should we be doing a better job of presenting a more
diversified front in terms of our programming? Absolutely. Is it
going to be a priority? Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   But what can executives and groups like the NAACP do when faced
with comments from a successful producer like Dick Wolf, who will
be introducing his ``Law &AMP; Order'' spinoff ``Special Victims Unit''
this fall on NBC? The two leads in the new police drama,
Christopher Meloni and Mariska Hargitay, are white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't be very apologetic about my casting,'' said
Wolf. ``I mean, `New York Undercover' (his mid-1990s Fox series) is
the only minority lead show that's ever been renewed on network
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf emphasized what others said about casting the best actors
for the roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at a lot of actors and they were not all-white, but
I am not going to put myself in a position for apologizing for not
casting an African-American or a Hispanic actor when there were
other actors who better fulfilled the structure and what the
creative idea was in the show,'' he said. ``But it was an open
casting call. I mean, the best actors got the job. I don't care if
they're white, black, Hispanic, Asian or any mixture thereof.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Moonves, president and chief executive of CBS Television,
said that for every show his network considers for a pilot, ``We
discuss the options for adding minority characters to that show, if
a role by necessity can be colorblind. And we do it every day of
our lives. By the same token, I don't think you can madate that in
every series, there will be a minority character member.''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves' comments actually exemplify the problem facing the
minority community. If the creators don't think about minority
actors when they're coming up with the ideas for the series, or
widening the racial mix from the beginning, does adding ethnic
characters amount to tokenism?
</P>
<P>
   Things can be taken to the extreme. In The WB's new family drama
``Safe Harbor,'' a pair of young twins who are supposed to be sons
of the star Gregory Harrison have been replaced with what the
creator calls ``cosmic twins.'' One is black and one is white.
</P>
<P>
   Characters have to fit the show and the setting. And then the
producers have to find actors who fit the roles they've created.
Keeping an open mind is sometimes helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Roselyn Sanchez is one Hispanic actress who got a role on a new
fall show, playing a rookie cop on the Fox series ``The Badland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the script was written for a Latina. And I've seen
that so many times before that it's written for a Latina, but it
doesn't go to a Latina,'' said Sanchez, who acknowledged that her
heavy accent made her worry about losing the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went there and I said I'm going to be very Latina and
I'm going to try to do my best. And they went for me. And I'm very
grateful. Any white person or black girl can do it, you know. I'm
just proud that they took the chance and went with a Puerto Rican
accent for real.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Creators also had trouble convincing critics that some of the
minority actors introduced at the sessions had been planned all
along, even if they weren't seen in the pilots that were shown to
advertisers in May and critics in late-June.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Kumble, executive producer of ``Manchester Prep,'' a Fox
series that won't debut until the winter, introduced Sean Patrick
Thomas as one of the additions to the series. Thomas, who is black,
was featured in the film ``Cruel Intentions,'' which inspired the
series, but Kumble said that having Thomas in the pilot would have
taken away from the focus on the three main characters.
</P>
<P>
   He has a point, but saying he wanted Thomas because he's ``a
phenomenal actor'' made that point sound hollow. There had to have
been some way that his character could have been included in the
pilot without distracting us from the main focus. That is, if
Thomas was planned for the show all along as we were told.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, producers said they wanted to explore the
black/white issues that can arise in their shows.
</P>
<P>
   Judd Apatow, one of the creators of NBC's charming ``Freaks and
Greeks,'' based the high-school comedy-drama partially on his own
experiences. He went to an all-white high school, but some black
students entered the district before his graduation (the show is
set in 1980).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I want to explore that and how the dynamics changed
with new people in the school,'' Apatow said. ``So even though it's
mostly white now, we're going to address the issue when it comes
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rationalization for casting decisions took on almost ludicrous
tones when Martin Sheen joined the rest of the cast for a session
on NBC's ``The West Wing.'' Sheen, whose real last name is Estevez,
plays the president in Aaron Sorkin's White House drama. He was
asked how it feels to be a symbol for diversity for Latinos on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize I was a symbol,'' he said. ``I've been an
actor for 40 years. I've played all kinds of parts. I'm Hispanic by
birth and I'm Irish by trade,'' he said, referring to many roles
he's played as Irish-American characters.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sorkin, the creator of the show, took some knocks for the
pilot of his White House drama and its all-white cast, but
cautioned that critics and viewers shouldn't ``draw too big a
conclusion about this entire series from its first 42 minutes.
There are a lot of people we haven't met yet. These people aren't
going to be background scenery, nor will they be (as one critic
wrote) `kitchen help.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff will be black,
as will one of the president's personal aides. Other characters
will be Hispanic and Asian, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his praise for the quality of his core cast re-emphasized
the ``cast-the-best-you-can'' theory, which only makes you wonder
more about why they're all white. There is no real answer.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there is an answer. TV and movie writer Don Roos told The
Los Angeles Times last month, ``You couldn't do better than grow up
Jewish and gay if you want to be in show business. And you couldn't
do worse if you (grew up) black and Protestant.'' That's because
gays and Jews have more positions of power than blacks, Latinos and
Asians in Hollywood. Opening up that power structure is really the
only way for any meaningful change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people who develop and oversee network television
shows are white males who live in Malibu, Brentwood or Bel Air.
They don't know a lot of black people and they're not interested in
really writing those kinds of characters,'' said Paris Barclay, an
Emmy-winning director of ABC's ``NYPD Blue,'' and co-creator of the
midseason drama ``City of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Barclay, who is black and gay, created the show set at an
inner-city hospital with Steven Bochco, creator of some of the best
and most-acclaimed dramas in TV history.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, Barclay said, is to do what Bochco has done _
mentoring. ``None of the writers that we have on (`City of Angels')
have ever been on a staff before and half of them are
African-Americans and half of them are not. And these people are
getting a new experience, which is phenomenal and which is
something that we're always going to take with us as long as we're
in the business. If only other people in Steven's position took
that opportunity and took that time and sort of beat the bushes a
little bit more and found the young writers and directors who are
out there, and I'm telling you they're out there.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC shouldn't get all the blame in this issue. Consider its new
``Third Watch,'' in which five of the nine lead characters are
people of color.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sassa, President of NBC West Coast, made a personal and
impassioned statement on the diversity issue. He is an
Asian-American himself, and recalls being angered ``growing up,
seeing David Carradine as a Chinese guy (as Kwai Chang Caine on
``Kung Fu'')''
</P>
<P>
   He wants more than just a diverse array of actors on screen.
Sassa said he wants ``meaningful diversity. You not only want to
see someone that looks like you on TV, you want to see someone that
is a role model, someone that you want to be with, someone that you
want to be like, someone that you want to aspire to be.''
</P>
<P>
   While some have suggested that the networks are only targeting
white viewers to appease advertising demands, Sassa said that makes
no sense. Networks make most of their money from their owned and
operated stations, he said. NBC has 13 such stations in such major
markets as New York, Los Angeles, Philadelphia, Chicago, Miami and
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, these are all markets that have a higher
concentration of minority populations. It's totally within the
business sense _ it makes good business sense _ to try to reach
these minority groups in order to get bigger audiences. So it's not
only the right thing to do, but this is something that makes
business sense.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
