<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ANNIVERSARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PREPARES GRAND 50TH ANNIVERSARY CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's Communist leaders have always loved a good
anniversary, which gives them a chance to portray the country
exactly as they want and to mobilize a good share of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the 50th birthday of the People's Republic of China
this Oct. 1 has been vested with special value by leaders who want
to assure their people that the revolution has indeed been a
success. In addition, the extravaganzas have clearly been designed
to build up President Jiang Zemin as one of the titans of Communist
Party history.
</P>
<P>
   With some last-minute rushing, a surprising number of
construction projects set for completion by then appear to be on
schedule. Army tanks and troops, exemplary students, a float-load
of fashion models and hundreds of thousands more special honorees
have been out rehearsing the big day's parade and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   About the only apparent hitch in the preparations has gone
unpublicized: the missing wax statue of Jiang at the Museum of the
Revolution on Tiananmen Square. The museum is commemorating the
50th with a special exhibit depicting ``Great Men of China,'' all
life-size in wax.
</P>
<P>
   First comes Deng Xiaoping, the late mastermind of China's
economic opening, standing beside the huge black car in which he
cruised China's anniversary celebrations in 1984, the year the
party approved the extension of the economic reforms from the
countryside to the cities. Later in this small show _ it only
features 10 heroes _ is a large showcase for Mao, the founding
father, gazing thoughtfully from a mountaintop.
</P>
<P>
   The final diorama, the only one intended to celebrate a living
hero, has a startlingly different backdrop: a painted skyline of
modern, high-rise Beijing, complete with an understated touch of
smog. But the red platform for Jiang's statue is glaringly empty.
</P>
<P>
   A wax statue of Jiang was made, but someone up high, it seems,
rejected it as unacceptable. None of the museum staff could say
exactly why.
</P>
<P>
   The preparations for Oct. 1 have not exactly turned Beijing into
``a big park,'' as one newspaper declared, but it has made it a
little less clogged and ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Several avenues and sidewalks have been widened and lined with
grass and billboards removed along Changan Avenue, the thoroughfare
that runs along Tiananmen Square. Around the city, thousands of
substandard houses and street stalls, most used by migrants from
rural China, have been knocked down.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the new environmental concerns here, the Communist
Party newspaper, People's Daily, reported enthusiastically that on
Oct. 1 people will see ``a new vision of blue skies, clear rivers,
green grass and broad avenues.'' Because that vision is a bit ahead
of reality, though, the government is using drastic measures to
create a Potemkin paradise.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the authorities hope to temporarily suppress the
acrid smog that normally envelops Beijing. They have decreed that
from Sept. 21 to Oct. 1, more than 25 of the city's largest, most
polluting industries will be prohibited from burning coal and oil.
Many large trucks, farm vehicles and most out-of-city cars will be
barred from the city for 10 days or more.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of the new China, the Oct. 1 parade of 140,000
people will include _ along with a major showing of troops, tanks
and the latest rockets _ a float bearing 30 leading fashion models.
For the first time, too, the parade will include handicapped people
in wheelchairs and a contingent of private businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   But Communism still reigns, and the flashy elements may be
overshadowed by more customary themes. The entire procession,
including more than 90 floats, will be divided into three sections,
each honoring a phase in the party's glorious history.
</P>
<P>
   The first will celebrate the ``arduous epic,'' as People's Daily
described it, of the creation of the People's Republic and its
initial three decades under Mao. The second will honor the
achievements of the Deng era, from the late '70s to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The third will begin with a float _ its design unannounced and
rather hard to imagine _ honoring the 15th Party Congress of 1997.
That is when Jiang stepped out of the shadow of the deceased Deng,
laying out his own version of further economic change. This third
section is expressly designed to honor the achievements of the
current leadership ``with Jiang Zemin at the core,'' as they say.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's dances and flag shows on Tiananmen Square, like
the parade set up for television cameras, will hew to the theme
``Congratulations, Motherland,'' said one of the chief planners,
Zhao Dongming. Two hours of entertainment will reach a climax with
the song titled ``Congratulations, Motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   The song will be accompanied by 100,000 dancers, said Zhao, who
when he is not planning national galas is head of the Beijing
Office of Spiritual Civilization. (This refers not to spirituality
but fighting unhealthy cultural influences.)
</P>
<P>
   Parade and dance practice has gone on for months, but in the
last two weeks the first two big on-site rehearsals, on Changan and
Tiananmen Square, took place, closing streets and disrupting
traffic for hours. In the first rehearsal, tanks rumbled along
Changan _ an eerie reminder to many onlookers of the suppression of
the demonstrations in Tiananmen Square in 1989, the last time large
numbers of tanks headed down this road.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the second rehearsal, Saturday night, huge crowds
of would-be passengers formed at bus stops all over the city, as
hundreds and hundreds of buses were diverted to take students and
dancers to Tiananmen Square. But residents seem to accept the
repeated inconveniences with a shrug, typically saying, ``What can
you do? It's the 50th anniversary.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why China is spending so much for the holiday, one of
Saturday night's gawkers, Zhu Chaochao, a 42-year-old engineer,
laughed and said, ``If you lived long enough in China you'd
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things have implications for the present,'' he said of
the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   At the Museum of the Revolution, the director of the wax
exhibit, Xu Yi, said ``It's not very likely'' that a new Jiang
figure will be ready by Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appearance of the figure is very important,'' she said,
``because leaders have to be shown at their best, fully reflecting
their place in the life of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Xu said it seemed inconceivable to her that Jiang might have
personally inspected and rejected the initial rendition, but she
added, ``We have to listen to the opinions and suggestions of our
superiors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't an ordinary exhibition,'' she said. ``It has
historic significance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
