<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     09-01 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV03-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I WANT TO BE PRESIDENT BECAUSE ...
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday, Sept. 3)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you believe, as I do, that we should take lessons in good
government only from countries that have even more embarrassing sex
scandals than our own, then you will surely be delighted by this
idea from British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to dismantle the heredity-based House of Lords,
Blair has ordered all 633 blue bloods to write a brief essay
explaining why the member would like to be in the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will presumably consider the essay, which must be 75
words or less, in determining which, if any, lords get to keep
their seats in an election later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Columnist Giles Coren of The Times of London was kind enough to
suggest the following essay for those lords who may be unaccustomed
to expressing themselves with such commonplace things as words and
sentences:
</P>
<P>
   ``Am proactive self-starter with good working knowledge of
estate management, horsemanship, dithering, dribbling and claret
drinking ... Have experience in the intricacies of the tax system _
specifically in relation to inheritance tax loopholes _ and
seller's knowledge of the art market.''
</P>
<P>
   Many lords are outraged by the essay rule, which just proves, to
me at least, that it's a wonderful idea, and one that would work
equally well for candidates running for office in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. presidential campaign is a grueling affair for all
concerned, especially the voters. Although the election is still 14
months away, voters are already bored and cranky and would pay
money to get the thing over with tomorrow, if such a thing were
possible. Instead, we are doomed to watch millionaires in plaid
shirts and jeans holding press conferences in the middle of Iowa
pig farms to deny that they (the millionaires, not the pigs) have
ever used cocaine, or at least not recently.
</P>
<P>
   The present system is tedious and annoying and very expensive
without giving voters any useful information or any idea how the
candidate will pan out once elected.
</P>
<P>
   It would be better, or at least no worse, to simply require
candidates to submit a short essay one week before the election and
let voters use that to make their decision.
</P>
<P>
   All essays would be required, by law, to begin with the words
``I want to be president because ...'' but beyond that the
candidates are free to say whatever they want, as long as they say
it in 75 words or less.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates should feel free to borrow from the following
``form'' essay if they have trouble coming up with 75 words on
their own:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be president because I have the (leadership,
fund-raising, coke-snorting) skills necessary to lead America into
the (17th, 19th, 21st) century. Our nation's facing (difficult,
moderately challenging, partly sunny) days ahead and it's important
that a qualified (man, woman, dancing chicken) is at the (helm,
wheel, bar) to (steer, run aground, sell to the highest bidder) our
ship of state. During my (years, months, seconds) in the (White
House, statehouse, big house) I (accomplished, fantasized about,
saw on TV) many things and forged many (lasting, easily forgotten,
10-minute) relationships with some of the (world's, nation's, local
lingerie-modeling studio's) most (influential, corrupt,
well-endowed) (leaders, terrorists, massage therapists). Let me
(use, abuse, pad) my (skills, ambitious spouse, bank account) to
(build, destroy, mortgage) a (better, worse, pretty much the same)
America.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
