<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7699 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BOSNIA02-COX     09-01 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bosnia-Herzegovina celebrate peace with national holiday
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bosnia and Herzegovina will create a national
holiday to commemorate the signing of the Dayton Peace Accords,
officials announced Wednesday, cementing Nov. 21 as a date of
historical significance to the region.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton lauded the announcement, calling the date ``a
symbol of multiethnic democracy and solidarity between the people
of the United States and the people of Bosnia-Herzegovina.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In so doing,'' Clinton said, ``the leaders of every ethnic
community in Bosnia-Herzegovina have made clear that Dayton marked
not merely the end of a war, but the beginning of a new country and
a blueprint of its future.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, made by the triad of presidents who govern the
country, came as Dayton officials prepared to invite them to Ohio
for the annual celebration of the peace treaty that was brokered in
1995 at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base. This year, Dayton's
celebration of the treaty will begin Nov. 13 when the Sarajevo
Philharmonic Orchestra joins the Dayton Philharmonic Orchestra in a
Concert for Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Glynn, spokeswoman for U.N. Ambassador Richard
Holbrooke, attended the announcement in Sarajevo and said Dayton
was remembered warmly during the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talked about the city of Dayton and the people opening
their hearts to them and that it meant so much to achieving
peace,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke was the chief negotiator for the U.S. in the peace
talks that led to a formal splitting of disputed lands between the
warring parties of the region.
</P>
<P>
   R. Bruce Hitchner, director of UD's Center for International
Programs, said commemorating the signing of the Dayton agreement is
a good sign for the future of the troubled region. It reaffirms the
determination of people there to achieve the principles of
cooperative life on which the treaty is based, Hitchner said.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia and Herzegovina continue to exist under a tense peace
that is aided by an international military force, including a large
U.S. contingent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only day of the year that unifies the country,''
Hitchner said of Nov. 21. ``It's the only idea that unifies the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
