<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7700 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-CISNEROS-JUDGE-$ADV05     09-01 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-JUDGE-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNCONVENTIONAL JURIST PRESIDES IN CISNEROS CASE
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 5.
 &HT;    VBy JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin looked at the
federal prosecutors and $495-an-hour defense lawyers arrayed before
him. ``I can try a case in two days,'' he asserted.
</P>
<P>
   The boast last July was tinged with defensiveness. The colorful
and sometimes controversial judge prides himself on his ability to
cut through legalistic lollygagging. But he was speaking on the
12th day of what he had predicted to be a two-day hearing to
prepare for the trial of former federal housing secretary Henry G.
Cisneros, who is charged with lying in an FBI background check
about paying ``hush money'' to his former mistress.
</P>
<P>
   The pretrial wrangling has hardly burnished Sporkin's reputation
for keeping things moving in his court. But the preliminary hearing
provided a preview of how the unconventional jurist will preside
when jury selection finally begins this week.
</P>
<P>
   Lounging on his big leather-padded rocking chair in midsummer,
Sporkin fidgeted impatiently as the two sides clashed over
admitting into evidence secret recordings made by Cisneros's
ex-lover, Linda Jones. Chomping on ice and occasionally yawning
broadly, Sporkin shifted his glasses from his nose to his forehead
to the top of his head. He summoned documents to read and then
leaned back, shutting his eyes long enough to make onlookers wonder
whether he was drifting off.
</P>
<P>
   But hearing something that pricked his interest, he would
suddenly lift his arms into the air and interrupt lawyers
mid-argument, or pepper witnesses with his own questions.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the unpredictable world of what critics have dubbed
``Sporkin's law,'' and what fans applaud as justice with
spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   Washingtonian magazine once rated him among the top judges on
the local bench, although not without a mixed review. He is a
``bright, engaging, often baffling jurist,'' the journal said. ``He
is also a restless soul with little patience for legal games.''
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin is given to blunt, off-the-cuff observations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there are people who don't know how to tell the
truth,'' he opined in July, after hearing Jones admit to lying
repeatedly to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   After Jones described how she edited taped conversations with
Cisneros, then filed a lawsuit and plotted a public relations
campaign that included appearing on a tell-all TV show, Sporkin
wryly asked, ``Is this more of the 'Kosovo strategy? Bomb him into
submission?' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Sporkin warned the Cisneros lawyers from the
early going that, despite their vigorous objections, he almost
certainly would allow some of the tapes to be heard at trial. When
lead defense attorney Brendan V. Sullivan made a dramatic
demonstration to lampoon the tapes as doctored-up phonies, Sporkin
listened with open admiration.
</P>
<P>
   But a month later, he ruled that most of the contents of 26
recordings could be used as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin earned a reputation for toughness as a career lawyer who
headed enforcement at the Securities and Exchange Commission.
Although his zeal in attacking businesses earned him the ire of
conservatives, Sporkin formed a tight bond with then SEC chief
William Casey.
</P>
<P>
   When President Reagan made Casey director of the CIA, he took
Sporkin along as his general counsel and loyal defender. Reagan
rewarded Sporkin by appointing him to the bench in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   His career on the court has not been all smoothness, however.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago he was unceremoniously dumped from the federal
government's first antitrust action against Microsoft Corp. after
he mentioned reading a book on the company and then ruled that a
settlement offer was too easy on the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   The Circuit Court of Appeals issued a sharp rebuke, concluding
that his ruling had been swayed by his extracurricular reading and
calling him biased against Microsoft. Sporkin's decision was
reversed, and he was taken off the case.
</P>
<P>
   He has been involved in other high-profile cases:
</P>
<P>
   _ He ordered the Navy not to dismiss a sailor, Master Chief
Petty Officer Timothy R. McVeigh of Hawaii, who described himself
as ``gay'' on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ He ordered the Federal Elections Commission to investigate
allegations that the late Commerce Secretary Ronald H. Brown sold
seats on overseas trade missions for Democratic campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   _ He blocked the merger of four of the nation's top drug
wholesalers this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Now 67, he has taken senior status and spoken publicly of trying
to set up an academic institute on crisis management, a long-time
interest of his.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his ice-chomping irreverence continues to rule in
Courtroom 6 of the U.S. Courthouse. On one hearing day, the court
was summoned into afternoon session by two young boys, chanting
``Hear ye! Hear ye!'' Once ensconced on his rocking chair, Sporkin
announced that these were his grandsons. He confided cheerfully
that neither had any interest in becoming a lawyer, or a judge.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
