<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW TETRIS? BOOOOOOOOOOOORING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tetris is been one of those games that, from a distance, look
boring. But once you start playing, it becomes help-me-I-can't-stop
addicting.
</P>
<P>
   When it first came out in the '80s, a lot of fans were saying
that they were so hooked, they dreamed about different ways to
position the game's falling-from-the-sky jigsaw-puzzle pieces. Then
they'd wake up and beat everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Through the arcade, Super Nintendo, PC and Nintendo's Game Boy,
Tetris has been passed down from one video-game generation to the
next. The newest incarnation _ The New Tetris (Nintendo for N64,
$60, all ages) _ is, oddly, the easiest to master, making it a bit
on the _ dare I slag a Tetris title? _ boring side.
</P>
<P>
   The big deal is that up to four people can play. Yeah, big deal,
all right. And, granted, playing _ and, in my case, creaming _
three other players would be a blast. That is, if it weren't so
easy.
</P>
<P>
   What makes The New Tetris so unchallenging: Before a piece
drops, it casts a shadow of where it's gonna land, revealing how
the puzzle will look. Part of Tetris' fun was making mistakes, then
learning from them; this is almost like cheating and not getting in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Nintendo made it easier on purpose, to get younger kids
into it. Gotta say I'd rather see my kid playing this than, say,
Slaughter House 2000. It's probably the only game I could beat the
kid at, too.
</P>
<P>
   To compete with Sega's upcoming Dreamcast machine, arriving
Sept. 9, Sony and Nintendo have dropped the prices of their home
machines _ the PlayStation and Nintendo 64 _ to $99. (And you
bought one a year ago for $200.) If you wanna spend a few extra
bucks on the N64, go for Nintendo's Star Wars Episode I: Racer
bundle. You get the unit, one controller and the Star Wars game for
$120.
</P>
<P>
   Well known with the ages 3-8 in-crowd, Pajama Sam is a little
cartoon character from Humongous Entertainment that, like Barney
and Big Bird, teaches kids how to think logically, remember junk
and solve problems. (Picking out clothes, though, is obviously not
one of Pajama Sam's strong points, as proved by his Superman
Underoos outfit. Can we recommend something from Pokemon?)
</P>
<P>
   Parents looking for a good deal simply can't go wrong with
Humongous' latest Pajama Sam release, the Pajama Sam Deluxe Pack.
Selling for $20, the set includes two new Pajama Sam CD-ROMS _
Pajama Sam 2: Thunder and Lightning Aren't So Frightening and
Pajama Sam's Lost &AMP; Found _ and a pretty neat watch with a
detachable character. I'm never gonna play these games, so I'm
giving my pack to the little sister of this girl I'm dating.
Keeping the watch, though. C'mon, it's cute.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
