u i BC-PANAMA-INAUG-NYT &LR;      09-01 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-INAUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMA SWEARS IN ITS FIRST WOMAN PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ Mireya Moscoso, a schoolteacher's daughter
who grew up in rural poverty, was sworn in Wednesday not only as
Panama's first woman president but also as its first president who
will lead a completely sovereign country, once the United States
withdraws its remaining troops and hands over the Panama Canal on
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Those twin themes flavored her inaugural address, one in which
she repeatedly urged the Panamanian people to join her in
eliminating poverty and corruption and in reviving the civic and
moral spirit of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment, when we are about to end the century and our
nation ends a historic era with the departure of a foreign
presence, when we are ready with pride and dignity to usher the new
millennium with our sovereignty fully rescued, it is I, the first
woman, who has received the trust of the Panamanian people,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We begin to make real the hopes of thousands of Panamanian
women over the centuries who, through generations of history, have
nourished the hope that our society recognize their ability and
merit, and share with all the men of this country the great
responsibility of leading the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by her young son, Ricardito, she entered the
National Stadium and raised her arms in a symbolic embrace of the
cheering, flag-waving crowd of thousands of Panamanians from
throughout the country. The site was a gesture to the populist
pillars of her Arnulfista Party, which was named after her late
husband, Dr. Arnulfo Arias, who was elected and forced from the
presidency three times.
</P>
<P>
   Although her father was a teacher, her political education came
during her marriage to Arias, a legendary _ and somewhat eccentric
_ nationalist whose own beliefs included fascist and mystical
leanings. She has often invoked his memory in her speeches, and her
address Wednesday was filled with poignant references.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is the beginning of the period of government he never
had a chance to fulfill for the benefit of the poor and
marginalized of Panama,'' she said. ``How much I wish my mother and
father and Dr. Arnulfo Arias were sitting in front watching this
historic day. But I know they are in heaven blessing us and saying
`Mireya, keep on and fulfill the work I could not finish.'''
</P>
<P>
   While the audience included heads of state and diplomats,
notably absent was the man she defeated in last May's election,
President Ernesto Perez Balladares, who left the Presidential
Palace even before the inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   The slight was the final skirmish in a summer-long battle marked
by moves that could hobble his successor's administration, such as
packing the Supreme Court with his political allies and appointing
associates from his Revolutionary Democratic Party to civil service
posts.
</P>
<P>
   President Moscoso, 53, leads the nation into its most important
period, as it takes over the canal and some $4 billion dollars in
surrounding property.
</P>
<P>
   Although the canal is a $700 million operation, it is not a
windfall, because much of that revenue goes back into operations.
Several companies have invested in tourism and other projects, but
some observers said the United States should provide more help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't tried to support them with a package of trade and
investment incentives that will ensure the transfer of facilities
and land be done smoothly,'' said Bob Pastor, a political scientist
at Emory University and former member of the National Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso vowed to run the canal efficiently and safely,
projecting an international image of stability. In her address
Wednesday, she reminded citizens of their new relationship with the
canal and the challenges and opportunities of Panamanian ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the 31st of December, at 12 noon, we will once and for all
attain our true independence,'' she said. ``From then on, we will
have to go on a new path, one where we will have to provide all the
elements of a national identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Her supporters have high expectations because of her promises to
create jobs, alleviate poverty and deliver better social services.
In a country where more than a third of the population is in
poverty, many voters became suspicious of government after her
predecessor's policies of privatization and open markets resulted
in little they could see, except for miles of new highways. He has
left behind an unemployment rate of approximately 14 percent, $7
billion dollars in debt and little cash to pay for Moscoso's
platform.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign diplomats said she has only vaguely explained how
she will translate her intense grass-roots appeal into a workable
social and political program.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very good at retail politics, in sensing the mood in a
crowd,'' one diplomat said. ``But don't talk to her about big
policy details. She goes blank.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso has said she would not privatize any more state-run
industries, though few remain. She has also said she wants to raise
tariffs to help farmers devastated by imports, although her ability
to do so is limited by Panama's membership in the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   She has suggested dipping into a $1.7 billion fund generated by
her predecessor's sale of state industries, but her slim majority
in the Legislature may not prove strong enough to push through such
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   While viewed as having the most pro-American administration in
decades, the president has chosen a Cabinet of relatively young
professionals with little government experience. They have been
hampered by the outgoing administration's almost total lack of
cooperation in any transition meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But Roberto Eisenmann, an informal adviser on social issues,
said the president was focused on the task ahead and aware of the
risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few months ago when the euphoria of her victory was still
present, I was in a meeting with people who were talking about the
difficulties of governing with a strong opposition in the
Assembly,'' Eisenmann said Tuesday. ``A loyal supporter stood up
and said, `Dona Mireya, remember you have the people!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``With a serenity that was really remarkable she said, `I have
the people today. I could lose it tomorrow if we don't dedicate
ourselves and work for the people.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7711 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIGERIA-PEACE-ART-2TA     09-01 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-PEACE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER NEW REFORM-ORIENTED PRESIDENT, NIGERIA IS A DIFFERENT PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Gasoline stations, once the defining image of
Nigeria's seemingly willful collapse, have undergone a remarkable
transformation since the military rulers handed over power to
civilians three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the mile-long lines that choked roads, made fistfights
part of the Nigerian streetscape and transformed gas stations into
high-security zones swarming with soldiers, police officers, thugs
and the long-suffering ordinary Nigerian, citizen of the world's
sixth-largest producer of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Now most gas stations operate the way an Agip station on Iju
Road here does: motorists pull up to a pump and drive away a minute
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is fundamental change in things,'' said Abiodun
Akinloye, 34, an attendant at the station for six years. ``Before,
the tension was too high. People were begging to buy fuel and
sometimes had to wait for days. Now you buy fuel at the actual
price and at your own convenience. Everything has become fine.
Everybody is feeling fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months after Africa's most populous nation inaugurated its
first civilian government in 16 years, gas stations offer perhaps
the clearest promise of what could become one of the most
remarkable political transformations on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Only 15 months ago, Nigeria was held in the grip of a rapacious
military regime that had turned the country into an international
pariah and manipulated oil supplies so that Nigerians often had to
pay several times what Americans do for a gallon of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Today, after a year of traumatic events that pushed this fragile
nation to the brink of civil war, Nigeria is intact, but its
president, Olusegun Obasanjo, has quickly pushed reforms that are
altering its face. Nigerians, an industrious people paralyzed until
last year by the repressive military under Gen. Sani Abacha, are
now even talking of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like Joseph getting out of the pit to get to the palace
in Egypt,'' said Baba Adi, a lawyer and prominent member of the
president's People's Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even the government's fiercest critics, who argue that it has
yet to make lasting changes, acknowledge that there is greater
individual freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's temporary,'' said Beko Ransome-Kuti, a well-known
human rights campaigner who spent three years in jail under Abacha,
``it's a nice holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is perhaps too soon to talk of democracy, the end of
the military state has visibly affected daily lives here. Obasanjo
has forbidden politicians from driving in convoys with sirens
blaring, once a common practice. Several streets in Lagos have been
renamed for slain pro-democracy activists.
</P>
<P>
   The notorious security forces that patrolled cities with
unchallenged authority _ known here in Lagos as Operation Sweep _
have grown tamer. In Lagos the forces are now called by the less
sinister Rapid Response Squad.
</P>
<P>
   On Iju Road, often made impassable in the past by motorists
waiting at its many gas stations, soldiers and policemen once
posted at checkpoints every two miles have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   So there is no one now shaking down Isaac Bodunrin, 45, and his
fellow cab drivers for the equivalent of 20 cents every two miles.
``If we can continue like this, there will be progress in this
country,'' said Bodunrin, who in the past was often left with
nothing at the end of the day but now makes about $10. ``If we can
drive free, I can do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The job that Obasanjo has done so far includes changes in many
vital sectors. He has established a panel to investigate human
rights violations since the mid-1980s and another one to look into
government contracts awarded since 1976. He has sent an
anti-corruption bill to the National Assembly, though many say the
proposal goes too far in potentially invading people's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   On the burning issue of the Niger Delta, the source of Nigeria's
oil but still profoundly poor, Obasanjo proposed legislation toward
its development. In addition, in a highly symbolic act, he
permitted the family of Ken Saro-Wiwa, the writer who was hanged in
1995 for criticizing the government's oil policies, to claim his
body.
</P>
<P>
   In the oil industry, the source of almost all of Nigeria's hard
currency, he has cut out shadowy middlemen from sales of crude oil
and rescinded prospecting contracts awarded to cronies of the
military regime.
</P>
<P>
   The president, a retired general who was Nigeria's military
ruler from 1976 to 1979, shook up the military by forcing about a
hundred top officers to retire. Most were northerners who dominated
the military and ruled the country for all but 10 years since
independence from Britain in 1960, and their successors were chosen
from diverse regions. His government also announced plans to cut
troop strength significantly.
</P>
<P>
   In his choice of ministers, the president has tried to strike a
balance among the dominant ethnic groups and the many minorities.
The move has drawn praise from many pressure groups and Western
diplomats. But it has been criticized by northerners, who say they
are now being marginalized, and by the Ibo from the east, who say
they have not gotten any top ministerial positions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the changes, critics say the Obasanjo administration
has not taken urgently needed steps to address the roots of
Nigeria's problems. According to the constitution, which was handed
down by military decree, the appointments of judges, the control of
police officers and the direction of primary schools all still rest
with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics argue that unless the relationship between the
federal government and the 36 states is renegotiated _ and that
includes the formula by which oil revenues are shared _ Nigeria
will remain a divided nation, with most of its ethnic groups
feeling oppressed by another group. In the last three months,
hundreds have died in ethnic skirmishes across the country,
including two clashes between the Yoruba and the Hausa, who with
the Ibo are the country's largest ethnic groups.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We must sit down and decide what to say together,'' said Ayo
Opadokun, general-secretary of the National Democratic Coalition,
the main civilian opposition group to the Abacha military
government. ``If not, we may have to look for the U.S.S.R. on the
map.''
</P>
<P>
   Until reforms are written into law, democratization remains
overly dependent on Obasanjo's personality, say critics. That is a
dangerous situation in a country where one man, whether Abacha or
Obasanjo, can completely change the direction of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Obasanjo dies today, what happens to Nigeria?'' asked
Ransome-Kuti. Mohammed Ashorobi, a member of the national executive
committee of the president's party, argued that Obasanjo has begun
to lay ``the foundation for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The priority, he said, has been to try to meet the country's
essential needs, a task made easier by the recent rebound in crude
oil prices to more than $20 a barrel. In addition to the
availability of gasoline, electricity service has improved
noticeably in many parts, and the government recently announced
that the price of a phone line would fall significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Ashorobi said, ``Regarding the basic comforts of life, the
current regime has been able to bring some confidence into society
where there was only despair before.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Iju Road, in a cacophony of human voices and engine sounds,
its two lanes teem with pedestrians, cars, motorcycles, peddlers
selling everything from vegetables to raw meat. With the gasoline
lines now gone, traffic moves in both directions, slowly but
surely.
</P>
<P>
   At the Agip station, three yellow fuel trucks were parked
waiting to discharge their load, two of them for the last seven
days because the station simply did not need more fuel. The
situation would have been unthinkable just months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerians have not seen such plentiful gasoline since 1993 when
Abacha let the country's refineries deteriorate, thereby forcing
one of the world's top oil producers to import refined products,
through his middlemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change came with the new government, so we are all
happy,'' said Adeniyi Johnson, 40, a civil servant who drove his
white Volkswagen Beetle to a pump. ``I hope it will continue this
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The gas bounty even pleased those who had benefited from the
artificial scarcity. In the past, soldiers would sometimes take
over the station and control the lines, moving drivers ahead in
exchange for a bribe. At the end of the day, the soldiers would tip
the thugs who informally controlled the lines, at the very bottom
of the corruption food chain.
</P>
<P>
   One former regular, Eyo Kulaba, 25, said he was able to save
enough money from the bribes he collected to buy a used motorcycle.
And so in Nigeria's peculiar job classification, he had moved up
from being an ``area boy'' _ a jobless youth who hustles for tips
and bribes on the streets _ to an ``okada man,'' a youth who
ferries passengers around on his motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I benefited materially, I was not very happy that
people were suffering daily,'' Kulaba said. ``People were bashing
each other's vehicles to get fuel and there was always a lot of
fighting. It was really terrible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
