<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A's </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAYNES IS THE APPLE OF THE OAKLAND A'S 
</HEADLINE>
 -HNS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRIAN MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They piled into the clubhouse at Yankee Stadium just
short of midnight on Tuesday, whooping and hollering like Little
Leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, though, the Oakland A's were celebrating a big-league
win, a 3-2, 11-inning, in-your-face job against the defending
champions on the Yankees' own patch of grass in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the clubhouse, the emotions flowed, and tributes were
paid to what was one of the most pivotal performances of the season
_ and who in their right-thinking noggin would have anticipated
these words to hang in the air on the eve of September in an
unlikely A's playoff chase?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hear it for Jimmy Haynes!'' the cry went out, and cheers
went up.
</P>
<P>
   How about that: Let's hear it for Jimmy Haynes.
</P>
<P>
   For Jimmy Haynes, a man so down on his luck that he was thought
ousted from any role but mop-up reliever down the stretch. For
Jimmy Haynes, a pitcher who had lost the confidence of his
clubhouse. For Jimmy Haynes, who stared down demons _ not to
mention Derek Jeter, Bernie Williams and the rest of the Bombers _
to turn in seven innings of five-hit, eight-strikeout ball, to hold
the swaggering Yankees to two runs, to give his a team the boost to
pull out a win that again ranks among the season's finest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the best,'' manager Art Howe said. ``We all
cheered him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' said right fielder Matt Stairs.
</P>
<P>
   And from the man of the hour himself, Georgia-born Jimmy Wayne
Haynes: ``They don't get much better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Haynes took the mound despite a million reasons not to
believe in him. He was on a four-game losing streak. He had been
bounced from the rotation. He had been pounded by the Yankees as
recently as Aug. 9, when he failed to pitch out of the second
inning.
</P>
<P>
   He was dueling David Cone. He was trying to keep the A's two
games back of streaking Boston in the American League wild-card
race. And the decision to start him came only after
behind-the-scenes chicanery revealed a rift in the decision-making
process between manager Art Howe and general manager Billy Beane,
with Beane naming Haynes as the starter just 24 hours before game
time.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of all that, Haynes began the game by striking out
Chuck Knoblauch and Jeter on his 90-mph-plus fastball, and ended
his seven innings by fanning Luis Sojo looking on a wicked
curveball to kill a Yankee threat.
</P>
<P>
   In between, he was brilliant, save for a mistake pitch to
slugger Paul O'Neill, who pounded a two- run homer in the third to
give New York a 2-0 lead that looked like it might be enough. But
Haynes would yield no more. Given a choice of sinking into oblivion
or staking his turf and daring the Yankees to beat him, Haynes
chose the John Wayne route.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only sink so far in this game,'' third base coach Ron
Washington said, ``and then you're either up, or you're out.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Rick Peterson has handled the chore of building
Haynes back up, piece by piece. His work was validated on Tuesday
night when Haynes' confidence was oozing, when Haynes took the late
August pressure and made it his friend.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson remembers sitting with Haynes and Howe in the manager's
office in the visiting clubhouse at Yankee Stadium on Monday, and
telling Haynes that he would be given the start on Tuesday.
Peterson noticed a glow in Haynes' face. There was a glow on
Peterson's face talking about Haynes, too; he was visibly moved by
Haynes' stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself: He believes he can do it,'' Peterson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there were questions, that against David Cone, in one
of the biggest games of the year, were we crazy? It's a beautiful
moment for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes got the team through the seventh tied 2-2, and the A's
did the rest. Doug Jones followed suit with three innings of
one-hit relief to keep it locked, and after pinch hitter Rich
Becker delivered John Jaha home with an RBI single in the top half
of the 11th, new closer Jason Isringhausen pitched out of a
bases-loaded, one-out jam to save it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows what we're made of,'' said Howe, who deemed it too
early to determine whether Haynes would make a start on Sunday
against the Tigers. Expect it, though.
</P>
<P>
   Of all things, Haynes took strength in the venue. He felt the
aura of Yankee Stadium, he said, and it fueled him. A typically
intense Yankee crowd of 33,476 cheered against him. Haynes fed off
of it, saying the atmosphere made him better.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates and coaches could only stand and cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People doubted whether I could pitch,'' Haynes said. ``That's
not the way it is. I can pitch with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday at the House that Ruth Built, Haynes stopped
being a nobody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
