<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-PUBLIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK OK'S PLAN TO GO PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. has approved a
detailed plan to become a publicly traded company, including a
provision that would set aside up to 5 percent of the shares in
stock plans for the insurer's employees, executives, and board
members.
</P>
<P>
   It was expected the Boston insurer's board would approve a plan
to sell stock, a proposal the company has aired for over a year.
Yet, the final plan contained new details, including a name for the
holding company _ John Hancock Financial Services Inc. _ that will
sell the stock and own the insurance unit, which would be renamed
John Hancock Life Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's board also scheduled a Nov. 30 vote in which
policyholders would be asked to approve or reject the plan.
Policyholders, however, won't know the value of the stock they
would receive as compensation on the day they vote because the
value would be determined only when the stock hits the market
through an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The Hancock board's approval Monday, revealed by the company
Wednesday, is another step in a tortuous process to transform the
nations' ninth-biggest insurer from a company owned by its 2.8
million policyholders to one owned by the investing public.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to policyholders, the plan must be approved by
insurance regulators in New York and Massachusetts, and from the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been refining this plan over a period of more than a
year,'' said Stephen Brown, chief executive and chairman of
Hancock's board. ``This starts the public process.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has scheduled public informational hearings across
Massachusetts on Oct. 25 in Springfield, Oct. 27 in Marlborough,
and Oct. 29 in Westport. A public hearing, conducted by regulators,
will be held on Nov. 17, prior to the policyholder vote.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock said earlier that it hoped to sell its stock in the
first quarter of 2000. Given the board's approval, the insurer
appeared on track to meet that schedule. The performance of the
high-flying stock market is an unknown that may change the
insurer's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Few details emerged about which parties _ employees,
policyholders, and executives _ would receive how much stock under
the process known as ``demutualization.''
</P>
<P>
   But the plan explicitly barred the insurer from issuing any
stock or stock options to board members and top-level management
for a year after the public offering. The provision was required by
regulators over Hancock's proposal for a six-month waiting period.
</P>
<P>
   But stock for rank-and-file employees has no such restrictions,
and the company is devising a plan to issue stock to employees
through their 401(k) retirement plans, bonuses, or other channels,
said David D'Alessandro, president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to convert the company culture to people who are
completely aligned with stockholders' interests,'' D'Alessandro
said.
</P>
<P>
   Details of such plans have not been hammered out, the insurer
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for policyholders _ the current owners of John Hancock,
through their policies _ the amount of stock they receive would be
based on two factors. First, each eligible policyholder would
receive a fixed number of shares. Then, additional shares would be
issued proportionate to the value of Hancock policies eligible to
receive dividends.
</P>
<P>
   One Wall Street estimate put Hancock's value, in the stock
market, at $10 billion. Based on that, each of the company's 3.7
million policies outstanding would bring in about $2,700, on
average, in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Policyholders can receive cash or stock or can accept credits
that would increase the value of their policies.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock disputed the estimate, noting that the insurer's value
would be set only when the stock is sold and that some
policyholders may receive significantly less than the average.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Fliegelman, an analyst who covers Hancock for Moody's
Investors Service Inc. in New York, called the number of shares
that would be available after the stock sale ``sort of irrelevant.
That's like going into a pizzeria and asking how many slices in a
pie. It could be eight, 10, 12, or 100.''
</P>
<P>
   He added Hancock's documents won't contain that information.
``Only the market is going to do that,'' Fliegelman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
