A7723 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-TAKE-FIVE-COLUMN-TEX     09-01 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAKE-FIVE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET YOUR KID'S SLEEP RHYTHM BACK IN SYNC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We know what you did this summer. All glorious no-school season
long, your kids stayed up till the wee hours and then slept until
noon every day. Now that summer's over, they can't wake up in time
to catch the bus. They're making mornings miserable.
</P>
<P>
   We got some advice from Dr. Joel Steinberg, professor of
pediatrics at the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center
at Dallas and medical director of the sleep disorders clinic at
Children's Medical Center of Dallas. Turns out there's something
you can do to get the kids back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg gave us a good reason to put a stop to those
late-night habits, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleep deprivation has been well-documented to have an adverse
effect on academic performance,'' Steinberg says. Kids who don't
get enough sleep aren't as attentive in school and usually end up
with lower grades.
</P>
<P>
   When your kids are not tired at bedtime and not ready to wake up
when they need to, they are suffering from phase-delay syndrome or
delayed-sleep syndrome. It's as if you're in Texas but your body's
on West Coast time, Steinberg says. But with a conscious effort,
you can get back into a good sleep schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Here are five ways to correct those back-to-school sleep-rhythm
blues:
</P>
<P>
   Limit your child's caffeine intake. Eliminating caffeine is
ideal, Steinberg says, because it is a stimulant and not a dietary
necessity. But it's likely to sneak into kids' diets through tea,
chocolate and soft drinks, so be sure those are consumed early in
the day and not near bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   Do not put your child to bed until he or she is truly tired, no
matter how late the hour, but wake the child at the same time every
day, even on weekends. At first that may mean less sleep, but a
consistent wake-up time lets the body adjust its sleep rhythm. If
you're getting up at the same time every day, you'll start getting
tired at the right time every night.
</P>
<P>
   Let the sun shine in: Exposure to bright light upon awakening
will help your child's sleep rhythms adjust. When the body's
internal clock is thrown off, getting up in time for school is like
waking in the middle of the night. Bright light helps your internal
clock to reset itself by suppressing the body's secretion of
melatonin, which tells the body to sleep. If your child's room
doesn't get a lot of sunlight, turn on a bright lamp or two in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Direct the time spent in bed toward sleeping only, with less
time for bedtime struggles, reading or playing, even if that means
less total time in bed. If kids associate bed with other
activities, going to bed won't mean going to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting him to bed at 9 and having him toss and turn until 11
is very disturbing to the child,'' Steinberg says. Soon, the idea
of bed becomes frustrating instead of restful, creating more
problems.
</P>
<P>
   See a pediatrician if your child continues to demonstrate sleep
difficulties. Sometimes, sleep problems are more than a summer
hangover; they can be the result of asthma or allergies.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
