<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-BELL-ATLANTIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T, BELL ATLANTIC TRADE BARBS OVER SERVICE IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ An AT&AMP;T executive on Wednesday accused Bell
Atlantic of ``incompetence'' and said New York should deny the
company entry into the long-distance market. And Bell Atlantic
responded with a suggestion that AT&AMP;T quit whining and start
competing.
</P>
<P>
   The two telecommunications giants are embroiled in an
increasingly acerbic battle over local and long-distance markets.
Bell Atlantic is seeking federal permission to invade AT&AMP;T's
long-distance market, which it cannot do until the local market is
open for competition.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Morrissey, the AT&AMP;T vice president for law and
government affairs, said Bell Atlantic was not yet up to the task
of providing competitors with suitable local telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   Morrissey, commenting on a Public Service Commission hearing on
Tuesday, said that while Bell Atlantic has made progress in
offering other companies access to its local equipment, service
remains subpar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not treat competitors who interface with their systems
at the same parity level they do when they treat their own
customers,'' Morrissey said. ``In the marketplace, this obviously
presents a real problem to us when we have to acknowledge to a
small business customer that if you go with AT&AMP;T, because of
problems with the Bell Atlantic systems, you run an eight to 15
percent chance that your service will be disrupted, and at least a
10 percent chance that your number will be dropped from the
directory. This obviously has a pretty severe impact on a small
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrissey said he did not suspect Bell Atlantic of intentionally
providing competitors with inferior service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe they are intentionally doing bad,'' he said.
``I think it is more incompetence rather than intentional.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark A. Marchand, spokesman for Bell Atlantic, which serves the
Northeast and Mid-Atlantic states, characterized Morrissey's
remarks as inaccurate, offensive and petty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a shame to see behavior such as this,'' Marchand said.
``The message from Bell Atlantic to AT&AMP;T is: Give it up, get over
it and compete like everybody else instead of asking for your
market to be protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchand said that over 70 companies are now offering local
telephone service in New York, many of them using Bell Atlantic
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``To use a phrase like `incompetent' is insulting,'' Marchand
said. ``I hope every Bell Atlantic employee, and we have 44,000 in
New York, sees this and knows how AT&AMP;T feels about the work they
do. It is a ridiculous, second-grade taunt, and not something we
want to have any part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic plans to petition the Federal Communications
Commission in the next several weeks. The FCC will then seek an
advisory opinion from the state Public Service Commission on
whether the local market in New York is open to competition.
</P>
<P>
   The major long-distance carriers, as well as Attorney General
Eliot Spitzer, contend that the local market is not yet fully open,
and therefore Bell Atlantic should be denied immediate entry into
the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic hopes to be selling long-distance service to New
Yorkers by early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Bell Atlantic has made substantial progress, which we
acknowledge, they are not ready for prime time,'' Morrissey told a
news conference on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Marchand said AT&AMP;T is engaged in a ``last gasp, desperate effort
... to keep us out of the long-distance market. ... AT&AMP;T chooses to
sit on the sideline and, for the most part, whine while all the
other companies come in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
