<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALCOLMX-DONATION02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A revelation in letters: Educated, tender Malcolm X
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Malcolm X is a modern legend, the subject of a Spike
Lee movie and an Alex Haley book. But in important ways, he's not
well known at all.
</P>
<P>
   Emory University has acquired a cache of Malcolm's private
papers that are likely to fill many of the gaps, and even to change
some of the popular notions about the assassinated civil rights
leader's formative years.
</P>
<P>
   The material _ including letters to and from him, personal
receipts, school work and photos _ mostly covers the period
1938-1955, when Malcolm was in his teens and 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really quite stunning, really extraordinary,'' said
Randall Burkett, head of Emory's Woodruff Library African-American
Studies Collection. ``It's a real coup for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows there were a lot of Malcolm Xs out there, not just
the angry, militant one people think of,'' said Leroy Davis, a
professor of African-American studies at Emory.
</P>
<P>
   A collector in Boston bought the papers from a family member,
then sold them to James Allen, an Atlanta antiques dealer, and his
partner, John Littlefield, for an undisclosed sum. Allen and
Littlefield are lending them to Emory's library.
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes a wealth of correspondence, both to and
from Malcolm. Most of it is from 1938 to 1955, when Malcolm was a
teen-ager and young adult, but some of the papers are from the
'60s. The collection also includes a box of cuff links and other
jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   It will be available to researchers starting Tuesday, and will
likely be in high demand. Scholars say the Allen-Littlefield
collection not only is unique _ other than these letters, almost
none of Malcolm's early correspondence has been found _ but also
sheds new light on one of the most admired, feared and important
civil rights leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Malcolm's letters suggest that, despite his
self-cultivated persona as an uneducated street tough, Malcolm X
was extremely articulate. His letters are elegant, well-punctuated
and laced with sarcasm, humor, even tenderness.
</P>
<P>
   A number of books on Malcolm X paint inaccurate pictures of the
fiery civil rights leader, says David Garrow, an Emory historian
and author of a Pulitzer Prize-winning book on Martin Luther King
Jr. The new collection will help scholars correct those pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given how well known and appropriately celebrated Malcolm is,
it's embarrassing that the historical scholarship on him is so
modest and spotty and incomplete,'' says Garrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This material shows what an immensely talented individual he
was, even when he was 20 years old,'' Garrow says. ``A lot of us,
even within the scholarly community, sort of had the sense that
Malcolm was a no 'count until the Nation of Islam made him grow up
and get his act together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we see he had his act together early. This collection
makes crystal clear that Malcolm was someone of very impressive
intellect, though nonetheless clearly troubled, long before he
became a Muslim.''
</P>
<P>
   Born Malcolm Little in 1925, Malcolm grew up in Lansing, Mich.
After his father's murder and his mother's institutionalization, he
moved to Boston. Malcolm became a petty criminal as a teen-ager,
and was sent to prison in 1946 at age 21. There he became a
disciple of Elijah Muhammad, head of the Nation of Islam, who
preached rigorous asceticism and advocated a separate nation for
blacks. Released in 1952, Malcolm devoted his life to what then was
called the Black Muslim movement, rejecting civil rights leaders
like King who were pressing for integration.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm, who adopted the initial ``X'' because he considered
Little a ``slave name,'' in speeches referred to whites as devils
and once met with Ku Klux Klan leaders because he agreed that total
separation of the races was the only way for African-Americans to
achieve equal rights.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1964, after in-fighting sparked by Malcolm's success and
celebrity, he broke with the the Nation of Islam. The same year,
after traveling to Mecca, the seat of Islam in Saudi Arabia, his
views toward whites softened. Scholars like Garrow and Davis
contend he was coming closer to King's integrationist views when he
was assassinated in New York in 1965 by followers of Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   One of Malcolm's legacies was the burgeoning black-power
movement of the '60s. Allen, himself an expert on Malcolm, says he
opened his collection to scholarship because he considers Malcolm
as important in the civil rights struggle as King.
</P>
<P>
   The papers and other artifacts tend to ``personalize him and the
times in which he lived, enumerate the demons he fought and
overcame, and rekindle the devotion and love he inspired in life,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Emory's Davis says the collection also offers new insights into
Malcolm as a historical figure and could fill in blanks that don't
exist about King, whose life was much better documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earliest letters speak to Malcolm's adolescence,
especially his friends and associates in the eighth grade at age
14, in a local high school in Mason, Mich.,'' Davis says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a five-and-dime notebook that Malcolm turned into a
makeshift yearbook, he revealed all of his classmates' likes,
dislikes, favorite pastimes, girls and boys and teachers admired in
his school. What obviously comes through in the construction of the
questions is Malcolm's early quest for perfectionism, his
organizing ability in particular, and discipline in tasks he really
enjoyed,'' Davis says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm was perhaps a closet intellectual, even in those days,
at least in the eighth grade.''
</P>
<P>
   Other documents speak to darker facets of Malcolm's early life.
In one letter, his sister Hilda complains he stole from her ``all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That indicates Malcolm's problem with theft didn't just begin
when he fell in with the wrong crowd,'' Garrow says. ``That, in a
nutshell, is the intriguing, complicated irony of Malcolm. We've
got this impressively bright person writing these extremely
articulate, expressive letters, and on the other hand, we've got
someone who is clearly headed down the serious juvenile delinquent
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Later letters describe Malcolm's life in prison and his
conversion to Islam.
</P>
<P>
   In one, Malcolm writes proudly of his self-discipline,
describing how, when made angry by ``prejudiced, narrow-minded''
guards, ``I counted to 10. One good thing you learn how to do while
you're in here, and that is how to use a little self-control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In one letter to his half-sister Ella from prison, Malcolm
talks about a book he is writing and asks Ella for good quality
pens for Christmas,'' Allen says. In another he writes also of a
desire to be transferred to another prison because ``they have a
fine library down there and one can learn so many more different
things. My only reason for wanting to go is the library alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Together these two letters tend to undermine one image Malcolm
wanted to portray. As the spokesperson for the Nation of Islam, he
portrayed himself as an irretrievable and illiterate hoodlum until
his introduction to Elijah Muhammad and his painful conversion to
Islam,'' Allen says. ``Now we know that his intellectual life and
ambitions were fully engaged prior to his conversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis says when word of the collection gets out, it's likely to
attract other letters and Malcolm memorabilia now in hands of
people he knew, and who may want to make it available to scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Malcolm X's prominence, and Emory's superior
research facilities, it increases the likelihood of much more
material being added to it,'' Davis says. ``It is of course not
just Emory that would be attractive but the city of Atlanta, the
birthplace of MLK Jr. and a major center of black activist activity
during Malcolm's lifetime and after.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
