<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NO PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We no longer have to worry about Gidone Busch. He
won't freak out and frighten his neighbors in the Borough Park
section of Brooklyn anymore. He's been taken care of by the police.
He's dead.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and the police commissioner would like you to believe
that the bullet-riddled Busch had been some monstrous, hulking
figure _ a big man armed with a claw hammer that he was ready to
embed in the skulls of all and sundry.
</P>
<P>
   At a City Hall press conference, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
earnestly told reporters, ``He was in the course of attacking a
police officer with, I think we have a picture of it, a hammer _''
</P>
<P>
   At which point Police Commissioner Howard Safir helpfully
interjected, ``A claw hammer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A claw hammer,'' said the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, of course, was to make Busch seem as menacing, as
dangerous, as possible, and thus take some of the heat off the
police officers who killed him. Said Safir: ``A claw hammer is a
very dangerous instrument and had not the police officers, in my
opinion, taken the action, that could have been planted in one of
our sergeants' brains.''
</P>
<P>
   The hammer was, in fact, an ordinary household hammer. And
Busch, who was mentally ill and extremely agitated, used it to hit
Police Sgt. Terrence O'Brien on the arm and on the thigh. He did
not attack the sergeant's head, and he did not seriously hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   As for Busch being a hulking figure _ well, he was tall.
According to the medical examiner, he was 6-3. And he weighed all
of 159 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   There were six cops at the scene. They didn't pounce on this
raving stringbean and drag him to the ground and handcuff him. Why
go to all that trouble when you've got a gun on your hip? Why take
the humane route when you can just blow somebody away?
</P>
<P>
   Four of the officers opened fire on Busch, hitting him 12 times.
</P>
<P>
   The matter was handled very efficiently. Less than 10 minutes
elapsed between the 911 call that summoned the officers and the
barrage of gunfire that ended Busch's life.
</P>
<P>
   The sense in the city that there is a serious problem with the
Police Department grows with each new example of excessive force.
Borough Park is a quiet place with little crime and a high level of
respect for the police. The killing of Busch surprised, angered and
dismayed many of the residents. ``Why did they have to kill him?''
was the standard refrain.
</P>
<P>
   While the mayor and the police commissioner have said it appears
the cops acted appropriately, other officials expressed
bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not faulting the individuals involved,'' said Council
Speaker Peter Vallone, ``but I am faulting the system which, as we
head into the 21st century, doesn't seem to be able to figure out
any way of stopping a sick person from trying to hurt somebody
other than killing him.''
</P>
<P>
   The borough president of the Bronx, Fernando Ferrer, asked,
``Was this kind of massive force actually necessary to subdue a man
with a hammer?''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer said the debate over police tactics and attitudes should
not be ``hijacked'' by police-bashers on the one hand and knee-jerk
supporters of the police on the other. He said most New Yorkers
were saying, in effect, ``Wait a minute, I like the city I live in
when crime is down, but I also want these bad contacts with
civilians to go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer favors the creation of an independent monitor for the
Police Department, and he would like civilian complaints against
the police to be dealt with honestly and effectively _ which is not
something that happens very often now.
</P>
<P>
   The place where such complaints are taken most seriously is in
court. Comptroller Alan Hevesi expects the annual cost of settling
lawsuits against the Police Department to surpass $40 million in
fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nixon going to China, the one New Yorker who could do
something real about the police problem is Giuliani. But he won't
even acknowledge that there is a problem. So there will be no
gathering of bright and responsible civic leaders to look at ways
of curbing the excesses and improving relations between the police
and the people they are supposed to serve. No advice will be sought
and no unsolicited advice will be taken.
</P>
<P>
   We await the next barrage of gunfire.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
