<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-SETBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN FLAW TO DELAY AMTRAK'S HIGH-SPEED TRAIN SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Colo., Mass., R.I., Conn.) (th) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amtrak's new 150-mph express train, which was
supposed to begin service between Washington and Boston this year,
will be delayed several months because the wheels on the passenger
coaches vibrate at high speeds and are wearing out too quickly, the
railroad said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak is counting on the new service, called Acela, to lure
business away from the airlines and to generate $180 million a year
in profits. Those profits are supposed to help the railroad meet a
cut-off in operating subsidies at the end of the 2002 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   George Warrington, Amtrak's president and chief executive, said
the railroad would face a shortfall in the next fiscal year as a
result of the delay. But he said Amtrak would make ends meet with
new revenue, most of which is derived from one-time deals. He would
not say what these deals were, but said they did not include sales
of assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about taking the time necessary to get this train
right,'' said Warrington during a conference call with reporters.
``As a practical matter, it's not a tough choice because we have no
interest in cutting corners, and accepting a train that does not
meet performance standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The flanges of the train wheels, which descend along the inside
edge of the rails, are wearing out too quickly, according to
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The problem came to light in shakedown testing on a high-speed
track in Pueblo, Colo. A French company, Alstom SA, which builds
the wheels, is redesigning the suspension to reduce wear, but
testing will take several months.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak said it would know in 60 days when the trains would be
ready. Alstom and its partner, Bombardier Inc. of Montreal, said
the trains would be ready for delivery in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is a phenomenon known to rail engineers as
``hunting,'' a side-to-side oscillation of the wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Warrington and the president of Bombardier, Jacques Lapare, were
not specific about the cause of the problem, but Lapare said that
it became apparent only because of instrumentation on a test train
at Pueblo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a safety issue, it's like a maintenance aspect,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The builders are altering the stiffness of the suspension to
eliminate the problem, Lapare said.
</P>
<P>
   The delay comes on the heels of reports from the Transportation
Department and the General Accounting Office, an investigative arm
of Congress, raising questions about whether the railroad will be
ready to give up operating subsidies after 2002. The GAO
anticipates that subsidies will be required indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak is also upgrading the tracks between Washington and
Boston, said Warrington, which should lead to improved service even
before the high-speed trains are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Electrification of the tracks from New Haven, Conn., to Boston
will be finished in December, he said. That will allow two electric
trains that the railroad is now refurbishing to begin service on
that stretch in January, reducing travel times from New York to
Boston by 48 minutes to as much as one hour, 48 minutes. The
electricity is scheduled to be turned on Wednesday night in the
first segment, an 18-mile stretch of track west of Warwick, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   The tracks in Rhode Island have been extensively rebuilt. Nearly
400,000 railroad ties have been replaced 15 bridges have been
repaired, among other steps. The Acela will reach maximum speed
there in Rhode Island. Through much of the rest of the route the
speed of the trains will be limited by curves.
</P>
<P>
   The wheel problem is the second setback for the high-speed
train. The first was the discovery that the benefits of a tilt
mechanism, designed to improve passenger comfort in high-speed
curves, could not be fully realized. The tracks are too close
together, so that trains passing in opposite directions might
sideswipe each other. Railroad officials say, however, that the
trains should still meet the trip-time improvements called for in
the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The contract includes penalties for late delivery, beginning at
$1,000 per train per day and rising to $13,500 per train per day.
Officials said Wednesday that they did not know what the penalty
would be because they did not know how much the deliveries would be
delayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
