<SLUG> BC-MADEMOISELLE-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDE NAST HIRE'S HEARST EDITOR TO EDIT MADEMOISELLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain )   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the second time in two years, Conde Nast has plucked an
editor of Hearst's Cosmopolitan magazine to run one of its
magazines. Wednesday, Mandi Norwood, the editor of British
Cosmopolitan, was named editor-in-chief of Mademoiselle magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Norwood, 35, succeeds Elizabeth Crow, who resigned last week
after nearly six years as editor in chief. Last year, the editor in
chief of American Cosmopolitan, Bonnie Fuller, joined the Conde
Nast magazine Glamour.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Norwood's appointment comes at a critical time for
Mademoiselle. Circulation has slipped from 1.3 million in 1995 to
1.1 million in 1998; for the six-month period ending in June, sales
of single copies at the newsstand _ a generally reliable barometer
of consumer enthusiasm for a magazine _ dropped by 16.5 percent.
Advertising pages are down slightly: for the period from Jan. 1 to
Aug. 31 this year, the magazine sold 691 advertising pages. For the
same period last year, the figure was 819, according to the
Publishers Information Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   But most importantly, Mademoiselle _ a magazine for young women
that offers advice about career, relationships and cellulite cream
under headlines like ``Fear and Lusting at the Office'' _ has more
competitors than ever before in its 64-year history. Just last
week, Advance Publications, the parent company of Conde Nast,
acquired Fairchild Publications, which publishes one of
Mademoiselle's competitors, Jane.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Crow became editor in chief in 1993, Mademoiselle was
in direct competition with the mass-market titles Cosmopolitan and
Glamour. Now, ``Millie'' _ its nickname in the corridors of Conde
Nast _ faces competition from both of those titles, as well as an
ever-expanding field of relatively new women's magazines, a group
that includes Jane; Marie Claire, a joint venture between Hearst
Magazines and Marie Claire Album of France; Time Inc.'s In Style,
and even Rodale's New Woman magazine, which recently unveiled a
redesign oriented to younger readers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Norwood has been the editor of the British edition of
Cosmopolitan since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, she edited Company, a lifestyle and fashion
magazine for young women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
