<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7736 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-0902-CO     09-01 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PALESTINIAN-ISRAELI DEAL STALLS, REMAINS A KEY TO ALBRIGHT'S
VISIT
 &HT;    900&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-EGYPT-0902.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Israeli and Palestinian negotiators worked late
Wednesday night trying to give U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright the gift she needs for her Middle East tour _ a deal to
remove old obstacles in the peace process and let her focus on the
lofty goal of regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli officials said talks ended after 1 a.m. (local
time), and that it was unclear when they would resume. A deadlock
could throw a wrench into Albright's plans to join Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak in overseeing the signing of an agreement
to re-start the stalled Middle East peace process at a palace in
the ancient Egyptian port city of Alexandria Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The palace was being prepared Wednesday even as negotiators in
Jerusalem postured, delivered ultimatums, called off and resumed
talks. U.S. President Bill Clinton called Mubarak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat Wednesday to urge a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The land-for-security deal being considered would cover steps
that were meant to be completed months ago but floundered under
former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. A resolution
would clear the way for Albright to turn her attention to the
larger issues still remaining in the peace process between Israel
and the Palestinians. It would also add impetus to Albright's hopes
to restart talks between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The trip comes amid expectations fueled by the presence of a new
Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, and indications from Arab
leaders that they are anxious to make peace. Albright's aides have
characterized the trip as the start of a push to, ``close the
circle of peace in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a desire to have peace,'' Albright told reporters on
her plane Wednesday. ``There is a sense we have to move on. And
what I want to do is to play a fruitful role.''
</P>
<P>
   But, first that requires a resolution of snags in the Wye River
Memorandum, which was signed in Washington by Israelis and
Palestinians nearly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Wye itself was meant to repair the 1993 Oslo peace plan, in
which Israel was scheduled to withdraw its occupying troops from
undetermined portions of the West Bank, captured from the Arabs in
the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wye accords were halted in January by then-Prime
Minister Netanyahu, who originally opposed the Oslo process. Barak
promised to restart the process, but the methodical former general
wanted more certainty about the course the peace process would take
and insisted on restructuring the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis are hesitant to give up land in a process in which they
do not know the final outcome. Also, Barak worried that handing
over the 13 percent of the West Bank land set out in Wye would
endanger enclaves of Israeli settlers to Arab attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, who comes under frequent criticism for taking the
Palestinians down the Oslo path, wants to get any land as soon as
possible. Even with the Wye land, he will control only 40 percent
of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The deal approached Wednesday would slow down the schedule for
land hand-overs. The transfers would resume within days but be
spread through mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the two sides would be well into discussions on
the major issues between them and of primary concern to Barak,
including whether Israel will share Jerusalem or allow millions of
Palestinian refugees return to land in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   A major snag also existed Wednesday over the release of
Palestinian prisoners, many of whom killed or tried to kill
Israelis. To Palestinians, the inmates are prisoners of war who
should be released during peacetime. Their continued detention
despite the Oslo process makes Arafat look weak. To Israelis, they
are terrorists and their release could create a political firestorm
for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides appeared to be nearing a figure between 350 and
400 prisoners, down from the 650 the Palestinians wanted.
</P>
<P>
   If such arrangements on land transfers, timetables and prisoners
are reached, they would grant little more to the Palestinians than
they felt they were already promised. But, Israel holds the land
and, under the current Wye deal, has many opportunities to halt the
process. As late as Wednesday afternoon, Barak threatened to be
especially tough in implementing Wye if Palestinians did not let
him renegotiate it.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been reports that Barak, if allowed to move
quicker into the final issues, might be willing to recognize
Palestinian statehood or give them slightly more land.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to really see that we are not making concessions for
five years without having a clear understanding of what the picture
will look like when it is over,'' said Barak advisor Jacob
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   A Palestinian analyst said the deal could be a hard sell to the
restless Palestinian people lead by Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly like Netanyahu forcing Arafat to compromise Oslo
with Wye, now Barak is forcing Arafat to compromise Wye with
this,'' said Ghassan Khatib, a former Palestinian negotiator.
``This process is becoming a process of compromising the
compromises.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   But, a deal would help Albright. She has insisted she does not
want a re-run of fruitless trips under Netanyahu's term, in which
she got bogged down refereeing the details of the
Palestinian-Israeli dispute. It made all the parties look bad. Even
this trip was postponed from last month, when the negotiations
snagged.
</P>
<P>
   From Egypt, Albright is expected to travel on to Israel, Syria
and Jordan to lay the groundwork for regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   A deal between Israel and the Palestinians Thursday could put
pressure on Syria to resume long-stalled talks with Israel. Barak
has announced that he will pursue peace in the track that looks to
have the most potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a type of competition between the Palestinians and
Syrians,'' Khatib said.
</P>
<P>
   Syria seeks the return of the Golan Heights, which Israel
captured in 1967. In return, Israelis hope that Syria will rein in
anti-Israeli Hezbollah guerillas in Lebanon, a country Syria
effectively controls.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Israel would be expected to end its occupation of
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
