<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-HEART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIABETES SINGLED OUT AS HEART DISEASE RISK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Diabetes-Risk)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a new strategy to attack the nation's No. 1 killer, the
American Heart Association is for the first time Wednesday called
diabetes a major risk factor for heart disease, ranking it with
high blood pressure and smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Adding particular weight to the announcement, which is being
formally published in the association's journal Circulation next
week, is the support being thrown behind it by the National
Institutes of Health, the American Diabetes Association and the
Juvenile Diabetes Foundation International.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes as scientific evidence is emerging about the
relationships between the two diseases, which affect millions of
Americans, and as the US demographics are changing and putting more
people at risk of adult-onset, or type 2, diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the aging of the population, the growth in obesity and
the increase in the number of minorities who are at higher risk in
this country are already starting to lead to an increase in type 2
diabetes, say health officials. And that suggests that the nation's
successes so far in addressing heart disease might also be reversed
if nothing is done, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the predominant reason for the American Heart
Association giving attention to this area,'' said Dr. Robert H.
Eckel, chairman of the group's nutrition committee, which worked on
the scientific statement on diabetes and heart disease. ``As type 2
diabetes increases. . ., the relationship to heart disease can only
increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter J. Savage, deputy director of the division of
epidemiology and clinical applications at the National Heart, Lung
and Blood Insitute (NHLBI), agreed. ``Diabetes is becoming an even
more important risk factor.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart association's naming of diabetes as a major modifiable
risk factor is one of three additions it has made since 1992 _
obesity and sedentary lifestyle being the other two. Previous
additions occured in the 1960s, when high blood pressure and
cholesterol were included.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials hope the listing of diabetes will focus the
attention of patients and physicians on preventing or aggressively
treating the disease and its complications.
</P>
<P>
   opt trim this graph A new generation of drugs to control blood
sugar levels and studies showing the importance of strictly
regulating blood pressure and cholesterol levels for diabetics are
available, but the word has not yet filtered down to many primary
care physicians and patients, say heart and diabetes specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that could be better treated, but it is just not being
done,'' said Dr. William Castelli, former director of the federally
funded Framingham Heart Study and now director of the Framingham
Cardiovascular Institute. In addition to the national campaigns
that already exist against high cholesterol, high blood pressure
and smoking, ``we need a campaign against high blood sugar and we
also need a campaign against obesity.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1 million Americans a year die from cardiovascular
disease, while more than 59 million suffer from some form of it,
whether it be heart disease, high blood pressure, or stroke.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 10.3 million Americans have been diagnosed with
diabetes, while another 15 million are believed to have undiagnosed
diabetes or elevated blood sugar levels not yet high enough to be
called diabetes. All of them are at greater risk of heart disease,
up to four times greater than people who have normal blood sugar
levels.
</P>
<P>
   But because diabetes is rarely, if ever, listed on death
certificates, the disease ``is very much underestimated as a
contributor to death rates,'' said Dr. Judy Fradkin, deputy
director of the division of diabetes, endocrinology and metabolic
disorders for the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and
Kidney Diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Yet studies have found that about 80 percent of people with
diabetes go on to develop some form of cardiovascular disease, said
Fradkin, whose agency joined the National Heart, Lung and Blood
Institute and the diabetes groups in supporting the heart
association's statement in an editorial in Circulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time that they pay a little more attention to
diabetes,'' said Dr. Om Ganda, senior physician at the Joslin
Diabetes Center and an associate clinical professor of medicine at
Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   While a family history places people at greater risk of type 2
diabetes, so does being overweight, increasing age and being a
member of a minority group. The United States has one of the
highest rates in the world of both diabetes and heart disease,
largely as a result of the sedentary lifestyle and poor diet here.
And blacks, Latinos, Asians and Native Americans have some of the
highest rates of diabetes in the United States, according to Ganda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
