<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PANAMA02-COX     09-01 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking control of canal top challenge in Panama, diplomat says
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Neither Mireya Moscoso, who was sworn in Wednesday as
the new president of Panama, nor her Arnulfista Party has any
significant experience in governing. And she and her allies will
have little time to learn as they face the dual _ and inseparable _
challenges of invigorating their nation's economy and taking
control of the Panama Canal, said Robert Pastor, a diplomat and
Emory University professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The canal is so important to Panama's economy, you can't
really separate one from the other,'' Pastor said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But, despite the importance of the moment, the Clinton
administration has done little to help ensure a smooth transition
of the canal's control, Pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   The key question, he said, is: ``How do we help her make this
transition? I don't hear anyone in the administration asking, let
alone answering, that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso, 54, took the oath of office 31 years after her husband,
Arnulfo Arias, was overthrown by Gen. Omar Torrijos. Moscoso won
election in May by defeating Martin Torrijos, the late dictator's
son.
</P>
<P>
   In her inaugural address, Moscoso pledged ``efficient and
responsible'' administration of the canal. ``My government intends
to increase the autonomy of the canal so it may operate without any
partisan political influence,'' she told a cheering crowd of 25,000
at Panama City's new baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor has played a significant role in recent Panamanian
history. Working on the National Security Council during President
Jimmy Carter's administration, Pastor helped negotiate the treaty
that calls for the transfer of the canal to Panamanian control by
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1989, he negotiated an agreement with Panamanian
strongman Manuel Noriega to allow Carter and others to monitor a
Panama election. Carter declared that election fraudulent _ helping
create an atmosphere that, though it was not Carter's intent,
helped legitimize the U.S. invasion of Panama under President
George Bush later that year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, President Clinton nominated Pastor to become ambassador
to Panama, but the appointment was blocked by Sen. Jesse Helms
(R-N.C.), chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Moscoso is the second freely elected president since the 1989
invasion. Pastor said the importance of her assumption of power is
that voters decided to switch parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents a step toward consolidating democracy,'' he
said. ``Whenever you have a peaceful change in administration from
one party to its opposition in a fragile democracy, then that's an
encouraging step.''
</P>
<P>
   Transfer of the operations of the canal _ running the locks and
making sure shipping travels well _ should go smoothly, he said,
because the Panamanians have long experience at it, Pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   But transfer of the canal's facilities and bases and security
planning are going poorly, he said. And neither government has had
the foresight to give much consideration to security issues, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pastor dismissed concern expressed by Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott (R-Miss.) that, in hiring Hong Kong-based Hutchison
Whampoa Ltd. to manage some canal ports, Panama has given China
control over the waterway. ``Among the many fears that are being
voiced by members of Congress, this idea must rank among the most
absurd,'' Pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
