<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SUBURU-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-01 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBURU-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBURU ROLLS OUT HUGE CAMPAIGN, BUT STICKS TO FAMILIAR THEMES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.J., Australia, Japan)   By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suburu is rolling out the largest advertising campaign in its
history, but don't expect to see a new cast of characters or any
other drastic changes to its existing theme. Instead, the company
is sticking by an old adage: ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hogan of ``Crocodile Dundee'' fame continues as Subaru's
spokesman in the integrated campaign from Subaru's agency of six
years, Temerlin McClain in Irving, Texas, and the campaign
continues to emphasize safety and performance features, including
all-wheel-drive technology. Subaru, however, is doubling the amount
of broadcast and print placements and backing the ads with $70
million to $80 million to push its revamped Legacy line and its
2000 Forester model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Subaru understands who they are,'' said David Lyon, group
account director at Temerlin McClain, a unit of True North
Communications. He added, ``That's why you see consistency, focus,
continuity, and you see the courage to stay with what's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Clive Chajet, chairman of Chajet Consultancy, a brand and
corporate image company in New York, agrees that sticking to a
similar format seems to be the right formula for the Subaru of
America unit of Fuji Heavy Industries of Japan. ``Given the
intensity of the noise level of automobile advertising, essentially
the only way they are breaking through the clutter is staying with
what they already have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest campaign for the company's redesigned Legacy
models, which include the Outback wagon, the Outback sedan and the
Legacy GT, the overall slogan is still, ``The beauty of all-wheel
drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nine new television commercials, which began running
nationally last month, are for the Outback models. In one spot for
the Outback sedan, a sleek black car is shown cruising through a
city and passing imagery of the Australian Outback, including a
woman walking a kangaroo on a leash, crocodiles in potholes and a
herd of sheep crossing the street at a crosswalk. Hogan steps out
of his Subaru and says, ``My kind of town.''
</P>
<P>
   A spot for the Outback Sport vehicle, which is aimed at younger
consumers, shows Hogan tagging along with his nephew en route to an
outdoor concert. The two drive on a dirt road through a variety of
obstacles to demonstrate the car's performance and horsepower. As
they reach their destination, passing tattooed fellow concertgoers,
the nephew says, ``This might not be your type of crowd, Uncle,''
to find Hogan already body surfing in the mosh pit. The Outback tag
line is, ``The world's first sport utility wagon.''
</P>
<P>
   A third commercial to demonstrate the traction and control of
all-wheel-drive technology has Hogan in the classic Subaru chase
scenario in the jungle. Two other spots for the Forester emphasize
its carlike handling and that it is easier to climb into than other
sport utility vehicles. The Forester slogan is, ``Sport utility
tough, car easy.'' Another commercial, showcases the entire line of
Subaru's all-wheel- drive vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone would look at the work and say there is a
significant departure from what we have done,'' Lyon said, ``though
we have done some things differently to call attention to the fact
that we have a new car.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, who has been in the Subaru campaign for five years
``represents everything we want to say about this car _ that it's
rugged, it's adventurous, it can provide the driver with a lot of
confidence and that it's fun,'' Lyon said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, ``We had to find a way to use Paul a little
differently to make sure that we signal news that we have a new car
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cyphers, vice president for marketing at Subaru in Cherry
Hill, N.J., said the company's sales figures were argument enough
for continuing with the current theme. ``We've had three wonderful
years back to back _ each year is better than the last,'' he said.
``And this past year was our best sales year in over 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last six years, Subaru said that sales in the United
States had grown more than 50 percent. As of July, Subaru had sold
85,478 cars this year, up 8 percent, from the corresponding period
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   `` Hogan continues to work for us. The type of ads that we do
continue to work, and we are targeting those people with the active
life style who have a high propensity to buy our cars,'' Cyphers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most Subaru buyers are college-educated, make approximately
$75,000 annually and enjoy an active life style involving canoeing,
hiking and skiing, Cyphers said.
</P>
<P>
   Lyon added that Subaru was also trying to win over consumers who
had become disillusioned with sport utility vehicles, which are
essentially light trucks and have poor fuel economy.
</P>
<P>
   As Subaru has brought itself back from a string of declining
sales ending in the early 1990s, it has grown from a marketer of
niche products like front- and four-wheel-drive vehicles that were
positioned as cheap and reliable to a full-line producer of
mainstream offerings like upscale all-wheel-drive sedans, sports
utility wagons and the Forester sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The print portion of the campaign gives readers glimpses into
the active, outdoor-oriented life styles of Subaru owners. Six ads
began appearing in the August issues of publications including
Automobile, National Geographic, Outside, People, Southern Living,
Smithsonian and Time. All the ads refer consumers to a refurbished
Subaru corporate Web site, subaru.com or to a special site designed
to showcase the new line, 2000.subaru.com. In addition to search
engines like Yahoo, Subaru interactive banner ads have been placed
on sites like Autobytel and Carpoint. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
