<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7745 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CARE02-COX     09-01 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Milosevic releases 2 CARE workers from prison; 1 remains
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three weeks ago, Samira Pratt said she would like
nothing better than to have her husband, languishing in a Yugoslav
prison, released in time for the birth of their first child.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my husband, and I really need him,'' she said from
Canberra, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The baby was due Aug. 30. But she may yet get her wish.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic released two
employees of the relief organization CARE Australia _ Peter Wallace
and Samira Pratt's husband, Steve.
</P>
<P>
   The baby is overdue. But if Steve Pratt can make it to Australia
in good time, he may yet help with the birth.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt and Wallace, both Australians, were arrested March 31 as
they tried to leave Yugoslavia shortly after the start of the NATO
bombing campaign. On April 8, a third CARE Australia employee,
Branko Jelen, a Yugoslav citizen, also was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Espionage charges against the three were dropped, but they were
convicted by a closed military court of passing secret information
out of the country. After appeals for sentence reduction were
granted, Pratt was still left with a prison term of eight years;
Wallace was left with one year and Jelen was left with three.
</P>
<P>
   CARE officials have maintained that the men did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The three appealed for clemency on humanitarian grounds. On
Wednesday, after meeting with former Australian Prime Minister
Malcolm Fraser, who is chairman of CARE Australia's board of
directors, Milosevic ordered Pratt and Wallace released.
</P>
<P>
   Jelen, however, remains in prison.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Milosevic, Fraser traveled to the prison, an
hour or more outside of Belgrade. There, according to Peter Bell,
president of CARE USA, an affiliated relief organization based in
Atlanta, Fraser met the governor of the prison, ``shared a glass of
plum brandy, and walked out with the two prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   The men were taken to Croatia, and are expected to travel to
Great Britain, where they will be counseled by psychologists
experienced in treating prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good news, but it's incomplete,'' said Bell. CARE
officials will not be satisfied _ nor will they discuss resuming
humanitarian operations in Yugoslavia _ until Jelen is released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We re determined to keep a light focused on him,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the atmosphere at CARE USA headquarters in Atlanta
was festive, and the feeling of relief was palpable. One worker
posted a sign out front that said, simply, ``They're Free.''
</P>
<P>
   CARE Australia chief executive Charles Tapp accompanied Wallace
and Pratt to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both stunned and amazed to be free,'' he told
Australian Associated Press. ``They're in reasonable condition
given what they've been through. I'm going to take them for a beer
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The men were buoyed by support from around the world. Former
President Jimmy Carter wrote Milosevic a letter supporting the
men's release, thousands of people wrote letters and e-mails, and
children in Atlanta _ the sons and daughters of CARE employees _
drew pictures for the men to use in decorating their cell.
</P>
<P>
   CARE employees speculated that Pratt, who is scheduled to
participate in a news conference from London today, may bolt for
Australia as quickly as he can.
</P>
<P>
   He had sent a message to CARE workers asking that they buy his
wife a stuffed bear as a present. Now, they hope he will deliver
the present himself _ and arrive in time to help his wife deliver
the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
