<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7746 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-LITTLEANIMALS-TE     09-01 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LITTLEANIMALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU WON'T MISS THIS MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``All the Little Animals'' is the type of movie you could
describe as deceptively simple, if only it weren't so intent on
telling you that it's deceptively simple. It's an allegorical
little movie about an innocent's struggle between father figures _
and about other themes that you might not notice at first blush,
except that the movie is so intent on putting them across.
</P>
<P>
   The innocent is a British lad named Bobby (Christian Bale), who
hasn't been running at full mental speed since he was injured in a
car accident as a child. For most of his life, Bobby has remained
inside his London house, playing with his pet mouse and only
occasionally interacting with other people. After his doting mother
dies, he's left in the hands of a calculating stepfather (Daniel
Benzali), who threatens to put Bobby in a home if he doesn't sign
over the family department store. Driven to desperate measures,
Bobby discovers _ almost by accident _ that although he feels like
a prisoner in the house, all he has to do to escape is walk away.
</P>
<P>
   And walk he does, and hitchhike, till he's nearly reached the
Cornwall region of the southwest English coast a few hundred miles
from London. It's there that he meets Mr. Summers (John Hurt), a
curmudgeonly hermit sort who has little use for other people but
finds enough sweetness in Bobby to enlist him in his daily task:
making sure that all the area's road kill receives a decent burial.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, this looks like another quirky indie story, but
it's also a parable about city vs. country, greed vs. altruism,
and, of course, good vs. evil. Director Jeremy Thomas, working from
Walker Hamilton's novel, almost scuttles the material because he's
too reverential toward its subtle ecological undertones. It's hard
to miss subtleties in a movie in which the bad guy is named Mr.
DeWinter and the good guy Mr. Summers.
</P>
<P>
   As Bobby, Bale is a little annoying _ he's the type of actor who
communicates sweet naivete by perpetually leaving his mouth hanging
open. He's stuck between more accomplished pros, although Benzali's
deftly malevolent performance is undercut a little bit by his
unfortunate resemblance to Austin Powers' Dr. Evil. As for Hurt, he
could probably play a cantankerous sort like Mr. Summers in his
sleep; his only false note here is an overplayed temper tantrum
that looks to be as much a fault of the directing as of his acting.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the way through, the movie takes a turn from its
allegorical bent to more standard suspense, which Thomas builds
surprisingly well. The climax has its pros and cons. Coming after
more lyrical, literary segments, it feels like a degeneration into
the violent norm. But it also ups the interest level in a movie
that sometimes takes itself too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Little Animals'' is rated R for brief but relatively
graphic violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Little Animals''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 1-5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jeremy Thomas
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Christian Bale, John Hurt, Daniel Benzali
</P>
<P>
   Length: 112 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT &LR;      09-01 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO SALES   JUMP SHARPLY   IN AUGUST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mich.)   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ In a sign that strong consumer spending continued to
power the American economy last month, many auto makers announced
Wednesday that their sales soared in August, with the biggest
growth occurring for some of the most expensive models with the
highest profits.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler AG said that its Chrysler, Dodge, Plymouth, Jeep
and Mercedes-Benz brands had their best August ever, together
climbing 9.6 percent from already brisk sales in August 1998. Honda
Motor reported that its sales had climbed 10.5 percent in August
from a year earlier, to the highest level ever for any month, while
Toyota Motor reported its best August ever in the United States
with a 2.8 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors said that its sales jumped 63.4 percent. But its
sales in August of last year were severely depressed because a
54-day strike had just ended and dealerships had not yet been
restocked with popular models.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives and dealers were jubilant about the strength of
the market last month. ``It was unbelievable, it was as hot as
Texas,'' said Alan B. Helfman, a Chrysler, Plymouth and Jeep dealer
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly sales of new automobiles have long been an important
barometer of the economy's health, because they account for 4
percent of the nation's economic output and because auto makers
announce the sales immediately at the start of the next month. Alan
Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, made his reputation
as an economic consultant while working for the steel and auto
industries in the 1950s and 1960s. He has watched auto sales
reports closely ever since, although noting that the auto
industry's role in the economy has diminished somewhat over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle E. Gramley, a former Federal Reserve Board governor and now
a consulting economist for the Mortgage Bankers' Association of
America, said the soaring sales increased the chances that the
central bank would raise short-term interest rates at the next
meeting of its interest-rate policy committee on Oct. 5,
particularly if other economic indicators showed the same strength
as the August auto sales.
</P>
<P>
   While the minutes of recent committee meetings show that the Fed
keeps expecting consumers to become satiated with big-ticket
purchases and slow their spending, Gramley said, ``These auto sales
say it is not happening.''
</P>
<P>
   In another indication of economic strength, the Conference
Board, a New York business group, said Wednesday that the Index of
Leading Economic Indicators had shown an increase of three-tenths
of a percent in July. But the Commerce Department announced
separately that construction spending was surprisingly weak in
July, which could mean that the Federal Reserve's two small
interest-rate increases this summer are starting to hurt the
housing market.
</P>
<P>
   But the rate increases seem to be having little effect on the
auto market. ``Demand has exceeded our expectations and everyone
else's in the industry,'' said Paul Ballew, GM's general director
of industry and market analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Jameson, DaimlerChrysler's vice president for sales and
marketing operations, said that the pace of sales actually
increased after the Fed's most recent increase in short-term rates,
on Aug. 24. ``We closed 3 or 4 percent higher than we had
forecasted in the middle of the month,'' he said. ``There are a lot
of people who have made a lot of money in the stock market, and it
seems like they're cashing it out.''
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler also raised Wednesday its forecast for auto
sales next year, predicting very strong sales of 16 million
vehicles, including heavy trucks. That would be a little less than
this year, which is on course for a record 17.2 million vehicles,
according to DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Sport utility vehicles sold best last month, followed by pickup
trucks, with cars and minivans trailing. Auto makers and dealers
make their biggest profits on sport utility vehicles because supply
has outstripped demand, allowing many models to be sold at full
retail price with little discounting.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of new designs has increased competition in the
market for mid-sized sport utility vehicles. But with
DaimlerChrysler offering lower-cost leases on the Jeep Grand
Cherokee this summer, sales shot up last month to the highest level
ever, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Helfman said that while his dealership stocked a dozen models of
cars, minivans and sport utility vehicles, just one model, the Jeep
Grand Cherokee, accounted for 100 of the 210 vehicles sold last
month. If Chrysler, Plymouth or Jeep built an even larger sport
utility vehicle, the size of a Ford Expedition, it would sell
extremely well too, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had a big one, there'd be another 30 or 40 sales _ man,
we'd be eating caviar down here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor is scheduled to release its sales figures on
Thursday. Auto analysts predict that it will show only a small gain
from a year ago, when Ford dealerships profited from the lack of
inventory at rival GM dealerships. Without Ford's sales, auto
makers' market shares cannot be calculated precisely. Ballew said
that GM's share should be ``pretty close'' to 30 percent, the
company's target.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Motor, which has been struggling, reported a 7.7 percent
drop in sales last month from a year ago. But Subaru, a unit of
Fuji Heavy Industries, announced that August was its best month in
12 years, with a 9 percent improvement from last year, while
Mitsubishi Motors said that its sales had jumped 43 percent.
Volkswagen, which has been riding the popularity of the New Beetle
and the mid-sized Passat sedan and wagon, posted a 34 percent
increase in August sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
