<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELEE ERUPTS NEAR UN HEADQUARTERS IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ In the most brazen violence since Monday's
generally peaceful vote on the future of this tiny island
territory, gun- and machete-toting pro-Indonesia militias and
rock-hurling backers of independence clashed outside UN
headquarters here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The militias shot and hacked to death one man and chased, beat,
and shot at journalists and United Nations workers. At least a
half-dozen Timorese were seriously injured in the melee.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian police, who are responsible for keeping the peace in
the disputed territory, took more than an hour to send
reinforcements to the chaotic scene. Officers firing weapons were
able to restore order after about half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The escalating violence prompted an emergency meeting of the UN
Security Council in New York and calls from New Zealand for an
international military force to maintain order in East Timor, a
former Portuguese colony that was forcibly annexed by Indonesia 23
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some 150 locals, UN staff, and journalists scrambled over the
walls into the UN compound and hid in cars to escape clubbings and
gunfire by militia members, who wore black T-shirts and
red-and-white headbands representing Indonesia's national colors.
After attending the funeral of one of their comrades killed in an
earlier clash, the militias marched into a pro-independence
neighborhood near the UN compound and set up roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   Two houses were torched and three large fires blazed outside the
compound, spewing black smoke. Outnumbered Indonesian soldiers at a
nearby military post locked their gates rather than intervene to
stop the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The situation here appeared to be deteriorating sharply just two
days after an estimated 99 percent of the population turned out in
a largely peaceful vote to choose between autonomy under Indonesian
rule and full independence for the former Portuguese colony. With
the people of East Timor, population 800,000, believed to have
voted for independence by a wide margin, pro-Indonesia militias
broke promises to lay down their arms and resumed a seven-month
campaign that has destabilized the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups and diplomats have evidence that the
Indonesian military has supplied weapons and training to militias,
many of which formed to oppose Indonesian President B. J. Habibie's
January pledge to let East Timor decide its own future in a
UN-sponsored vote.
</P>
<P>
   There were unconfirmed reports Wednesday night that five people
had been killed in the clash in Dili, and journalists saw a
half-dozen people in one local clinic who were wounded by gunfire.
The streets of Dili were empty, and large groups of people were
seen fleeing their homes for the hills above the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The violence prompted Portugal, the territory's onetime colonial
power, to demand that Indonesia keep its pledge to maintain peace
whatever the result of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan called on police
``to arrest those responsible for the violence and to take
immediate steps to ensure it does not happen again.'' His spokesman
said it was unlikely that UN troops would be sent to the territory,
since Indonesia is responsible for security.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's representative asked UN officials to come up with
``ideas for contingency plans'' if the situation in East Timor
spirals out of control, but the Security Council would not discuss
the possibility for fear it would further destabilize the
situation, UN sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia objects to bringing in any UN peacekeepers, and a few
hundred unarmed UN civilian police allowed in have been unable to
stop armed groups from rampaging.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand Foreign Affairs Minister Don McKinnon said in
Wellington that if conditions worsen, New Zealand, Australia,
Japan, and the United States should send in a peacekeeping force
independent of the UN.
</P>
<P>
   But Australia, the only major nation to give recognition to
Indonesia's rule over East Timor, said it would not join any non-UN
force. Australia is anxious not to tread on the toes of neighboring
Indonesia, but its military is believed to have prepared troops for
deployment in East Timor if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   UN officials collected ballot boxes in Dili to prevent counting
fraud and to maintain the secrecy of how each local district voted.
Officials began tallying votes Wednesday, and results will be
announced in New York next week.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia invaded East Timor, an island territory the size of
Connecticut on the eastern end of the Indonesian island chain, in
1975, shortly after Portugal withdrew from the colony. An estimated
200,000 people died in the next five years from civil war,
guerrilla fighting, starvation, and disease.
</P>
<P>
   If the vote goes for independence, the UN-brokered plan calls
for Indonesian forces to remain until the parliament in Jakarta
revokes its annexation of East Timor when it meets this fall. Only
then, the UN has said, would it consider sending in peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's military commander in East Timor, Colonel Mohammad
Muis, said his forces were on full alert. Jakarta said 360 officers
of an elite unit would fly in Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Costello, head of an observer delegation from the
Atlanta-based Carter Center, said, ``The Indonesian government
needs to recognize there will now be calls for stronger
international action if they fail to fulfill their obligations'' to
maintain order under agreements signed in May at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Joe Lauria contributed to this report from the
UN in New York.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
