<SLUG> BC-MED-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL SCHOOLS SEE DECLINE IN ENROLLMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of applicants to medical schools declined nearly 5
percent last year, continuing a downward trend since applications
peaked in 1996, according to a study published Wednesday in the
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The author of the study and others in the field said the trend
may result from cyclical patterns in applications, which tend to
dip in prosperous times when students have more options for
high-paying careers.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors may include a toughening job market for recent
medical school graduates, and doctors' complaints of excessive
paperwork and a loss of autonomy brought on by the growth of
managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Applications reached an all-time high in 1996, when 46,968
people applied for roughly 16,200 openings at the 125 medical
schools accredited by the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   But since then applications have dropped about 12 percent, to
41,004 last year. Figures for 1999 are not yet available, but Dr.
Barbara Barzansky, the principal researcher and director of medical
schools services for the American Medical Association, said
applications in May were down 2,000 from the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
   The number of applications from minorities _ blacks, American
Indians, Mexican Americans and Puerto Ricans _ also declined at
higher rates. Since 1996, Barzansky said, the drop among that group
was 12.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The data set off a round of speculation over how to explain the
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Barzansky said a decline in the number of doctors is not likely
because medical schools were still drawing two or three people per
available slot and there is no indication the quality of candidates
is declining, since grade point average and medical college
admission test scores have remained about the same over the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
   But the dip in underrepresented minorities raises some concern
because it comes amid aggressive recruiting of minorities by
medical schools, she said. One explanation could be reverberations
from affirmative action debates, leading some minority students to
believe there are fewer opportunities at the schools, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A continuation of that trend could hold broader implications.
``Students who are from minority groups are more likely to serve
minority groups,'' she said. ``In addition, there is a feeling a
diverse student body is considered a good learning experience for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andrew Frantz, the associate dean of Columbia University's
College of Physicians and Surgeons, said that there were a little
more than 3,000 applicants for 150 spots last year at his college,
a decline of more than a 1,000 since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Frantz noted that applications also rose and fell during the
1970s and 1980s, usually in stride with the economy. He said he was
not alarmed because there is hardly a shortage of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the boom we've had since 1995 has encouraged people to
think they can make more money elsewhere,'' Frantz said. ``I'm
being partly facetious but I do suspect it has something to do with
the economic boom, and if and when our next recession comes we will
see an increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordon Cohen, president of the American Association of Medical
Colleges, agreed that the economy may explain the trend but also
attributed it to the growth of managed care. ``It's hard to argue
that it is not playing some role,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Pisano, a spokeswoman for the American Association of
Health Plans, a trade group based in Washington that represents
1,000 managed care organizations, said blaming managed care was
``too simplistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a transition going on from the old system to the new
system and I think people who want medicine as a career will not be
daunted by the challenges,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pisano suggested an oversupply of doctors as another factor.
The Journal of the American Medical Association last year reported
that one quarter of physicians who recently completed residency
training reported difficulty in finding employment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
