<HEADLINE>
FASTER NEW YORK-TO-BOSTON TRAINS SEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to take a sting out of the delay in the
Northeast Corridor high-speed rail line, Amtrak officials promised
Wednesday that travelers will have a somewhat speedier ride between
Boston and New York City in January, when the line is fully
electrified.
</P>
<P>
   The electrified service, which now run only between New York and
New Haven, will be completed soon after the New Year and will shave
48 minutes to an hour and 40 minutes off the Boston-New York trip,
Amtrak President George Warrington told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The high-speed line, which will shorten the Boston-New York trip
to about 3 hours, and the New York-Washington route to about 2
hours, will be delayed until spring because of mechanical troubles
with the new trains, Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   The wheels are scraping against the tracks, presenting a
maintenance headache, but not a safety problem, said Jacques
Lapare, president of the Montreal-based Bombardier Transportation,
North America, one of the two companies building equipment for the
high-speed line.
</P>
<P>
   While travelers are being mollified, the consortium building the
high-speed trains is being punished. For every day Bombardier and
the France-based ALSTOM are late, they will have to pay a fine of
up to $270,000, Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   The delay is embarrassing to Amtrak, which has been touting the
fast, luxurious new line. But waiting is preferable to rushing
ahead with a substandard system, Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about taking the time necessary to make the trains
right,'' Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   While testing the French-modeled trains in Pueblo, Colo.,
manufacturers found that too much pressure was being put on the
wheels when the trains sped around the curves of the American
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanics have to fiddle with the suspension systems to create
more ``give'' for the wheels, so they do not scape the tracks,
Lapare said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delay is unfortunate, but not unusual when new technology
is being introduced into a new environment,'' Lapare said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim RePass, president of the National Corridors Initiative that
has been pushing hard for a high-speed line for a decade, lauded
Warrington for making ``a good management decision, instead of a
political decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better to delay the system and have it work right, rather than
meet a deadline that's media-driven,'' said RePass, who was a
management consultant before heading the advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Amtrak nor Bombardier officials would say which of the
two firms in the consortium would have to pay the fines, although
ALSTOM is responsible for the train construction, said Amtrak
spokesman Rick Remington.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of how to apportion the penalty burden is something
that ``will be worked out within the consortium,'' said Lapare of
Bombardier.
</P>
<P>
   The fine, which will range from $1,000 to $13,500 per day for
each of the 20 train sets ordered, will not be determined until the
fixed trains are delivered and the financial damage is assessed,
Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   The other elements of Amtrak's $2.6 billion project are on track
and will be delivered as scheduled, Warrington said. Improvements
to the lines, including repairs of bridges and replacement of
wooden ties with concrete ties, will be done this year, Remington
said.
</P>
<P>
   Once electrification of the remaining segment of the New
York-Boston line is finished by early January, Amtrak will run four
round-trip trains per day, Warrington said.
</P>
<P>
   On slower trains that make four stops and now chug for well over
five hours between New York and Boston, the time would be shortened
to about three hours and 50 minutes. When the high-speed train is
introduced later in the spring, the time will be cut to three
hours, Remington said.
</P>
<P>
   The new trains have been operating at 165 miles per hour in
testing but will operate at only 150 miles per hour once put to
use, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Warrington said he could not estimate how much the delay would
cost Amtrak in operating revenues. But he insisted that Amtrak
would ``more than close any kind of revenue loss'' with a series of
unspecified commercial projects.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to detail the plans, but said Amtrak would not sell
any of its assets.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Amtrak has generated cash through arrangements such
as selling its rights-of-way to fiber optic cable providers, a deal
under which fiber optics companies pay Amtrak to lay cables
alongside the tracks. Amtrak also has an exclusive concessions deal
with Pepsi-Cola, Remington said.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1996, Amtrak pulled in $90 million through such
agreements, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
