<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WAKE OF CORRUPTION CASE, U.S. FOCUSES ON AID TO RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration said on Wednesday it
wants assurances that international financial aid already sent to
Russia has not been lost to corruption, but stopped short of
calling for a halt in future loans to Moscow from the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to defend the administration's policy of supporting aid
to Russia _ and to defuse an issue that could have political
ramifications for Vice President Al Gore _ Treasury Department
officials and John D. Podesta, the White House chief of staff, said
the administration wanted to be certain that no money loaned to
Russia by the IMF had been moved surreptitiously out of the
country. They were responding to reports of alleged money
laundering in which billions of dollars were sent by Russians
through the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that the IMF money is going to
reform-oriented projects,'' Podesta said Wednesday in an appearance
at the National Press Club. ``The IMF, in its latest lending, has
instituted additional safeguards, but we want an accounting of the
ways the IMF money has been spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous investigations of monetary fund loans to Russia have
found no evidence that the money had been misused, and Justice
Department officials have told their counterparts at the Treasury
Department that they have no evidence that the money laundering
investigation involves the proceeds of IMF loans. Officials at the
IMF on Wednesday repeated that they have no evidence of any misuse
of loans to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's wait and see what the facts are,'' Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear how much new evidence the administration hopes
to assemble. Officials at the monetary fund said they have not
undertaken new studies of how Russia has used past loan proceeds
since news of the money laundering investigation broke on Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the monetary fund has had some serious problems with
Russia, including questions about whether the Russian central bank
used transactions with an offshore affiliate known as Fimaco to
deceive the IMF about the country's financial condition. The fund
is now waiting for a follow-up report on the Fimaco case from the
accounting firm of PriceWaterhouseCoopers on a separate matter that
looks at the Central Bank and its affiliates in Britain, France and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the IMF is conducting a routine review of its
current lending agreement, which was signed last July.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is eligible for $4.5 billion in loans from the fund over
the next year and a half, of which $640 million was disbursed as a
first installment in July. The next installment, probably of
roughly the same size, is scheduled to be released in the next
several months. Like the first installment, the next one is
intended to help repay previous loans, and will simply be
transferred from one IMF account to another without entering the
Russian banking system. Russia already owes the fund about $16
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers said in an interview
published Wednesday by USA Today that the ``United States will not
support disbursement'' of the next loan installment to Russia from
the monetary fund ``without adequate safeguards to assure that any
funds disbursed are used properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials said Summers was not implying _ as the
headline on the USA Today story suggested _ that the United States
was ready to block the next loan installment.
</P>
<P>
   It would be ``premature to make any judgments as to whether
Russia will meet the conditions'' for the loan, said Michelle
Smith, a spokeswoman for the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   The statements suggested that the administration wanted to
express concern about the possibility that the international aid
had been misappropriated without changing its policy toward Moscow
as Russia struggles to continue its rocky transformation toward
democratic capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators are looking into the movement of at least
$4.2 billion from Russia through the Bank of New York over the past
18 months. However, some investigators estimate that as much as $10
billion may have flowed through the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have said the money might have come from some
combination of organized crime, corporate embezzlement and
political graft. Given the sums of money involved, there has been
speculation that some of the money might have come directly or
indirectly from international aid packages, of which the loans from
the IMF are the largest component.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of hard evidence, Republicans in Congress have
used the case to raise questions about the administration's policy
of granting aid to Russia, and to renew their attacks on the
monetary fund as inefficient and perhaps unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals in the presidential race have also used the case to
attack Gore, who long prided himself on his role in helping to
manage the administration's Russia policy.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Russian officials denounced reports that they might
have misused the international aid. Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
said the reports came from people ``who do not want our country to
take on its role in the world as a great power.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Livshits, Russia's ambassador to the Group of Eight
industrial nations, said the previous studies by the monetary fund
and PriceWaterhouseCoopers showed no misuse of money and that he
did ``not understand this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem in resolving the questions lies with the way
the monetary fund operates. Until now, money loaned by the IMF to
Russia has typically gone into the Russian Central Bank. Although
agreements between the monetary fund and its borrowers include
economic benchmarks that the country must meet to qualify for
further aid, they do not specify precisely how the money is to be
used.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the money becomes intermingled with the borrowing
country's other foreign currency reserves, making it all but
impossible to trace where any particular dollar or euro or ruble
might go.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large it goes to the central banks, and it's their
money to use appropriately,'' said William Murray, a spokesman for
the monetary fund. ``We do not earmark _ we don't say, `Of this $1
billion, $600 million has to go to pension subsidies.' We don't
track individual transactions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
