<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNATIONAL-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia senator slams FALN releases
 &HT;    By Don Melvin and Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Criticizing President Clinton's decision to grant
amnesty to 16 Puerto Rican nationalists, Sen. Paul Coverdell
(R-Ga.) said Wednesday that he will hold hearings on the
administration's policy toward terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations terrorism
subcommittee, has expressed outrage over Clinton's decision to
commute the sentences of 16 Puerto Rican nationalists jailed for
their involvement with FALN, the Armed Forces of National
Liberation, a militant group calling for Puerto Rican independence.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell said the group was responsible for 100 bombings, six
deaths and 130 injuries. None of those whose sentence Clinton
proposed for commutation, however, was convicted of killing or
injuring anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this administration setting a new standard that only
successful terrorists should be punished?'' Coverdell wrote in a
letter to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings are scheduled for Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   CARE aid in East Timor reminder of challenges there
</P>
<P>
   While a referendum on independence this week sparked optimism in
East Timor, Atlanta-based CARE USA supplied a reminder of some of
the challenges that still face the Asian island.
</P>
<P>
   CARE is distributing food to about half the 53,000 people
displaced by recent conflict between forces in favor of
independence and those supporting continued ties to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families that have been displaced by the conflict are almost
entirely dependent on host villages for food, water and shelter,
but these villages are still recovering themselves from a severe
drought, a national economic downturn and then the unrest in the
province,'' said Isam Ghanim, CARE USA's regional director for Asia
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The western half of Timor, formerly called Netherlands Timor,
became part of Indonesia in 1949. The eastern half remained a
province of Portugal until 1975, when it was occupied by Indonesia
_ an annexation never recognized by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of East Timor voted this week on whether to become
independent, but the results may not be announced until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Monsoon flooding strikes early in India
</P>
<P>
   CARE USA is trying to ease a crisis in India, where monsoons
have hit early and hard, causing flooding that has affected 5
million people through displacement or disease, said Bob LaPrade,
CARE USA's deputy director for Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   CARE is feeding about 80,000 families _ about 1 million people _
in Bihar, India's poorest state.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have large tracts of land that are little seas with tiny
little islands,'' said LaPrade, who recently returned to Atlanta
after inspecting the area.
</P>
<P>
   While the flooding this year is severe, LaPrade noted that there
was severe flooding last year in nearby Bangladesh. Deforestation
has exacerbated the problem, and the expanding population has
forced people to live in flood-prone areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human suffering is increasing, actually, each year,'' he
said. ``The International community needs to start looking at this
as a larger problem, a regional problem.'' Early warning systems
and perhaps a system of dams may be needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmaker returns from Congo visit
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Cynthia McKinney has returned from a mission to the
Democratic Republic of Congo during which she visited local
hospitals and met with President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney joined efforts by Atlanta Hawks player Dikembe Mutombo
to improve health care. The basketball player has created the
Dikembe Mutombo Foundation, which is building a hospital in the
capital, Kinshasa. During her visit, McKinney saw children being
vaccinated against polio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Republic of Congo has 10 million children who
need to be vaccinated against this disease,'' she said. ``Our goal
is to replace fatal gunshots with life-saving polio shots. I think
we are accomplishing that goal, but so much more needs to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   N. Ireland official honored
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie ``Mo'' Mowlam, the British secretary of state for
Northern Ireland, is being honored in Atlanta this week. The
American Political Science Association gave her its Hubert H.
Humphrey award for her career in public service.
</P>
<P>
   Mowlam, educated in the United States, was appointed in 1997 and
played a key role in securing the Good Friday Agreement that is
supposed to end the conflict in Northern Ireland. In 1998, she
walked into the Maze prison in Belfast to negotiate with convicted
killers and other criminals. The agreement, however, has been in
danger recently of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
