<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TRUANCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUANTS TO GET QUICK TRIP TO `Y' COUNSELORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Tracking down truant public school students was the
easy part for police last year. But with no place to bring them,
officers could do little more than jot down names, scold the
students _ and let them go.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in October, youngsters between the ages of 12 and 15
had better beware: Police will haul those playing hooky to one of
nine truancy centers being created in YMCAs throughout the city.
Teachers and parents will be called. Schoolwork will be done. And
if students don't shape up, they could be assigned a probation
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might make me not skip school,'' admitted Josh Currivan,
14. He will be a freshman at West Roxbury High School when classes
begin next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has ever stopped me when I played hooky last year, and
I never got in trouble for it,'' Currivan said. ``If they pulled
you over and arrested you, that might work. But a lot of kids just
do what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement of the truancy centers follows two
years of successful efforts to slow rampant truancy in the city's
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Overall daily attendance rose 1.3 percent to 91.8 percent in the
past year. And the number of chronically absent students _ those
with more than 15 absences _ declined 12 percent in the last two
years, school officials said. Two years ago, more than 25 percent
of schoolchildren missed three or more weeks of classes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while daily attendance at high schools increased nearly
two percentage points last year, chronic truancy by older students
remains troublesome and among the worst in the country. Boston high
school students miss 28 days a year, four days more than the
average of the country's 10 largest cities, according to a 1997
report for the Boston schools by Bain &AMP; Company, a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The number may be even greater, as students report a regular
practice of showing up for homeroom _ often fourth period in high
school _ and then leaving. Because attendance is based on being
present in homeroom, some students know they can be counted and
then disappear.
</P>
<P>
   The new truancy centers probably won't help those high school
students, since those over 15 have the right to drop out and police
cannot force them to attend school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a long way to go with high schools,'' said city
Superintendent Thomas Payzant.
</P>
<P>
   While many students play hooky simply because they don't want to
go to school, others stay home to work or care for siblings. Still
other students have said they are afraid of violence in schools or
of being hurt while walking to school. The end result is students
who fall too far behind in coursework and fail or drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Last year police wrote up some 1,000 students they found
lingering around the city during weekly truancy sweeps. But the
students soon learned they would not be returned to schools because
they lacked the resources to handle them.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach, made possible in part with a $300,000 grant
from the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, will have police pick up
students and take them to the nearest YMCA. There, YMCA officials
will meet with students and decide whether they need a stern
warning or more complex services.
</P>
</TEXT>
