<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKERS-GORE (Washington) _ Despite his emphasis on workplace
issues and his backing from several labor groups, Vice President Al
Gore trails Texas Gov. George W. Bush among working Americans, who
give the vice president little credit for the booming economy. A
Rutgers-University of Connecticut poll shows Bush beating Gore 49
percent to 34 percent. By MARK HELM. (Also filed in the ``w''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLONING-TEXAS (Houston) _ Texas A&AMP;M scientists on Thursday will
unveil a calf cloned from a 21-year-old bull that performed in the
Houston rodeo and appeared on the ``David Letterman Show.'' Named
Second Chance because the original animal, now dead, was known as
Chance, the 3-week-old calf has significant implications for the
Texas cattle industry and A&AMP;M's effort to clone a mixed-breed
collie. By TODD ACKERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-AUDIT (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas state auditor blasts
the state's alternative education programs _ where violent students
are supposed to be banished _ saying schools too often don't send
violent students to them, student performance is not tracked and
minorities, special education students and students at risk of
dropping out are disproportionately placed in these programs. By
KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas agency in charge of
implementing the sweeping overhaul of welfare has put hundreds of
millions of dollars at risk because of improper monitoring and
oversight, according to a new state audit. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-INS (Brownsville, Texas) _ INS Commissioner Doris
Meissner talks about progress made since the Operation Rio Grande
crackdown on illegal immigration along the Rio Grande began two
years ago. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-BELL-ATLANTIC (Albany, N.Y.) _ AT&AMP;T and Bell Atlantic
executives trade accusations in the battle over long-distance
service in New York state. Bell Atlantic is seeking federal
permission to invade AT&AMP;T's long-distance market, which it cannot
do until the local telecommunications market is open for
competition. By JOHN CAHER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BEST-BUY-MUSIC (Houston) _ Best Buy, the Minneapolis-based
retail giant, has come up with a marketing program _ called Find
'Em First _ that helps young musicians. ``That Find 'Em First
commercial has given me tremendous national exposure,'' says
musician Mary Cutrufello, who released her first CD last year and
who is featured in a Best Buy commercial. By GREG HASSELL. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Houston Astros and New York Mets wrap
up a three-game series at tonight in the Astrodome. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BKN-COMETS (New York) _ Advance on the Women's National
Basketball Association Championship Series between the Houston
Comets and the New York Liberty. By W.H. STICKNEY.
</P>
