<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-BUDGET-TAXES-ART-NYT &LR;      09-01 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-TAXES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PODESTA URGES GOP TO END `PHONY DEBATE' ON TAX BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: CORRECTS day in lede to Wednesday. ) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House chief of staff on Wednesday urged
the Republican majority in Congress to send President Clinton its
$792 billion tax cut bill so that he could promptly veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the tax measure early last month but lawmakers
have refrained from forwarding it to the White House, where it
faces certain rejection. Republicans have been stumping across the
country for their tax plan during the current congressional recess,
hoping to generate public support. Clinton and his aides have taken
every opportunity to criticize the proposal as an unwarranted
windfall for the rich and a threat to the booming American economy.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Podesta, the White House chief of staff, pleaded with
the GOP leadership Thursday morning to release the bill ``so we
don't have to keep fooling around with the phony debate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to veto it,'' Podesta said in an appearance at the
National Press Club. ``So send it down to us so that we can veto it
and then move forward, putting first things first and seeing
whether we can find some bipartisan agreement on these other major
budget questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and members of Congress have been out of Washington for
the past two weeks and there has been no movement on this year's
tax-and-spending debate beyond the occasional rhetorical salvo like
the one fired Thursday morning by Podesta. Congressional officials
said Thursday that the leadership intends to send the tax-cut bill
to the White House by the middle of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is clearly spoiling for the fight over taxes and
spending to resume. Polling and political experience have persuaded
the president and his advisers that they hold the high ground of
public opinion in the looming struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has argued that projected federal budget surpluses
should not be given away in the form of tax cuts but rather
``invested'' in education, technology, the environment and an
expansion of Medicare benefits to include prescription-drug
coverage for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinarily camera-shy Podesta took advantage of a relatively
news-free week in Washington to venture out of his West Wing office
to attend a crowded news conference at the Press Club. In his
prepared remarks, he complained about Republican plans to pay for
their tax cut in part through what he called ``devastating''
reductions in the administration's proposed federal spending for
research and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a 19th century budget for a 21st century economy,''
Podesta said of the Republican spending plan. ``One has to wonder
whether the people designing these budgets spent too much time
watching Fred Flintstone and not enough time watching the
Jetsons.''
</P>
<P>
   Podesta said that Congress had cut the administration's request
for civilian research and development spending by $1.8 billion from
roughly $38 billion and had cut $1 billion from the
administration's proposed $13.6 billion for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration. Republicans also blocked a
proposed $200 million increase in funding for the National Science
Foundation, Podesta complained.
</P>
<P>
   He said that, until now, American science and technology have
traditionally enjoyed strong bipartisan support in Washington.
Congress has long lavished substantial funding on the American
space program, medical research, fundamental science and advanced
military technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this year, the Republican-led Congress _ to make room for
their risky tax plan _ is playing politics with science and
technology funding,'' Podesta said. ``They have proposed deep cuts
in many important research programs. And in so doing, they are
threatening the potential progress of innovation in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Morra, spokeswoman for the House Appropriations
Committee, said that the White House was indulging in the luxury of
sniping from the sidelines while congressional appropriators tried
to devise a budget beneath stringent spending limits decreed in the
1997 balanced budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week another Cabinet officer or White House official
complains about some part of the budget we've underfunded,'' Ms.
Morra said. ``We've done the best we can to prioritize spending
under very tight caps.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the administration's budget submission in January
included $42 billion in tax increases and user-fee increases that
Congress rejected, money that is not available for new spending on
research, technology or anything else. In addition, the
administration is preparing to submit emergency supplemental
spending requests for Kosovo, the Middle East and disaster relief
for Turkey without specifying how they should be paid for, Ms.
Morra noted.
</P>
<P>
   She said that many of the research accounts that were cut were
contained in the appropriations bill for the departments of
Veterans Affairs and Housing and Urban Development that also
includes money for Nasa, the National Science Foundation and the
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morra said that a majority of the committee decided to
increase spending on veterans' health programs substantially,
requiring offsetting reductions in research programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about prioritizing,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
