<SLUG> BC-CD-CHRISTINA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTINA AGUILERA CD IS WORTH YOUR ALLOWANCE
</HEADLINE>
 AGUILERA-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, no, I thought, not another one.
</P>
<P>
   This was a couple of weeks ago, as Christina Aguilera's ``Genie
in a Bottle'' began to pretty well take over the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Cute song, good chorus, but man _ how many young pop singers are
we going to throw against the wall to see who sticks? And then
Aguilera came to Six Flags in Arlington to play that End of Summer
Bash and was, according to our reviewer Malcolm Mayhew,
overshadowed by Run-D.M.C.
</P>
<P>
   If we're to believe my buddy Malcolm, Aguilera _ an 18-year-old
from Pittsburgh first heard on the soundtrack to ``Mulan'' _ cannot
sing live. Or dance very well. And I always believe Malcolm, as
should you.
</P>
<P>
   So I wasn't looking to be that impressed by her self-named
12-track CD. At all. Another anonymous bit of disposable candy-pop
by yet another cute kid.
</P>
<P>
   But Christina Aguilera is a pleasant, if modest, surprise.
Although nobody will ever confuse the material here with truly
great pop music, and it's repetitive on more than a few occasions,
and it does include two songs from the queen of schmaltz, Diane
Warren, it's far from all bad.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the (relative) maturity of Aguilera's voice
puts her at least one cut above her closest rival, the omnipresent
Britney Spears. There are no rap interludes and very little Latin
influence; those looking for a hip-hop/pop/Latin CD reminiscent of
Jennifer Lopez's can look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   What the CD offers is pure pop _ danceable stuff, torch ballads,
medium-tempo cuts, and it shows that if given a little time to
mature, Aguilera might (just might) be capable of some good, adult
pop music somewhere down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reflection'' from the ``Mulan'' soundtrack is here, but the
best songs are ``Come on Over (All I Want Is You)'' and ``Love Will
Find a Way,'' both uptempo numbers with a bit of R&AMP;B slinkiness.
The arrangements are nice and simple, the hooks memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilera's voice shows some nice maturity on these tracks, as it
does on ``Reflection.'' She may never be more than a one-hit
wonder, but right now Aguilera is OK. Whether she will develop into
something more than a flash in the pan who does a couple of songs
to prerecorded tracks at a pop radio station-sponsored show is
anyone's guess. I wouldn't bet on it, but I wouldn't be totally
surprised, either.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
