<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NONCOMPETE AGREEMENTS' AREN'T FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ If professional football were like many
businesses, Neil Smith and Dale Carter would have signed noncompete
agreements with the Kansas City Chiefs and been forced to sit out a
season before playing with the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   They also might have had to excuse themselves when the Broncos
studied Chiefs' films because they knew Chiefs' secrets.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't, of course. They took their talents and knowledge to
the Broncos and used them from day one. (No jokes, please, from
Smith or Carter detractors.)
</P>
<P>
   Contrast their full-speed-ahead job changes with recent movement
in another industry _ moves that led to a breach of contract
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   One Kansas City area advertising agency, Barkley Evergreen &AMP;
Partners, is suing another, Sullivan Higdon &AMP; Sink, for inducing
three employees to violate their noncompete agreements with Barkley
Evergreen. In other words, Sullivan Higdon this summer hired three
men who previously worked together at Barkley Evergreen.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the outcome of this agency vs. agency lawsuit,
Barkley Evergreen still could go after the individuals for
noncompete contract violations. It's a kind of legal action that's
repeated daily in courtrooms nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Call me mystified.
</P>
<P>
   Confidentiality agreements I understand. It really wouldn't be
nice for the guy who knows Campbell's recipe for tomato soup to
hand it over to rival Heinz. Granted, nice is sometimes different
from business reality, but I see fairness and logic in trying to
prevent blatant trade-secret leaks.
</P>
<P>
   But noncompete agreements? Workers have jumped ship for better
offers as long as there has been more than one candle maker in
town. The soup guy doesn't make the move as a blank slate.
</P>
<P>
   If you're good at what you do, if a competitor makes you a
better offer, if a client wants to follow you to the new place _
well, isn't that what business competition is all about?
</P>
<P>
   Inducing a fellow worker to change jobs or inducing a client to
change companies is not an easy thing. There's no lasso or
bullwhip. There's free choice. There can be counteroffers. The free
market says the best person or best product wins.
</P>
<P>
   A typical noncompete agreement _ once limited to top management
but now sought from other workers _ prohibits an employee from
competing with an employer for a year after leaving that
employment. Typically, the agreements say a worker won't call on
the employer's customers. Some agreements also say a worker won't
raid the employer's talent.
</P>
<P>
   These contracts are hard to enforce. Violation allegations
usually come through the grapevine. Verification is difficult. It
comes down to arguments of coincidence vs. inducement.
</P>
<P>
   There may be valid reasons for noncompete pacts to exist, but
I'd bet some companies are rethinking the time and expense involved
in trying to enforce them. They may see it's more efficient to
focus on attracting and keeping the best talent than chasing after
the ones that left.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, an industry leader doesn't have to panic if an
also-ran competitor hires someone away. Copiers are just that.
Copiers. Remember who had the benefits of the employee's work
first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7784 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HILLARY-ENTHUSIASM-BO     09-01 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-ENTHUSIASM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTATERS CURIOUS, NOT IMPRESSED, BY HARD-TRAVELING HILLARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKANEATELES, N.Y. _ Edward G. Mogren, a retired manufacturing
manager, got up from his front porch to see what ``all the
commotion'' was down the street. It was Chelsea Clinton heading
into the town library.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other residents of this scenic lakeside village,
the 78-year-old Mogren wasn't passing up the chance to see Chelsea,
President Clinton or first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While Mogren said Mrs. Clinton's decision to vacation here is
politically ``so obvious,'' he did give her some credit over her
likely Republican opponent, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
``She has crisscrossed the state, and I don't think Giuliani can
say that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mogren doesn't like the Clintons' politics and won't vote
for Mrs. Clinton if she runs for the US Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wrong of her to think that she can become a
representative for the state of New York when her entire knowledge
of it has been acquired in a few months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first family arrival on Monday for a five-day vacation
_ after a nine-day stay on Martha's Vineyard and a weekend in the
Hamptons _ even their political enemies have rolled out the welcome
mat.
</P>
<P>
   The village mayor, Don Price, a Republican, Wednesday presented
the president and Mrs. Clinton with a painting of the lake and a
box of postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Though Republicans outnumber Democrats better than 2-to-1 in
this town of 2,700 people (with 4,800 more in surrounding areas),
residents have lined up outside restaurants and shops the Clintons
haven't even visited, hoping they will.
</P>
<P>
   But, whether that enthusiasm will translate into actual votes
for Mrs. Clinton is less clear. With polls showing her either
locked in a statistical deadheat or slightly trailing Giuliani,
political analysts say her chances of winning the seat held by
Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the Democrat who is retiring,
could hinge on a strong showing in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, the spokesman for Mrs. Clinton's Senate
exploratory committee, tried to knock down any political connection
to the trip. ``She's not looking at this visit in a political
context,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton Wednesday she was having such a ``great time'' in
the Finger Lakes region that she had called her mother the night
before. ``It reminds me so much of where I spent my childhood,
because I spent every summer at the little lake in northeast
Pennsylvania,'' she said. ``The nights were cool, and the mornings
were cool, and it warmed up. It's my favorite kind of weather. It's
so nostalgic.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mrs. Clinton running strong among voters in New York City
and Giuliani more favorable to those in the surrounding suburbs,
the first lady must capture about 40 percent of the vote upstate,
said John Zogby, a pollster for the Utica-based Zogby
International.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton and her family on Monday visited the State Fair in
nearby Syracuse, a rite of passage for New York politicians. After
spending Tuesday out of public view, she and the president stopped
at a coffee shop Wednesday and toured several museums that were on
Mrs. Clinton's Saving America's Treasures tour last year. Wednesday
night, they had dinner with Mark Gearan, a Massachusetts native,
former head of the Peace Corps, and now president of Hobart and
William Smith Colleges in Geneva, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, they are scheduled to attend a $250-per-person
fund-raiser for Mrs. Clinton's exploratory committee and later a
$1,000-per-person reception at Mulrooney's Restaurant in Syracuse,
all part of the $600,000 she hopes to have raised for her campaign
before returning to Washington Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Miringoff, director of the Marist Institute for Public
Opinion in Poughkeepsie, which has been polling voters on her
Senate campaign, said Mrs. Clinton needs to settle on finding a
house to wear down her carpetbagger image.
</P>
<P>
   ``By flying in and out, she simply underscores the fact that
she's not from New York, and establishing residency, in a symbolic
way, says she is,'' Miringoff said. But once Mrs. Clinton does put
down roots in New York, he said, ``the first question people are
going to ask is, `Is this Splitsville?' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's why, Miringoff said, ``we've seen this very visible
effort on the part of the Clintons to show this is merely her
moving to New York to establish herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Zimmerman, a political science professor at the State
Univeristy of New York in Albany, said, ``It is very important for
her to have the president's support, and to show she is a good,
devoted wife and now she's got a devoted husband.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the streets of Skaneateles, being the first family cuts
both ways.
</P>
<P>
   John Angyal, owner of Johnny Angel's Heavenly Hamburgers,
renamed a $3.50 grilled baloney and cheese sandwich ``the Hillary
special _ mostly baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   But Angyal, a Republican who says he ``would never vote'' for
Mrs. Clinton, is nonetheless miffed at Doug Clark, owner of Doug's
Fish Fry just three doors down. Clark had told a reporter he would
refuse to serve the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lied to the American people,'' Clark said Wednesday. ``He
pointed his finger and said he did not have sex with that woman.
He's a disgrace to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Angyal shot back, ``They are still the president and first
lady . . . They've been elected twice. Somebody likes them,
apparently many people do, which is what I've seen over the last
couple of days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
