<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-GREENWAY02-COX     09-01 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-GREENWAY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia dips into reserves to buy land along Chattahoochee River
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes said Wednesday he expects to tap into
state reserve funds to buy environmentally sensitive land along the
Chattahoochee River as part of his effort to preserve one-fifth of
the state's undeveloped areas for green space.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes wouldn't say how much money he will ask the state to ante
up for the project, but said he's likely to ``pay for it with
cash'' next year out of Georgia's reserve funds or from a $582
million surplus from the fiscal year that ended in June.
</P>
<P>
   The money would help start a second phase of an aggressive
land-buy for a 180-mile park along the river, stretching from Helen
to Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be the major green space,'' Barnes said of the
river corridor spanning the top half of the state. ``This is good
business sense. It's not a bunch of tree-huggers ... saying we
shouldn't have any growth whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia also is planning two state parks along the river between
Atlanta and Columbus to provide natural areas for ``underserved''
portions of the state, said Department of Natural Resources
Commissioner Lonice Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike others that focus on lodges and golf courses, the new
2,000-to-3,000-acre parks will be built around nature trails, bike
paths and interpretive centers, Barrett said. About $10 million has
been set aside for the undisclosed sites.
</P>
<P>
   As for the governor's riverfront proposal, ``There couldn't be
better timing,'' said Don Stahle, development director of the Trust
for Public Land's southeast regional office in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   River frontage along the Chattahoochee costs about $1 million a
mile, according to state figures. About 166 miles _ representing
land along both sides of the river _ are still targeted for
acquisition as part of the river protection plan Barnes launched
this year in conjunction with the Trust and a host of private
donors.
</P>
<P>
   That initiative has raised about $23 million in private
donations to match about $75 million from state and federal funds,
a private foundation grant and other sources to buy at least 75
miles of the river corridor, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to talk about specific dollar amounts, Barnes
said he wants the state to be ``a major participant'' in the second
phase of the river protection effort, indicating a commitment
possibly larger than the $15 million Georgia allocated earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting the Chattahoochee corridor, Barnes said, is key to
his plan to push the state's fast-growing counties to allot 20
percent of their undeveloped land for a series of greenbelts.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes unveiled his 20 percent plan at a national governor's
conference last month. He said county officials would have to
include the green space goal in their land use plans or risk losing
state money for infrastructure _ everything from roads and bridges
to schools and water-sewer expansion. He proposed incentives _
including state money to help with the land purchases _ for local
governments to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the green space plan _ who grumble that it could be
an expensive infringement on private property rights _ cautioned
against dipping into reserves that hedge against economic
downturns. But they gave guarded approval to use state surplus
money for the river program.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly what we should be doing,'' said state Senate
Minority Leader Eric Johnson (R-Savannah). ``Obviously, there's a
limit to how much we can spend, but it's a legitimate use of tax
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the surplus, Johnson said, is preferable to levying new
taxes. But local governments, not just the state and private
donors, should have a say in what properties are acquired, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
