<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7788 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-600(2TA     09-01 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-600(2TAKES)(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALISTINIAN-ISRAELI TALKS STALL ON EVE OF ALBRIGHT'S ARRIVAL  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ By very early Thursday morning, the optimism of
Israeli and Palistinian negotiators had soured, and it seemed
unlikely that a new agreement would be reached before Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright's arrival in Egypt later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   A signing ceremony that was to be held in Alexandria on Thursday
afternoon was put in doubt after Israelis and Palestinians played a
classic hand of Middle Eastern brinkmanship that ended in a
stand-off on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It remained possible that negotiations over the peace
initiative, which were on-again, off-again all Wednesday, would
resume after sunrise Thursday morning. But after a tense day of
diplomatic double-dare, it seemed equally possible that the
Israelis and the Palestinians would not resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, it would be left to Albright _ perhaps alongside
Hosni Mubarak, the Egyptian president _ to help them finalize a new
plan for reviving the frozen peace process. State Department
officials have said that Albright would be reluctant to mediate the
fine-point details of the current dispute, preferring that the
parties work those out themselves.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat cut short a trip to the
Netherlands to fly to Alexandria late Wednesday before hopes had
been dashed that negotiations would begin again. A late-night
Israeli security Cabinet meeting ended without public comment, but
a spokesman for Prime Minister Ehud Barak said he was not
optimistic that there would be any celebrations _ or summits _ in
Egypt later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the prime minister go to Alexandria?'' asked David Zisso,
a spokesman for Barak. ``Alexandria was meant to be the place for
the signing of an agreement, so right now it doesn't seem that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to measure whether Wednesday was a day of
last-minute panic or a genuine crisis. Each side, and particularly
the Palestinians, seemed to need to show its people that it was
prepared to sweat out every last detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the endgame and closing process of these agreements,
there is always room for a crisis,'' a top Israeli diplomat said
late Wednesday afternoon. ``We are in such a situation now.''
</P>
<P>
   After 15 rounds of negotiations between the Israelis and the
Palestinians last month, it all come down to one last sticking
point: 50 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   When the Israelis pushed away from the negotiating table on
Wednesday, that was what separated them from the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the Israelis had agreed to release 350 prisoners
while the Palestinians wanted 400. The Israelis, who have insisted
that they would not release any prisoner who had murdered an
Israeli, said they couldn't find 50 more who met their criteria for
release.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, according to an Israeli negotiator, said:
``Invent them.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides were using Albright's trip to the region as an
artificial deadline for completing a detailed plan for carrying out
the U.S.-brokered Wye River memorandum. The Wye agreement is a
land-for-security deal that was sealed in Wye, Md., last fall only
to be suspended by the previous Israeli government of former Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations last month represented the first peacemaking
efforts of Ehud Barak. The new prime minister has an ambitious plan
to forge a broad peace in the region. With the Palestinians, he
aims to complete a final status peace agreement by the end of next
year. Reviving the Wye agreement is, for the Palestinians, a
prerequisite first step to final status talks, which were to have
started Wednesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Since Barak is determined to make concrete achievements quickly
and Arafat wants a deal, it seemed unlikely that they would allow
the issue of 50 prisoners to sour their infant relationship.
Modifying the Wye agreement is baby play compared with tackling the
sensitive final status issues, like Jerusalem and the return of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But a top Israeli negotiator said Wednesday of the Palestinians,
``I've come to believe that for them the prisoners are almost more
important than the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly that is the issue that resonates with the Palestinian
public, especially the mothers whose sons are behind bars for
political or terrorist acts committed before the Palestine
Liberation Organization gave up its violent struggle against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiators have not forgotten a sobering moment
that followed the completion of the Wye memorandum last fall. The
villa of Mahmoud Abbas _ the second in command of the Palestinian
Authority _ was pelted with stones because some Palestinians
believed that their leaders had failed them.
</P>
<P>
   The peace memorandum, while calling for Israel's release of 750
prisoners, did not specify that they should be what the
Palestinians call political prisoners. And indeed, as they feared
he would, Netanyahu took advantage of that vagueness by releasing
many common criminals before the agreement was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that the stoning incident made such a
strong impression on the Palestinian leadership that they now want
to make it as clear as possible to their people that they have held
their ground this time.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israelis, too, would suffer a backlash if they seemed
too lenient in their prisoner release policy. The issue is
particularly jarring to some Israelis when set against the backdrop
of a stabbing murder that took place last weekend. A young Orthodox
Jewish couple was killed in a nature reserve near Meggido, and
police suspected a nationalist motive, if not terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the military arm of Hamas, an Islamic
fundamentalist group, claimed responsibility for the killings.
</P>
<P>
   A large front-page advertisement in the Haaretz newspaper on
Wednesday said, ``Death trap! The terrorists butcher a young
student couple and in return Ehud Barak releases terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   After a long sleepless night of talks on Tuesday, Israeli and
Palestinians negotiators felt close enough to a deal to schedule
separate press briefings for Wednesday afternoon. Then the air of
crisis descended.
</P>
<P>
   After waiting hours for Saeb Erekat, the Palestinian negotiator,
to descend to the lobby of the King David Hotel, Israeli
journalists received a pager message from their prime minister's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government considered the negotiations over, the
message said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Thursday, the message continued, the Israelis would
begin carrying out the Wye agreement unilaterally, sticking very
literally to the text. Everything negotiated over the last month _
from specifics on prisoners to those on opening the seaport _ would
be thrown out, an official said later.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat fumbled through a short statement. ``I would urge my
colleagues in the Israeli government to refrain from any
insinuations and threats,'' he said. ``We will continue to try to
bridge the gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Gilad Sher, Israel's lead negotiator, was pulling away
from the table, the conversations were continuing behind closed
doors at the King David. When Sher left, Haim Ramon, a minister in
the prime minister's office, quietly took his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything will be resolved,'' Ramon said as he left hours
later.
</P>
<P>
   By early Thursday morning, that seemed less clear. Negotiators
were supposed to return to the table after a late-night Israeli
security Cabinet meeting finished, but they later dropped those
plans as Israelis decided that there was nothing to talk about
until the Palestinians accepted their final compromise position.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Israeli and Palestinian negotiators have held 15 rounds
of fairly amicable and constructive talks since the beginning of
August. Both sides said the discussions had gone a long way toward
rebuilding trust that had frayed during the tense years of the
Netanyahu administration.
</P>
<P>
   In these talks, they hammered out a four-page draft document
muddily entitled: ``Memorandum on Implementation Timeline of
Outstanding Commitments of Agreements Signed, and the Resumption of
Permanent Status Negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   What it amounted to was a reiteration of and plan for carrying
out the Wye memorandum _ almost a year after it was signed amid
great ceremony at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In this tense conflict, where every interim agreement is
celebrated as a break-through achievement, the agreement is often
not enough and has to be re-negotiated to hold up.
</P>
<P>
   The re-negotiation process is often confusing, even to the
participants.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, watching Arab television in Saudi Arabia, reportedly
balked when Erekat announced last month that he had achieved an
agreement with Israel for the opening of a seaport in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   He reportedly shook his head, asking aides what kind of an
achievement that could be when the seaport had already been
guaranteed by Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   In the new memorandum for carrying out the Wye memorandum, the
Israelis and the Palestinians set a timetable for Israeli
withdrawals from the West Bank _ the first pullback would take
place immediately as would the first release of prisoners. They
also defined the steps toward opening safe passage routes between
Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the prisoners, they squabbled Wednesday over the
wording of the text. The Israelis wanted to say that a framework
for a final peace agreement would be accomplished within six months
of the memorandum's signing.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians wanted to include a specific date.
</P>
<P>
   That reminded some experts here of a wording crisis that almost
derailed the Hebron agreement in the mid 1990s. The Israelis wanted
the document to call for an Israeli pullback in April of 1998,
while the Israelis insisted it should be in the fall. The
negotiations were at a breaking point when the late King Hussein of
Jordan offered a compromise: ``mid-year.''
</P>
<P>
   The pullback still hasn't happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
