</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-LETTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY'S FATHER RECEIVES DONATION REQUEST FROM CLINTON
COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A form letter seeking contributions was sent by
President Clinton's legal defense fund to the father of Monica
Lewinsky, whose affair with the president led to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's father, Dr. Bernard Lewinsky, a Los Angeles
oncologist, was not happy to get the request. ``Return to sender,''
he wrote on the envelope. ``You must be morons to send me this
letter!''
</P>
<P>
   An image of the front of the envelope was published in The Los
Angeles Times on Wednesday along with a brief account of the
episode. The report did not say when Lewinsky received the letter,
and he could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Lucas, a Washington lawyer with the firm of Arnold &AMP;
Porter who serves as outside counsel to the fund, said Lewinsky's
name might have appeared on a list of prospective donors that was
obtained by the fund's direct-mail consultant. ``We certainly are
sensitive to Dr. Lewinsky's reaction,'' Lucas said. ``It was
inadvertent.''
</P>
<P>
   According to figures recently released by the fund, $5.3 million
of the $10.5 million in legal bills accumulated by Clinton and his
wife, Hillary, have been paid.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7792 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WACO-ZEALOTS-2TAKES-N     09-01 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-ZEALOTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARS OF EFFORT BY TWO MEN SPURRED RE-EXAMINATION OF WACO 
</HEADLINE>
  (With WACO-INQUIRY) 
(th) 
 By JIM YARDLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Michael McNulty and David Hardy refused to let go. In
the six years since the Branch Davidian compound went up in flames
on April 19, 1993, the two men have waged an obsessive quest to
discredit the official account of what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Espousing views popular with many right-wing groups, McNulty in
particular has blamed federal agents for the deaths of the Branch
Davidian leader, David Koresh, and about 80 of his followers, a
position many critics regard as anti-government propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   He and Hardy, however, regard as government propaganda the
official explanation that Koresh and his followers carried out a
suicide pact by setting fire to the compound and shooting
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Now the fire at the compound, near Waco, has emerged again as a
national issue. As much as anyone else, McNulty and Hardy helped
set in motion the events that have led Attorney General Janet Reno
to consider an independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona lawyer, Hardy, 48, requested, then sued the federal
government for documents and evidence related to Waco. Both men
pushed the Texas Rangers to launch an inquiry into the evidence
under state control.
</P>
<P>
   They also fed information to lawyers representing the families
of deceased Branch Davidians in a wrongful death lawsuit. And
McNulty, 53, a documentary filmmaker from Colorado, toured the
state evidence lockers four times, unearthing what he says are
potentially flammable devices capable of starting a fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike and Dave deserve the lion's share of the credit for
coming up with the evidence,'' said Joe Phillips, a lawyer for the
Branch Davidian families in the wrongful death lawsuit, scheduled
to go to trial in federal court in Waco on Oct. 18. ``They've been
working on this for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Waco is looming as a potential embarrassment for the
FBI and the Justice Department. Congress is issuing subpoenas for
evidence and witnesses in response to disclosures that the FBI,
despite denials to the contrary, used pyrotechnic tear-gas
canisters on the morning of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of it all, McNulty and Hardy are enjoying a broad
new forum, appearing regularly on radio and television programs.
McNulty often uses his media appearances to promote his forthcoming
documentary, ``Waco: A New Revelation.'' In an interview on Court
TV, McNulty waved a handwritten sign with a 1-800 number for the
film.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, say they fear that, while the two men may have
come up with some information worth examining, they have spread
unsubstantiated and misleading information as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really unfortunate,'' said Mark Potok, a spokesman for
the Southern Poverty Law Center, a group that monitors the militia
movement and other anti-government groups. ``This has given
credence to the rest of McNulty's view, which are unsupported.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews, McNulty said he and Hardy met about a
decade ago in Southern California, either at a pistol range ``or
some kind of gun get-together.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, a former Interior Department lawyer in Washington, said
he returned home to Arizona in 1990 and soon entered private
practice, writing law review articles, including one he co-authored
tracing the legal history of militias.
</P>
<P>
   He described himself as ``an obsessive compulsive'' whose pet
issue is his belief that law enforcement is becoming dangerously
militaristic. Convinced that Waco proved his point, Hardy filed
eight Freedom of Information requests against the Justice
Department and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   He got nowhere in what became a paper trail of fruitless
correspondence with government officials. In 1996, Hardy filed a
lawsuit, claiming that the government was stonewalling his efforts
to obtain documents and evidence that belonged in the public
domain.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, much of that evidence was stored in Austin,
inside the evidence rooms of the Texas Department of Public Safety.
In the aftermath of the Branch Davidian fire, the Texas Rangers
were asked to investigate and collect crime scene evidence, and
they kept it.
</P>
<P>
   But when Hardy requested evidence from the Rangers under the
state's public records act, he was told that only the Justice
Department could authorize access to the evidence. When he wrote to
the Justice Department, he was told that the evidence was under the
control of the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, a federal judge agreed that Hardy had been wrongly
denied documents and, as a penalty, awarded him more than $32,000
in legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of his paper trail, Hardy wrote one letter to Texas
officials bluntly saying, ``Did it ever occur to you guys that
you're being set up?''
</P>
<P>
   McNulty, meanwhile, was pushing on a different front. Until the
early 1990s, he sold insurance in Southern California, living
comfortably until he said the national company he represented
decided to uproot from the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   A Vietnam veteran who converted 20 years ago from Catholicism to
the Mormon faith, McNulty said the Branch Davidian fire reminded
him of a bloody incident in Mormon history, the Haun's Mill
Massacre of 1838. In that episode, a mob in Missouri herded Mormons
into a grist mill and shot them to death. Ultimately, the Mormons,
led by Joseph Smith, were ordered out of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   With his insurance business in disarray, McNulty said he became
increasingly consumed with Waco, obtaining evidence such as a copy
of an infrared videotape of the incident. He moved his wife and
five children to Ft. Collins, Colo., and became a producer on a
documentary, ``Waco: Rules of Engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   A critical assessment of the role of the government, the film
was nominated for an Academy Award. The executive producer, Dan
Gifford, filed a lawsuit against McNulty, accusing him of selling a
pirated and re-edited version of the film, though the dispute was
settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Oscar nomination (the film did not win), ``Rules of
Engagement'' also was criticized for failing to accurately present
evidence that placed the government in a favorable light, and for
numerous inaccuracies.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Mark Pitcavage, a historian who specializes in
right-wing extremist groups and operates The Militia Watchdog Web
site, said the film made McNulty a celebrity among followers of
right-wing, anti-government groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Waco documentary was highly publicized, but the
inaccuracies were not,'' Pitcavage said. ``I don't think the
McNulty Waco documentary could even remotely be considered
objective.''
</P>
<P>
   McNulty strongly denied that he is ``an anti-government type''
and stoutly defends the findings in his first documentary. He
claimed that his upcoming film will detail his claims that federal
agents started the Waco fire and killed the Branch Davidian
followers. He has supported himself during his investigations with
payments from his film company, MGA Films, and with stipends paid
by plaintiff's lawyers in the civil case.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
