<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS &LR;      09-01 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST TALKS NARROW FOCUS ON LAND-FOR-SECURITY ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ A long night of tense Israeli-Palestinian negotiations
ended in Jerusalem without a deal, but both sides held out hope
that a signing ceremony would still take place in Egypt Thursday
for a new agreement to move the long-stalled peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators were trying to hammer out the details of a
revised ``land for security'' accord before US Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright's arrival in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Albright landed in Morocco Wednesday and is expected to arrive
in Alexandria, Egypt, Thursday for the possible signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we will reach a conclusion of the present negotiations
within the next few hours,'' Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat told
reporters in the Netherlands just before the talks had concluded
and before he cut short a trip to the Hague, reportedly to head to
Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Israeli Cabinet minister Chaim Ramon emerged from a
Jerusalem hotel after a negotiating session between Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators, saying, ``Everything will be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   The key sticking point, negotiators on both sides said, was the
issue of the release of Palestinian prisoners currently held in
Israeli prisons.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides were said to be locked in debate over the fate of
fewer than 50 prisoners. The Israelis agreed to release some 350,
and the Palestinians were demanding at least 400 be freed. The
Palestinians originally requested 650 be release.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye River deal, brokered by President Clinton last October
at the Wye River plantation in Maryland, was signed in Washington
by Arafat and then Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. It
called for Israel to hand over land to the Palestinians in return
for security measures and for Israel to release Palestinian
prisoners. But Netanyahu froze the interim agreement only two
months later after handing over just two percent of West Bank land
to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The release of prisoners is an emotional issue for both sides.
The Palestinians say these are prisoners of war and political
detainees who fought for the Palestinian cause. Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak has insisted he will not violate an Israeli vow
not to release prisoners who have taken part in the killing of
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's intense public sentiment against releasing Palestinians
with Israeli ``blood on their hands,'' as Barak has put it, ran
higher than usual with news Wednesday that the military wing of the
radical Islamic group Hamas claimed responsibility for killing an
Israeli couple hiking in the West Bank Monday and pledged to
continue its attacks against Israeli and Jewish interests around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye deal, as originally conceived, called for the release of
750 Palestinian prisoners and a three-stage Israeli troop
withdrawal from a further 13 percent of the West Bank in return for
further security steps to be taken by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   If that 13 percent of the West Bank is ceded to the Palestinian
Authority, the Palestinians would be left with full or partial
control of roughly 40 percent of the West Bank, which Israel
captured from Jordan in the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   Under the emerging agreement, the next Israeli troop pullback
would begin in the next few days, to be followed by a second one
Nov. 15 and a third one at the end of the year or the beginning of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides appeared to have compromised on a new deadline for
a final peace agreement, which would tackle the thorny issues of
the status of Jerusalem, the fate of millions of Palestinian
refugees, and the distribution of water resources.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has expressed an eagerness to implement the Wye agreement
and reportedly is willing to accept Arafat's cherished goal of an
independent Palestinian state in an effort to move quickly to
resolving the so-called ``final status'' issues.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he believes the longer the interim agreements
take, the more likely the process is to hit snags along the way
that will further delay the final peace. But to avoid that, Barak
has said he wants to fold the final phases of troop withdrawals in
the Wye agreement into the final status talks. It is a move that
the Palestinians are leery of because they believe it could in the
end leave them with less West Bank land and a weaker bargaining
position.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is hopeful the agreement will be reached so she can
avoid playing the role of mediator and instead concentrate on
laying the groundwork for a resumption of direct talks between
Israel and Syria over the Golan Heights. After stopping in Israel
and in Palestinian Authority administered territories on Friday,
Albright is expected to visit Syria on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Syrian negotiating track was derailed in 1996.
Syrians claim the Israelis agreed in principle to a full withdrawal
from the Golan Heights, which they captured in 1967, but Israel
disputes that.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Foley said, ``It's an obstacle
that can be overcome pecisely because both sides want to overcome
it. They want to be back at the table instead of talking about how
they negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Egypt was preparing the presidential palace in
Alexandria for the signing ceremony. But despite what promises to
be a day of fanfare and handshakes, there are many skeptics in the
Arab world. They wonder how the truly tough issues, such as the
status of Jerusalem and the fate of Palestinian refugees, can be
negotiated if the two sides can get held up over 50 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Sayed al Said, political analyst and director of the Al
Ahram Strategic Center in Cairo, said, ``Forgive me for not joining
in the euphoria. But why should a deal that has already been agreed
upon need to be revised? These are games that the Israelis are
playing. I don't see it as a positive sign of movement forward, but
as a worrisome sign over how things will go in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Esmat Abdel Meguid, secretary general of the Cairo-based
Arab League, who was instrumental in the early phase of acheving a
peace agreement between Egypt and Israel in 1979, was less
pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know something about dealing with the Israelis,'' he said.
``Barak still has a chance to prove himself. His predecessor was a
hopeless case, but we still have hope for Barak. But he must move
quickly and stop playing these games.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
