<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAMING THE NEW WONDERS OF THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his forthcoming ``Seven Wonders: Timeless Tools for a
Healthier Planet'' (Sierra Club; $12.95),  &UR; John Ryan &LR;  of the
Northwest Environmental Watch finds the following causes for seven
different kinds of joy:
</P>
<P>
   The bicycle, the condom, the ceiling fan, the clothesline, Thai
food, the public library and the ladybug.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CELEBRITY TREATMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jenny Craig &LR;  announced Wednesday &LR;   &LR; that  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  has
been on its diet program since early this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky is not getting services free in exchange for the
announcement and is being treated like any other client, said Craig
spokesman  &UR; Brian Luscomb &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Barbra Streisand &LR; , on the other hand, seems to think that
playing the stock market is like making reservations in a
restaurant: A star can get in where everyone else is turned away.
</P>
<P>
   A recent item mentioned Streisand's contacting thestreet.com
before it went public and requesting (successfully) the privilege
of getting in on the friends and family list before the public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Business Week reports that Streisand called E-Loan, a
Dublin outfit that went public earlier this year, and made the same
request. The head of the company was ``so thrilled _ and impressed
with Streisand's gumption to call people she has never met,'' that
she put her on the friends and family list, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
   Personals called Streisand's spokesman _ who wished to be
identified only as spokesman _ to inquire about the buy and whether
she'd been using her clout with other companies as well. ``A lot of
companies simulate these stories in order to attract investors,''
he said. ``I imagine that she makes some inquiries, but it's not
like she spends all her time on it. Everything is misleading. Her
first job is being an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said the story about Streisand and thestreet.com
wasn't true; CEO  &UR; Kevin English &LR;  confirmed to Personals that it
was.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RULES AND REGULATIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - A judge has ruled that  &UR; Alan Edelstein &LR; , a disgruntled
employee who has been giving muckraker  &UR; Michael Moore &LR;  a dose of
his own medicine _ calling him, e-mailing him, following him around
with a bullhorn and challenging him in public _ must stand trial
for harassment. Moore had filed charges against Edelstein, whose
lawyer told MSNBC that the issue was ``freedom of speech. Michael
Moore's behavior has been the epitome of hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   - The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences is suing
Sotheby's for emblazoning its catalog covers with images of Oscars
for sale. All of the Oscars auctioned off in recent years were from
before 1951, when the winners began signing agreements not to sell
their prizes. The academy allows the pre-1951 sales but is upset
about the use of the Oscar images for what it deems advertising.
The lawsuit claims that Sotheby's infringed upon the academy's
copyright and trademark by using the statue ``as a pawn for
commerce,'' lawyer  &UR; David Quinto &LR;  told the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   - According to a Marin County police report forwarded by
 &UR; Robert Steiner &LR; , ``Someone in the 5800 block of Nave Drive reported
that a man (was) screaming behind Nave Bowl. An officer contacted a
religious group involved in a group hug.'' In additional mysterious
crime news, a woman accused of trespassing in a store was seen a
few minutes later outside wearing ``a tribal hat and pink jeans.''
Can anyone describe a Marin tribal hat?
</P>
<P>
   - A reader who stays regularly at the Harvard Club in Manhattan
forwards a memo dated Jan. 1, 1999: ``Although the House Committee
has decided to end the experiment in casual dress at breakfast in
the Main Dining Room, a discreet display of business papers will
continue to be permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MMM-MMM-GOOD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Francis Rigney &LR;  forwards the entire ingredient list for Sweet
'n Low Li'l Bits Chocolately Candies, as printed in the Nutrition
Action Newsletter:
</P>
<P>
   Maltitol, salatrim, cocoa powder, sodium caseinate, gum arabic,
Yellow 5, Yellow 6, Red 40, Blue 1, Blue 2, titanium dioxide,
lecithin, acesulfame K, natural flavor, artificial flavor, carnauba
wax, beeswax and confectionary glaze.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw (Queen Elizabeth II) once, in Vancouver. She was driving
by about 10 feet away, and she was in a beautiful dove gray outfit
and pillbox hat, and she was doing her wave and she looked like a
real nice lady. I hope she is. Because, for all her faults, we love
our Queen, as W.S. Gilbert said. Also, she looked very Jewish to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; David Mamet &LR;  in the Telegraph of London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
