NYT-09-01-99 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7795 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WACO-ZEALOTS-2NDTAKE-     09-01 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-ZEALOTS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOUSTON: civil case. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until just over a year ago neither McNulty nor Hardy had been
able to collect much, if any, evidence from the government. Then,
McNulty began telephoning assistant U.S. Attorney Bill Johnston,
one of the federal prosecutors in Waco who had handled the criminal
case against several Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very skeptical when he heard who I was,'' McNulty said.
</P>
<P>
   McNulty placed scores of calls to Johnston, prodding and
cajoling for access to the locked state evidence room. Toward the
end of 1998, McNulty said he confronted Johnston with copies of
records from Fort Bragg, N.C., that suggested members of an elite
military unit were present at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he had obtained the documents from Hardy. Unlike the
Justice Department or the FBI, the military responded quickly to
Hardy's FOIA requests, providing documents that detailed how
members of the elite Delta Force military unit were present at Waco
during the day of the fire. The Pentagon now says there were three
Delta Force soldiers present as observers.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Johnston decided that McNulty should be allowed to
peruse the evidence with a camera crew. He said he contacted the
head of the Justice Department's office of public relations in
Washington for final approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be a party to even the appearance of
stonewalling him,'' said Johnston. ``Ultimately, this is the
public's evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Between November 1998 and March 1999, McNulty said he paid four
visits to the evidence rooms in Austin, always escorted by at least
one Texas Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   He said he found at least four projectiles that he believes are
pyrotechnic and other potentially flammable devices known as
``flashbangs'' that had been discovered inside the compound.
</P>
<P>
   On one visit, McNulty said he brought a munitions expert to take
samples for later testing. He said he reported his finding to the
Texas Rangers, noting that some evidence listed on the inventory
was missing or mislabeled.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, the lawyer, meanwhile, had continued to try to get both
the Rangers and the Justice Department to grant his FOIA requests.
Frustrated, he said he made copies of his correspondence and sent
them to Jerry Patterson, a former Texas state senator. Patterson is
a conservative Republican who authored the state's 1995 concealed
weapons law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm the go-to-guy for the black helicopter crowd,''
joked Patterson, now a lobbyist in Austin. He said Hardy's Texas
friends ``called me up and said the Department of Public Safety has
possession of evidence that brings a whole new light on what
happened at Waco. We feared that the evidence will be turned over
to the Department of Justice never to see the light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said he first contacted Clay Johnson, chief of staff
for Gov. George W. Bush, who referred him to James B. Francis Jr.,
chairman of the Texas Department of Public Safety. He said he met
with Francis, explaining that neither the Rangers nor the Justice
Department claimed to control access to the Waco evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mess,'' Francis said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Department of Public Safety began an
investigation of the evidence in the storage rooms. Francis said
the Rangers would complete their report in time to respond to a
congressional subpoena for a hearing planned for Sept. 7. The
department also asked U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. to
take possession of all evidence related to the Branch Davidian
case, much of which remains with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   In a sweeping order issued earlier this month, Smith ordered the
government to hand over everything ``in any way relevant'' to the
Branch Davidian siege and subsequent fire. The judge noted that the
plaintiffs in the civil case ``have a right to seek access'' to the
evidence. On Tuesday, Justice Department lawyers sought to block
Smith's order and maintain control of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the court decided that the evidence was worth taking
control of, it was the triggering device of everything that has
happened since then,'' Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   Francis would only speak in broad terms about the evidence, but
he said there were eyewitness accounts and photographs that raised
questions about whether the Delta Force participated at Waco. By
law, military units such as the Delta Force are allowed to observe
but not operate inside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are military guys in body armor and in face paint,''
said Francis, describing pieces of evidence. ``It might be
significant evidence when all the facts come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless Smith grants a continuance, the wrongful death lawsuit
will begin in about a month. Michael Caddell, the lead plaintiff's
lawyer, said that government lawyers have stymied all of his
discovery attempts since the case was filed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Caddell said he has had to rely on McNulty and Hardy to
provide him with copies of documents and evidence. He estimated
that he has paid McNulty between $40,000 and $50,000 for services
such as testing of evidence, lab work and investigative help.
</P>
<P>
   ``His access to information has been critical,'' Caddell said.
``He has looked at information that Congress didn't see and the FBI
didn't see or didn't want to acknowledge.'' Without evidence
provided to him by McNulty and Hardy, Caddell said Smith might have
granted a government motion to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, everything was pushed fully into the public eye last
week when a former senior FBI official told Lee Hancock of the The
Dallas Morning News that two potentially flammable tear-gas
projectiles were used at Waco by an FBI hostage rescue team on the
same morning as the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Danny Coulson, said he learned of the canisters in
recent weeks after years in which FBI officials, including himself,
had denied that any potentially flammable projectiles were used. He
declined to say how he heard of the canisters. Justice Department
officials initially denied Coulson's claims but later recanted.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview earlier this week, Coulson reiterated his belief
that the canisters were not connected to fire. On that day, FBI
agents using tanks had sprayed tear gas into the Branch Davidian
compound in an attempt to forcibly end the siege.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance as it applies to the fire is none,'' Coulson
said. ``The real significance is that the attorney general and many
FBI officials, including myself, have given statements that
pyrotechnic devices were not used, and now we know that is an
error. It goes to the very credibility of the inquiry conducted by
the Department of Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   For critics of McNulty and Hardy, the new admissions by the
government are particularly frustrating. ``They deserve a little
bit of credit,'' Pitcavage said grudgingly. ``But you wish that
someone else had discovered this stuff instead. These guys have
ulterior motives.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hardy and McNulty make no apologies. ``I'm downright happy
about it,'' said Hardy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
