u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-01 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFFERSON SEES RESILIENCY IN PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Shawn Jefferson has been around the NFL for nine
years. He's survived a lot. He went to a Super Bowl with the San
Diego Chargers in 1994, lost, then watched the almost instant
dismantling of that team in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Former Chargers and present Detroit Lions coach Bobby Ross told
Jefferson he had to let him go because the Chargers were making
room for younger receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, Bill Parcells scooped up Jefferson, signing him
to a four-year deal that expires at the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson understands how teams can win and he also understands
how teams can die quickly. He's witnessed a subtle but constant
erosion of the Patriots since they appeared in the 1997 Super Bowl,
but he insists it isn't San Diego all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' said Jefferson, who has played in 127 of a possible
128 regular-season games and who last year averaged 22.7 yards per
reception. ``This team has shown tremendous resiliency over the
years. We've lost players and we've lost games, but we always come
back strong and show what we are. I think we're a tough team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson said the Patriots, who Thursday night will attempt to
atone for the 45-14 shellacking they received from the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers last Saturday in their exhibition finale against the
Carolina Panthers in Charlotte, N.C., have shown a different
attitude in practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out the other day and started to fly around,'' he
said. ``We can't let one bad game in the preseason bother us. I
think we have to take these setbacks, learn from them, and then
don't make the same mistakes over and over again. I think we've
done that in the past and we'll do it again. It shows that you're a
mature team if you can do that. I think we've done that time and
time again. When we take a blow, we don't sulk. We'll be ready to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson said that while the Patriots need to finish the
exhibition season strongly, ``We're just prepping for the regular
season. We don't have all of our packages in yet. Preseason is a
warmup for the regular season. Teams look at preseason in different
ways. You call it dress rehearsal. Whatever. We have to execute.
But I think we're way ahead of where we were last year. We've shown
improvement every game. Our offense has the potential to be
something special. It's the second year of this system and I think
we all feel comfortable in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, who was mentioned this offseason as a player who
might be cut for salary cap purposes or traded to fill another need
_ the Jets reportedly were ready to pounce if he were cut _ has
survived and is still starting opposite Terry Glenn. At the age of
30, Jefferson remains a deep threat. If you watch Jefferson's deep
routes, he's open more often than not. Yet in the Patriots'
offense, he's often no more than a decoy. He gets the defensive
backs to chase him downfield to open things up for Ben Coates or so
Drew Bledsoe can throw to Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   It's a role Jefferson has accepted without much fanfare. He's
also taken on the role of mentor to younger receivers such as Glenn
and Tony Simmons, and still he works on scout teams _ playing the
part of the opponent's top receiver _ so he can prepare starting
cornerbacks Ty Law and Steve Israel. Jefferson does it without
being asked, setting an example for younger players.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Jefferson understands this may be his final year
in New England. The team didn't address his contract status in the
offseason. He will earn a nice salary of $1.8 million this season,
and given the fact he's done quite well in the stock market, he
will likely never have to worry about money.
</P>
<P>
   There was a brief recent conversation with Patriots owner Bob
Kraft, who expressed gratitude to Jefferson for what he's meant to
the team, but whether that translates into a contract extension
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson has watched as other veterans _ such as Todd Collins,
Willie Clay, Dave Wohlabaugh, and Tom Tupa _ have gone elsewhere.
Jefferson said he's not afraid of relocating and told personnel
head Bobby Grier before camp started that he would accept whatever
was best for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Even recently, there were reports of the Dallas Cowboys looking
into a deal for Jefferson, but the Patriots wanted linebacker
Randall Godfrey in return so nothing came of it.
</P>
<P>
   Grier then announced that none of his receivers were going to be
traded, fearing what occurred last season when three of them
(Jefferson not included) went down in a 10-day period.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's top asset is durability. The only game he's ever
missed was his second as a Patriot, in 1996, when Parcells kept him
out because he had suffered a mild concussion the week before in
Miami. Jefferson is still upset that Parcells cost him a perfect
attendance record and ended his consecutive-game streak at 81.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of this, it's obvious the Patriots are grooming Simmons
to take Jefferson's place. Jefferson understands this and just
keeps showing up for work, helping Simmons and anyone else who
needs it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had people who helped me when I was coming up with
Houston,'' said Jefferson. ``Warren Moon took me aside and showed
me how to play and how to act. I always remembered that, and I'll
always be willing to do that for a young kid. We're a team. I've
been around a long time. If I can help a kid be better, that's good
for our team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
