A7810 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-KIDS-STRAWPOLLS-TEX     09-01 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-STRAWPOLLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAW POLLS TEST CANDIDATES' SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSAMY BROWN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   News of the GOP straw poll taken Aug. 14 in Ames, Iowa, made the
front pages of newspapers nationwide in the past couple of weeks.
The poll marked an important early step in a long process to select
our next president. The series of events will ends with the
national election Nov. 4, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Many straw polls occur in the presidential election process, but
few draw as much attention as the one in Iowa; the next big one is
a Democratic Party straw poll in Orlando, Fla., in December.
</P>
<P>
   What is a straw poll?
</P>
<P>
   A straw poll tests the opinions of a group of voters. In this
case, members of the Republican Party voted on their choice for the
top candidate for president from among the individuals in their
party. This year, a record 24,000 Iowans voted in this event.
</P>
<P>
   The event, which has been held since 1979, is not like a regular
election in that voting is not free _ the price to participate is
$25. The money raised goes toward the Republican Party of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Any political party can hold straw polls. The outcome of a straw
poll has no official effect on the presidential race. The poll
serves only as an early test of a candidate's organization in a
particular state, and it generates a lot of coverage by the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say that the event serves as more of a popularity
contest than an indication of how much support exists for any
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say that voting may be biased because the
candidates' campaigns often provide transportation, food and the
tickets required to take part in the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the name come from?
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of theories on the origin of the name.
</P>
<P>
   One says that taking a straw poll of opinion is kind of like
throwing a handful of straw in the air to see which way the wind
blows it, according to a ``San Francisco Chronicle'' report. The
Iowa Republican Party's Web site credits author John Selden with
writing, ``Take a straw and throw it up into the air _ you may see
by that which way the wind is.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the origin of the word comes from political
tradition. In elections of long ago, each voter would get a piece
of straw and place it in the pile for his or her candidate of
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Why are straw polls taken?
</P>
<P>
   A strong showing in a straw poll, such as the one in Iowa, can
help candidates get attention _ and, they hope, more money for
their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   A poor showing in the poll shows a lack of support for the
candidate. Lamar Alexander's weak standing in the Iowa poll caused
him to drop out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   What are the next steps?
</P>
<P>
   Americans can expect to see the results of new polls practically
every day in the months leading to the election. But the next
serious stage in the race for the presidency involves state
caucuses and primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Then, next summer, delegates from all the states and Washington,
D.C., will come together at the Republican and Democratic
conventions to decide which candidate will be the party's nominee
for president. After that, the real fun begins as the parties
square off against each other in the contest to see who will be
elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Terms to know
</P>
<P>
   Political party: a group that joins together because its members
share many ideas about what the government should do. The main
parties in the United States are:
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party, nicknamed Grand Old Party or GOP. Its symbol
is an elephant.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party. Its symbol is a donkey.
</P>
<P>
   A new independent party, the Reform Party, was begun in 1996 by
Dallas businessman Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Candidate: someone seeking an elected office. Qualifications to
be president are that the man or woman must have been born in
America, be at least age 35 and have lived in the United States for
at least 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates: officials chosen by the public to represent it in
political-party votes.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential primary: statewide elections to select delegates to
the party's national nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   Caucus: a private meeting of political-party members to select
delegates for a state or national nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Project Vote Smart; The Dorsey Dictionary of American
Government and Politics, by Jay M. Shafritz.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
