<HEADER>
A7811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TURTLE-RESCUE-ART-NYT     09-01 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURTLE-RESCUE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEERS SEEK TO PROTECT INJURED TURTLES AND RESCUE THEIR NESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: N.C., S.C., Ga., Fla.) (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EMILY YELLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPSAIL BEACH, N.C. _ During lunch Tuesday at the Topsail Beach
Shop and Grill here, most people were checking with their neighbors
to see how they weathered Hurricane Dennis and the evacuation. But
anyone who walked up to Jean Beasley's table first asked how the
sea turtles fared.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Beasley and the six people at her table, sea turtles are
like family. Everyone at the table spends much of their summer
helping turtles through birth, sickness and even death.
</P>
<P>
   They are among more than 100 volunteers in the Topsail Turtle
Project who patrol the 26-mile-long beach of Topsail Island every
day, all summer, to protect the more than 180 sea turtle nests laid
this season.
</P>
<P>
   And each of them also volunteers at the Karen Beasley Sea Turtle
Rescue and Rehabilitation Center here, named in memory of Ms.
Beasley's daughter, who founded the Topsail Turtle Project. The
hospital is caring for nine injured or ill sea turtles, found along
the beaches of North Carolina, South Carolina and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beasley, 63, a retired teacher, is the director of the
turtle project and of the turtle hospital, as it is called.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers share a love of the big, mysterious, prehistoric
creatures who lumber from the sea every year to burrow nests in the
sand. The female turtles, which are often 200 to 300 pounds, lay a
clutch of about 125 eggs, cover them with mounds of sand and then
amble back into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I first saw a mother turtle come up and nest at the steps of
my house 30 years ago,'' Ms. Beasley said. ``And it was such an
awesome sight that I have been committed to the turtles ever since.
They are such benign, magnificent creatures.''
</P>
<P>
   The turtle eggs hatch about two months after the nest is dug.
The hatchlings then join together in the night to push up the sand
covering them and, guided by the light of the moon, make their way
into the ocean. They go into a ``swimming frenzy'' for a few days
until they reach warmer waters, where they live for their first
year or more.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if everything goes well.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of the hatchlings make it to water, said Terry
Meyer, 42, one of five volunteer coordinators who work with Ms.
Beasley. ``About 1 in 1,000 of those will survive the first year.
And about 1 in 5,000 to 10,000 will reach adulthood, which is
anywhere from 20 to 30 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   There have always been many natural predators, like sharks, in
the sea. In addition, hurricanes threaten the nests of the turtles,
who have a life span of more than 100 years. But in the past few
decades, human activities are what has put the turtles on the verge
of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Beach-front development has thrown off the turtles' nesting
instincts. Lights from houses and businesses sometimes trick the
baby turtles into heading inland instead of into the sea. If they
do not get to the water soon after hatching, they die. And
motorboat propellers and the nets and hooks of commercial fishers
have killed many turtles.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all five species of sea turtles found on the shores of
this country are on the endangered or threatened species lists of
the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beasley, Ms. Meyer and thousands of other volunteers along
the Southeastern coast are determined to make sure the turtles do
not become extinct. In North Carolina, which is the northernmost
region in the United States with sea turtle nests, 21 such
volunteer groups, totaling about 500 people, patrol about 320 miles
of beaches.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina, Georgia, Florida and a few other states have
similar projects, which are mandated and financed by the Federal
Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers sit with the turtles' nests at night when they
look ready to hatch, protecting the hatchlings from natural
predators like ghost crabs.
</P>
<P>
   They ask vacationers unfamiliar with the effects of lights on
the hatchlings to keep their outside lights and beach-front house
lights off at night. They patrol the beaches at dawn looking for
new nests, and then block off the nests so that people will not
inadvertently disturb them. And they teach people about sea
turtles, which are particularly beguiling to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turtles and kids always go together,'' said Ruth Boettcher,
who works for the North Carolina Wildlife Resources Commission as
the North Carolina sea turtle project coordinator, overseeing the
ea turtle protection groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody's curiosity about them is sparked when they are
young, it stays with them,'' Ms. Boettcher said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, preliminary data from the states have shown the
highest number of nests since records have been kept, which is
about the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ms. Beasley said, ``Until we have at least a decade of
growth in the number of nests, I wouldn't say the population has
increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Hurricane Dennis did not seem as threatening as
Hurricane Bonnie last year, the volunteers did not evacuate the
turtles as they did then. Today they hooked up water pumps in the
turtle hospital, which they had disconnected before the storm, and
fed the turtles for the first time since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Ms. Meyer and the other volunteers began checking today on
each of the nests. In a few days, the volunteers will report
</P>
<P>
   to the state on the storm's effect on the nests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turtles teach us that we are just specks in a great big
world,'' Ms. Meyer said. ``Through these turtles, we learn how
important it is to take care of other things in the world besides
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
