<SLUG> BC-MIT-GAS-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAS MAY HAVE COME FROM GROUP'S SUPPLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- MIT is investigating whether the gas that killed a
junior came from ``a community canister'' used by other students,
school officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A school spokesman said campus police had received a tip that
the nitrous oxide that asphyxiated 22-year-old Richard A. Guy,
whose body was found in a dorm room early Tuesday, ``was available
for a certain community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How big that community was, I don't know,'' said Kenneth
Campbell, MIT's spokesman, who offered no other details. ``That's
one of the things that police are looking into.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the information that students other than Guy may have
had access to the nitrous oxide, also known as laughing gas, was
given to police ``presumably by someone in the MIT community.''
</P>
<P>
   The university said its investigation is focusing on who may
have supplied the gas to Guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the investigation is complete, and we fully expect that
to be prompt, we will take whatever action is appropriate based on
that report,'' said Rosalind Williams, MIT's dean of students and
undergraduate studies, noting that inhalation of the gas is
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   MIT also corrected its earlier report that the body of Guy, a
native of Mission Viejo, Calif., was found in his dorm room, which
was on the top or fifth floor of his East Campus residence hall. A
female student found Guy alone in a neighbor's room on the fifth
floor. She had gone there to feed a cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who had the room was not at MIT, so presumably
(Guy) had a key,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   He could not say whether the gas canister contained markings
that would make it easy to trace to its supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Campus police are treating Guy's death as an accident. His body
was discovered with a plastic bag on _ but not over _ his head,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   As the probe into Guy's death continued, students returning to
classes in Cambridge acknowledged that life on a campus where Nobel
laureates teach and the nation's top students learn can be an
academic pressure cooker. But they warned that the tragedy may have
had nothing to do with the advent of another year of classroom
rigors.
</P>
<P>
   And they called the popular image of MIT as a place of students
wearing pocket protectors and staring at computer screens day and
night a one-dimensional caricature.
</P>
<P>
   ``MIT in some ways does pressure its students,'' said Eric J.
Plosky, a columnist for the student newspaper The Tech. ``But how
students respond to it individually does not always a trend make.''
</P>
<P>
   Plosky said a column he wrote earlier this week that implored
MIT students not to wrap themselves too tightly in the cocoon of
academia was written with tongue planted firmly in cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a world outside your MIT course work,'' Plosky wrote.
``Don't neglect it. Entering freshman often succumb to various
kinds of physical and psychological sloth. Immersing themselves in
the celebrated geek culture of MIT, students many times become
completely apathetic about happenings off campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Plosky said that because it is unclear what happened to Guy,
there are no clear conclusions that can be drawn from his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be the last person to say that what happened to
Richard Guy is the result of academic pressure at MIT,'' he said by
telephone from the dormitory where Guy died, and where police
Wednesday were carrying away boxes of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said MIT makes no apologies for the short-term
pressures and demands on campus. It's part of its longtime legacy,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This characteristic of MIT is terribly important in our way of
life here and in our self-identity,'' Williams said. ``That has
real positives and real negatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the negatives are that we have a lot of students here
and they're at an age where there are types of dangerous behavior
that are well-known in this age group.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams said MIT's dropout rate is lower than the national
average and its binge-drinking rate is about half that of the
national norm.
</P>
<P>
   As students made plans for a memorial service for Guy, friends
and associates at his Ames Street dormitory declined to speak to
reporters. Campus officials said they believe Guy's family had
arrived from California to make funeral arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult when someone so young dies,'' said Matthew
McGann, a senior management major and president of MIT's
Undergraduate Association. ``People want to grieve in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   McGann said MIT, mindful of the need to improve life away from
the classroom, has increased funding for student activities
three-fold over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people here _ not by any means the majority _ who
are incredibly devoted to their academics and there are people in
the faculty going for the Nobel Prize, but that is a small
percentage of our population,'' McGann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to have a well-rounded life, and students want to
be involved in things outside of the classroom and the
laboratory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seema Sanzgiri, a premed senior from New Orleans, called MIT's
curriculum challenging but not ``cut-throat competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people do feel a lot of stress here,''
Sanzgiri said. ``Coming from high school the transition is very
hard. MIT does a lot to ease that transition. I think what happered
(to Guy) was just an accident. I don't think it had to do with
academic pressures, especially since the year hasn't even started
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Guy's inhalation of a substance commonly used as a
anesthetic by dentists came a week before classes were to resume.
</P>
<P>
   Pure nitrous oxide dissolves in the bloodstream. It pushes
oxygen out from the blood into the lungs and deprives the brain and
other organs of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kruger, associate executive director of the
Washington-based National Association of Student Personnel
Administrators, said nitrous oxide is hardly the recreational drug
of choice on most college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most students don't know the toxicology of nitrous oxide,''
Kruger said. ``It's one of those invisible things that you don't
smell and can't see and it's very difficult to intervene if someone
is doing this quietly in his room.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, the MIT spokesman, said the death of Guy and the 1997
alcohol overdose of freshman Scott Krueger does not mean MIT has an
unusual problem with substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a couple of people overdose _ one on alcohol and one
on nitrous oxide,'' he said. ``I can't think of that as a
pattern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
