<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARGAIN HUNTING LIFTS MAJOR MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks finished higher Wednesday as bargain hunting
overshadowed interest-rate jitters in advance of fresh statistics
on the tight American job market.
</P>
<P>
   Halting a four-session skid that had lopped nearly 500 points
from last week's record level, the Dow Jones industrial average
gained 108.60 points, or 1 percent, to 10,937.88, paced by a 2
11/16-point jump in IBM which has benefited this week from new
contracts with Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq market and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also
climbed. The Nasdaq market jumped 11.45 points, or 0.4 percent, to
2,750.80. It is now up 25.45 percent for the year. The S&AMP;P 500 rose
10.66 points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,331.07.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to identify sustainable trends in a week like
this,'' said Timothy E. Woolston, a portfolio manager at Boston
Advisors. ``Everybody's waiting for the numbers.'' The job and
earnings report for August is to be published Friday, and on
Thursday the Labor Department is to report on last week's
first-time applications for unemployment insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy E. O'Grady, senior portfolio manager at First Capital
Group in Philadelphia, said, ``Inflation is still a potential
issue, an item to contend with.''
</P>
<P>
   An initial belief that the Federal Reserve's Aug. 24
credit-tightening would be its final one of the year has been
seriously undermined, most recently by Tuesday's survey of
corporate buyers, who reported paying markedly higher prices last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates make stocks less competitive with bonds,
making corporate borrowing more expensive and, for some, more
difficult. Rates were narrowly mixed Wednesday, edging up for
longer-maturity bonds while money rates eased.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks and those of paper and forest products companies
made some of the day's biggest gains, the latter helped by an
upgrade at Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper, one of 23 Dow blue chips to advance, rose 1
9/16, to 48 5/8, while Willamette Industries was up 3 1/2, to 43
1/8, and Fort James, Westvaco, Champion and Weyerhaeuser each rose
more than a point. Georgia Pacific, now up 46 percent so far this
year, climbed 15/16, to 42 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Among the drug makers, Warner-Lambert jumped 2 1/4, to 68 5/8,
and Merck, Bristol-Myers and Schering-Plough posted gains of more
than a point.
</P>
<P>
   Retailing stocks, beaten up of late, rebounded slightly in most
cases, though J.C. Penney surged 1 7/8, to 38 1/8, while Sears lost
5/16, to 37 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T was up 2 3/8, to 47 3/8, and General Electric was up 1 3/8,
to 113 11/16. Intel was another sizable gainer, up 1 1/4, to 83
7/16, after the company introduced a new line of networking chips.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Qualcomm, the cellular company, fell 23 1/2,
to 168 11/16, after an analyst at Everen Securities warned of an
earnings shortfall after meeting with management.
</P>
<P>
   Juniper Networks was another casualty, sliding 24 3/4, to 180
1/4, after registering 5.75 million shares for a secondary
offering, more than half from company officials.
</P>
<P>
   MMC Networks was battered for a second day, losing 4 1/8, to 26
3/4, on top of a 38 percent drop Tuesday after IBM said it would no
longer make products using MMC chips.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover on the New York Stock Exchange was 697.1 million, with
1,715 advancing issues and 1,288 declines. New 52-week lows swamped
new highs, however, 97 to 25.
</P>
<P>
   Major European markets closed about 0.5 percent to 1 percent
higher, but the best overseas gains were 2.1 percent in Tokyo and
3.2 percent in Sao Paulo, Brazil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
