u f BC-PICUTRETEL-BOS &LR;      09-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICUTRETEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDER GAUT REGAINS CONTROL AT TROUBLED PICTURETEL CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PictureTel Corp., once the world's premier maker of
videoconferencing equipment, is brining back one of its founders to
lead its battle against growing competition from Internet-based
technology and service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Norman E. Gaut, 61, who helped get PictureTel launched in 1984
and was chairman and chief executive for 10 years before retiring
last year, said he is resuming those titles ``until I get this
thing in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   He succeeds Bruce R. Bond, 53, a former America Online Inc.
executive who was hired in February 1998 in an effort to turn
around PictureTel's already sagging fortunes. Gaut called Bond's
resignation, submitted on Tuesday, ``a joint decision between the
board and him.'' Picturetel is located in Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Gaut praised Bond, who had been with AT&AMP;T Corp. and US West, for
developing a strong recovery strategy, but said continuing declines
in both sales and earnings forced a change in command.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not overly pleased with the way things were heading,''
said Gaut, who remained a member of PictureTel's board after his
retirement as chairman. ``We were not making any headway in
shareholder value, and there were product issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Those ``product issues'' included an ouburst of customer anger
last spring following shipment of PictureTel's newest
videoconferencing units. The product, named SwiftSite and produced
in a joint venture with Intel Corp., had so many hardware and
software bugs that they had to be recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' Gaut said in a telephone interview, ``we blew
that. In the future we are only going to get products out that are
fully quality assured.''
</P>
<P>
   A SwiftSite upgrade came out in June and the company says it has
shipped 6,000 units _ but after a promotional discount to $4,000
per unit is making no profit on them.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel shares that had traded as high as 43 1/8 in late 1995
and early 1996 have hovered between 5 and 6 for most of the past
year as red ink continued to mount. Following more than a decade of
profitability, PictureTel has been in black during only one of the
past nine quarters and predicts further losses this year.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel shares, traded on Nasdaq, closed at 4 13/16, down
23/32, a 13 percent decline. Bond's resignation was announced after
the close of trading Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the entire videoconferencing market faces an
uncertain future until such generic Internet operating issues as
bandwidth availability are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, rivals including Sony Corp. and Polycom Inc.
are taking advantage of cheap digital technology to produce
``set-top'' units that compete against SwiftSite and undercut the
costly top-of-the-market product line tha established PictureTel's
reputation during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The low end is where the future of this business is,'' said
David Dines, an analyst for Aberdeen Group in Boston. ``PictureTel
leads at the high end, but I see few buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaut said PictureTel's strategy recognizes this. The company
hopes to reestablish itself primarily as a service provider, making
and selling low-cost units but backing them up with broad bandwidth
network connections to ensure high-quality pictures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
