<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DENNIS02-COX     09-01 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENNIS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. island sliced in two by Dennis
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tropical Storm Dennis has stranded 5,000 people on
North Carolina's Hatteras Island, cut in half by pounding waves
that washed away a three-quarter mile section of N.C. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Another 700 people on Ocracoke Island, just south of Hatteras,
are cut off from food and water.
</P>
<P>
   In a symbolic blow to Hatteras, at North Carolina's eastern tip,
the National Park Service has canceled Saturday's plans to relight
the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse at Buxton.
</P>
<P>
   Relocated inland this summer from its perilous perch overlooking
the Atlantic, the historic beacon has survived Dennis, the National
Park Service said.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency crews have mobilized to ferry food, water and other
supplies to Hatteras. But as of Wednesday night, strong winds
prevented state ferry boats from making the 4 1/2-hour trip from
Manns Harbor across the Pamlico Sound to Hatteras Village, at the
island's southern tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for a window for the wind to drop below 25
mph,'' said Donald Chapman, assistant director of the North
Carolina State Shipyard at Manns Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are starting to run low on food and supplies and the
like,'' Chapman said. ``They are without electricity and phones. It
is not life threatening, but it sure is inconvenient for them.''
</P>
<P>
   A Coast Guard helicopter airlifted a pregnant Hatteras Island
woman who went into labor Wednesday. Amber Simerly, 19, was
transported to Albemarle Hospital in Elizabeth City. The hospital
wouldn't release information about Simerly's condition.
</P>
<P>
   After pounding the North Carolina coast Monday, Dennis turned
out to sea and stalled. Tuesday, it began backtracking, lashing the
Outer Banks with gale-force winds and 14-foot waves.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 5,000 residents and tourists stayed on Hatteras
Island after Sunday's evacuation order. They were stranded when
waves dumped sand, and in some places, washed out, the island's
two-lane highway.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a National Guard convoy drove four-wheel-drive
vehicles down N.C. 12 and delivered supplies as far south as Avon.
</P>
<P>
   They were unable to travel farther because waves cut an
8-foot-deep breach between Avon and Buxton, at one of the island's
most narrow stretches.
</P>
<P>
   The sea had washed over the spot as recently as May, but crews
quickly reopened N.C. 12, the island's only north-south road.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis' damage is far more severe. ``One-half to three-quarters
of a mile of paved road has been cut off,'' National Park Service
spokesman Bob Woody said.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency crews' top priority is getting supplies to stranded
people, according to North Carolina's emergency response team. The
next step is getting the people off the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is getting the road clear so we can get some
help to those people,'' said Sgt. Craig Garriss of the North
Carolina Highway Patrol. ``They're in dire need of help.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hatteras Village, ham radio reports indicated extensive
flooding had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   On Ocracoke Island, flooding was widespread and islanders
remained without power Wednesday. But ham radio operator Dale Mutro
said everyone seemed to be getting along all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had a high tide just a little bit ago, and sound-side
flooding is still quite severe,'' Mutro said. ``But it's not as bad
as it was at the height of the storm. With every high tide, the
water's still way on up there.''
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center forecasters said Dennis, once a
Category 2 hurricane, could be downgraded further, but likely would
linger near the North Carolina coast for days, moving to the
southwest without making landfall.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast is distressing to hotels, restaurants and other
northeastern North Carolina businesses counting on a big Labor Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is looking bad; everyone is canceling,'' said Jodi Sherman,
assistant manager of the ocean-front Best Western hotel in Kill
Devil Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to be our last big opportunity to make some
money,'' she said, ``but Dennis the menace took it away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
