<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoky odor prompts return of AirTran flight
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An AirTran Airways DC-9 with 76 passengers and five
crew members bound for Orlando, Fla., on Wednesday returned to
Hartsfield International Airport after members of the flight crew
said they smelled a smoky odor in the cockpit and cabin, the
airline said.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported, and the passengers were put on a
later flight, according to AirTran spokeswoman Carla Maruskin.
``The oxygen masks never came down,'' Maruskin added.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran mechanics inspected the plane to see what may have
caused the smoky odor, but the tests were not complete late
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, flight 357, had reached 4,000 feet after a 10:30 a.m.
departure when the captain said he smelled smoke, according to
AirTran Atlanta station director Curtis Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   A flight attendant also said she smelled smoke in the cabin. No
one saw any smoke, Maruskin said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane landed and parked on a taxiway. The passengers left
the aircraft by flight stairs and were shuttled back to Concourse C
to meet another plane. The passengers were on the tarmac and kept
in a secure area during the transfer, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie White, who was traveling from Chicago for a visit to
Disney World, said she and her husband, nephew and two children
almost boarded the flight after arriving to change planes in
Atlanta. AirTran invited them to take the plane, although they were
booked on a later Orlando flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't because it made no sense to get to the airport ahead
of our luggage and have to wait on it to come on the later plane,''
White said.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about what happened, she said, ``It made me very
nervous. But we have no choice but to go on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
