u f BC-KOREA-BANKS-NYT &LR;      09-01 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREA PLANS HUGE CASH INFUSION FOR INSOLVENT SEOULBANK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Britain)   By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The South Korean government plans to
declare the ailing Seoulbank insolvent on Thursday before injecting
billions of dollars into it after talks to sell it to a foreign
bank broke down, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the government's financial watchdog agency,
the Financial Supervisory Commission, said officials planned to
request the cash infusion at a meeting on Thursday. The
representative did not specify an amount, but Seoulbank said it
expected to receive 4 trillion to 5 trillion won, or $3.4 billion
to $4.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC Holdings PLC, the big British bank, withdrew its $900
million offer for a 70 percent stake in Seoulbank on Tuesday.
Regulators said the talks had broken down because of differences in
the assessment of Seoulbank's bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea made a pledge to the International Monetary Fund in
late 1997 to sell Seoulbank and another ailing institution, Korea
First Bank, to foreign buyers in exchange for a $57 billion bailout
loan. The sales of the two banks are considered litmus tests for
Seoul's willingness to open its financial market to foreign
investors and accept international expertise in a traditionally
closed industry.
</P>
<P>
   The government holds more than a 90 percent stake in both banks
after recapitalizing them early this year, injecting 1.5 trillion
won ($1.27 billion) into each bank. It agreed in December to sell a
51 percent stake in Korea First to Newbridge Capital Ltd. and then
agreed in February to sell the Seoulbank stake to HSBC.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts feared that the failure to sell Seoulbank had set a
negative precedent that would affect negotiations to sell Korea
First.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a possibility that the sales will not take place,''
said Kim Dae Sik, an economics professor at Chung Ang University.
He said potential buyers in the future would raise the same issues
in assessing nonperforming loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiations take a lot of time, and that is what the current
administration does not have,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said that although the government might feel it was losing
money by quickly selling both banks to foreign buyers, such
selloffs would raise foreign investor confidence and reduce South
Korea's financial burdens.
</P>
<P>
   But the government's decision to inject capital into Seoulbank
while holding on to Korea First may be what it wants _ to retain
the banks to foster corporate reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes coordination between banks and the government for
successful restructuring,'' said Chang H. Lee, a senior banking
analyst at Daiwa Securities. ``If Seoul and Korea First banks fall
into the hands of foreign investors, that coordination would be
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that an injection of 4.5 trillion won in public money
would be enough in the short run for the banks to assist in
corporate restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   However, as selloffs fail to materialize, the banks' equity
continues to be eaten up through write-offs of nonperforming loans,
further damaging foreign investor confidence, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace of restructuring has slowed down more than I had
expected,'' said James Han, a bank analyst for Jardine Fleming
Securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
