A7830 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-WELFARE-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      09-01 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT FINDS TEXAS AGENCY PUTTING $830 MILLION IN FEDERAL, STATE
FUNDING AT RISK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A troubled state agency has jeopardized hundreds
of millions of dollars through its lax oversight of locally run
welfare-to-work programs, according to a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state auditor's highly critical report on welfare reform
implementation at the Texas Workforce Commission comes as Texas
increasingly turns to private companies and faith-based groups to
perform government work.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush championed hiring local contractors to carry
out welfare-to-work programs _ such as job placement, counseling,
training and child care _ as part of the state's landmark welfare
reform legislation in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The new audit, however, identifies up to $830 million in federal
and state funding that has been placed at risk because of the
state's inadequate oversight and monitoring of the way contracts
are awarded by 26 new local workforce development boards. Federal
funding is contingent on strict controls and accountability by the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not agree that funds were at risk,'' said Texas
Workforce Commission spokesman Larry Jones. ``We are implementing
virtually all of their recommendations. There are still some
findings with which we do not agree.''
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, financial safeguards at the Texas Workforce
Commission itself were so weak that the agency awarded three
job-training contracts to a Dallas company that declared bankruptcy
just five months later, the auditor's report said.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Medical Assistance Program Advisors Inc., had
contracts to place welfare recipients into jobs in the San Angelo,
Texarkana and Amarillo areas, Jones explained.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that state workers did have to scramble to take over
the program when the company declared bankruptcy last January.
Jones added that private contractors now undergo more rigorous
checks of their financial viability before contracts are awarded.
</P>
<P>
   The state audit said that incident was just one of 13 directly
mishandled by the agency as it awarded local service contracts
under the federal Temporary Assistance for Needy Families, or TANF,
grant. The process ``did not ensure that it paid a fair price for
services or that the bidders were financially sound,'' according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
   Other findings in the audit conclude:
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency certified 16 local workforce boards to dole out
contracts before making certain they were financially ready to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   _ Up to $9.6 million in TANF funds were jeopardized in the 13
employment service contracts directly awarded by the agency.
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency's oversight is inadequate to identify all problems
and some problems are not adequately tracked or resolved when they
are discovered.
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency is not providing timely and responsive technical
assistance to the local boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate the state auditor's work and recommendations on
how to strengthen these local boards,'' said Bush spokesman Ray
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is a leader in shifting workforce development to the
local level and these local boards are a relatively new phenomenon.
. .I think the Workforce Commission has gotten the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Bresette, who analyzes welfare policy at the Center for
Public Policy Priorities, said the findings come as no huge
surprise to those who have watched the agency's rocky past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Texas Workforce Commission has been criticized not
just in this audit but in other circles, budgeting circles, for
appearing not to have adequate methods for tracking and monitoring
these contracts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, however, he pointed out that the commission was
given the enormous task of merging incompatible accounting systems
and even work cultures as part of the state's sweeping welfare
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   The Workforce Commission was created four years ago as the
federal government began giving states more control over the
welfare system. In turn, Bush championed creation of the new agency
to consolidate 28 programs scattered elsewhere and to oversee the
transfer of welfare programs to the local level.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions have sharply attacked the Workforce Commission's
handling of programs that help the poor and the working poor,
especially as private contracting pushes state workers out of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say at this point that it's an agency
that's been beset by trouble since its inception. I'm not saying
they have an easy job, but the facts are the facts,'' said Rick
Levy, a lawyer for the Texas AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   While Jones said the Workforce Commission has successfully moved
51 percent of the welfare population off the roles since 1995, Levy
said it's clear they didn't all land in jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't have adequate information about where those
folks are going, how many of them are working,'' he said. ``The
total focus is the-numbers-off-welfare, but there is a lot more
towards building an economy in Texas that works for everybody than
just playing a numbers game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
