<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SEA TO (NOT SO) SHINING SEA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH MARTIN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For some, nature is a proving ground. Others see
it as a sacred place with special powers than can help us regain
perspective and passion.
</P>
<P>
   Using nature's mirror for reflection into the inner world is an
old and noble genre. Henry David Thoreau wrote brilliantly on the
simple, rustic life in ``Walden''; more recently, Aldo Leopold's
``Sand County Almanac'' is a classic in conservation and seasonal
reflection.
</P>
<P>
   But it can be tricky play, often turning into self-conscious
pontificating and self-absorbed navel-gazing.
</P>
<P>
   Two books reveal the contrasts: ``A Year by the Sea'' would
appear to be headed toward shallow New Age cliches yet is enriched
by mature wisdom and some fine description of the natural world,
while ``Eye on the Sea'' is composed of poorly connected essays and
weak writing. The like-titled books are written by Massachusetts
authors, but that's where the similarities end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Year by the Sea: Thoughts of an Unfinished Woman'' by Joan
Anderson (Doubleday; $22.95) is a memoir about a woman who slows
life's pace by living alone in a Cape Cod cottage. She refuses to
accompany her husband to an out-of-state job and seeks to renew her
love for life.
</P>
<P>
   Though it starts like it might turn into a Lifetime network
victim-of-the-week story, the title by a veteran journalist is
strongly evocative: ``Gently lured by the sea's distant roar, I
begin to stroll to her music. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's use of natural metaphors to describe her inner state
_ though sometimes strained by overreaching _ is often poetic:
``The frothy white caps appear as a ruffled chorus dancing across
the surface of the sea, spitting, hissing, kicking all the way,
acting very much like the woman I'm becoming, not content unless
I'm tickling the rocks, slivering up the shore, embracing
everything in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   A simple existence by the breakers helps her recover her
moorings. Anderson's strong description moves the 196-page book
well beyond familiar territory.
</P>
<P>
   Some may be put off by the flowery style, while others might not
like the almost embarrassingly personal narrative. But it seems to
work well for the genre.
</P>
<P>
   Nature lovers will enjoy the description of how swimming among
seals and staying overnight on an island alone rejuvenated a tired
soul. Our rating: HHH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, it's hard to see how anyone could find much
value in ``Eye on the Sea: Reflections on the Boating Life'' by
Mary Jane Hayes (Breakaway Books; $22).
</P>
<P>
   Hayes is trying to be poetic and ends up being vague. She aims
for wisdom but achieves pedantry. Worst of all, the writing is
clumsy, like a landlubber on a sailboat for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Hanover, Mass., author writes, ``(A boat's) vulnerable
condition and attitude focused for me a human and very moving
truth: that boats _ beneath their infinite variety _ are but one
(and one of the most versatile and inspiring) of the outward
expressions of the spirit of man: and in particular his courage,
his curiosity and ingenuity, his desire to be challenged.'' She's
way off-course there _ and in many spots elsewhere _ in the
188-page book.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the problem is with organization. The title was poorly
conceptualized _ each chapter is wayward.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes' writing lacks concrete details that give a sense of the
moment _ there are few good descriptions. Cliches prove weak
substitutes: ``Maine is as much a state of being as it is a
place.''
</P>
<P>
   The state of Hayes' style is insufficient. Nature writing should
be rich in description and vision; this lacks either. Our rating:
(zap)H &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Guidebooks don't have to be complicated, daunting or lengthy. The
best often are deceptively simple. They should be like gifted
teachers, explaining so clearly students are not left in a fog.
</P>
<P>
   Derek C. Hutchinson, a resident of South Shields on the
northeast coast of England, efficiently and crisply proves his
expertise in ``The Basic Book of Sea Kayaking'' (Globe Pequot
Press; $7.95).
</P>
<P>
   Introductory chapters focus on equipment and include such
elementary tips as ``dress for immersion'' and ``don't paddle
alone.'' More difficult tasks are added later on: How to load the
kayak, how to embark and disembark, how to lift and carry the boat
and how to recover after falling out of the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best elements is the full-color illustrations. They
are especially helpful for capsize drills and addressing the
deepest fear many kayakers have _ getting caught upside down. The
A-B-C description and drawings are just what beginners need to
overcome the apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson, often writing with the touch of a feathery paddling
stroke, has explained the fundamentals of the recreation in just 78
pages. The title might well be an ideal complement to prepare tyros
for their maiden voyages. Our rating: HHH{ &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
