<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7852 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     09-01 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   You Don't Have to Be a Star, Baby, to Be in This Internet Show 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In the future, anyone can be a television star or a published
novelist. And the future is a lot closer than you think.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies _ one public and sitting squarely in Silicon
Valley, and one private and based in lower Manhattan _ are out to
turn traditional media models upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The firms are Fatbrain.com and Pseudo Programs. Mountain View's
Fatbrain this week unveiled an online way for authors of everything
from magazine articles to technical manuals to weighty literary
novels to get their work published and distributed with ease _ and
with 50 percent royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo, the New York company, is running an Internet
``television network'' with an impressive 70 hours of original
programming a week.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies are out to prove the transformative nature of
the Internet. It won't be easy. Competition is fierce. Established
media giants will want to squash them or own them. And there's no
guarantee that the consumer mass market will even buy into their
concepts of catering to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Fatbrain. The company is not content merely to sell
professional and technical books online, Amazon-style. This week,
it unveiled eMatter, the concept it hopes will revolutionize
publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Using eMatter, any author can post a work of any style or length
for sale on the Fatbrain site. The author pays Fatbrain $1 a month
for the service and then splits the sales with the company 50-50,
much more than authors' typical 5 percent royalties.
</P>
<P>
   People can read what they want, how they want to: Short pieces
can stay on the screen, 10-page essays can be printed out, and
Fatbrain can send books to the printing press (with additional
costs for binding, artwork and hard covers). Already, said Fatbrain
President and CEO Chris MacAskill, ``About 10.8 percent of our
sales, we print and bind and send them out.''
</P>
<P>
   How does this change the world? Many ways, MacAskill says:
</P>
<P>
   _It lets authors publish works that otherwise had no forum.
</P>
<P>
   _It solves inventory problems for publishers. (And Fatbrain has
signed up such publishers as Macmillan USA, McGraw-Hill, O'Reilly
and Associates, the Motley Fool, Salon.com and the Coriolis Group.)
</P>
<P>
   _Works never have to go out of print; they can sit at Fatbrain
until someone wants to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   _Authors can update or alter their works any time, and readers
can buy only the chapter they need.
</P>
<P>
   Authors can start posting to Fatbrain now, and the first items
go on sale October 15.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street responded enthusiastically. The stock soared 60
percent Tuesday alone, before it slid back yesterday. It posted an
18 percent drop, closing down $4.38, at $19.69 _ still double its
opening price in January.
</P>
<P>
   But some on the Street see hurdles. Analyst Randall Roth at
Renaissance Capital in Greenwich, Conn., said shorter articles are
hard to sell because ``it's just a hassle. People don't want to
have chapters of books for $2 charges on their credit cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Longer works will face serious competition, as print-on-demand
grows in popularity and becomes an option offered at big companies
like Barnesandnoble.com and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Pseudo Programs CEO Larry Lux _ who visited San
Francisco last week _ must solve some fundamental problems, such
as: Who wants to watch television while sitting at their computer?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the site (www.pseudo.com) already boasts 700,000 unique
visitors a month, and that's before it's done any real promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo offers nine ``channels'' and 55 shows, with topics
including professional wrestling (``And Justice for Brawl''),
computer games and hip-hop music.
</P>
<P>
   It's sort of a cable access meets the Web. It's cheap to produce
and distribute. Anyone with passion can be a host. Why tilt at
windmills, trying to sell a program to a network or put a new cable
channel on an already crowded lineup, when you can go online for
microbucks?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the business of cranking out content and delivering
highly segmented audiences to advertisers,'' Lux said. ``It's much
simpler and more cost-effective to do it through the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazes me,'' Lux said. ``It's such a departure from
traditional media.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOMETHING SONY: Sony Electronics last month showed off Sony Style,
a splashy magazine produced by Time Inc. Custom Publishing, the
folks who produce a similar publication for Starbucks named Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Sony actually is charging money for the magazine _ $5.95 _ and
sells full-page color ads for $7,500. The premier issue features
ads from the Gap, eBay, Altoids and Yahoo, among others, but not
from Sony.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's not so strange when you consider all the Sony
plugs in the editorial copy. The magazine contains articles about
Sony's new San Francisco playland, Metreon; about Sony's robotic
dog; about how Hollywood filmmakers use Sony digital cameras; and
about how designers made Sony's sleek laptop, the Vaio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SLIPPERY SLATE: Could shifting winds in Redmond, Wash., be bad news
for Slate?
</P>
<P>
   After all, Slate is Microsoft Corp.'s online magazine, and tea
leaf readers see the software giant bailing out on its media
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, Michael Kinsley _ Slate's editor _ doesn't show
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no reason to expect anything cataclysmic is on the
way,'' Kinsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Ominous signs include Microsoft's sale in July of its Sidewalk
city guides and the hiring _ widely reported, but still not
formally announced _ of former Silicon Graphics chief executive
Richard Belluzzo to run its Internet operations.
</P>
<P>
   Will boss Belluzzo move the company more into e-commerce and
away from low-margin content? ``Everybody here is curious about
what's going to happen, what a new guy is going to do,'' Kinsley
said. ``We've been given very positive encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinsley is irked at pundits asking, ```What about Slate?' as if
they know something,'' he said. ``If they know something, they know
something I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DREAM TEAM TIME: In 1995, former San Francisco Examiner columnist
Bill Mandel, now working in high-tech PR, wrote a memorable story
in SF Weekly called ``The Dream Team.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, he posited that a combined San Francisco daily newspaper
could achieve greatness by pulling together the most talented
writers from The Chronicle and Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Mandel says that scenario now appears likely to play out. Hearst
Corp., the owner of the Examiner, has bought The San Francisco
Chronicle and says it is seeking a buyer for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Mandel scoffed at the notion of Hearst inviting competition,
predicting that his ex-employer soon will merge with The Chronicle.
He said, ``Hearst is looking for a buyer for the Examiner like O.J.
is looking for the real killers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
id Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to fostd &LR; sfgate.com, call (415) 777-6004 or
fax (415) 543-2482.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
