r f BC-MACQA-MACQ&AMP;A_SFCHRON &LR;      09-01 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACQA-MACQ&AMP;A </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MAC Q&AMP;A/HENRY NORR
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Apple Macs Now Have Chops to Play MP3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: My Windows-using buddies are heavily into MP3 music from the
Web, and they've been busting my chops because they claim the Mac
can't do MP3. Can that really be true? I looked at the feature on
MP3 in The Chron's Datebook section a few weeks ago, but I didn't
find anything about the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Good news: Your buddies are all wet. Or at least behind the
times. Until a few months back, there really wasn't much support
for MP3, currently the most common format for downloadable digital
music, on the Mac _ not because Apple's hardware couldn't handle
it, but simply because the required software wasn't available.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, all that has changed, and now, there's a plethora of MP3
programs for the Mac. For starters, Apple's QuickTime 4, available
free at www.apple.com/quicktime, can play back most MP3 files.
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention when installing, though: By default, the installer
proposes a ``minimum'' setup, and if you just say OK to that, you
won't get the files needed to play MP3. Instead, choose a ``full''
or (if you really know what you're doing) custom installation.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a snazzier player and especially if you want to
create your own MP3 files from your CDs, you'll need to go beyond
QuickTime.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many third-party programs that have cropped up
recently, the most polished and professional is Casady &AMP; Green's
SoundJam MP; you can download a seven-day demo for free or the full
program for $39.99 at www.soundjam.com, or buy the packaged version
($49.99 list, including a stereo cable) from a retail or catalog
outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders include MacAMP ($25) and MacAMP Lite ($10),
available at www.macamp.net, and Xing Technology's AudioCatalyst
($29.95) at www.xingtech.com.
</P>
<P>
   There's one area where the Mac continues to lag: You need a PC
to load music onto the leading first-generation MP3 portable
players, such as the popular Rio from RioPort (formerly Diamond
Multimedia) and the Nomad from Creative Labs.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, that soon will change, too: The Rio 500, a new
version due any day now, will work with any Mac that has USB ports,
notably the iMac, the upcoming iBook and the blue-and-white Power
Mac G3s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Reading Mac Disks on PC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any way I can set up my PC at work to read floppies
I bring in from my home Mac?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure, but Windows by itself won't do the trick _ you'll have
to install Asome special software on your PC. I use a program
called MacDrive 98 from Media4 Productions (about $65, available at
www.media4.com or at some stores and catalog outlets).
</P>
<P>
   But there are lots of other options, including a free program
called HFVExplorer. For a complete rundown, look at
www.macwindows.com/disks2.html, part of a Web site devoted to
facilitating peaceful coexistence between Macs and PCs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Navigating Memory
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much memory should I allocate to Netscape Navigator? I
crash a lot when I run it at a little more than minimum.
</P>
<P>
   A: The more memory you can allocate to Netscape (within reason),
the faster it'll run and the less it'll crash. Same goes for
Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds as if you've reduced Netscape's ``preferred'' RAM
settings below the original setting (``4,000 K'' for Navigator
4.08). As you're discovering, that's living dangerously. Your
system will be much more stable if you give it (and just about any
other application you use) at least as much memory as the
developers wanted when they set the original ``preferred'' values.
That's especially true if you use plug-ins that let you enjoy
QuickTime, Shockwave and other multimedia formats from your
browser.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I generally increase the preferred allocation for
all my applications by at least 50 percent above the default
amount. You may not be able to keep as many programs open at once,
but to me, increased stability and speed are well worth that price.
</P>
<P>
   To modify an application's preferred memory allocation, first
make sure the program isn't running. Then go to the folder where
you keep it, highlight (single-click) its icon and choose Get Info
from the File menu.
</P>
<P>
   A small panel with information about the program will open. If
you're running Mac OS 8.5 or 8.6, click on the pop-up menu labeled
General Information, select Memory and change the number in the
Preferred box; if you have an older version of the Mac OS, you'll
immediately see the Preferred box.
</P>
<P>
   I'll catch hell from some Mac enthusiasts for saying this, but
memory management is one area where Windows is more user friendly
than the current Mac OS. Microsoft's OS dynamically allocates the
available memory among open programs, so users don't have to bother
with such arcane details. Fortunately, Mac OS X, a major new
version due early next year, finally should fix this problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send feedback to Henry Norr at hnorr &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
