<HEADER>
A7858 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DSL-DSL_SFCHRON &LR;      09-01 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DSL-DSL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Voice over DSL could provide high-speed Net access, multiple  phone
numbers over a single wire 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Households and small businesses that need lots of phone lines for
Internet service, fax machines and talkative teens may soon have a
cheaper alternative than buying these services a la carte.
</P>
<P>
   Several Bay Area companies are testing a technology called voice
over DSL, which will let customers get a high-speed Internet
connection and up to 16 telephone lines over a single copper wire.
</P>
<P>
   DSL, short for digital subscriber line, uses a portion of the
same copper wire that carries telephone service to also provide
Internet access that is up to 50 times faster than a dial-up modem.
DSL is ``always on,'' meaning users don't have to dial their
Internet service provider each time they want to check out a Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   DSL, which costs about $50 per month plus a setup fee, is
gaining popularity among Internet users, but right now it only
carries data.
</P>
<P>
   The new technology will split the DSL portion of the wire into
multiple channels, so it can carry voice and data at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area companies such as Santa Clara's CopperCom, Sunnyvale's
TollBridge Technologies and Jetstream of Los Gatos are among those
making voice over DSL equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the applications that will help DSL take that
next step and become more widely used,'' said Charles Carr, an
analyst with Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, when a household or small business wants to add a
second or third phone number, a technician must come out and may
need to install additional wiring. Extra residential phone lines
cost $11.25 per month each, plus monthly taxes and installation
charges.
</P>
<P>
   With the new technology, companies don't have to put in
additional wires. As a result, DSL providers can instantly provide
additional phone numbers and are expected to charge less than
Pacific Bell for additional lines, although no prices have yet been
set.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can use one wire to carry high-speed Internet access
and layer on 16 phone lines on top of that, the savings can be
significant,'' said Cynthia Ringo, CEO of CopperCom.
</P>
<P>
   Voice over DSL could be especially attractive for small
businesses, which typically pay more for additional phone lines
than either residential customers or big businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, small businesses tend to pay more for their voice
lines and there's probably a bit more profit margin to be made in
that arena, especially with packages of multiple lines,'' said
Jeannette Noyes, who tracks the DSL market for International Data
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It could also be a bargain for households that want separate
phone lines for each family member, a phone and a fax for a home
office and fast Internet connections for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the residential market, certainly there are households with
four or more telephone lines that would be interested in this
service,'' Noyes said.
</P>
<P>
   As more carriers offer voice over DSL, the price will continue
to fall, which could pressure Pacific Bell to lower its prices for
second phone lines as well.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is a downside. Since the wire carrying DSL is
shared by both voice and data, Internet speeds decline as more
telephone lines are in use.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies developing voice over DSL say the degradation
of the line is not significant and that even when multiple phone
numbers are in use, most users will still be able to access the
Internet at 128 kilobits per second. That's more than twice as fast
about 20 times faster than a  &LR; asstandard 56 kbps dial-up modem.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the voice quality of voice over DSL seems comparable to
a traditional phone line, according to industry watchers. DSL can
also support services such as call waiting, caller ID and call
forwarding.
</P>
<P>
   But the new technology has the same limitation as regular DSL
service: Users must be within three miles of a phone company's
central switching office, because the farther the DSL signal
travels, the more it degrades.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers probably won't get access to voice over DSL for at
least a year, but business customers can expect to see it in
mid-2000. Customers who already have DSL will be able to add the
voice over technology to their existing service.
</P>
<P>
   DSL providers are still testing the technology to make sure it
can withstand heavy use. Small businesses are accustomed to
temporary glitches in Internet service but will not tolerate an
interruption in phone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The equipment that allows us to do this technology is still
relatively new ,and people are much more sensitive to voice than
data,'' said Michael Malaga, CEO of NorthPoint Communications of
San Francisco, a DSL provider.
</P>
<P>
   The new technology will be offered by phone companies that
compete with the regional Bell companies, such as GST Telecom, and
by traditional DSL providers, such as NorthPoint and Covad
Communications of Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, ISPs and phone companies may offer it as well.
Pacific Bell already offers regular DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the voice over DSL providers will buy equipment from
companies such as CopperCom, Jetstream and TollBridge. These
companies make ``enablers,'' which let DSL lines carry voice.
Enablers about the size of an external modem sit at the customer's
home or office. Larger enablers sit at the central switching office
of the phone-service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Voice over DSL providers are bullish on technology but admit
that it might take awhile it to catch on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a little more tempered (than regular DSL),
because people aren't going to immediately swap out their voice
lines for voice over DSL,'' said NorthPoint's Malaga. ``With DSL,
people were looking to upgrade from a dial-up connection to a much
faster connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Malaga said, if companies and consumers realize they can
save money by using voice over DSL, it will start to catch on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just another example of competition working,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
