</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- WACO-INQUIRY, 09-1 --
Christian leaders pray in front of the Justice Department on
Wednesday during a demonstration calling for a full investigation
of the FBI's handling of the Branch Davidian standoff near Waco
Texas in 1993. From left are: Randall Terry, the founder of
Operation Rescue, Director of Christian Defense Coalition Rev.
Patrick Mahoney, Rev. Robert Schenick of the National Clergy
Council, Rev. Imagene Stewart of the African American Women's
Clergy Association and Brandi Swindell of the American Center for
Law and Justice. The man in the background at left is unidentified.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- BUDGET-TAXES, 09-1 --
White House Chief of Staff John Podesta, left, waits to address
reporters at the National Press Club on Wednesday. Podesta urged
the Republican majority in Congress to send President Clinton its
$792 billion tax cut bill so that he can promptly veto it. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WATERLOO, N.Y. -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- CLINTON, 09-1 --
First lady and potential candiate for the U.S. Senate from New
York, Hillary Rodham Clinton, greets supporters on Wednesday,
including Ben, a West Highland White Terrier. President Clinton and
his wife took a tour Wednesday of historic sites in central New
York, including a house where abolitionist Harriet Tubman lived.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LAGOS, Nigeria -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- NIGERIA-PEACE, 09-1
-- Workers at a gasoline station assist a customer in August. The
humble gas station, once the defining image of Nigeria's seemingly
willful collapse, has undergone a remarkable transformation since
the country's military rulers handed over power to civilians three
months ago. Gone are the mile-long lines and fistfights over scarce
fuel which transformed gas stations into high-security zones
swarming with soldiers, police officers and thugs. (Norimitsu
Onishi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- BRISCOE-SLAVERY, 09-1 --
Connie Briscoe and a photograph of her great-great-grandmother
Susan. Ms. Briscoe, who has sold over a million copies of her two
novels about the romantic travails of buppies, or black urban
professionals, has ventured into her past and into slavery for her
new book, ``A Long Way From Home,'' released last month. (Nancy
Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- MTV-AWARDS, 09-1 -- MTV and
the Met? They may sound incompatible, but next Thursday MTV plans
to present its 16th annual Video Music Awards in the elegant opera
house at Lincoln Center. Judy McGrath, MTV's president, finds Met
officials ``open-minded.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- NY-NORTH-SHORE-HOUSE-3, 09-1
-- Carol and Millard Prisant have restored their North Shore home
to the ideal from which it had sadly lapsed. The exuberant central
hall has encaustic tile from England and faux finishes. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- NY-NORTH-SHORE-HOUSE-2, 09-1
-- The 1950s kitchen in Carol and Millard Prisant's North Shore
home got a coat of paint, a new chandelier and a wallpaper border.
The three-story structure with curved Flemish gables was a model of
Romantic architecture in New York's emerging steamboat suburbs in
the mid-19th century. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- NY-NORTH-SHORE-HOUSE-1, 09-1
-- Carol Prisant at the Gothic-style entry to her Romantic home.
Conceived in 1862 as the country house of the future and esigned by
the Staten Island architect Frederick S. Copley, it offered many
innovations, including picture windows and integrally colored
encaustic tile floors. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) GEORGETOWN, Texas -- Sept. 1, 1999 --
CIR-CALCULATOR-GAMES-2, 09-1 -- Charles Sullivan, 15, of
Georgetown, uses his graphing calculator for both tedious
calculations and games. Calculators are supposed to help kids learn
math. What the kids have also learned is how to reprogram them for
their own purposes including games and some math programs that help
test-takers in ways teachers never planned. (Mathew Sturtevant/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PRINCETON, N.J. -- Sept. 1, 1999 --
CIR-CALCULATOR-GAMES-1, 09-1 -- Douglas Myers, left, and his
brother, Greg, have written calculator programs that they say will
help with SAT tests. ``There is no work involved, you just run the
program, plug in the known values, and watch your answers appear,''
says their Web site (members.aol.com/highersat). (Laura Pedrick/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 09-1 --
Cold chisels are used to cut through hard materials like metal or
masonry. They are often used to cut or shape metal when the stock
is thick and where other tools, like a hacksaw or tin snips, would
be unsuitable. The striking end of the cold chisel is chamfered to
reduce mushrooming and burring caused by constant hammering.
(Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- CIR-DISTANCE-LEARNING-2,
09-1 -- Carole S. Fungaroli, who is writing a book on the value of
college degrees, is a critic of virtual colleges. ``I think it's
going to be the joke of the 21st century,'' says Ms. Fungaroli, a
lecturer in English at Georgetown University. ``I don't see
anything that these people are offering that you can't get better
on campus.'' (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DEERFIELD, Ill. -- Sept. 1, 1999 --
CIR-DISTANCE-LEARNING-1, 09-1 -- Andrew M. Rosenfield of Unext.com,
an ambitious venture in Net-based distance learning. This summer,
the company began delivering executive training and, eventually, a
full MBA over the Internet. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) JAFFREY, N.H. -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- RUINED-FARM-BOS, 09-01
-- Ann Sawyer checks with one of the calves that survived the barn
fire that killed 120 cows at the Sawyer's farm. The pink medicine
on the calf's back is covering a burn. It will help keep flies off
the burn and prevent infection. ``To me, it was just a whole bunch
of cows,'' said fire chief Jack White. ``But she (Ann Sawyer) knew
their names. You realize this was a way of life.'' (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- CIR-POLITICAL-ACTIVISM, 09-1
-- Demonstrators at Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's inauguration in 1998.
As more people go online, community organizers are finding new ways
to harness the power of the Internet. The basics of organization -
using communication to start a group or keep it together, and
finding information that will arm community organizers with data -
are, one by one, moving into cyberspace. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BAILEY ISLAND, Maine -- Sept. 1, 1999 --
WOM-HAGERMANS-BOS, 09-01 -- The Hagerman sisters, from left,
Whitaker, 11, Jamison, 18, Casey, 29, and Kulin, 23, race up a hill
at their family's vacation home. The sisters, who each have
impressive athletic credentials, know all about the rapid changes
in girls' and women's sports spawned by the passage of Title IX in
1972. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MANCHESTER, N.H. -- Sept. 1, 1999 --
CELLULAR-TRANSCEPT-BOS, 09-01 -- Steven Johnson, Transcept's
president and Chris Cole, the company's marketing director test
their product with cables running from the ceiling in their lab.
Transcept, spun off from Lockheed Martin Co. in late July with a
$17 million infusion from a New York investment house, sells
systems that replace 100-foot cell towers with devices about the
size of a toolbox that hang off telephone and utility lines. (Frank
O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- CIR-WEBCAMS-2, 09-1 --
Creative Labs VGA Webcam III, priced at $80. Prices for Webcams
have become reasonable; rebates and discounts available for many
models can bring the cost of Webcams down sharply from list prices.
(Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- CIR-WEBCAMS-1, 09-1 -- The
Logitech Quickcam Pro, priced at $150. Webcams have brought out an
odd combination of the voyeur and exhibitionist. (Tony Cenicola/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT108) TAJURA, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-WAR, 09-01 -- Mohamed Tutu, 28, a father of four,
inspects a house in the village that was damaged by government
forces in April. When Sudanese government forces attacked this
village, killing its inhabitants was of little immediate concern.
As it has been throughout the campaign to cleanse Sudan's isolated
Nuba Mountains of its rebellious population, the primary mission
was to destroy the people's ability to feed themselves and to drive
them off the land. (Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT107) LOKICHOGGIO, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- SUDAN-AID-WORKERS-HNS, 09-01 -- Cargo planes with
various humanitarian aid groups are parked in April on
Lokichoggio's airfield, said to the the second busiest airport in
eastern Africa. For a decade now workers have labored under an
umbrella of U.N. and private relief agencies that have delivered
tons of food and other supplies to the victims and perpetrators of
the war in Sudan, one of the world's deadliest and most intractable
wars. (Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT106) NUBA MOUNTAINS, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., SEPT. 5 -- SUDAN-NUBA, 09-01 -- Saleman Kuku, a Sudanese
rebel, stands watch at an airfield in an undisclosed area of the
Nuba Mountains as sacks of food are unloaded from an aircraft in
April. As it has been throughout a campaign to cleanse Sudan's
isolated Nuba Mountains of its rebellious population, the primary
mission of government forces in the region is to destroy the
people's ability to feed themselves and to drive them off the land.
(Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT105) PANTHOU, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-5-HNS, 09-01 -- A woman feeds a child at a feeding
center run by Doctors Without Borders in April. The facility is
designed to provide nourishment to children who are below 70
percent of their minimum weight requirement. Depriving citizens of
food is a vicious tool of modern warfare. And in Sudan, a poor
country in East Africa, the government is using hunger as a weapon.
(Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT104) PANTHOU, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-4-HNS, 09-01 -- Abuk Garang, 12, scrabbles to
collect grains of cereal spilled on the ground after a food drop
from aircraft with the United Nations relief effort in April.
Established 10 years ago to aid the vicitms of Sudan's intractable,
16-year-old civil war, the U.N.-led operation has been unable to
eradicate hunger, a preferred weapon in the conflict. (Andrew
Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT103) PANTHOU, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-3-HNS, 09-01 -- Ajou Deng hangs from a scale at a
feeding center sponsored by Doctors Without Borders in April. The
organization has more than 90 volunteers working in southern Sudan,
where the group runs supplementary and therapeutic feeding centers
for children. (Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT102) PANTHOU, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-2-HNS, 09-01 -- Sudanese women and children race to
a site where bags containing food where air-dropped in April. Some
of the sacks of food burst on impact when hitting the ground
spilling grain that is scooped up by those who are quick to get to
the scene. Depriving citizens of food is a vicious tool of modern
warfare. And in Sudan, the government is using hunger as a weapon.
Because international relief now plays such a large role in war,
concern is growing that in the rush to aid the afflicted, the
relief may be abetting those who have a stake in the conflict.
(Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT101) SOUTHERN SUDAN -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN, SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-1-HNS, 09-01 -- Sacks of food are dropped from a
C-130 Hercules cargo plane, under contract to the United Nations,
onto a field in southern Sudan in April. Depriving citizens of food
is a vicious tool of modern warfare. And in Sudan, a poor country
in East Africa, the government is using hunger as a weapon. Because
international relief now plays such a large role in war, concern is
growing that in the rush to aid the afflicted, the relief may be
abetting those who have a stake in the conflict. (Andrew
Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
