<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Wednesday, 09/01/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-BUSCH, 09-1 -- The
Busch family, from left, Gregg, Glenn, Dr. Norman B. Busch and
Gideone (Gary) Busch in a family photo. Ten years ago, at the age
of 21 and with a promising medical career in front of him, Gidone
Busch learned he had an incurable kidney disease. It was that
knowledge, said his family and friends, that capsized all the plans
he had for his life, driving him on a search for spiritual
enlightenment and sometimes sending him skidding into immobilizing
depressions. Gideone Busch was killed Monday by police when,
authorities claim, Busch approached officers with a hammer. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) RIO RANCHO, N.M. -- Sept. 1, 1999 --
COMPUTERS-SCIENCE-2-B&AMP;W, 09-1 -- Computer industry jobs attract
young people. A worker removes silicon wafers from a bath at the
Intel Corp. plant in Rio Rancho. (Steve Northup/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- NY-RAPE-DNA, 09-1 --
Attorney Barry Scheck with Vincent H. Jenkins, also known by the
Muslim name of Warith Habib Abdal, during a news conference on
Wednesday. Abdal, imprisoned for 17 years for the 1982 rape of a
Buffalo woman, walked out of prison Wednesday after being cleared
by a DNA test. Scheck helped handle Jenkins' case as co-director of
the Innocence Project at the Cardozo School of Law in New York.
Jenkins is the 61st inmate in the United States to be exonerated by
DNA testing and the 36th since 1996, he said. (James Estrin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-2, 09-1
-- The hand of a man shot by police is seen as the body lied inside
a gypsy cab on Wednesday in Harlem. A police officer fatally shot
the man after the victim allegedly tried to cheat a cab driver out
of the fare he owed. It was the second deadly police shooting this
week, and appeared to be accidental. On Monday, four officers fired
12 shots at Gary Busch, a Brooklyn man who was beating a police
sergeant with a claw hammer and refused orders to put it down. (Don
Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) RAHWAY, N.J. -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- COMPUTERS-SCIENCE, 09-1
-- Chemists at work in the biochemistry lab at Merck in Rahway. A
sense is growing in some business quarters that the sheer ubiquity
of computers has deflected attention from more traditional sciences
and skills. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- FOOD-WRAPS-COX, 09-1 -- Why
have we gone wrap crazy? Probably because they provide a quick meal
for those on the go and the combination of fillings - from the
healthy to the decadent - is limitless. (William Berry/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-5, 09-1 -- Andre
Agassi practicing at the U.S. Open on Wednesday. The second-seeded
Agassi has become the clear favorite for the title now that
injuries have ousted world No. 1 Pete Sampras and 2-time reigning
champion Pat Rafter. (Steve Berman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-4, 09-1 --
Tennis legend John McEnroe playing guitar during a U.S. Open
fundraising event Tuesday evening for the New York City Parks
Department Youth Tennis Program. As McEnroe will readily admit, his
best chords are still struck on the court. (Steve Berman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-3, 09-1 --
Croatia's hard-serving Goran Ivanisevic, a Wimbledon runner-up for
the third time last year, opened this year's U.S. Open with a 7-5,
7-6 (7-5), 4-6, 6-2 victory over Finland's Ville Liukko. Ivanisevic
had lost five of seven matches since this year's Wimbledon. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-2, 09-1 --
Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario during her match against Australia's Nicole
Pratt at the U.S. Open on Wednesday. The 10th seeded Spaniard
defeated Pratt 6-2, 6-2 in 81 minutes. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-1, 09-1 --
Martina Hingis needed only 46 minutes to blast France's 34th-ranked
Sarah Pitkowski 6-1, 6-1, at the U.S. Open on Wednesday. Hingis,
the No. 1 seed, has been in the last two Open finals. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-SHOOTING, 09-1 --
Police are jeered by people near the scene of a police shooting on
Wednesday in Harlem. A police officer fatally shot a man after the
victim allegedly tried to cheat a cab driver out of the fare he
owed for a ride from jail. It was the second deadly police shooting
this week, and appeared to be accidental. On Monday, four officers
fired 12 shots at Gary Busch, a Brooklyn man who was beating a
police sergeant with a claw hammer and refused orders to put it
down. (Spencer Platt/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- WACO-INQUIRY, 09-1 --
