<P>
   (NYT108) TAJURA, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-WAR, 09-01 -- Mohamed Tutu, 28, a father of four,
inspects a house in the village that was damaged by government
forces in April. When Sudanese government forces attacked this
village, killing its inhabitants was of little immediate concern.
As it has been throughout the campaign to cleanse Sudan's isolated
Nuba Mountains of its rebellious population, the primary mission
was to destroy the people's ability to feed themselves and to drive
them off the land. (Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT107) LOKICHOGGIO, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 5 -- SUDAN-AID-WORKERS-HNS, 09-01 -- Cargo planes with
various humanitarian aid groups are parked in April on
Lokichoggio's airfield, said to the the second busiest airport in
eastern Africa. For a decade now workers have labored under an
umbrella of U.N. and private relief agencies that have delivered
tons of food and other supplies to the victims and perpetrators of
the war in Sudan, one of the world's deadliest and most intractable
wars. (Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT106) NUBA MOUNTAINS, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., SEPT. 5 -- SUDAN-NUBA, 09-01 -- Saleman Kuku, a Sudanese
rebel, stands watch at an airfield in an undisclosed area of the
Nuba Mountains as sacks of food are unloaded from an aircraft in
April. As it has been throughout a campaign to cleanse Sudan's
isolated Nuba Mountains of its rebellious population, the primary
mission of government forces in the region is to destroy the
people's ability to feed themselves and to drive them off the land.
(Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT105) PANTHOU, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-5-HNS, 09-01 -- A woman feeds a child at a feeding
center run by Doctors Without Borders in April. The facility is
designed to provide nourishment to children who are below 70
percent of their minimum weight requirement. Depriving citizens of
food is a vicious tool of modern warfare. And in Sudan, a poor
country in East Africa, the government is using hunger as a weapon.
(Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT104) PANTHOU, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-4-HNS, 09-01 -- Abuk Garang, 12, scrabbles to
collect grains of cereal spilled on the ground after a food drop
from aircraft with the United Nations relief effort in April.
Established 10 years ago to aid the vicitms of Sudan's intractable,
16-year-old civil war, the U.N.-led operation has been unable to
eradicate hunger, a preferred weapon in the conflict. (Andrew
Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT103) PANTHOU, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-3-HNS, 09-01 -- Ajou Deng hangs from a scale at a
feeding center sponsored by Doctors Without Borders in April. The
organization has more than 90 volunteers working in southern Sudan,
where the group runs supplementary and therapeutic feeding centers
for children. (Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT102) PANTHOU, Sudan -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-2-HNS, 09-01 -- Sudanese women and children race to
a site where bags containing food where air-dropped in April. Some
of the sacks of food burst on impact when hitting the ground
spilling grain that is scooped up by those who are quick to get to
the scene. Depriving citizens of food is a vicious tool of modern
warfare. And in Sudan, the government is using hunger as a weapon.
Because international relief now plays such a large role in war,
concern is growing that in the rush to aid the afflicted, the
relief may be abetting those who have a stake in the conflict.
(Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT101) SOUTHERN SUDAN -- Sept. 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN, SEPT.
5 -- SUDAN-AID-1-HNS, 09-01 -- Sacks of food are dropped from a
