<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DAVIDIANS-SMITH02-COX     09-01 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIANS-SMITH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No hearing likely regarding evidence from assault on Davidian
compound
 &HT;    By Mark England and Tommy Witherspoon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ No hearing is likely to be scheduled on a
government motion questioning the authority of U.S. District Judge
Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco to order the production of all evidence
relevant to what happened at Mount Carmel, a federal court official
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The court official, who asked not to be named, said Smith will
probably issue an order this week based upon a previous ruling.
Smith is trying hard to ensure the Branch Davidian civil lawsuit
begins on Oct. 18, the court official said.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9, Smith, acting on a request from the Texas Department
of Public Safety, ordered government agencies _ and any individuals
with pertinent evidence _ to produce all records, documents,
photographs, audio and video tapes related to the raid on Mount
Carmel, the 51-day siege and the fire on April 19, 1993, that
killed David Koresh and 75 followers.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Justice protested the order Tuesday,
filing a 19-page motion arguing that Smith exceeded his authority;
put an ``unwarranted and substantial burden'' on the federal
government as it prepared to defend itself against the civil
lawsuit filed by Davidian survivors and others that is set for Oct.
18; and threatened to disrupt Attorney General Janet Reno's
investigation of why it took six years to learn that incendiary
devices were used against the Branch Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the latter, Reno, according to Justice Department
sources, was searching for a qualified outsider but had reached no
final decision Tuesday, spokesman Myron Marlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department motion, signed by William Blagg, the U.S.
Attorney for the Western District of Texas, said that the
principles of separation of power prevent a federal court from
``acting as an independent investigator'' of the events that gave
rise to the litigation before it.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said they don't object to the U.S. Marshal's
Service taking custody of the Davidian evidence that was held by
the DPS _ just to Waco's Smith requiring the government to produce
additional evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's motion comes as there is renewed
interest in the Davidian case _ fueled by the FBI's admission that
military tear gas canisters, which are incendiary devices, were
fired on the day of the Mount Carmel fire.
</P>
<P>
   However, both the FBI and Reno have said there is no evidence to
suggest the blaze was set by the tear gas canisters, which were
lobbed at a concrete bunker 40 yards from the wooden compound a few
hours before the fire erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Bill Johnston of Waco _ who this week
revealed the existence of 1994 notes detailing a paralegal's
interview with members of the FBI's Hostage Rescue Team, in which
they admitted using military tear gas _ announced that he will keep
a lower profile in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston was criticized by attorneys for the jailed Davidians.
They questioned his motive for releasing the notes, given that he's
named in them as having sat in on the Hostage Rescue Team
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   In his defense, Johnston said his action was an effort to warn
Reno about the notes' existence, not protect himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should not be a spokesman regarding the issues as the
inquiry moves forward,'' Johnston wrote in a letter faxed to the
media. ``Therefore, unless unforeseen circumstances arise, I do not
intend to comment further publicly, after today, regarding the
matter at hand until such time as Congress has had the opportunity
to perform its work.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
