<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BEANIE-BABIES-NYT &LR;      09-01 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEANIE-BABIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT MAY BE TOO SOON TO BURY THE BEANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DANA CANEDY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Beanie Baby backlash has begun.
</P>
<P>
   As word spread Wednesday that the maker of Beanie Babies would
``retire'' all of the pint-size stuffed animals by the end of the
year, many consumers were outraged.
</P>
<P>
   Some were simply disappointed at the thought that the toys might
actually be discontinued. More, though, said they were furious at
being manipulated by the maker of Beanies, Ty Inc., for what was
probably a publicity stunt to ratchet the through-the-roof prices
for the toys even higher.
</P>
<P>
   There may be something to those hunches.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the McDonald's Corp. said Wednesday that it
would continue to offer Teenie Beanies again next year as part of
its Happy Meal promotion. And last month, Ty filed trademark
registration requests for several new Beanie-related names with the
Patent Trademark Office of the Commerce Department. One is for Bean
E Bears, and toy industry experts said Wednesday that it was likely
that all the hype about Ty's intentions might come down to a slight
name change for new versions of what are essentially the same toys.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, parents and consumers simply want a straight answer
from the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I'm tired of being put off by a company that has
no care or concern for the consumer,'' said Phyllis Karpinski, a
researcher for an executive search firm in Coral Springs, Fla., who
has a collection of about 300 Beanies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a sneaking suspicion that they are trying to clear the
shelves all out and they are going to come out with more at the
beginning of the year,'' said Ms. Karpinski, whose collection
includes Hoot the owl and Mooch the monkey. ``I think this is just
a millennium kind of thing. If it is, I'll quit buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who left messages on Ty's Internet chat rooms
expressed similar sentiments. Though some expressed support for the
company, the headlines reflected an overwhelming frustration among
cybercustomers. One said, ``Let's boycott.'' Another customer
pleaded, ``Could you please work on improving your communication
with us, your CUSTOMERS!!''
</P>
<P>
   Ty was unfazed. Asked specifically if the company was interested
in clearing up the confusion for customers, Anne Nickels, a Ty
spokeswoman, said, ``We have no comment at this time.'' She said
the founder, Ty Warner, also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The company posted a terse, cryptic announcement on its Web site
on Tuesday that started the Beanie buzz. The statement said simply
that ``All Beanies will be retired'' as of Dec. 31. The consensus
among consumers and toy industry experts Wednesday was that Ty,
which does not advertise and instead relies heavily on marketing
gimmicks, was simply engaging in a corporate game of ``gotcha'' to
drive sales as Beanies begin to lose their appeal to youngsters who
have moved on to Pokemon and Furby.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great risk here of having the whole thing backfire
in Ty's face,'' said Cliff Annicelli, managing editor of
Playthings, a trade publication. ``If Ty is manipulating what
children want, that is going to affect the parents of those
children. I think they have a right to feel like they are being
manipulated at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics, Annicelli said, hurt the entire toy industry.
``After going through the last few Christmases with seemingly
manipulated shortages of toys and constant questions going on about
`how come I can't get Tickle Me Elmo or why can't I get Furby,'
this certainly doesn't help in terms of the perception of the toy
industry on the part of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Beanie owners, though, were taking the news in stride. ``I
think they should give a little more information, but I'm sure
that's part of their strategy,'' said Shelley Mosby, the mother of
a 2-year-old who received Beanies as gifts at birth. ``I just think
it's marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there was a mix of consumer fury and frenzy, as
people rushed to snap up the toys. A Manhattan cabdriver whose
fares Wednesday included a man from Collectingnation.com, an online
auction site that specializes in Beanies, found himself on a
shopping spree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a guy in my car, from nation something, he was going to
be on four talk shows today,'' said the driver, Joseph Kastner.
``He was frantic,'' Kastner added. ``He said buy whatever you can
buy.''
</P>
<P>
   On that advice, the cabdriver headed directly to Candy and Nuts
Too on Park Avenue in Manhattan, where he bought 19 Beanies,
including Beak the bird. ``I know this guy's expensive, but what
are you going to do?'' And with only a hint of buyer's remorse at
having paid $230 for his new plush pals, he added ``I'm broke,
believe me I should not have done this. I can't believe how cute
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers said their Beanie business was beginning to pick up
but would probably surge in the days ahead as more people got word
of the announcement by Ty. Michael Updegraff, assistant manager at
Noodle Kidoodle in Manhattan, said people were buying ``to a
limited degree,'' about 30 people by 12:30 p.m. or so, which he
considered a lot. ``The older styles are moving much more rapidly''
like Snort'' the bull and Spinner the spider.
</P>
<P>
   The general reaction to the news? ``They're in shock, I think,''
Updegraff said. ``The regular Beanie people, they don't know what
it means.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
