<HEADER>
A7869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AUTOIMMUNE-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      09-01 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOIMMUNE-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOIMMUNE FALTERS; VERTEX SOARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The quest to find a major medical treatment for the 2.1 million
Americans _ 70 percent of them women _ who suffer from rheumatoid
arthritis has led to one local company's near shutdown and
another's potential success.
</P>
<P>
   AutoImmune Inc. said Wednesday the drug it had under development
has failed. At the same time, Vertex Pharmaceuticals Inc. Wednesday
said it would receive up to $82 million for its promising compound
that has so far tested well in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, several new drugs to treat the disease _ in which
hands, wrists, and feet become painful, swollen, and stiff _ were
approved by the US Food and Drug Administration. And with more than
$2 billion spent annually by consumers on various treatments for
the disease, more than two dozen drugs are now under development,
most focused on reducing both the signs and symptoms of rheumatoid
arthritis and retarding bone damage.
</P>
<P>
   AutoImmune, of Lexington, Mass., said results from its pivotal
clinical trial involving 772 rheumatoid arthritis patients at 36
medical centers were disappointing. The drug proved to be no better
than the placebo.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will dismiss most of its remaining 26
employees and spend the next few weeks determining its future
direction. AutoImmune shares, which were as high as 18 1/4 in 1997
and have been sliding since, closed Wednesday at 7/8, down 2 1/2 on
trading of 3.5 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   AutoImmune, which spent about $10 million for the phase III
clinical trial to test its oral tablet drug Colloral, will have
about $6 million in cash after the employee layoffs, according to
chairman and chief executive Robert C. Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to launch the phase III Colloral trial was
controversial, since an earlier trial failed to demonstrate
statistically significant effects. AutoImmune had tried
unsuccessfully to develop a similar oral tolerance drug to treat
multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any second thoughts or nagging feelings over what
we did or how we did it,'' said Bishop. ``This is just one of the
vagaries of pharmaceutical development, but we have to move
forward. I am proud of the people and team that we put together.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other end, Vertex is optimistic that its proposed oral
drug for rheumatoid arthritis, called HMR 3480/VX-740, will succeed
based on early testing in Europe by Hoechst Marion Roussel, which
helped fund its initial development. Vertex is in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Those positive results prompted Hoechst to seek to alter and
expand its initial agreement, retaining all rights to the drug and
funding its development for a trio of disorders with Vertex
receiving royalties on global sales.
</P>
<P>
   Hoechst will pay Vertex $20 million in license fees plus an
additional $62 million for successful development of the drug for
rheumatoid arthritis, the first targeted disorder. Vertex will
receive an additional $124 million if it successfully develops the
drug for two other disorders for a total of $206 million, making
the deal Vertex's single-largest research and development
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   The Vertex drug, known as an interleukin-1 beta converting
enzyme, is expected to compete against Embrel, a genetically
engineered injectable drug approved by the FDA last September. It
was developed by Immunex Inc. of Seattle and is marketed by the
Wyeth Ayerst Laboratories, a unit of American Home Products.
</P>
<P>
   Embrel inhibits one of the key proteins that plays an important
role in the cascade of reactions that causes rheumatoid arthritis.
Another drug, Celebrex, marketed by Pfizer Inc., inhibits an enzyme
that plays a key role in pain and inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   For Hoechst, the Vertex drug would be its second major drug for
treating rheumatoid arthritis. Last fall, Hoechst gained FDA
approval for Arava, an oral medication that reduces symptoms of the
disease and retards bone damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge market with an aging population of baby boomers
that is underserved, and having an oral tablet vs. an injectable
should give us a significant advantage,'' said John Randle, a
Vertex program executive.
</P>
<P>
   Vertex shares closed Wednesday at 28 3/4, up 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
