<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-PENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS SUGGESTS CASH-BALANCE PENSION PLAN MAY VIOLATE
AGE-DISCRIMINATION LAWS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Ohio, Ind.)   By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cash-balance pension plans have drawn heavy criticism lately
because they often reduce the pensions of older workers. In fact, a
memo written by an Internal Revenue Service district director one
year ago _ and released Tuesday by a member of Congress _ stated
that one cash-balance pension plan may violate age-discrimination
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Cash-balance pension plans have become popular with employers
because they are cheaper and can offer better benefits to young
workers unlikely to spend their career in one place.
</P>
<P>
   But middle-aged employees at a number of companies that have
converted to cash-balance plans have complained about benefit
reductions that they say can take away up to 50 percent of the
value of their pensions. In response, some lawmakers in Washington
have sought to stop cash-balance conversions through legislation or
action by federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional pension-plan benefits are typically calculated using
the number of years an employee was at a company and final pay, so
most of the value of the pension is based on years late in a
person's career. Under cash-balance plans, companies contribute a
percentage of an employee's pay to an account every year, and then
guarantee that money will grow at a certain interest rate, such as
the yield on a Treasury bill. At retirement, that account is the
pension.
</P>
<P>
   The September 1998 IRS memo, released Tuesday by Rep. Bernard
Sanders, a Vermont Independent and critic of cash-balance plans,
could fuel efforts to slow cash-balance conversions. In the memo,
the IRS district director in Cincinnati, C. Ashley Bullard, told
IRS officials in Washington that one company's cash-balance plan
may not comply with age-discrimination rules because the ``plan's
benefit accrual rate decreases as a participant attains each
additional year of age.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said in a statement, ``This memo bears out what I and
others have been saying: If the rate of accrual goes down as
workers get older, then the plan violates the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullard declined comment Wednesday. A spokesman for the IRS, Don
Roberts, said the memo merely reflected internal agency debate
about a pension plan at one specific company. He declined to say
whether the IRS had made any formal decision relating to the plan.
In the memo, he said, regional IRS officials were seeking guidance
from the national office about the one plan, and the document did
not necessarily reflect the position of Bullard. It ``is not
precedent-setting and may not be cited as a broad statement'' of
IRS policy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   IRS officials are also working on a response to a letter from
some members of Congress about whether cash-balance plans violate
age-discrimination or other rules.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the company that was the subject of the memo was
blacked out, but according to people close to the matter, it refers
to the Onan Corp., a subsidiary of the Cummins Engine Co. based in
Fridley, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   As previously reported, the IRS, in a filing in a lawsuit in
U.S. Tax Court, has taken the position that an Onan pension plan
should be stripped of its tax-exempt status because of the way it
converted to a type of cash-balance plan. If the judge in that case
agrees with the IRS, Onan will be given the opportunity to correct
any problems with the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Cummins said Wednesday that the company had not received
confirmation that Onan was the subject of the IRS memo, and that
the agency had not raised age discrimination in the tax court case.
``Onan does not believe there can be age discrimination when
everyone who makes the same amount, no matter what age, gets the
same company contribution each year,'' said the spokeswoman, Marya
M. Rose.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
