<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PITCHING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWE'S SORE TOE KEEPS HIM FROM GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Red Sox reliever Derek Lowe reported to work Wednesday
and got the medical OK to miss Wednesday's game against the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who had appeared in four of the team's last five contests,
was excused because the pain from an ingrown toenail he's had the
last month had become unbearable. After an impromptu media session,
he was scheduled to have it removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched for four of five days, so they decided it was the
good day to take it out so I can pitch again,'' said Lowe. ``It's
just for a day. I'll pitch again tomorrow if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of guys with bumps and bruises this time of the
year, but you have to put those aside. You have six months to heal
in the offseason, so you have to go as hard as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   His brief departure came on a day when help was arriving. Rod
Beck, acquired Wednesday in a deal with the Cubs, showed up just
prior to game time. The addition of Beck should help improve a
bullpen that has gone through many changes since Tom Gordon exited
with an elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great. The guy had 51 saves last year,'' said Lowe of his
new teammate. ``He knows how to pitch in late games. He's been a
closer for I don't know how many years and he's done it in playoff
pressure and done a tremendous job. Whenever you can add a guy like
that, all it does is make the team a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last four appearances, Lowe pitched 4 1/3 innings,
allowing a hit and a walk and striking out five, while recording a
win and picking up three saves. In 60 appearances this season, Lowe
is 5-2 with an earned run average of 2.76, 10 saves, and 3 blown
saves.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe leads Red Sox relievers in appearances, innings (88), and
strikeouts (64).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason I can do it is I throw a majority of
fastballs,'' said Lowe of his durability. ``I'm a fastball pitcher
and your arm has a tendency to bounce back more when you're
throwing strictly fastballs. I'm not going to say you're feeling
100 percent when you're out there. But that's the job you're asked
to do and you do it the best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-year major leaguer said he would prefer starting,
``but if you look at my track record, it's not too good,'' said
Lowe, who began last season as a starter and went 0-7 before
recording his first victory. ``I think I could be a much better
starter (now) just because I've been in the league a couple of
years. I've got more confidence. My changeup has gotten a lot
better than it was last year, my curveball, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game, you don't dictate what you do. Management has a
plan for everybody. You just go out and pitch and your goal is to
stay healthy. Everyone wants to go to the World Series and if the
best chance is for me to be a set-up guy, that's what I will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe is a quality set-up man but doesn't mind closing. He said
someone who has been in the league for two years should not make
demands on his role. He is merely trying to improve his skills to
aid the team during the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think last year helped me a lot in pitching,'' said Lowe.
``The stretch run of last year, pitching in September and then
pitching in postseason, helped me to pitch under pressure and enjoy
the atmosphere because this is exciting, this is what every player
plays for.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to relax and still make quality pitches. This
last two weeks really helped me out. Hopefully I can still learn
and have it to lean on in the end of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
