u f BC-DELL-SPOTLIGHT02-COX     09-01 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-SPOTLIGHT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell site focuses on founder
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp., which claims its direct
contact with customers inspires virtually everything it does, is
now offering all Michael, all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The new Web pages at www.dell.com/michael blend Chief Executive
Michael Dell's views on the personal-computer industry with
personal, even trivial, ``factoids'' about him (he likes to work
standing up at his desk, for one).
</P>
<P>
   The site includes Dell's speeches, his view of the Internet,
details about computers he uses, an interactive game for children
and a link to the Austin Children's Museum Dell Discovery Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Round Rock-based company says most of the content is simply
responding to customer interest in the founder, who attracts crowds
of autograph-seekers when he appears in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting so many requests for this kind of information
about Michael that we decided to consolidate it and make it
available to everybody,'' Dell spokeswoman Patty Rowell said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the site also signifies that the chief executive, who used
to be uncomfortable in front of audiences, accepts his role as an
industry icon. The subject of an increasing number of news media
profiles and TV interviews, he also appears in a round of recently
started TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, 34, has typically resisted moves that might be seen as
self-promotion. His book, ``Direct from Dell,'' which was published
last spring, is a dry history of his company and a description of
how its direct model works. There is little biographical
information.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Dell opposed an employee's suggestion to change the
company's name from PC's Limited to Dell Computer Corp. when it
launched the business in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to be seen as a man who was pushing his ego out
in the marketplace,'' said Andrew Harris, the U.K. executive who
prevailed on the name change.
</P>
<P>
   Even last year, Dell seemed uncomfortable offering his opinion
on issues that didn't directly involve his company. In May 1998, a
reporter approached him at an Austin hotel where he was speaking to
ask for comments about Andy Grove's surprise decision to step down
as CEO of Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, who knows Grove personally, looked blankly at the
reporter, while her tape recorder picked up only background sounds.
His Web site, which resembles a site on Grove at intel.com, is
further evidence that those days are over. Harris, who left Dell
and started Hand Technologies, an Austin PC company, said Michael's
wife, Susan, helped him grow comfortable in his high-profile role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Susan had a big impact, because Susan is a gregarious
lady,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
