<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGH-KITE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS HIGH AS A KITE IN THE SKY _ 'WAY TOO HIGH, IN FACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KATHY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Larry Frakes was flying high _ too high,
really _ and then he came reeling down to earth. Or at least his
kite did.
</P>
<P>
   A 39-year-old Bell Helicopter machinist and all-around tinkerer
and inventor, Frakes gets his thrills from seeing how high he can
fly his homemade, modified box kite.
</P>
<P>
   His exhilaration, however, came to an abrupt halt Monday night
when his rainbow-colored, 4-foot-tall kite soared to 2,500 feet,
where it interfered with air traffic at three local air strips, put
the medical helicopter service on standby and sent the police
helicopter zooming up to check the altitude of the potentially
catastrophic toy.
</P>
<P>
   Police pilot Ron Paddock and Officer F.C. Ferguson, acting as
relief flight officer, initially couldn't locate the kite while
flying at 500 feet.
</P>
<P>
   From the ground, another officer told them to look up, Ferguson
said. Their immediate response was a few choice words. The kite was
cruising at 2,000 feet, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frightened me. If you get tangled up in that cord, it'll
bring you down. It doesn't make sense to do something that
idiotic,'' said Paddock, who said he feared that the rotors of the
helicopter, Air One, might get caught in the kite's cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife said he probably was trolling for aliens,'' Paddock
said. ``It's the only UFO in the city that's now been identified.''
</P>
<P>
   Frakes said the kite reached 2,500 feet _ almost five times the
height of the tallest downtown building _ before the helicopter
arrived to help Officer R.P. Ross, who was in a patrol car, search
for the kite flyer. But Frakes said he had reeled it in about 500
feet by the time the officers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did notice one small aircraft had to move to avoid hitting
it, but I really think the pilot was overexaggerating,'' Frakes
said. ``He wasn't that close to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The kite, which Frakes designed and built in four months after
he helped his daughter with a school kite project, is equipped with
a red strobe light to increase its visibility to pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Frakes became a bit sheepish when Ferguson and Ross traced the
kite's line to his home and informed him that his high-flying
gambit had stopped traffic at Sycamore Air Strip and had caused
planes to be diverted from Meacham _ a major general aviation
center _ and Spinks airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me feel kind of stupid, but I brought it down,'' he
said. ``I like flying it high. There's an adrenaline rush when it
goes way up. I tried to push it to its maximum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like watching it fly real high with the clouds as a
backdrop. It's very peaceful.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sherry, and two daughters, Alicia, 13, and Lauren, 10,
don't like to see the kite soar that high because it becomes only
only a dot in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't see kites being flown at that height in Fort
Worth,'' Ferguson said. ``This is one for the memory books.''
</P>
<P>
   Roland Herwig, a Federal Aviation Administration spokesman in
Oklahoma City, said he had no information about the incident, but
he said that any time a kite exceeds 150 feet, ``then we would like
to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Frakes initially was discouraged after talking to police, but
now said he is more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't stop flying the kite,'' he said. ``I just won't fly it
as high as I like.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
