<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    European teams no lock to qualify for Euro 2000
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many of Europe's top teams are feeling the pressure as
Euro 2000 qualifying resumes during the next week. Czech Republic
is the only team to clinch a place in next summer's 16-nation
finals in Belgium and Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Reigning World Cup champion France trails the Ukraine by a point
in Group 4 and must play Saturday in Kiev, then at Armenia on
Wednesday. Midfielder Zinedine Zidane returns for France after a
five-match injury absence.
</P>
<P>
   Defending European champion Germany is tied with Turkey at the
top of Group 3 but travels to Finland on Saturday and is without
promising midfielder Sebastian Deisler, who has an injured thigh.
</P>
<P>
   In Group 5, Englandneeds all three points from a home match
Saturday against Luxembourg to tie second-place Poland, then has to
play in Warsaw on Wednesday in its finale. Sweden leads Poland by a
point. Injuries have affected England, too, as goalkeeper David
Seaman and defender Sol Campbell are out of action for both games
and Michael Owen might be relegated to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   All nine group winners and the second-place team with the most
points automatically qualify. The eight other runners-up will play
for the last four spots.
</P>
<P>
   Spain has a commanding goal differential in Group 6, but Israel
and Austria are only two points behind. Italy is cruising in Group
1 but is host to Denmark, tied for second with Switzerland.
Portugal and Romania, battling for the top of Group 7, meet in
Bucharest on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Group 8 is playing catch-up because of postponements by the NATO
bombings in the Balkans. Ireland beat Yugoslavia 2-1 Wednesday in
Dublin to take the lead by a point, but has to play Saturday at
second-place Croatia and then at Malta on Wednesday. Yugoslavia,
two points behind, is host to Macedonia on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Champions League: ``B'' is for brutal
</P>
<P>
   Cries of protest are coming from Barcelona, Fiorentina and
Arsenal after they were placed in Group B of the initial European
Champions League draw; the fourth, weaker member is AIK Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   That foursome is the most difficult as the expanded 32-team
event starts Sept. 14 after three qualifying rounds that yielded
few surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Manchester United should be able to prevail
against Group D rivals Olympique Marseille, Croatia Zagreb and
Sturm Graz. Runner-up Bayern Munich will have a challenge in Group
F with Rangers, PSV Eindhoven and Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   England: Robson to Newcastle?
</P>
<P>
   Former England manager Bobby Robson, a childhood Newcastle fan,
has expressed interest in managing the floundering club after the
resignation of embattled Ruud Gullit. The 0-5-1 Geordies, off to
the worst start in their 107-year-old history, suffered a 5-1
defeat to Manchester United on Monday, with former Newcastle star
Andy Cole scoring four goals.... Liverpool dominated injury-plagued
Arsenal 2-0 Saturday, as Robbie Fowler and Patrick Berger got the
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Bayern fights, then wins
</P>
<P>
   Roque Santa Cruz, 18, scored the lone goal to lead Bayern Munich
to its first win of the Bundesliga seasonSaturday over tiny
Bavarian neighbors Unterhaching.
</P>
<P>
   Bayern's defenders Lothar Matthaus and Bixente Lizarazu got into
a fight at a Friday practice. Lizarazu was fined $5,300 for
punching Matthaus in the face. Bayern midfielder Mario Basler,
involved in a contract dispute, was fined $10,000 for staying late
at a Munich disco the night before the game. Two years ago, Basler
was fined for making a habit of attending Oktoberfest.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Hat trick for Vieri
</P>
<P>
   The world's richest soccer player got his Inter Milan debut off
to a bang Sunday. Christian Vieri, who signed for an international
record of $50 million this summer, had a hat trick in a 3-0 win
over Verona.... But several Serie A favorites didn't fare as well
in their season openers, including defending champion AC Milan,
which blew two leads in a 2-2 draw with newly promoted Lecce.
Juventus drew 1-1 at home against Reggina, playing its first match
in Serie A.... Fiorentina got a goal from Enrico Chiesa to edge
Bari 1-0, while Lazio, which beat Manchester United on Friday in
the UEFA SuperCup, got early goals from new signees Juan Veron and
Simone Inzaghi in defeating Cagliari 2-1 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Rayo scores another upset
</P>
<P>
   Newly promoted Rayo Vallecano scored its second consecutive
upset in the Primera Division. Manuel Carrabal scored the clincher
with three minutes left, asRayo Vallecano beat Mallorca 2-1....
Rivaldo had a goal and an assist as Barcelona beat Racing Santander
2-1. Ex-Liverpool midfielder Steve McManaman had his first Spanish
goal in Real Madrid's 4-1 win over Numancia.
</P>
<P>
   France: Fit to be tied _ four times
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth match in a row, first-division favorite Olympique
Marseille has drawn, Saturday by a 1-1 score against Bastia. AS
Monaco, tied for the lead with three teams, got two goals from
David Trezeguet in a 3-0 win over Troyes. Paris St-Germain could
have taken over sole possession of first place, but lost 1-0 to
Olympique Lyon, which joined the top group on a penalty-kick goal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
