<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7877 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-MARCH-(TRIMS)-NYT &LR;      09-01 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MARCH-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REJECTS CITY APPEAL ON HARLEM RALLY
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal appeals court on Wednesday emphatically
rejected the city's final legal challenge to a Harlem youth rally
and, in an unusual step, explicitly ordered the Police Department
not to oversee the event with ``undue rigidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Searching for a way to head off the violence of a similar rally
held last year, the judges also ordered organizers of the event,
billed as the Million Youth March, to make ``all reasonable
efforts'' to end the event promptly and peacefully by the judges'
deadline of 4 p.m. Saturday. If the organizers fail to make a
sincere effort, the judges warned, they could be held in contempt
of court.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city said that they would not appeal the ruling,
even though Mayor Rudolph Giuliani called it ``one of the more
irresponsible decisions that I have seen a court render.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These judges have their heads in the sand,'' he said Wednesday
of the three judges who heard the case in the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness they don't have to govern a city,'' the mayor
said, ``because things would be really dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Giuliani said he would not grant a permit for what he
called a ``hate march.'' In turn, the march's primary organizer,
Khallid Abdul Muhammad, vowed to hold the rally anyway, calling it
a ``love march.'' City lawyers went to court, arguing that a
history of inflammatory, racially charged speeches by Muhammad was
sufficient cause to deny the permit, but those arguments were
rejected on Tuesday by U.S. District Judge Denny Chin.
</P>
<P>
   In upholding that ruling on Wednesday, the judges ordered the
city to grant a rally permit under virtually the same terms and
conditions as last year's event. Once again, the event will be held
on Malcolm X Boulevard between 118th and 124th Streets. The event
is scheduled to start at noon and end at 4 p.m., as it was last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But even those seemingly straightforward parameters failed to
head off a serious confrontation last year, when, just after 4
p.m., a phalanx of officers swept toward the stage, only to come
under furious attack from demonstrators who hurled chairs and
anything else they could get their hands on. Dozens were injured.
</P>
<P>
   As they questioned lawyers for the city and the Million Youth
March during oral arguments Wednesday morning, the judges were
plainly determined to avoid a repeat of last year's violence, while
also directly challenging much of the angry bluster that has
characterized public statements on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   They were visibly impatient with the city's argument that
Muhammad's angry exhortations last year for violent resistance
against ``attacks'' by the police constituted a valid basis for
denying a rally permit this year. Judge Jon O. Newman asked the
city's corporation counsel, Michael D. Hess, to cite a legal
precedent in support of this position. ``Any court ever done
that?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Hess paused. ``May I have a moment?'' he asked. He paused some
more. He was unable to come up with a case.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Later, Newman asked Hess whether the city had ``given
instructions to the Police Department concerning techniques to be
used'' at the conclusion of the rally.
</P>
<P>
   No, Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   Frowning, Newman suggested that such conversations take place
immediately, and he invited Hess to spell out recommendations he
would make to the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Hess replied that he would tell the police that ``all efforts
should be made'' to end the rally promptly and safely. Still not
satisfied, Newman asked Hess whether promptly meant ``at the stroke
of 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess conceded that there ``should be some flexibility,'' but the
judges, in a written order, were far more explicit. The Police
Department, the judges wrote, ``may announce that the crowd must
begin to disperse at 4 p.m., but must allow a few minutes to permit
the dispersal to begin, and may not forcibly act to disperse the
crowd unless it is apparent, within a few minutes after
announcement of a requirement to disperse, that dispersal is not
about to begin or, if begun, is not continuing with reasonable
dispatch.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the judges said that nothing in their order
limited ``any reasonable action'' by the police ``to respond to any
acts of violence'' or to arrest anyone who otherwise violates the
law.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When it came to the rally organizers, the judges repeatedly
expressed concern about Muhammad's insistence on marching with or
without a city permit. Newman asked a lawyer for the organizers,
Roger Wareham, whether Muhammad and the other organizers were
prepared to abide by whatever restrictions the court imposed on the
rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they are,'' Wareham replied. But here, too, the judges in
their written order left little room for misunderstanding about the
responsibilities of the rally organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the Million Youth March, the judges wrote, ``have
represented to this court that they will abide by the street
limitations that have been agreed upon, and by the time limitations
ordered by this court, that they will end their rally at the time
designated by this court, and that they will make all reasonable
efforts to disperse those in attendance as promptly and peacefully
as possible, and these representations are hereby made an order of
this court.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet within hours of these admonitions for reason and restraint,
city officials and rally organizers resumed squabbling over several
details, such as the placement of barricades and whether subway
service to the area would be shut down, as it was last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we go again,'' Wareham said with disgust, after trying
unsuccessfully to arrange a meeting with city officials Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Hess and police officials declined to discuss preparations for
the rally, saying those were ``operational'' details that could not
be disclosed. Hess said he did not know whether the subways would
be closed again, or whether fewer officers would be sent to the
rally, or whether barricades would be used more sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the city was prepared to agree to the organizers'
demands for a reduced police presence, Hess said yes, there was one
item that might be negotiable. The organizers have asked the city
not to send police helicopters buzzing low over the crowd, as
happened at the conclusion of last year's rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that's something to be seriously considered,''
Hess said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to find any accommodation have been complicated by a
steady stream of insult and invective flowing between the two
protagonists. Giuliani, who seems to delight in mispronouncing
Khallid Muhammad's name, has referred to the event as the
``Khalleel Mao-hammad hate march.'' Muhammad has called Giuliani a
``racist, cantankerous, constipated cracker.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, during a news conference in Harlem to
promote the rally, Muhammad continued his harsh criticism of
Giuliani, accusing him of attempting to create a climate of
repression and fear. He was joined by about 50 supporters, who
punctuated his remarks with chants of ``black power.'' Several wore
T-shirts bearing Muhammad's picture over the words, ``The white
man's worst nightmare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
