<SLUG> BC-BBO-BALLSUIT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fan hurt by thrown bat loses court case
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A man seriously injured by a flung baseball bat during
a 1997 Atlanta Braves game has struck out in his attempt to collect
damages.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous opinion, a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta rejected a lawsuit by Sterling
Lapinski, a former Georgia Power Co. employee whose skull was
shattered by a bat flung by New York Mets catcher Todd Pratt.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lapinski) assumed the risk of injury from the bat
accidentally released by the New York Mets ballplayer,'' the court
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski's lawyer, Bill deGolian, said he may ask the court to
reconsider its decision. ``We're terribly, terribly disappointed,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the July 11, 1997, game, Lapinski sat in field-level seats
behind the third-base dugout. In the fifth inning, Pratt swung and
missed at a Tom Glavine fastball and flung his bat into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski, who was talking to a waitress at the time, heard the
yells and turned toward the field. Pratt's bat slammed into his
forehead. The impact shattered his skull, crushed his sinus cavity
and tore the lining of his brain. He was taken to Crawford Long
Hospital. Doctors said the injuries increased his risk of seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, handed down last week, relied on a 50-year-old
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, the Georgia Court of Appeals, considering a lawsuit by
a spectator injured by a wildly thrown baseball during a game in
Thomasville, said a person who accepts a seat in an unprotected
portion of the grandstand ``voluntarily assumes the risks inherent
in such a position.'' The court recognized injury by ``foul balls,
flying bats and other like missiles'' as an inherent risk.
</P>
<P>
   DeGolian had argued that a flung bat was a much rarer occurrence
and something a player should be able to control.
</P>
<P>
   In each of Pratt's first three trips to the plate during the
game, his bat sailed into the stands. Only Lapinski, struck during
Pratt's second at-bat, was seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
