<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7881 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FISH-COMPENSATION-BOS     09-01 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-COMPENSATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TO ANNOUNCE COMPENSATION FOR DISTRESSED FISHERMEN  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Hundreds of hard-pressed New England fishermen will
receive up to $1,500 for each day that their fishing grounds were
closed by regulators this past spring, under a federal
disaster-relief program that Vice President Al Gore plans to
announce Thursday during a visit to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The $5 million aid package targets some of the region's most
vulnerable fishermen, the crews of small boats from Gloucester to
eastern Maine villages that ply the near-shore waters of the Gulf
of Maine. There, the once-plentiful codfish have become so scarce
that regulators have all but closed the entire fishing ground.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the federal aid, fishermen must help in
scientific research over the next two years in an effort to end
disagreements between scientists and fishermen over the severity of
the fishing crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long, we acted as if the ocean's resources were
infinite, and we must help those who are now paying the price,''
said Gore in a statement prepared for release Thursday.
``Ultimately, our goal must be to rebuild sustainable fisheries so
that the working families of the New England coast can again reap
the harvest of the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials and fishermen praised Gore's announcement as an
important step in helping fishermen hard hit by recent limits on
their livelihoods, while also helping scientists better understand
the problems. For instance, cod, long a staple of New England
fishing, are not producing many young fish, and biologists don't
know why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think fishermen would rather go out and fish, but I'm glad
to hear'' of the disaster relief, said William Amaru, a member of
the New England Fishery Management Council that sets fishing
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The relief package, negotiated with officials from
Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Maine, opens a new phase in aid
for New England's tattered fishing industry. Since the collapse of
the offshore Georges Bank fishing ground in 1994, the Commerce
Department has spent nearly $60 million on everything from buying
fishermen's boats to training them for new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But the program Gore will detail marks the first time that the
federal government has specifically targeted the 750 fishing boats
in the Gulf of Maine, a swath of water that includes the near-shore
fishing grounds from Cape Ann in Massachusetts east to the Canadian
border. Even as other fishing grounds slowly rebound, biologists
say the gulf is still reeling.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the problem, say industry analysts, is that
fishermen flocked to the Gulf of Maine over the last few years as
other fishing grounds were closed by regulators and the price of
cod ran high, causing a rapid depletion of the cod and other fish.
Now, Gulf of Maine cod populations are in the worst condition of
all major commercial fish stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the New England Fishery Management Council started
a wave of closures in the Gulf of Maine from February to June this
year to protect cod during spawning season. Since then, the council
has adopted an unpopular 100-pound limit on the cod catch,
effectively closing the gulf to cod fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, any fishing boat owner who can prove that the
Gulf of Maine closures forced him to miss fishing days can apply
for $1,500 for each lost day, though some of that money must be
shared with the crew. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration will notify eligible fishermen by mail in the next
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In return for each day of aid, fishermen must agree to a day of
fishing research, such as netting fish to check their abundance.
Fishermen and biologists have clashed repeatedly over the years,
with fishermen contending that the biologists overstate the fishing
crisis by undercounting the fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good start and that's the bottom line. More
industry-scientist endeavors need to be done,'' said Tom Hill,
chairman of the New England Fishery Management Council, which just
named a scientific steering committee to identify the major areas
of research needed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who will be at Boston's New England Aquarium to announce a
new federal task force on ocean conservation, said in a statement
that the new aid ``will bring fishermen and scientists together in
research collaborations that will improve our understanding of
ocean fisheries so we can better manage them in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
said the announcement will be just the first installment of federal
aid, if Congress approves aid measures put forward by President
Clinton or members of the Massachusetts congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are arguing that we need a long-term recovery program for
the Gulf of Maine,'' said one senior federal official. ``There's no
question this is a multi-year problem. Though cod is a bellwether
stock, the Gulf of Maine as a whole is being overfished.''
</P>
<P>
   To tide fishermen over, aid of the sort that Gore is announcing
will be needed on a long-term basis, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
