<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MALAYSIA-INVEST-ART-N     09-01 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-INVEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA ENDS MOST CONTROLS ON INVESTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
DW) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Taking a major stride back into the
world's financial mainstream, the Malaysian government Wednesday
lifted a steep tax on the repatriation of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
   The move is expected to uncork a stream of capital out of
Malaysia, as overseas fund managers withdraw money that had been
effectively locked in the country since the government imposed
sweeping capital controls last September.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several analysts said they expected the outflow to be on
the order of $1 billion to $2 billion _ far smaller than earlier
forecasts of $6 billion to $7 billion. As a result, the
long-awaited easing of restrictions caused little commotion in
stock prices here, which declined less than 2 percent _ an ordinary
fluctuation in an emerging market.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia was also buoyed by new statistics reaffirming that its
economy is in the midst of a remarkable recovery. The government
reported that the trade surplus rose to $1.52 billion in July, a 46
percent increase over the comparable period last year, on the
strength of surging exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some unreconstructed enemies of Malaysia,'' said
P.K. Basu, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston in Singapore.
``But most of the people I talk to are eager to invest in the
country again.''
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia's decision last year to impose controls made it a
maverick among Asia's economically stricken nations. While most of
its neighbors adhered to the International Monetary Fund's
prescription of open markets and high interest rates, Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad turned his back on the West, even laying
the blame for Asian ills on foreign currency traders.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir had relaxed the controls once before. In February, he
replaced a moratorium on removing foreign money with an exit tax
that penalized investors for withdrawing it in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia has not lifted all capital controls: Its currency, the
ringgit, remains nonconvertible outside the country, with an
exchange rate fixed to the United States dollar. Also, while
investors no longer have to pay a penalty for withdrawing money,
they will still be taxed on their gains.
</P>
<P>
   As with the exit tax, the capital-gains tax is graduated to
encourage investors to leave their money in Malaysia as long as
possible. Profits on investments held for less than a year will be
taxed at 30 percent; with investments held for more than a year,
the rate will be 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think too many people have capital gains on their
Malaysian investments, but for those that do, it's a factor,'' said
Bill Kaye, senior managing director of the Pacific Group, a Hong
Kong hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, Malaysia's experience would seem to vindicate
the 73-year-old Mahathir, who drew worldwide opprobrium when he
imposed the controls last September. He said they were necessary to
protect Malaysia from the destructive ebbs and flows of foreign
capital that had plunged the country into recession and ignited a
regionwide crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Critics here and in the United States predicted that Mahathir
would turn a nation that depended on trade into a pariah. Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter removed Malaysia from its influential Asian
emerging markets stock index. Foreign portfolio investment all but
evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malaysia has chosen to become a heretic, a pariah if you
like,'' Mahathir said in a speech then.
</P>
<P>
   He further alienated investors and others by ousting and
imprisoning his protege, Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim.
Anwar, who received a six-year prison term for what his defenders
say were politically motivated corruption charges and is now being
tried on accusations of sodomy, had advocated a more open financial
policy.
</P>
<P>
   As Malaysia has gradually loosened the capital controls, it has
won back some of the skeptics. Last month, Morgan Stanley
reinstated it on its index, effective next February. Prominent
economists, including Paul Krugman of the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology, note that the controls had some beneficial effects.
</P>
<P>
   By fixing its currency at a relatively low rate of 3.8 ringgit
to the dollar, Malaysia made its exports extremely competitive. Its
booming trade in computers and peripherals is the major reason its
economic output swung from negative statistics to 4.1 percent
growth in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pegged exchange rate is the key to Malaysia's export
success,'' Basu of Credit Suisse said. ``The predictability of the
exchange rate allowed exporters and foreign direct investors to
plan.'' He noted that the new rules could still put off investors.
The capital-gains tax will make it difficult for fund managers to
value their portfolios since they cannot calculate their profits
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye is among those who refuse to put money into Malaysia. ``Who
wants to be told the terms on which you can or cannot invest?'' he
said. ``They're putting themselves at an enormous competitive
disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia has attracted less foreign investment than South Korea
or Thailand, even though its economy has rebounded at least as
strongly as those countries have. But Basu said it was a sign of
Malaysia's strengths that it attracted more than $1 billion in
foreign money between March and July _ a period when it was not
included in Morgan Stanley's stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Basu said it would be a few weeks before one could judge the
magnitude of the capital exodus from Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir, however, said to reporters Wednesday that he was
confident the government could withstand the outflows, which he
estimated at $3 billion to $4 billion. It has accumulated $32
billion in reserves and is running a large current-account surplus.
With exports booming, economists said that at least for now,
Malaysia does not really need foreign money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
