<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROSE-BOOKIE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rose's former bookie hit with assault charge
 &HT;    By Lawrence Budd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The bookie infamous for taking the sports bets
that led to Pete Rose's lifetime ban from major league baseball
could be headed back to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Peters, 42, remained in the Warren County jail Wednesday, a
day after his arrest on charges including assaulting a police
officer. He was scheduled to appear this morning for a preliminary
hearing in Warren County.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Rose was banned from baseball for gambling,
largely based on Peters' records of bets placed on sports events by
the former Cincinnati Reds great, who still holds the career record
for hits.
</P>
<P>
   Peters, who ran his betting operation from Jonathan's Cafe in
Franklin, was convicted of tax evasion and drug trafficking charges
and sent to federal prison for two years in July 1989. After his
release from prison, he returned to Warren County and was working
for a Cincinnati company.
</P>
<P>
   About 3 a.m. Tuesday, Peters was accused of assaulting a
Springboro police officer and running away after being stopped near
the city's eastern limits. According to police reports, Peters was
weaving when he was pulled over. The officer reported that Peters
gave his father's Social Security number, then grabbed ``a small
object'' as he climbed from the car. When the officer spun Peters
forward in an attempt to get the object, Peters elbowed the officer
and escaped, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   According to a police report, the officer was injured and his
uniform was damaged.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested about five hours later by a Warren County
sheriff's deputy and taken to the county jail. On Wednesday, he was
held and bail was set at $50,000. He is charged with driving under
suspension, resisting arrest, falsification and assault.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of the assaulting charge, Peters faces up to 18
months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, his employer, Alan Aronson, was trying to help
Peters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really surprised. The only person he continues to hurt
is himself,'' said Aronson.
</P>
<P>
   Centerville lawyer Bill Knapp said he would be try to convince
the court to reduce Peters' bail amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure exactly what happened just yet,'' Knapp said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
