A7886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-IBM-COMMUNICATIONS-NY     09-01 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-COMMUNICATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM PREPARING TO SEEK ROLE IN COMMUNICATIONS INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM is making a bid to become a leading supplier of technology
to the communications industry, a move that is another step in the
company's campaign to tap the Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   The company is detailing its plan on Thursday with the
introduction of a new line of semiconductors for network equipment,
the creation of a communications research center and an alliance
intended to encourage the spread of industry-standard software in
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   The IBM move comes only two days after it announced a deal with
Cisco Systems, the leading producer of specialized computers for
relaying data traffic over the Internet. Cisco said it would
purchase $2 billion in parts like chips from IBM over the next five
years, and it also agreed to pay IBM for the use of its
intellectual property in networking.
</P>
<P>
   The current IBM plan for the Internet-era communications market
seems sound, analysts say. It is an extension of its accelerating
effort to exploit its industry-leading computer expertise in disk
drives, chips and flat-panel display screens by selling those parts
to other companies. So far this year, IBM has announced parts-sale
deals totaling $30 billion over the next seven years with companies
including Dell Computer, Acer, EMC and Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts noted that while its strategy is a good one, there
is an element of defeat in its parts deal with Cisco. IBM was once
the leader in the computer networking business that Cisco now
dominates. Yet Cisco, they say, moved to make sure that its data
routers adopted networking technology that could communicate with
different kinds of computers and over the Internet. IBM, by
contrast, clung too long to its own proprietary technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cisco would have never been alive if IBM had paid attention to
this business,'' said Howard Anderson, managing director of the
Yankee Group, a research firm. ``IBM bungled what was one of the
biggest market opportunities in communications in decades.''
</P>
<P>
   With its current strategy, IBM faces formidable competitors. The
Intel Corp. on Wednesday announced its own chip entry in the
communications market, and it is in head-to-head competition with
the IBM product. Both companies are introducing a ``network
processor,'' which Intel and IBM are marketing as nimbler, cheaper
alternatives to the custom chips that now power routers and
switches on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The new chips from Intel and IBM are programmable _ more like
the general-purpose microprocessors used in computers _ so that
changes can be made in the software to speed up or redirect the
flow of data packets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are realizing the flexibility that software can
bring to this market,'' said Kevin Reardon, director of strategy
for IBM's technology group.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications customers that have already placed orders
for IBM's network processors include Alcatel, Newbridge Networks
and Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's renowned research laboratories, analysts say, could give
it an edge in supplying the communications market. In the last two
years, IBM has come up with a series of advances in semiconductor
development and manufacturing that enable it to make chips that
consume less power and run at higher speeds, both big potential
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that IBM should have been Cisco in this market,
though that's also true of AT&AMP;T,'' noted G. Dan Hutcheson,
president of VLSI Research, a research firm in San Jose, Calif.
``But the situation today is that IBM is an outstanding R&AMP;D house
and a really good silicon shop. And in the long run, that could
give IBM tremendous leverage in this new world.''
</P>
<P>
   To focus its research, IBM is establishing a Communications
Research and Development Center, comprised of scientists at its
labs in Switzerland, Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And to try to encourage the adoption of industry-standard
software for the programmable chips, IBM said it would support the
open architecture announced by the C-Port Corp. in February. In
addition, IBM said that C-Port, a start-up company in North
Andover, Mass., had selected IBM to build its C-5 network
processor. For IBM, the manufacturing pact with a coming rival in
the new field is another way that the computer giant is selling its
expertise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
