<SLUG> BC-BIRTHCONTROL-MUSEUM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM PRESERVES CONTRACEPTIVES OF YORE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Sider to BIRTH-CONTROL) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The perfect contraceptive remains elusive, but we've come a long
way since women in China drank mercury to combat fertility 4,000
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Women have also, over the course of time, swallowed carrot seeds
and sipped alcoholic teas brewed from dried beaver testicles to
prevent pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the second century, they used vaginal plugs made of
gummy agents such as honey combined with the dung of crocodiles and
elephants, according to one display at the History of Contraception
Museum in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   And that's all just the beginning of a long human (but sometimes
hardly humane) history of birth control methods that vary from the
practical to the practically silly.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the IUD dates back at least 3,000 years when,
according to legend, smooth pebbles were inserted into the uteruses
of camels to prevent them from becoming pregnant during long desert
crossings. Cervical caps gained popularity with Casanova, who in
the mid-1700s advocated the use of half a squeezed lemon to cap the
human cervix and prevent conception.
</P>
<P>
   What is probably the first-ever written prescription for birth
control dates back to 1550 B.C. and is carefully printed out on a
scroll of papyrus on display at the contraceptive museum:
</P>
<P>
   ``To make a woman cease to become pregnant for one year, two
years or three years, tips of acacia and dates are triturated with
honey. Seed wool is moistened therewith and placed in her vulva.''
</P>
<P>
   The prescription from the Ebers Papyrus may actually have been
effective, says Percy Skuy, a past president of the Ortho-McNeil
drug company and founder of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acacia is a gum which breaks down to lactic acid, a known
spermicide that's even used today in some contraceptive jellies,''
Skuy points out in ``Tales of Contraception,'' his chronicle of the
museum and its unusual artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the ages, people have pursued the right to control
fertility, Skuy says. He began collecting contraceptive artifacts
as a product manager for Ortho Pharmaceutical, a company
specializing in the manufacture of family planning products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to search long and hard for some of these. People
just didn't save old contraceptives,'' says Walter Masanic,
director of public affairs for Janssen-Ortho, as the company is now
called in Canada. ``It is interesting that people thousands of
years ago were just as interested in controlling their own
fertility as people are today.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum, displaying more than 600 contraceptive items _ 300
IUDs _ is open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our exhibits come from the strangest places,'' Masanic says.
``We have one 14-karat-gold intracervical device that a lady just
brought to us and said, `This belongs to you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband had been a pharmacist, and when he died, she sold
the family business. She was removing personal items when she came
across the little gold device, and without knowing what it was, she
had a jeweler drill a hole in it and attach it to her charm
bracelet as a memento.
</P>
<P>
   Several years later, someone at a cocktail party saw the charm
and asked her if she knew what it was. When she learned, she had it
removed, and later took it to the museum to share with the public.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
