<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-COURT-NOMINATIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI TO NAME TWO TO HIGHEST COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- With the opening of the court's session nearly upon
him, Governor Paul Cellucci is expected to announce two nominations
for the Supreme Judicial Court Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift and the governor's
chief legal counsel, Leonard Lewin, were expected to wrap up the
interviews for the vacancies by Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate, appeals court Judge Francis Spina, appears to be
a strong contender for one of the slots.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Cellucci would like to announce his decision
sometime Thursday, if background checks on the candidates can be
completed in time.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares to make the final decision, Cellucci has kept the
process under tight wraps. One source said the governor, as of late
Wednesday, had not made up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Cellucci has been impressed by Spina, 52, who is
from Pittsfied. He was appointed to the bench in 1997 by Weld.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci is also looking at two other men, Christopher
Armstrong, a 63-year old appeals court justice who was appointed by
governor Francis Sargent, and Daniel Toomey, 55, a Superior Court
judge.
</P>
<P>
   Among the women Cellucci is considering are: Judith Cowin, a
superior court judge appointed by Weld and a former prosecutor with
strong Republican credentials; Margaret Sosman, 48, a superior
court judge who founded an all-woman law firm in Boston; Cynthia
Cohen, 50, a civil litigator with a Boston law firm; and Margot
Botsford, 52, a superior Court judge who was appointed by former
governor Michael S. Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Wednesday, in a suprise move, the governor's council
delayed until at least next week setting a hearing date for
Cellucci's nominee to be chief justice of the court, Margaret
Marshall. Cellucci said councilors were ``dragging their feet'' and
he tweaked them for trying to gain some media attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would be unfortunate, particularly given the
quality of this nomination,'' Cellucci said. ``This is probably
their moment in the spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Council Michael Callahan, who represents Marshall's district,
said he had not had a chance to talk with her and therefore wanted
to wait a week before setting a date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
