A7895 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SCHOOLS-AUDIT-HNS &LR;      09-01 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-AUDIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT SUGGESTS MINORITY, POOR STUDENTS BEING DUMPED IN ALTERNATIVE
PROGRAMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state's alternative education programs _
where violent and chronically misbehaving students are supposed to
be sent _ have become dumping grounds for minority and poor
students, a new state audit suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, school officials do not consistently remove violent
students _ even those who bring knives and firearms to school _
from regular classrooms to alternative school settings as required
by law, nor do they test these troubled students to see if they are
learning, according to a state auditor's report on Texas' Safe
Schools Program.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released Wednesday, is based on preliminary data
from the 1997-98 school year, the second year of operation of
alternative education campuses. The state spent about $50 million
on the two programs in that year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, under the Safe Schools Act, the Texas Legislature
established two types of school settings for troubled youths _
juvenile justice and disciplinary alternative education programs.
The Juvenile Justice Alternative Education Programs, or JJAEP,
exist in the state's 22 largest counties and are overseen by the
Juvenile Probation Commission; each school district must operate
its own disciplinary alternative education program, or DAEP, which
is overseen by the Texas Education Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The auditor's report, however, found that by the second year of
operation, minority, poor, special-education and students at risk
of dropping out of school had already become disproportionately
represented in alternative education programs.
</P>
<P>
   That does not come as a surprise to some.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected that a disproportionate number of students that we
would serve unfortunately would be represented by minority
populations, and that has been borne out,'' said David Wingard, who
runs Harris County's Juvenile Justice Alternative Education Program
_ the largest of its kind in the state with 934 students in the
1997-98 school year. That expectation, he added, is explainable in
large part by socio-economic factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minorities as a whole are disproportionately poor,'' Wingard
said. ``Income relates directly to academic achievement. We all
know that. Kids who are frustrated academically tend to act up, and
poor people tend to be powerless to fight the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Wingard added, however, that Harris county officials ``have
tried to do everything we know we can do'' to ensure that its
program does not become a dumping ground for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the auditor's report found that while minorities constitute
55 percent of all Texas public school students, they account for 72
percent of all students in juvenile justice programs and 64 percent
in the school district-run disciplinary programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some programs' large percentage of minority students
merely reflects the composition of the community, it may point to
inconsistent application of discipline policies as well,'' the
report states.
</P>
<P>
   The report also concludes that the law designed to make Texas
classrooms safer may not be achieving that goal because school
districts do not always expel violent students to JJAEPs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, auditors found at least 850 on-campus incidents
during the 1997-98 school year in which school officials did not
expel students to juvenile justice programs as required by law.
Those 850 incidents included 255 instances in which students
carried illegal knives to school; 218 other instances in which
students had weapons such as explosives and brass knuckles; 196
incidents of aggravated assault and 74 firearms incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some school officials base their expulsion or removal
decisions on local criteria that differ from the (law), while
others may be unaware of them,'' the report states. ``As a result,
some students who commit serious and violent offenses remain in
regular classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, JJAEPs serve expelled students who commit
serious or violent offenses and DAEPs serve students who are
removed from their regular classrooms for disruptive behavior or
felonies committed off campus. DAEPs may be located on the regular
school campus or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors also faulted the alternative education programs for
failing to track student performance to determine if they are
learning or improving their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Such practices, the auditors said, increase ``the risk of
charges of discrimination, inequity and civil rights violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Wingard, of the Harris County JJAEP, said his program measures
student performance in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a lot of money and a lot of effort to make sure that
the students are academically well served, and well served from the
standpoint of a lot of the social factors that negatively impact on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wingard added that he has long been troubled by the lack of
academic standards required of DAEPs under TEA regulations. TEA,
for example, has allowed alternative programs to be rated on
performance measures other than the state-mandated Texas Assessment
of Academic Skills test.
</P>
<P>
   Under the alternative accountability process, he added,
alternative education programs could be rated acceptable even
though their students may not be getting credit for their courses
because they miss too much school.
</P>
<P>
   TEA spokeswoman Debbie Graves Ratcliffe said the agency expects
some of the auditor's findings to change once complete data is
available. For example, some school districts miscoded student
disciplinary incidents, thus falsely inflating the number of
expellable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who send in the reports tend to be clerks who may not
have'' all the training on the Safe Schools Act requirements that
school administrators and teachers get, Ratcliffe added.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe added that TEA agrees with many of the audit's
findings and has already begun to implement the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the auditor's recommendations are calls for:
</P>
<P>
   _ Uniform measurements for alternative education programs,
including graduation and recidivism rates.
</P>
<P>
   _ TEA review of the criteria schools use for placing students in
alternative programs
</P>
<P>
   _ The establishment of more accurate data reporting methods.
</P>
<P>
   _ Additional training of school employees on the Safe Schools
Act.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
