<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-UMPS02-COX     09-01 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Umpires left feeling blue
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the last pitch in the last inning of the last
game Wednesday night, baseball changed. Blue turned a lighter
shade.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations of 22 umpires _ some of them the most
experienced arbiters in the game _ become official after the
conclusion of Wednesday's schedule, initiating an unprecedented job
turnover in the most demanding officiating job in American sport.
</P>
<P>
   The late Bill Klem, the first umpire admitted to the Hall of
Fame, was correct in his famed observance, ``It ain't nothin' 'til
I call it.'' Any ump worth a whisk broom can call this one only an
unadulterated mess.
</P>
<P>
   Plotting last July to improve job security via mass
resignations, the Major League Baseball Umpires Association has
instead facilitated the departure of nearly one-third of its
membership. Some of those departures _ NL strike zone phantom Eric
Gregg; AL veteran Richie Garcia, who blew the Jeffrey Maier home
run call in the 1996 ALCS and then signed autographs the next day _
do not seem ill-timed.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more painful. AL veteran Drew Coble has been tending
to his wife and her bout with terminal cancer. NL veteran Terry
Tata has worked seven postseason series in the 1990s alone. Both
resignations were accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five minor-league umpires stand signed and ready to step
into full-time jobs today. Throughout, there have been reports
through the umps' grapevine that many resignees will be hired back,
that it is posturing before real contract talks begin in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball has just had so many labor issues over the years,''
Hall of Famer George Brett said. ``Each one has caused work
stoppages and lock-outs and a cancellation of a World Series. It
took years for baseball to rebound from that. I don't think it can
afford another black eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, what is the solution? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do most umps.
</P>
<P>
   Here are stories about two men caught in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, rook
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nauert took out a loan 13 years ago and went to umpiring
school on a dare from a friend. He failed to get his certification
and slunk back to his Louisville home to work Little League games
and repay the loan, aware only that umpiring was ``the most
intriguing thing I'd ever come across.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later _ after securing another loan _ Nauert returned to
become a top qualifier out of Harry Wendelstedt's Florida ump
school and went straight into the minors, setting a course that
finally last April 1 landed him one of two vacant major-league
jobs. He cried when he got the news.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, he did not cry when he was informed in July his
resignation had been accepted by the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn how to shut out the distractions and put everything
out of your mind,'' he said. ``To say you don't think about
(resigning) is really not true because you do think about it. But
I've always approached this job as professional as possible. It's
something I dearly enjoy, to the point that I love doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nauert, who has lived in Atlanta since 1990, just celebrated the
birth of his and wife Kim's third child, Danielle, in June. A
first-year umpire draws $75,000 a year and now they could afford to
buy their first home. Nauert has no qualms with this initial
experience with his union.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys laid their lives on the line in 1979 (in an earlier
strike) for older umpires and I'll lay my life on the line for
these guys,'' he said. ``They all need to be back on the field,
including myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Nauert has received strong marks for his work this year, leaving
some wondering what baseball's front office motives really are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of young umpires come and go,'' said Jerry
Crawford, his crew chief. ``This kid is the absolute prototype of
what baseball is trying to hire.''
</P>
<P>
   Nauert declines to question his fate. His mother was just 53
when she died of cancer in 1993, leaving him with an object lesson
in how harshly life can treat the living. Now 36, he will be
recalling that lesson tonight
</P>
<P>
   A call from New York
</P>
<P>
   The general manager of the Columbus Clippers had just sent to
the umpires' dressing room for Marvin Hudson. He was back working
the Class AAA International League that night of July 22, after
returning from a fill-in job in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson has progressed quickly. This season is just his eighth as
a professional umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just gotten back from Montreal that day,'' he said. ``It
was about 15 minutes before walking out on the field when I got
called up to the GM's office. I thought I was going up there
because they were expecting a rain delay or something.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he just said Mr. Coleman had called and wanted me to call
him back. And I had to work the plate that night, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Coleman'' was National League president Len Coleman, and
the returned call later than night bore an invitation for Hudson to
become a full-time NL ump.
</P>
<P>
   His work would begin today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me by total surprise,'' Hudson said. ``I had the
answer that night, but I also wanted to make a couple phone
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson has been calling baseball since he was a student at
Marietta High School in the early 1980s, working T-ball games on
the weekends. A four-year career as a catcher at Piedmont College _
he had a failed tryout with the Braves _ had confirmed his feel for
the game and though he set out hoping just to work local prep and
college games, older umps advised that he shoot a little higher.
The period between Joe Brinkman's umpire school and Coleman's phone
call passed quickly. ``Getting the job the way I got it, that's not
the way you want to go about getting it. But I'm here,'' said
Hudson, married for 16 years with two children. ``I want the guys
to get their jobs back, just as bad as anyone who's been up here
all year. I don't want to see anybody lose their job.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as me and my family, I haven't celebrated yet. And I
won't celebrate until the other guys get their jobs back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
