<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7899 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-COMETS-LIBERTY-HN     09-01 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-LIBERTY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ The instant the 1999 WNBA finalists had been
established, someone from the league should have dashed to a store
for napkins, party hats and souvenirs with the inscription ``Old
Home Week.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Comets and the New York Liberty, opponents tonight in Game 1
of the best-of-three WNBA Championship Series at Madison Square
Garden, are quite familiar with this little gathering. They were
the first two teams to tussle for a title in 1997, the WNBA's
start-up year.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the championship was a single-game affair, and the
Comets won 65-51 at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That year was very special,'' Comets guard Cynthia Cooper said
Wednesday. ``It was the inaugural season, the first of any kind. It
was the first time in America that you had a major professional
women's basketball league, actually two leagues (including the
now-defunct American Basketball League).
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to make history. We were writing our names in
the history books. This is two years later, and we're facing New
York again.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case this year, when the Comets went 26-6 in the
regular season and beat the Los Angeles Sparks in the Western
Conference finals, the Comets in '97 were the class of the league
(18-10) and beat Charlotte to advance to the championship against
New York.
</P>
<P>
   It was close through the first half. Then Cooper, Tina Thompson,
Kim Perrot and the rest of the Comets really went to work over the
final 20 minutes to claim the inaugural title trophy.
</P>
<P>
   There was joy throughout the organization. Leslie Alexander's
belief in Van Chancellor, the ``fifth choice'' for coach whom
Alexander hired with implicit instructions to turn the Comets into
a winner, had been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor delivered the third world championship in four years
to Alexander, whose Rockets had prevailed in the 1994 and 1995 NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   So often denied the trip to the NCAA Women's Final Four he
wanted badly through 19 seasons as coach at Mississippi, Chancellor
finally had his cherished diamond-and-gold ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I look at that ring, I just get happy,'' Chancellor
said. ``It symbolizes so much for me. We've got two rings now, and
I still wear that first one.''
</P>
<P>
   The quest is on now for a third ring, ``No. 3 for No. 10,'' a
tribute to Perrot, who died of cancer Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   It's uppermost in the mind of Sheryl Swoopes. So, too, is the
chance to party with a familiar foe in an effort to salve some
personal wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year when we played New York in the championship, I
didn't really contribute. I didn't have a whole lot to do with us
winning the title that year,'' said Swoopes, who sat out the first
half of 1997 to give birth to her son. ``To me, this one's a little
more special and maybe even a bigger challenge for me personally,
to come out here tomorrow and kind of set the tone for the whole
series. We want to, hopefully, jump on them early.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a departure from the way the Comets began the
Western Conference finals against the Sparks. Still drained
emotionally from the death of Perrot, the Comets were easy fodder
and lost Game 1 75-60. They've done a 180 since.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team for the last few games has been playing in a way
that Kim would like to see,'' Chancellor said. ``They've faced all
kinds of obstacles and never once gave up. We were down by nine
points to LA (in the first half of Game 3 Monday night) and found a
way to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the way Kim played. She never gave up. She never gave
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cooper: ``I don't know exactly why teams can't knock us
out, even though I don't think that's exactly true. Teams have come
out and played extremely well and beat us. It's been proven that we
are beatable, we are human.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what we have to do is maintain our composure, concentration
and focus. And we've been able to do that. We've done it more
consistently maybe than other teams have done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're one of the more talented teams in the league.
But talent means nothing unless you play with heart. And I think
this team has a lot of heart and has demonstrated that throughout
our short WNBA career.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Garden lights go on tonight, Thompson believes
vengeance will be on the minds of the Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have been the first-ever WNBA champions, so there
might be a little bit of personal feelings there,'' she said.
``It'll definitely bring a lot of emotions to the series. They came
out and played hard (in 1997) and played us tough. I think we
expect the same thing in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets-Liberty rivalry actually began early in the '97
season, when the teams were both in the Eastern Conference and
played each other three times over the first 10 days of the season.
It received a bit more fuel this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets and Liberty played twice in the preseason, each
winning at home, then faced off twice more during the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets played dreadfully in a 74-71 road loss Aug. 8,
turning the ball over seven times in the final six minutes. But it
had been a quite different story at Compaq Center on July 3. The
Comets held New York to 15 first-half points and 50 overall. The
Liberty hit just 21.9 percent of its shots from the field, a WNBA
record low.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets and Liberty are tied at 5 in the overall series. But
the Comets own that pleasant 1-0 edge in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even thinking about 1997,'' Chancellor said. ``I'm
thinking about, `Can we beat the New York Liberty, right here in
Madison Square Garden, the toughest environment for us?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed (the first title game with New York), but all their
players have forgotten about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not. Let the party begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
