<SLUG> BC-HILTON-PROMUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILTON HOTELS DISCUSSES DEAL WITH PROMUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn . )  (dal) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hilton Hotels Corp., which was left standing at the altar
after its two most recent attempts to buy other hotel companies, on
Wednesday confirmed that it was in talks to acquire the Promus
Hotel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Although both companies declined to disclose details of the
negotiations, which were reported Wednesday in the Wall Street
Journal, Promus has a market value of $2.5 billion, and a deal
would most likely be worth more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton, which has about 275 hotels, had net income of $298
million last year on revenue of $1.77 billion. Promus, based in
Memphis, had net income of $154 million on revenue of $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Hilton fell 56.25 cents on Wednesday, to $11.6875,
while Promus rose $2.9375, to $32.
</P>
<P>
   Promus is one of the largest hotel companies in the United
States, according to Business Travel News, the trade publication.
Its holdings range from limited-service properties to suites and
full-service properties. Its hotels include Doubletree, Red Lion,
Embassy Suites, Hampton Inn and Homewood Suites. The Promus brands
are scattered throughout the United States but are also expanding
in Canada, Mexico and Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   The Promus portfolio consists of about 1,000 franchised
properties, almost 200 properties under management contracts, and
ownership of 62 properties. Its 192,000 rooms rank it eighth, well
behind giants like the Cendant Corp. (529,000); Bass Hotels and
Resorts, the owner of Holiday Inns (462,500), and Marriott
International (328,300).
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Promus have been in a slump since late May, when the
company lowered its earnings-per-share growth rate to single digits
from the midteens. The main reason for lowering the estimate was
Promus' difficulties in trying to rebrand many Red Lion Inns and
Hotels as Doubletrees. Doubletree Hotels, Guest Suites and Resorts
bought Red Lion in 1996, and Promus merged with Doubletree in
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton properties, most of which carry the Hilton name, are
among the favorites of business travelers. And while the
acquisition would give Hilton a broad range of properties, some
analysts wonder about the fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it is not easy for us to see how the companies would
fit together, their potential union is not the strangest concept we
have ever contemplated,'' said Jason Ader, an analyst at Bear
Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorn Hanson of PricewaterhouseCoopers said that although the
deal at reported levels ``would be dilutive to Hilton's
shareholders,'' it would also be Hilton's entry into the
extended-stay market, a fast-growing segment that encompasses
guests who spend at least five nights.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton lost the bidding for the ITT Corp. in 1997 and for
Wyndham International, formerly Patriot American, this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
