<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (dw)  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   H&AMP;R BLOCK AGREES TO BUY A DISCOUNT BROKERAGE FIRM
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;R Block said that it had agreed to buy Olde Financial, the
parent of the nation's fourth-largest discount brokerage firm, for
$850 million in cash, intensifying its push to become a broad-based
provider of financial services to Middle America.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is the latest in a two-year buying spree by H&AMP;R
Block, which has bought eight accounting firms, two mortgage
brokers and another brokerage firm. Analysts said the purchase made
sense, but investors sent H&AMP;R Block's shares down $4.625, to $51.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHER BID IS OFFERED FOR FRONTIER
</P>
<P>
   Trying to reinvigorate its flagging attempt to acquire Frontier,
Global Crossing has offered to modestly sweeten its bid in exchange
for Frontier's commitment to spurn other suitors, executives close
to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR STOCK GAUGES RISE SHARPLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks finished higher Wednesday as bargain hunting overshadowed
interest-rate jitters. The Dow Jones industrial average gained
108.60 points, or 1 percent, to 10,937.88. The Nasdaq composite
index jumped 11.45 points, or four-tenths of a percent, to
2,750.80. The S.&AMP;P. 500-stock index rose 10.66 points, or
eight-tenths of a percent, to 1,331.07.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.08 percent from
6.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
   HILTON HOTELS IN TALKS FOR PROMUS
</P>
<P>
   Hilton Hotels, which was left standing at the altar after its
two most recent attempts to buy other hotel companies, confirmed
that it was in talks to buy Promus Hotel, which has brands like
Doubletree and Embassy Suites.
</P>
<P>
   IBM SEEKS TO TAP WEB MARKET
</P>
<P>
   IBM is introducing a new line of semiconductors for network
equipment as part of its bid to become a leading supplier of
technology to the communications industry, another step in its
campaign to tap the Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   IRS QUESTIONS CASH-BALANCE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Cash-balance pension plans have drawn heavy criticism lately
because they often reduce the pensions of older workers. A memo
written by an Internal Revenue Service district director one year
ago stated that one cash-balance pension plan may violate
age-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   NEW LEADER TAKES OVER TRADE GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Mike Moore of New Zealand began his first day as leader of the
World Trade Organization already facing several challenges. First
on the agenda are global trade talks in Seattle in November. But
some trade experts say they think he will have a second full-time
job mending fences with envoys from developing countries who
supported his rival for Director General.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA TO DECLARE BANK INSOLVENT
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean government plans to declare the ailing
Seoulbank insolvent on Thursday before injecting billions of
dollars into it after talks to sell it broke down.
</P>
<P>
   NEW EDITOR NAMED AT MADEMOISELLE
</P>
<P>
   Mandi Norwood, the editor of British Cosmopolitan, was named
editor in chief of Conde Nast's Mademoiselle magazine.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL HIRES FUND MANAGER
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has hired James McCall as a fund manager, ending a
legal skirmish that pitted the firm and Mr. McCall against his
former employer, Pilgrim Baxter.
</P>
<P>
   LEADING INDICATORS UP 0.3%
</P>
<P>
   The Index of Leading Economic Indicators, a key barometer of
future activity, rose three-tenths of a percent in July, the same
rate as in the prior two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
