<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-OLDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H &AMP; R BLOCK TO BUY OLDE FOR $850 MILLION IN CASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Mich . , Ariz., Calif., New England, Ill.)  (dal) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intensifying its push to become a broad-based provider of
financial services to Middle America, H &AMP; R Block Inc. said
Wednesday that it had agreed to buy the Olde Financial Corp., the
parent of the nation's fourth-largest discount brokerage firm, for
$850 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   While the acquisition is Block's biggest ever, the company,
which is based in Kansas City, Mo., has been on a spending spree
over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   During that period, the company, which made its name as a
nuts-and-bolts tax preparation service, has bought eight accounting
firms, two mortgage brokers and Birchtree Financial Services,
another brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company opened H &AMP; R Block Financial Centers in
four markets during the 1999 tax season. By the end of this year,
it plans to open 70 such offices in Arizona, California, Illinois
and New England, offering financial services, home mortgages and
tax preparation under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the acquisition of Olde, we will have in place the major
building blocks to achieve our vision of becoming the preferred tax
and financial partner for our clients while offering an attractive
product portfolio for new Block customers,'' Frank L. Salizzoni,
the company's president and chief executive, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   From a strategic perspective, analysts said, the Olde purchase
makes sense. But investors were less than thrilled, and a big
credit rating agency said the way Block intended to finance the
acquisition was risky.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Block, which have run up sharply this year, slumped
$4.625, or 8.3 percent, to $51.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface, this deal looks like it should be good news,''
said Alexander Paris Jr., an analyst at Barrington Research in
Chicago. ``But the stock had been priced for perfection, and there
is execution risk here.''
</P>
<P>
   Block intends to borrow in the short term to pay for Olde,
adding to its debt load. Company executives said they intended to
put the Option One Mortgage Corp., which Block bought in April 1997
from Fleet Financial Services for $190 million in cash, up for
sale. Proceeds from that sale would be used to retire the debt.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement announcing the acquisition, H &AMP; R Block said
Olde, which is privately held, would add 6 to 8 cents a share in
its 2000 fiscal year, which ends April 30, and 20 to 30 cents a
share in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the deal raised eyebrows at Moody's Investors
Service. The rating agency placed Block's $1.15 billion under
review Wednesday for possible downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Moody's has an A-minus rating on Block's debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Logically, this deal holds together,'' said Steven Nelson, a
vice president and senior analyst at Moody's. ``But to fund any
sort of acquisition with short-term commercial paper while another
transaction, the sale of Option One, is in flux, is an aggressive
strategy. There have been a number of franchises similar to Option
One that have been put up for sale and have not been sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Olde's brokerage unit, the Olde Discount Corp., based in
Detroit, has 181 offices in 35 states and 1,200 representatives.
The firm has more than 600,000 active accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The company is just emerging from a scandal that last year
resulted in a $7 million settlement of allegations that its
management practices in the early 1990s encouraged its brokers to
defraud investors.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Securities and Exchange Commission contended
that Olde Discount's brokers promoted high-commission stocks over
lower-commission stocks more suitable to clients' needs. Brokers
who failed to sell their quota of high-commission stocks were
forced to forfeit their clients to other Olde Discount brokers, the
SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory agency gave clients who had maintained accounts
with Olde from 1992 through 1995 until March 9 this year to file
claims against Olde Discount for reparations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those penalties, the New York Stock Exchange
fined the company $1 million for bribing an exchange official to
obtain waivers of job requirements for more than 285 employees
between 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Mark A. Ernst, who was recruited to H &AMP; R Block from American
Express Financial Services in 1998 and is now the company's chief
operating officer, said in a telephone interview that Olde's
problems were behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mid-1990s, they made wholesale management changes and
changed the culture throughout the organization,'' he said. ``We
did extensive due diligence to make sure those issues are well
behind the firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Ernst's experience at American Express would be
critical in determining the success of H &AMP; R Block's
diversification drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Ernst is a highly qualified executive, one who was an
architect of American Express' foray into many of these same
markets,'' Paris said. ``He has done this before as part of a team.
Now, he will be doing this on his own.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
