<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7910 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-BUSCH-ART-2     09-01 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BUSCH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN KILLED BY POLICE SHOWED THE WORLD 2 DIFFERENT FACES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Israel)  (Eds: Absence of first name for Rabbi Nachman is CQ. See also
NY-POLICE-SHOOTING) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ten years ago, at age 21 and with a promising medical
career in front of him, Gidone Busch learned that he had an
incurable kidney disease.
</P>
<P>
   It was that knowledge, his family and friends said, that
capsized all the plans he had for his life, driving him on a search
for spiritual enlightenment in Orthodox Judaism and sometimes
sending him skidding into immobilizing depressions.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, he was a sweet-natured young man everyone
called Gary, who loved music and the quiet grace of celebrating the
Jewish Sabbath with friends. But Busch could also slide into a
deeply troubled and disoriented world of his own frenetic prayers,
fears and symbols.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides _ often incompatible and impenetrable _ followed
him to his death.
</P>
<P>
   The police officers who shot and killed him in Brooklyn on
Monday evening said Busch, tall and skinny at 6 foot 3 and 159
pounds, attacked them with a hammer outside his tiny basement
apartment in the Borough Park neighborhood. On that hammer, Busch,
31, a devoutly religious man who prayed so loudly the neighbors
complained, had carved the four Hebrew letters signifying the name
of God.
</P>
<P>
   A Brooklyn grand jury will begin hearing evidence next week to
determine whether the shooting of Busch by police was legally
justified, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn District Attorney Charles Hynes said that a grand jury
would be convened on Tuesday to examine the circumstances
surrounding the shooting. ``The facts and circumstances of this
incident warrant a careful review by the grand jury,'' Hynes said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury will look at the crucial nine-minute period
between the time police received a 911 call about a threatening man
wielding a hammer and the time the officers who responded called
for an ambulance to take Busch to a hospital, a law-enforcement
official said. The jury will also examine Busch's mental history
and see how well he was served by the mental health establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his good times, he was an outgoing fellow and would talk
and sing psalms around the Sabbath table,'' said Rabbi Yakov
Saacks, the director of the Chai Center in Dix Hills, N.Y., where
Busch grew up in suburban comfort on Long Island. ``In his bad
times, perhaps when he wasn't taking his medication, he didn't look
up from his prayer book or his food.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two different Gary Busches,'' the rabbi added. ``I
loved them both.''
</P>
<P>
   As they prepared for his funeral, Busch's family said he was a
gentle, if distressed, young man who never hurt anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a mental illness, no question about it,'' said his
father, Norman Busch, a retired dentist living in the Long Island
town of Bay Shore. ``But he was not a violent person. He was never
violent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Busch was hospitalized involuntarily for psychiatric
treatment three times at a hospital on Long Island, where doctors
said he had made threats to his parents and evinced signs of
paranoid schizophrenia. Two years ago, he entered a residential
program for the mentally ill in Borough Park, but soon checked
himself out against the advice of doctors who said they did not
believe he was capable of living on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his family said they did not recognize the man portrayed
in published reports since the shooting as behaving so erratically
that his neighbors called police, and as lunging with a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not what he was or who he is,'' his mother, Doris
Busch Boskey, said, weeping. ``They've created a person to explain
away or excuse what happened and what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch was studying to be a doctor at Mount Sinai Medical School
when he discovered, when all the students tested their own urine
sample as part of a classroom exercise, that he suffered from an
immune system problem. He was given a diagnosis of IgA nephropathy,
a disease that can lead to kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, his relatives said, Busch showed no signs of mental
instability. But the diagnosis shook him deeply and kicked off what
his father described as a ``series of incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that he thought he was going to die,'' recalled his
mother. ``It's just that it couldn't be cured. You constantly
worry. You can lose function of your kidneys, you might need
dialysis. It's on your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch continued his studies for a short time, but in his third
year of medical school, he told his family he wanted to drop out.
He read books on philosophy. He immersed himself in his favorite
classical music and jazz. He talked of finding a spiritual path to
well-being, of exploring the meaning of life. His own religion,
Judaism, called him and he moved to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Busch spent much of the next seven years there, trying out
different trends and practices within the religion. He studied
Hebrew and the Torah in a conventional Orthodox yeshiva in
Jerusalem. Drawn to the more mystical Hasidic movement, he delved
into the messianic Lubavitch sect.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, his family said, he drifted to the city of Safad in
northern Israel to study at a school dedicated to the mystical
teachings of Rabbi Nachman, founder of the Breslover Hasidic sect
who died in 1810.
</P>
<P>
   The school and its graduates, however, are not associated with
the mainstream Breslover sect, which has shunned them as a fringe
group that has gone too far in making a cult out of the rabbi's
memory. The group is known in Israel for spray-painting Nachman's
name on walls and bouncing up and down, as if in a trance, on
street corners.
</P>
<P>
   Busch threw himself into the group, worrying his relatives back
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get involved in the inner circle of a fringe group,
they are very warm and welcoming,'' Saacks said. ``But they had a
very narrow focus. They were only reading Nachman's books, only
discussing his teachings, only telling the message of their teacher
_ which I'm not sure what it is _ and not focusing on much else.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Busch had recently told family and friends that he realized the
group was too extreme and assured them that he was gravitating
toward the more mainstream Breslover Hasidic sect in Brooklyn and
in suburban communities like Lakewood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed drawn, still, into his own sometimes inscrutable
world of extremes, where his absorbing passion for religion turned
into a fervor that seemed to amplify his episodes of mental
instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bounced in and out of it,'' Saacks said. ``Last January, he
said he felt he was maybe too entrenched and saw that he had to
pull back. I welcomed that. And on Aug. 8, the last time I spoke to
him, he was back in the Breslov swing of things with `Rebbe Nachman
said this and Rebbe Nachman said that' and this very insular
approach to life.''
</P>
<P>
   What his family saw were periods of quiet, sometimes desperate
depression. His mother said Busch once kicked a hole in the wall of
his room in her house and became very agitated. ``He kept saying,
`I can't believe I did that. I love this house. I grew up in this
house,''' Mrs. Boskey recalled. Her son kept covering the patched
hole with a towel. Shortly after that, he became so depressed he
was hospitalized, she said.
</P>
<P>
   About three weeks ago, Netanya Ullman ran into Busch on the
subway in Manhattan. They had met briefly when both were studying
in Safad five years ago, she said, and when they met again, there
was an instant rapport.
</P>
<P>
   The couple decided to get married, she said, and spoke
constantly of Busch's interpretations of Nachman's teachings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about talking to God out loud and going into nature
and praying and very intense meditation,'' Ms. Ullman said.
</P>
<P>
   When he meditated, he would play music very loudly, she said.
Recently, he took to dancing with the hammer, which he called his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put God's name on it to make it something that would bring
holiness into the world,'' Ms. Ullman said. ``He'd go outside and
dance with it and raise it up and move slowly. He was like bringing
down light from his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was for holy purposes,'' she added. ``He wanted to bring
people closer and his way of doing that was this pushing toward the
boundaries of what's acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch's behavior drew comments from his neighbors in the
Orthodox Jewish neighborhood where he had moved last December in
the apparent hope of submerging himself in the close-knit religious
culture.
</P>
<P>
   But his family said he usually traveled to Orthodox communities
in upstate New York and New Jersey to celebrate the Sabbath, the
most important and family-centered event of the week for observant
Jews. He did not seem to connect with his neighbors, who said after
the shooting that they regarded Busch as an oddball whose ecstatic
dancing and music did not fit in.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, his parents said that Busch seemed content with his new
life. He had taken a course in computer programming and was
thinking of starting a business designing Web pages. Ms. Ullman
said he told her he wanted to start trading stocks on the Internet
and earn a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   But there were disturbing signs.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, he stopped by his brother Glenn's law office.
``He seemed agitated, but OK,'' his brother said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ullman said he stopped wearing his prescription eyeglasses.
When police came on Monday night, she suggested, he might not have
seen them as anything more than blurry threatening figures. ``Who
knows what he saw in his mind?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the tiny basement apartment, police said they found strange
scribblings on signs on the wall. One spelled out the word
``police,'' as ``pointedly off-wing litigating intensely careful
errand-deliverers.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, police said, Busch struck a passing car with his
hammer, and when the driver stopped and rolled down his window, he
swung at him and broke his nose.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, someone called 911 to report that a man at
Busch's address was menacing children in the neighborhood. When
officers arrived to question him, they said, he waved the hammer at
them.
</P>
<P>
   His family and friends, outraged by the shooting, said they
believe Busch was frightened and panicked by the armed police
officers. They said he was a spiritual man who wished for nothing
but peace, but often sought it in vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was happy with the path he had taken,'' his father said.
``But with mental disease, you do have periods of high emotion and
periods of calm. He was a loving wonderful person, but he was never
violent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
