<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COMMODITIES-MARKETPLA     09-01 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMODITIES-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED RULE COULD COVER UP COMMODITY TRADING VOLATILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The regulator of the nation's commodities markets is proposing a
rule change that would allow commodity trading advisers to smooth
out past returns in the performance records they present to
prospective investors.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, made by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission
and supported by the industry, could bolster business by making
commodities trading look less prone to wild swings, which have been
known to frighten away potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, commodity advisers would be able to use a
hypothetical account size to figure their returns for all sales and
promotional materials. Commodity advisers are now required to
calculate their returns based on the actual amount invested _ the
same way returns are calculated across the securities industry. But
commodity advisers would be able to choose a hypothetical account
larger than that chosen by the typical customer _ a size that may
not represent even one customer's account.
</P>
<P>
   Using a hypothetical account, or what the industry calls a
nominal account, that is larger than the typical customer's account
would have the effect of smoothing out the monthly performance of a
manager because his actual gains or losses would be judged as a
percentage of a larger investment base. That would make both losses
and gains smaller in percentage terms than that experienced by most
customers.
</P>
<P>
   George H. Painter, one of two administrative law judges that
hear cases brought before the CFTC, opposes the rule change. Using
a hypothetical account size opens up the possibility of fraud and
unrealistic expectations of good returns with low risk, he said.
``My problem is that adopting this proposal means that they are not
required to disclose the true results of what happened on those
accounts,'' Judge Painter said in an interview. ``It's to enable
CTA's not to disclose a disastrous result of old accounts. It's
absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   The commodities trading industry, which has an estimated $35
billion under management, has advocated a switch to nominal account
size for calculating returns for 12 years. But on Aug. 2, the CFTC
issued such a proposal for the first time. The commission, now
headed by William J. Rainer, has invited public comment on the
matter until Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the change say that the rule would help alleviate
the differences in returns that are the result of variations in the
amount of cash an investor borrows for commodities trading. Few
investors put up 100 percent of the recommended account size to
trade commodities. It is estimated that two-thirds of the money
invested in commodities goes into partly funded rather than fully
funded accounts. One of the lures of commodities trading is that
investors need put up only a fraction of a contract's value,
usually 5 to 10 percent, compared with 50 percent for stock
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   I. Michael Greenberger, director of the division of trading and
markets at the commission, said: ``To the extent that the `actual'
amounts invested by a large number of clients are significantly
different within a trading program, it is difficult to identify a
meaningful, useful rate of return for prospective customers. The
CFTC proposal would allow the adviser to base his calculation on
the actual investment strategy recommended, providing uniform,
realistic information to customers with full disclosure about
calculation of the rate of return and risks of investing in the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   And Arthur F. Bell Jr., managing partner of a certified public
accounting firm of the same name in Lutherville, Md., said that the
rule change would bring some discipline to commodity trading
advisers' track records. The rule, he said, ``gives some certainty
of what you're looking at versus looking at numbers depending upon
how much cash an investor has put up. Now you can go from one
trader to the next and have confidence that what you're looking at
was calculated in a similar fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics question why returns in commodities accounts should
use a hypothetical account size and therefore be calculated
differently from other investments, such as mutual funds. Moreover,
allowing commodity trading advisers to choose the account size that
they want to have their performance judged on leaves the
calculations subject to possible manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, according to opponents, the proposal
would make month-to-month fluctuations in commodities accounts
appear to be smoother and therefore make commodities seem more
conservative as investments. And because one commodities manager
could have a hypothetical account size that is far larger than
another, returns among many managers would not be comparable.
</P>
<P>
   An opponent of the rule is Katherine H. Daigle, assistant
professor of economics and finance at the University of
Mississippi. Ms. Daigle, who was an economist at the CFTC from 1990
through 1994, calls the proposal duplicitous.
</P>
<P>
   The current method of figuring returns is complex and needs to
be improved, she says. But if the commission wants investors to
receive information that is understandable, accurate and complete,
she says, it should require commodity managers to provide
calculations consistent with common practice, meaning returns on
actual funds managed by an adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The rule change, she said, would smooth out a commodity
adviser's returns. ``It's not going to look like they're doing
really badly and not going to look like they're doing really
well,'' she said. ``But from my point of view, investors ought to
be able to see what they really did and make their decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule change also seems at variance with the course taken by
the Securities and Exchange Commission, which has pushed mutual
fund operators to write their performance reports in plain English
that makes it easier to compare results with those of other
managers. Staff members of the CFTC emphasize that the rule would
take effect only after the public's response is assessed. Given the
controversy the proposal has already generated, how the CFTC
handles the rule change may be one of the first signs of where the
commission will go under its new chairman. Rainer, who was sworn in
last month, was a co-founder of Greenwich Capital Markets, a bond
trading firm in Greenwich, Conn. Between 1971 and 1981, Rainer held
various positions at Kidder Peabody &AMP; Co. Rainer declined to
comment on the proposal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
