u a BC-CLONING-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      09-01 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLONING-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M TO UNVEIL CLONED BULL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TODD ACKERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A cowboy may never sit astride his back, but there's
still a lot riding on Second Chance.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-week-old calf, a clone of a 21-year-old show bull named
Chance, will be introduced to the world Thursday at Texas A&AMP;M
University in College Station, and then watched, prodded and tested
to determine if he's aging prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is anxiously awaited by scientists concerned by
recent news that Dolly, Scotland's famous cloned ewe, may be aging
prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the oldest animal ever cloned, one that died of old
age soon thereafter,'' said Jonathan Hill, a research veterinarian
at A&AMP;M College of Veterinary Medicine, which will unveil Second
Chance at Thursday's news conference. ``If ever there were a good
research model to observe DNA showing premature aging, this would
seem to be it.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M has long been a leader in animal reproductive technologies,
but the cloning of Chance _ the world's first of a bull _ is the
Aggies' first from an adult cell. Most of A&AMP;M's work has involved
cloning from embryos and genetically altering animals, though it is
currently in the midst of a much-ballyhooed $2.3 million effort to
clone a dog named Missy, the so-called ``Missyplicity Project.''
</P>
<P>
   Chance himself was no stranger to attention in his lifetime. A
Brahman, he starred in the 1997 Kate Capshaw film ``The Locusts,''
appeared on David Letterman and competed in Houston rodeo show
events. He was described as unusually tame.
</P>
<P>
   Chance's owner, Ralph Fisher, suggested A&AMP;M take cells from the
ailing bull when he brought him to the veterinary college about a
year ago. Though it had no plans to clone Chance at the time, A&AMP;M
took the cells. And a month later, using state and private grants,
researchers decided to try cloning him.
</P>
<P>
   Second Chance was born after a successful nine-month pregnancy.
Though its lungs and heart were initially as fragile as those of
premature infants, he is healthy now, said Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so miraculous, my hair stands on the back of my neck when
I see him,'' said Fisher, a rancher from La Grange, Texas, who
calls Chance a family member and business partner and plans to
mount his hide. ``He's got the same eyes, forehead, big bones _
it's like deja vu.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Fisher, Chance resembled the Brahman bulls that
were imported from India in the 1930s _ big horns, big hump, loose
skin. Because of selective breeding, most bulls in the United
States today have lost much of that skin and usually all of their
horns.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M scientists already have performed and are waiting on the
results of the test to determine if Second Chance's cells show
telltale signs of wear typical of an older animal. Such cells have
shorter ``caps'' than average. The caps, called telomeres, prevent
a cell's DNA from ``fraying,'' which signals the cell to
self-destruct as part of the aging process.
</P>
<P>
   Dolly, for instance, has the DNA of a 6-year-old sheep, even
though it is only 3, an article in the journal Nature reported in
May. A&AMP;M scientists hope to get the results on Second Chance's
cells in about a month, but will continue to do the testing at
least once a year. Fisher will take possession of Second Chance at
6 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think if it passes the first test, it should be all
right,'' said Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Because Chance was so gentle, Hill noted that his cloning should
provide some evidence of how much personality is passed on in the
process. Thus far, Second Chance has been quite tame, said Hill,
but it's too early to tell if that's a result of Chance's DNA or
the inordinate amount of handling he's received.
</P>
<P>
   Hill also said the cloning of Chance is important because a bull
must usually be older before ranchers know if it is likely to
become their best meat producer, an important issue if cloning is
ever going to revolutionize the beef-cattle industry.
</P>
<P>
   Other mammals to be cloned besides Chance include of monkeys,
mice, cows and, of course, Dolly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
