u s BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT &LR;      09-01 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES RETAIN PAY, BUT NOT THEIR JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Opting to choose safe over sorry, the umpires
union accepted a settlement with Major League Baseball on Wednesday
that will retain the pay but not the jobs of 22 umpires whose
resignations had been accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The union trumpeted the settlement as a victory, but the
departing umpires, one-third of the union membership, did not get
what they wanted _ the right to continue working as major league
umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said Mark Johnson, one of nine American
League umpires whose on-field jobs end at 6 a.m. Thursday under the
agreement signed Wednesday at the federal Courthouse here. ``An
umpire wants to umpire and be out on the field. This is a critical
time of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Richie Garcia, a 25-year American League veteran, said he didn't
feel good either. ``I want to be on the baseball field,'' he said.
``He's taken that away from me. He doesn't want me on the field,
but he's paying me anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia referred to the Commissioner Bud Selig, who came under
heavy fire from the umpires and their union leader, Richie
Phillips. According to Phillips and the union's lead lawyer, Susan
Davis, Selig quashed part of the agreement under which he could
have directed the use of any or all of the 22 umpires during the
remainder of the season and the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear,'' said Davis, a New York labor lawyer, ``that
yesterday he would have had the discretion to put the umpires on
the field and this morning it was taken off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's lawyers left the courthouse without commenting on the
settlement or any elements of it, and Selig did not return
telephone calls seeking comment on the change the union attributed
to him. But Richard Levin, baseball's spokesman, said baseball's
lawyers had made it clear to the union's lawyers Tuesday night that
every element of the agreement had to be reviewed and approved by
Selig.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides were in U.S. District Court before Judge J. Curtis
Joyner ostensibly for a hearing on the union's request for a
preliminary injunction blocking the National and American leagues
from accepting the umpires' resignations. Joyner, however, urged
them to try to negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This judge is not letting anyone out of here,'' one of the
lawyers said well into the second day of talks that took place over
16 hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the union decided to play it safe and accept the
settlement, even after Selig's refusal to leave open the
possibility that the umpires could work in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still had the 22 guys' lives on the line,'' Jerry Crawford,
an NL umpire who is the union president, said. ``The guys were not
getting paid. As of right now, these guys are on the payroll and
they are employed. I think that's more of a sure thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball was confident it could avoid an
injunction, but its officials decided to make a deal to insure that
the umpires would not strike in support of their 22 departing
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the union and its officers ``agree that
they will not engage in any strike or work stoppage.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the total salaries of the 22 umpires of $3,389,500,
paid over a 12-month period on the first of each month, the leagues
will pay them the remaining quarter, or $847,375, and also continue
to provide health benefits. The 22 umpires also will share in the
post-season bonus pool, although the money will come out of the
bonuses the other umpires would normally receive.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to pay their salaries, however, Major League
Baseball was taking no risk. The question of its acceptance of the
resignations will be heard by an arbitrator under a grievance the
union filed with the American Arbitration Association last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If the umpires were to prevail in the arbitration and regain
their jobs, they would have received back pay anyway. If the
leagues win the grievance, however, the money they would have had
already paid out in salaries will be deducted from severance
payments that 16 of the umpires will receive.
</P>
<P>
   Money paid out to the six umpires who don't have 10 years of
service and therefore don't get severance will be recouped from a
$100,000 bond the union agreed to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
