<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-FRONTIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL CROSSING IS EXPECTED TO SWEETEN FRONTIER BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an attempt to reinvigorate its flagging effort to acquire the
Frontier Corp., one of the nation's biggest long-distance telephone
carriers, Global Crossing Ltd. has offered to modestly sweeten its
bid in exchange for Frontier's commitment to spurn other suitors,
executives close to the negotiations said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier's board met Wednesday night to consider Global
Crossing's latest offer, the executives said. If Frontier's board
does approve the new deal, the companies will probably announce the
agreement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If Global Crossing's offer is accepted, the companies intend to
announce a $500 million stock buyback, according to the executives
close to the deal. Both Frontier and Global declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The looming renegotiation is the latest episode in a takeover
soap opera that began in March when Frontier agreed to be acquired
by Global Crossing, an upstart international phone company, in a
deal then worth $10.8 billion in stock. Over the summer, Global
Crossing wrangled with Qwest Communications International, another
long-distance newcomer, for control of both Frontier and U S West,
the regional Bell giant, before the two competitors agreed to
divide the spoils, with Frontier going to Global Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   But the high-flying stock Global Crossing wanted to use as
currency to acquire Frontier has not held up. The
telecommunications sector in general has edged lower over the last
six months amid concerns of a price war. At the same time, some of
Global Crossing's shareholders have appeared concerned that a deal
for Frontier, with its somewhat sluggish local phone operations in
places like Mondovi, Wis., and Fort Dodge, Iowa, would slow Global
Crossing's growth.
</P>
<P>
   So Global Crossing's shares, which traded above $51 before the
original Frontier deal was announced, have plunged, closing down
$1.875 Wednesday, to $24. Bigger names in telecommunications have
also lost value over that time, but not as much. AT&AMP;T has fallen to
$47.375 from $55, MCI Worldcom to $76 from $88.125 and SBC
Communications to $49.75 from $53.375.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier's shareholders could have maintained some equanimity
through some of Global Crossing's drop. Global Crossing guaranteed
them $63 worth of stock for each of their Frontier shares, but only
so long as Global Crossing's shares stayed above $34.56. Below that
``collar,'' Frontier's stock owners were to receive a fixed ratio
of about 1.82 Global Crossing shares.
</P>
<P>
   So rather than $63, Frontier's shareholders are now set to
receive $43.68 a share, less than the $44.625 Frontier shares were
worth before the original deal was announced last spring. The
overall stock value of the deal has been reduced to $7.6 billion.
With Frontier's shareholders set to vote on the deal later this
month and no immediate rebound in Global Crossing's shares sure to
come, a renegotiation appeared in order to executives involved in
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the most solid way to bolster Global Crossing's offer
would be to add some cash to the mix. But Global Crossing does not
appear to be able to devote billions to such an effort.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, executives close to the negotiations said Global
Crossing's new offer was to give Frontier's stockholders two shares
of Global Crossing stock instead of 1.82. At Global Crossing's
current stock price, that would raise the value of the takeover to
Frontier's stock owners to $48 a share from $43.68 a share, an
increase of almost 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The catch, however, is that in order to win the higher ratio,
Frontier would have to agree to eliminate the deal's collars
altogether, according to people close to the negotiations. Frontier
would also have to agree not to consider other offers.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
