u f BC-WTO-MOORE-NYT &LR;      09-01 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-MOORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH LIGHT TOUCH, TRADE CHIEF TAKES OVER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., New Zealand, Switzerland)   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Mike Moore of New Zealand began his first day as leader
of the World Trade Organization on Wednesday with a reminder of
some nettlesome issues he faces as the top global trade arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   White placards with such slogans as ``God Is Dead; the WTO Has
Replaced Him,'' waved by a small but voluble band of demonstrators,
greeted him as he arrived in a chauffeur-driven black Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bit flattering I would have to say,'' Moore remarked
of the slogan. The protesters represent groups that have
increasingly criticized the trade organization as having too much
power. They are threatening to disrupt global trade talks in
Seattle late in November, which is scheduled as Moore's initial
challenge as director general. According to his count, he has 11
weeks to pull together a workable agenda on an array of complex
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's congeniality and breezily informal style may help smooth
over disagreements among the 134 often-fractious member countries
on issues as diverse as cutbacks in farm subsidies, the taxation of
electronic commerce, market access to financial services like
banking and insurance, and tariffs on industrial goods.
</P>
<P>
   Looming as particularly contentious is whether to include
genetically modified food on the trade talk agenda, in light of the
dispute between the United States and the European Union over
whether barring American hormone-treated beef from the Continental
market violates global trading rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we like it or not, these are issues the public is
concerned about,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Some trade experts think he will have a second full-time job
mending fences with envoys from developing countries who supported
his rival for director general, Deputy Prime Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-month contest escalated into a clash of wills with
delegates of many nations expressing resentment of Moore's support
from the United States. This was particularly true among nations
that contend they have not benefited from trade liberalization and
suspect the United States of having tried to undermine Supachai's
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a compromise was struck in which both men will serve
three-year terms, with Moore going first. ``It's been a lot of
drama and theater,'' the new trade chief said, ``but it will be
forgotten in six months because the real issues are so enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, 50, has spent much of his career in New Zealand, where he
was most recently opposition spokesman for trade and foreign
affairs. He worked briefly for the printers' union but mostly
served in government posts. In 1990, he was briefly New Zealand's
prime minister. ``I was there such a short time it made Gerald Ford
look like Franklin Roosevelt,'' Moore remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Jovial one-liners aside, he is well aware that he faces a tough
task in figuring out how the trade organization presents itself to
a public that is increasingly aware and suspicious of centralized
power over trade.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism over the lack of openness erupted last year when the
organization brushed aside American safeguards for endangered sea
turtles caught in shrimpers' nets. Such environmental or
conservation measures are at odds with the views of many emerging
economies, which have resisted opening their commerce to outside
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have have to recognize that many nongovernmental
organizations have enormous influence,'' Moore said, ``so we have
to engage them and show a more human face.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got something to hide, the best way is to give out
5,000 sheets of paper and dare people to find it,'' he said
jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he has repeatedly emphasized that the trade
organization is driven by its members' needs. To bring more smaller
economies into the fold _ about 30 countries are too poor to have
diplomats in Geneva _ Moore plans to help them better protect their
trading interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO now doesn't look like the real world,'' he said. ``It
looks too rich and clubby, so we have to work on that.'' That
includes admitting Russia and China to the group, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the trappings of his new job _ a six-figure salary, an
entertainment allowance, the luxury car and a spectacular view of
Lake Geneva _ obviously fit the the upscale model, although Moore
says he is too down-to-earth to have his head turned by such perks.
A worry, he said, is that he does not speak French _ something
considered tantamount to sin in Geneva circles.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, how will he know if he has been successful?
``If I manage to offend everybody, then I'm doing a good job,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
