<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7925 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     09-01 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA GOT JUST WHAT IT DESERVED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There is a sky-is-falling mentality hanging over
the Pacific-10 Conference, as everyone tries to overanalyze what
went wrong in Arizona's embarrassing loss to Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Everything from the Wildcats' offensive scheme to their tackling
ability has been questioned following the 41-7 thumping they took
in the Pigskin Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel disgusted, violated and what we've got to do is take
this (butt) whipping and learn from it,'' said Arizona linebacker
DaShon Polk, who played at Taft High.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one thing that needed to be learned, and somebody
forgot it when the game was scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Tomey was never going to take a team into Beaver Stadium,
with 97,000 rabid fans, and beat Joe Paterno.
</P>
<P>
   That is simply not something a program like Arizona's is capable
of doing. For that matter, neither is going to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to beat a downtrodden Nebraska team in San Diego,
but Penn State was never going to let a bunch of rubes come into
State College before a national-television audience and pull off an
upset.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona hones its success against teams like Iowa, Illinois and
New Mexico. That is a far cry from playing in Beaver Stadium and
giving Paterno an entire summer to prepare for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find out who we are,'' Tomey said. ``Right
now, we don't like what we see. We need to take the hurt and the
pain from this game and transfer that into positive energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, positive energy will come Sunday, when the Wildcats
play Texas Christian. That's their level of opponent, and as long
as Tomey remembers that, Arizona fans will be happy.
</P>
<P>
   The chosen one:The headline in The Daily Cal read ``Jesus in
Cleats'' when former Hart star quarterback Kyle Boller arrived in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Already, two reserve quarterbacks have left town. David Page
announced after spring drills he wasn't sticking around. And about
a week into fall drills, Ryan Sorahan said he, too, was leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Even temporary starter Sam Clemons admitted he thought about
transferring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crossed my mind,'' Clemons said. ``But I felt I could
handle this, that everything would be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   As to how the quarterback setup will play out, offensive
coordinator Steve Hagen said: ``(Clemons will) be our starter
against Rutgers (on Saturday). And Kyle will play. The cards will
fall where they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Football is king:You think Tennessee lets anything get in the
way of football?
</P>
<P>
   This summer, 6-foot-4, 240-pound rookie defensive end Constantin
Ritzmann was stranded in his native Germany for five weeks because
of visa problems.
</P>
<P>
   The state responded with Gov. Don Sundquist, a Tennessee
congressman and an ambassador to the U.S. Embassy in Berlin getting
involved to chop through the red tape.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching carousel:All Big East head coaches return this year,
making it the only conference that can make that claim.
</P>
<P>
   Full house:The SEC had six of the top 10 teams in national
attendance and its 12 teams played to 99.6 percent of capacity last
season. One of every five fans who attended a Division I-A game
last season was at an SEC game.
</P>
<P>
   Classified info:Former Hawkeyes linebacker Ryan Loftin, who
started 11 games last year but had been moved to the second team
this year, has been charged with felony extortion and misdemeanor
fifth-degree theft.
</P>
<P>
   His crime? He allegedly threatened coach Kirk Ferentz in a
letter and stole Iowa playbooks. According to court records, Loftin
threatened to expose classified information that would harm the
professional reputation and business of the victim. Loftin also
expected to force the victim to continue to provide support through
scholarship funds.
</P>
<P>
   Loftin, 22, has received his degree but had one year of
eligibility remaining. He left the team Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Bulking up: Ralphie IV, Colorado's 3-year-old buffalo mascot,
had a great year. Since her debut last Sept. 5, she doubled her
body weight from 400 pounds to 825.
</P>
<P>
   Her resume also shows she's one tough buff. Born on the Flying D
Ranch in Gallatin Gateway, Mont., in April of 1997, she was
separated from her mother at about a month old.
</P>
<P>
   Ranch hands found her in the jaws of a coyote, suffering from
bite marks on her neck. Bottle fed for about four months, she was
released back into the herd but didn't bond with the other buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder what she thinks of Rick Neuheisel? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Scott Wolf's college football column appears
Thursdays in the Daily News. He can be reached via e-mail at
Scwolf1aol.com.
</P>
