<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: VENEZUELA; COLOMBIA; MEXICO; CANADA; NORTHERN
IRELAND; ENGLAND; GERMANY; TURKEY; SIERRA LEONE; INDIA; VIETNAM;
CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: POLITICAL SHOWDOWN
</P>
<P>
   With Congress gutted by decrees that transferred its functions
to a new Constitutional Assembly, opposition legislators threatened
to convene an ``extraordinary session'' in defiance of the
measures, but also began a ``dialogue'' with leaders of the panel
in an effort to recover some congressional powers. For its part,
the assembly has begun deliberations on a new decree allowing them
to ``evaluate'' government employees and possibly fire those deemed
guilty of corruption or other misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: REBELS REPELLED
</P>
<P>
   In the heaviest fighting since mid-July, the army says it has
repelled an attack by left-wing rebels on a provincial town,
killing at least 47 guerrillas of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia. The attack was made in solidarity with an indefinite
nationwide strike called by more than a million unionized workers
and members of peasant associations.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: UNIVERSITY ULTIMATUM
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Barnes de Castro, the president of the National
Autonomous University of Mexico, issued an ultimatum to striking
students, saying their shutdown of the campus ``must not continue
for another day'' and warning he could use ``the force of the law''
to end it. He spoke to some 10,000 students and faculty at the
largest demonstration so far against the 134-day-old strike.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CHINESE INTERCEPTED
</P>
<P>
   Officials plan Thursday to start questioning 190 Chinese
migrants detained off Vancouver Island. Two other ships from China
were earlier intercepted as they sought to disembark 254
undocumented migrants. Reflecting a hardening of attitudes, a
national poll showed that 49 percent of respondents wanted the
undocumented immigrants to be deported, while 49 percent said they
should be allowed to apply as refugees.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: TORY CHIEF'S PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning the traditional bipartisan approach to British
policy-making in Ulster, the Conservative Party leader, William
Hague, attacked Prime Minister Tony Blair's refusal to halt the
continuing release of paramilitary prisoners there as ``an
outrage.'' The early release procedure is part of the faltering
peace settlement that will be the subject of a rescue effort in
Belfast next week by George Mitchell, a former U.S. senator and the
chairman of the talks that produced the April 1998 accord.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: CANING BAN EXTENDED
</P>
<P>
   Caning has been banned in Britain's private schools, 13 years
after corporal punishment was outlawed in state schools. The move
faces a legal challenge from a group of 40 private schools that say
violence against teachers has increased in state schools.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: BARAK'S SYMBOLIC VISIT
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak will be the first foreign
leader to visit Germany's new capital in Berlin since the
government moved there last month. Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder,
speaking on the 60th anniversary of the start of World War II, made
clear the visit had important symbolic value given ``Berlin's heavy
historic responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: AMNESTY BILL VETOED
</P>
<P>
   President Suleyman Demirel vetoed a bill passed by Parliament
that would have given amnesty to thousands of prisoners, including
some of the country's best-known gangsters and assassins. Many
political and civic leaders had protested the law. Parliament is in
recess until Oct. 1, and will then have a chance to override
Demirel's veto by a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA LEONE: REBEL LEADERS HELD
</P>
<P>
   Two commanders of the rebellion that recently signed a peace
accord with the government remained in captivity after a group of
former soldiers kidnapped them in Freetown. The soldiers are among
those who also held a group of U.N. officials in July for several
days, saying they had been excluded from the agreement. They had
been allied since 1997 with the Revolutionary United Front, whose
leader, Foday Sankoh, has yet to return to Sierra Leone almost two
months after the signing of an increasingly fragile peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: ELECTION ALERT
</P>
<P>
   After discovering several caches of explosives and ammunition in
New Delhi, the police are beginning a major effort to guard polling
places as the first round of parliamentary elections take place
this Sunday in the capital and other locations. Most recently, a
large supply of bomb-making materials was seized from a member of
an Islamic militant group active in hit-and-run raids in Kashmir,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM: SECOND THOUGHTS
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese army ``made mistakes'' when it took over South
Vietnam in 1975, the army newspaper said, indicating that a debate
continues in Hanoi over the decision by northern Communists to
destroy the freewheeling economy of the south, sending thousands of
South Vietnamese into re-education camps. The general who signed
the article, according to a Reuters report from Hanoi, said
soldiers had failed to heed Ho Chi Minh's warnings against
arrogance in victory.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: BRIGHT TOURISM FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   China is expected to become a major force in international
tourism in coming decades, the World Tourism Organization said in
Hong Kong. The Madrid-based group predicts that rising standards of
living will allow about 100 million Chinese to take international
trips by 2020, putting them in fourth place in numbers of travelers
after Germany, Japan and the United States. By the same time, China
will outrank France as the world's top destination, the
organization said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
