<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-ROGOVIN     09-01 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-ROGOVIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: A LEGACY OF CONSCIENCE FROM MILTON ROGOVIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three weeks ago an air-conditioned truck pulled up to Milton
Rogovin's house in Buffalo and carted away his entire archive of
photographic negatives, contact sheets and prints _ a lifetime of
work. When artists allude to posterity, they often do so only
half-believing in it, but this was posterity's actual moving van,
come to carry Rogovin's archive to the Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The day must have seemed strange in many respects, not least in
the faint but still discernible irony that hung over it. Rogovin's
career as a professional photographer began only after he refused
to testify before the House Un-American Activities Committee, a
refusal that diminished his livelihood as an optometrist. ``They
already had enough stool pigeons,'' Rogovin says. ``They didn't
need me.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1957. The next year Rogovin was asked by a friend to
photograph storefront churches in a black section of Buffalo, a
neighborhood Rogovin already knew well as a voting-rights activist.
The result was a series of photographs capturing the pathos,
religious and otherwise, of that urban communion. Since then
Rogovin, who will turn 90 in late December, has devoted himself to
a photography of implicit activism, to portraits of working men and
women, of the rural and urban poor in America and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense Rogovin has continued on his own the project of the
Farm Security Administration, the 1930s sponsor of some of the most
remarkable photographic work of this century. His subject is not
the Great Depression but the chronic depression that still shapes
the lives of the working poor and unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Rogovin's most striking photographic series rely on the
transformations that place and time bring about. In ``Working
People,'' Rogovin photographed his subjects at work, dressed in the
armor of heavy industry, and at home, dressed however they chose.
Labor transfigures, but so does leisure, and it is a little
alarming to notice how much more sharply defined Rogovin's subjects
seem in hard hats and shop aprons than in coats and ties and Sunday
dresses. But nothing transfigures like the years going by.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the past quarter-century, Rogovin went to
Buffalo's Lower West Side and photographed the same people in
settings of their own choosing. The result is a book called
``Triptychs,'' as pure a witnessing of time's movement, and the
ways in which poverty coarsens that movement, as there is.
</P>
<P>
   If it made sense, during the Depression, to send photographers
out into the countryside to chronicle the ``ill housed, ill
clothed, and ill fed,'' it makes equal sense to acknowledge, as
Rogovin's portraits do, that for many people those conditions have
never changed. An art raised upon that sad fact can sustain itself
in esthetic terms without falsely ennobling or falsely degrading
the people who stare at us still from these pictures. There is true
collaboration in Milton Rogovin's photographs, a conspiring of
artist and subject, and that is a legacy of conscience worth
preserving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 2237EDT &QL; 
