<HEADER>
A7945 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     09-01 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING OF HYPE COMES TO TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With trademark bombast, Don King staged a press
conference Wednesday at the venerable Biltmore Hotel in downtown
Los Angeles to hype the Nov. 13 rematch between Evander Holyfield
and Lennox Lewis at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, if only the two reigning heavyweight champions---Holyfield
owns the WBA and IBF belts, while Lewis is the WBC
titleholder---were able to provide as much action in the ring as
King does out of it.
</P>
<P>
   King, pursued by the United States government with a
resourcefulness usually reserved for the likes of Osama bin Laden,
easily stole the proceedings with his comedic mixture of double
entendres, non sequiturs, mangled polysyllabic utterances,
hyperbolic descriptions and a record-breaking name-dropping of
historical figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he took up basketball, Lennox Lewis would have been another
Michael Jordan,'' was just one of King's more mild pronouncements
during an amazing flurry of verbiage in which he also spoke of,
among many, many other things, the Lord and his Apostles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know Don King was a Christian,'' cracked Lewis,
deprived of becoming the undisputed heavyweight champion last March
13 at Madison Square Garden when he wound up with a much-disputed
draw against Holyfield in what most observers perceived as another
King-orchestrated fraud.
</P>
<P>
   My ears still are ringing from listening to King's booming
voice.
</P>
<P>
   And my stomach still is aching from the seizures of laughter I
suffered from hearing King's latest monologue, which was unique in
that it was even more frenzied, more surrealistic, more bizarre and
more downright entertaining than those he's dispensed in the past.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be singing Amazing Grace at my dear departure before
you'd be able to finish reading all the goofy things King
articulated during a session in which he made references to King
Henry VIII, Alexander Graham Bell, John The Baptist, Thomas
Carlyle, William Cullen Bryant, Shakespeare, Socrates, Plato,
August Busch, Frank Sinatra, Sammy Davis Jr. and, of course,
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been vilified, castigated, and, oh yes, indicted so many
times,'' said King, almost with a hint of pride. ``But I've always
come out on top at the end because America is a great country that
believes in me. It's the people that have made Don King. Without
the support of the American people, I'd be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, for sure, Don King would be in jail, having been acquitted
twice in federal trials in recent years by a jury of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there going to be another crooked decision this time?''
wondered wise guy sportscaster Joe McDonnell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Joe, it's so nice to see you!'' roared King. ``It wasn't a
corrupt decision last time. An unpopular one, yes. But the fight
game has a long history of unpopular decisions. People can view a
fight two different ways. The Holyfield-Lewis fight was much closer
than most people seem to think.''
</P>
<P>
   It was?
</P>
<P>
   What people?
</P>
<P>
   Don King?
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield?
</P>
<P>
   Lennox Lewis easily won the fight, no matter what the judges
decreed and it's doubtful the upcoming return engagement will be
any different.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Evander Holyfield, nearing 37, still is talking bravely,
although this time he's not going to make any silly third-round
knockout predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned my lesson from talking too much last time,'' said
Holyfield, who will earn another $15 million for the upcoming
frolic, the same as Lewis. ``There was no way Lennox was going to
let me knock him out in that third round. He was covering up and
running away from me, and it's impossible to knock out a guy when
he's doing that. But I'm going to beat Lennox this time. I promise
you there won't be any controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What will you differently?'' I asked Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``First off, I'm not going to fight as badly as I did the last
time,'' he said. ``I was sick during that fight. I had the stomach
cramps, and probably shouldn't have fought. But how could I not go
through with it? I had to fight, and I just had a bad performance.
I'll be better this time.''
</P>
<P>
   That's doubtful because Holyfield still will have to figure out
how to get inside the taller, bulkier Lewis, who is five inches
taller and will be at least 30 pounds heavier than Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield kept walking into Lewis' jab that memorable evening at
Madison Square Garden, and that scenario figures to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't change my strategy except this time I might try harder
for a knockout,'' said Lewis. ``I did everything properly last time
in the ring. I stuck and moved and avoided getting hit. Maybe I
should have been a little more aggressive. This time I will be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling this fight the `Search For The Truth,' '' said
King. ``We're finally going to find out who's the best heavyweight,
who deserves the title. What a show this is going to be! What a
truly magnificent event! People are going to descend on Las Vegas
by car, train, plane and Pony Express. This is the fight everyone's
been waiting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not really, Don.
</P>
<P>
   That one you're co-promoting with Bob Arum on Sept. 18 between
Oscar De La Hoya and Felix Trinidad is slightly more appealing,
considering that Lewis and Holyfield didn't exactly inspire
passions with their performances in their first fight.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there was far more animation after (italicize) that
snoozer over the scoring that there was during the 12 one-sided
rounds in which Lewis dominated what little activity there was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohhh, Doug, at least you've been around long enough to know
what the real story was on that fight,'' said Don King to me when I
questioned him about the scandalous scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I have been around long enough to know, Don, you
sly devil, that your Machiavellian behind-the-scenes maneuverings
played a vital role in one of the worst decisions in a sport with
an infamous history of such injustices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
