<SLUG> BC-FBC-HARTLEY-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTLEY HOLDS ON AT OREGON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been an NFL dream burning inside Tony Hartley since he
first grabbed a football as a youngster.
</P>
<P>
   It was the thing that made Hartley spend endless hours working
on his skills as a receiver at Los Alamitos High. The thing that
made him do what was necessary to immediately step on the field at
the University of Oregon and make a contribution. The thing that
made him do what he had to in the classroom at Oregon to stay
eligible to play football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never have I coached a guy that was more serious about being
great,'' Los Alamitos assistant coach Barry Sher said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the dream was the thing that the 6-foot, 190-pound
Hartley expected to come true following his junior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to succeed in life so bad,'' Hartley said, ````and I've
always felt football is my way to go. I've always said I would
leave after my junior year. But, to tell you the truth, going into
my junior year, I didn't know. I wasn't sure I was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   After the season's ninth game, though, Hartley decided he was
ready to test the NFL waters. The realization came moments after a
nine-catch, 242-yard, two-touchdown performance in Oregon's 27-22
victory over Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Washington game, I was thinking this would be it,''
Hartley said.
</P>
<P>
   But a strange thing happened on the way to the opportunity to
culminate a dream. Hartley decided to stay in Eugene.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of sweating his way through an NFL training camp
attempting to win a job this summer, Hartley resumed his familiar
position at receiver for the Ducks in preparation for tonight's
Oregon season opener on ESPN at Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to my mother (Bambi) a lot,'' Hartley said, ````and I
did a lot of praying. It was put in my heart to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision will allow Hartley to make up for what would have
been a disappointing way to end his Oregon career. The conclusion,
if he would have bolted, would have come with him sitting at home
after violating an unspecified team rule while the Ducks played
Colorado in the Aloha Bowl. His replacement that day - Donald
Haynes - had seven catches for 148 yards and a touchdown in a 51-43
Colorado victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt because I let the team down,'' said Hartley. ``I would
have had a big game. What I did is not something that is part of my
life. I made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aloha Bowl appearance should have culminated a breakout
season for Hartley, who had 48 receptions for 1,015 yards with 10
touchdowns. Twenty-eight catches, 628 yards and six touchdowns came
in the final six weeks of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is he helped (former Oregon quarterback) Akili
Smith make a lot of money,'' Sher said. ````The tape of (Smith)
during the draft looked like a Tony Hartley highlight film.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the season, Hartley looked into where he might fit in
that very NFL draft. The answer wasn't what he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ````I was told I was looking at the third or fourth round,''
Hartley said. ````That's not good enough. I feel I'm a
first-rounder. This year, I'll prove I'm a first-rounder.''
</P>
<P>
   Proving himself is nothing new to Hartley. As a Los Alamitos
senior, Hartley had 86 catches for 1,690 yards with 13 touchdowns.
Yet, when Parade Magazine selected its All-American team, it was
Los Al teammate Stanley Guyness, who had 46 receptions for 989
yards with 12 touchdowns, who made the squad.
</P>
<P>
   When discussion of the top Pac-10 receivers begins, the first
players generally mentioned are UCLA's Danny Farmer, USC's R. Jay
Soward, Stanford's Troy Walters and Arizona's Dennis Northcutt.
Yet, aside from possibly Farmer, Hartley was as productive as any
of them by the conclusion of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really kind of funny,'' said Oregon receiver coach Chris
Petersen. ``In a weird sense, that's kind of the way its been for
Tony in our program as well. At first, it was Pat Johnson and then
it was Damon Griffin. We've always had another go-to guy, yet
nobody makes as many plays as Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   However, even though Hartley worked with track coaches in the
spring to improve his speed, he won't ever bust a 4.3 in the
40-yard dash. And his size, while certainly adequate, is not going
to jump out at a scouting combine.
</P>
<P>
   What he will do, though, is make the plays when counted upon. In
three years, Hartley has latched on to 104 passes for 1,863 yards
with 19 touchdowns. Hartley could surpass the school record in each
of those categories with a big season. He is 58 receptions, 635
yards and five touchdowns shy of the standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he could be the toughest receiver in the Pac-10,''
said USC free safety Ifeanyi Ohalete, a former teammate at Los
Alamitos. ````He's definitely not slow. He has great hands, maybe
the best I've ever seen. He's strong, has good size and runs great
routes. I'd say he's a guy who belongs on the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   But, with the next level on hold, Hartley will finally get his
chance to be called the go-to guy for Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The timing isn't exactly the greatest with Smith in Cincinnati,
a pair of untested quarterbacks responsible for getting Hartley and
a group of new receivers. He knows he'll see double coverage in
nearly every game.
</P>
<P>
   Life couldn't be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being double-teamed can be tough,'' said Hartley. ``But I've
been waiting my whole career for this. I've never been the first
option at Oregon. What I have been is the guy who just happens to
be open. If I keep doing that, the NFL will notice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
