<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EAST-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RESPECTING THE VOTE IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Sept. 2:
</P>
<P>
   East Timor's long struggle to control its own destiny is at a
decisive juncture. Monday's U.N.-supervised referendum on the
territory's future status went off peacefully and with a remarkable
turnout of nearly 99 percent. The outcome, to be announced next
week, is expected to favor independence from Indonesia. But
militias backed by the Indonesian army have unleashed a new
campaign of violence aimed at thwarting independence. Indonesia's
president, B.J. Habibie, must act quickly and firmly to assert
control over the military, rein in the militias and fulfill his
promise to abide by the will of the Timorese people.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor has suffered mightily in recent decades. Abandoned by
Portugal in 1975 after three centuries of colonial rule, it was
quickly invaded and annexed by Indonesia, which has ruled the
territory harshly. But with last year's overthrow of Indonesia's
longtime dictator, Suharto, and his replacement by Habibie, Jakarta
changed its approach. Habibie offered the Timorese a plan for local
autonomy under continued Indonesian rule, then declared that if
autonomy was rejected, Indonesia would leave East Timor by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Those decisions did not suit Indonesia's powerful army, which
feared encouraging separatist movements in other restive
territories. Independence also alarmed some East Timorese who had
served the Indonesian authorities. Their combined resistance gave
birth to the militia movement, armed and protected by local units
of the Indonesian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Militia attacks have killed hundreds of civilians this year.
There is a danger that militia violence will now escalate in a
furious attempt to forestall independence. President Clinton
rightly warned Habibie last week that failure to control the
militias would damage relations with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the results of the referendum, Indonesia remains
officially responsible for security in East Timor for the next
several months. Habibie must send disciplined and reliable police
and military forces into East Timor with orders to disarm the
militias and see that the referendum results are carried out.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
