</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BROOKLYN-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SHOOTING IN BOROUGH PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Sept. 2:
</P>
<P>
   The fatal shooting of a mentally disturbed man in Brooklyn,
N.Y., has raised concerns again about the use of excessive force by
New York City police officers. Gidone Busch was shot 12 times by
police in a confrontation on Monday evening. Six officers were
called to the scene when Busch, an Orthodox Jew who lived in the
largely Hasidic neighborhood of Borough Park, had behaved in a
threatening manner to others on the street. The officers tried to
use pepper spray to subdue him, but opened fire after he struck one
of them with a hammer and defied orders to drop it.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, several hundred residents took to the streets
to protest the killing. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police
Commissioner Howard Safir met with Jewish community leaders Tuesday
to explain the circumstances of the shooting. The Police Department
is conducting an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Although comparisons have been made between this incident and
the fatal shooting of Amadou Diallo in February, there are some
differences. In the Diallo shooting, officers fired 41 shots at an
unarmed man who was standing in a doorway. Busch, by contrast, was
wielding a hammer and was said to have attacked an officer with it.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, the officers called the Emergency
Service Unit, which is equipped to handle the emotionally
disturbed, but Busch attacked them before that unit arrived. The
police say that as the officers backed away to give him room, one
stumbled and fell and another, trying to protect the first, was hit
repeatedly on the arm and thigh with the hammer until he too fell.
At that point the police ordered Busch to drop the hammer, and when
he failed to, opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   The police are trained to use deadly force only as a last
resort, to save a life. Given that a hammer blow to an officer's
head could be fatal, that criterion may well have been met.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is understandable that many citizens are asking
whether deadly force was absolutely necessary against a man who did
not have a gun and who was outnumbered six to one. Was there no
other way to disarm him or wrestle him to the ground? Clearly, a
thorough investigation is needed to look at such questions and to
test the police account of the events.
</P>
<P>
   Even if this shooting conformed to police guidelines, that does
not mean the guidelines for dealing with disturbed people should go
unexamined. The police have 100 such calls a day. It may be time to
consider giving every patrolman increased training and a wider
array of nonfatal weapons to restrain or disable troubled
individuals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
