u a BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-NY     09-01 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND JURY TO BE CONVENED IN FATAL POLICE SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-POLICE-BUSCH) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn grand jury will begin hearing evidence
next week to determine whether the shooting death of a mentally
ill, hammer-wielding man by police in the Borough Park section of
Brooklyn on Monday night was legally justified, officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn district attorney, Charles Hynes, said that a grand
jury would be convened on Tuesday to examine the circumstances
surrounding the shooting of Gidone Busch, 31, an emotionally
disturbed man who officials say was fatally shot by police officers
after he struck and injured one of them with a hammer. ``The facts
and circumstances of this incident warrant a careful review by the
grand jury,'' Hynes said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to hearing evidence about what took place in the
crucial nine minutes between the time police received a 911 call
about a man wielding a hammer threateningly and the time the
responding officers called for an ambulance to take Busch to a
hospital, the grand jury will examine Busch's mental history and
see how well he was served by the mental health system, a law
enforcement official said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are being sent to several hospitals where Busch
was treated for mental illness to check records and try to
determine whether it was appropriate for Busch to be released, the
official said. Busch was involuntarily committed to hospitals three
times in 1996 and 1997, and had sought treatment at other hospitals
since then, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart London, a lawyer for the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, said he was confident that the grand jury would find
that the four officers had acted appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time the man was shot he was within four feet of the
officers,'' London said. ``They were concerned not only abut their
own safety but the safety of others. He was a danger to himself,
others and the police officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials have said that when the officers arrived at
Busch's house after receiving the 911 call, he menaced them with a
hammer. One officer tried to subdue him with pepper spray, but it
was ineffective. Then, police said, Busch beat Sgt. Terrence
O'Brien with the hammer.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, Sgt. Joseph Memoly and Officers William Loshiavo and
Martin Sanabria began shooting, police said, firing 12 shots, all
of which hit Busch. Two other officers did not fire their weapons,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien suffered minor lacerations on his wrist, arm and thigh,
officials said. One of the officers at the scene told investigators
that he saw Busch ``try to strike Sgt. O'Brien in the hip area near
the sergeant's gun belt,'' an investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting drove hundreds of Orthodox Jews into the streets of
Borough Park to protest the shooting and ask why it was necessary
for police officers to shoot a man armed with a hammer. And it led
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to move swiftly to try to reassure Jewish
leaders about the incident, which threatens to erode at least some
of his support in a neighborhood that has long been one of his
political strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   Busch's mother, Doris Busch Boskey, said that she would call for
a federal investigation of the case. ``I really want to get all the
facts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And she said police should be better trained to handle people
with mental illness. ``If they had more training with people with
emotional problems they would know how to deal with this,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir defended the officers involved
and said that police were adequately trained to deal with
emotionally disturbed people.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the department was constantly examining nonlethal
alternatives to guns in subduing people, but that most of those
available _ including foams, nets and nonlethal bullets _ worked
only ``sporadically.'' Even Taser guns _ which the department uses
to administer electric shocks to people _ fail about a third of the
time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Safir also stepped up his criticism of state Assemblyman Dov
Hikind, who represents Borough Park and has been a vociferous
critic of the shooting. ``I don't think Dov Hikind was helpful,''
Safir said, likening Hikind's response to the shooting to that of
the militant Jewish Defense League. ``I think he and the JDL,
instead of asking for calm, were trying to incite the crowd, and I
think responsible elected officials should not do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hikind said that he found the commissioner's remarks
``stupefying'' and that he had spent hours at the shooting scene on
Monday night trying to calm the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a single arrest made. There wasn't a single piece
of glass broken,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
