<HEADER>
A7967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT &LR;      09-01 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVANISEVIC STILL CAUTIOUS DESPITE FIRST-ROUND VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Croatia, Finland, Spain, Switzerland, France, Britain,
Australia)  (See also TEN-NOTEBOOK) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Goran Ivanisevic has been trying for 11 years to
deploy his serves like dynamite and crack this $14 million U.S.
Open wide open like a safe. But when Goran Ivanisevic looked around
Wednesday and surveyed the wreckage of a tournament suddenly bereft
of Pete Sampras and Patrick Rafter, the brooding, bearded Croat
didn't think he was home free.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Grand Slam is nobody's tournament,'' said the 27-year-old
stringbean best known for admitting to suicidal impulses after his
three unsuccessful treks to the Wimbledon final.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Mount Everest. You cannot ever predict who's going
to win any Grand Slam,'' Ivanisevic declared after a 7-5, 7-6
(7-5), 4-6, 6-2 defeat of the Finnish unknown Ville Liukko.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with 10 first-round losses on his 1999 report card that
includes just two victories in five summer hardcourts events, this
victory over a 125th-ranked qualifier assumed morale-building
dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible,'' said Ivanisevic, who has never won a
slam.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic was one of several relieved winners on a relatively
drama-free afternoon where 56th-ranked Tara Snyder's 7-5, 6-3 upset
of the 43d-ranked Mirjana Lucic, 17, the Wimbledon semifinalist,
was the main surprise and 17th-seeded Felix Mantilla was the only
deposed seed. The Spaniard fell to Magnus Norman, 1-6, 6-1, 6-2,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The top-ranked Martina Hingis confessed to never breaking a
sweat in her 6-1, 6-1 dismissal of Sarah Pitkowski but said she
wasn't worried about advancing too easily and peaking too early.
``I think I can save myself,'' said Hingis, who captured one of her
five Grand Slam titles here in 1997. ``I won a Grand Slam before,
hopefully it wasn't the last one. I know how to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   As the night session's headliner, the third-seeded Venus
Williams, who has noted that the only danger to her designs on
claiming her first Grand Slam title here are the leg-cramping rides
between Manhattan and the National Tennis Center, did not
disappoint. With her hair swept into a beaded chignon and her
second-round outfit _ traditionally white but untraditionally
backless _ on display under the spotlights, the 19-year-old
powerhouse reached the third round with a 6-4, 6-3 disposal of
35th-ranked Anne-Gaelle Sidot of France.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, the Open continued to experience the
aftershocks of Tuesday's dual debacle: the withdrawal of the
top-seeded Sampras to nurse a herniated disc in his lower back and
the defending champion Rafter's tortured default after dropping
serve in the first game of the final set of his five-setter with
Cedric Pioline with a recurrence of a rotator cuff problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``With them or without them it's tough, always tough,''
Ivanisevic said. ``Without them now is different story. But there's
so many other good players there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's cataclysmic developments not only removed a two-time
defending champion and a four-time champion from contention,
robbing the Open of its odds-on favorites to clash in the
semifinals and leaving a pair of glaring vacancies in the upper
half of the men's draw, it guaranteed that Sampras will lose his
No. 1 ranking to second-seeded Andre Agassi or third-seeded Yevgeny
Kafelnikov after the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's descent will be even steeper: he will tumble out of the
top 10.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate and future consequences to those two stars
presented immediate opportunities to their comrades in the top
half.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those players, Britain's Rusedski, who downed Spain's
Juan Carlos Ferrero, 4-6, 6-2, 6-3, 6-4, and Haas, who handled the
19th-ranked Thomas Enqvist, 6-2, 6-4, 7-6 (8-6), counted their
blessings after passing the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly opens up the draw,'' said Haas, a 21-year-old
German who has spent the past decade at the Florida think tank of
Nick Bollettieri, the coach who guided Agassi through his formative
years. ``There's actually three top players who did really well
here last year and haven't had the chance to play, like
Philippoussis or Sampras or Rafter,'' he said, referring to the
1998 runner-up, semifinalist, and champion, respectively. ``You
have to give Agassi a pretty good chance at it, the way he's been
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Haas declined to link the slight hip flexor strain he sustained
while galloping for a forehand in the third set to the injury jinx
that has plagued his side of the draw. ``I don't think it's much of
a problem; it was still good enough to keep playing,'' he said,
more pleased about his straight set dismissal of this year's
Australian Open runner-up than worried by his aches and pains.
``Enqvist was one of the players close to being seeded; I'm sure
everybody watched who was going to draw him. I was the one who got
him.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rusedski, on the rebound from the foot injury that knocked
him out of Wimbledon, hasn't had a banner summer, he saw no reason
why he couldn't retrace the path he took the 1997 Open final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it definitely is a little more open,'' he said. ``I
think I have a good chance to win the tournament. But the key for
me is to get to that second week.''
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras 's replacement, the 130th ranked Mikael Tillstrom
of Sweden, failed to get past his first-round encounter with
Russia's Marat Safin. Safin prevailed, 6-2, 5-7, 6-4, 2-6, 6-4 in 2
hours 39 minutes. . . . The 15th-seeded Amelie Mauresmo, who became
a French heroine and unwilling celebrity when she revealed her
lesbianism during her breakthrough run to the Australian Open
final, was the only seeded woman to drop a set. But 20-year-old
rebounded against Marianne De Awardt, 4-6, 6-1, 6-3. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
