<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7979 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-HARDEMAN-HNS &LR;      09-01 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-HARDEMAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ After 357 days of watching and waiting, Texas A&AMP;M
running back D'Andre ``Tiki'' Hardeman will get an early birthday
present Saturday night when the Aggies open the season against
Louisiana Tech in Shreveport, La.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hardeman will turn 23 on Sept. 7, three days after his first
game action in nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Hardeman's last game was against Louisiana Tech
last Sept. 12. He played in only the first two games of 1998 before
being ruled academically ineligible and missing the rest of the
Aggies' Big 12 championship season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've been looking forward to this for a long time,''
Hardeman said. ``Last year was hard, being on the sideline and
watching the team win and knowing that I was supposed to be out
there but I couldn't because I didn't take care of my business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good way to come back. That was my last game last year,
and this year it's my first game. I want to see if I can start up
where I left off.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman was the Aggies' leading rusher with 105 yards on 24
carries last year before an error by the A&AMP;M registrar's office was
discovered. The wrong grade for a course taken by Hardeman was
inadvertently posted, and when the error came to light, his
grade-point average was too low for him to be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman remained at A&AMP;M and did well enough in class to regain
eligibility for his fifth season. He will start at fullback
Saturday, displacing for the moment Ja'Mar Toombs, who took over
for Hardeman and gained 422 yards as a true freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiki already has established that he's a very good runner,''
said Aggies coach R.C. Slocum. ``But at this point, he's a better
blocker than Ja'Mar. Tiki has demonstrated over several years that
he can block. Both of them will play, but Tiki will start.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hardeman arrived at A&AMP;M in 1995, it was assumed he would
make a name for himself as a top-flight ball-carrier and not as a
blocking fullback. The Galena Park native was a Parade All-American
after gaining 1,729 yards in his senior season at North Shore High
School and was considered the top running back in the state after
the 1994 high school season.
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman was a tailback for A&AMP;M in 1995, when he gained 313
yards on 62 carries as a freshman. He excelled the next season,
gaining 660 yards with 17 touchdowns on 109 carries, an average of
6.1 yards per carry. That season he picked up the nickname
``Touchdown Tiki.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hardeman's career never blossomed the way many believed it
would. In 1997, he was moved out of the tailback spot by Dante
Hall, who led the team with nearly 1,000 yards rushing. Playing
fullback, Hardeman gained 508 yards rushing that season and
averaged 5.6 yards per carry.
</P>
<P>
   Before the eligibility snafu ended his season last year,
Hardeman gained 79 yards on 14 carries and scored three touchdowns
in a 28-7 win over Louisiana Tech. There was speculation he would
not return to A&AMP;M, instead taking his chances at making an NFL
team. But when Hardeman was advised he likely would not be drafted,
he worked toward regaining his eligibility and staying in shape for
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been very easy (not to come back),'' Hardeman
said. ``I chose the hard road to follow, and now it's paying off.
For the most part, it was tougher going through this mentally. You
have to go do a lot of thinking about what you have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made the best out of the situation, and now I'm back.
Coach Slocum supported me, talking to me every day about what I had
to do to get back. I listened to him, did what I had to do, and now
I'm back.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said he was looking forward to seeing Hardeman return.
The 5-10, 240-pounder will give the Aggies a bruiser in the
backfield and a short-yardage specialist. Hardeman has 30 career
rushing touchdowns, tied for sixth in Aggies history. In addition,
he has four touchdown receptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiki's always been a great worker on the field,'' said Slocum.
``We've never had any complaints with work habits on the field or
his toughness. He is a physical back who can run the ball up inside
and hammer it up in there in short-yardage downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been impressed with the way he's come back. He's always
been able to play himself into shape because he practices so
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman has been especially diligent in preparing for this
season. He knows this is his last chance to produce at College
Station and also knows he could play a large part as the Aggies
defend their Big 12 title. He admits it was difficult to switch
from tailback to fullback, but he did so because A&AMP;M's coaches
determined it would be better for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard at first, but they felt that was the best thing
for the time,'' Hardeman said. ``That means I have to adjust to
playing fullback and get my mind set to playing fullback.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they are in a battle for playing time, Toombs and
Hardeman have become good friends. Toombs said both players have
asked running backs coach Lawrence Livingston about the possibility
of playing at the same time. With Hardeman and Toombs weighing a
combined 475 pounds, it would literally be a full-house backfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about it, we could pound on teams,'' said Toombs.
``I don't know what might happen, but we could have some real
power.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hardeman said that in short-yardage situations the
alignment could be effective. But he is more focused about the
reality of playing in a game again Saturday night than on a
whimsical formation that may never occur.
</P>
<P>
   Hardeman has a second chance for a senior season, and he wants
to make the most of it. While it was disappointing not being a part
of last year's Big 12 championship team, he might be able to
contribute to a team that has the goal of winning a national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that everything happens for a reason, so maybe me being
ineligible last year was the best thing that could have happened,''
Hardeman said. ``What happened last year, I just took it, kept a
positive attitude, and now I'm ready to go do what I can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
