<HEADLINE>
TEST REVEALS SMALL TEAR IN RAFTER'S SHOULDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Rafter, the two-time U.S. Open champion whose
latest title defense ended almost before it began _ with a sobering
first-round default on Tuesday night _ underwent a magnetic
resonance imaging test Wednesday at the Hospital for Special
Surgery in Manhattan that revealed a small tear to the rotator cuff
of his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The injury does not require surgery at this time, but Rafter's
rehabilitation period appeared to likely force him to miss the
coming Davis Cup semifinal between Russia and Australia on Sept.
24-26.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of facing surgery or a lengthy layoff, Rafter had
previously played down the shoulder problem as chronic tendinitis
but apparently came into the Open with the rotator cuff injury,
which contributed to his 4-6, 4-6, 6-3, 7-5, 1-0 loss to Cedric
Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's manager and brother, Steve, said that the player
consulted with two Manhattan orthopedists on Wednesday, including
the U.S. Davis Cup physician David Altchek, after receiving the MRI
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been at doctors' offices all afternoon. It's one of those
things where they're not certain how long he's had it, and they're
going to be treating it constantly,'' Steve Rafter said. ``He
obviously wants to be available for the Davis Cup the same way he
wanted to come here to the Open and defend his title, but it would
be silly to come back for the Davis Cup and reaggravate it. He's a
sensible guy. I'm sure he'll listen to the doctors and not do the
wrong thing. The positive thing is the MRI showed no injury to the
cartilage.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter said that John Newcombe, the Australian Davis Cup
captain, had suggested to him before the Open that regardless of
what transpired at the tournament, he ought to skip the Davis Cup
semifinal and take the rest of the year off to make sure the
shoulder problem did not follow him into next year.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rafter, the first defending Open champion to falter
in the first round, felt the Open and the Davis Cup were more
crucial to him than next year's Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Rafter exited the stadium to the tune of boos
from a late-night crowd that felt entitled to watch him go the
distance and scrap it out with Pioline in a sudden-death fifth-set
tie breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter said he wanted to quit after the fourth set because he
realized the shooting pain in his serving arm would never permit
him to advance past Round 2 even if he outlasted Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once one person starts booing, I guess the rest of them do,''
Rafter said. ``To be booed off, that hurts, no doubt about it. It
is very disappointing. I mean, what can I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Even Pioline took exception to the booing. ``He loves the
tournament,'' he said. ``If he gave up it's because he had a
serious problem. I think it's not fair from the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Dose of Tennis
</P>
<P>
   The children on the playgrounds around the Fort Greene section
of Brooklyn used to look with amusement at Levar Harper-Griffith.
``Hey, here comes Arthur Ashe,'' they'd call out to the kid who had
to set up his own net on the ramshackle courts in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   While his friends were often busy playing basketball, he fell in
love with tennis in an environment far removed from any country
club. It was a fascination that seemed inevitable after his mother
introduced him to tennis when he was all of 2 days old.
</P>
<P>
   That was when she wrapped him in a blanket and took him to his
first U.S. Open, on Sept. 6, 1981. In the years since,
Harper-Griffith has become a regular at the event as he slipped
past security and found his way onto the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he has a free pass. Three days removed from his 18th
birthday, Harper-Griffith and his partner, Andy Roddick, won their
first-round doubles match, 6-2, 6-2, Wednesday, scoring an upset
over the NCAA doubles champions, K.J. Hippensteel and Ryan Wolters.
</P>
<P>
   As the 1999 USTA National Boys' 18 doubles champions,
Harper-Griffith and Roddick received an automatic entrance into the
Open's main draw. Having the train to the National Tennis Center to
hit balls as a child and rising through the inner-city tennis
programs started by Ashe, Harper-Griffith made his return to his
home turf a success. Yet to some degree he remains as wide-eyed as
he was when he was a youngster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm walking around, saying, `Hi,' to Jim Courier and
Ivanisevic,'' said Harper-Griffith, who was ranked sixth in the
Boys' 18 last year and is mulling over when he will turn pro.
``You've got to try and act like you're cool about it, but every
time you pass them, you smile a little bit. These are the guys I've
been watching on TV since I was like, 8.''
</P>
<P>
   _ SELENA ROBERTS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
