<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLTZ-SCAROLINA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOU HOLTZ IS TRYING TO RESCUE WOEBEGONE SOUTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting on the credenza behind the desk in Lou Holtz's office at
William Brice Stadium are three things that could make his
inaugural season as the University of South Carolina football coach
a little easier to handle: a bottle of Rolaids, a bottle of
Excedrin and a bottle of Stress Tab vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the Gamecocks finished 1-10 last season, that they
play in the Southeastern Conference _ one of the toughest in
college football _ and that 8 of the 11 teams on their 1999
schedule played in bowl games last season, including Tennessee,
which won the national championship. Holtz is going to be reaching
behind his desk a lot this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't send me a schedule before I accepted the job, so
I never knew who we played until after I accepted the job,'' Holtz
said recently in an interview following a morning practice at the
university, in Columbia. ``When I saw the schedule I thought it was
somebody's pre-season top 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't cry for Lou Holtz. His daunting task begins Saturday when
the Gamecocks open the season at North Carolina State, but he is
back in his element. He is accustomed to taking over moribund
college football programs and turning out winners, usually within
two years. In 1972, Holtz took over a North Carolina State team
that had gone 3-8-1 the year before and guided it to an 8-3-1
record and a victory in the Peach Bowl. The next year the team went
6-0 in the Atlantic Coast Conference and won the league
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz had great success in seven seasons at Arkansas before
moving to Minnesota in 1984, taking over a team that had gone 4-18
over two seasons and had lost 17 straight Big 10 games. His first
Minnesota team was 4-7, but in his second season, Minnesota got off
to a 5-1 start before it finished 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his 1986-96 tenure at Notre Dame, during which his
team won a national championship, in 1988, that burnished Holtz's
image as a college football program savior. The reputation prompted
Mike McGee, the South Carolina athletic director, to offer Holtz
the head-coaching job three times before he accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The situation at South Carolina seems to resemble that with the
New York Jets, who were coming off a 3-11 season when Holtz took
over in 1976. Unlike his various college experiences, Holtz was not
able to turn around the Jets' fortunes. He left one game before the
season ended, having coached them to a 3-10 mark, and the team
continued to stumble afterward.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina, which once belonged to the ACC, has no winning
tradition in football, except for George Rogers winning the Heisman
Trophy in 1980. The Gamecocks have won just one bowl game (the
Carquest Bowl in 1995) and have never won more than 10 games in a
season since their program started in 1892.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, college football's version of Elmer Gantry, has rolled
into town to give the Gamecocks a winning identity after the
dismissal of Coach Brad Scott. A record number of season tickets
(53,000) have been sold, and the Gamecock Club, an athletic booster
association, has raised a record $8.3 million for the athletic
programs at South Carolina since Holtz was hired last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the job and said we could win here,'' Holtz said.
``You look at the loyalty of the people. We have 87,000 fans a
game. You've got great fan support. You've got a great stadium.
You've got good athletes in the state of South Carolina. The
problem is they leave. I take the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, 62, cited burnout as the reason he left Notre Dame
following the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of his departure, the university's football program
erupted in controversy, starting with the successful age
discrimination lawsuit filed against Notre Dame in February 1997 by
a former offensive line coach, Joe Moore, then age 65. Moore
contended that he was fired by Bob Davie after he took over from
Holtz in November 1996 because Davie thought Moore was too old to
coach.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Davie, who contended he fired Moore because he
had been disrespectful to Holtz and other coaches, admitted that
while he was defensive coordinator in Holtz's final year at Notre
Dame, he and Moore had a conversation questioning Holtz's mental
stability. Holtz said in a statement he was ``completely
mystified'' at that remark and that Davie ``never said anything but
positive comments to me personally.''
</P>
<P>
   In another case, Kimberly Dunbar, a former Notre Dame booster,
acknowledged using some of the $1.2 million she embezzled from her
employer to buy gifts for Notre Dame football players _ some during
Holtz's tenure. National Collegiate Athletic Association
enforcement officials have recommended that the contact between
Dunbar and the Notre Dame players be considered a secondary
infraction, which means the university would avoid major sanctions.
A decision from the NCAA is pending.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Holtz said he had never heard of Dunbar, had never met her and
wasn't aware of players receiving gifts from her when he was there.
He said didn't believe there was any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notre Dame has never talked to me about that situation,''
Holtz said. ``If there is a major violation, I'd find that hard to
believe. I know the people at Notre Dame, and there is no way
possible that there was ever anything but a great effort to run the
most honest program in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   McGee, the South Carolina athletic director, said he became
familiar with Holtz when facing Holtz's North Carolina State team
as head coach at Duke in the early 1970s. McGee believes that
Holtz, who signed a five-year contract that pays $600,000 annually,
is committed for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every institution that he's coached he's brought a higher
level of play both from the commitment of the athlete to improved
fundamentals,'' McGee said. ``That back-to-basics approach was
something that we needed. Also, when I was at Duke and he was at
North Carolina State for those seven years, I saw up close and
personal that he always had a strong staff. He has made the comment
that the staff he has here is the best he's ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Davie's suspicion that Holtz was slipping mentally in his
last year at Notre Dame, McGee said: ``I checked everything out at
Notre Dame, not because I was suspicious of Lou Holtz, but because
I had to. Due diligence was done. I've known Lou a long time and I
put zero stock in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz said he accepted the job at South Carolina at the urging
of his wife, Beth, who he said has regained strength after battling
throat cancer for two years. The job became more attractive to him
after his son, Skip, decided that he would give up his head
coaching job at Connecticut and join his father at South Carolina
as the Gamecocks' offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here sight unseen,'' said Skip Holtz, who worked with
his father for four seasons at Notre Dame. ``I asked him if this
was something he really wanted to do, and he said it was. That's
all I needed to hear. Having the opportunity to work with Lou Holtz
again, being back in the SEC coaching football is a win/win
situation. I couldn't lose.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was away from football, Holtz was a motivational
speaker, earning as much as $20,000 an appearance, and he worked as
a college football analyst for CBS Sports. All the while he said he
missed coaching.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent morning practice, Holtz gathered his offensive
unit around him and spent 45 minutes going over each of 130 plays
from scrimmage. Holtz lined up against behemoth offensive linemen
to demonstrate the proper blocking angle on certain plays. He did
it over and over again. He wanted each player to know his
assignment as well as the assignments of the players around him.
The bedrock of his coaching philosophy is drilling fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaching is trying to eliminate a mistake before it happens in
a game,'' Holtz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gamecock players have taken to Holtz's approach, screaming
included.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always told me that he was real intense, and he is
intense,'' John Abraham, a senior outside linebacker, said. ``I
kept seeing all those clips of him grabbing people by the jersey
and grabbing them by the facemask. But he treats us like men. I
want to play up to my potential, and that's what he wants for each
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz and his staff got a late start recruiting, but still
managed to get running back Derek Watson, a 6-foot-1-inch,
205-pound running back who was Football in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   It was a significant signing for South Carolina followers who
are still galled at the fact that three of the four down starting
linemen on Tennessee's national championship team are from South
Carolina. Watson, of Williamston, S.C., had verbally committed to
Tennessee before accepting a scholarship with the Gamecocks.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere around the South Carolina football program is the
opposite of last year's. Ray Green, a senior defensive back, said
that as the losses mounted last season, players openly argued with
each other on the sideline and coaches questioned each other's
decisions in play calling. ``The losses just snowballed and it just
killed our morale,'' Green said. ``There was no control. The heart
of the team just wasn't there.'' Holtz has instilled greater
discipline and confidence in the players in the few months he has
been on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to come out every game knowing that we've prepared
to win,'' said Arturo Freeman, a senior free safety who missed all
of last season with a knee injury. ``We have confidence in our
ability and we have confidence in the play selections. On defense
it's no more of that `let's try to hold them down.' We're coming in
with an attack attitude. There are no more doubts. You can go to
bed the night before the game expecting to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz said he can't do anything about outside expectations for
the team this season. He won't predict how many games the team will
win and he is concerned that the players' confidence will be shaken
if they experience too many early-season losses. The Gamecocks open
on Sept. 4 at North Carolina State, which defeated the powerhouse
Florida State last year, and play Georgia at Athens the following
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be a pretty good football team by the middle of the
year,'' Holtz said. ``How do we build confidence? That's the
question. If somebody has expectations, that's their concern. I
want us to be as good as we can be and build it on a firm
foundation.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
