<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA HAS SECONDARY CONCERNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In two decades as a defensive coach, UCLA's Bob
Field has opposed Peyton Manning, Drew Bledsoe and John Elway. He's
tutored Bruins standouts Jamir Miller and Carnell Lake. He's
coached in the Rose Bowl and the Bluebonnet Bowl. He's designed
man-to-man defenses and zone defenses for young teams and veteran
teams, good teams and bad teams.
</P>
<P>
   But since his arrival in Westwood in 1978, Field has never
experienced anything like his current dilemma: Of the five
cornerbacks available for Boise State, only one has played college
football. The Bruins will use senior Jason Bell and four freshmen
Saturday night _ and Boise State knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No.1 thing they want to do is throw the football,'' Field
said. ``They believe in running, but their priority, the thing
they've done best, is throw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel good about the way our guys have worked. They don't
have much experience, but if they recognize formations and get
lined up right, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos averaged 246.5 passing yards per game last year.
Although their skill players are unproven, they have a massive
offensive line (306 pounds per man) and a veteran quarterback (Bart
Hendricks) who's mobile and throws a soft, deep ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will counter with Bell, redshirt freshman Joe Hunter,
true freshman Ricky Manning, redshirt freshman Paul Nelson (a
converted receiver), and redshirt freshman Lovell Houston, who's
doubtful because of a strained thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know we're vulnerable, and they're going to try to pick
on us,'' Hunter said. ``They'll come after us, and that's fine. We
can't worry about it. We just have to make a statement that we're
ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   How they stand: Bell and Hunter will start. Manning is the top
reserve. He'll spell the starters and play in passing situations as
the third cornerback. Nelson is the fourth cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remember our fundamentals, our footwork, the things
we do in practice,'' Hunter said. ``We have to stay calm, be
patient, and just play. We can't think too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Jason Stephens will start at strong safety and senior
Joey Strycula at free safety. Junior Jason Zdenek, of West Hills,
is the third safety and will play both positions. Sophomore Julius
Williams, a converted cornerback, is the fourth safety.
</P>
<P>
   On certain third-and-long situations, UCLA will use receiver
Freddie Mitchell and tailback DeShaun Foster to bolster the
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good: In practice, at least, UCLA's defense looks
more confident and better organized _ much better organized _ than
it did last year. Field's simplified system has helped, as has the
defensive line's maturation.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA should never be 99th in the nation,'' head coach Bob
Toledo said of last year's defensive ranking. ``There's much less
confusion, and they're better fundamentally. They're playing hard
and confidently. I have a better feeling than I did a year ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
