<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     09-01 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A BIG SHOT, AN OLD SHOT, A NEW SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ricky Ledee was a wide-eyed 13-year-old when he got
his first glimpse of Darryl Strawberry. Granted, it was mostly of
the top of Strawberry's baseball cap, not the best of views, from a
distant row in the corner of the right-field upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were home, at Shea Stadium, against Houston that summer
day in 1987, only beginning their descent from the crest of a
championship season. Ledee at the time had his own waves of emotion
to ride. His father, a well-known salsa singer, was recently
deceased after falling asleep at the wheel of his car.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Ledee decided it was as good a time as any to flee the
scene, escape the pain. She stretched the budget, flew Ricky and
her two younger sons from their home in Salinas, P.R., to New York.
A sister was living in Brooklyn, and that's where they stayed, and
a promise was made to her oldest son. During a month in New York,
he would go to a baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets were the kings, who you wanted to see,'' Ledee said.
``Not that I could see that good, but it didn't matter. My first
game. I could see the field. How could I forget?''
</P>
<P>
   He remembered Strawberry hitting a muscular double, and that's
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the big shot in those years,'' Ledee said.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is 12 years later, and if Ledee isn't such a big shot
himself, he has at least made the most of his opportunity to play
left field for the most famous baseball team there is. When Darryl
Strawberry walked back into the Yankees' clubhouse Wednesday
afternoon _ an inevitability that might have been at Ledee's
expense had he allowed it to be _ it was already established that
Strawberry was returning as the spare part he has reduced himself
to.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, in the lineup Wednesday night against the Oakland
right-hander Omar Olivares, confronted the hollow specter of a
faded 37-year-old star, who is more of a threat to himself than
anyone else, with the best month of his baseball life. He hit .371
in August, drove in 14 runs, left the suggestion of the minor
leagues far back in the rearview mirror. Even if it is as part of a
platoon, there should be no turning back now on the Yankees'
commitment to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had faith in myself, but that's because my mother always had
faith in me,'' he said. ``She was pregnant when my father died, and
she couldn't work and we struggled, but even though I was the
oldest son, she always made me pursue my dream of being a
ballplayer. Without her, I'd probably be, I don't know, in
Alaska.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed at the thought of such misdirection, his words as
soft as his southpaw swing is sweet. But the voice turned firm when
he spoke of the discomfort he feels when his mother calls from
Salinas, not to be confused with Beverly Hills, to make the
occasional financial request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell her, `I don't want you to have to ask,''' he said. ``I
say, `Whatever you need, whatever my brothers need, it's there.'
That's what it's for. We have something now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee, no rich athlete, pulling down a couple of hundred grand,
said, ``This is family, responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is what makes Ricky Ledee such a comfortable fit on a
team that counts professionalism and accountability foremost among
its governing principles. ``This is more than a place where you
just come and play baseball,'' Ledee said. His eyes scanned the
nearly empty room. ``You have people who care about their families,
who care about each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, it is asked why the Yankees take Strawberry
back when he has failed them before, when they don't much need him.
Eyes roll in the direction of the owner, but you get the idea that
if George Steinbrenner had the players vote, Joe Girardi or Scott
Brosius or some other compassionate soul on this most human of pro
sports teams would stand up to say that Strawberry is family,
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet as he is, Ledee said, in fact, he would have been quick to
second the motion, and not because Strawberry was a big shot in the
eyes of a heartbroken kid.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee had been at his dressing stall when Strawberry, reporting
to work early, walked in, and right over. They hugged and
Strawberry looked Ledee in the face and said: ``You are the left
fielder. I'm happy for you. You've earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Strawberry, his life's prognosis no better than day to
day, at least acknowledging his tenuous reality. The view of a
troubled man once seen as larger than life from a distant seat in
the sky may not get any better than that. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
