<SLUG> BC-BEANIE-BABIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT BEANIE BABIES MYSTERY DEEPENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are Beanie Babies headed to the giant toy box in the sky?
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer, Ty Inc., says it's retiring all current and
soon-to-be-released Beanies at the end of the year. That leaves
open the possibility of new models in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But a leading collectibles analyst and expert on Beanie Baby
marketing says he believes the toys are not coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ty is getting out at the top, just like an aging football star
who comes to his senses and says it's time to call it a career,''
said analyst Harry Rinker of Rinker Enterprises, a leading research
center for antiques and collectibles in Vera Cruz, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Rinker said Wednesday that he thinks that Ty Inc. did not want
to get stuck with warehouses overflowing with Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   Rinker, whose sharp insights and critical assessments of the
Beanie craze earned him the nickname ``Beanie Meanie,'' added: ``Ty
recognizes everything is trendy. We as a society don't have long
attention spans. They got three good years out of this. I mean
Tickle Me Elmo dolls was (popular) for what, four months?''
</P>
<P>
   Rinker said that now is a perfect time for people to sell
Beanies if they want to get anything for them. ``Five years from
now ...,'' he said, trailing off with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Rinker did not rule out the possibility that Ty may have
something up its sleeve for next year. He said Ty Warner, the
company's head, is a ``great market manipulator'' who is good at
drumming up support for the fad.
</P>
<P>
   Already, he said, this week's publicity is guaranteed to give
Beanie Babies one last popular push timed well to coincide with the
company's scheduled release of a new line of Beanie Babies in a
couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the fate of Beanie Babies was mulled over and over
Wednesday as the Great Beanie Mystery deepened and fans scrambled
to learn if one of the decade's hottest crazes was over.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Brook, Ill.-based Ty Inc. wasn't spilling the beans about
the fate of pellet-filled Butch the Bull Terrier, Goochy the Ty-dye
Jellyfish, Kuku the Cockatoo and their gang of furry friends.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation was fueled by the company's Web-site posting of a
cryptic and tersely worded message Tuesday: ``VERY IMPORTANT NOTICE
_ On December 31, 1999 at 11:59 p.m. (Central Time) ... All Beanies
will be retired''
</P>
<P>
   The news immediately affected fans and sellers of the toy.
</P>
<P>
   Maddy Johnson, a 6-year-old Seattle collector of Beanies, said
she would ``feel kinda sad'' if the toys went away. She has a dozen
babies and says they are fun to play with because ``there are all
sorts of animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddy's older brother, Charlie, 10, said where he and Maddy see
Beanies as fun, other kids see dollar signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend will say, `Hey, this one is worth a lot!''' Charlie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Beanie Babies have become big-time collector items, particularly
among adults. Predictably, Tuesday's announcement influenced
Internet auction sites.
</P>
<P>
   California-based online retailer Ebay reported its auction area
for ``Beanies'' increased slightly to 10,700 postings early
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At Seattle's Amazon.com, company spokeswoman Sharon Greenspan
noticed more attention to Beanies, adding, ``as news spreads, more
people are listing, and bidding is becoming more active.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Beanie Baby auction site Collectingnation.com, the number
of bids was dramatically higher.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers Wednesday said it was impossible to learn what was
going on because it was difficult to get through to Ty Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Altman of Boehm's Candy Express in Seattle's Capitol Hill
neighborhood tried to contact Ty for nearly six hours Wednesday
before finally reaching someone.
</P>
<P>
   Even then it was only a chipper Ty receptionist who answered her
questions by saying: ``It's a big secret. We can't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beanie Boom started in the specialty toy market when Ty
introduced the toys in late 1994. By 1996, the toys hit number
eight on the annual survey of best-selling toys published by
Playthings, a New York-based trade publication that racks toy
trends. Their popularity soared so high that, at the peak, some
stores reported selling 40,000 Beanie Babies a day.
</P>
<P>
   That generated big money for privately held Ty Inc., which
within three years was earning about $250 million in annual
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, the popularity began to show signs of fatigue.
Last year, Rinker predicted Beanies had started to peak. Retailers
said last Christmas would probably be their last hurrah. And in the
second quarter of 1999, the Web site www.AbsoluteBeanies.com
reported online bid values for Beanies had dropped 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Altman, who had her business increased tenfold by Beanie
Babies, said the toy _ whether it stays or goes _ has forever
changed her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone had told me that five years ago a little stuffed
toy animal would turn my life around, put a line outside my
business, make phones ring off the hook and cause hundreds of
people to sleep outside my store door ... I would have said they
were out of their mind. It's been an exciting and fun ride.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990901.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CLINTONS-HOUSE-NYT &LR;      09-01 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PENDING' NOTICE IS POSTED ON HOUSE THE CLINTONS TOURED RECENTLY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ As word spread here that someone _ perhaps the
president _ had signed a contract to buy the Dutch Colonial that
the Clintons toured on Saturday, a steady stream of cars looped
around the tiny cul-de-sac called Old House Lane for a peek at The
House, and a CNN camera crew descended on the hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Chappaqua, a suburb that is not easily impressed, was
in a tizzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the talk of the Grand Union,'' said Ellis Lesser, a
32-year-old mother of two who runs a stationery business from her
home. ``Everybody I know is very excited. It'll certainly make the
property values go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents appeared pleased that the Clintons' designs on
the five-bedroom house, at 15 Old House Lane, suggested that
Chappaqua had won the strange suburban real estate pageant that had
been unfolding in Westchester for weeks as the first couple scoured
the county. But they also braced for the fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the main qualm _ that we could become a tourist
attraction,'' said Nina Gorki, who was running errands on King
Street in the business district. ``It's a quiet town, and we love
it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is widely expected to run for the
U.S. Senate from New York, has to establish residency in the state
by Election Day 2000 to be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   The Westchester Multiple Listing Service, a computerized roster
that gives the status of properties for sale in the county,
indicates that the house is ``pending,'' which means a contract has
been signed and all conditions are met. But the listing does not
say who the intended buyer is.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that means it's a done deal,'' Elio DeCecchis, a real
estate broker in Tarrytown, said Wednesday after checking the
house's status on his computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   The ``pending'' designation, which was updated from ``active''
status on Tuesday, also signals that real estate brokers are no
longer showing the house to prospective buyers. Typically, home
buyers will sign a contract that is subject to a number of
conditions, like their being approved for a mortgage and the
house's passing an inspection.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, between vacationing on Martha's Vineyard in
Massachusetts and attending fund-raisers in the Hamptons, the
Clintons stopped in Chappaqua and spent two hours inside the
110-year-old house, which resembles an old-fashioned rambling
seaside cottage. It was the only house the Clintons looked at that
day. Two weeks earlier, the couple had toured five houses.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Sloane, a broker with Brown Harris Stevens in Manhattan
who has led the search on behalf of the Clintons, could not be
reached for comment Wednesday. On Tuesday night, however, she said
she had ``no news of a signed contract.'' She then changed her
comment to ``no news of an unconditional contract.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``If there were a signed contract with no caveats,
there would have been an announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation was rife among realtors and residents today that one
condition might have to do with security. The house sits on just
1.1 acres _ far smaller than any of the five properties the
Clintons saw in mid-August. The Secret Service has to sign off on
any residence the Clintons might buy.
</P>
<P>
   A 35-acre plot of land that was recently approved for a
subdivision rises behind 15 Old House Lane but does not abut the
property. There is some concern that the future development could
pose a danger to the Clintons because the parcel looks down on the
backyard.
</P>
<P>
   There were unconfirmed reports that either the Clintons, or
possibly the Secret Service, were trying to buy adjacent land or a
piece of the subdivision. One neighbor, Charles Chepigin, whose
house occupies 1.58 acres to the immediate east of the Dutch
Colonial, said he had ``no comment at this point'' when asked if he
had been contacted about selling part of his property.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch Colonial, an 11-room, 5,200-square-foot house, is
listed at $1,695,000. It has a white-shingled exterior, and its two
wings are punctuated by fan windows and topped by gambrel roofs.
Across the back of the house, overlooking a pool, is a sweeping
porch with a long row of stout white columns. A detached barn
functions as a garage and could also serve as quarters for Secret
Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   The house's owners, Dr. Jeffrey Weisberg and his wife, Cheryl,
have lived there more than a decade, the neighbors said. Their
property taxes last year were $25,900.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lesser, who owns the stationery business, is a member of the
same book club as Ms. Weisberg and has been inside the house.
``It's gorgeous,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The one concern in Chappaqua Wednesday seemed to be the traffic
that motorcades and such might bring. A hamlet in the town of New
Castle, Chappaqua is prized for its public schools, its elegant old
houses and its hilly, wooded terrain. Many residents feel there are
too many Volvos and BMWs on the winding roads as it is.
</P>
<P>
   But Bonni Pactor, who was walking her golden retriever, Timber,
in the small downtown, dotted with coffee shops and antiques
stores, was not too worried. ``People are concerned about traffic,
but she's going to be in New York City most of the time,'' she
said, referring to Mrs. Clinton. ``I can't imagine she'll be
hanging out in Chappaqua all that much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
