<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. VISIT IS BRIEF FOR NFL OFFICIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARSON _ They came, they saw, they reviewed, they got out of
Dodge.
</P>
<P>
   And in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Three high-ranking members of the NFL staff made a whirlwind
one-day stopover in Southern California on Wednesday, meeting with
representatives of all four areas vying for that fleeting Los
Angeles expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Then they boarded a flight back to New York by 4 p.m. and left
without a single comment.
</P>
<P>
   Fear not, many more meetings remain scheduled. The NFL expansion
committee will meet Sept. 9 in Washington D.C., staff members are
tentatively scheduled to meet with representatives of Los Angeles
and Houston in New York on Sept. 13, and the entire NFL ownership
will meet Oct. 6 in Atlanta, presumably to finally award the 32nd
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between all that is the NFL's Sept. 15 deadline, when
the Coliseum, Carson, Hollywood Park and Anaheim are all supposed
to have their packages finalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they're going to change it or not, but they've
established and changed deadlines in the past,'' noted Carson city
manager Jerry Groomes.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hectic NFL effort was to gather a current assessment
of each site, and the different options available, so that the
staff would be able to make an updated presentation to the
expansion committee in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL was represented Wednesday by Roger Goodell, executive
vice president of league development, Neal Glat, director of
strategic development, and Jeff Pash, executive vice president and
legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Groomes and Carson attorney Darold Pieper, they
met with Ed Roski Jr. with the Coliseum group, Anaheim Mayor Tom
Daly and presumedly Marvin Davis, who holds an option on the land
at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   A Davis spokesperson said he had no comment, even on whether the
meeting even had taken place.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles City Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas issued a
statement, again trying to rally the troops, that ended with: ``We
will play until the very end. We play to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered Coliseum effort is currently trying to design a
new financing scheme based on potential tax increment derived from
activity generated at a renovated Exposition Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``To other sites that wish to re-emerge as potential venues, we
say, `Don't even think about it,''' Ridley-Thomas said in his
statement.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is exactly what the NFL asked the others to do
last month when it grew frustrated at the lack of public funding
surrounding the Coliseum following its six-month Southern
California exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had given a shot to Carson as they gave to the
Coliseum, we would have nailed it,'' Groomes said. ``They wouldn't
be looking for anybody else right now. But can we nail this in two
weeks? Not likely.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carson project includes a connecting shopping mall.
Previously, it was championed by potential franchise owner Michael
Ovitz. When the NFL selected the Coliseum as the Los Angeles site,
Ovitz then designed plans for it, angering some Carson officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a much different situation now,'' Groomes said. ``All
of what was presented to the NFL in the past about Carson went
through Ovitz. This is a conversation directly between us and the
NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   The previous Carson project included $180 million in bonds to
help develop the former dump site. Groomes said the city will
ultimately develop the site regardless of what happens with the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't view ourselves as a desperate community trying to
find a life raft in this NFL franchise,'' he said. ``Frankly
speaking, without suggesting we're not interested, we can take it
or leave it. We're going to move on with or without this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
