<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAGGAGE AND ALL, STRAWBERRY COMES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Darryl Strawberry folded his powerful arms, swayed in
a blue chair and leaned forward when he spoke, using the dozens of
reporters in front of him as amateur psychiatrists. Strawberry
talked about making a serious mistake, about being an alcoholic and
about the thrill of finally returning to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   There was no bluster or bragging from this Strawberry. He was
sullen and contrite. He hugged almost every Yankee he saw, looked
as physically imposing as ever and claimed that it did not matter
whether he was on the post-season roster.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, Strawberry treated his return news conference at
Yankee Stadium Wednesday night like one of the Alcoholic Anonymous
meetings he says he attends at least once a day. ``This time
around, when I looked in the mirror, I looked at the enemy,''
Strawberry said. ``It was me. It wasn't anyone else. Didn't no one
tell me to pick up that drink. That's the disease of alcoholism. If
you're not doing the 12-step program, you're going to drink, I
don't care who you are. You could be me or you could be Joe Blow.''
</P>
<P>
   After Strawberry was arrested for possessing three-tenths of a
gram of cocaine and for solicitation of a prostitute last April 14
in Tampa, Fla., he said that he had been drinking and was
depressed. He said that had helped push him into a compromising
situation. Strawberry pleaded no-contest to the charges and was
suspended from baseball for 113 days. He emphasized Wednesday that
he never should have resumed drinking and never should have
committed any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   So Strawberry, now 37 years old, began another well-publicized
comeback Wednesday, his fourth with the Yankees since 1995, and
probably his last. If the owner George Steinbrenner had not
supported Strawberry and had tried to void his contract for
behavioral reasons, Strawberry's career would probably have ended.
</P>
<P>
   It nearly did last October, when he had surgery for colon
cancer. But after six months of chemotherapy that ended in April,
the Yankee doctors say there has been no sign of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite sure he feels like this is it,'' said David Cone, a
teammate of Strawberry's with the Mets and Yankees. ``He needs to
take advantage of this one.''
</P>
<P>
   To conquer addiction, Strawberry said that he once again
participated in Alcoholic Anonymous' 12-step recovery program. He
said with pride that he was two weeks away from being sober for
five months. He focused exclusively on alcoholism and did not
mention cocaine once.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people that relapse, but they're not Darryl
Strawberry,'' he said. ``Some die. Some never make it back. It's a
gift to be able to make it back, and I accept that gift. That's the
most important thing. I put my recovery at the top of my list. No
matter what pain I might face, I can't allow myself not to go to
meetings anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   While Strawberry waved a bat like a toothpick during batting
practice, Manager Joe Torre spoke about how he would try to find
him some at-bats in the final month of the regular season. Torre
hinted that Strawberry would start at designated hitter against
Oakland Thursday afternoon because Chili Davis would be rested in
the day game after a night game.
</P>
<P>
   With 332 career home runs, including 24 in 101 games last
season, Strawberry is a formidable presence on the Yankee bench,
and Torre would love to spot him as a pinch-hitter a few times a
week. But he is unsure whether the 17-year veteran can stay sharp
with so few at-bats. So Torre might use Strawberry in left field or
at DH once or twice a week, and as a pinch-hitter a few times, to
determine whether he can help the Yankees in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is a weapon, we'll incorporate it into the club,'' Torre
said. ``We pretty much have to figure out if he is a weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   When Strawberry was asked about his surgically-repaired left
knee and his mobility in the outfield, he gave a brief response
about feeling fine. Then he started talking about spirituality.
Similarly, when he was questioned about his chances of making the
post-season roster, the chief reason he spent almost a month at
Class AAA Columbus getting into baseball shape, Strawberry again
sounded very mellow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not important at all,'' Strawberry said. ``What's
important to me is to live one day at a time and take care of
myself. I'm not saying I don't want to be on the playoff roster. If
I get playing time and I play well enough and Joe feels that way,
fine. If not, that's fine, too.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
