<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SHOWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL SHOWERS, AUTHOR OF CHILDREN'S BOOKS, DIES AT 89  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Mich., Wash.)   By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Showers, author of a series of science books for young
readers and a former editor for The New York Times, died on July 17
at the home of his daughter, Dr. Kate B. Showers, in Orange, Mass.
He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote some 25 science-related books in the ``Let's Read and
Find Out'' series, all first published by Crowell. One of them,
``Before You Were a Baby'' (1968), was written jointly with his
wife, Dr. Kay Matteson Sperry, a psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   The first in the series, ``Find Out by Touching'' (1961),
enjoyed a success that led Showers to keep on writing juvenile
nonfiction. Another book in the series, ``The Listening Walk''
(1961), was praised by a reviewer in The New York Times Book Review
who wrote, ``An ordinary walk won't seem like the same old route
after being alerted by Paul Showers to listen for sounds along the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Showers' other books included ``The Moon Walker,'' about how
babies learn to move, ``Sleep Is for Everyone,'' ``Use Your
Brain,'' ``How You Talk,'' ``Me and My Family Tree,'' ``A Book of
Scary Things'' and ``The Bird and the Stars.'' His writings have
been translated into Dutch, French, Japanese and Portuguese and
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   He was on the staff of The Times' Sunday department from 1946 to
1976, serving as a copy editor on the Sunday magazine and in other
posts. He also wrote numerous articles and book reviews for The
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Sunnyside, Wash., he spent much of his youth in Michigan
and received a bachelor's degree in 1931 from the University of
Michigan. He became an Army staff sergeant in World War II and was
an editor of Yank, the Army weekly, in Okinawa. Early in his career
he worked for The Detroit Free Press and The New York Herald
Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   His 1946 marriage to Dr. Sperry ended in divorce in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his daughter, a research fellow at Boston University,
who has since moved to Petersham, Mass., he is survived by a
grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-01-99 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
