<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SULLIVAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM MAYO SULLIVAN ,  PHILANTHROPIST, DIES AT 78  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Mayo Sullivan, a New York insurance broker
and longtime benefactor of classical music in the city, died on
Tuesday at his home here. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was renal cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan was a past president of the Metropolitan Opera Club,
which he joined in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   He also sat as an advisory director on the board of the
Metropolitan Opera and was a vice president of the Bagby Foundation
for the Musical Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Brooklyn, Sullivan graduated from Georgetown University
in 1943. He served as a lieutenant in the combat infantry and was
severely wounded in an assault on a German machine-gun nest during
the Normandy landing, in June 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan is survived by his wife of 26 years, Francoise Siebers
Sullivan; a brother, Raymond P. Jr. of Scottsdale, Ariz., and two
sisters, Molly Sullivan and Katherine S. Meehan, both of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
