<SLUG> BC-NY-LABOR-CAMPAIGN-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR BEGINS CAMPAIGN TO PROTECT EFFORTS TO JOIN UNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The city's trade unions kicked off the nation's Labor
Day celebrations on Wednesday with a large rally in Central Park
that highlighted one of the labor movement's principal themes,
claiming that employers often violate the right of workers to join
unions.
</P>
<P>
   To hammer home that theme, the labor movement used six immigrant
workers as spokesmen, and they described how their employers had
either dismissed them or threatened them to discourage them from
forming unions.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast that brought together 400 labor leaders,
politicians and religious leaders, one of the immigrants, Fatima
Pareja, a 34-year-old leather worker from Ecuador, told how a
handbag factory had dismissed her because she supported a
unionization drive aimed at improving wages and safety conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The other immigrant spokesmen _ two limousine drivers, a
computer operator, a janitor and a food-service worker _ also
described how they and their fellow workers had been harassed for
supporting a union.
</P>
<P>
   ``These six workers represent millions of workers who want to
make themselves and our movement stronger by joining our unions,''
said John J. Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO. ``But they cannot
do so because their employers are willing to bend the law and break
the law and use the courts to remake the law. It is a national
disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who heads a federation with 13 million members,
returned to New York, his hometown, for the march and rally, hoping
that it would set the tone and theme for dozens of other union
rallies scheduled for this weekend in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said that with Wednesday's rally, the labor movement was
beginning a new campaign called ``Voice at Work: Freedom to Choose
a Union.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort, he said, would ``shine a light of shame on employers
who violate workers' rights not only in New York City, but in
thousands of communities across our country.''
</P>
<P>
   At the breakfast at the Sheraton New York Hotel, Denis Hughes,
the new president of the New York State AFL-CIO, urged the dozens
of labor leaders to pressure political officials to do more to
safeguard workers when they speak out for unions and hold elections
to win union representation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the new civil rights movement of the next millennium,
and we're going to fight for it,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's unions held their Labor Day rally on Wednesday rather
than on the actual Monday holiday because they saw that it was
difficult in past years to persuade large numbers of workers to
attend a parade on a three-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders also decided this year not to hold the rally on
the Saturday after Labor Day _ as they had the last three years _
because this year that day is the Jewish holiday Rosh Hashana.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's rally was far smaller than the parades of the last
three years. The police estimated that more than 100,000 union
members marched in each of those parades up Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the New York City Central Labor Council, the
umbrella group representing the city's more than 1 million union
members, estimated that 25,000 people took part in Wednesday's
march along Central Park South and the subsequent rally at the
Central Park Summerstage. But several union officials said
privately that there were probably not more than 10,000 people at
the rally.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the march, there was a large turnout from workers
representing electricians, carpenters, teachers, teamsters,
operating engineers and garment workers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, labor leaders said they had no intention of
trying to turn the rally into a huge event, saying they would
husband their energies for future rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McLaughlin, president of the city's central labor council,
said that over the next year the city's unions would stress several
themes: improving public education, insuring adequate health care
for all New Yorkers and providing child care for all working
families that need it.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the events, one of the main themes was how to help
immigrant workers raise their wages, improve their working
conditions and remove obstacles to their joining unions.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Rivera, who worked for a contractor that did computer work
for the city's child services agency, said her employer refused to
pay overtime or holiday pay and fired several workers who backed a
union, including her.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed Bedir, a limousine driver from Egypt, said his employer
had sought to block a unionization drive and deny benefits by
declaring that his drivers were independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boss tried to take advantage of us,'' Bedir said,
``because we were immigrants and didn't know our rights, but we
will fight him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said, ``It's shocking to hear what things are like for
so many immigrant workers who try to form unions.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
