<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-0902-C     09-01 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-0902-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN PRESIDENT HECKLED BY OPPOSITION DURING STATE OF UNION
SPEECH
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo's annual state
of the union address turned into a raucous event Wednesday night,
with mostly leftist opposition members of Congress punctuating the
speech with verbal attacks about corruption and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why so much optimism if 30 million people live in poverty?''
said one of a number of banners also waved at the normally calm
event.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo _ who has clearly staked out greater democracy in Mexico
as his legacy _ was interrupted repeatedly when he touched on
topics like rural poverty and reforms that have been enacted to end
corrupt elections.
</P>
<P>
   Hecklers from Mexico's leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party
(PRD) also criticized Zedillo for his administration's policies in
Chiapas state.
</P>
<P>
   Banners urged the president to ``stop militarization'' and
withdraw Mexican troops from that state in southern Mexico, which
has been rocked over the last several weeks by renewed clashes
between the Mexican Army and civilian sympathizers of the state's
Zapatista rebels.
</P>
<P>
   At first the heckling from members of Congress seemed limited to
a small group. But the angry mood was contagious. After Zedillo
finished his speech, members of Zedillo's party _ the long-ruling
Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI _ began to wave fists and
shout insults at the opposition congressman who was chosen to
deliver a rebuttal to Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1997, Mexico's Congress was dominated by the PRI, which
usually rubber-stamped whatever the president sent to it. Now
Mexico's opposition parties form an majority bloc in Congress, from
left to right.
</P>
<P>
   The parties are even considering forming an alliance to
challenge the PRI in next year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo is entering his last year as president and despite the
catcalls he appears to be enjoying a his highest level of
popularity. On Wednesday, Mexico City's Reforma newspaper published
a poll showing that 66 percent of Mexicans approve of the way
Zedillo is managing the country.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo devoted the first part of his speech to describing
advances in education, healthcare and other social services.
Hecklers first exploded when he began to talk about Mexico's
agricultural population, and he suggested that Mexico is ``leaving
behind'' a crisis that has hurt its farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the dispute for land is over,'' Zedillo also said,
drawing more jeers.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Medina Plascenia of Mexico's conservative National Action
Party, who later delivered the rebuttal, ordered the hecklers to
respect Zedillo. But as Zedillo's speech went on, Medina ended up
having to beg for calm from his opposition colleagues more than
half a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Zedillo kept speaking over the din, urging tolerance
and describing electoral reforms designed to give candidates equal
access to the media and to make the country's 2000 presidential
elections the most competitive in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today in Mexico no one is persecuted for his ideas or beliefs,
nor for organizing to fight for those beliefs,'' Zedillo added,
over jeers. ``Today in Mexico nobody is censured for what they say,
write or publish.''
</P>
<P>
   At first Zedillo appeared stunned by the heckling, but then he
began to smile and deliver his planned remarks more loudly and
deliberately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tolerance is to respect the practices and opinions of others,
although they may be different from our own,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After shaking hands with Zedillo, Medina began his rebuttal,
instantly drawing shouts of protest from Zedillo supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does us no good to hear one more time that 'things are
going well' while poverty continues to dangerously increase,''
Medina said, looking uncomfortable as congressmen on the floor
milled around, shouting at him and at each other.
</P>
<P>
   After the event was over, a Zedillo administration aide said he
thought Zedillo was ``a bit amused at the spectacle'' of the
evening. ``But I don't think he liked it,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
