<SLUG> BC-WHIDBEY-JETS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY TO EXPAND PROWLER FORCE AT WHIDBEY ISLAND N.A.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pentagon has authorized the Navy to create a new EA-6B
Prowler squadron at Whidbey Island Naval Air Station in response to
higher-than-anticipated demands on the radar-jamming units during
the air war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The squadron will have a standard makeup of four aircraft and
184 personnel, including 24 pilots and electronic countermeasures
officers and 160 enlisted technicians. The unit would be the fifth
Whidbey-based Prowler squadron dedicated to supporting Air Force
units that operate from land-based facilities overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to beef up the Prowler force is one of the first
Pentagon steps to adjust the armed forces in the wake of a review
of ``lessons learned'' from Kosovo, a Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
   The primary impetus for creating the new squadron is to avoid
undue strains on the Prowler force and its people, the Pentagon
official said. ``This is sort of like a relief valve,'' the
official said. ``It will allow a little bit more flexibility (for
the Prowler aircrews) and it will allow more time between
deployments.''
</P>
<P>
   Three months after the Kosovo conflict ended, the pace of
overseas deployments has already resumed for the Whidbey units. Of
the six units that flew combat missions in Kosovo, one is still on
deployment, two have returned and left on new overseas missions, a
fourth is preparing to deploy for six months in late September, and
the other two are engaged in training missions at the Oak Harbor
base located about 55 miles northeast of Seattle, a Whidbey
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon plan includes accelerating research into developing
a new jamming aircraft to replace the EA-6B by 2015, officials
said. The military trade newsletter ``Inside the Navy,'' which
initially disclosed the plan earlier this week, said the new
F/A-18E/F Super Hornet is the most likely candidate to become the
follow-on aircraft for the Prowler, which first entered service in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said initial steps to organize the new Whidbey
squadron would begin in 2001 with activation in 2003. ``There is a
long lead time'' for assembling the aircraft and personnel and
initial training, a Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense officials said Wednesday they could discuss the
tentative plan only on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to expand the Prowler force by only one squadron of
four aircraft stems from the fact that the EA-6B airframe is no
longer in production and there are no plans to reopen the assembly
line. There are 123 Prowlers in the Navy-Marine Corps inventory, of
which about 31 are undergoing modernization or maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials say they are arranging loans of aircraft to units
in training and providing deploying squadrons with the full number
of Prowlers they require. During Kosovo, one Whidbey squadron
returned home without any of its aircraft, which were left behind
in Europe and divided up among several other squadrons flying
combat missions.
</P>
<P>
   There are 19 EA-6B Prowler squadrons in service, including 14
based at Whidbey Island, four operated by the Marine Corps out of
Cherry Point, N.C., and one operated by the Navy Reserves at
Andrews Air Force Base near Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The EA-6B mission is to knock out enemy air-defense systems by
jamming radar systems and by hitting them with the missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department relied heavily on the Prowlers to defend
U.S. and NATO aircraft during the 78-day air campaign against
Serbia, which involved thousands of air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Prowler is the U.S. military's only electronic warfare
aircraft and is essential to protect both American and allied
planes in combat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
