<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8136 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ABORT-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      09-01 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORT-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA GIRL'S ABORTION CASE ADDS TO DEBATE IN KANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if Kansas didn't have enough conflict over abortion, now
comes Arizona with new ammunition for the battle.
</P>
<P>
   The case of a 14-year-old girl, who six months into her
pregnancy received approval to travel from Arizona to Kansas for an
abortion, may help galvanize sentiment in the Kansas Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tony Powell of Wichita, an outspoken abortion opponent,
said, ``Cases like this once again bring us to the reality that
Kansas is the abortion capital of the nation. I think this case
helps us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Erika Fox, an abortion rights advocate and vice president
for public policy for Planned Parenthood of Kansas and
Mid-Missouri, said the girl's case illustrates the difficult
choices a troubled pregnancy may lead to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think that it is necessarily harmful to our cause,''
Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, a possible rape victim, apparently will end the
pregnancy at Women's Health Care Services in Wichita, where
physician George Tiller has gained wide attention for providing
late-term abortions. One report Wednesday said she already had
arrived in the state.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, foes of abortion have tried to pass laws that
would stop late-term abortions in Kansas. One law did go on the
books in 1998, but it has been faulted for being contradictory and
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Next year could be showdown time for a new abortion law.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, members of the House and Senate face re-election,
meaning they'll be particularly sensitive to heated issues like
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Arizona case is the second in which a girl came to
Kansas for a late-term abortion she could not get at home. The
other was a Michigan case in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some of us, it is a rallying call,'' said Sen. Karin
Brownlee of Olathe, a leading abortion opponent. ``It's disturbing
that Kansas is known for this type of business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Lana Oleen of Manhattan, an advocate of abortion
rights, said of the Arizona case, ``I think it's a very sad
situation that will be exploited by some.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many places in the United States offer late-term abortions,
a practice that opponents of abortion condemn. Such abortions
involve a far more developed fetus than abortions done in the early
weeks of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona teen is 24 weeks pregnant. No clinic in Arizona
provides abortions at that stage.
</P>
<P>
   The girl lives under the control of state authorities rather
than parents, and she ran away for several weeks after becoming
pregnant. The Arizona Supreme Court ultimately approved her
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In the Michigan case, a 12-year-old girl who came to Kansas for
an abortion was said to have been impregnated by her teen-age
brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think it's helpful to be able to visualize the
type of situation a family could face,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, people opposed to abortion gathered outside
Tiller's office in Wichita in an attempt to talk to the Arizona
girl, said David Gittrich, executive director of Kansans for Life,
the Wichita-based anti-abortion group.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be cited during debate in the Legislature next
year, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can guarantee we're going to address it in the elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature probably will consider several abortion bills. A
ban on a procedure called ``partial-birth abortion'' is one
possibility. There also could be an attempt to outlaw all late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Dick Bond of Overland Park, who favors abortion
rights, expects a full battle over the issue and said the Arizona
girl's case might be cited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it adds any more arguments than were already
present,'' Bond said. ``I've anticipated a high-level, intense
debate in an election year.''
 &LR; tag1:To reach John A. Dvorak, who covers Kansas government and
politics, call {(816) 234-7743} or send e-mail to
{jdvorak &LR; kcstar.com}
</P>
</TEXT>
