<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK BUYS OLDE FINANCIAL CORP. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ H&AMP;R Block Inc. said Wednesday that, in its
largest diversification bid yet, it was paying $850 million in cash
to buy Olde Financial Corp., owner of the country's fourth-largest
securities discount brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Olde Discount Corp.'s brokerage offices in 35 states serve more
than 600,000 clients, whose incomes and other household
circumstances on average nearly match those of about one-fourth of
Block's traditional tax service clients, Block and securities
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts described the purchase as a good fit that could
increase Block's profit at least 6 cents a share this fiscal year,
which will end in April, and help Block become a broader-based
company more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Block's stock fell as much as 13 percent in
heavier-than-normal trading on the New York Stock Exchange before
it recouped more than half of that in a late rally. The shares
closed Wednesday at 51, down 4 5//8.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors sold initially because credit rating
agencies, including Moody's Investors Service Inc., expressed
concern about the debts Block is piling up with its two-year string
of acquisitions and because Olde has had highly visible run-ins
with securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Olde and three of its former executives, including its
then-chairman and founder, last year agreed to pay $7 million to
settle federal allegations that the company encouraged its brokers
to defraud clients by promoting stocks that paid the highest
commissions to brokers. Olde paid the settlement without admitting
to or denying the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Block went to great lengths in the purchase negotiations to make
sure Olde has reformed its practices and ``now has a compliance
culture that is considered sound,'' said Linda McDougall, Block's
media relations chief.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Block's debt nor Olde's trouble with regulators appears
insurmountable, and Block's revenue and earnings will increase
markedly when Block further pulls its many new parts into a whole,
said analyst Pete Heckmann at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's time during the next 12 to 18 months for the company
to buckle down and integrate,'' Heckmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Olde has a sales force of about 1,200 registered securities
representatives in 181 offices across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming that the acquisition is completed before tax-filing
season starts in January, ``we will have in place the major
building blocks to achieve our vision of becoming the preferred tax
and financial partner for our clients,'' said Frank L. Salizzoni,
Block's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Olde, a privately held firm based in Detroit, will be the second
securities broker that Block, of Kansas City, has bought in a
two-year drive to begin converting as many of its 9,000 U.S.
seasonal tax offices as practical into year-round full-service
financial centers. Block also owns Birchtree Financial, a much
smaller Kansas City financial planning organization that offers
stock, bond and mutual fund trading.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Block's other big buys have been of major regional
accounting firms that serve business and higher-income clients.
Included is the previous record $290 million it paid this summer
for the nation's seventh-largest accounting firm, McGladrey &AMP;
Pullen.
</P>
</TEXT>
