<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-BUSINESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUMP'S CASINO DEAL STILL NOT SEALED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ What are the odds that The Donald is coming
to Kansas City?
</P>
<P>
   It's still up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the $15 million deal that Donald Trump
reached in January to buy the Flamingo Hilton Casino in Kansas
City, either party could walk away from the deal if it didn't close
by midnight Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, however, is still bogged down in background checks at
the Missouri Gaming Commission, which has taken longer than
expected to deliver its judgment on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Now the deadline has come and gone, and Hilton is rumored to be
quietly shopping the property to parties other than Trump.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies, however, are maintaining poker faces. Neither
would comment last week on the approaching deadline. Neither
returned calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A Hilton subsidiary still owns the Kansas City casino despite
spinning off virtually all of the rest of its far-flung casino
empire into Park Place Entertainment Inc. last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't heard anything from either company,'' said Harold
Bailey, a spokesman for the Gaming Commission. ``We're not at this
time ready to make a recommendation to the commissioners regarding
(Trump's) suitability to do business in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission next meets on Sept. 22 in St. Louis. If the
Trump-Hilton deal falls through, the commission is back to where it
was in January, reopening Hilton's licensing investigation because
of bribery and perjury allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
